aV \u000a                Senate Democrats tried their hand at tax reform counter-messaging Tuesday in a public letter sent and signed by the vast majority of Senate Democrats.  \u000a            By COLIN WILHELM  08/02/2017 05:21 PM EDT  Everyone in Washington agrees that the tax code doesn\u2019t work. Just don\u2019t expect them to agree on how to fix it, especially across party lines.   Senate Democrats tried their hand at tax reform counter-messaging Tuesday in a public letter sent and signed by the vast majority of Senate Democrats, 45 out of 48, urging Republicans not to use a budgetary maneuver known as reconciliation to pass tax reform solely with GOP votes. Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) was quick to shoot down the suggestion.  Story Continued Below  Nonetheless, senators on both sides of the aisle paid lip service to working with the other party for a more bipartisan process on reshaping the tax code to aid economic growth.   The most intriguing part of the letter was not what it said, but the three signatures it lacked \u2014 from Sens. Heidi Heitkamp (D-N.D.), Joe Manchin (D-W.Va.) and Joe Donnelly (D-Ind.), all of whom are up for reelection in states where President Donald Trump is popular.  All three played down the significance of their demurral from the letter, and it's certainly too early to read much into it other than political caution.  \u201cWe believe that the most important thing is no more debt, my God, we\u2019re in enough debt, we need something that doesn\u2019t increase the debt,\u201d said Manchin, who added that he hoped to work with the White House and Republicans on reforming the tax code but had yet to receive any outreach.  Sign up for our tax policy newsletter and stay informed \u2014 weekday mornings, in your inbox.  By signing up you agree to receive email newsletters or alerts from POLITICO. You can unsubscribe at any time.  The Democrats\u2019 message appears to anticipate that Republicans will write a bill with temporary provisions \u2014 a tactic that House Speaker Paul Ryan mapped out in a meeting with conservative groups last week \u2014 in order to gain a favorable budgetary score for provisions that come with a high price tag but quick economic benefit.  A spokesperson for Heitkamp said, "Sen. Heitkamp is approaching tax reform with an open mind and she wants work across the aisle to help make reforms that will grow the economy and support working families."   But few saw an outbreak of bipartisanship as realistic.   \u201cI don\u2019t think this is going to be 1986, when you had a bipartisan effort to scrub the code,\u201d McConnell said at a weekly press availability, invoking the year in which a comprehensive \u2014 and bipartisan \u2014 overhaul of the tax code last occurred.   \u201cIt\u2019s their best opportunity to work with us and get something done,\u201d said Senate Finance Chairman Orrin Hatch (R-Utah). But in the next breath he added, \u201cIf not, then blame the Democrats.\u201d   When asked about Democrats demanding in their letter that tax reform not add to the deficit, Hatch said: \u201cTell them to grow up.\u201d   Sen. John Thune of South Dakota, the No. 3 GOP senator, said that the Democratic letter asked for steps \u201cthat aren\u2019t consistent with what we want to see in a pro-growth tax reform bill.\u201d But Thune also said he hoped to find some Democrats willing to work with Republicans on tax reform, and predicted that both parties would be able to offer amendments in a Finance Committee markup.  \u000a  \u000a            By ELANA SCHOR  \u201cI would like to see us at least attempt to try and work with the Democrats, see if there are any of them who are available and are willing to work with us on tax reform that we think truly is pro-growth,\u201d Thune told reporters.  According to a recent Gallup poll aggregate, Trump's approval ratings are highest in Manchin's and Heitkamp's home states. In Donnelly's Indiana, Gallup aggregated a 48 percent approval rating for Trump.   McConnell noted the absences, suggesting that, \u201cDemocratic senators who did not sign the letter ... may be open to pro-growth tax reform.\u201d   While Republicans may be able to more quickly find broader agreement among themselves on a tax overhaul, a few extra votes from moderate Democrats would provide the majority leader with a luxury he doesn\u2019t have in the health care debate.   Liam Donovan, a former National Republican Senatorial Committee staffer who now handles legislative and political affairs for the Associated Builders and Contractors, said estate tax repeal \u2014 which Republicans have promised to include in their effort \u2014 could be floated as a carrot in front of vulnerable Democrats like Manchin, Heitkamp and Donnelly to bring them to the table. Manchin was the lone Democrat to cross the aisle on a 2015 bill to repeal the estate tax.  But, \u201cat the end of the day I don\u2019t expect them to be there,\u201d said Donovan.   Aaron Lorenzo, Bernie Becker and Elana Schor contributed to this report.   Missing out on the latest scoops? Sign up for POLITICO Playbook and get the latest news, every morning \u2014 in your inbox.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
