aV \u000a            By MADELINE CONWAY  01/19/2017 01:24 PM EST  Ivanka Trump says it is \u201cinappropriate\u201d to speculate that she will effectively serve as first lady in her father\u2019s administration and occupy an office in the East Wing.  \u201cI think it\u2019s an inappropriate observation,\u201d Trump told the ABC News program \u201c20/20\u201d for a segment set to air Thursday night. \u201cThere\u2019s one first lady and she\u2019ll do remarkable things.\u201d  Story Continued Below  President-elect Donald Trump\u2019s wife, the former model Melania, was a reluctant campaigner, and she plans to stay in New York City for several months after the inauguration before moving to Washington so that their young son, Barron, can complete the schoolyear there.   But Ivanka, Trump\u2019s oldest daughter, was a regular surrogate for the campaign and has advised him on policy issues including parental leave and the environment. Ivanka\u2019s husband, Jared Kushner, is also an incoming senior adviser to the president-elect, and the couple is moving to Washington with their three children.  All that has prompted widespread speculation that Ivanka may fulfill some of the first lady\u2019s traditional duties in Melania\u2019s place.  She pushed back on that in her interview with ABC, though. She also discussed her transition from leader at the Trump Organization to Washington, describing it as \u201cemotional.\u201d  \u201cIt\u2019s emotional that I\u2019m stepping away from my business, and my father will be president, and hopefully I can be there to support him and to support those causes I\u2019ve cared about my whole professional career,\u201d she said.  ABC also spoke with Trump\u2019s two adult sons, Don Jr. and Eric, for the segment. Both sons are taking over managerial control of their father\u2019s business empire, an arrangement that has not satisfied ethics experts, who say it does not eliminate Trump\u2019s many financial conflicts of interest.  \u000aPresidential Transition   \u000a            By DAVID SIDERS  Eric, though, suggested that his father will be too busy to get involved with the business as president.  \u201cMy father has the biggest responsibility of any person, arguably, on the planet, and that\u2019s to run the United States of America,\u201d Eric Trump said. \u201cHis focus is going to be running this country.\u201d  Missing out on the latest scoops? Sign up for POLITICO Playbook and get the latest news, every morning \u2014 in your inbox.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
