aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Margaret Harding McGill, Ashley Gold, Nancy Scola, John Hendel and Steven Overly   SINCLAIR'S ASSIST FROM THE FCC \u2014 Sinclair Broadcast Group is expanding its conservative-leaning television empire into nearly three-quarters of American households \u2014 but its aggressive takeover of the airwaves wouldn\u2019t have been possible without help from President Donald Trump's chief at the Federal Communications Commission, Margaret and John report. Sinclair, already the nation\u2019s largest TV broadcaster, plans to buy 42 stations from Tribune Media in cities including New York, Chicago and Los Angeles, on top of the more than 170 stations it already owns. It got a critical assist this spring from Republican FCC Chairman Ajit Pai, who revived a decades-old regulatory loophole that will keep Sinclair from vastly exceeding federal limits on media ownership. The FCC and the company both say the agency wasn\u2019t giving Sinclair any special favors by reviving the \u201cUHF discount,\u201d which has long been considered technologically obsolete.  Story Continued Below  With the regulatory path eased, and Republicans in control of Congress, Sinclair has focused its bare-bones lobbying effort on tamping down Democratic opposition. Senate Commerce Committee ranking member Bill Nelson (D-Fla.) recounted the broadcaster\u2019s charm offensive, noting that Executive Chairman David Smith \u201cwas in my office\u201d in June discussing the Tribune deal. Following the meeting, Nelson told John he saw no need for great congressional objection on his part: \u201cI really haven\u2019t gotten into that and I don\u2019t intend to. That\u2019s an issue that is in front of the various administrative agencies. So I\u2019m going to let them use their expertise.\u201d Sinclair\u2019s PAC cut a $1,500 check for Nelson on June 13, around the time of that meeting, following one for $1,000 in March. Republicans show general confidence in the deal\u2019s federal approval: \u201cI don\u2019t know why it shouldn\u2019t go forward,\u201d Sen. Roger Wicker (R-Miss.) told POLITICO.   U.S. DIGITAL SERVICE SETS ITS SIGHTS ON REBUILDING \u2014 In the waning days of the Obama administration that created it, the USDS's ranks had swelled to about 200 programmers, designers and others charged with upgrading citizens' digital interactions with the federal government. That's shrunk down to 160 people at least in part, says Matt Cutts, the former Google software executive now serving as USDS's acting administrator, because of the freeze on federal hiring Trump imposed when he arrived in office. In a new story on USDS's next steps, Cutts talks about why the agency has kept its head down during the previous six months, how the digital service fits into Trump's Washington and why he doesn't think his team will be asked to build a so-called Muslim registry anytime soon. Nancy has the story. When it comes to recruiting, says Cutts, "It's not a secret that Silicon Valley tends to lean left." But he adds, \u201cthe bigger challenge we face is letting people know about the opportunity. We're still here. We're working on projects that matter. We're hiring."   \u2014 The Trump administration plans to further tap the expertise inside technology companies \u2013 but it's unclear how those plans relate to USDS. The White House Office of American Innovation will create \u201ccenters of excellence\u201d that pair experts from tech firms with government employees on projects related to cloud computing, data center consolidation and open data, Steven reports. White House senior officials shared an update of those plans during a phone call Thursday with representatives from nearly two dozen technology companies, including Apple, Oracle, Amazon, Google, Intel and Microsoft. CEOs from those firms took part in the inaugural meeting of the innovation office's American Technology Council in June.   LEAVING ON A JET PLANE \u2014 The Senate has officially cleared out for the August recess, leaving a plume of #jetfumes in its wake \u2013 and the last-minute passage of six tech and telecom bills, Ashley reports. The measures include Sen. John Thune's MOBILE NOW Act, which would free government spectrum for commercial use; Sen. Amy Klobuchar's Improving Rural Call Quality and Reliability Act and the Kari's Law Act, which would require multi-line telephone systems to let users directly call 9-1-1 without any code or prefix. Also approved were Sen. Dean Heller's FCC Consolidated Reporting Act; Sen. Bill Nelson's Spoofing Prevention Act; and the DIGIT Act from Sens. Deb Fischer and Cory Booker, which would encourage government investment and development in the Internet of Things.   \u2014 On the nominee side: The Senate confirmed Jessica Rosenworcel and Brendan Carr to be FCC commissioners, but opted to hold off on adding another term for FCC Chairman Ajit Pai, Ashley and John report. The chamber will take a recorded vote on Pai when it returns in the fall, providing Democrats the opportunity to demonstrate their opposition, given the moves he's taken on issues like net neutrality.   \u2014 But that's not all: The Senate also approved Vishal Amin for IP czar and Peter Davidson, a former top Verizon lobbyist, for Commerce Department general counsel. One notable nominee who's still awaiting confirmation: Makan Delrahim, Trump's pick for DOJ antitrust chief.   GOOD FRIDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we are here for some of these new Halo Top flavors. Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.   Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Email us the details at techcalendar@politicopro.com.   ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: The private sector and government must work together to support diversity and expansion of STEAM education, with a special focus on computer science programs. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. More: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  FIRSTNET HITS 10 STATES \u2014 Michigan has become the latest state to opt in to FirstNet and AT&T's state plans, making it the 10th to join. Michigan was also among the states that issued an RFP to look at competitive options for the state plan.   DEMS SUGGEST MORE NET NEUTRALITY WITNESSES \u2014 Democrats from the House Energy and Commerce Committee wrote to Republican panel leaders Greg Walden (R-Ore.) and Marsha Blackburn (R-Tenn.) suggesting eight more witnesses to testify at the net neutrality hearing set for September. The committee has invited CEOs of major tech companies like Google and Facebook to testify, while Democrats have complained about a lack of inclusiveness for smaller companies and entrepreneurs. \u201cWhile we appreciate you scheduling a hearing to look at how the FCC is eliminating the ground rules for the internet ecosystem, we continue to believe that the witness list must be expanded beyond the Chief Executive Officers of eight large corporate interests,\u201d wrote Reps. Frank Pallone (D-N.J.) and Mike Doyle (D-Pa.). See their suggested witnesses here.   INVESTORS BACK ENTREPRENEUR VISA RULE \u2014 Sixty national and regional groups representing venture capitalists and entrepreneurs urged the Department of Homeland Security to reconsider its plans to abandon the International Entrepreneur Rule \u2014 an Obama-era policy that established temporary visas for foreign-born entrepreneurs who launch investor-backed companies in the U.S. In comments filed Thursday, the groups say entrepreneurs offered visas through the program would create U.S. jobs \u2014 a key tenet of Trump\u2019s campaign platform and economic agenda. \u201cThe International Entrepreneur Rule will allow the world\u2019s best entrepreneurs to create jobs in our country, rather than overseas where they will then compete with American workers and companies,\u201d the letter states. The National Venture Capital Association spearheaded the comments, which were endorsed by the Internet Association, Engine, FWD.us, the Information Technology Industry (ITI) Council and TechNet, among many others.   FCC ADDS TO BROADBAND GROUP \u2014 Pai announced the members of the final working group for his Broadband Deployment Advisory Committee, which he launched earlier this year and tasked with developing recommendations to speed the build-out of high-speed internet service. The working group, Streamlining Federal Siting, will explore methods for reducing barriers to build infrastructure on federal lands. Members include officials from the Agriculture, Interior, and Housing and Urban Development departments.   SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014   \u2014 Uber reportedly knowingly supplied drivers with defective vehicles: "Uber managers in Singapore were aware of [a] Honda recall when they bought more than 1,000 defective Vezels and rented them to drivers without the needed repairs, according to internal Uber emails and documents reviewed by The Wall Street Journal and interviews with people familiar with Uber\u2019s operations in the region," the WSJ reports. \u2026 The company has also rolled out plans to expand its trucking offerings, enabling more users to use its Freight App, which connects drivers and shipping companies, TechCrunch reports.   \u2014 The Far Right and YouTube: "Like the much smaller Tumblr (which has long been dominated by lively and combative left-wing politics) or 4chan (which has become a virulent and effective hard-right meme factory) YouTube is host to just one dominant native political community: the YouTube right," The New York Times reports. "They are monologuists, essayists, performers and vloggers who publish frequent dispatches from their living rooms, their studios or the field, inveighing vigorously against the political left and mocking the 'mainstream media,' against which they are defined and empowered."   QUOTE OF THE DAY \u2014 In a speech on the Senate floor, Sen. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) slammed the Democrats' new antitrust platform, quipping that former FTC Commissioner Joshua Wright referred to the "progressive" approach as "hipster antitrust." "And nobody would mistake me for a hipster," the Utah Republican added.   QUICK DOWNLOADS   Twitter's bet on live video: Business Insider profiles the company's chief operating officer and his push for live video.   Kalanick brings on "CEO advisory" firm: "Ousted Uber CEO Travis Kalanick has hired high-profile 'CEO advisory' firm Teneo to help him manage his own embattled interests, according to several sources close to the situation," Recode reports.   Swipe right for mentorship: LinkedIn has a new Tinder-like tool that aims to help users find mentors, TechCrunch reports.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
