aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from John Hendel, Ashley Gold and Margaret Harding McGill  WILL THEY OR WON'T THEY? \u2014 We're tracking whether the Senate votes to confirm the three FCC nominees (GOP Chairman Ajit Pai, Democrat Jessica Rosenworcel and Republican Brendan Carr) before heading out of town for the August recess. The Commerce Committee approved the trio Wednesday and a Thursday vote, likely via hotline, is looking possible, but senators were still negotiating some sticking points.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 Democrats don't want Carr to be confirmed for two consecutive terms. \u201cThe Dems over here are not going to let that second term go,\u201d Commerce Committee Chairman John Thune (R-S.D.) told John Wednesday. He hinted that Republicans could settle for a single term.   \u2014 Republicans want to attach a bunch of bills. They're aiming to push through six pieces of telecom legislation with the confirmations. That would include Thune's MOBILE NOW Act, which would free up government spectrum for commercial use. The measure got caught in a partisan tussle over Rosenworcel's (failed) confirmation last Congress.   HAPPY RURAL BROADBAND MONTH \u2014 The FCC will vote today on several items devoted to that theme, including a public notice to kick off the second phase of the Connect America auction. That\u2019s set to start in 2018 and distribute up to $198 million annually in subsidies for 10 years to providers committed to bringing voice and broadband to hard-to-reach areas.   \u2014 The agency has also teed up a proposal on Mobility Fund subsidies for telecom companies building out 4G LTE, something supported by AT&T; potential changes to paperwork ISPs must fill out to provide broadband coverage data to the agency; and an inquiry into whether mid-band spectrum can be used for next-generation services, including wireless broadband.   PORTMAN PUSHES ANTI-SEX-TRAFFICKING BILL \u2014 Sen. Rob Portman (R-Ohio) talked big-ticket legislation like tax and health care reform with President Donald Trump on Wednesday, but he made sure to mention another of his top priorities: an anti-sex-trafficking bill introduced this week. The bill, which would amend Section 230 of the Communications Decency Act, has sparked major pushback from the tech industry, which fears a wider array of online platforms will be held liable for content posted by users.    \u2014 Sen. Kamala Harris (D-Calif.), who filed pimping and money-laundering charges against Backpage.com as California attorney general, said the measure was an important one. "I think it's very important, and I have a whole history on working on trafficking, in particular on the work that I've done for years when I was District Attorney of San Francisco and even before that when I was a line prosecutor in the D.A.'s office of Alameda County," she told MT.   \u2014 A number of tech groups including the Internet Association and Consumer Technology Association have voiced their opposition to the bill. In another coalition letter, R Street Institute, TechFreedom and New America's Open Technology Institute are among the others sharing concerns about the additional liability tech companies could incur if the bill were to become law.   GOOD THURSDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we're really digging the fashion on "Insecure." Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.   Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Email us the details at techcalendar@politicopro.com.   ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: The private sector and government must work together to support diversity and expansion of STEAM education, with a special focus on computer science programs. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. More: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  ZUCK TO WORK WITH FORMER CLINTON POLLSTER \u2014 "Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg and his wife, Priscilla Chan, have hired Democratic pollster Joel Benenson, a former top adviser to President Barack Obama and the chief strategist to Hillary Clinton\u2019s failed 2016 presidential campaign, as a consultant, according to a person familiar with the hire," POLITICO's Annie Karni reports. "Benenson\u2019s company, Benenson Strategy Group, will be conducting research for the Zuckerberg-Chan Initiative, the couple\u2019s philanthropy."   WICKER, SCHATZ RALLY FOR 5G \u2014 Sens. Roger Wicker (R-Miss.) and Brian Schatz (D-Hawaii) introduced a resolution championing the deployment of 5G mobile broadband technology. "Potential benefits [of 5G deployment] include three million new jobs, $275 billion in investment from the wireless industry, and a boost of $500 billion to the economy," according to a news release.   DEMOCRATIC INCUBATOR STARTS INVESTING \u2014 Higher Ground Labs, a campaign tech incubator started by Obama administration alums, selected 10 startups for its first cohort of investment, The Hill reports. \u201cFor too long, progressives have counted on Presidential campaigns to incubate and build campaign technology \u2014 a strategy that isn\u2019t optimal when conservatives like the Koch brothers and the Mercers are pumping big money into permanent GOP campaign technology companies,\u201d said Ron Klain, the chairman of HGL's advisory broad and a former aide to President Obama. The chosen startups include GroundGame, Qriously and Tuesday Strategies. HGL is also among the firms that contributed to an $8 million Series A round for texting platform Hustle, a tool used by both the Clinton and Sanders campaigns during the election.   AT&T CHALLENGES STARZ MERGER STUDY \u2014 In a white paper submitted to the Justice Department, former Trump transition adviser Jeff Eisenach said the AT&T-Time Warner merger could lead to increased prices and reduced choices for consumers of premium channels. Eisenach argued that AT&T would have the incentive to steer pay-TV subscribers to Time Warner-owned HBO and away from rivals Showtime or Starz. The study was commissioned by Starz. AT&T spokesman Michael Balmoris responded, "This conclusion doesn't square with the facts. We fully expect the DoJ to base its analysis on the facts and the law, as it always does, and not the work of HBO's competitors.\u201d   MORE TIME ON NET NEUTRALITY? Public Knowledge, the Electronic Frontier Foundation and several other groups want an eight-week extension on the deadline for reply comments in the FCC's net neutrality proceeding. The groups argue the comment periods for prior rulemakings on the topic were longer, and noted that the current proceeding already has a record-breaking 15 million filings. "This volume alone warrants an extension of time for the replies," they write. "The current schedule does not afford interested persons enough time to read and properly consider the record, let alone to prepare their own replies." The deadline for reply comments is Aug. 16.   SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014   \u2014 Tech industry slams Trump-backed immigration proposal: "Tech advocacy groups slammed an immigration bill endorsed by President Donald Trump, saying it would harm \u2014 not help \u2014 the industry's ability to recruit highly skilled foreign workers," Steven reports.   \u2014 Some funding platforms curb alt-right accounts: "Over the past five months, PayPal has banned or hobbled the accounts of several prominent people and groups that promote far-right politics. Crowdfunding platforms like GoFundMe, Patreon, and YouCaring have also cut fundraisers for alt-right-associated causes and people," BuzzFeed reports.   \u2014 Facebook still working on diversity: "Its 2017 data, released on Wednesday, revealed small gains for women at the Menlo Park, Calif.-based giant. Still, the company's technical or STEM roles, as well as its executive leadership, remain overwhelmingly white and male," Forbes reports.   TRANSITIONS \u2014 Glenn Lurie, an AT&T executive who helped shape the company's exclusive deal for Apple's iPhone a decade ago, is retiring, per The Wall Street Journal.   BYE, BYE VERIZON CENTER \u2014 D.C. locals will have to get used to calling the sports venue a different name soon. Verizon announced it's ending its sponsorship of the arena, and there's no immediate word of a new moniker, though Capital One is a rumored possibility.   QUICK DOWNLOADS   Raising the (solar) roof: "Tesla has completed its first solar roof installations, the company reported Wednesday as part of a second-quarter earnings report," Bloomberg reports.   What's old is new again: The Wall Street Journal looks at how cord-cutters are using TV antennae, these days.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
