aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  08/02/2017 10:00 AM EDT  \u000a                    Updated 08/02/2017 09:03 AM EDT  With help from Ashley Gold, John Hendel, Steven Overly and Margaret Harding McGill  FCC TRIO GETS SENATE COMMERCE VOTE \u2014 FCC Chairman Ajit Pai and commissioner nominees Jessica Rosenworcel and Brendan Carr are all due for a vote during this morning\u2019s Senate Commerce Committee markup, while negotiators tangle over confirmation specifics behind the scenes.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 Committee Chairman John Thune told Ashley on Tuesday: \u201cI hope that hearing will go by smoothly \u2026 it would be great if we could get [the nominees] disposed of by voice vote.\u201d So will that free up legislation that\u2019s been held up? \u201cI hope so; that\u2019s the case that we\u2019re making to the Democratic leadership in the Senate. Once these nominees that they were concerned about get freed and busted loose in the Senate, it ought to open up the opportunity to get some of the telecom bills. I think we have half a dozen bills or so that have been held up that really have bipartisan support and should get passed. I\u2019m hoping we\u2019ll see that, maybe as early as this week.\u201d  \u2014 The goal after Senate Commerce signs off on the FCC nominees is to \u201cget them in a cleared package\u201d of nominations being negotiated among Senate leaders, with the hope of confirmation before August recess, Thune told John. The South Dakota Republican said it\u2019s a question of whether Democrats want to force roll call votes or whether \u201cthey\u2019re willing to take some sort of a deal\u201d that allows the nominations to move in the bigger leadership-negotiated package. Commerce Committee ranking member Bill Nelson (D-Fla.) said with the right deal, the FCC nominees could move fast on the floor. \u201cYou know what greased lightning is?\u201d Nelson told John of the possible speed.   \u2014 Part of what\u2019s under negotiation now is whether to confirm FCC General Counsel Brendan Carr for two consecutive terms on the commission, Sen. Brian Schatz (D-Hawaii) told reporters. Democrats see potentially withholding a second term for Carr as an important factor in easing confirmation of a successor to Democratic Commissioner Mignon Clyburn. Sen. Ed Markey (D-Mass.) noted that an interest in pairing the next Democratic nominee with a Republican one remains a priority. \u201cI want to ensure that there\u2019s a guarantee that we\u2019re going to have a merger of the next Democratic nominee with one of these Republican nominees, as a guaranteed confirmation,\u201d he told MT. Thune told Ashley he knows some Democrats have concerns but said there\u2019s \u201cplenty of precedent\u201d for similar circumstances.   \u2014 NTIA Administrator nominee David Redl is also up for a vote, after it was delayed because of questions Sen. Ted Cruz (R-Texas) had about Redl\u2019s stance on the ICANN transition \u2014 which was completed last year. Cruz still has some outstanding concerns about Redl and sent a letter to Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross alongside Sen. Mike Lee (R-Utah) about the nomination, Ashley reports. Redl "espoused a policy position directly contrary to the position taken out by the secretary of Commerce and directly contrary to the position of President Trump," Cruz said Tuesday. "I and a number of other senators want to receive some significant clarity on that question." During his confirmation hearing Redl said, \u201cThe reality is that we\u2019re in the situation we\u2019re in. ... It would have been very difficult to put the genie back in the bottle," when Cruz asked whether he thought the ICANN transition was \u201cwise and prudent.\u201d   COULD NAFTA INCLUDE VISA UPGRADES? \u2014 Companies are interested in making it easier for top talent to go across borders, but Congress isn\u2019t quite sold on such policies, Pro Trade\u2019s Adam Behsudi reports. \u201cNow, as Mexico and Canada consider their demands ahead of the renegotiation of NAFTA, U.S. reluctance to address labor mobility terms in the context of trade deals is likely to remain unchanged, despite companies clamoring for reforms that would ease cross-border movement of workers tending to the complex and tight-knit supply chains that have developed over NAFTA's 23-year lifespan. \u2018Anything that looks like a back door into the immigration system is going to be a challenge,\u2019 said Daniel Ujczo, a lawyer based in Columbus, Ohio, who specializes in cross-border business issues between the U.S. and Canada.\u201d Read more, here.   BLUMENTHAL TALKS TECH\u2019S CONCERNS ON SECTION 230 BILL \u2014 Sen. Richard Blumenthal (D-Conn.), one of the chief sponsors of an anti-sex-trafficking bill that would narrow the protections of Section 230, responded to some of the concerns that tech groups have raised about the increased liability and legal costs the legislation could lead to. \u201cAs attorney general for years and years, I urged these companies to respect their responsibility, and they moved by millimeters toward a recognition of that obligation and some action on it,\u201d he told MT. \u201cI respect their arguments, but I just think there has to be some action to protect people from the Wild West of a lawless site that encourages trafficking and destroys human lives. They have some responsibility to do better. \u2026 They\u2019ve been inching toward realization, but it has to be more than voluntary at this point.\u201d When asked whether he thought existing laws could address this issue, Blumenthal asked, \u201cAre they working? I don\u2019t think so, and I know firsthand the obstacles to enforcing those laws, so I know their weaknesses and we need to strengthen them.\u201d  GOOD WEDNESDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we can\u2019t get enough of these pairings. Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.  Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Email us the details at techcalendar@politicopro.com.  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: The private sector and government must work together to support diversity and expansion of STEAM education, with a special focus on computer science programs. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. More: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  SOURCES: TRUMP TO TAKE ACTION AGAINST CHINA FOR IP THEFT: President Donald Trump will soon call on U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer to open an investigation against China under Section 301 of the Trade Act of 1974 for violations of U.S. intellectual property rights and forced technology transfers, two administration officials told POLITICO.   An announcement is expected late this week, but an official cautioned it could slip into next week. U.S. companies have complained they are often forced to share valuable technology with Chinese counterparts as a condition of doing business in the country. Section 301 allows the U.S. to impose unilateral duties against countries that impose barriers to U.S. exports.  The action would give Lighthizer a leading role in a lengthy investigation that could peer into all aspects of Chinese industrial policies and potentially result in unilateral U.S. trade sanctions.   Frustration that China is not doing more to persuade North Korea to rein in its nuclear program seems to be motivating the administration to fire a shot across the bow on the trade front, one source said. Many in the business community are likely to silently cheer the action as long overdue, but others may be worried about a further souring of the business environment and possible Chinese retaliation, a second source said.   TIME FOR LIFELINE? Senate Commerce is eyeing a hearing on the FCC\u2019s Lifeline program before the August recess, according to sources on Capitol Hill and in the telecom industry. One tentative date could be next Wednesday, although plans could change depending on when the Senate leaves town. The hearing follows a GAO report critical of the program.  ENTHUSIASM FOR AIRWAVES \u2014 All three FCC commissioners were among those lauding the bipartisan AIRWAVES spectrum legislation, introduced Tuesday in the Senate and scoring points from everyone from CTIA to Public Knowledge. Pai called the measure \u201cforward-thinking\u201d and praised its inclusion of the rural set-aside idea he pushed last year. \u201cThere is a lot to like in the bill, including firm spectrum deadlines and auctions for key bands,\u201d said Commissioner Mike O\u2019Rielly. \u201cNotably, the bill directs the Commission to study how unlicensed spectrum can be harnessed to meet the needs of rural communities,\u201d Commissioner Mignon Clyburn noted.  FOXCONN OUT OF THE BAG \u2014 President Donald Trump may be on a crusade against leakers, but it turns out he may not be the best at keeping confidence, either. At a White House small business event Tuesday, Trump said Foxconn Chairman Terry Gou told him the company may invest as much as $30 billion in the U.S. That\u2019s triple the $10 billion the Taiwanese electronics manufacturer recently announced it would spend on a new facility in Wisconsin. "He told me that off the record, so I promised I wouldn't tell anyone," Trump said to laughs. Trump did not elaborate further. Foxconn has an investment partnership with Japan-based Softbank, which has pledged to pump $50 billion into U.S. investments. \u201cThat\u2019s called big business, by the way,\u201d Trump told those gathered. \u201cYou\u2019ll be big business. You\u2019ve got to start out small but you\u2019re going to be big like that.\u201d  THE FIRST A.I. PRESIDENT? \u2014 Rep. John Delaney (D-Md.) may be a longshot presidential contender by most any measure, but the main tenet of his political platform could get techies excited. The three-term lawmaker says that artificial intelligence and automation (among other transformative technologies) should be front and center in the 2020 race. \u201cChange historically or innovation historically has been very positive, but it\u2019s not positive for everyone,\u201d he said. The government needs to fix that. How? Delaney proposes public education that extends from prekindergarten through either community college or a post-high school certificate. He also wants portable health care and retirement benefits so that workers can more easily change jobs or pursue entrepreneurial ventures. Pros can read more about Delaney, including his views on guaranteed minimum salaries, A.I. regulation and research funding, in this Q&A.  APPLE HINTS AT JOBS ANNOUNCEMENT \u2014 Apple CEO Tim Cook told analysts Tuesday that the company will have \u201csome things\u201d to say about company job growth and investment later this year. It\u2019s unclear whether those \u201cthings\u201d include the three \u201cbig, big, big\u201d plants that Trump recently referenced in a Wall Street Journal interview. Cook certainly didn\u2019t say as much in a conference call following the company\u2019s quarterly earnings announcement. However, Cook sees opportunities to help existing plants expand or \u201ceven maybe set up shop in the U.S. for the first time.\u201d In May, Apple invested $200 million of its $1 billion advanced manufacturing fund in a Corning factory in Kentucky that makes glass for its gadgets.   TECH LEADERS TALK TERRORISM \u2014 \u201cNearly every terrorist plot we uncover today has a digital dimension,\u201d Acting Homeland Security Secretary Elaine Duke said in a statement. That\u2019s why Duke was in San Francisco on Tuesday for a meeting with leaders from Microsoft, Twitter, Facebook, Snap and YouTube, among other companies. They formed the Global Internet Forum to Counter Terrorism in June to create a united front against the spread of terrorist propaganda online. \u201cFrom their virtual safe havens, groups like ISIS and al Qaeda have recruited followers in every single U.S. state and around the world,\u201d Duke said. \u201cA global crisis needs a global response, which is why I commend the companies here today for establishing this forum. Their platforms reflect the values of our open society \u2014 freedom of expression, debate, and ultimately tolerance. This is the opposite of the repressive worldview espoused by terrorist groups. Although they are trying to exploit these tools to do harm, the efforts discussed today will help us turn the tide against terrorists online.\u201d The companies plan to meet again in the coming months and recruit other tech firms to join their effort, they said. The meeting was closed to the press.  SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014  \u2014 The Uber CEO search continues: The company is \u201clooking forward,\u201d according to Salle Yoo, Uber\u2019s general counsel, who spoke at an all-hands meeting where the ride-sharing giant sought to quell rumors that former CEO Travis Kalanick was orchestrating his return, BuzzFeed reports.   \u2014 Facebook\u2019s got video-chat hardware in the works: The device aims to make users feel like they are in the same room as one another, Bloomberg reports.   \u2014 Bitcoin\u2019s existential crisis: \u201cBitcoin power brokers were unable to come behind a single solution that would have preserved a unified cryptocurrency by Tuesday morning's deadline,\u201d Business Insider reports. \u201cAs such, the digital currency has officially forked and split in two: bitcoin cash and bitcoin.\u201d  TRANSITIONS \u2014 CCIA has a series of personnel updates: Marianela Lpez-Galdos joins CCIA\u2019s Washington office as director of competition and regulatory policy. Isabelle Styslinger also joins the D.C. team as research analyst, with a focus on emerging technology. Christian Borggreen, previously director of international policy for CCIA\u2019s Brussels office, is being promoted to vice president and the new head of office for CCIA Europe. \u2026 Jeffrey Epstein has joined Hogan Lovells\u2019 Space and Satellite practice as counsel in Northern Virginia. \u2026 Kurt Kelty, Tesla\u2019s director of battery technology has departed the firm, Bloomberg reports.   QUICK DOWNLOADS  Trump admin readies IP trade case vs. China: \u201cThe Trump administration is preparing a broad move against China over trade, according to people with knowledge of its plans, amid growing worries in the United States over a Chinese government-led effort to make the country a global leader in microchips, electric cars and other crucial technologies of the future,\u201d The New York Times reports. \u201cThe trade case will focus on alleged Chinese violations of American intellectual property, according to three people with a detailed knowledge of the administration\u2019s plans.\u201d  Lyft helps ferry riders to Amtrak: \u201cLyft and Amtrak are teaming up on a partnership that will allow Amtrak app users to book a trip directly in the train operator\u2019s mobile software,\u201d TechCrunch reports.   Forget selfie sticks: What about a selfie drone? Snap is reportedly in talks to acquire a company that specializes in such tech, The Verge reports.  Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
