aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  08/01/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Nancy Scola, John Hendel and Margaret Harding McGill.  HUMAN TRAFFICKING BILL RAISING TECH\u2019S HACKLES \u2014 Senators including Rob Portman (R-Ohio) and Claire McCaskill (D-Mo.) are expected to introduce a bill as soon as today aimed at combating online human trafficking, legislation that comes after the lawmakers\u2019 investigation into controversial classified ad site Backpage.com, Nancy reports. The pending measure already has some in the tech industry on high-alert. They\u2019re alarmed about what it would do to narrow Section 230 of the 1996 Communications Decency Act, a landmark provision that limits website operators' liability for what their users post. Yes, they're quick to say, human trafficking is a menace. But they argue the proposed bill would make it legally precarious to operate sites like Reddit, Facebook and Airbnb, while drawing scrutiny away from true bad actors.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 "The bill jeopardizes bedrock principles of a free and open internet, with serious economic and speech implications well beyond its intended scope," Michael Beckerman, president of the Internet Association, tells MT. Adds Evan Engstrom, executive director of Engine, an advocacy group representing tech startups: "Section 230 is the foundational law of the internet, and starting to carve out exceptions to it scares people."   Whether senators buy those arguments \u2014 or instead see them as a dodge for sites unwilling to accept their role in facilitating horrid behavior \u2014 will be the debate of the coming days. We're tracking.   NET NEUTRALITY TAKE-AWAYS \u2014 Breathe easy, tech CEOs. House Energy and Commerce Republicans on Monday extended their deadline to RSVP for a Sept. 7 hearing on net neutrality legislation. That buys the execs some time to try to get out of a sticky situation. While a few tech players, including Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg, have made positive noises about net neutrality legislation \u2014 a longstanding goal of Republicans \u2014 their active participation in crafting such a bill could alienate Democrats and activist groups that want to keep the fight focused on the FCC. And tech companies don\u2019t seem inclined to spend all their political capital on net neutrality right now, given their array of priorities (tax reform, anyone?) in Washington.  \u2014 Democrats see the hand of Big Telecom in all this. Republicans want tech CEOs \u201cto go on the record to say that there should be legislation,\u201d Rep. Anna Eshoo, a Silicon Valley Democrat long active in telecom issues, told POLITICO. \u201cIt\u2019s the big ISPs that are pushing for the legislation.\u201d She accused the internet service providers of \u201cpolitical cross-dressing\u201d in which \u201cthey pound their chest, they say they\u2019re for net neutrality. You are? We\u2019ve got the protections. What\u2019s wrong?\u201d ISPs \u201cwant legislation so that it is tailor-made for them to do what they want to do, and they don\u2019t want any cop on the beat, they don\u2019t want FCC in it,\u201d she said.  \u2014 Watch Aug. 7. That\u2019s the date E&C Chairman Greg Walden (R-Ore.) wants to gather all interested parties in person to offer feedback on his 2015 net neutrality bill. His staff is soliciting industry feedback now. \u201cBy the end of next week, we should all have a good idea of whether there is any chance of moving forward together,\u201d GOP chief counsel Robin Colwell emailed industry officials.   TODAY: A NEW SENATE SPECTRUM PACKAGE \u2014 Sens. Cory Gardner (R-Colo.) and Maggie Hassan (D-N.H.) will unveil the Advancing Innovation and Reinvigorating Widespread Access to Electromagnetic Spectrum, or AIRWAVES, Act, which MT first reported was in the works back in June. The 10-page measure includes a number of provisions, including identifying spectrum bands for unlicensed use and freeing up mid-band spectrum. It would also create a rural set-aside, in which the FCC would allocate a tenth of proceeds from any spectrum auction and put it toward wireless broadband for unserved and underserved consumers. (Sound familiar? FCC Chairman Ajit Pai floated a similar idea last fall as part of his digital empowerment agenda).   \u2014 AIRWAVES \u201coffers innovative ways to avoid a spectrum crunch, pave the way for 5G service, and provide critical resources to rural America\u201d to continue \u201cbuildout in unserved and underserved areas throughout Colorado and the country,\u201d Gardner said.  GOOD TUESDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we\u2019re looking forward to The Bachelorette finale next week. Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.  Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Email us the details at techcalendar@politicopro.com.  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: The private sector and government must work together to support diversity and expansion of STEAM education, with a special focus on computer science programs. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. More: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  ICPA: IT\u2019S BAAACK \u2014 Sens. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), Chris Coons (D-Del.) and Dean Heller (R-Nev.) have officially resurrected the International Communications Privacy Act, which would create a legal framework for U.S. law enforcement to obtain electronic communications data of U.S. citizens, even when this information is stored overseas. The bill would require the use of a warrant for such inquiries and also would establish a standard for officials to access the data of foreign nationals in certain cases. See the full bill here.   \u2014 Apple, Google, AT&T and Microsoft are among the tech and telecom giants that have called for such legislation. \u201cFor far too long, technology companies, law enforcement and, ultimately, the courts have been forced to choose between competing interpretations of an outdated statute,\u201d Microsoft President Brad Smith writes in a blog post. \u201cThese conflicts of law put businesses in a no-win situation, putting American technology companies at a disadvantage.\u201d   GOOGLE RESPONDS TO EPIC\u2019S FTC COMPLAINT \u2014 Google is hitting back against a complaint that privacy watchdog EPIC filed with the FTC on Monday. In the complaint, EPIC argues that the search giant\u2019s tracking of user shopping data lacks both transparency and a clear way to opt out. A Google spokesperson emphasized that the company \u2014 which has a new feature that aims to trace the impact of its online ads on brick-and-mortar purchases \u2014 prioritizes privacy and uses \u201cdouble-blind encrypted technology\u201d so it does not see any individual\u2019s data or purchasing patterns. The spokesperson says users are able to easily opt out through their activity settings, but adds there\u2019s no explicit alert that prompts them to choose this option. The FTC has not contacted Google about the EPIC complaint, according to the spokesperson.   GOP TAKES ON LIFELINE (AGAIN) \u2014 Rep. Austin Scott (R-Ga.) brought back his End Taxpayer Funded Cell Phones Act before House lawmakers left town. That\u2019s the legislation that GOP leadership fast-tracked straight to floor consideration immediately after its introduction last year. (They tried to advance it under suspension of the rules, and it went down 207-143.) It now has 18 GOP backers, triple what it had before. \u201cMy bill will reform the Lifeline Program and restore it to its original purpose of providing landline services and prohibit Universal Service support for mobile services,\u201d Scott said. A GOP leadership aide said there\u2019s no talk on when and if the measure may be brought to the floor this time around.   NET NEUTRALITY BACKERS SEEK MERGER INFO \u2014 Trade group INCOMPAS wants the FCC to include redacted materials from recent mergers involving Comcast, Charter and AT&T in its review of Chairman Ajit Pai\u2019s proposal to roll back the agency\u2019s net neutrality rules. The group, which counts Netflix and Sprint among its members, said economic studies, internal company presentations and other data submitted as part of the commission\u2019s merger review process shows that ISPs have incentive to curb competition. The information would be vital in a court review of final rules, INCOMPAS CEO Chip Pickering told POLITICO. \u201cThe FCC has taken a position that the ISPs do not have the means and the motive to act against online competitors,\u201d Pickering said. \u201cAnd if that\u2019s the question, you have to look at all the evidence. And a refusal to consider the evidence, I think any court would find unreasonable.\u201d  \u2014 INCOMPAS noted that its request would not make the information available to the general public. Instead, only certain parties would be able to see the documents \u2014 the same confidentiality the FCC used in the merger reviews. Comcast, Charter and AT&T opposed the request in filings last week, arguing that sharing the information in the net neutrality proceeding risks disclosure of sensitive documents. Charter said the \u201cunprecedented request is a harmful fishing expedition, which, if granted, would violate federal law.\u201d Pickering finds the companies\u2019 opposition suspect: \u201cTheir nuclear reaction for simply asking for the evidence to be included continues to beg the question, \u2018What do they have to hide?\u2019\u201d INCOMPAS asks the FCC to act by July 31. Agency representatives did not respond to a request for comment Monday.  SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014  \u2014 Facebook COO on encryption: \u201cSheryl Sandberg defended Facebook's use of encryption in its popular messaging service WhatsApp, telling a BBC radio show that what limited data remains accessible can be useful to law enforcement as it seeks to thwart terrorist activity,\u201d The Washington Post reports.   \u2014 YC\u2019s Sam Altman to press on California\u2019s housing policy: As part of his new effort, The United Slate, the techie has established a loose policy platform on issues like access to housing, tax reform and expanding the social safety net, Recode reports.   \u2014 Spotify makes a push into podcasts, as rumblings of IPO continue: \u201cSpotify will fund a new batch of original podcasts in the coming months,\u201d Bloomberg reports.   TRANSITIONS -- Valerie Jarrett, a longtime senior adviser to former President Barack Obama, is now on Lyft\u2019s board of directors, Steven reports. \u2026 John Donovan has been named AT&T Communications CEO, per FierceWireless.   QUICK DOWNLOADS  Clyburn talks women in leadership: Democratic FCC Commissioner Mignon Clyburn gives an interview on the issue. Listen here.   Tax reform on a tight timeline: \u201cThe White House expects tax reform legislation to move quickly through Congress this fall, advancing through the House in October and clearing the Senate in November, legislative director Marc Short said Monday,\u201d POLITICO\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo reports.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
