aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  07/31/2017 10:01 AM EDT  With help from John Hendel  RSVP WATCH \u2014 Today is the day Silicon Valley\u2019s top CEOs must tell the House Energy & Commerce Committee if they\u2019ll show up for the Sept. 7 hearing on net neutrality legislation. The invited tech executives \u2014 for Alphabet, Amazon, Facebook and Netflix \u2014 \u201cabsolutely should come in and testify and participate in the process,\u201d said Rep. Ro Khanna, a California Democrat representing part of Silicon Valley. \u201cI hope that many of them will take a strong view for net neutrality and against repealing it because many of the employees and many of the techies in the Valley, they very much believe in net neutrality and keeping the internet open and free and a place of innovation.\u201d It\u2019s the \u201cnext stage for these tech leaders\u201d following other advocacy on federal and state issues on immigration and LGBT rights, he said. \u201cIt would show a humility, it would show a respect for the political process, and it would show how important net neutrality is to free speech and innovation in the 21st century.\u201d   Story Continued Below  \u2014 Republicans are eager to hear from them. \u201cThe tech CEOs should be here,\u201d Rep. Marsha Blackburn (R-Tenn.), who chairs E&C\u2019s telecom panel, told POLITICO. \u201cI think they\u2019ve been talking to everybody but us, so it\u2019s important that they come and talk with us about this. We want the opportunity to hear firsthand from them.\u201d E&C Chairman Greg Walden (R-Ore.) agrees: \u201cWe need to hear from the edge providers, we need to hear from Netflix, we need to hear from the ISPs. It\u2019s time that they had the opportunity to express their views to us that often they\u2019re expressing around the country.\u201d   NEXT UP: FCC REAUTHORIZATION BILL MARKUP? \u2014 House lawmakers may have skipped town Friday for the long August recess, but Blackburn wants her telecom panel to dive into a markup of Republicans\u2019 draft FCC reauthorization bill after Labor Day. \u201cI am hopeful that we\u2019re going to be able to, as soon as we come back, move the reauthorization bill,\u201d Blackburn told POLITICO of a September markup. \u201cGo ahead and move that, get that part of the process behind us, and then move on to a broadband bill. So we\u2019re working through that. I\u2019ll spend a lot of time on that in August.\u201d House Republicans had floated an FCC reauth proposal last Congress but never marked it up. During last week\u2019s FCC oversight hearing, E&C ranking member Frank Pallone (D-N.J.) called the current draft \u201cflawed,\u201d not \u201cserious\u201d and lacking Democratic input.  \u2014 SENATE COMMERCE TO VOTE ON FCC: All three FCC nominees are up for a vote during a Senate Commerce Committee markup on Wednesday when the panel will also consider NTIA Administrator nominee David Redl. A bill examining how the FCC collects data on commercial mobile service and commercial mobile data service, is also up for review.   GOOD MONDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we still want to see The Emoji Movie despite the lukewarm reviews. Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.  Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Email us the details at techcalendar@politicopro.com.  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: The private sector and government must work together to support diversity and expansion of STEAM education, with a special focus on computer science programs. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. More: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  PRIVACY GROUP\u2019S FTC COMPLAINT ABOUT GOOGLE -- The Electronic Privacy Information Center, a privacy watchdog, is filing a complaint with the FTC over how a new system from the tech company tracks users\u2019 shopping behavior. In its complaint, EPIC argues that Google, which rolled out a feature that aims to link the impact of online advertising with users\u2019 brick-and-mortar purchases by analyzing credit card data, needs to be more transparent about how it monitors this information. The group is also calling for the company to offer a clear way for users to opt out of this program. \u201cEPIC requests that the Commission initiate an investigation into Google\u2019s in-store sales tracking algorithm to determine whether it adequately protects the privacy of millions of American consumers,\u201d the group writes.   FIRST IN MT: A HILL BOOST FOR WHITE SPACES -- Rep. Kevin Cramer (R-N.D.) assembled 42 House lawmakers for a letter to the FCC today favoring use of TV white spaces for rural broadband, a plan popularized by Microsoft. The ask: \u201cpreserve at least three, 6 MHz television white spaces [spectrum] channels in every media market.\u201d Cramer secured sign-on from senior Republicans such as House Republican Conference Chairwoman Cathy McMorris Rodgers (Wash.) and Rep. Darrell Issa (Calif.), as well as tech-friendly Democrats including Reps. Peter Welch (Vt.),Suzan DelBene (Wash.) and Anna Eshoo (Calif.). One loud critic is the National Association of Broadcasters, and last week saw skeptical op-eds from former Federal Emergency Management Agency administrator Craig Fugate and Harvard Law School professor Susan Crawford. But these lawmakers, with ties to the Rural Broadband Caucus and leadership, say TV white spaces \u201chave strong potential to revolutionize broadband internet accessibility in rural areas\u201d and create dependendable internet connections that are \u201cextremely cost-effective requiring minimal infrastructure investments.\u201d And don\u2019t forget, a similar letter is likely coming from governors.   THE JOBS ACT AND THE STITCH FIX IPO \u2014 Stitch Fix, an e-commerce company that sends personalized clothing recommendations to users, has confidentially filed for an IPO, a move that was made possible via the 2012 JOBS Act, Recode reports. The legislation enables \u201cemerging growth\u201d firms to confidentially submit registration information including details about financial statements and risk factors to the SEC so as to receive feedback without the public exposure. The SEC recently expanded the scope of this practice to all companies, as part of a move to bolster more IPOs, USA Today reports. Blue Apron\u2019s paperwork also indicated it took advantage of the "emerging growth company" designation created by the JOBS Act when it went public earlier this year.   SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014  \u2014 About that Charter-Sprint merger: Charter isn\u2019t exactly interested in acquiring the wireless carrier, Reuters reports. \u201cSprint proposed a merger with Charter as the wireless carrier seeks an alternative to a deal with T-Mobile that has so far not come to fruition, sources familiar with the matter told Reuters on Friday. Japan's SoftBank Group Corp, which controls Sprint, proposed a complex transaction that would create a new company and be controlled by SoftBank, the sources said.\u201d  \u2014 Some Tesla customers get hands on cheaper Model 3\u2019s: Well, 30 customers (who also happen to be employees) did, at least, The AP reports. The electric vehicle maker rolled out the cars at a company party on Friday and admitted there would be challenges in ramping up production. \u201cWe're going to go through at least six months of manufacturing hell," CEO Elon Musk said. "It's going to be quite a challenge to build this car."  \u2014 Apple takes down VPN apps in China\u2019s app store: \u201cThe Chinese government\u2019s crackdown on the internet continues with the news that Apple has removed all major VPN apps, which help internet users overcome the country\u2019s censorship system, from the App Store in China,\u201d TechCrunch reports. Meanwhile, in Russia: President Vladimir Putin has signed legislation that prohibits the use of VPNs, Reuters reports.   TRANSITIONS -- AT&T announced personnel moves that would take place following its merger with Time Warner. \u201cJohn Stankey, who ran AT&T\u2019s DirecTV division, will supervise integration planning for the merger and lead the Time Warner businesses after the deal closes. \u2026 John Donovan, formerly group president for AT&T Technology, will take over the phone and TV businesses. Lori Lee, who runs global marketing, also will lead AT&T\u2019s international businesses,\u201d per Bloomberg.   QUICK DOWNLOADS  Pulling back the curtain on the hunt for an Uber CEO: Competing interests have made it tough to find consensus on candidates, The New York Times reports.   Twitter\u2019s subscription play: \u201cTwitter has a new business idea: It wants to charge advertisers a monthly fee for the company to handle all of their promoted tweets,\u201d Recode reports.   Honolulu cracks down on texting at crosswalks: The city has passed a bill that would fine residents who are viewing their mobile devices while crossing the street, The Verge reports.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
