aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  \u000a                    Updated 07/28/2017 08:41 AM EDT  With help from Ashley Gold and John Hendel  TECH DODGED A BORDER TAX BULLET \u2014 Some of the biggest tech companies are likely breathing a sigh of relief now that the border-adjustment tax on imports is officially dead, a development that the White House and congressional leaders announced on Thursday. Companies like Apple, HP and Tesla, which rely on global supply chains, could have faced a hefty new tax bill if the border-adjustment proposal became law. The tech industry continues to eye other elements of tax reform like a reduced corporate tax rate. But good luck finding the details of what a future tax package will look like.  Story Continued Below  BEHOLD, A BIPARTISAN BROWSER ACT \u2014 Rep. Marsha Blackburn (R-Tenn.) just scored a victory with her privacy legislation known as the BROWSER Act. Rep. Dan Lipinski (D-Ill.) is signing on as its first Democratic co-sponsor. Blackburn, as you may recall, has struggled to win support from E&C Dems for this measure.   NEW ICPA BILL COMING \u2014 Hot on the heels of the Electronic Communications Privacy Act reintroduction from Sens. Mike Lee (R-Utah) and Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.), Sens. Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), Chris Coons (D-Del.) and Dean Heller (R-Nev.) are due to announce the return of the International Communications Privacy Act, according to a Hill aide. ICPA would provide a legal framework for U.S. law enforcement agencies to obtain electronic communication records of U.S. citizens that are stored overseas, which would include the use of a warrant. Google, BSA | The Software Alliance and SIIA are among those that have voiced their support for the return of the bill.   \u2014 Speaking of ECPA: Lee and Leahy on Thursday unveiled a new version of ECPA, which would require law enforcement to obtain a warrant for Americans\u2019 emails that are more than 180 days old. It would also create a warrant standard for tracking location information, including on cell phones. A previous version of the legislation got bogged down in the Senate last term, after Sen. John Cornyn (R-Texas) added amendments that appeared to give the FBI more leeway for surveillance. Lee also introduced a companion to the House\u2019s Email Privacy Act. Read the new version of ECPA, here.   SELF-DRIVING CAR BILL HEADS TO HOUSE FLOOR \u2014 The first self-driving car bill to move through Congress has officially made its way through committee and is now on its way to the House floor, Pro Transportation\u2019s Tanya Snyder reports. The measure, approved by the House Energy & Commerce committee by a vote of 54-0 on Thursday, \u201cattempts to create a framework for massively expanding the number of vehicles that aren\u2019t equipped with basic safety features like steering wheels and brakes,\u201d she writes \u201cAnd it seeks to curb the extent to which states and localities can limit their reach.\u201d  PAI\u2019S TOUGH CHOICE CONTRABAND CELLPHONES \u2014 FCC Chairman Ajit Pai wants to rid U.S. jails and prisons of cellphones that could be used to enable crimes, but he faces an uneasy balancing act of juggling the interests of the wireless industry and those of prison officials, John reports. Tackling contraband phones is high priority for Pai, who united FCC commissioners in March to spur the commission to look at technological fixes to the problem of illicit phones in correctional facilities. Technology may provide a solution where physically banning them has failed. But wireless companies aren't on board with what prison officials want. Read more here.  GOOD FRIDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we loved this running joke. Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.  Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Email us the details at techcalendar@politicopro.com.  REDDIT TO LAWMAKERS: AMA \u2014 Members of the website\u2019s policy and executive teams are hitting the Hill to build relationships with lawmakers and discuss issues including net neutrality. Reddit co-founder Alexis Ohanian previously told POLITICO he thinks net neutrality will ultimately be addressed through legislation. The visit marks the first time Reddit has made an official company trip to D.C., and follows its hiring of Jessica Ashooh to run policy operations.  AT&T HITS AT VERIZON ON FIRSTNET \u2014 Earlier this week, Verizon called on the FCC to clarify whether states and their business partners would be able to develop their own \u201ccore\u201d networks for FirstNet. AT&T, in a filing to the agency today, slams Verizon\u2019s request. \u201cVerizon is wrong on both the policy and the law, and is woefully late to the debate,\u201d AT&T writes, adding that the FCC has already determined that \u201cthe permissibility of a separate state core are outside the scope of its responsibilities.\u201d AT&T also notes that the Public Safety Spectrum Act \u201csimply does not provide that a state may opt-out and then deploy its own public safety core network.\u201d   \u2014 West Virginia on Thursday became the seventh state to opt in to the national first responder network being built out by AT&T and FirstNet. \u201cMobile broadband access is a critical, life-saving technology that needs to be in the hands of every first responder,\u201d said Sen. Joe Manchin (D-W.Va.).  BILLS, BILLS, BILLS \u2014 Rep. Will Hurd (R-Texas) has introduced his SMART Wall bill, which would use high-tech resources such as sensors, radars, LIDAR, drones and cameras to secure the border with Mexico. Hurd has been using research from Anduril Industries, controversial VR entrepreneur Palmer Luckey\u2019s company. More details here.   SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014  \u2014 Bannon\u2019s reported views on tech giants: \u201cTech companies like Facebook and Google that have become essential elements of 21st century life should be regulated as utilities, top White House adviser Steve Bannon has argued, according to three people who\u2019ve spoken to him about the issue,\u201d The Intercept reports. \u201cBannon\u2019s basic argument, as he has outlined it to people who\u2019ve spoken with him, is that Facebook and Google have become effectively a necessity in contemporary life.\u201d  \u2014 Apple secures a 5G license from FCC: The company received FCC approval for testing millimeter wave technology in locations around its Northern California headquarters, DSLR reports.   \u2014 Google invests in tech training in Africa: The tech company aims to provide online skill training to ten million people in Africa across the next five years, according to CEO Sundar Pichai, Reuters reports. It also intends to offer software development training to 100,000 people living in Nigeria, Kenya and South Africa.   TRANSITIONS \u2014 Yancey Strickler, CEO of Kickstarter, is leaving his role, per VentureBeat.   QUICK DOWNLOADS  Foxconn\u2019s Wisconsin tax incentives: \u201cThe deal with Foxconn [announced by Trump on Wednesday] ... comes with a heavy price tag for Wisconsin taxpayers: $3 billion in state tax credits that dwarf the typical incentive package companies receive from local governments,\u201d The New York Times reports.   More details on Facebook\u2019s subscription plans: \u201cFacebook says it wants to help publishers sell subscriptions. But Facebook says it doesn\u2019t want a piece of the revenue those subscriptions generate, or any of the data involved in the transaction,\u201d Recode reports.   About those Uber rumors: HPE CEO Meg Whitman squashed them with a series of tweets, which noted plainly, \u201cUber\u2019s CEO will not be Meg Whitman.\u201d GE CEO Jeff Immelt is reportedly being considered for the role, The Wall Street Journal reports.   #Sports: Twitter\u2019s 24/7 sports network, \u201cStadium,\u201d is slated to go live in the fall, VentureBeat reports.   It\u2019s the week of tech farewells: Apple announced that it\u2019s discontinuing the iPod Nano and Shuffle, The Verge reports. (Microsoft previously announced the end of Paint, and Adobe is phasing out Flash.)Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
