aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  07/27/2017 10:01 AM EDT  With help from Steven Overly, John Hendel, Margaret Harding McGill and Tanya Snyder  TRUMP TRUMPETS FOXCONN MANUFACTURING PLANT \u2014 President Donald Trump minced no words at a White House ceremony yesterday, saying his administration\u2019s pro-business policies are the chief reason that Foxconn, and its Chairman Terry Gou, decided to open a new manufacturing plant in the U.S. "In other words, if I didn't get elected, he definitely would not be spending $10 billion,\u201d Trump said of Gou. That\u2019s how much the Taiwanese electronics maker plans to invest in the factory, which will initially employ 3,000 workers to build LCD monitors for computers and other electronics, Steven reports.  Story Continued Below  But Foxconn\u2019s decision to locate the facility in Wisconsin is a clear political win for Gov. Scott Walker and House Speaker Paul Ryan, who stood at the president\u2019s side during his remarks. Both Republican politicians played an active role in wooing Foxconn not only to the Badger State, but to Ryan\u2019s own district. That will likely serve him well politically as other factories \u2014 including a massive GM plant \u2014 in his corner of Wisconsin have packed up and moved out in the last decade, leaving voters there with fewer options for employment. \u201cFor southeastern Wisconsin, this is an absolute game changer,\u201d Ryan said yesterday. \u201cIt means more jobs and more security and more prosperity for families. It is another example of how our region is truly a manufacturing powerhouse.\u201d  If the name Foxconn rings a bell, it may be because of a number of reports about how the company as a supplier for Apple has faced scrutiny in the past for poor treatment of Chinese workers and the suicide nets it installed on some buildings after some employees leaped to their deaths.  TECH: #LETTHEMSERVE \u2014 Leaders from the tech community sharply criticized the Trump administration\u2019s move banning transgender service members in the military, making the decision the latest flash point between the industry and the White House, Nancy and Steven report. Facebook executives Mark Zuckerberg and Sheryl Sandberg, Google CEO Sundar Pichai, Apple CEO Tim Cook and Twitter CEO Jack Dorsey are among those who vocalized their opposition to this policy change. "We are indebted to all who serve. Discrimination against anyone holds everyone back. #LetThemServe,\u201d Cook tweeted. Salesforce posted a company statement of support for \u201cequality for all.\u201d Oath, the union of Yahoo and AOL\u2019s online properties, also chimed in with its backing of its LGBTQ workers and diversity.   TRUMP ADMIN REACHING OUT TO TECH ON STEM \u2014 "White House officials including Ivanka Trump have begun an outreach campaign to major technology, business and education leaders including Laurene Powell Jobs and Apple\u2019s Tim Cook for advice on shaping funding approaches to science, technology, engineering and math education in U.S. public schools," Bloomberg reports.   NEW FCC NOMINATIONS WRINKLE \u2014 Senate Commerce has a vote on FCC nominations planned for Aug. 2, that will include two Republicans (FCC Chairman Ajit Pai and General Counsel Brendan Carr) and one Democrat (former Commissioner Jessica Rosenworcel). Also on deck: NTIA administrator-nominee David Redl. But Democrats may want a GOP commitment to set up smooth confirmation for the next Democratic FCC opening, whenever Commissioner Mignon Clyburn departs. In multiple scenarios \u2014 such as not giving Carr a second full term or only confirming Carr and Rosenworcel now \u2014 \u201cCommissioner Clyburn\u2019s replacement could be paired with Carr or Pai,\u201d a Democratic aide said, adding that Thune and Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell want to confirm Pai, Carr and Rosenworcel together.   \u2014 Sen. Ed Markey (D-Mass.) confirmed interest in securing GOP commitment on the next Democratic commissioner confirmation, although said he\u2019s heard nothing from Clyburn on when she may leave. \u201cI want to just make sure that there\u2019s a guarantee, you know, that the next Democrat is in, so we have to work out some kind of formula to guarantee that is a part of whatever\u201d nominations plans are made, Markey told POLITICO. Thune said there\u2019s \u201cbeen no formal engagement\u201d with him yet.    \u2014 The Commerce markup is also slated to include a bill from Sens. Roger Wicker (R-Miss.) and Joe Manchin (D-W.V.) that focuses on developing methodology at the FCC for data collection on commercial mobile service and commercial mobile data service.  SELF-DRIVING CAR MARKUP, ROUND TWO \u2014 The full House Energy and Commerce Committee is due to mark up a bill on self-driving cars that came together yesterday following a period of frenzied negotiations, Pro Transportation\u2019s Tanya Snyder reports. This legislation, which is the first of its kind to move through Congress, would set up distinct roles for federal and state governments for overseeing the deployment of self-driving vehicles, and addresses the issues of preempting state laws and safety exemptions. Read the full text of the legislation, here.   AXING THE FCC\u2019s UHF DISCOUNT \u2014 That\u2019s what House Democrats want to do as part of the Local and Independent TV Protection Act, expected to be introduced today. The FCC reinstated the discount earlier this year. That drew much Democratic pushback and became the regulatory change enabling the Sinclair Broadcast Group/Tribune Media merger. Reps. Jared Huffman (D-Calif.) and David Price (D-N.C.) are lead authors. Other Dem backers: Reps. Anna Eshoo (Calif.), Raul Grijalva (Ariz.), Ro Khanna (Calif.), Jerry McNerney (Calif.), Jamie Raskin (Md.), Jan Schakowsky (Ill.) and Jackie Speier (Calif.). The bill has backing from Free Press, Public Knowledge, the National Hispanic Media Coalition, Common Cause and Consumers Union.   START YOUR ENGINES \u2014 Startup advocacy group Engine hits the Hill today to talk net neutrality with lawmakers on both sides of the aisle, with a focus on members of the House and Senate Commerce Committees. Representatives from startups across the country including CrowdMed, Simply Made Apps, Shapeways, Pearlbend Ventures, Lookfar and MapBox will make the trek to discuss the role that net neutrality plays in enabling their businesses to thrive.   GOOD THURSDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where these dogs are sending us into cuteness overload. Send your pups, tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.  Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Send it our way by emailing the details to techcalendar@politicopro.com.  ASCAP, BMI ESTABLISH MUSIC DATABASE \u2014 The two performing rights groups have announced they\u2019re setting up a searchable database of musical works to provide a reference point for song ownership and licensing, Variety reports. This move comes on the heels of the introduction of a bill from Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner (R-Wis.) that would create a digital database of copyright ownership and licensing information for musical works. The House Judiciary Committee offered its support for ASCAP and BMI\u2019s efforts via Twitter, while the Digital Media Association observed that it underscores the need for the Sensenbrenner legislation.   GOOGLE.ORG\u2019S JACQUELLINE FULLER ON FUTURE OF WORK \u2014 The tech giant\u2019s charitable arm on Wednesday announced a $50 million commitment to "to help people prepare for the changing nature of work." The sum will be invested in various organizations that research and develop tools to enable people to adapt to shifts in the labor market. Google.org President Jacquelline Fuller sat down with reporters for a roundtable following the announcement to discuss these investments and talk about how the organization views its focus moving forward.   On how Google\u2019s own AI efforts could affect the workforce: \u201cWe\u2019re very optimistic about technology, and we think machine learning, in particular, is very promising in terms of boosting productivity. We also want to make sure we are investing in efforts that are helping, make sure that everyone including the most vulnerable workers are able to upscale to meet those changes in work.\u201d  On what\u2019s next: \u201cThe themes where we feel like we can really double down and have an impact are: this concept of lifelong learning, particularly online education. And particularly for those who are most underserved, both in the U.S. and internationally, in developing countries. \u2026 And this idea of economic opportunity, really helping get ahead of that. \u2026 The third piece that cuts across both of them is inclusion.\u201d   MCCARTHY HUDDLES ON VETS AND TECH \u2014 House Majority Leader Kevin McCarthy (R-Calif.) held a roundtable discussing veterans and tech training on Wednesday. Attendees included Reps. Khanna, Kathleen Rice (D-N.Y.) and Steve Knight (R-Calif.). The talk followed passage of the VET TEC Act earlier this week. The group discussed ways to scale tech education opportunities for veterans and build a mentorship community to help veterans transitioning into civilian life. Participants in the roundtable also included: Microsoft\u2019s Danny Chung, the Auto Alliance\u2019s Jonathan Weinberger, the Student Veterans of America\u2019s Jared Lyon and Will Hubbard, Operation Code\u2019s Dave Molina, NS2 Serves\u2019 Laura Carmack, and Marine Corp. veterans Andrew Bailey and Natasha Mulford.   SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014  \u2014 Uber v. Waymo update: \u201cUber's former chief executive, Travis Kalanick, has hired the former top federal prosecutor in San Francisco to represent him ahead of a deposition in a high-profile trade secrets case against Alphabet's Waymo self-driving car unit,\u201d Reuters reports. On the Waymo front, a federal judge has called on Google co-founder Sergey Brin to provide a deposition for the case, Recode reports.   \u2014 Facebook profits stay strong: It now has more than two billion monthly users but has cautioned that revenue growth will likely slow as it reaches the threshold for the number of ads it can show users, The Verge reports.   \u2014 Whitman departs HP board: \u201cHewlett Packard Enterprise chief executive Meg Whitman has left HP's board of directors. Whitman has served as chairman of HP's board since the separation of HP Inc. and Hewlett Packard Enterprise in November 2015,\u201d CNET reports. Whitman is also reportedly on the short list for the Uber CEO position, though \u201can HP rep says she is committed to her job there,\u201d Recode reports.   TRANSITIONS \u2014 Richard Engelman, a former Sprint director of spectrum resources who previously worked as a chief engineer at the FCC, has joined Wiley Rein as a consultant.   SPOTTED \u2014 At the launch of the Creative Thread Foundation, a group dedicated to promoting diversity in media and entertainment: Kimberly Brooks of Fusion TV and Congressional Multicultural Media Caucus Co-Chairs Yvette Clarke (D-N.Y.), Tony Cardenas (D-Calif.), and Judy Chu (D-Calif.); Hispanic Heritage Foundation\u2019s Tony Tijerino and Asian Americans Advancing Justice\u2019s Jiny Kim.   \u2014 Henry Louis Gates, of Fusion TV and the Root, will serve as chair of the nonprofit and other founding members include Amazon, Spotify, AT&T, Disney, CBS, Fox, Entertainment Software Association, NAB, MPAA, NAACP, UnidosUS, National Action Network, National Urban League, National Hispanic Media Coalition, and National Coalition of Asian Pacific Americans.  QUICK DOWNLOADS  \u201cSnowfall\u201d director questions Google\u2019s approach to copyright: During an event on the Hill hosted by CreativeFuture, the co-creator and director of the FX show John Singleton noted, \u201cYou have a huge multibillion dollar corporation trying to destroy copyright (cough) Google,\u201d according to a group spokesman. Google responded to a request for comment with more info on its efforts combating piracy, here.   Seattle\u2019s software job boom: \u201cSeattle is home to more open software jobs than Silicon Valley, accounting for one out of every six postings in the U.S.,\u201d The Seattle Times reports.   1492: Amazon\u2019s healthtech lab: \u201cAmazon has started a secret skunkworks lab dedicated to opportunities in health care, including new areas such as electronic medical records and telemedicine,\u201d CNBC reports.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                       