aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from John Hendel, Nancy Scola, Ashley Gold and Steven Overly  A \u2018BIG, BIG, BIG\u2019 BITE OF THE APPLE \u2014 President Donald Trump told The Wall Street Journal that Apple CEO Tim Cook has committed to building three manufacturing plants in the U.S. Not just any plants, but \u201cbig, big, big\u201d ones. If such factories are in the works, Apple does not appear ready to say so. The company declined to comment. Trump\u2019s thin-on-details remark raises some obvious questions: Where will the factories be located? What will they build? And how many people will they employ? But it could also have policy implications as several companies (Samsung, Toyota, Intel, Ford, etc.) have used investment promises to curry favor with the president. It remains to be seen whether the plans Trump revealed will be tied to Apple\u2019s own goals in Washington \u2014 including its top priority of reducing corporate taxes.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 The Trump-Apple relationship is already a complicated one. On the campaign trail, Trump blasted the company for making products in China \u2014 but since his victory he\u2019s tempered the hot rhetoric. Meanwhile, Cook, like other Silicon Valley heavyweights, is engaged in a delicate dance with the White House. The Apple CEO was spotted dining with Ivanka Trump and Jared Kushner shortly after the inauguration, and though he criticized the president\u2019s decision on the Paris climate accord, Cook joined other tech leaders at the White House last month to discuss government IT. In May, Apple launched a $1 billion fund to invest in U.S. advanced manufacturing companies \u2014 an announcement, many observed, that was likely to please the administration.   VAN DYCK DEPARTS USDS \u2014 Haley Van Dyck, the longtime Obama administration official who helped launch the U.S. Digital Service in 2014, has left that office, OMB confirms. Van Dyck, who once held the formal title of deputy USDS administrator, had quietly stayed on to guide the agency through the start of the Trump presidency, we reported back in March. "Haley's passion for improving digital services for the American people has been second to none," Matt Cutts, the former Google engineer-turned-acting USDS administrator, said in a statement. "Haley had a specific goal of assisting USDS through the administration transition and left when she felt that was completed to the best of her abilities. Although the USDS team is sad to see her go, we're excited to see what's around the corner for Haley and wish her the best."  TODAY: COMMERCE TOP LAWYER NOMINEE ON DECK \u2014 The Senate Commerce Committee holds a confirmation hearing for a slew of Trump nominees, including Peter Davidson, the former Verizon lobbyist who\u2019s up for general counsel at the Commerce Department. As we previously reported, Davidson spent more than ten years leading the telecom giant\u2019s government relations operation and worked for the U.S. Trade Representative during the George W. Bush administration. The Commerce general counsel could play a key role in helping navigate issues around Privacy Shield and spectrum management.  GOOD WEDNESDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we are addicted to Sanrio\u2019s latest. Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.  Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Send it our way by emailing the details to techcalendar@politicopro.com.  A MOMENT FOR NET NEUTRALITY LEGISLATION? \u2014 House Energy and Commerce Chairman Greg Walden (R-Ore.) put a marker down for a Sept. 7 hearing on net neutrality legislation, inviting tech and telecom CEOs, but don\u2019t expect Democrats to jump on board immediately. It\u2019s a \u201ca tremendous idea\u201d but \u201cthe courts are going to need to give some finality to this before we look at legislation,\u201d Rep. Mike Doyle (D-Pa.), the telecom panel\u2019s top Democrat, told POLITICO, referring to the expected legal challenge to FCC Chairman Pai\u2019s net neutrality rollback. Doyle said he doesn\u2019t see \u201cany serious legislative activity this year,\u201d adding, \u201cThis is not even in the talking stages.\u201d   \u2014 But Walden told POLITICO he wants legislation to move this Congress, pointing to a 2015 draft bill he sponsored with Senate Commerce Chairman John Thune (R-S.D.) as a starting point. But that draft banned paid prioritization, which telecom panel Chairman Marsha Blackburn (R-Tenn.) insists should be legal. \u201cIt\u2019s an open question,\u201d Walden said of that internet fast lanes provision, saying he anticipates debate about the pros and cons in September. Lawmakers can find common ground if \u201cwe can get everybody to holster their rhetoric and their politics for a day or two,\u201d he said.  \u2014 Free Press\u2019s Candace Clement, meanwhile, slammed E&C for only inviting CEOs: \u201cWho will represent internet users, innovative startups and independent voices at this hearing? This is an internet hearing without the internet.\u201d Doyle and Rep. Frank Pallone (D-N.J.) agree \u2014 they penned a letter to Walden and Blackburn asking for the committee to invite more witnesses to the September hearing.   WHEELER IN CHARM CITY \u2014 Rep. John Sarbanes (D-Md.) and former FCC Chairman Tom Wheeler are due to make the rounds in Baltimore today, where they\u2019ll push for protection of the net neutrality rules. Sarbanes\u2019 office said the 11 a.m. event will be livestreamed on the congressman\u2019s Facebook page.   SIX DOWN, DOZENS TO GO \u2014 New Jersey becomes the sixth state to opt in to FirstNet, the government\u2019s public safety broadband communications network.   TECH TRAINING FOR VETS BILL PASSES HOUSE \u2014 A modern-day GI bill, which sets up training for veterans in technical fields, passed the House earlier this week. The VET TEC Act, which was introduced by House Majority Leader Kevin McCarthy (R-Calif.) \u201cestablishes a pilot program that allows veterans to attend non-traditional technology programs [like Udacity] that will help them get jobs right after completion.\u201d McCarthy will hold a roundtable this morning to discuss the bill and opportunities to educate veterans as the workforce shifts. Veterans, veteran advocacy organizations, Microsoft, and bipartisan members of Congress are among those due to attend, according to a spokesman.  SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014  \u2014 Musk says Zuckerberg has \u2018limited\u2019 view of AI: OpenAI founder Elon Musk had some tough words for fellow tech leader Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg, TechCrunch reports. In response to a story that chronicled how Zuckerberg called Musk\u2019s warnings about AI \u2018irresponsible,\u2019 Musk hit back with his own critiques. \u201cI've talked to Mark about this. His understanding of the subject is limited,\u201d he tweeted.   \u2014 Google fights Canadian ruling on search results and piracy: Canada\u2019s highest court has ruled that Google must globally remove search results of particular pirated products, and the tech company is pushing back via the U.S. courts system, Wired reports.   \u2014 Uber is working on how it treats drivers: The ride-sharing firm unveiled a series of features aimed at improving its relationship with drivers, NPR reports. Among the updates: a hotline that drivers can use to reach corporate HQ when they need it.   TRANSITIONS \u2014 Kate Tummarello, a policy analyst at the Electronic Frontier Foundation (and former MT scribe), heads to Engine as a policy analyst. \u2026 April Boyd, previously head of Yahoo public policy, is now leading Oath\u2019s global government relations and policy development team, as well as the Oath business and human rights program. Oath is the name of the entity that formed when Verizon acquired Yahoo and combined its online properties with AOL. \u2026 Mlika Carroll, a policy adviser to Sen. Brian Schatz, will join the Internet Association as senior vice president for global government affairs. \u2026 Per POLITICO Influence: Amazon has brought on five new public policy managers in its Washington office: Liz Garner, Dan O'Connor, John Drake, Chris Wilson and Matthew McCardle. Garner came from Merchant Advisory Group, O'Connor from the Computer and Communications Industry Association, and Drake from the American Trucking Associations. Wilson came from 21st Century Fox, and McCardle was at Boeing. \u2026 Rachelle Johnson is now director of government affairs for budget and appropriations for Motorola Solutions. She was previously at the Podesta Group.  QUICK DOWNLOADS  Bezos, Gates have invested in Uber rival: They\u2019re among the techies backing Convoy Inc., a trucking logistics company, Bloomberg reports.   CCIA responds to Qualcomm: The tech group hits back at Qualcomm\u2019s claims that it\u2019s \u201cmisdirecting the International Trade Commission.\u201d  Facebook TV gears up for its debut: The first original shows could air as soon as mid-August, Bloomberg reports.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
