aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from John Hendel  FCC IN THE SPOTLIGHT TODAY \u2014 Amid the ongoing net neutrality debate, the House telecom subcommittee scrutinizes the FCC today at an oversight hearing that will also examine a draft bill reauthorizing the agency. All three commissioners will testify and tipped their hands by releasing testimony in advance. They\u2019ll weigh in on the draft bill, which would make changes including allowing an owner to have a broadcast station and newspaper in the same market and creating an economics and data office at the commission. The House proposal precedes any offering from the Senate, where Commerce Chairman John Thune (R-S.D.) has said he also intends to put forth legislation.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 E&C ranking Democrat Frank Pallone (D-N.J.) will call out his Republican counterparts for unilaterally putting together a reauthorization draft that did not include any Democratic contributions, according to prepared remarks. \u201cThe Republican majority recently surprised us all with a 42-page reauthorization bill that had absolutely no Democratic input,\u201d he\u2019ll say. \u201cThis bill is flawed. It slashes $18 million from the FCC\u2019s budget \u2014 the same agency that is having issues keeping its website up and running. This is not serious legislation.\u201d  \u2014 FCC Chairman Ajit Pai is expected to praise the reauthorization in his testimony and call out tenets of the bill that address spectrum payment policies and post-incentive auction repacking. Republican FCC Commissioner Mike O'Rielly also plans to lend "strong support" for the GOP draft. But he will also urge Congress to go further and include several other changes to commission process.  \u2014 Meanwhile, Democratic commissioner Mignon Clyburn will focus on preserving Title II reclassification of ISPs and the need to modernize the Lifeline program in her remarks.  ANTITRUST TALKS COMMENCE ON AT&T-TIME WARNER \u2014 Discussion has begun between U.S. antitrust officials and representatives from AT&T and Time Warner about conditions that would enable the $85 billion merger to go through, Bloomberg reports. While the merger is a vertical one \u2014 a category that\u2019s posed fewer antitrust challenges in the past \u2014 many media groups have argued that AT&T\u2019s ownership of content companies like CNN and HBO could lead the ISP to prioritize them. Democrats have also raised fears about the harm this merger could cause users by reducing competition and raising costs. Of late, there have been additional questions about the White House using this deal as leverage over CNN, following criticism from President Donald Trump of the news organization. Time Warner CEO Jeff Bewkes has dispelled such concerns and has plans to leave his role if the merger is approved, The New York Times reports.   GOOD TUESDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we challenge you to spot the difference. Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.  Got an event for MT\u2019s tech calendar? Send it our way by emailing the details to techcalendar@politicopro.com.  TRUMP ACCUSES WAPO OF \u2018LOBBYING\u2019 FOR AMAZON \u2014 Trump\u2019s tweets targeting both The Washington Post and Amazon continued on Monday. The tweets appeared to allege that the publication was \u2018lobbying\u2019 for the e-commerce company on the issue of taxes. \u201cSo many stories about me in the @washingtonpost are Fake News. They are as bad as ratings challenged @CNN. Lobbyist for Amazon and taxes?,\u201d one tweet read. These tweets coincide with other criticism that Trump has leveled against both companies. He has previously critiqued The Post\u2019s coverage and claimed that the publication is being used to help Amazon reduce its online taxes. Though the two entities are both linked to Jeff Bezos, they are separate from one another. Interestingly, among its lobbying hires this past year, Amazon has brought on several Trump campaign and transition associates including Brian Ballard and Dan McFaul of Ballard Partners and Robert Wasinger of McGuireWoods.   VERIZON\u2019S FIRSTNET STATE COMMENTS \u2014 While AT&T secured the contract for the FirstNet buildout earlier this year, competitors including Verizon are emphasizing the need for choice on state plans. \u201cA key aspect of the FirstNet framework established by Congress is ensuring that states have options for how they participate in that network,\u201d said Will Johnson, Verizon SVP of federal regulatory and legal affairs, in a statement about a recent filing to the FCC. \u201cVerizon\u2019s letter to the FCC is designed to respond to the needs of our public safety customers and to present states with viable opportunities to choose their own network partners and their own network configurations, as Congress envisioned.\u201d  NOT SO FAST \u2014 Rep. Andy Biggs (R-Ariz.) was seeking co-sponsors last week for a House companion to the Protecting Internet Freedom Act, sponsored by Sen. Mike Lee (R-Utah). But a Biggs spokesman told POLITICO plans changed and that no bill is forthcoming. The GOP freshman instead will bring up his support for such legislation at his next so-called \u201cFreedom Fridays\u201d session, which spotlight regulations Biggs judges unconstitutional. No word on just why Biggs changed his tune. Rep. Marsha Blackburn (R-Tenn.), for what it\u2019s worth, stressed Monday afternoon at the Brookings Institution that she wants a House Energy and Commerce net neutrality bill negotiated with Democrats.   \u2014 E&C legislative priorities, per Blackburn: next-gen 911, media ownership, encryption and privacy as well as FCC reauthorization. Shortly after FCC reauth, E&C will turn to NTIA reauthorization legislation, Blackburn said. She also insisted that contrary to a New York Times report, the administration remains focused on an infrastructure package.   DEMS TO TACKLE INTERNET ACCESS \u2014 The Democrats\u2019 new economic agenda takes aim at companies for consolidation and market concentration, but that\u2019s not the only tech and telecom-related item on its list. Still to come, the Democrats intend to roll out plans that ramp up high-speed internet access across the country, according to a release from Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer\u2019s office.   SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014  \u2014 What\u2019s going on at Snopes? The Atlantic has the full story behind the competing interests that have led the fact-checking website to start a Kickstarter to keep the lights on.   \u2014 Facebook\u2019s latest acquisition takes on piracy: The tech giant has purchased Source3, a startup that identifies intellectual property that\u2019s been shared sans permissions, Recode reports.   \u2014 Spotify and Warner Music close to a licensing deal: As the music streaming service gears up for its IPO, it could soon check one of the boxes that it needs to go public, Reuters reports. Spotify and Warner Music may ink a licensing agreement by September, which is a key royalty deal the streaming service has been angling for.  MEANWHILE, IN EUROPE\u2014   \u2014 EU scrutinizes tech giants\u2019 user terms: \u201cEuropean Union authorities have increased pressure on Facebook, Google and Twitter to amend their user terms to bring them in line with EU law after proposals submitted by the tech giants were considered insufficient,\u201d Reuters reports. \u201cThe European Commission and consumer protection authorities in the bloc wrote to the three companies in June, asking them to improve their proposed changes to user terms by the end of September.\u201d  SPOTTED: At TechFreedom\u2019s opening reception for its Back to the Future of Policy summit at the CTA Innovation House last night -- Berin Szoka and Austin Carson, TechFreedom; The Hon. Chris Cox; Katie Barr, Glen Echo Group; Nathan Leamer, FCC; Kevin Bankston, OTI; Jesse Blumenthal, CKI; Michael Hayes, Jamie Boone and Maya Sharma, CTA; Nuala O'Connor, CDT; Jeff Weiand, Whip Scalise; Alex Kreilein, SecureSet; Richard Seiersen, Twilio; Hugh Gamble and Danielle Gilliam-Moore, Salesforce; Alex Wirth, Quorum; Rachel Wolbers, Engine; Charles McCray, Amazon; Raj Bharwani and Sarah Jorgenson, House Science Research and Technology Subcommittee; Steve DelBianco, NetChoice; Tom Struble, R Street Institute; Matthew Kiessling, Travel Tech; Aya Kiy, Cognizant; Tommy Leander, Rep. David Schweikert; Bijan Madhani, CCIA; Christopher Morris, Threat Track; Troy Stock, OGR IT Subcommittee; Jimmy Ward, Rep. Liz Cheney (R-Wy.). Fitting with the theme, some of the group posed with a DeLorean at the event.   The think tank is holding its first policy summit today, which will include discussion with Rep. Stephanie Murphy (D-Fla.) and a panel featuring staff from the offices of Rep. Jim Langevin (D-R.I.) and Sen. Cory Gardner (R-Colo.). More info here.   TRANSITIONS \u2014 Sundar Pichai, Google\u2019s CEO, has joined parent company Alphabet\u2019s board of directors, per The Verge. \u2026 David Nagel, former CTO of AT&T and SVP for Research and Development at Apple and current General Partner at Fort Ventures, is joining the RapidSOS Advisory Board.   QUICK DOWNLOADS  Qualcomm hits back at CCIA: It responded to critiques of an import ban on certain iPhones that the company has previously called for, Reuters reports.   Roombas can gather data as well as crumbs: And the machine\u2019s creators intend to sell it as part of their business strategy, Reuters reports.   It\u2019s been a good run, Microsoft Paint: After 32 years, the tech company is scrapping the nostalgia-inducing graphics program, The Guardian reports.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
