aV \u000a            By LI ZHOU  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Nancy Scola, Steven Overly and John Hendel  DEMS "BETTER DEAL" TARGETS TECH, TELECOM \u2014 The economic agenda being released by Democratic congressional leaders Chuck Schumer and Nancy Pelosi during a swing through Virginia today includes a rethinking of the country's antitrust laws -- an overhaul that would have major implications for everything from cable ISPs to the country's most successful internet companies. The four-page "Cracking down on corporate monopolies" doc, posted by Axios, highlights telecom as one of the five prime targeted industries: "[T]he market for those services is so concentrated that consumers rarely have any meaningful choice of provider, and prices are high enough to be prohibitive for many." The proposed AT&T-Time Warner merger would "only enable the resulting behemoths to promote their own programming, unfairly discriminate against other distributers [sic] and their ability to offer highly desired content."  Story Continued Below  The Dems' antitrust proposal would, too, upend how regulators treat the country's biggest data-driven companies -- i.e. much of Silicon Valley. "Merger standards must explicitly consider the ways in which control of consumer data can be used to stifle competition or jeopardize consumer privacy," Schumer, Pelosi and co. say. Given that the party's new agenda is meant to reconnect Democrats with what a wide swath of citizens are thinking and feeling, this antitrust plank is a sign the left has judged that Americans today are unsettled by Big Tech and Big Telecom.   BROADBAND INFRASTRUCTURE ON SLOW TRACK \u2014 The Trump administration\u2019s grand infrastructure plans \u2014 which include broadband buildout \u2014 are \u201cfast becoming an afterthought\u201d amid a pileup of other legislative priorities like the debt ceiling, tax reform and healthcare, The New York Times reports. Here\u2019s how the Times describes the \u201cbroad outlines\u201d of the developing proposal: \u201cThe plan would include \u2018massive permit reform\u2019 to cut approval times on major projects to two years or less, from 10; loans and grants to improve rural infrastructure; and funding for \u2018transformative projects,\u2019 like broadband and power grid improvements.\u201d  SCARAMUCCI DRAWS LESSON FROM DAVE EGGERS \u2014 In his first spin at the podium on Friday, new White House Communications Director Anthony Scaramucci cited a 2013 Dave Eggers novel about life inside a Google-and-Facebook-esque tech company to argue against giving reporters an omniscient read on what goes on inside the White House. "On some of this stuff, it's unnecessary to go into that granular detail," said Scaramucci. "It's almost like the book "The Circle,\u201d where you're wearing, like, a police camera on you when you're having conversations. I don't think that's fair to the president." The book \u2014 made into an Emma Watson-Tom Hanks film earlier this year \u2014 got mixed reviews for its dystopian depiction of Silicon Valley. But it looks like it has at least one close reader among senior White House staff.   Lest you think that's the new White House comms director's sole claim to geekiness, know that, in the introduction of one of Scaramucci's own books, entrepreneur Peter Diamandis writes that, "in September 2014, Anthony attended the Executive Program of Singularity University (SU), the Silicon Valley-based institution focused on exponential technologies that I co-founded with artificial intelligence legend (and Google\u2019s Chief Innovation Officer), Ray Kurzweil."   GOOD MONDAY MORNING and welcome to Morning Tech, where we are cracking up at this action movie tag team. Send your tech and telecom tips to lzhou@politico.com and @liszhou. Catch the rest of the team\u2019s contact info after Quick Downloads.  THE WEEK AHEAD IN CONGRESS \u2014 The FCC gang heads to the Hill this Tuesday for an oversight hearing before the House telecom subcommittee. \u2026 The Senate Commerce Committee holds another confirmation hearing Wednesday for a slew of Trump nominees, including Peter Davidson, who\u2019s up for Commerce Department general counsel.   TRUMP MAKES ANOTHER DIG AT \u2018AMAZON WASHINGTON POST\u2019 \u2014 In one of his latest tweets targeting media companies, Trump once again hit at the "Amazon Washington Post" \u2014 two separate entities which he\u2019s taken to criticizing as one body, likely because they are both linked to billionaire Jeff Bezos. \u201cIt's hard to read the Failing New York Times or the Amazon Washington Post because every story/opinion, even if should be positive, is bad!\u201d Trump wrote on Sunday evening. He has also tweeted in the past accusations that Bezos was leveraging The Washington Post to reduce Amazon\u2019s taxes.   GRILLING (AND HEALTHCARE TALK) WITH ZUCK \u2014 Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg decided to go live on Sunday and share some afternoon grilling with his followers \u2014 along with a few of his ideas on issues including healthcare. \u201cYou hear a lot in the social debates of today around healthcare. I think it\u2019s really important that we serve every person and that every person has the healthcare they need,\u201d he said. \u201cBut, one of the big issues in doing this is that it\u2019s really expensive today, because we don\u2019t have cures and preventions for all these diseases.\u201d Zuckerberg emphasized that bolstering investment in the work of organizations like the National Institutes of Health and making more long-term research investments could help society get closer to that goal and ultimately cut down on the number of people who get sick. He also talked about the need for a strong social safety net and STEM education among the myriad subjects that came up during the livestream. Watch the full discussion, here.  IA ADDS LOBBYING MUSCLE \u2014 The Internet Association has enlisted four lobbyists from S-3 Group to work on patent reform, copyright and intellectual property matters, including intermediary liability. Those issues aren\u2019t new to IA\u2019s members like Google, Facebook and Amazon, but they\u2019ve taken on new urgency as digital trade objectives as NAFTA 2.0 negotiations begin. Lobbyists listed in the registration filing are Mike Ference and Rob Collins \u2014 who both worked for former Majority Leader Eric Cantor \u2014 as well as ex-Capitol Hill staffers Kate Dickens and Todd Wooten.   VMWARE\u2019s 5G PLAY \u2014 An executive for the Silicon Valley-based cloud computing subsidiary of Dell Technologies tells POLITICO that telecom companies will need to pick up the pace for 5G, with the next generation of mobile phones set to go live within the next two to three years. \u201cA challenge here is that the pace of transformation needs to follow the pace of innovation in the telecom industry,\u201d VMware Executive Vice President Shekar Ayyar said in an interview during a recent Washington visit. \u201cHistorically that\u2019s not been the case.\u201d VMware is pushing virtualization to help big wireless companies process all the data of the high-bandwidth future connectivity. \u201c5G is a technology that is otherwise largely going to be useless without the benefit of virtualization coupled at the two ends of that spectrum,\u201d he said, adding that his company along with Microsoft and Cisco will be seeking partnerships with internet service providers.  SILICON VALLEY MUST-READS \u2014  \u2014 Newsmax presses for FCC delay on Sinclair-Tribune: \u201cNewsmax Media wants federal regulators to slow their review of Sinclair Broadcast Group\u2019s proposed $3.9 billion purchase of Tribune Media, saying the deal raises concerns about media concentration,\u201d Bloomberg reports. \u201c\u2018I am calling for delay,\u2019 Christopher Ruddy, chief executive officer of Newsmax, a conservative outlet with a 24-hour cable news channel, said in an interview. \u2018I think it needs more vetting.\u2019\u201d  \u2014 China\u2019s AI ambitions: \u201cThe country laid out a development plan on Thursday to become the world leader in A.I. by 2030, aiming to surpass its rivals technologically and build a domestic industry worth almost $150 billion,\u201d The New York Times reports. \u201cReleased by the State Council, the policy is a statement of intent from the top rungs of China\u2019s government: The world\u2019s second-largest economy will be investing heavily to ensure its companies, government and military leap to the front of the pack in a technology many think will one day form the basis of computing.\u201d  \u2014 U.K. tightens up drone rules: Government officials are rolling out a policy requiring drone registrations and safety tests by those who wish to use them, Engadget reports.   TRANSITIONS \u2014 Aditya Agarwal, CTO of DropBox, is leaving the company.   QUICK DOWNLOADS  Scaramucci deleting old tweets: The White House comms director acknowledged he\u2019s cleaning out his Twitter account, as reports surfaced of older tweets that criticized his now-boss, President Trump.  Are tech companies turning into monopolies? Some economists seem to think they could be, Bloomberg Businessweek reports.  Tech theater: The latest in homages to Apple founder Steve Jobs\u2019 life and work is an opera that debuted in Santa Fe, The Guardian reports.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Eric Engleman (eengleman@politico.com, @ericengleman), Angela Greiling Keane (agreilingkeane@politico.com, @agreilingkeane), Nancy Scola (nscola@politico.com, @nancyscola), Margaret Harding McGill (mmcgill@politico.com, @margarethmcgill), Ashley Gold (agold@politico.com, @ashleyrgold), Steven Overly (soverly@politico.com, @stevenoverly), John Hendel (jhendel@politico.com, @JohnHendel) and Li Zhou (lzhou@politico.com, @liszhou)  ** A message from the Intuit Tax and Financial Center: Across the country, there is a growing \u2013 and overdue \u2013 awareness of the need to increase our focus on STEAM education, but a greater focus on computer science programs is needed. Successfully increasing STEAM education in the computer science field demands a partnership between higher education, the private sector and government. Educational institutions must expand their computer science offerings to help educate a new swath of students who will be the skilled workers of tomorrow. This investment in our future workers will provide American companies with the skilled workers they need to continue leading the way in technological innovations. Read more: http://bit.ly/2v6FiFX **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
