aV \u000a            By BEN WHITE and AUBREE ELIZA WEAVER  08/01/2017 08:00 AM EDT  BYE, BYE MOOCH \u2014 Well that was quick! We told you Monday that Anthony Scaramucci was is in deep, deep trouble. Not so much because of what he said about Reince Priebus and Steve Bannon but because the reaction to it was so strongly negative and drove President Donald Trump out of the spotlight, usually a death sentence. So it\u2019s not surprising that Trump put up no resistance when new chief of staff John Kelly, a retired Marine general, made his first order of business showing Mooch the door.   What we don\u2019t know for sure at this point: Whether Scaramucci will get his Ex-Im Bank job back. All Sarah Huckabee Sanders said was Mooch doesn\u2019t have the job \u201cat this time.\u201d Because if Scaramucci doesn\u2019t get the job back, he loses any shot at tax deferral for his sale of SkyBridge. HNA said Monday that the sale remains on track to close. But keep your eyes on that. Scaramucci did not return MM\u2019s calls and texts for comment on his status.   Story Continued Below  One source close to the Ex-Im bank said of Scaramucci coming back: \u201cLikely but not confirmed.\u201d   THE MOOCH\u2019s WILD RIDE via POLITICO\u2019s Josh Dawsey, Annie Karni, and Tara Palmeri: \u201cBy late in the weekend, Scaramucci knew his job could be in jeopardy. One person who spoke to Scaramucci before he showed up to work Monday said he was concerned about his job security but continued to think the New Yorker comments might blow over and his job might be saved, this person said. He was planning to announce communications hires soon\u201d Read more.   NOT GONNA BE MISSED \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Steven Shepherd: \u201cVoters won\u2019t miss Anthony Scaramucci \u2026 In his brief tenure he made a mostly negative impression, according to a new POLITICO/Morning Consult poll conducted last Thursday through Saturday\u201d Read more.   IS THE HARD PIVOT FINALLY HERE? \u2014 White House legislative director Marc Short on Monday laid out yet another super ambitious timetable for tax reform at a Koch Brothers network event, saying a bill would be introduced at the beginning of September, move through the House in October and the Senate in November. Meanwhile, Senate Republicans made clear they have no plans to try again to repeal Obamacare, which would theoretically make Short\u2019s timetable possible. But \u2026   There are the small matters of funding the government in September and raising the debt limit by October. Not to mention passing budget resolutions to set up a reconciliation vehicle for tax reform. And then there are the remaining issues to be resolved on taxes including the pass-through rate, expensing, the corporate and individual rate levels and the elimination of fiercely guarded deductions. Not easy. Not at all easy.   One senior administration official working on tax reform said of Short\u2019s timetable: \u201cHope springs eternal.\u201d   One senior DC lobbyist on the timetable: \u201cProbably not doable. But not impossible. All the dominos would need to fall perfectly.\u201d   KUDLOW MORE SANGUINE \u2014 MM spoke with informal Trump adviser Larry Kudlow about the timetable: \u201cI think it\u2019s a good very good schedule. I think they have to decide whether to go big or small, whether to do the entire package including individual rates or skinny it down to just business rates and maybe increase the standard deduction. But they will figure that all out pretty fast \u2026   On if they don\u2019t do individual rates: \u201cBusiness taxes include pass-throughs that are often small businesses so they have to make that case. They have to make the cast that corporate tax cuts in general, the benefits are 70 percent to wage earners \u2026 You have to make the middle class part of this.\u201d   On making the sale: \u201cThe good news is they are going to sell it on the road. The president may do an Oval Office speech to the nation on it. The White House is much more prepared for a tax discussion than they were six months ago for a health care discussion. The spadework has been done and everyone is much more conversant on this. There are some issues to be resolved but they know their stuff.\u201d   NOT SO HOT ON PASS-THROUGH RATE CUT \u2014 American Bridge\u2019s Andrew Bates: \u201cNothing says 'populism' like a Treasury secretary from Goldman Sachs, who reports to an NEC director from Goldman Sachs, promising to crisscross the country with a Koch Brothers organization to sell a massive, veiled tax cut for the wealthiest Americans. This tax plan is shaping up to be a scam that'll rig the economy for the rich at everyone else's expense.\u201d   SO LONG O\u2019CARE REPEAL? \u2014 Per Reuters, Finance Committee Chair Orrin Hatch \u201csaid on Monday that senators for now are too divided to keep working on healthcare overhaul legislation and that he and other senior Republicans will take that message to the White House\u201d   And per POLITICO\u2019s Burgess Everett and Jennifer Haberkorn: \u201cSenate Republicans have no plans to revive their party-line attempts to repeal Obamacare this summer, despite \u2026 Trump\u2019s increasing frustration over the chamber\u2019s failed attempts last week to gut the law. \u2026   \u201cPrivately, Republican aides said there was essentially no chance that McConnell will take another shot at repealing Obamacare soon. On Monday, there was discussion among Senate staffers of a \u2018hard pivot to tax reform,\u2019 one Senate aide said.\u201d Read more.   U.S. SANCTIONS VENEZUELA \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Zachary Warmbrodt: \u201cThe Treasury Department announced \u2026 it is targeting Venezuelan President Nicols Maduro with sanctions, accusing him of widespread human rights abuses. Treasury said in a release that all of Maduro's assets subject to U.S. jurisdiction were frozen and that U.S. persons were prohibited from dealing with him\u201d Read more.   OOPS \u2014 An MM source passes along Treasury\u2019s YouTube page which remains \u2026 all videos from the Obama administration.   GOOD TUESDAY MORNING \u2014 Welcome to the dog days of August! Email me on bwhite@politico.com and follow me on Twitter @morningmoneyben. Email Aubree Eliza Weaver on aweaver@politico.com and follow her on Twitter @AubreeEWeaver.  THIS MORNING ON POLITICO PRO FINANCIAL SERVICES \u2014 Lorraine Woellert on Rep. Jeb Hensarling\u2019s request for an investigation into whether CFPB Director Richard Cordray violated a ban on political activity by federal employees. To get Morning Money every day before 6 a.m., please contact Pro Services at (703) 341-4600 or info@politicopro.com.  DRIVING THE DAY \u2014 Trump keeps up the tax reform push at an event this afternoon with small businesses \u2026 Senate Finance at 10:00 a.m. holds a hearing on \u201cAmerica's Affordable Housing Crisis: Challenges and Solutions\u201d \u2026 FHFA Director Watt speaks at 7:30 p.m. to the NAREB Annual Convention in New Orleans.  MORE ON McWILLIAMS FOR FDIC \u2014 Cowen\u2019s Jaret Seiberg: \u201cThis should be broadly positive for banks by providing the missing cog needed to advance regulatory relief proposals next year. If there is downside, it could be for the biggest banks as we suspect [Jelena] McWilliams will be a supporter of leverage capital rather than risk-based capital\u201d   HENSARLING PUSHES CORDRAY PROBE \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Lorraine Woellert: \u201cHouse Financial Services Chairman Jeb Hensarling (R-Texas) has asked for an investigation into whether CFPB Director Richard Cordray violated a ban on political activity by federal employees.  \u201cCordray might be weighing a run for governor in his home state of Ohio next year, a move that would require him to leave his post at the watchdog agency before his term expires. Cordray has not publicly stated his intention, and his bureau continues to publish rules and take enforcement actions\u201d Read more.   MNUCHIN: RAISE DEBT LIMIT BY SEPT. 29 \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Zachary Warmbrodt: \u201cTreasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin told House and Senate leadership today that it's \u2018critical\u2019 for Congress to increase the nation's borrowing authority by Sept. 29. \u2018I urge Congress to act promptly on this important matter,\u2019 Mnuchin said in a letter.  WHAT IF TRUMP FIRED CORDRAY \u2014 Cowen\u2019s Jaret Seiberg: \u201cWe believe there would be a strong Democratic backlash if \u2026 Trump fired Richard Cordray as CFPB director. This backlash may make it impossible for Democrats to agree to even common sense changes to banking rules as part of the year-end spending bills. It also would provide little immediate relief given the time needed to confirm a Trump nominee.\u201d   WALL STREET LIVID OVER WELLS FARGO\u2019S LATEST SCANDAL \u2014 CNBC\u2019s Tae Kim: \u201cAnalysts are angry over the latest Wells Fargo scandal where hundreds of thousands of the bank's customers were overcharged. Wells Fargo shares fell 2.6 percent Friday after The New York Times first reported the news. The stock closed 1.2 percent higher Monday, meanwhile.  \u201cThe article cited a 60-page internal report, which revealed more than 800,000 of Wells Fargo's auto loan customers were charged for car insurance they did not need. Wells Fargo estimated the mistaken auto insurance sales would cost the bank $80 million in damages. Piper Jaffray said the true cost is likely understated.\u201d Read more.  INVESTORS DITCHING TECH STOCKS \u2014 Bloomberg\u2019s Luke Kawa: \u201cPigs get fat, hogs get slaughtered. Such a risk-averse adage appears to be front of mind for investors, who fled high-flying technology names at the fastest pace in nearly a decade last week. Outflows from PowerShares QQQ Trust Series 1, which tracks the Nasdaq 100 Index topped $3.7 billion for the five sessions ending July 28, the most since early November 2007\u201d Read more.  DOLLAR\u2019S FALL THREATENS FOREIGN STOCK MARKETS \u2014 WSJ\u2019s Riva Gold and Mike Bird: \u201cA surprise fall in the U.S. dollar is taking the fizz out of international stock markets and prompting investors to damp overseas expectations for the months ahead.  \u201cEuropean and Japanese benchmarks \u2014 which were among the world\u2019s best performers in the spring \u2014 have lagged behind the S&P 500 since the dollar fully erased its postelection rally two months ago. Analysts are cutting their earnings forecasts for companies in these regions as the dollar\u2019s unexpected drop has upended more optimistic projections.\u201d Read more.  PENDING HOME SALES RISE \u2014 Reuters\u2019 Lucia Mutikani: \u201cContracts to buy previously owned U.S. homes rebounded in June after three straight monthly declines, but the housing market remained constrained by a shortage of properties available for sale. Other data on Monday showed that factory activity in the Midwest slowed this month after hitting a three-year high in June, with manufacturers reporting declining orders\u201d Read more.  APPLE + INFLATION = BIG DEAL FOR MARKETS \u2014 CNBC\u2019s Patti Domm: \u201cAugust trading kicks off Tuesday on what could be one of the more important market days of the summer. The PCE inflation data report, which is closely watched by the Fed and a key to its decisions on interest rates, leads a series of major economic reports, including personal income and spending, and car sales.  \u201cBefore the bell, there are dozens of earnings reports, from companies such as Pfizer and Under Armour, but the market is really waiting for Apple earnings after the bell. Apple is expected to report adjusted earnings of $1.57 per share, a nearly 11 percent gain, on a six percent jump in revenue to $44.89 billion in the June quarter, according to analyst-consensus estimates from Thomson Reuters.\u201d Read more.  GREENSPAN: NO BUBBLE IN STOCKS \u2014 Bloomberg\u2019s Oliver Renick and Liz McCormick: \u201cEquity bears hunting for excess in the stock market might be better off worrying about bond prices, Alan Greenspan says. That\u2019s where the actual bubble is, and when it pops, it\u2019ll be bad for everyone.  \u201c\u2019By any measure, real long-term interest rates are much too low and therefore unsustainable,\u2019 the former Federal Reserve chairman said in an interview. \u2018When they move higher they are likely to move reasonably fast. We are experiencing a bubble, not in stock prices but in bond prices. This is not discounted in the marketplace.\u2019\u201d Read more.  WORLD BANK\u2019S EXPANDING REMIT SPARKS DEBATE \u2014 FT\u2019s Kate Allen: \u201cThe World Bank is best known as a lender to emerging economies, but what is less widely appreciated is its substantial role as an asset manager \u2014 just one part of a much broader remit it has adopted in recent years.  \u201cNow, as it marks this month the 70th anniversary of its first loan, the institution finds its expanding operation attracting both praise and criticism. The bank, which was set up to fund postwar reconstruction in Europe, handles $184bn of assets for 65 clients including sovereign wealth funds, pension funds and central banks and manages a $567bn derivatives portfolio.\u201d Read more.  LATE CREDIT CARD PAYMENTS STOKE FEARS FOR BANKS \u2014 WSJ\u2019s AnnaMaria Andriotis: \u201cCredit-card losses are mounting, a reversal from a six-year trend that could be a warning sign for markets and the broader economy.  \u201cThe average net charge-off rate for large U.S. card issuers \u2014 the percentage of outstanding debt that issuers write off as a loss \u2014 increased to 3.29 percent in the second quarter, its highest level in four years, according to Fitch Ratings.\u201d Read more.  ALSO FOR YOUR RADAR \u2014   BANKING IN SAMOA \u2014 American Banker\u2019s Rob Blackwell emails: \u201cI wrote a story about banking in American Samoa. It\u2019s more complicated than it might seem. The only U.S.-based institution pulled out three years ago, and the island\u2019s leaders have struggled to form their own institution.\u201d Read the piece.   FOXCONN\u2019S SWEET WISCONSIN DEAL \u2014 IBT\u2019s David Sirota and Jay Cassano: \u201cApple supplier Foxconn has in recent years been accused of poisoning waterways near its facilities in China. Now Republican Gov. Scott Walker of Wisconsin is not only proposing to give the company a $3 billion taxpayer subsidy, his administration has also quietly slipped language into a bill that would exempt the Taiwanese conglomerate from state environmental protection laws.\u201d Read more.   Ben White is POLITICO Pro's chief economic correspondent and author of the \u201cMorning Money\u201d column covering the nexus of finance and public policy.  Prior to joining POLITICO in the fall of 2009, Mr. White served as a Wall Street reporter for the New York Times, where he shared a Society of Business Editors and Writers award for breaking news coverage of the financial crisis.  From 2005 to 2007, White was Wall Street correspondent and U.S. Banking Editor at the Financial Times.  White worked at the Washington Post for nine years before joining the FT. He served as national political researcher and research assistant to columnist David S. Broder and later as Wall Street correspondent.  White, a 1994 graduate of Kenyon College, has two sons and lives in New York City.  Aubree Eliza Weaver is a Web producer for POLITICO Pro. She graduated from Le Moyne College in her hometown of Syracuse, N.Y., where she was the editor-in-chief of her school\u2019s newspaper, The Dolphin; co-hosted a political segment on the school\u2019s news station, LCTV; and worked as a photography assistant in the Visual Arts department. As a student, Weaver interned with various communications organizations, including the publicity department of Regnery Publishing and serving as a news broadcast intern at Time Warner Cable\u2019s Syracuse affiliate, YNN.  Immediately following her graduation in May 2013, Weaver moved to D.C. to work as a summer program adviser for The Fund for American Studies\u2019 Institute on Political Journalism, an educational nonprofit that offers courses, internships, lecture series and other opportunities for college students and recent grads. She was a student in the program in the summer of 2011, when she first fell in love with D.C.  In her free time, Weaver loves to read and write (as all journalists do), play guitar until her fingers are numb, drink more coffee than she\u2019d care to admit, and spend time with her family.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
