aV \u000a            By VICTORIA GUIDA and AUBREE ELIZA WEAVER  07/28/2017 08:24 AM EDT  QUARTERLY GDP NUMBERS DAY \u2014 If 3 percent economic growth is the ultimate measure of success of the Trump administration, the White House may get a small taste of victory today when second-quarter GDP numbers are released. Actually, economists are expecting the economy to show just under 3 percent growth, but that may be enough for the White House to claim it\u2019s making progress in its pledge to push the country beyond the anemic growth of the Obama years.  The Atlanta Fed\u2019s GDP Now estimate sets an expectation of 2.8 percent, which would still be twice as fast as the first quarter\u2019s expansion. Whether that growth can be sustained through the year is open to question.  Story Continued Below  MUFG Union Bank's Chris Rupkey: \u201cNet, net, the economy still has legs in this long expansion from the end of the recession if [Thursday\u2019s] data on exported goods and durable goods orders are to be believed. Business spending on equipment is still rising at a good clip in the second quarter, and exports of capital goods in June are up sharply. Don\u2019t count this economy out yet is the message of today's economic news as this expansion could make a run at the longest upturn in the economy\u2019s fortunes in modern economic history looking back to the 70s. The only risk we see is that the economy is running out of workers to do the heavy lifting and make us grow with jobless claims hovering just above the lowest levels in decades. The economy's growth profile and outlook for continued expansion is better than you think.\u201d  ICYMI: Brookings Institution\u2019s Aaron Klein on how to achieve economic growth: \u201cWhat will improve economic growth? There are three I\u2019s that can do this: immigration, infrastructure, and investment. However, their ability to bring us up to 3% growth is both doubtful and irrelevant.\u201d Full piece here.  JUST IN: CEOs TO THROW WEIGHT BEHIND TAX REFORM \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Nancy Cook: \u201cThe Business Roundtable is embarking on a multi-million-dollar national TV and radio campaign, beginning in early August, to give tax reform extra momentum over the congressional recess. Done in cooperation with White House, Treasury, and House and Senate leadership, this is BRT\u2019s effort to cast a potential tax overhaul as a once-in-a-generation opportunity.  \u201c\u2018Members of Congress will hear from business leaders \u2014 and more importantly, their constituents \u2014 that tax reform is the single best way to increase investment in U.S. communities, create good jobs and promote a stronger economy,\u2019 said Joshua Bolten, President & CEO of Business Roundtable.\u201d Read more.  \u2019CAUSE THEY\u2019RE THE TAX MEN \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo and Colin Wilhelm: \u201cWhite House and congressional leaders officially acknowledged Thursday that a controversial tax on imports would be dropped from tax reform, but otherwise provided no new details on a broader plan they expect to start moving through Congress in the fall.  \u201cThe import tax, called border adjustability, was pushed by House Speaker Paul Ryan as a way to fund tax cuts, but it prompted a fierce backlash from retailers, other import-dependent industries and conservative activists. With that tax off the table, Congress, the White House and advocacy groups hope to present a more united front on tax reform, though other disagreements will surely flare as lawmakers work on a replacement.\u201d Read more.  BANK REG HEARING DEBRIEF \u2014 Federal Reserve nominee Randal Quarles and Comptroller of the Currency nominee Joseph Otting faced the Senate Banking Committee on Thursday, and came out with relatively few, if any, scratches. This wasn\u2019t the first rodeo for Treasury veteran Quarles, who seemed relatively comfortable testifying (and therefore kept all his answers highly vague). Otting faced heat from Democrats over his past with OneWest, but more of the focus was on the Fed nominee sitting next to him.  From yours truly: \u201cThe Federal Reserve is set to shift course in its regulation of the nation's banks, but the result won\u2019t look anything like the rhetoric President Donald Trump has used in the past to bash Wall Street. At his nomination hearing Thursday, Randal Quarles, Trump\u2019s nominee for the Fed\u2019s top regulatory post, charted a vision of bank supervision that largely reflected the positions staked out by Fed Gov. Jerome Powell, who currently holds that job at the agency.\u201d Read more.  Transparency for stress tests? Quarles implicitly indicated he might go farther in making information available about the Fed\u2019s annual stress tests, pointing repeatedly to a \u201clack of transparency\u201d that he would like to change. But he added that because he had so few details on the content of the tests, he couldn\u2019t speak to what should specifically be made public.  Otting on regulation: \u201cThe capital structure that we have in place today is highly complex, and I think it needs to be examined. \u2026 Overall, I think the regulatory system we have in place today has resulted in banks understanding their risks much better.\u201d  MM included a regulatory analogy yesterday from an old Quarles speech about how one should be expected to miss two or three planes a year. He was read back that quote during his hearing and said it was \u201cprobably the most unfortunate use of language I\u2019ve ever made, and I do not stand behind that statement.\u201d  THE CFTC\u2019S WHITE WHALE \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Patrick Temple-West and Catherine Boudreau: \u201cPresident Donald Trump\u2019s three nominees for the CFTC on Thursday pledged to complete work on a rule aimed at curbing speculation in energy commodities, a controversial regulation that has repeatedly been stalled over the years.  \u201cThe Senate Agriculture Committee\u2019s confirmation hearing for the three \u2014 Republicans Dawn Stump and Brian Quintenz and Democrat Rostin Behnam \u2014 underscored how one of the biggest issues facing the derivatives markets has not advanced since the last time a trio of agency nominees testified in March 2014. During Thursday's hearing, Stump, Quintenz and Behnam agreed that they would work to finalize the so-called position limits rule, which was included in the 2010 Dodd-Frank Act.\u201d Read more.  FOR THE UHHHHH, WHAT? FILE \u2014 White House Communications Director Anthony Scaramucci to the New Yorker\u2019s Ryan Lizza: \u201c\u2018The swamp will not defeat him,\u2019 he said, breaking into the third person. \u2018They\u2019re trying to resist me, but it\u2019s not going to work. I\u2019ve done nothing wrong on my financial disclosures, so they\u2019re going to have to go f \u2014 - themselves.\u2019 \u2026 \u2018What I want to do is I want to f \u2014 -ing kill all the leakers and I want to get the President\u2019s agenda on track so we can succeed for the American people.\u2019\u201d Read more.  WHITE HOUSE DRAMA AFFECTING MARKETS? \u2014 Fox Business\u2019 Charlie Gasparino: \u201cThis is not a good time to be rushing to make big bets either way. I can tell you that traders that I speak to, major investors are increasingly skittish about not just the lack of clarity on tax cuts but on the White House dysfunction. I never thought I\u2019d say this, but Reince Priebus, getting rid of Reince Priebus is considered at least a marginal negative on the markets. \u2026 This sort of drama between he and Scaramucci, I\u2019m hearing from traders it\u2019s starting to like bleed over. Like, what the hell is going on over there?\u201d  YOU MADE IT TO FRIDAY \u2014 Thanks for hanging with me this week. Ben White will be back in your inboxes Monday, so give him a shout at bwhite@politico.com and on Twitter @morningmoneyben. Email Aubree Eliza at aweaver@politico.com and follow her on Twitter @AubreeEWeaver, and always feel free to send financial regulatory news to me at vguida@politico.com or @vtg2.  THIS MORNING ON POLITICO PRO FINANCIAL SERVICES \u2013 Zachary Warmbrodt on how Democrats led by Rep. Maxine Waters are getting under Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin\u2019s skin. To get Morning Money every day before 6 a.m., please contact Pro Services at (703) 341-4600 or info@politicopro.com.  IMPENDING DOOM FOR LIBOR \u2014 POLITICO Europe\u2019s Cat Contiguglia: \u201cFor the first time, a regulator has made it clear that it expects LIBOR to disappear, in less than five years. In a speech on Thursday, the U.K. Financial Conduct Authority\u2019s Chief Executive Andrew Bailey laid out a plan to manhandle the market off of the interbank lending rate by 2021. The overarching narrative was \u2018voluntary\u2019 market cooperation. But the transition would be underpinned by a strong regulatory influence to force banks to support LIBOR for the next four to five years and then to push the market off of it by the end of 2021.\u201d Read more.  VOLCKER TALK \u2014 The Financial Stability Oversight Council meets today and the Volcker rule is on the docket. There\u2019s some momentum behind regulatory relief around the rule, which prevents banks from trying to make money off short-term price changes in financial markets, through trades made on their own behalf. In the last week, regulators have taken a couple of targeted steps to give banks some wiggle room under some very specific provisions.  As for concrete changes to the rule, all of the agencies are actively looking at it, but don\u2019t expect any proposals until next year. If you\u2019re wondering about the realm of the doable, PwC has a new paper out this week that categorizes Volcker revisions based on their likelihood and impact. There are three moves they see as both highly likely and highly likely to have an impact: simplifying the definition of proprietary trading, making it easier to hedge, and reducing \u201ccompliance burden.\u201d The paper is here.  ANOTHER BRICK IN THE WALL \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Sarah Ferris: \u201cThe House passed a $789 billion defense spending package Thursday to fund the Pentagon, veterans\u2019 benefits and nuclear programs, while supporting what GOP leaders have dubbed a "down payment" for President Donald Trump's border wall. In a 235-192 vote, the chamber wrapped up work on the Make America Secure Appropriations Act, H.R. 3219 (115), which bundles four of the 12 spending bills to fund the government beyond Sept. 30.\u201d Read more.  SEC MAKING PROGRESS ON CYBERSECURITY \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Patrick Temple-West: The Securities and Exchange Commission improved the security controls over its key financial systems and information, the Government Accountability Office said in a report on Thursday. But the agency still has work to do, including consistently protecting its network boundaries from possible intrusions, and identifying and authenticating users, among other things. Read the report.  STOCKS DIP \u2014 AP\u2019s Stan Choe: \u201cU.S. stock indexes pulled back from their record highs Thursday after drops for technology, health care and industrial stocks offset another big gain for telecoms.  \u201cThe Standard & Poor's 500 index fell 11 points, or 0.4 percent, to 2,467 as of 3 p.m. Eastern time. Earlier in the day, it had been up by 6 points to extend its record run. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 20 points, or 0.1 percent, to 21,731, and the Nasdaq composite fell 63 points, or 1 percent, to 6,359. The Russell 2000 index of small-cap stocks fell 11 points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,431.\u201d Read more.  DOLLAR CLAWS BACK EARLY LOSSES \u2014 FT\u2019s Dave Shellock: \u201cThe dollar clawed back early losses against the euro, and Treasuries gave back some of the previous day\u2019s gains as the markets continued to digest Wednesday\u2019s policy statement from the Federal Reserve.  \u201cIt was the currency markets that grabbed the headlines as the dollar climbed off a two-and-a-half year low against the euro and held above the 111 level versus the yen. Sterling retreated from a 10-month high. Some in the markets pointed to news of a strong rise in headline U.S. durable goods orders last month, although the reading excluding transportation was less impressive.\u201d Read more.  BULL MARKET\u2019S GROWTH PROBLEM \u2014 WSJ\u2019s Justin Lahart: \u201cStocks are hitting records and valuations are at 15-year highs, both signs of confidence. But a closer look at what is driving the rally shows that the eight-year bull market may be nearing its end.  \u201cThe current earnings season makes it clear that investors are paying up for companies that are generating strong growth in earnings and revenues and ignoring or selling stocks where growth is anything less than stellar. In the past, that was a sign that the stock market rally, and the economic expansion, were in their final stages.\u201d Read more.  ALSO FOR YOUR RADAR \u2014   DEUTSCHE BANK REPORTS SHARP RISE IN PROFIT \u2014 WSJ\u2019s Jenny Strasburg: \u201cDeutsche Bank AG\u2019s cost-cutting moves helped it beat analysts\u2019 expectations in the second quarter, but year-over-year revenue fell in all three business divisions as its chief executive faces pressure to revive results amid a continuing overhaul.  \u201cDeutsche Bank shares closed down 6.6 percent Thursday in trading in Germany, to \u20ac15.52. They\u2019re down about 20% from their highs earlier this year after the lender put behind it a major litigation threat and then embarked on a successful \u20ac8 billion capital raise.\u201d Read more.  The bank was also met with news that former chiefs have agreed to waive substantial back pay. FT\u2019s Laura Noonan: \u201cDeutsche Bank has finally managed to recoup \u20ac38.4m of deferred bonuses from its pre-crisis management, offering a sliver of good news on a day when the lender\u2019s shares fell 6.5 percent on disappointing earnings.\u201d Read more.  TWITTER SHARES TUMBLE AS USER GROWTH STALLS \u2014 Reuters\u2019 Angela Moon and Pushkala A: \u201cTwitter Inc shares plunged more than 14 percent on Thursday after the social media platform disappointed investors with stagnant monthly active user growth in the second quarter.  \u201cDespite its appeal among celebrities and public figures, Twitter has struggled to sustain its closely watched user growth even as it invests in features and live content to help draw viewers and boost user engagement. It is in stiff competition for advertising dollars with other platforms like larger rival Facebook Inc and Snap Inc\u2019s messaging app Snapchat.\u201d Read more.  Aubree Eliza Weaver is a Web producer for POLITICO Pro. She graduated from Le Moyne College in her hometown of Syracuse, N.Y., where she was the editor-in-chief of her school\u2019s newspaper, The Dolphin; co-hosted a political segment on the school\u2019s news station, LCTV; and worked as a photography assistant in the Visual Arts department. As a student, Weaver interned with various communications organizations, including the publicity department of Regnery Publishing and serving as a news broadcast intern at Time Warner Cable\u2019s Syracuse affiliate, YNN.  Immediately following her graduation in May 2013, Weaver moved to D.C. to work as a summer program adviser for The Fund for American Studies\u2019 Institute on Political Journalism, an educational nonprofit that offers courses, internships, lecture series and other opportunities for college students and recent grads. She was a student in the program in the summer of 2011, when she first fell in love with D.C.  In her free time, Weaver loves to read and write (as all journalists do), play guitar until her fingers are numb, drink more coffee than she\u2019d care to admit, and spend time with her family.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                        