aV \u000a            By VICTORIA GUIDA and AUBREE ELIZA WEAVER  07/27/2017 08:00 AM EDT  TRUMP\u2019S BANK REGULATORY NOMINEES UNDER THE SPOTLIGHT \u2014 It\u2019s a big day in bank regulatory land: President Donald Trump\u2019s picks for Federal Reserve vice chair of supervision and comptroller of the currency will have their confirmation hearing this morning, yielding some insight into what the Trump era of bank regulation will bring. And what Trump\u2019s first Fed nominee plans to say about post-crisis rules sounds little different than those from anyone else at the central bank.  From your host, Victoria Guida, and Zach Warmbrodt: \u201cRandal Quarles, President Donald Trump's nominee to become the Federal Reserve vice chair of supervision, will tell the Senate Banking Committee on Thursday that his goal is to refine post-crisis regulations while protecting the ability of the financial system to withstand shocks. \u2018Regulatory policies enacted since the financial crisis have improved the safety and soundness of the financial system,\u201d Quarles says in his prepared testimony obtained by POLITICO. \u201cBut as with any complex undertaking, after the first wave of reform, and with the benefits of experience and reflection, some refinements will undoubtedly be in order.\u2019  Story Continued Below  \u201c \u2026 Joseph Otting, who has been nominated as comptroller of the currency, in his own testimony largely highlights his own background, without going into much detail on his regulatory philosophy. But he defends his time as CEO of OneWest, the bank co-founded by Steven Mnuchin, now Trump's Treasury secretary, that has faced criticism for its foreclosure practices.\u201d Read more.  PROGRESSIVE GROUPS JUMP INTO THE FRAY \u2014 Public opposition to Quarles and Otting had been relatively muted up until this past week, but progressive groups have lined up in recent days to oppose both.  Americans for Financial Reform criticized the Fed nominee for failing to take action to prevent the financial crisis. \u201cMr. Quarles was an important part of the GW Bush financial regulatory team that missed the signs of the oncoming financial crisis and failed to take effective action as Wall Street risks grew out of control,\u201d the group said in a letter to senators. \u201cHe has shown no evidence that he has learned sufficiently from this failure.\u201d  Fed Up and Popular Democracy raised warnings about Quarles\u2019 penchant for a strict monetary policy rule, as well as his regulatory attitude. \u201cWhile serving as a Treasury official earlier in his career, Quarles dismissed the notion that regulators should take \u2026 action against speculation and risk, saying, \u201cMarkets are always ahead of the regulators, and frankly that\u2019s how it should be. It\u2019s analogous to the advice that my father provided me that \u2018if you don't miss at least two or three planes a year, you're spending too much time in airports.\u2019 Quarles\u2019 cavalier and simplistic attitude toward regulation raises serious questions about whether he should be entrusted with the top regulatory job at the nation\u2019s foremost economic policymaking institution.\u201d  Public Citizen, meanwhile, blasted the Fed nominee for making money through his stakes in troubled or failed banks, citing a Reuters story that pointed to his role in Carlyle Group\u2019s investments in Boston Private Financial Holdings Inc. and BankUnited.  The group also hit Otting for \u201ctens of thousands of foreclosures, including 35,000 in California alone\u201d during his time at OneWest that \u201cwere concentrated in minority communities.\u201d And it cited OneWest subsidiary Financial Freedom\u2019s $89 million settlement with HUD, which covered claims that the unit had improperly collected government payments it didn\u2019t qualify for.  The California Reinvestment Coalition renewed its criticism of Otting, putting out fact sheets on CFPB complaints against OneWest while he was CEO and on his overall record at the helm of the bank.  QUARLES, IN HIS OWN WORDS \u2014 From his prepared testimony: \u201cI believe I am well qualified to undertake this role. \u2026 I have had experience over my career with the financial sector from many different points of view. \u2026 While this long experience has given me substantive insight into the issues that the Federal Reserve\u2019s Vice Chairman for Supervision will face, it has also reinforced my commitment to what I think is the single most important characteristic of a good policy maker: the need to be humble.\u201d  OTTING, IN HIS OWN WORDS \u2014 From his prepared testimony: \u201cWith the assistance of the many dedicated women and men of OneWest Bank, we were able to create the largest hometown bank headquartered in Southern California. It was able to grow beyond primarily mortgage originations to a bank with a full suite of products and services for local businesses, families and consumers. Helping build this company is something I am and will remain proud of.\u201d  ONE MORE WORD ON OTTING \u2014 From someone who has known him for years. Allan Zaremberg, president and CEO of the California Chamber of Commerce, described Otting as focused, direct and involved in his community.  \u201cI don\u2019t think there\u2019s any question that he has an inordinate amount of expertise in his industry, but he is also a straight shooter,\u201d Zaremberg told MM. \u201cYou know what he expects of you. And I would say there\u2019s no question that he\u2019s a person who expects people to follow the rules and to be ethical. \u2026 I would expect nothing less of him as a regulator.\u201d  BUSY, BUSY \u2014 Today\u2019s going to be a full morning on Capitol Hill for financial regulatory nerds. Before the hearing for Otting and Quarles, the Banking Committee will meet at 9:45 a.m. to consider the nominations of multiple HUD nominees, two Commerce nominees, as well as Trump\u2019s pick for assistant Treasury secretary for financial institutions, Chris Campbell. But the fun doesn\u2019t stop there: The Senate Agriculture Committee at 9:30 a.m. will consider the nominations for three CFTC commissioner seats: Rostin Behnam, Brian Quintenz and Dawn Stump. Meanwhile, Mnuchin will testify before the House Financial Services Committee at 10 a.m. on international finance. Here are his opening remarks, obtained by POLITICO.  IT\u2019S ALMOST FRIDAY \u2014 Please send tips to me at vguida@politico.com or @vtg2, and email Aubree Eliza at aweaver@politico.com and follow her on Twitter @AubreeEWeaver. As always, you can reach Ben White at bwhite@politico.com and on Twitter @morningmoneyben.  THIS MORNING ON POLITICO PRO FINANCIAL SERVICES \u2014 Patrick Temple-West on Dawn DeBerry Stump, one of the Republicans Trump has nominated to join the CFTC, and her career as a derivatives industry lobbyist. To get Morning Money every day before 6 a.m., please contact Pro Services at (703) 341-4600 or info@politicopro.com.  COMING SOON TO A THEATER NEAR YOU \u2014 From your host: \u201cThe Federal Reserve's top policy-making body said [Wednesday] the central bank expects to start allowing some assets to roll off its $4.5 trillion balance sheet \u2018relatively soon,\u2019 signaling that its plan could be put into action as soon as September.\u201d And no rate hike, as expected.  UNIFIED TAX PLAN COMING THIS WEEK \u2014 Scoop from POLITICO\u2019s Nancy Cook: \u201cThe \u2018Big 6\u2019 tax reform group, composed of White House officials and congressional leaders, plans to release a broad-brush tax proposal [by the end of the week] before the House leaves for its August recess, according to six sources close to the administration, lobbyists and former Republican congressional staffers. More of a messaging document than a detailed policy blueprint, the plan is meant to present a unified front on tax reform after the Republicans\u2019 mixed and often fractured messages on its health care bills.\u201d Read more.  MM sidebar: Think this one will be longer than one page?  MOOCH WATCH, REDUX \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Lorraine Woellert: \u201cAnthony Scaramucci finally has his White House job, but he still stands to profit from an ownership stake in his investment firm SkyBridge Capital.  The incoming White House communications director earned $4.9 million from his ownership stake in SkyBridge in addition to more than $5 million in salary between Jan. 1, 2016, and the end of June, when he joined the Export-Import Bank, according to a financial disclosure filed with the Office of Government Ethics. The disclosure form hasn\u2019t been previously reported.\u201d Read more.  Notable tidbit: \u201cScaramucci has been on unpaid leave from Ex-Im since the day he started there, June 19, a bank spokeswoman said, foregoing his $172,100 salary as chief strategy officer.\u201d  A \u2018NO\u2019 FOR GARRETT \u2014 Speaking of Ex-Im \u2026 POLITICO\u2019s Zachary Warmbrodt: \u201cSen. Catherine Cortez Masto plans to vote against former Rep. Scott Garrett\u2019s nomination to lead the Export-Import Bank, a spokesman for the Nevada Democrat told POLITICO. The reasons are his views on LGBT issues and his record of trying to shut down the bank. Yesterday, the National Association of Manufacturers and the Nevada Manufacturers Association ran an ad designed to persuade Cortez Masto and her Republican Senate colleague, Dean Heller, to oppose Garrett\u2019s confirmation. A spokeswoman for Heller did not respond to a request for comment.  \u201cSen. Bob Corker, another Banking Committee member, is keeping more of an open mind. \u2018Who knows?\u2019 the Tennessee Republican told POLITICO, \u2018someone like that who\u2019s opposed it but now knows they\u2019re going to lead it could end up being an inspired choice.\u2019 Corker said he wanted to sit down and talk with Garrett, whom he described as a \u2018very knowledgeable guy.\u2019\u201d  WHAT STUDENTS KNOW ABOUT MONEY \u2014 US Bank on Wednesday rolled out a study on college students\u2019 financial literacy. One of the main findings is that students across the board wish they knew more about how to manage their money.  From the bank: \u201cCredit, in particular, stands out as an area where students continue to need more financial education during their college years: Many students believe common myths. For example, 55% of students do not know that their credit score is not impacted by how much money is in their bank account. There is a gap between white and multicultural students; 84 percent of white students say they know what a credit score is, compared with 77 percent of African-American students, 75 percent of Hispanic students and 68 percent of Asian students. There\u2019s a gender gap, too, although male students don\u2019t realize it. Females demonstrated more knowledge than males about what a credit score is used for.\u201d See the full results here.  FINRA GETS A NEW SHERIFF \u2014 Wall Street self-regulator FINRA has named Susan Schroeder as the head of its enforcement division. Schroeder, who joined FINRA in 2011, previously worked as deputy head of enforcement. Before her time at the organization, she was a partner in WilmerHale\u2019s Securities Litigation and Enforcement practice. The change is a result of FINRA360, the regulator\u2019s ongoing effort to optimize its regulatory operations.  ALSO FOR YOUR RADAR \u2014   WHY RUSSIA\u2019S MARKET IS RISING AFTER SANCTIONS BILL APPROVAL \u2014 Bloomberg\u2019s Ksenia Galouchko: \u201cAs it stands now, the most negative aspect of the bill for Russia, according to analysts, is that U.S. President Donald Trump can no longer ease or revoke the sanctions unilaterally, a possibility that boosted appetite for Russian assets after his election last year. Even that\u2019s less of a concern after Russia\u2019s economy \u2018rebalanced and adjusted\u2019 to the penalties, which were originally imposed as punishment for Moscow\u2019s role in the Ukraine crisis in 2014, according to Julian Rimmer at Investec Bank Plc in London.\u201d Read more.  MNUCHIN: CONSERVING CASH COSTING TAXPAYERS \u2014 WSJ\u2019s Kate Davidson: \u201cTreasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin said Wednesday his agency\u2019s efforts to conserve cash until Congress raises the federal borrowing limit impose a \u2018significant\u2019 cost on taxpayers. Government debt hit the borrowing limit in mid-March, and the Treasury has been using these \u2018extraordinary measures\u2019 since then to raise cash to keep paying the government\u2019s bills on time.  \u201cTestifying before a Senate panel Wednesday, Mr. Mnuchin repeated his previous remarks that the government can keep employing those measures and maintain enough cash to pay its bills \u2018through September.\u2019 But he acknowledged those efforts come with a cost to taxpayers, which one senator estimated to be around $2.5 billion.\u201d Read more.  ENTHUSIASM FOR CORPORATE DEBT NEARS POST-CRISIS HIGH \u2014 FT\u2019s Eric Platt: \u201cInvestor enthusiasm for corporate debt has neared levels not seen since before the start of the credit crisis, in a deepening endorsement of a global economic recovery that has already propelled U.S. stock markets to record heights.  \u201cIn several parts of the U.S. bond markets, companies are now able to raise money at a lower cost, relative to government bonds, than they have for the past decade \u2014 buoyed by quickening global growth and soothing noises from central banks.\u201d Read more.  STOCK INVESTORS CASHING IN ON \u2018SHARING ECONOMY\u2019 \u2014 CNBC\u2019s Rebecca Ungarino: \u201cAs the \u2018sharing economy\u2019 has expanded and morphed into a seeming catch-all term for companies that connect strangers through technology, equity investors may be able to cash in on the technology-driven trend. That\u2019s according to an exhaustive recent report from Bank of America Merrill Lynch. The report concludes the sharing economy's influence has blown up so tremendously in recent years, touching essentially every aspect of consumers\u2019 lives, that it\u2019s created a host of new business models.\u201d Read more.  AMAZON REACHES $500B \u2014 FT\u2019s Adam Samson: \u201cAmazon\u2019s market value on Wednesday smashed through the half-a-trillion dollar mark for the first time, underscoring the rapid appreciation in the e-commerce giant\u2019s share price. The market value has surged by $146.3bn since the end of 2016, rising as high as $502.6bn on the day. In comparison, Wal-Mart, the world\u2019s biggest retailer by revenues, has seen its market capitalisation tick up by $23bn in 2017 to $235.4bn.\u201d Read more.  Aubree Eliza Weaver is a Web producer for POLITICO Pro. She graduated from Le Moyne College in her hometown of Syracuse, N.Y., where she was the editor-in-chief of her school\u2019s newspaper, The Dolphin; co-hosted a political segment on the school\u2019s news station, LCTV; and worked as a photography assistant in the Visual Arts department. As a student, Weaver interned with various communications organizations, including the publicity department of Regnery Publishing and serving as a news broadcast intern at Time Warner Cable\u2019s Syracuse affiliate, YNN.  Immediately following her graduation in May 2013, Weaver moved to D.C. to work as a summer program adviser for The Fund for American Studies\u2019 Institute on Political Journalism, an educational nonprofit that offers courses, internships, lecture series and other opportunities for college students and recent grads. She was a student in the program in the summer of 2011, when she first fell in love with D.C.  In her free time, Weaver loves to read and write (as all journalists do), play guitar until her fingers are numb, drink more coffee than she\u2019d care to admit, and spend time with her family.  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell 