aV \u000a            By BEN WHITE and AUBREE ELIZA WEAVER  07/24/2017 08:00 AM EDT  HERE COMES THE MOOCH \u2014 Busy Friday at the White House with Anthony \u201cMooch\u201d Scaramucci finally getting a gig (and a big one!) and Sean Spicer heading for the exits. Chief of staff Reince Priebus and chief strategist Steve Bannon both got humbled by Scaramucci\u2019s appointment as communications director. Don\u2019t believe the spin about Mooch and Priebus being best buds. The chief of staff killed Mooch for other jobs and tried again here. He failed and he\u2019s now basically chief of staff in title only.   As of late Friday, West Wing sources told MM that Bannon was still furious and sulking and about even money to quit. In fact, Bannon seems more likely than Priebus to leave first. Why the animosity toward Scaramucci? For Priebus, he doesn\u2019t want another high-power, high profile adviser who can go straight to Trump, which Scaramucci can.   Story Continued Below  For Bannon, Scaramucci is just another Wall Street globalist who is tight with Gary Cohn and Dina Powell and believes in climate science, generally opposes protectionism and previously backed Scott Walker and Jeb Bush before grudgingly jumping on board the Trump Train.   For Wall Street, it\u2019s probably pretty good news. Mooch is a super smooth operator who has good relationships with both Republicans and Democrats and should be a help in the tax reform push as he understands all the issues at play.   But none of it will matter if Trump continues to sabotage himself with Tweets about presidential pardons or if the various Russia probes produce agenda-crushing revelations.   White House infighting is a real problem and Scaramucci could potentially improve things here. But it\u2019s the guy at the top that matters and so far the new communications director\u2019s main agenda items seem to be to flatter Trump and encourage him to be more like \u2026 Trump. Not sure that will work.   SOME MOOCH HIGHLIGHTS FROM THE SUNDAY SHOWS \u2014 To CNN\u2019s Jake Tapper: \u201cListen, there's obviously a communications problem, because there's a lot of things that we have done as it relates to executive orders, bills that have been signed, economic progress.\u201d   On briefings: \u201cSo, Sarah Huckabee is the president secretary. If you're asking me for my personal opinion \u2014 and maybe the president will be upset for giving my personal \u2014 we should put the cameras on. That's no problem. I don't think we need to have the cameras off.\u201d   On leaks, to Chris Wallace on \u201cFox News Sunday": \u201cOne of the first things I want to do, as was just mentioned, we got to get the leaks stopped \u2026 If we don't get the leaks stopped, I am a businessperson, and so I will take dramatic action to stop those leaks. \u2026   \u201cI'll be traveling with the president this week and we're going to focus and refine the messaging from the White House. He's one of the most effective communicators that's ever been born, and we're going to make sure that we get that message out directly to the American people\u201d   ICYMI, I wrote about Mooch\u2019s long journey to the White House communications director job on Friday.   OLD TWEETS \u2014 Mooch spent some of the weekend killing old Tweets (and being upfront by announcing he was doing it.) Via WaPo's Kristine Phillips: \u201cIn previous tweets, the Wall Street financier called Hillary Clinton 'incredibly competent\u2019 and appeared to be at odds with his new boss on issues such as gun control, climate change, Islam and illegal immigration.\u201d Read more.   MORE ON WHAT WE LEARNED from Mooch (who has had that nickname since 1978) on the Sunday shows.   TOUGH JOB AHEAD \u2014 Via CNN: \u201cThe President's approval rating has fallen 6 percentage points to the lowest at the six-month mark of any president since the dawn of modern public opinion polling, according to this week's ABC News/Washington Post poll. And Democrats lead Republicans when Americans are asked who they would vote for on a generic congressional ballot for 2018.  \u201cBut it's certainly not all positive news for the party opposing the White House. While history points to likely Democratic victories in the upcoming midterm elections, the numbers show a few Achilles' heels that threaten the opportunity\u201d Read more.   GOP NOT GIVING UP ON HEALTH CARE \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Brianna Ehley: \u201cIf the Senate\u2019s latest Obamacare repeal efforts collapse this week, Republicans will \u2018go back to the drawing board\u2019 and try again, Senate GOP conference chairman John Thune said on Sunday.   \u201cAs Republicans' efforts to undo the 2010 health care law hit seemingly insurmountable roadblocks, members of the party have floated working with Democrats to stabilize insurance markets or moving on to other priorities. But Thune, a Republican senator from South Dakota, insisted Sunday that the GOP is committed to dismantling the law\u201d   LAUNCHING TODAY: START-UP ADVOCACY GROUP \u2014 John Dearie emails: \u201cI left the Financial Services Forum at the end of June to launch a new 501(c)(3) organization called the Center for American Entrepreneurship (CAE), which will launch [Monday] \u2026 CAE\u2019s purpose is to work with policymakers in Washington, and the state and local levels across the country, to enhance policy circumstances for new business formation, survival, and growth. \u2026   \u201cThere are remarkable people from all over the country involved on CAE\u2019s board and Advisory Council, and we currently have funding from the Ewing Marion Kauffman Foundation, Visa,Wells Fargo, UPS, Bank of America, and Goldman Sachs, and are talking with many others\u201d Read more. Follow them @startupsUSAorg  GOOD MONDAY MORNING \u2014 Hope everyone had a nice weekend! MM has some family business to attend to so will be out through Friday\u2019s edition. But you will be in very capable hands. Email me on bwhite@politico.com and follow me on Twitter @morningmoneyben. Email Aubree Eliza Weaver on aweaver@politico.com and follow her on Twitter @AubreeEWeaver.  THIS MORNING ON POLITICO PRO FINANCIAL SERVICES \u2014 Patrick Temple-West and Zachary Warmbrodt on the United States\u2019 efforts to ease the EU\u2019s \u201cAmerica first\u201d concerns over bank deregulation. To get Morning Money every day before 6 a.m., please contact Pro Services at (703) 341-4600 or info@politicopro.com.  DRIVING THE WEEK \u2014 Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell plans to hold a vote Tuesday to begin debate on Obamacare repeal but at the moment he is short of the votes \u2026 Even if debate begins it\u2019s not clear what bill will get a vote \u2026 Trump is scheduled to make a \u201cstatement\u201d on health care Monday afternoon.  Trump hits the road (with the Mooch) for \u201cAmerican heroes\u201d week beginning Monday in West Virginia and continuing Tuesday in Ohio \u2026 Senate Banking on Thursday holds confirmation hearings for Joseph Otting to be Comptroller and Randy Quarles to be vice chairman of supervision at the Fed.  Senate Appropriations has a hearing Wednesday at 10:00 a.m. on the Treasury budget \u2026 Pew Charitable Trusts, the W.K. Kellogg Foundation, and the Senate Economic Mobility Caucus hold a forum on Monday at noon on \u201cEconomic Mobility, Economic Security, and the Future of Employment.\u201d   House Freedom Caucus Chair Mark Meadows, R-N.C., speaks at the Nat\u2019l Press Club \u2026 FOMC meets Tuesday and Wednesday but there are no projection updates and no press conference and no big changes are expected.   WALL STREET WAKING UP? \u2014 Stan Collender in Forbes: \u201cJamie Dimon, CEO of J.P. Morgan Chase, is one of the most powerful people on Wall Street and, therefore, in the world. That's why it was both amusing and frightening to hear that he was extremely unhappy about what's happening \u2026 or, more correctly, not happening \u2026 in Washington. \u2026   \u201cFor at least one glorious moment, everyone who is frustrated with Donald Trump and Congress had their feelings validated by one of Wall Street's brahmins. The scary part is that Dimon and his colleagues should have realized long before now that they had seriously misread the impact of the 2016 election\u201d Read more.   REGULATORS HEARING PREP \u2014 Cap Alpha\u2019s Ian Katz on Thursday\u2019s nomination hearing: \u201cQuarles and Otting will both get tough questions about their views on regulation, especially on rules affecting big banks. Senators Elizabeth Warren (D-Massachusetts) and Sherrod Brown (D-Ohio) will almost surely get in a few zingers.   \u201cOtting in particular will take some heat because of his past as CEO of OneWest. But we expect both to get through the Senate confirmation process. It\u2019s likely that Quarles will pass with a more comfortable margin than Otting.  CLICK \u2014 Newt Gingrich sat down to talk Trump, tax reform and Obamacare with Larry Kudlow. Hear it here.   RAND PAUL: NOT ALWAYS BEST TO BUY AMERICAN \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Brent Griffiths: \u201cKentucky Sen. Rand Paul said Sunday that there\u2019s a reason why buying American-made goods is not always the best the option: cost. \u2018You know, I think all of us have this goal to buy American, but we have to think this thing through,\u2019 Paul told Jake Tapper on CNN\u2019s "State of the Union."  \u201cTapper was pressing Paul on why \u2026 Trump touted Made in the USA goods all week, but still hires foreign workers at his Mar-a-Lago Club in Florida and his company manufacturers a bevy of Trump-branded clothing products abroad. The libertarian-leaning Paul said global trade \u2026 allows for Americans to buy cheaper goods, stretching their dollars so they could then use their savings to pay for things\u201d Read more.   INFRASTRUCTURE STALLED \u2014 NYT\u2019s Glenn Thrush on the Sunday A1: \u201c[A]n ambitious public works plan, arguably his best chance of rising above the partisan rancor of his first six months in office, is fast becoming an afterthought - at precisely the moment Mr. Trump needs a big, unifying issue to rewrite the narrative of his chaotic administration.   \u201cInfrastructure remains stuck near the rear of the legislative line, according to two dozen administration officials, legislators and labor leaders involved in coming up with a concrete proposal\u201d Read more.   STOCKS FALL BEFORE EARNINGS FLURRY \u2014 Bloomberg\u2019s Adam Haigh: \u201cStocks in Asia dropped in early trading ahead of a week packed with earnings results and a Federal Reserve interest-rate decision. The euro extended gains. Equities gauges were down in Japan, Australia and South Korea and oil extended declines before an OPEC meeting on Monday\u201d Read more.  THE ONE MARKET WHERE TECH STOCKS AREN\u2019T IN CHARGE \u2014 WSJ: \u201cTech shares have been on a tear this year, driving up stock markets around the world. One market, however, has been a notable exception to this trend: China. Investors have been rushing out of the country\u2019s domestically listed technology companies in droves\u201d Read more.  DEUTSCHE, BARCLAYS HIT HARDEST BY FIXED INCOME FALLS \u2014 FT\u2019s Laura Noonan: \u201cDeutsche Bank and Barclays are expected to emerge this week as the biggest European casualties of the fixed-income trading slump that dogged U.S. banks\u2019 second-quarter earnings, but analysts do not believe the situation is serious enough to merit swingeing cutbacks at either institution.  \u201cThe big five Wall Street banks reported an average fall in fixed-income trading revenue of 17 percent for the three months to June compared with the same period a year earlier, ranging from a 40 percent fall at Goldman Sachs to a drop of just 4 percent at Morgan Stanley, which took an axe to its fixed income, currencies and commodities (FICC) division in late 2015.\u201d Read more.  CHINA\u2019S DEBT SPECTER COULD HAUNT FED MEETINGS \u2014 Reuters\u2019 Marius Zaharia: \u201cIn September 2015, the U.S. Federal Reserve cited risks from China as a key reason for delaying its first interest rate hike in a decade. A wall of Chinese debt maturing in the next few years could jolt the country back into the U.S. central bank's policy deliberations\u201d Read more.  TOP WALL STREET CHIEFS CELEBRATE $314M IN GAINS \u2014 FT\u2019s Laura Noonan: \u201cThe men running two of Wall Street\u2019s biggest banks saw the value of their shareholdings rise by a combined $314m in 2016 as stock market prices rocketed in the aftermath of Donald Trump\u2019s election as U.S. president.   \u201cBut while Jamie Dimon and Lloyd Blankfein each enjoyed $150m-plus rises in the value of their stock and options in JPMorgan Chase and Goldman Sachs, respectively, the average gains for the other 18 best-paid chief executives at international banks last year was $4m.\u201d Read more.  BATTLE OVER YELP FOR BANKS \u2014 WSJ\u2019s Yuka Hayashi: \u201cA government complaint database popular with consumers has become the latest battleground for efforts to curb the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau\u2019s authority.  \u201cThe public database run by the bureau draws thousands of complaints about companies each week. But businesses say it spreads unverified negative information about them. Now the Trump administration wants to make the information private, saying the information isn\u2019t sufficiently verified by the government. Critics say the move would weaken a tool for consumers and businesses to resolve disagreements.\u201d Read more.  VANGUARD CLOSING IN ON BLACKROCK \u2014 FT\u2019s Chris Flood: \u201cVanguard is closing in on BlackRock\u2019s title as the world\u2019s largest asset manager after pulling in more than $1bn a day of investor money since the start of the year.  \u201cThe two heavyweights of the investment industry are attracting unprecedented inflows into their low-cost exchange traded funds amid rising investor dissatisfaction with the high fees and poor performance of active managers that strive to beat the market.\u201d Read more.  ALSO FOR YOUR RADAR \u2014   TRANSITIONS \u2014 Per release: \u201cTom Koonce, an executive director at JPMorgan Chase, will join the bipartisan lobby shop Rich Feuer Anderson in August. Koonce is one of Washington's top democratic financial services lobbyists and strategists. Rich Feuer Anderson, founded in 2003, represents a variety of clients including: Amazon, BlackRock, PwC and SWIFT.\u201d   PARDON ME? \u2014 Via POLITICO: \u201cTrump claimed on Saturday morning that \u2018all agree\u2019 that he has full power to pardon, following reports that his legal team is exploring his ability to pardon not only his allies and family members but also himself.  \u201c\u2018While all agree the U. S. President has the complete power to pardon, why think of that when only crime so far is LEAKS against us. FAKE NEWS,\u2019 Trump tweeted.\u201d Read more.   OOPS! \u2014 POLITICO\u2019s Cristiano Lima: \u201cSenior White House adviser and son-in-law to \u2026 Trump Jared Kushner reported 77 undisclosed assets and more than an additional $10 million in previously unreported holdings, according to revised financial documents filed Friday, which his legal team said were \u2018inadvertently omitted\u2019 from prior financial disclosure filings\u201d Read more.   Ben White is POLITICO Pro's chief economic correspondent and author of the \u201cMorning Money\u201d column covering the nexus of finance and public policy.  Prior to joining POLITICO in the fall of 2009, Mr. White served as a Wall Street reporter for the New York Times, where he shared a Society of Business Editors and Writers award for breaking news coverage of the financial crisis.  From 2005 to 2007, White was Wall Street correspondent and U.S. Banking Editor at the Financial Times.  White worked at the Washington Post for nine years before joining the FT. He served as national political researcher and research assistant to columnist David S. Broder and later as Wall Street correspondent.  White, a 1994 graduate of Kenyon College, has two sons and lives in New York City.  Aubree Eliza Weaver is a Web producer for POLITICO Pro. She graduated from Le Moyne College in her hometown of Syracuse, N.Y., where she was the editor-in-chief of her school\u2019s newspaper, The Dolphin; co-hosted a political segment on the school\u2019s news station, LCTV; and worked as a photography assistant in the Visual Arts department. As a student, Weaver interned with various communications organizations, including the publicity department of Regnery Publishing and serving as a news broadcast intern at Time Warner Cable\u2019s Syracuse affiliate, YNN.  Immediately following her graduation in May 2013, Weaver moved to D.C. to work as a summer program adviser for The Fund for American Studies\u2019 Institute on Political Journalism, an educational nonprofit that offers courses, internships, lecture series and other opportunities for college students and recent grads. She was a student in the program in the summer of 2011, when she first fell in love with D.C.  In her free time, Weaver loves to read and write (as all journalists do), play guitar until her fingers are numb, drink more coffee than she\u2019d care to admit, and spend time with her family.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
