aV \u000a            By ADAM CANCRYN (acancryn@politico.com)  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  CONGRESS LEAVES, OBAMACARE LIVES \u2014 Well, this certainly isn\u2019t where Republicans thought they\u2019d be after seven months with full control of Washington.   Obamacare is still the law of the land. Each of the many GOP repeal-and-replace plans is dead in the water. And as Congress officially heads home for August recess, there\u2019s renewed talk \u2014 against all odds \u2014 of bipartisanship on health care.   Story Continued Below  The last seven months have served as a master class in the difficulties of translating a simple mantra into complex legislation, particularly in doing it quickly and with almost no margin for error.   The result is a White House still searching for its first major legislative win and a Republican-controlled Congress that\u2019s rudderless on how to handle what\u2019s been the GOP\u2019s defining domestic policy issue for nearly a decade, Pro\u2019s Jennifer Haberkorn and Paul Demko report.   "I still think something gets through, just because there's families that are not going to be able to afford their insurance, middle income families," said Bill Cassidy (R-La.). "It's going to be a lot of effort."  The August recess state of play. Obamacare is still standing, but it\u2019s mighty wobbly. President Donald Trump is mulling cutting off funding for the law\u2019s cost-sharing subsidies, a decision that would upend the already-anxious Obamacare markets, driving premiums up and some insurers out of the market altogether.  Even without that, there are currently 19 counties at risk of having no options for Obamacare coverage in 2018. And congressional Republicans are split between clinging to their repeal pledge, despite seeing no clear legislative direction, or working to fix Obamacare, and betraying their biggest promise to their base. More from Jen and Paul here.  LIBERTARIANS SCORE BIG ON 'RIGHT-TO-TRY' BILL \u2014 The Obamacare fight may be intractable, but Congress just advanced two major bills that could have much further-reaching effects on the nation\u2019s health care system.   First, the Senate voted unanimously to approve \u201cright-to-try\u201d legislation giving people with life-threatening disease access to unapproved experimental drugs, in what Pro\u2019s Sarah Karlin-Smith writes is a victory for libertarian advocates.   Sen. Ron Johnson (R-Wis.) shepherded the bill through the chamber, overcoming initial opposition from the pharmaceutical lobby to advance a proposal that would pave the way for patients to get drugs that haven't received FDA approval.   There\u2019s still some healthy skepticism of the bill; the legislation doesn\u2019t require drugmakers to make experimental treatments available, and the FDA\u2019s own compassionate use program already approves 99 percent of requests. But Johnson and libertarian backers like the Goldwater Institute have sold the measure as giving patients a \u201cright to hope.\u201d  "Opposing right-to-try laws is akin to opposing motherhood, apple pie, and the American flag; you just don't do it and expect to be re-elected," Wayne State University oncologist David Gorski wrote. More from Sarah here.   Senate clears FDA user fee reauthorization. The Senate also voted 94-1 to reauthorize the FDA's user fee programs for five years, clearing the way for the agency to continue collecting fees from the industry that make up roughly half its yearly budget. More for Pros here.  TRUMP TO GOP: GET BACK TO WORK ON REPEAL \u2014 Congressional Republicans might not know what to do about Obamacare, but the message from the White House couldn\u2019t be clearer: Dismantle Obamacare by any means necessary. Trump at a rally in West Virginia criticized Republican senators for falling short on repealing and replacing the law, and urged them to keep trying until they succeed.  \u201cCongress must get to work and deliver Americans the great health care that they deserve, the great repeal and replace that they\u2019ve been talking about for seven years,\u201d he said, encouraging his supporters to pressure the GOP until it finds the votes. \u201cCall your congressmen, call your senators, call everybody. Get them to have the guts to repeal and replace Obamacare, which is a disaster."  In between lamenting the failed health care vote, Trump did single out one senator for praise: West Virginia's Shelley Moore Capito, who voted to open debate on Obamacare after weeks of holding out over concerns about the state's Medicaid expansion population.  What didn't get a mention. Trump held the rally in Huntington, W. Va., one of the towns hardest-hit by heroin and opioids in a state that's suffered most from the crisis. The president railed against drug dealers, gangs and narcotics pouring across the border from Mexico. But the opioid crisis itself never got a mention, nor did Trump offer any ideas for addressing a nationwide problem that he pledged during the campaign to solve.   \u000a                            President Donald Trump continues to criticize congressional Republicans for failing to send him an Obamacare repeal bill | Darron Cummings/AP Photo  THANK GOODNESS IT'S FRIDAY PULSE \u2014 Where we're kicking off the August recess with a few days of substitute PULSErs. Send tips, story ideas and schoolyard pranks to acancryn@politico.com and @adamcancryn on Twitter.  With help from Renuka Rayasam (@renurayasam)  YOUR WAY-TOO-EARLY SEPTEMBER CHEAT SHEET \u2014 In the words of Sen. Orrin Hatch, \u201cit\u2019s going to be a busy fall.\u201d A short list of health care items awaiting Congress when it comes back in September:  \u2014 Reauthorization of the Children\u2019s Health Insurance Program  \u2014 CBO scores of a raft of repeal proposals, including the Graham-Cassidy plan and Ted Cruz\u2019s amendment letting states waive Obamacare protections  \u2014 Bipartisan HELP Committee and Finance Committee hearings   \u2014 Another White House decision on funding the cost-sharing subsidies  \u2014 Negotiating, and then passing (maybe), the first major bipartisan Obamacare bill stabilizing the market  ONE MORE AGENDA ITEM: TAX REFORM \u2014 Republicans are intent on overhauling the tax code when they return to Washington, a monumental effort that requires the GOP's full attention if it hopes to push a partisan tax bill through Congress in just the next few months.   But here's the big problem: Republicans just can't quit on trying to tear down Obamacare. The will-they-won't-they dance on repeal that consumed seven months of work and political will isn't likely to end any time soon, complicating GOP hopes of speeding through a rewrite of the nation's tax code, POLITICO's Bernie Becker and Aaron Lorenzo write.   SENATE WHIPAROUND: THE FLURRY OF FINAL HEALTH CARE VOTES  New mental health chief confirmed. Elinore McCance-Katz will be installed as HHS\u2019 first assistant secretary for mental health and substance abuse, after the Senate voted to confirm her among a series of outstanding nominees across the administration. A clinical psychiatrist, McCance-Katz returns to the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration just two years after she quit the agency amid disagreements with leadership.   Now, she\u2019s the SAMHSA\u2019s top official, Pro\u2019s Brianna Ehley reports. The assistant secretary for mental health post was created by the 21st Century Cures legislation, which aimed to elevate mental health issues within HHS. More for Pros here.   Also confirmed:  \u2014 Former Indiana health official Jerome Adams is the new surgeon general. More for Pros here.  \u2014- Lance Allen Robertson as assistant secretary for aging  \u2014 Robert Kadlec as assistant secretary for preparedness and response  Senate clears measure targeting opioid addiction treatment. The Senate\u2019s final round of votes included unanimous consent for legislation aimed at ensuring doctors know when they\u2019re treating patients with opioid addiction. The bill backed by Sen. Joe Manchin requires HHS to develop best practices for docs and hospitals to note painkiller sensitivity in patients\u2019 charts, our eHealth colleague David Pittman writes, so they don\u2019t prescribe drugs to patients susceptible to overdose.  The legislation passed after revisions this week that maintain patient control over the sharing of addiction histories, a concession to privacy concerns. More for Pros here.  Hearing aid bill passes. Folded into the FDA user fee bill was a measure making hearing aids available over the counter. The legislation allows those with mild to moderate hearing loss to buy hearing aids without a prescription, a change that the AARP had championed as a way to drive down costs. It passed over the opposition of the hearing aid industry, which has argued that diagnosing the need for hearing aids should be left to professionals.  ** A message from PhRMA: ICYMI: National Sheriffs\u2019 Association says importation proposals \u201cwould jeopardize law enforcement\u2019s ability to protect the public health; threaten the safety of our drug supply; and endanger law enforcement officers, their canines, other first responders.\u201d http://onphr.ma/2hl5WFY **  WELCOME HOME GOP: 80 PERCENT OF VOTERS DISAPPROVE OF REPUBLICAN HEALTH CARE AGENDA \u2014 Voters surveyed in a Quinnipiac University poll overwhelmingly oppose the way congressional Republicans handled health care in their first seven months on the job \u2014 a period dominated by the failed bid to repeal and replace Obamacare. That includes 60 percent of self-identified Republicans, amid a broader sea change in support of preserving the current law, POLITICO's Jake Lahut writes. Just 22 percent still want to see a full repeal of Obamacare, while only 25 percent of respondents liked any of the GOP\u2019s replacement solutions.  What is getting support: Single payer. A narrow majority \u2014 51 percent \u2014 favor replacing Obamacare with a Medicare-for-all system, versus 38 percent opposing it. More from Jake here.  NEW PROBE INTO ZINKE-MURKOWSKI CALL ON HEALTH CARE \u2014 The Interior Department inspector general\u2019s office is investigating \u201cpotential legal and ethical violations\u201d tied to Secretary Ryan ZInke\u2019s call to Sen. Lisa Murkowski over her vote against opening debate on Obamacare repeal, it said in a letter to two House Democrats.   Zinke reportedly hinted that public land and energy projects in Alaska could suffer over Murkowski\u2019s opposition to the health care effort. Murkowski maintains she didn\u2019t take Zinke\u2019s call as a threat, and representatives for both say they maintain a good relationship.  New Jersey to let insurers refile 2018 rates \u2014 State regulators are giving insurers on the Obamacare markets another shot to submit their rates for 2018, in the latest sign of the anxiety tied to Trump's threats to end payments for cost-sharing subsidies.   The original rate-filing deadline was June 21, but the Christie administration opened the process back up after acknowledging that they may no longer reflect the risk insurers are taking on. Horizon Blue Cross Blue Shield of New Jersey, the state's largest insurer, said in a statement that "were it not for uncertainty surrounding the future of the [Affordable Care Act], Horizon would be proposing a single-digit rate increase." More for Pros here.  Texas House okays abortion reporting requirements for minors. State lawmakers tentatively approved a measure requiring doctors performing abortions on minors to report how the patient received consent for the procedure. Doctors would have to report where parental consent took place. If the patient received a judicial bypass, allowing her to waive parental consent, the report would have to include whether a doctor or another advocate helped her through the process. In case of an emergency abortion, the doctor would have to report whether there was time to obtain consent.  The Texas Medical Association, which rarely weighs in on abortion legislation, didn\u2019t take a formal position on the bill, but did provide testimony saying it \u201ccalls for details on deeply personal decisions and on medical care, and reporting that does not contribute to public health.\u201d  A similar measure already passed the state Senate earlier in the special session.  \u2014 House lawmakers also voted unanimously to restore funding to disabled children\u2019s therapy providers in Medicaid. The issue has become a lightning rod in a state with an already lean Medicaid program.  Two years ago, Texas cut the rate that pediatric providers received in Medicaid, saying that the rates were too high compared with other states. During the regular session earlier this year, state lawmakers drew repeated fire from disability and children\u2019s health advocates. The Senate tempered the House\u2019s call to fully reverse the cuts, restoring about 25 percent of the funding.  While the measure wasn\u2019t on the special session agenda laid out by Gov. Abbott earlier this summer, House lawmakers argued it was too important to ignore. After final approval in the House, the measure will head to the Senate.  The nonstop nature of the Trump era is keeping politicians from their regular nip-and-tuck sessions, Vanity Fair's Kenzie Bryant writes.  The New York Times editorial board examines Republicans' turn toward bipartisanship \u2014 and away from Donald Trump \u2014 on Obamacare.  HealthInsurance.org contributor Wendell Potter argues that Trump's threat to destroy Obamacare could inadvertently pave the way for a single-payer health care system.  Forget deciding whether Obamacare is a success or failure \u2014 we first need to agree on what we expect the law to actually accomplish, Bloomberg View's Megan McArdle writes.  The Atlantic's James Hamblin knows how to simultaneously make a dent on climate change and improve the nation's health: Eat beans instead of beef.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
