aV \u000a            By DAN DIAMOND (ddiamond@politico.com; @ddiamond)  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  WHY TRUMP'S IN A HOLDING PATTERN ON SUBSIDIES \u2014After the inability of Republicans in Congress to repeal and replace Democrats' health law, the White House is not expected to immediately end key Obamacare subsidies despite President Donald Trump's threats, officials said. In fact, they could remain in place indefinitely, some officials told POLITICO's Josh Dawsey and Jennifer Haberkorn.  The administration has slowed its decision in order to hear from lawyers, who are studying how the payments could be ended and what legal liabilities the administration could face if the payments stop, according to administration officials. Lawyers and some administration officials have raised questions about ending the payments but are expected to offer an analysis later in August, West Wing officials said.   Story Continued Below  ... One official said the analysis could arrive as soon as next week. A different official said the White House was in no hurry and wanted to consider all factors before making a decision. Another payment is due approximately Aug. 22. More.  PULSE CHECK: Looking at Trump's legal threat to the ACA. Nicholas Bagley, a University of Michigan law professor and expert on the ACA legal fight, breaks down the subsidy battle and Trump's legal predicament on this week's episode of POLITICO's health care podcast.  "This is the single biggest and most urgent question facing the Affordable Care Act, and how Trump resolves it will have political consequences for years to come," Bagley said. Listen here, starting at the 22:45 mark.  THE EMERGING BIPARTISAN PUSH ON ACA FACES STEEP CLIMB \u2014 Senate HELP Chairman Lamar Alexander (R-Tenn.) and ranking Democrat Patty Murray of Washington are up against both time and history in their race to stabilize the shaky Obamacare markets and solidify their status as the chamber's top dealmakers.  The pair has just a few weeks before a self-imposed deadline to bridge deep partisan divisions over the health care law and pass a bill by the end of September, when insurance companies make their final decisions on 2018 Obamacare plans. And that's assuming they can first unite their own committee \u2014 a patchwork of political interests that includes iconoclastic conservative Rand Paul, moderate Republicans Susan Collins and Lisa Murkowski and liberal firebrands Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren, POLITICO\u2019s Jennifer Haberkorn and Adam Cancryn write. More for Pros.  \u2026 Meanwhile, several conservative senators, as well as President Donald Trump, haven't given up on repealing the law outright. Sens. Ted Cruz (R-Texas) and Paul have balked at any proposal that aims to fix Obamacare rather than roll it back. "I think it would be a serious mistake to bail out the insurance companies instead of honoring our promise to repeal Obamacare," Cruz said.  CHIP debate could reopen Obamacare fight. Political fallout from Republicans' failed Obamacare repeal effort could complicate reauthorization of the bipartisan Children's Health Insurance Program covering millions of kids, POLITICO's Rachana Pradhan writes.  Lawmakers wrapped up in the bitter, monthslong fight over Obamacare repeal have made little progress on legislation extending CHIP, which is set to expire after September. Republican and Democratic lawmakers say lingering issues from the Obamacare debate could spill into CHIP negotiations with precious few days left on the legislative calendar before Sept. 30.  "People want to use CHIP for everything," said Sen. Orrin Hatch, who chairs the powerful Senate Finance Committee that will spearhead the chamber's legislation. More for Pros.  \u2026 State officials and other groups tracking the issue believe Congress will eventually extend CHIP funding, due to the program's popularity, but they're still worried by the lack of legislative progress so far. The House Energy and Commerce Committee has held just a single hearing this year on reauthorizing CHIP. The Senate Finance Committee in May canceled its only scheduled hearing on CHIP as it started work on an Obamacare replacement.  AARP thanks Collins, Murkowski and McCain. The advocacy group is now running ads in the three senators' home states, thanking them for voting against the Senate GOP's last-ditch health bill last week. Watch the ad for Collins in Maine, the ad for Murkowski in Alaska and the ad for McCain in Arizona.  \u2026 Arizona would have been "screwed" under the GOP plan, McCain told a radio show host on Wednesday, The Hill reported.  \u000a                            President Donald Trump remains quiet about his plan to potentially yank key Obamacare subsidies. | Getty  Senate vote on FDA user fees this morning: The Senate is expected to vote to send a five-year reauthorization of FDA's user fee programs to the president\u2019s desk. The Senate came to an agreement to vote on a clean version of the bill passed by the House earlier this year, H.R. 2430 (115), after agreeing to let Sen. Ron Johnson get a separate vote on an updated version of his right to try bill. Lawmakers are also expected to vote on two other drug related bills: Jessie's law and the Benefit Act.   Bipartisan leadership of the Senate HELP Committee worked on a compromise version of Johnson's bill which will allow seriously ill patients in all 50 states to skirt FDA when requesting access to experimental medicines. It added some new safety protections for patients to satisfy skeptical public health advocates. However, their response Wednesday was lukewarm.  Patti Zettler, a former FDA associate chief counsel, called the bill an \u201cimprovement,\u201d but she still takes issue with its underlying premise. \u201cThe fundamental problem with the bill is not resolved in that it still envisions removing, or drastically reducing, FDA's role in expanded access," said Zettler, referring to FDA's program for granting patients access to experimental drugs outside of clinical trials.   Read more here from Pro\u2019s Sarah Karlin-Smith.  THIS IS THURSDAY PULSE \u2014 And this is your author's last PULSE for the next week, as he heads out west for a brief break. I leave you in the capable hands of my colleagues, starting with ace Adam Cancryn \u2014 you can find him at acancryn@politico.com or @adamcancryn on twitter.   With help from Renuka Rayasam (@renurayasam), Adam Cancryn (@adamcancryn) and Sarah Karlin- Smith (@SarahKarlin)  POLITICO Pro Policy Summit, Sept. 14: An all-day summit featuring deep-dive conversations and incisive interviews that explore policy trends inside and outside government. Space is limited to current Pro customers at the director level or above. Learn More.  ONLY HALF-JOKING \u2014The Onion \u2014'Repeated Attempts At Eradicating Obamacare May Have Created Ultra-Resistant Super Law'  \u2014That's a headline from the satirical publication The Onion, but legal experts see some merit in the claim. "After persistent efforts by Republicans to wipe out the healthcare law over the past seven years, experts warned Wednesday that the repeated attempts at eradicating Obamacare may have created an ultra-resistant super law," More.  FOIA FOLLOW-UP \u2014 Nonpartisan watchdog American Oversight on Wednesday filed asking for an urgent review of the FOIA documents first published in PULSE yesterday. The group maintains that many of HHS's and OMB's redactions are too aggressive and aren\u2019t covered by existing statute.  ... Drawing on one of those FOIA documents, Wednesday's PULSE wrote that budget chief Mick Mulvaney held a conference call on March 14 with Anthem CEO Joe Swedish, just days after Swedish endorsed Republicans' health care effort. However, Anthem said that Swedish \u2014 who did talk to President Donald Trump and HHS Secretary Tom Price on March 14 \u2014did not connect with Mulvaney. "This call was not on Joe\u2019s calendar and Joe did not speak with him," a spokesperson said. "We cannot speak to why they were emailing about this."  An OMB official says that Mulvaney was invited to join the call in person.  ** A message from PhRMA: ICYMI: National Sheriffs\u2019 Association says importation proposals \u201cwould jeopardize law enforcement\u2019s ability to protect the public health; threaten the safety of our drug supply; and endanger law enforcement officers, their canines, other first responders.\u201d http://onphr.ma/2hl5WFY **  Hospitals pan charity care reporting change. The industry's advocacy groups are up in arms over CMS\u2019 planned change to the way providers report their uncompensated care costs, decrying the system as vague and untested. The shift finalized in a 2018 payment rule will incorporate additional data submitted by hospitals to determine how much each facility receives in payments to cover charity care. CMS had proposed the new requirements in the past, but held off on implementing them until this year, saying it\u2019ll continue to tweak the process to ensure hospitals accurately report their data.  \u201cGNYHA believes CMS has made an egregious error in implementing this policy,\u201d the Greater New York Health Association said in a statement. \u201cDespite this setback, we will continue to pursue an administrative remedy and go to Congress to mitigate this extremely unwise policy decision.\u201d  CMS will distribute roughly $6.8 billion to cover uncompensated care costs, up $800 million from the prior year.  Tom Price celebrates Part D premium decline. The HHS secretary in a statement on Wednesday noted that it's the first time in five years that Part D premiums have gone down, a development that PULSE first flagged in Wednesday's newsletter.  "Lowering drug costs is a key principle of President Trump\u2019s efforts to address the challenges in our healthcare system, and HHS is committed to doing all we can to increase the affordability and accessibility of care," Price said in a statement.  \u2026 PhRMA also praised the Medicare news as "further evidence that Part D continues to provide beneficiaries with access to affordable prescription drug coverage. Year after year, the monthly premiums have been and continue to be regularly stable."  Molina Healthcare drops out of two states. The insurer is exiting the Obamacare marketplaces in Wisconsin and Utah and is seeking to hike premiums by an average of 55 percent in the seven remaining states where it sells coverage, the company announced on Wednesday.  The changes are part of a restructuring designed to improve the company's finances following a major leadership shakeup earlier this year. Molina, which has 950,000 exchange customers, reported $230 million in losses in the second quarter of this year, compared to a $33 million profit during a comparable period in 2016. More for Pros.  Texas: Women not able to access family planning services. After Texas removed Planned Parenthood from its women\u2019s health program, the number of women accessing contraception in the state declined 41 percent from 2011 to 2016, according to a new report from the left-leaning Center for Public Policy Priorities. Women getting health care services in the state declined 39 percent over that time.  Texas is now asking the Trump administration for an 1115 family planning waiver to help fund its Healthy Texas Women program, which doesn\u2019t include abortion providers like Planned Parenthood, POLITICO's Renuka Rayasam reports from Austin. But the CPPP report says that the state hasn\u2019t been able to fill the absence left by Planned Parenthood, which once served 40 percent of clients in the women\u2019s health program before it excluded abortion providers.  Texas: State still dead last when it comes to overall health care access and affordability. A report from the Episcopal Health Foundation found that 23 percent of Texas adults and 10 percent of children in the state still lack health insurance. The report's authors blame Texas\u2019 decision not to expand Medicaid and its restrictive eligibility standards for the state\u2019s high uninsured rate. They also say that the state\u2019s Hispanic population is hardest hit, with 60 percent of Hispanic children and half of Hispanic adults lacking a medical home.   By Paul Demko  President Trump receives largely failing marks from consultant Jeff Goldsmith for his efforts to push health care legislation through Congress. More.   Supporters of transitioning to a single-payer health care system, or Medicare-for-all, haven\u2019t honestly wrestled with the vast challenges it would present, argues Dean Baker in The Nation. More.  Writing in Health Affairs, Obamacare legal expert Tim Jost explores what would be the likely ramifications if Trump cuts off cost-sharing subsidies. More.  JoAnna Novak describes in The New York Times what it\u2019s like to live with the constant specter of panic attacks. More.  Medical personnel are trained to \u201cmove on\u201d after dealing with traumatic cases. But failing to talk about what happened can be bad for patients and providers, argues Jay Baruch in STAT. More.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
