aV \u000a            By DAN DIAMOND (ddiamond@politico.com; @ddiamond)  08/02/2017 10:00 AM EDT  President Donald Trump has repeatedly warned he may yank key Obamacare payments if the law isn't repealed, but a court ruling on Tuesday throws a wrench into that plan.  NO RESOLUTION ON SUBSIDIES YET \u2014 There's still no announcement about whether the White House will continue funding Obamacare's cost-sharing subsidies, even after a scheduled administration meeting on Tuesday on the payments.   Story Continued Below  Trump has increasingly threatened to pull the payments and let the law implode \u2014 especially if the Senate refuses to vote on Obamacare repeal again. The administration soon faces a deadline to declare whether it will continue fighting a court ruling that the previous administration illegally made the payments without a congressional appropriation.   \u2014 If Trump nixes Obamacare subsidy, legal fight could drag on. That's because more than a dozen Democratic state attorneys general can intervene in the case, a federal appeals court ruled Tuesday. The AGs argue the Trump administration, by planning to dismantle Obamacare, doesn't represent their states' interests and therefore their residents could be harmed by its decisions. More for Pros.   Some experts like Jonathan Turley, who was the House's lead counsel at the lower court level but is no longer directly involved in the case, had argued that if the Trump administration dropped the appeal, the case should end.  \u2014Trump's own comments hurt him. The president's threats to eliminate the payments helped support the AGs' case, the court ruled. "In other words, President Trump\u2019s loose lips have once again created problems for his lawyers," Nicholas Bagley writes at The Incidental Economist. "Go figure."  \u2014 One other legal concern. John Bies, who was a top official in the Office of Legal Counsel during the Obama administration, says that the issue for insurers isn't whether the funds were legally appropriated \u2014 it's whether the government made the commitment. \u201cThe only impact of not paying them up front is the headache and additional cost of litigation \u2026 if the insurers sue, they're going to win," Bies said.  \u2014 Lamar Alexander to Trump: Pay the subsidies for now. The chairman of the Senate HELP Committee on Tuesday said he\u2019s urged Trump to pay the subsidies through September so Congress has time to craft a bipartisan stabilization plan that would include one year of funding for the payments.  \u201cWithout payment of these cost-sharing reductions, Americans will be hurt,\u201d Alexander said, adding that any stabilization legislation would need to be narrow and also include greater flexibility for states.  MEANWHILE \u2014 No significant movement on repeal, but some signs for repair. Senate Republicans continued to rebuff the White House's talking points and inch toward possible compromise.  \u2014McConnell: 'Our problem on health care was not the Democrats.' Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell again pushed back against Trump\u2019s pleas to kill the legislative filibuster to pass health care legislation, pointing out that the GOP didn't have sufficient Republican votes for a simple majority.   \u2026 McConnell added that the party still could repeal Obamacare on a party-line vote through budget reconciliation, although didn't suggest the GOP would immediately take up health care again.  \u2014Alexander, Patty Murray plan bipartisan hearings to shore up Obamacare. The chairman and ranking member of the Senate HELP Committee are planning a series of hearings aimed at crafting bipartisan legislation to shore up the markets by mid-September. Alexander emphasized that the work will be bipartisan and that the hearings will feature a range of health policy experts, including state insurance commissioners, patients and insurance industry representatives. More for Pros.  \u2014Lawmakers unmoved by Trump threat to ax money for their insurance. The president has said that if the Senate doesn't repeal the ACA, he'll take away their own health benefits.  "If that's what he wants to do, he ought to just do it," Bob Corker (R-Tenn.) told POLITICO. But as "probably he's learned over the last couple of weeks, threats don't really go over particularly well. My advice would be to either do it or don't do it." More for Pros.  \u000a                            President Donald Trump's threats to stop making key Obamacare payments just hit a major legal hurdle. | Getty  WELCOME TO WEDNESDAY PULSE \u2014 Where in the past week, we've seen the GOP's ACA replacement fail, the "straight repeal" fail, the "skinny repeal" fail and now Trump's threat to implode the market get partially defanged. Safe to say Obamacare had a better 10 days than Anthony Scaramucci? Send tips to ddiamond@politico.com or @ddiamond on Twitter.  With help from Sarah Karlin-Smith (@SarahKarlin) and Adam Cancryn (@AdamCancryn).  McCONNELL MOVES FDA BILL FORWARD \u2013 The Senate majority leader filed a motion to proceed to the FDA user fee reauthorization bill Tuesday night, meaning a procedural vote on the bill should come by Thursday, POLITICO's Sarah Karlin-Smith reports. However, GOP aides said leadership is working on an agreement that could speed up a vote on the bill, H.R. 2430 (115), so it could come sooner this week.  FIRST IN PULSE: MORE INSIDE LOOKS AT THE WHITE HOUSE's HEALTH STRATEGY \u2014 Budget chief Mick Mulvaney helped strategize around the Republican bill's CBO score and HHS Secretary Tom Price's team chipped in to provide political cover as the administration pushed forward on its health care strategy this spring, according to internal documents shared with PULSE.  The documents, which were obtained by the nonpartisan government transparency group American Oversight through a FOIA request, offer a look into how the Trump White House approached Obamacare repeal between January and May.  Among the takeaways from the 2,760-page document dump:  \u2014Mulvaney actively helped coordinate strategy. For instance, Mulvaney traded emails with House Speaker Paul Ryan's policy director about the bill's CBO score \u2014 a week before the CBO issued its devastating initial analysis on Republicans' replacement bill. Mulvaney also held a conference call with Anthem CEO Joe Swedish in mid-March, less than a week after Swedish broke with much of the health care industry to endorse the GOP bill.  \u2014Price and HHS provided cover. With the House's initial vote looming in March, the HHS secretary scheduled a series of one-one-calls that included Rep. Dave Brat (R-Va.) and other skeptical Republicans. Price also scheduled one-on-one calls with Alaska Sens. Lisa Murkowski and Dan Sullivan, who were openly concerned about the impact on their state.  The GOP Doctors Caucus also reached out to Price, scheduling a morning meeting a week before the initial vote and seeking to learn "how the Docs Caucus can be helpful in messaging the ACA replacement.\u201d  \u2026 The emails show how Price and his team were actively involved in providing political cover. \u201cYou and Lance [Leggitt] and the Secretary have been incredibly helpful to us in this process and I want to keep you very looped,\u201d the chief of staff for House Majority Leader Kevin McCarthy told Kristin Skrzycki, one of Price's top deputies. About two hours later, after Price issued letters of support for the reconciliation bills, McCarthy's chief of staff wrote to Skrzycki again: "Super, super helpful. Thank you, thank you."  \u201cIf you could convey your pleasure to the [White House], our operation would appreciate it,\u201d Skrzycki responded. \u201cWe\u2019ll sing praises from the Capitol balcony,\u201d McCarthy's staffer told her.  \u2014The administration redacted a lot. Hundreds of pages of the OMB-related documents were heavily redacted under a statute claiming that the messages were protected as inter-agency or intra-agency communications \u2014 even though the communications were with Congress. For instance, Mulvaney's communications with Ryan and Senate Budget Committee Chairman Mike Enzi were largely blacked out.  "We're very confident that the law will not support these redactions," said Austin Evers, the head of American Oversight who worked as a top lawyer in the Obama administration. "You're not allowed to use redactions to prevent embarrassment, and \u2026 these are deliberations between the administration and the Hill on a catastrophic legislature failure. I can imagine they don't want to show the public how the sausage was not made."  ** A message from PhRMA: ICYMI: National Sheriffs\u2019 Association says importation proposals \u201cwould jeopardize law enforcement\u2019s ability to protect the public health; threaten the safety of our drug supply; and endanger law enforcement officers, their canines, other first responders.\u201d http://onphr.ma/2hl5WFY **    SURGEON GENERAL NOMINEE: GUNS 'AREN\u2019T INHERENTLY A PUBLIC HEALTH PROBLEM' \u2014 The Trump administration\u2019s pick for surgeon general defended gun ownership at his confirmation hearing on Tuesday, arguing that it\u2019s violent criminals \u2014 not the guns they use \u2014 that are the problem.   \u201cWhat we have to do is separate the tool from the perpetrator,\u201d Jerome Adams told the Senate HELP Committee. \u201cGuns and gun owners aren\u2019t inherently a public health problem, but the violence certainly is.\u201d  Adams\u2019 view differs sharply from his predecessor, Vivek Murthy, who had called for stronger gun control efforts. More for Pros.  Giroir ducks Title X funding question. Assistant secretary for health nominee Brett Giroir dodged on whether he thinks all qualified providers should receive Title X family planning funding, saying only that he\u2019ll implement whatever laws Congress passes.   Sen. Patty Murray had tried to pin down Giroir on the program, following GOP efforts to deny funding to Planned Parenthood or defund Title X altogether. But Giroir said he\u2019s \u201cobliged\u201d to enforce any restrictions placed on the program.   Senate HELP Committee reviews nominations of Adams, Giroir and three others today. Their nominations will be considered in executive session.  WSJ interview: Trump focused on speed of deal as benchmark for health plan success. The full transcript from Trump's interview with The Wall Street Journal, which was conducted last Tuesday and scooped by POLITICO's Josh Dawsey and Hadas Gold, featured several asides about the speed of passing a bill, a recurring theme in the president's comments about health care.  The president \u2014 confident that Republicans' health bill would pass, ahead of Sen. John McCain's imminent return to Washington \u2014 bragged that he was far ahead of the pace of former President Barack Obama, who needed "a year and a half" to pass the Affordable Care Act. (It was actually 14 months into his first term.)  Trump also took a similar swing at his one-time presidential rival. "Hillary Clinton, smart person, she was the first lady of the country, her entire life was spent \u2014 her entire eight years was spent trying to get health care. Never even came close," Trump said in the interview. More.  ... Yes, Clinton took a leading role in the failed effort to reform the health system in the early 1990s as a first lady, not an elected politician. But she also played a substantial role in the creation of the Children's Health Insurance Program, which covers millions of kids.   Part D premiums drop slightly. The average base monthly premium is $35, CMS announced this week, and it's the first time in five years that the average plan premium will drop, consulting group Avalere pointed out on Tuesday.   CVS implements new value-based drug programs. The nation's largest pharmacy benefit manager announced new programs for several types of cancer, obesity treatments and chronic obstructive pulmonary disorder drugs as part of its 2018 prescription drug formulary.  The programs will require drug companies to provide CVS with \u201cadditional value\u201d if certain targets aren\u2019t met; manufacturers would be required to offer additional value if patients don\u2019t achieve a minimum level of weight reduction on obesity medicines, for example.   \u2026 It wasn't immediately clear what CVS means by \u201cadded value\u201d and how drug companies would compensate CVS and health plans in these instances, Sarah Karlin-Smith points out. But CVS says the programs are designed to align reimbursement to a pre-defined outcome (outcomes-based management) or establish a cost threshold based on expected utilization of a drug (cost cap-based contracting.) CVS excluded 17 new drugs on its standard formulary in 2018.  California: Obamacare rate hike would be 12.5 percent, but 24.9 percent if Trump kills Obamacare payments. Exchange officials warn the price of some plans would even double if the federal government stops funding critical Obamacare cost-sharing payments that defray the cost of covering low-income residents.   In what Covered California head Peter Lee called the "best worst-case scenario," the exchange will add a 12.4 percent surcharge on benchmark silver-tiered plans to reflect the lost federal payments. Consumers on those plans would then receive higher subsidies to offset the added cost. And insurers will offer comparable coverage outside the exchange for people who don't qualify for subsidies. More for Pros.  \u2026 Although all 11 plans offering coverage in the exchange will continue to sell next year, industry giant Anthem Blue Cross is dramatically shrinking its footprint. The insurer will only sell in three regions next year, down from 19 this year.  By Victoria Colliver  The Washington Post\u2019s Carolyn Y. Johnson looks at the trajectory of a generic epilepsy drug to show why the generic drugs industry is failing to be the savior of drug prices. More.   Also writing in the Washington Post, conservatives Lanhee Chen and Tevi Troy offer a range of legislative and regulatory strategies for Republicans seeking to fix Obamacare and address problems in health care. More.  Brian Hawkins, the longtime head of Washington's VA Medical Center, has been fired for mismanagement problems such as unsanitary conditions and lack of supplies, NBC4 Washington\u2019s Scott MacFarlane reports. More.   A lobbyist group for doctors and their insurers is taking credit for pushing malpractice legislation through the House, the Washington Post\u2019s Kimberly Kindy writes. More.   Vox\u2019s Dylan Scott gives us this handy guide to the next four months of Obamacare deadlines. More.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
