aV \u000a            By DAN DIAMOND (ddiamond@politico.com; @ddiamond)  07/31/2017 10:00 AM EDT  MUST-READ: "How Republicans got stuck on repeal," by POLITICO's Jennifer Haberkorn, who offers a sweeping look at how a promise to repeal-and-replace the ACA on Day 1 turned into a six-month morass that they still don't know how to get out of. More.  DECISION ON OBAMACARE SUBSIDIES COMING \u2014 MAYBE BY TOMORROW. Senior administration officials are meeting with President Donald Trump on Tuesday to discuss the billions of dollars that are owed to insurance companies through Obamacare's cost-sharing reduction (CSR) program, two administration sources tell POLITICO. A decision could be made at that meeting and announced shortly thereafter.  Story Continued Below  Trump has repeatedly threatened to yank the subsidies as leverage to force Congress to act on repeal. But \u2014 so far \u2014 the administration has made the monthly payments.  HOW THE SUBSIDY THREAT COULD BACKFIRE \u2014 If Trump does pull the subsidies now, the ACA markets could swiftly implode as insurers pull out, rather than risk massive losses, or they could hike their prices to make up for the lost funding. Either outcome would have immediate effects for the 10 million Americans who shop the exchanges and the millions more who shop off of them.  But canceling the subsidies could trigger multiple problems for Trump.  \u2014 Problem #1: The feds might end up spending more next year. Even if the subsidies get pulled, "we expect most [insurers] who have filed an initial application for 2018 to remain in the marketplace," Standard and Poors wrote on Friday. But the plans would look for ways to offset the lost funding, most likely hiking the prices of their benchmark silver plans. That means the value of the ACA's tax credits would go up dramatically and the federal government would spend more.  "If issuers loaded the cost of unfunded CSRs onto their silver plans, as we think they will, lower-income people could qualify for very low cost or free bronze coverage and for gold plans at relatively low premiums," Kurt Giesa of Oliver Wyman told PULSE. That could lure new customers, Giesa added, and "this could cost the federal government a substantial amount in new premium subsidies."  An earlier Kaiser Family Foundation estimate projected that defunding the CSRs would cost taxpayers an additional $2.3 billion.  \u2014 Problem #2: There would likely be lawsuits. Insurers have signaled that they'd sue over CSRs and there's precedent to believe them.  There already are nearly two dozen active lawsuits over the ACA's risk corridor payments, which Republicans in Congress significantly restricted, POLITICO's Paul Demko writes. \u201c[The Obama administration] repeatedly assured us it was there and it would be a clear obligation of the government,\u201d said Tom Policelli, CEO of Minuteman Health, which is among those suing the government. \u201cEven the federal government is subject to the rules.\u201d More for Pros.  \u2014 Problem #3: There could be more momentum on Capitol Hill to address CSRs. Bipartisan lawmakers in both chambers have said the payments need to be made, and funding was included in the now-abandoned Obamacare repeal-and-replacement bill.  "I\u2019m troubled by the uncertainty that has been created by the administration," Maine Sen. Susan Collins \u2014 a key holdout on the ACA repeal bill \u2014 said on "Meet the Press" on Sunday. "That\u2019s one thing that Congress needs to end. We need to make very clear that that subsidy is important to those very low income people and we need to appropriate the money to ensure that it continues." But the eagerness to prop up ACA markets isn't shared by all Republicans.  CENTRIST LAWMAKERS WANT TO FUND CSRs \u2014 The Problem Solvers caucus, a bipartisan group of 43 House lawmakers that includes notable names like GOP Rep. Fred Upton, will release a package of proposals today that include funding Obamacare's subsidies, POLITICO's Heather Caygle and Paul Demko scooped last night.  The group also wants to:  \u2014 Change Obamacare's employer mandate so that it applies only to companies with more than 500 workers.  \u2014 Create a federal stability fund that states can tap to reduce premiums and other costs for people with extremely expensive medical needs.  \u2014 Scrap Obamacare\u2019s medical-device tax, an idea that has received bipartisan support in the past.  More.  \u2026 The proposal got plaudits from Andy Slavitt, who led CMS during the Obama administration. \u201cI think it\u2019s a really serious and good start that can be worked through,\u201d he said. \u201cI hope it becomes the basis for further conversations and agreement.\u201d   \u000a                            President Donald Trump is weighing a strategy to gut key pieces of Obamacare. | Getty  TOM PRICE DANCES AROUND TRUMP's 'LET IT IMPLODE' COMMENTS \u2014 The HHS Secretary was repeatedly asked by ABC's Martha Raddatz to clarify: Will the president take actions to make the ACA collapse?  "'Let Obamacare implode, then deal,'" Raddatz said, referencing Trump's tweets and comments. "What does that mean?"  "I think what that does is punctuate the seriousness with which he understands the American people are having to deal with the current situation," Price responded.  \u2026 Price did say on "Meet the Press" that he would "follow the law of the land" \u2014 but added that Americans' "health and wellbeing is being harmed right now by the current law."  REGULATORS CALL ON CONGRESS TO FIX MARKETS BEFORE AUGUST RECESS \u2014 The National Association of Insurance Commissioners on Friday also urged lawmakers to immediately fund the CSRs through 2018 and appropriate other funds long-term to help states shore up their markets.  Their statement: "We are deeply concerned that Washington's preoccupation with the political ramifications of this debate distract from the real-world implications being felt, as we speak, by Americans who are simply trying to go to the doctor, get care, or battle illness and find a way to pay for it all for themselves and their loved ones."  WELCOME BACK TO PULSE \u2014 Where we're always ready to cover the health care battle. Tips to ddiamond@politico.com or @ddiamond on Twitter.  With help from Paul Demko (@PaulDemko)  SENATORS BRAINSTORMING NEW REPEAL EFFORT \u2014 Sens. Lindsey Graham, Bill Cassidy and Dean Heller met with the White House on Friday in an attempt to write legislation that could get 50 Republican votes, POLITICO's Burgess Everett, Josh Dawsey and Rachael Bade reported.   The proposal would block grant federal health care funding to the states and keep much of Obamacare\u2019s tax regime. White House officials also met with House Freedom Caucus chairman Mark Meadows (R-N.C.) to brainstorm how to make the idea palatable to conservatives, according to two sources familiar with the meeting. More.  MORE FALLOUT  \u2014 Administration eyes ways to weaken the ACA. The White House for months has taken steps to undercut the ACA independent from Congress, POLITICO's Rachana Pradhan writes. Friday's collapse of Senate Republicans' slimmed-down repeal bill could push Trump to escalate those efforts, possibly by taking aim at the law's individual mandate. More for Pros.  \u2014 What it would take to save Obamacare. House and Senate lawmakers have already begun to contemplate a series of bipartisan fixes meant to shore up the Obamacare markets and prevent mass insurer defections, POLITICO's Adam Cancryn writes. But those efforts \u2014 and the future of Obamacare markets serving roughly 10 million people \u2014 depend largely on whether GOP leadership is willing to set aside its repeal pledge after seven years. More for Pros.  \u2014 The new rules of health reform. The months-long repeal process \u2014 and its ultimate collapse \u2014 was a reminder of some old unbreakable rules of health reform, and a look at new rules going forward, your PULSE author writes. More for Pros.  MEANWHILE: TRUMP WANTS GOP TO VOTE AGAIN ON OBAMACARE \u2014 The president spent the weekend taunting Congress to stop being "quitters," at one point threatening to take away their own health insurance coverage. (He can't.)  \u2014 Mick Mulvaney says Congress shouldn't vote on anything else. The budget chief said all other legislation \u2014 including on raising the debt ceiling \u2014 must wait. "In the White House's view, they can't move on in the Senate," Mulvaney said on CNN's "State of the Union." "You can't promise folks you're going to do something for seven years, and then not do it."  BUT THE MATH DOESN'T WORK \u2014 Unless Collins or Sen. Lisa Murkowski flip after months after opposition to permutations of the current bill, Sen. John McCain's absence for weeks to treat his brain cancer will lock the GOP at a 49-vote ceiling on Obamacare repeal efforts.  STATE WEEK: CHIP fight could be looming next. Congress is brushing up against its deadline to reauthorize CHIP by the end of September, and state health officials are anxiously awaiting assurances from Capitol Hill that the program will quickly be approved, POLITICO's Brianna Ehley reports. More for Pros.  By Jennifer Haberkorn  Sen. Bernie Sanders told CNN that he's preparing to introduce a single-payer health care bill. More.  Sen. Chuck Schumer wants the FDA to investigate the health consequences of chemicals used in fast food packaging, the AP reports. More.  Republicans' failures to repeal Obamacare prove that it's officially become the nation\u2019s health care system, Kaiser Family Foundation\u2019s Drew Altman and Larry Levitt argue in The Washington Post. More.  John Fund in National Review skewers Sen. John McCain as one of the \u201cstandard-issue politicians he likes to rail against.\u201d More.  Conservative pundit Tomi Lahren, who is critical of Obamacare, says she's on her parents\u2019 health insurance plan because she\u2019s under 26 \u2014a key ACA protection. More.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
