aV \u000a            By DAN DIAMOND (ddiamond@politico.com; @ddiamond)  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  WHAT HAPPENED AND WHAT'S NEXT  Senate Republicans' years-long push to repeal Obamacare is dead \u2014 for now \u2014after a shocking late-night defeat. And that will put the short-term focus back on HHS and the Trump administration, which again face looming decisions about the fate of the ACA markets.  Story Continued Below  49-51. That was the margin of the Senate vote and at 1:38 a.m. today, Majority Leader Mitch McConnell declared defeat and pulled the Obamacare repeal reconciliation measure from the floor.   Republicans left the Capitol in the early hours of Friday morning disappointed in the defeat. Some said they were privately relieved now that two months of high drama are over. But what's next is uncertain.  The GOP thought they had the votes; Senate leadership was optimistic throughout the day and Vice President Mike Pence made a near-midnight trip to the Capitol to break a tie if Sens. Susan Collins and Lisa Murkowski joined with Democrats as expected. But Sen. John McCain \u2014 after cryptically telling reporters "watch the show" \u2014 broke with his party and withstood furious lobbying. His vote against the bill provoked audible gasps and scattered applause. Watch that moment.  POLITICO's John Bresnahan, Burgess Everett, Jennifer Haberkorn and Seung Min Kim have details from the gripping floor drama. More for Pros.  McCONNELL: 'A DISAPPOINTMENT INDEED' \u2014 Speaking after the failed vote, the majority leader blamed Democrats for not engaging "in a serious way" in efforts to patch the health care law. "I imagine many of our colleagues on the other side are celebrating, probably pretty happy about this," a seemingly stunned McConnell said from the floor.   'IT'S TIME TO MOVE ON' \u2014 McConnell quickly pivoted to possible fixes. "The American people are hurting and they need relief," he said, adding that Democrats needed to play a constructive role after months of blocking Republicans. "What are their ideas?" McConnell said. "It'll be interesting to see what they suggest as the way forward."  While members of both parties have called for stabilizing the fragile individual insurance market, McConnell didn't explicitly endorse that plan in his brief remarks. "[The] bailing out of insurance companies, without any kind of reform, is not something I want to be part of," McConnell said.  McCAIN: 'I THOUGHT IT WAS THE RIGHT THING TO DO' \u2014 That's what the Arizona senator said as he left the Capitol, although he didn't want to get into his reasoning for joining Collins and Murkowski, who have consistently held out against Republicans' efforts. But he also criticized the ACA as a flawed law and again urged the Senate to return to regular order and hold hearings on health care.   Thursday afternoon, McCain had called for bipartisanship as the only way to avoid years more of destructive conflict.  Before voting no, McCain was lobbied in-person by Pence and spoke with President Donald Trump by phone, rebuffing them both.  MUST-READ: 'How McCain upended Obamacare repeal' by Seung Min Kim, Burgess Everett and Jennifer Haberkorn.  TRUMP WEIGHS IN: 'LET OBAMACARE IMPLODE' \u2014 "3 Republicans and 48 Democrats let the American people down," Trump posted on Twitter at 2:25 a.m., about an hour after the vote. "As I said from the beginning, let ObamaCare implode, then deal. Watch!"  WHAT ABOUT TOM PRICE? \u2014 Trump had said, only part-jokingly, that the HHS secretary's job was in jeopardy if the bill didn't pass.  And even if Price stays, there are real questions about the role that he and his agency will play now that the avowed opponent of Obamacare is stuck \u2014 again \u2014 with overseeing the law's fragile markets. Industry leaders have said they've had productive conversations with Price in private, but his public attacks on the ACA have contributed to waning confidence in the program's future.   The GAO is reportedly investigating if HHS broke the law by using government resources to promote Republicans' repeal plan.  AND WILL HHS PAY OUT COST-SHARING REDUCTIONS? \u2014 The next payment to insurers participating in the ACA markets is looming in three weeks, and the administration has played high-stakes chicken with the payments for months.  THANK GOODNESS IT'S FRIDAY PULSE \u2014 REALLY, TGIF. Your author is heading to California for POLITICON and hoping to catch a few Zzzs on the plane. But you can always tip him at ddiamond@politico.com or @ddiamond on Twitter.  Shout-outs to POLITICO's late-night health care crew: reporter Jennifer Haberkorn (@JenHab), Paul Demko (@PaulDemko), Rachana Pradhan (@RachanaDixit) and editors Jason Millman (@JasonMillman), Adriel Bettelheim (@abettel) and the inimitable Joanne Kenen (@JoanneKenen).  \u000a                            Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell said "it's time to move on" after the GOP health vote failed.. | Getty  CASSIDY: 'MAYBE IT CHANGES NOW' FOR BIPARTISAN APPROACH \u2014 The Louisiana senator said he was surprised and disappointed after the vote, but slightly optimistic that the grueling fight over repeal was a necessary step before moving to collaboration.  "I\u2019ve always been open to [working with] Democrats," Sen. Bill Cassidy told POLITICO's Paul Demko. He added that the "Cassidy-Collins [plan] was written specifically to get Democrats on board \u2026 but no one would work with us. If I sound frustrated and angry about that, that\u2019s true, but maybe it changes now.\u201d  ** A message from PhRMA: ICYMI: National Sheriffs\u2019 Association says importation proposals \u201cwould jeopardize law enforcement\u2019s ability to protect the public health; threaten the safety of our drug supply; and endanger law enforcement officers, their canines, other first responders.\u201d http://onphr.ma/2hl5WFY **  INDUSTRY, ADVOCATES RESPOND  Insurers: We need market fixes ASAP. Both AHIP and the Alliance of Community Health Plans on Thursday had urged the Senate to abandon their skinny repeal plan and instead focus on shoring up the fragile individual insurance markets.  \u201cWithout adequate financing and some form of a continuous coverage mechanism, we fear the individual market is unsustainable,\u201d read a letter from ACHP chief executive Ceci Connolly.  Activists: We still have massive rallies this weekend. Obamacare supporters are still planning on going ahead with a coast-to-coast series of 125 events called "Our Lives Are On The Line," including a national event with House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi and 60 partner organizations in Washington, D.C.'s Freedom Plaza on Saturday evening. The groups also are launching a new initiative called "Health Care Voter" to distribute pledge cards to supporters that are intended to keep elected officials accountable.  Meanwhile, a five-week-long "Drive For Our Lives" bus tour kicks off on Saturday from Los Angeles and will travel to 18 states, with advocates and leaders like former HHS Secretary Kathleen Sebelius and Virginia Gov. Terry McAuliffe scheduled to join.  Iowa: Medica was spooked by 'skinny' repeal. The last insurer standing in the state's Obamacare exchange had been alarmed by the Senate's plan. "If they repeal the individual mandate and do nothing else, they will be taking the one action universally understood to be bad," Medica VP Geoff Bartsh told the Des Moines Register. "Premiums go up and the market becomes more unstable." More.  Alliance for Health Policy talks prescription drug affordability. Scheduled to speak at the 11:45 a.m. discussion in Dirksen: Former Rep. Henry Waxman; Joel White of the Council for Affordable Health Coverage; Steve Miller of Express Scripts; David Mitchell of Patients for Affordable Drugs; and PhRMA's Robert Zirkelbach. More.  Francis Collins, Nora Volkow outline NIH-industry work on opioids. The NIH director and the director of the National Institute on Drug Abuse write in NEJM about how they're working to address the epidemic. "Recent NIH\u2013industry partnerships, such as the Accelerating Medicines Partnership, demonstrate the power of public\u2013private collaboration in speeding the development of new medications," they write. "Ending the opioid crisis will require this kind of collaboration." More.  Breitbart's Joel Pollak argues that Trump has a "golden opportunity" to push a new health policy, where the government would provide free, basic care for everyone and optional private insurance covers everything else. More.  The New York Times looks at the Obama administration alumni who were loudly cheerleading against the GOP repeal bill. More.   Also in The New York Times, Jan Hoffman profiles the patients who have been anxiously watching the health care debate because they're worried their own care is threatened. More.  Some Minneapolis restaurants are adding a surcharge to diners' tabs that they say is necessary to pay for staff health insurance. More.  At HealthLeaders, Tinker Ready looks at why hospital rankings are so complicated. More.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
