aV \u000a            By DAN DIAMOND (ddiamond@politico.com; @ddiamond)  07/27/2017 10:00 AM EDT  A Trump administration Cabinet secretary reportedly threatened Alaska over Sen. Lisa Murkowski's holdout on health care, and a bipartisan group of 10 governors has come out against the Senate GOP's latest repeal plan.  But first \u2014 the fight over Obamacare in the Senate has increasingly centered on two questions: Will Republicans support a "skinny" repeal bill, and what will be in it?  Story Continued Below  'SKINNY' BILL NOT GETTING HEFTY SUPPORT YET \u2014 Both centrist and conservative Republican senators are raising concerns about the so-called skinny repeal, which would roll back the ACA's individual and employer mandates and a handful of other provisions while leaving much of the rest of the law intact.  \u201cI don\u2019t like it,\u201d said Sen. David Perdue of Georgia, a reliably conservative member. \u201cBecause I don\u2019t know where we end up. This whole [health care system] holds together or falls apart in totality. We\u2019ve got a system that is collapsing.\u201d  Centrist GOP Sens. Rob Portman of Ohio and Shelley Moore Capito of West Virginia were undecided. Another Republican from a Medicaid expansion state, Sen. Dean Heller of Nevada indicated he would back it. POLITICO stalwarts Burgess Everett, Jennifer Haberkorn and Seung Min Kim go deeper: More.  \u2014 House GOP isn't a fan of idea. Leaders privately worry that vulnerable House Republicans have already taken tough votes \u2014 cutting $800 billion from Medicaid, for instance \u2014 that their Senate GOP colleagues refuse to support, exposing those House members to serious political jeopardy in November 2018, POLITICO's John Bresnahan reports. More.  \u2014 Conservative groups aren't embracing it, either. \u201cA skinny repeal just kicks the can down the road,\u201d Andy Roth of Club for Growth told POLITICO's Adam Cancryn. \u201cAnd then what? They will find their principles and courage then? Doubtful.\u201d More for Pros.  DEMS THREATEN TO SIT OUT UNTIL 'SKINNY' BILL RELEASED \u2014 The minority party says it won't offer amendments in the interim, POLITICO's Seung Min Kim reports. \u201cOnce the majority leader shows his hand, reveals what his bill will actually be, Democrats will use the opportunity to try and amend the bill," Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer announced on Wednesday night. More.  Meanwhile, wonks and the CBO took a crack at modeling what a skimpier version of repeal would mean for the markets.  'SKINNY' REPEAL'S OUTSIZED IMPACT \u2014 Dropping the individual mandate would almost certainly mean young and healthy people will drop coverage and take their chances, while older and sicker people stay in Obamacare markets and drive up insurance prices. \u201cThere\u2019s no doubt it would increase premiums,\u201d said Larry Levitt, senior vice president for special initiatives at the Kaiser Family Foundation, even if experts don\u2019t agree on quite how much.  CBO ESTIMATE: 16 MILLION MORE UNINSURED NEXT YEAR \u2014 That's according to an estimate of a mockup bill requested by Senate Democrats and shared Wednesday. Under the projection, 44 million Americans would be uninsured by 2024, up from 28 million under current law.  The mockup included repealing Obamacare\u2019s individual and employer mandates, medical device tax, community health center funding and prevention fund, in addition to defunding Planned Parenthood \u2014 all changes that the GOP is reportedly considering.  \u2014 Another estimate: Premiums go up by 20 percent. That's according to an analysis by the liberal Center for American Progress, which offered a state-by-state projection of the impact.  \u2014 But a death spiral is unlikely for the Obamacare markets, experts say. Why? Because generous subsidies would remain in place, which more than 80 percent of Obamacare customers receive, POLITICO's Paul Demko writes. That means they\u2019re largely protected from big premium increases and would have little incentive to drop their coverage. More for Pros  The final bill will almost certainly be different from the mockups that CBO and analysts are reviewing, partly in order to meet budget reconciliation requirements, which is one reason why Republicans said \u2026   GOP: DON'T READ INTO CBO ESTIMATE \u2014 Senate Republicans downplayed the estimate as preliminary. "It's speculation written up by some [Democratic] staffers," said one Republican aide. "That's embarrassing on their part. CBO hasn\u2019t issued any new score."  PESKY BUDGET CONCERNS \u2014 While there had been speculation that amendments authored by Sens. Ted Cruz and Rob Portman might be included in skinny repeal, CBO's estimate of Democrats' mockup suggests it wouldn't be possible to add those amendments and still achieve the $133 billion in deficit reduction from the House bill.  "This achieves less deficit reduction than I expected and would not comply with Senate rule requiring [that] amendments to reconciliation bill not reduce deficit reduction because on-budget savings are less than House bill," said Ed Lorenzen of the Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget, reviewing the estimate. CBO projected $130 billion in net deficit savings and just $78 billion in on-budget savings over the next decade, based on the mockup of the Senate GOP bill.   WHITE HOUSE REPORTEDLY THREATENS ALASKA OVER MURKOWSKI VOTE \u2014 Interior Secretary Ryan Zinke called both of Alaska's senators on Wednesday to alert them that Murkowski's opposition on this week's motion to proceed vote was putting projects at risk across the state, Erica Martinson reports for the Alaska Dispatch News. Alaska leaders have been working with the administration on priorities like new drilling opportunities and building a major road.  Zinke's call was a "troubling message," said Sen. Dan Sullivan. "I'm not going to go into the details, but I fear that the strong economic growth, pro-energy, pro-mining, pro-jobs and personnel from Alaska who are part of those policies are going to stop," he added. More.  \u000a                            President Donald Trump's administration reportedly threatened Alaska over Sen. Lisa Murkowski's holdout vote on health care. | Getty  THIS IS THURSDAY PULSE \u2014 Where we want you to keep reading. (But we'll never threaten you if you quit.) Send tips to ddiamond@politico.com or @ddiamond on Twitter.  With help from Paul Demko (@PaulDemko), Brianna Ehley (@BriannaEhley) and Victoria Colliver (@vcolliver)  WHAT'S ON TAP TODAY \u2014An amendment offered by Sen. Steve Daines (R-Mont.) that would expand Medicare to the entire U.S. population is currently teed up for a vote at 2:15 p.m. ET. While Daines doesn't support the single-payer measure, it would force Democrats to cast a much-watched vote on single-payer health care, an emerging issue for their progressive supporters.  About 10 hours of debate are still remaining, which means that unless either side gives up time, the earliest that vote-a-rama could start is at 8 p.m. tonight.  PULSE CHECK: Ben Wikler says 'the Resistance' isn't futile. The Washington director of MoveOn.org defends progressives' fight against the Trump agenda and says they've already won a major victory by simply delaying the health care repeal process. Listen here.  ** A message from PhRMA: ICYMI: National Sheriffs\u2019 Association says importation proposals \u201cwould jeopardize law enforcement\u2019s ability to protect the public health; threaten the safety of our drug supply; and endanger law enforcement officers, their canines, other first responders.\u201d http://onphr.ma/2hl5WFY **    10 GOVERNORS SPEAK OUT AGAINST SENATE 'SKINNY' REPEAL \u2014The bipartisan letter to Senate leaders includes five Republican governors, who join their Democratic colleagues to warn that the plan as currently reported will drive insurers from the market and lead to higher premiums.  Those GOP governors: Nevada's Brian Sandoval, Massachusetts' Charles Baker, Ohio's John Kasich, Maryland's Larry Hogan and Vermont's Phil Scott. See the letter.  SKIMPY BILL IS 'TROJAN HORSE' FOR BIGGER CHANGES\u2014 That's according to Bob Greenstein at the Center for Budget and Policy Priorities, who argues that Senate Republicans who vote the measure through will enable House Republicans to make deeper health cuts during conference negotiations. More.  "The 'skinny repeal' bill is a Trojan horse designed to resuscitate the effort to repeal large parts of the ACA and impose big Medicaid cuts that would jeopardize coverage for millions of the nation\u2019s neediest people," Greenstein writes. "By contrast, if the Senate rejects [it] this week, the bipartisan process that \u2026 both parties are advocating could finally commence."  \u2014Study: ACA reduced health disparities. A new study published in Health Affairs shows the Affordable Care Act significantly reduced the gap in health disparities among low-income and high-income earners.   Boston University School of Public Health researchers found that states that expanded their Medicaid programs under the ACA saw the insurance coverage gap between people with incomes below $25,000 and people earning more than $75,000 annually fell by 46 percent between 2013 and 2015. In states that did not expand their Medicaid programs, that coverage gap fell by 23 percent. The study also found income gaps in access to primary care doctors. More here.  Value of health care transactions soared in second quarter. The health care industry completed 219 deals totaling nearly $50 billion in the second quarter of this year, according to the latest figures from consultancy PwC.   The number of transactions fell by 15 percent compared to the same period in 2016, but the value of those deals skyrocketed by 201 percent. The reason: 10 \u201cmegadeals\u201d \u2014 defined as more than $1 billion \u2014 that accounted for almost 90 percent of the monetary value. Pros can read the report here.   Centrist Republicans are banding together and undermining House GOP leaders. Some in the moderate Tuesday Group have started to adopt the power-in-numbers strategy of the Freedom Caucus. And the get-tough approach is yielding results, POLITICO's Rachael Bade reports.  Resistance from moderates almost torpedoed the House Obamacare replacement this spring, and resulted in billions in additional funding to help people with pre-existing conditions \u2014 a requirement for some centrists' support. \u201cThey rely on us to achieve outcomes that they can\u2019t always advocate themselves, okay? And please, use that on the record,\u201d said Tuesday Group co-leader Charlie Dent. More.  House resoundingly rejects efforts to cut CBO. For all their complaints, it turns out many House Republicans will come to the defense of the nonpartisan scorekeeper when push comes to shove. Working through a four-bill spending package, the House voted Wednesday evening to reject two amendments that would drastically slash funding for CBO amid ongoing Republican criticism of the way the office has handled estimates of plans to repeal and replace Obamacare. More for Pros.  Having a baby in California? You might want to Yelp that. Yelp has teamed up with the California Health Care Foundation and Cal Hospital Compare to offer quality ratings for maternity care on all the hospitals in the state that deliver babies, POLITICO's Victoria Colliver reports.  Expectant parents can go on the site to find out, for example, how many C-sections are performed, the hospital\u2019s breastfeeding success and episiotomy rates, and whether vaginal births after C-sections are offered. The ratings will only be available for maternity care at California hospitals for now, but Yelp hopes to roll out to other states with additional partnerships.  Hal Wolf named new head of HIMSS. The former Kaiser executive succeeds Steve Lieber, who announced late last year he was retiring after more than 17 years leading the massive health IT trade group. Wolf is expected to start in September and assume full duties by the end of the year.  Buchalter adds three to its health care practice. Andy Selesnick and Damaris Medina \u2014 both formerly of Nixon Peabody \u2014 and Suzanne Cate Jones, who was with Theodora Oringher, have joined as shareholders in Buchalter's health care practice in Los Angeles.  A subsidy offered to lure Aetna to New York state would benefit one of Gov. Andrew Cuomo\u2019s donors, IBT\u2019s Jay Cassano and David Sirota write. More.  House Republicans blocked a bill that would have let VA doctors prescribe pot for pain. More.  Amazon reportedly has a secret skunkworks team dedicated to health care technology projects, CNBC\u2019s Eugene Kim and Christina Farr report. More.  At Health News Review, Trudy Lieberman scrutinizes the industry-backed campaign pushing to roll back the ACA\u2019s Independent Payment Advisory Board. More.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
