aV \u000a            By DAN DIAMOND (ddiamond@politico.com; @ddiamond)  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  WHAT'S NEXT: COMPLICATIONS, UNPREDICTABLE CHOICES AND NO GUARANTEES \u2014 Though the GOP succeeded at bringing their health repeal effort to the floor, there's no guarantee they'll emerge from a multi-day effort with a full or partial repeal of Obamacare, POLITICO's Paul Demko points out.   One point of evidence: Last night's failed vote on the Senate GOP's revised repeal-and-replace package. Nine Republicans joined with Democrats to defeat the measure \u2014 and it only gets trickier from here.  Story Continued Below  Here's what to watch in the days ahead.  \u2014 Today: Vote on the repeal-only bill. The bill will almost certainly fail, given objections by moderates who worry about striking down the ACA's coverage expansion without a replacement.   But allowing the straight repeal vote is necessary to get legislation to the floor, Paul Demko points out. It allows conservative hardliners like Sens. Rand Paul and Mike Lee to tell voters they followed through on campaign promises to dismantle the Affordable Care Act.  It will also give conservative advocacy groups, still crusading for repeal, a chance to hold accountable any senators who vote no on the bill. The advocates may seek to sic primary challengers on senators who fail to back straight repeal.  \u2014 Probably tomorrow: Vote-a-rama begins. Both parties will get a chance to offer amendments to the bill and, theoretically, the process allows for unlimited amendments as long as they are relevant. (Democratic Sen. Chris Murphy reportedly has "100 amendments" ready to go.) At least a few dozen will likely be voted on.  Here's where Democrats get to offer a laundry list of ideas and force Republicans to take tricky votes. That could include efforts to stabilize the Obamacare markets, such as seeking funding for cost-sharing subsidies that the Trump administration has threatened to eliminate \u2014 which could make the markets implode.  \u2014 Parliamentarian review. To keep provisions flagged by the parliamentarian as a no-go, the GOP could try to get 60 votes \u2014 a nonstarter with every Democrat opposed. Or Republicans can try to modify the language to past muster. For instance, the party already tweaked language about defunding Planned Parenthood that the parliamentarian had flagged.  Earlier on Tuesday, the parliamentarian ruled against two key provisions in the GOP plan \u2014 to change age rating and ease the creation of "association health plans" for small businesses. More for Pros.  \u2014 Fallback: A 'skinny' repeal. As a last-ditch effort, Republicans are floating a stripped-down package that would scrap the individual and employer mandates and the medical device tax. While no senators would like the measure, they might vote for it to keep the repeal drive going \u2014 and to negotiate with the House on a compromise package. It's not clear that even the fallback measure can garner the 50 votes needed to pass. More.  \u000a                            Sen. Mitch McConnell brought a defunct ACA repeal bill back from the dead. | Getty  HOW THE GOP BROUGHT ACA REPEAL BACK \u2014 Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell fed a steady diet of reminders to holdout senators that boiled down to a simple message: A vote against even debating Obamacare repeal is a vote to keep it in place.  That won over conservatives like Rand Paul and even a vulnerable incumbent like Sen. Dean Heller. Once Sen. John McCain announced he'd be returning to the chamber for the vote, GOP leaders say they knew they had momentum and a chance to win.  POLITICO's Burgess Everett, Seung Min Kim and Jennifer Haberkorn tell the story from inside the caucus. Keep reading: More.  \u2014'He played good cop, bad cop all by himself.' McConnell used a combination of hardball politics, personal persuasion and lots of money \u2014 hundreds of billions of dollars were available to pay for more add-ons to the bill in order to get some votes \u2014to round up 50 Republicans to support the motion to proceed to the bill. POLITICO's John Bresnahan goes inside the victory. More.  RON JOHNSON WAS A KEY HOLDOUT \u2014 By the end, the Wisconsin senator, who had accused McConnell of a "breach of trust" over plans to cut Medicaid, was the last Republican to decide on the motion \u2014 and the final member of his party to cast a vote.  The tensions were on full display: When Johnson finally emerged on the Senate floor on Tuesday afternoon, he headed to McConnell\u2019s desk and the two engaged in a tense, 10-minute face-to-face talk. McConnell\u2019s face turned increasingly red, and the GOP leader threw up his hands multiple times.  "He was expressing some of his frustration," said Senate Majority Whip John Cornyn, who watched the fiery colloquy with his arms crossed and a grimace on his face. "But I\u2019m glad he voted to proceed to the bill."  WHAT MIKE LEE'S TEXT MESSAGES REVEAL \u2014 The Utah senator, returning on a flight to Washington on Monday, was spotted texting his concerns by an eyewitness who described the messages to POLITICO.  In one text, Lee told a recipient that he might still vote to proceed to the repeal debate, but that it was \u201cstill too early to do so in good conscience because we\u2019re not being told anything.\u201d  \u201cThis leadership line of pass something, anything, is dangerous and potent,\u201d Lee typed out in another message, written in large enough font that fellow passengers could easily read his words, according to the eyewitness. In another text, Lee wrote: \u201cThis bill is nothing more than bailing out insurance companies with a few minor reforms thrown in for good measure.\u201d  Lee's office didn't dispute the messages when asked.  MEANWHILE \u2014the nine Republicans who voted against BCRA. Sens. Rand Paul, Lindsey Graham, Dean Heller, Jerry Moran, Tom Cotton, Mike Lee, Bob Corker, Lisa Murkowski and Susan Collins joined Democrats in opposition to the modified bill. It included a proposal from Texas Sen. Ted Cruz allowing insurers to sell plans that don't comply with several Obamacare rules for coverage, and a proposal from Sen. Rob Portman adding $100 billion to the replacement plan to help Medicaid expansion enrollees purchase private insurance. More for Pros.  McCain \u2014 hours after vowing, in an attack on the Senate's health care process, that he couldn't vote for the bill as written \u2014did vote for this modified version of BCRA.   WELCOME TO WEDNESDAY PULSE \u2014 Where as July leans into August, we realized that health care ate our summer vacation (and our summer reading list along with it). What's been your favorite book to escape from Washington's political fights? Send picks and tips to ddiamond@politico.com or @ddiamond on Twitter.  With help from Renuka Rayasam (@RenuRayasam)  Actuaries urge Senate GOP to take up fixes to insurance markets. "As senators consider their votes on any legislation, ensuring the sustainability and stability of markets should be front of mind," said Cori Uccello of the American Academy of Actuaries, urging the Senate to permanently fund cost-sharing reduction payments to insurers and increase funding to help defray the cost of premiums.  The actuaries also urged the GOP to use their insights as they seek to dismantle the Affordable Care Act. \u201cLegislators can draw on the actuarial profession\u2019s expertise during this consequential moment for the health care system,\u201d Uccello reminded lawmakers.  ** A message from PhRMA: ICYMI: National Sheriffs\u2019 Association says importation proposals \u201cwould jeopardize law enforcement\u2019s ability to protect the public health; threaten the safety of our drug supply; and endanger law enforcement officers, their canines, other first responders.\u201d http://onphr.ma/2hl5WFY **  Senate Dems plan to drop nominations blockade if health effort fails. While Democrats have dragged out confirmations while the chamber remained mired in the health care debate, they\u2019re pledging to drop their blockade if the GOP\u2019s Obamacare repeal effort fails, POLITICO reports.   The GOP also claims that Democrats aren\u2019t negotiating on a budget deal, veterans\u2019 legislation and Food and Drug Administration fees until the Obamacare debate is over. More.  Drug control office to argue for its funding. Richard Baum, the acting head of ONDCP, will testify at this morning's reauthorization hearing, along with GAO's Diana Maurer, Stanford's Keith Humphreys and Fed Up!'s Don Flattery.  Medicare proposes slight cut for home health agencies. CMS is planning a slight pay cut for home health agencies in 2018, the agency said in a proposed rule published on Tuesday. The proposal would reduce Medicare payments to the agencies by 0.4 percent next year, saving the federal government an estimated $80 million. That change is driven in part by CMS' planned phase out of a provision boosting pay rates for certain home health services delivered to rural patients.  Missouri: Lawmakers send abortion regulations to governor. After state Democrats filibustered, the GOP-led legislature moved a series of regulations to Republican Gov. Eric Greitens for his expected signature. Among the regulations: More protections for whistleblowers in abortion clinics and a requirement that women must meet with a physician three days before undergoing an abortion. More.  Texas: Hospitals sound their frustration with federal government. Hours after the U.S. Senate voted on Tuesday to open debate on ACA repeal, Texas hospitals and other health care providers testified to the state\u2019s House Appropriations Committee meeting that Congressional proposals to cut Medicaid would hurt Texas, POLITICO's Renuka Rayasam reports from Austin.  \u201cWhen the federal government starts limiting investment, where do those dollars go? said Stacy Wilson, president at Children's Hospital Association of Texas, at the evening hearing. Wilson told state lawmakers, many of whom are championing the idea of getting more flexibility to run Texas\u2019 Medicaid program, that flexibility would come with a price: \u201cYou will have to make some tough decisions about very vulnerable populations,\u201d she said.  \u2026 During the hearing, Texas\u2019 health commissioner Charles Smith estimated that the ACA will cost Texas $316 million in state funds over the next two years. Most of those costs come from requirements that make it easier for people to maintain Medicaid enrollment such as moving from six month to 12-month certification, getting rid of the asset test and changes to income requirements.  But when pressed by lawmakers, Smith pointed out that repeal wouldn\u2019t necessarily mean that the state gets that money back. He said that those costs would likely get shifted to other programs and that savings from ACA offset other health care costs in the state.  \u201cIt\u2019s like a plate of spaghetti,\u201d said Smith. \u201cYou pull on one string and get a whole lot more.\u201d  Texas: Hospitals also worry that repeal debate is delaying an HHS decision on 1115 waiver funds. Last October, the Obama administration extended the state\u2019s 1115 waiver through December 2017. But at the hearing state lawmakers and hospitals said they were worried about the slow-moving negotiations to further extend the waiver, a crucial source of funding for Texas hospitals.  \u201cThe D.C. situation has gotten very problematic,\u201d said John Hawkins, senior vice president at the Texas Hospital Association. HHS and CMS have been too busy with ACA repeal policy to focus on the state\u2019s application, he said: \u201cI don\u2019t think CMS understands how this money shores up the safety net in Texas.\u201d  Without the waiver, about half the rural hospitals in the state will have to close, said Don McBeath, of the Texas Organization of Rural & Community Hospitals.  By Rachana Pradhan  Celgene will pay $280 million to settle a fraud lawsuit over cancer drugs, Katie Thomas reports for the New York Times. More.   The Cleveland Plain Dealer's editorial page excoriates Sen. Rob Portman\u2019s Tuesday vote on the Senate\u2019s revised Obamacare repeal bill. More.   Rachel Bluth in Kaiser Health News examines opposition from hospitals and physicians to price transparency measures. More.   The brains of 99 percent of former NFL players studied showed signs of a disease linked to repeated hits to the head, Reuters reports based on a JAMA study. More.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
