aV \u000a            By DAN DIAMOND (ddiamond@politico.com; @ddiamond)  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  DRAMA \u2014 AND MOMENTUM \u2014 BUILDING TOWARD SENATE VOTE. The vote to start debate on their health bill is today, and the Senate GOP is sounding more confident.  The dramatic announcement Monday night that Sen. John McCain, who underwent brain surgery just 10 days ago, would return to Washington for the Tuesday vote added to the surge of momentum \u2014 although with several senators still publicly undecided, the outcome isn't yet completely certain.  Story Continued Below  President Donald Trump and Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell on Monday engaged in a furious campaign to pressure holdouts, and they further stressed that the first vote is just to get legislation to the floor, where it can then be amended.   \u000a                            Sen. John McCain will return for Republicans' health care vote. | Getty   McConnell spent the day cajoling his members and meeting with Vice President Mike Pence to plot strategy. The majority leader was still short of the votes to even open debate, and Republicans still don't know what they'd be voting to allow debate on if they agree to go along with McConnell on the procedural vote.  If McConnell manages to round up the 50 votes, it would be a huge political victory for him and for the Republicans who have seen their legislative agenda stalled.  POLITICO's Jen Haberkorn, Seung Min Kim and Burgess Everett have more on the late-breaking developments \u2014 and remaining uncertainties. Keep reading: More.  \u2014 Publicly undecided on the procedural vote as of late Monday: Sens. Shelley Moore Capito, Rob Portman, Cory Gardner, Lisa Murkowski, Mike Lee, Dean Heller and Jerry Moran. What they're seeking: clarity on whether repeal and replace, or just repeal, is the ultimate end game. But McCain's return to Washington suggests that GOP leaders see the gap closing \u2014or closed.  \u2014 Seemingly against the vote: Sen. Susan Collins said she was opposed to proceeding to a litany of possibilities and seems like the firmest \u201cno\u201d vote on Tuesday \u2014 unless, she added, \u201cit's going to be a brand-new bill, in which case I can't tell you.\u201d  Trump to Tom Price: If vote fails, 'I'll say, Tom, you're fired.' The president was speaking in West Virginia at the Boy Scout Jamboree last night \u2014 and while he appeared to be joking, there's a kernel of truth behind his frustration sources have said, with his broader legislative package stalled.  \u2026 Trump also put pressure on Republican senators across Monday, appearing with Capito and using his popular Twitter feed to urge the caucus to repeal the ACA. More.  Some conservatives remain deeply leery. Policy analyst Chris Jacobs says it's a "sucker's bet" for Republicans to vote on a motion to proceed, arguing that the bill already is flawed and will only get worse given the parliamentarian's rulings and likely compromises.  "If senators have objections to the bill now, they should vote down the motion to proceed, for the bill \u2014 likely on substance, and certainly on process \u2014 isn\u2019t going to get much better, and almost assuredly will get worse," Jacobs writes. More.  \u2026 Jacobs also shared a letter with reporters, sent by McConnell in 2009, where Republicans asked for a number of courtesies related to Democrats' health care legislation that year \u2014 including "full text and full CBO scores on a health care bill publicly available for 72 hours prior to a vote on the motion to proceed," Jacobs points out.  THIS IS TUESDAY PULSE \u2014 And you have a motion to proceed to the rest of our email. Send tips to ddiamond@politico.com or @ddiamond on Twitter.  With help from Rachana Pradhan (@RachanaDixit) and David Pittman (@David_Pittman)  A duel to settle ACA repeal? That's what Texas Rep. Blake Farenthold suggested on Monday, when he blamed "some female senators from the Northeast" for slowing down the GOP effort and telling a local radio station that he might challenge them to a duel if the supposedly obstructing lawmakers were men.  Farenthold's remark appeared to be a reference to Sens. Susan Collins (R-Maine) and Shelley Moore Capito (R-W.Va.), both of whom have expressed some degree of hesitancy toward Senate Republicans' specific plans to repeal and replace former President Barack Obama's signature health care legislation.  ** A message from PhRMA: ICYMI: National Sheriffs\u2019 Association says importation proposals \u201cwould jeopardize law enforcement\u2019s ability to protect the public health; threaten the safety of our drug supply; and endanger law enforcement officers, their canines, other first responders.\u201d http://onphr.ma/2hl5WFY **  Mayors worry about GOP health plan. A POLITICO poll of mayors \u2014 nearly 80 percent of whom were Democrats, in line with the generally liberal tilt of city halls around the nation \u2014 found deep pessimism about plans to roll back Medicaid coverage and other possible cuts to federal spending. For instance, mayors expect that repealing the ACA would cut the number of insured residents of their cities by more than 10 percentage points \u2014 not a prospect they take lightly. More for Pros.  Biotechnology Innovation Organization: Dems' plan on drug costs is 'bad deal' for patients, innovation. BIO took a swipe at Democrats' three-pronged approach to stop large price increases for prescription drugs and give the federal government more power to influence what Medicare pays for medicines. One measure would create a Senate-confirmed enforcer to identify medicines with "unconscionable" price increases and impose fines on manufacturers that are proportional to the size of the price hike.  "These so-called \u2018transparency requirements\u2019 would do nothing to lower patient costs or provide useful information to consumers," BIO said in a statement, arguing that the measures instead "would have a chilling effect on investment in new cures, particularly with smaller companies."  Unhappy House GOP appropriators press leadership to delay recess. House Republican appropriators are pressing Speaker Paul Ryan to cancel the first week of recess and tackle a massive spending package full of goodies for the base \u2014 a strategy leadership rejected last week. More.  MACRA lobbying plummets under Trump. The number of groups lobbying Congress on Medicare's payment law dropped to 58 in the second quarter this year, more than a 25 percent drop from the 81 working on the issue in the same period last year, according to POLITICO's David Pittman. Organizations lobbying on MACRA spent just over $18 million in the last three months, compared to more than $27 million for the same period in 2016. Those dropping the issue include Humana, AARP and Premier, along with several state hospital associations.  Public health groups petition courts over FDA deeming lawsuits. Six organizations are seeking permission to intervene in the lawsuits \u2014 brought by the e-cigarette and cigar industries against the FDA \u2014 warning that the Trump administration may not sufficiently defend the agency's 2016 rule on e-cigarettes and other tobacco products. The groups include the American Academy of Pediatrics, the American Cancer Society Cancer Action Network, the American Heart Association, the American Lung Association, the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids and Truth Initiative.  Massachusetts is exploring Obamacare waivers. The waivers would set up a premium stabilization fund in lieu of the health law's cost-sharing reductions \u2014 which Trump has threatened to gut \u2014 and revive a state employer mandate instead of having to comply with the federal requirement, according to a draft proposal released Monday.   The proposal includes six requests that Massachusetts wants the Trump administration to approve, including asking for federal permission to administer the ACA's small business tax credit to boost how many employers obtain them. Massachusetts will accept comment on the proposal until Aug. 25, and changes, if approved, would go into effect starting in 2018. See the notice | See the proposal.   Few pharmacy customers are more savvy than Libby Rosenthal, a physician and editor of Kaiser Health News. And yet, even she was confounded by her recent trip to buy what should've been an inexpensive drug. More.  The California Health Care Foundation rebuts a WSJ editorial that criticized the state's Medicaid program. More.  Robin Schatz looks at how one health system is deliberately giving infected livers to patients who would otherwise die without a transplant. More.  NYT's Julie Creswell, Reed Abelson and Margot Sanger-Katz have a stunning look at how one emergency management company aggressively ramped up surprise billing of patients. More.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
