aV \u000a            By DAN DIAMOND (ddiamond@politico.com; @ddiamond)  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  Republicans' zombie bill limps into a key week, with a major vote looming even though GOP leaders don't appear to have the support, know the order of amendments or have a reconciliation-proof bill ready yet.  HOW THE WEEK COULD GO  Story Continued Below  Motion to proceed still expected for Tuesday. After two canceled votes, Republicans say they'll finally hold a vote on whether to bring a bill to the floor, no matter what.  There's still confusion about which bill will be voted on, however \u2014 the unpopular Obamacare replacement bill or a resurrected version of the 2015 straight repeal bill \u2014 and leaders' comments on Sunday didn't clarify that.  "Ultimately, that's a judgment that Sen. McConnell will make at some point this week before the vote," said Sen. John Thune on "Fox News Sunday."  Will McCain appear in time for the vote? It's not clear whether Arizona Sen. John McCain will make a dramatic return after his invasive medical procedure just nine days ago and subsequent diagnosis of brain cancer. But without McCain, the calculus is against Senate Republicans, whose effort fails if two members break ranks and vote against advancing the bill.   And as of this weekend, six Republicans were on record against the replacement bill and three were against the straight repeal bill, which is why \u2026   Pressure is being ramped up on moderates. Vice President Mike Pence stumped with Ohio Sen. Rob Portman on Saturday and President Donald Trump will be with key holdout Sen. Shelley Moore Capito in West Virginia today.  IF THE MOTION TO PROCEED IS SUCCESSFUL ... Then the Senate moves into 20 hours of debate on the bill, while Republican leaders will rush to win over holdouts and ready their amendments.   But as of now, it doesn't appear they have the votes.  McCONNELL's POSSIBLE STRATEGY: WIN BY LOSING \u2014 A defeat on the motion to proceed could spark a conservative backlash and a new round of dealmaking \u2026 or at least that's what Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell is hoping, POLITICO's Jen Haberkorn and Seung Min Kim report.  Top Republicans also are acknowledging that they could lose this week. \u201cWhat will happen is, if and when that were to occur, we\u2019ll go back to the drawing board and get a bill up,\u201d Thune said on Sunday. \u201cWe are going to vote to repeal and replace Obamacare. It\u2019s not a question of 'if,\u2019 it\u2019s a question of \u2018when.'\u201d More.  ALTERNATE OUTCOME: A PIVOT AWAY FROM OBAMACARE \u2014 It's possible that a failed vote could establish a decisive end to the public Obamacare repeal debate \u2014 at least for now. That would allow the Senate to move on after two months to other priorities, like tax reform, and possibly notch some legislative wins.  Meanwhile, a handful of Republicans have loudly called for open hearings on health care and there are other pieces of unrelated health legislation \u2014 like the FDA user fees bill \u2014 that have been tabled until ACA repeal is done. If we finally see movement on those priorities, it's a sign that the Obamacare fight is officially on hold.  MORE COMPLICATIONS   Big chunks of the bill were seemingly knocked out on Friday, when the Senate parliamentarian ruled that major provisions didn't comply with Senate rules on reconciliation, including:  \u2014 Defunding Planned Parenthood for one year   \u2014 Banning coverage of abortion in Obamacare insurance plans  \u2014 Appropriating funds to pay for the cost-sharing reductions to subsidize insurers' participation in ACA markets  \u2014 Instituting a six-month lockout on consumers who fail to maintain continuous coverage  \u2014 Changing the way New York funds Medicaid (widely viewed as a way to win over GOP holdouts from the Empire State for the House bill)  Democrats and progressive groups loudly celebrated, noting that some key conservatives' votes seemingly rested on including those provisions. They added that knocking out the New York-specific provision would make it harder for the GOP to craft state-specific deals to win over holdout senators.  More for Pros | See Senate Democrats' release  However, conservative groups said they still support the motion to proceed, noting that Republicans say they have replacement language ready to go \u2014 or that the GOP could simply overrule the parliamentarian.  More parliamentarian rulings are coming. One to watch: the parliamentarian's decision on the Consumer Freedom amendment, authored by Sen. Ted Cruz, which would allow insurers in specified circumstances to sell plans that don't comply with ACA regulations. That provision has been crucial to winning over conservatives, although the insurance industry and others have said that it would be unworkable.  An overlooked loophole that would benefit Democratic governors too? Liberal wonks don't like the Senate replacement bill, but they're quietly discussing one possible upside: The bill would fast-track state innovative waiver applications, which could allow governors to go around their legislatures and get near-automatic approval from the HHS secretary, so long as their proposals don't increase the federal deficit.  That provision has been seen as a vehicle for conservative governors to make dramatic overhauls to their insurance markets, Nicholas Bagley wrote at Vox last month. But it also could unlock quick action on progressive priorities in some states, such as expanding coverage to undocumented Americans (like lawmakers in California have explored) and subsidizing insurers to provide services like contraception, wonks believe.  THIS IS MONDAY PULSE \u2014 Where we continue to watch 2009 and 2017 unfurl like distorted reflections of each other. Eight years ago on Sunday: then-President Barack Obama was stumping for his health bill in Cleveland, visiting the city's biggest hospital and hosting a two-hour town hall. See video.  PULSE remembers watching (and writing) about that town hall as a fledgling health policy analyst. Where were you eight years ago this summer? Send tips to ddiamond@politico.com or @ddiamond on Twitter.  With help from Adam Cancryn (@AdamCancryn)  \u000a                            President Donald Trump is openly pressing senators to move on the health bill, but it's not clear if anyone's yet swayed. | AP photo | AP Photo  WHAT THE WHITE HOUSE IS TELLING CONSERVATIVES \u2014 Vice President Mike Pence and HHS Secretary Tom Price assured conservative groups on Friday that the ACA repeal effort is in good shape, an upbeat meeting meant to rally the groups to put pressure on GOP senators to open debate.  \u2014 Pence said that he doesn't expect any last-minute surprises from GOP leaders if they take up the straight repeal bill, such as voting down that bill and then pivoting to a compromise bill that\u2019s not acceptable to conservatives, according to a source in the room.   \u2014 Price talked up his agency's report showing that the Cruz amendment would drive down premiums and boost enrollment \u2014 conclusions that budget and policy experts have roundly panned as faulty and misleading. Price didn't mention that criticism, and instead encouraged groups to use the report in their campaigns to get GOP senators to support the motion to proceed.  He also hinted that HHS is looking for ways to tweak the Cruz amendment after the fact to make it more workable and allow for split risk pools \u2014 a change that would be aimed at winning over conservatives who say the proposal wouldn't be effective unless the individual market is split into two groups: sick, higher-cost people and healthy, lower-cost people.  Attendees included social conservative groups including Susan B. Anthony List, Family Research Council and Faith & Freedom, as well as other conservative grassroots mainstays like Heritage Action and Club for Growth.  ** A message from PhRMA: ICYMI: National Sheriffs\u2019 Association says importation proposals \u201cwould jeopardize law enforcement\u2019s ability to protect the public health; threaten the safety of our drug supply; and endanger law enforcement officers, their canines, other first responders.\u201d http://onphr.ma/2hl5WFY **  Trump makes veiled threat to Republicans. "If Republicans don't Repeal and Replace the disastrous ObamaCare, the repercussions will be far greater than any of them understand!" the president stated on Twitter on Sunday evening. Earlier in the day, Trump went after members of his own party, saying Republicans "do very little to protect their President."  Scaramucci: Trump will gets health care done. The new White House communications director vowed on CBS's "Face the Nation" that the president would ultimately succeed, even if this week's vote fails.  "He always gets what he wants," Scaramucci said. "He's got very, very good karma." Watch video.  To watch today: Trump making 3:15 p.m. statement on health care. The president is scheduled to be speaking from the White House.  Murray and Wyden want a briefing with HHS and contractors. Sens. Patty Murray and Ron Wyden, the respective ranking members of the Senate HELP and Finance committees, are out with a letter to HHS Secretary Tom Price this morning, asking for an explanation behind the agency's evaluation of Sen. Ted Cruz's Consumer Freedom amendment. HHS issued a glowing report of the amendment's impact \u2014a conclusion that was at odds with external analyses \u2014but the agency didn't release a full explanation of how it arrived at that conclusion. POLITICO first reported that the analysis was produced in conjunction McKinsey.  "We write to request a briefing on this analysis with representatives from HHS and McKinsey or any other contractors or subcontractors whose data or analyses were used to produce HHS's report," Murray and Wyden write. Read letter.  Schumer: No more 'namby-pamby' Dems. The Senate Majority Leader said on ABC's "This Week" that the Democratic agenda being unveiled on Monday is "bold" and will win over voters who deserted the party for Trump.  "We were too cautious, we were too namby-pamby," Schumer said, vowing to be more ambitious on economic issues.  Among the agenda items that Democrats are considering or will consider:  \u2014 Drug pricing fixes. Schumer said the agenda would include ideas to "just go after these drug companies when they raise prices so egregiously and people can't afford these drugs."  \u2014 Single-payer health care. Schumer said that Democrats would take a look at the idea, although he stopped short of full endorsement and said that lawmakers needed to "stabilize" the current health system first.  \u2014 Medicare and Medicaid expansion. Schumer also said that Democrats would look at these programs, too. "Medicare for people above 55 is on the table. A buy-in to Medicare is on the table. Buy-in to Medicaid is on the table," he offered.  David Durenberger: 'There are no do-overs.' Writing in USA Today, the Minnesota Republican who served three terms in the Senate urges current GOP senators to vote against the health bill, warning that they'd be running the risk of passing a bill with unclear impact on their state budgets and residents.  "Take it from me: A no vote on the Motion to Proceed this week is the only one that will be defensible in the years to come," Durenberger writes. "The good news is we haven\u2019t run out of time to ask questions and to work together to fix what needs fixing if we take the time to return to regular order and hold hearings." More.  Tiberi will tackle ineffective Medicare regulations. Rep. Pat Tiberi, the Ways and Means Health Subcommittee chairman, will announce an initiative today intended to eliminate red tape in the Medicare program.  Under the Provider Statutory & Regulatory Relief Initiative, Tiberi is soliciting suggestions to "reduce legislative and regulatory burdens on Medicare providers" and improve efficiency and quality for beneficiaries. See the form and submissions can be sent to WMProviderFeedback@mail.house.gov.  Tea Party Patriots activists are delivering 1.5 million signatures, calling for ACA repeal. They'll be delivering them to McConnell's office this morning, with supporters urging congressional Republicans to keep their health care promises.  Covered California releases three reports on reform-related issues. The exchange dropped three reports late on Friday, POLITICO's Victoria Colliver reports from Sacramento, including:  (1) An analysis that shows how Senate Republicans' plan to repeal and replace Obamacare would destabilize the individual insurance market. The analysis argues the bill\u2019s proposal of a new, lower \u201cbenchmark plan\u201d with a 58 percent actuarial value would provide \u201clittle to no value\u201d for the vast majority of Americans.  (2) A report on why funding subsidies for insurance companies is not a "bailout," and   (3) An explainer about how risk stabilization or reinsurance funding is necessary to keep the markets from collapsing. \u201cReinsurance programs could be administered virtually overnight and the pay-off for consumers could be to immediately reduce premiums for 2018," argues John Bertko, Covered California\u2019s chief actuary.  STATE WEEK: More states eye waivers to stabilize insurance markets. Alaska earlier this month became the first state to win a waiver from the Trump administration to help prop up its lone Obamacare insurer. Last week, New Hampshire announced it will seek a waiver for a state-run reinsurance program to keep its individual insurance market from collapsing.  It's a realization that states must deal with market turbulence regardless of what Congress does, and that policymakers in Washington clearly want to make it easier for states to devise their own solutions, as long they don't drive up the federal deficit. More for Pros.  Lynn Quincy, Healthcare Value Hub now at Altarum Institute. The hub, which was launched by Consumer Reports in 2015, is intended as a networking and resource center for advocates and researchers.   Many rural Americans were hit with high premiums in ACA exchanges, but they won't necessarily get relief under Republicans' bill, NPR's April Dembosky reports. More.  Two life-threatening events shaped Aetna CEO Mark Bertolini's view of the U.S. health care system, Julia LaRoche reports for Yahoo Finance. More.  Small business owners are split over the GOP reform push, Stacy Cowley writes in the New York Times. More.  In the Washington Post, Robert Samuelson says that we've failed to have a rational discussion about the nation's growing health care cost burden. More.  ** A message from PhRMA: Myth About Drug Importation: U.S. government would make sure medicines are safe. Fact: The government has authority to allow drug importation if the secretary of HHS certifies imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans and would generate cost savings for consumers. No secretary has been able to do that. Proposals to allow the importation of drugs into the U.S. would expose Americans to unregulated drugs that U.S. officials cannot guarantee are safe. To date, no HHS secretary \u2013 Democrat or Republican \u2013 has certified that imports would not threaten the health and safety of Americans or would generate cost savings for consumers. Allowing the importation of drugs from other countries into the U.S. would lead to potentially dangerous outcomes for patients and increase the burden on law enforcement to prevent unregulated medicines from harming Americans. Get the facts at http://onphr.ma/2u12plT **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
