aV 08/04/2017 07:52 AM EDT  By Heather Caygle (hcaygle@politico.com or @heatherscope)  With an assist from Seung Min Kim   Story Continued Below  SEE YOU LATER \u2014 Happy Friday. Congress is officially out for recess. The Senate passed a bill funding the FDA and approved dozens of nominees before bolting for the exits Thursday afternoon. But Republicans heading back to their constituents have no major legislative achievements to tout, despite the GOP controlling Congress and the White House. It\u2019s a far cry from January, when GOP lawmakers received socks with President Trump\u2019s face on them and were promising to do big things in the coming months.   Remember the GOP\u2019s 200-day plan? Republican leaders said the GOP-controlled Congress would repeal Obamacare, fund Trump\u2019s border wall and overhaul the tax code, all by August. None of those things have been done.   Ryan looks ahead to 2018: \u201cIf we don\u2019t do our job we will depress turnout,\u201d Speaker Paul Ryan said Thursday in Wisconsin about the 2018 midterms. \u201cI am frustrated as well.\u201d More from the Wisconsin State Journal: http://bit.ly/2feTMxv   Republicans feel the heat: Coming back in September, top Republicans say they know their next big legislative goal \u2013 overhauling the tax code \u2013 can\u2019t meet the same fate as the GOP effort to repeal Obamacare. \u201cOn the next big thing, we can\u2019t fail,\u201d said Sen. John Thune of South Dakota, the third-ranking Senate Republican. \u201cWe have to double down on tax reform.\u201d Jennifer Steinhauer with the New York Times: http://nyti.ms/2uqokyf   INDEPENDENCE DAY \u2014 Senate Republicans did get one thing accomplished during their last week before recess: resisting strong-arms efforts by the president. Elana and Seung Min: \u201cThe GOP delivered an unstated declaration of independence from their own Republican president by passing a Russia sanctions bill he resisted, rebuffing his demands they try again on health care after the spectacular implosion of Obamacare repeal, even taking steps to head off any attempt by Trump to fire the special counsel investigating him, Robert Mueller.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2uqv3Is   HAPPY FRIDAY Y\u2019ALL. Welcome to Aug. 4 and thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill. Your Huddle host is doing a happy dance because Alabama is once again No. 1 in the preseason coaches poll. Bres, our bureau chief and huge Bama fan, is also over the moon. Roll Tide!   THURSDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: You guys really loved my hidden link to the Go-Go\u2019s \u201cVacation.\u201d So it\u2019s not just me that\u2019s ready for recess, huh?  AN EXTRA SPECIAL DELIVERY \u2014 Welcome to the world, Harry Cole Everett! Papa Burgess e-mails: Harry Cole Everett was born at 11:15 p.m. on Aug. 1 after a long delivery that his mom Emily fought through valiantly. Harry was 8 pounds and 19.5 inches tall at birth, but we still haven't measured his wingspan. The whole family is now at home resting comfortably. Big, big congrats to the growing Everett family!! See the youngest member of POLITICO\u2019s Congress team: http://bit.ly/2uqc3K0   WHAT THE HILL IS READING \u2014 Special counsel Robert Mueller has impaneled a grand jury in his Russian meddling probe, \u201ca sign that his inquiry is growing in intensity and entering a new phase, according to people familiar with the matter,\u201d the Wall Street Journal reports. \u201cThe grand jury, which began its work in recent weeks, signals that Mr. Mueller\u2019s inquiry will likely continue for months.\u201d Del Quentin Wilber and Byron Tau: http://on.wsj.com/2uqmZrn.   The grand jury has already issued subpoenas related to Donald Trump Jr.\u2019s meeting with a Russian lawyer last year who claimed to have incriminating information on Hillary Clinton, Reuters reports. Jared Kushner and Paul Manafort also attended the meeting. Karen Freifeld and John Walcott with more: http://reut.rs/2uqo9D9   Follow the money: Federal investigators \u201chave seized on Trump and his associates' financial ties to Russia as one of the most fertile avenues for moving their probe forward,\u201d CNN reports. \u201cThe web of financial ties could offer a more concrete path toward potential prosecution than the broader and murkier questions of collusion in the 2016 campaign, these sources said.\u201d Evan Perez, Pamela Brown and Shimon Prokupecz: http://cnn.it/2uqzK5b   Probe inflames Hill tensions: Two Republican House Intelligence Committee staffers traveled to London earlier this summer to track down Christopher Steele, the former British intelligence operative who compiled a controversial Trump dossier, Ali Watkins reports this morning. But the trip has inflamed simmering tensions between House and Senate investigators, who are worried the aggressive move could spook Steele. More: http://politi.co/2uqyfUs   ON THE DEBT CEILING \u2014 OMB Director Mick Mulvaney is now falling in line with other top administration officials, saying he supports a clean debt ceiling hike. Treasury Secretary Steve Mnuchin has been pushing for a clean bill, saying lawmakers need to raise the debt limit by the end of September. Previously, Mulvaney had been advocating for any debt ceiling increase to also be accompanied by spending cuts. When asked about his position on Thursday, Mulvaney told reporters he was for "the simplest debt ceiling increase that we can get." Business Insider\u2019s Bob Bryan: http://read.bi/2uqyX4l   WHAT\u2019S NEXT FOR OBAMACARE? Republicans leave Washington with no clear idea what\u2019s next for their effort to repeal Obamacare. And everyone is all over the map on next steps: \u201cSenate leaders want to just drop the issue altogether. Conservatives say they\u2019re still fighting for repeal. Moderates want to launch a bipartisan effort to fix the shaky Obamacare system,\u201d Jen Haberkorn and Paul Demko report.   Reality check: \u201cAfter seven years of unity on repealing Obamacare, Republicans are rudderless on how to talk about or address the defining domestic policy issue of nearly the past decade for their party, and they have no clear plans despite holding all the levers of power in Washington.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2uqsw1a   SOMETHING TO WATCH \u2014 Senators, along with current and former Hill staffers, have received the official go-ahead from the Senate to testify at Sen. Bob Menendez's upcoming bribery trial in New Jersey, Diamond Naga Siu, Josh Gerstein and Seung Min report. Opening arguments are slated to begin Sept. 6 with jury selection starting later this month. It\u2019s unclear which senators or aides have been subpoenaed to testify. More: http://politi.co/2fe60qk   DeSANTIS DEMANDS PROBE INTO IT STAFFER \u2014 Rep. Ron DeSantis (R-Fla.) wants DOJ to take a deeper look into the finances of Imran Awan, Rep. Debbie Wasserman Schultz\u2019s recently fired IT staffer. Awan was arrested last week on one count of bank fraud while trying to fly to Pakistan. He and his family \u2013 also former Hill staffers \u2013 have been the center of a criminal investigation on Capitol Hill involving computer equipment theft. \u201cNational security aside, the case has a political dimension for DeSantis, a likely candidate for governor who has mused about calling Wasserman Schultz to testify before the judiciary panel about the case,\u201d Daniel Ducassi and Marc Caputo report. More: http://politi.co/2uq7Ztr   NEXT FOR McCAIN: IMMIGRATION REFORM? Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) says he wants to revive bipartisan talks on immigration reform when he returns from cancer treatment in September. McCain told the Arizona Republic he recently broached the idea with Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.). Both men were part of the "Gang of Eight\u201d immigration push in 2013. "Immigration reform is one of the issues I'd like to see resolved," McCain said. "I've got to talk to him (Schumer) about when would be the best time. I think there are all kinds of deals to be made out there. I really do." Dan Nowicki with more: http://bit.ly/2feCtfU   CAT GOT YOUR TONGUE \u2014 Do House Democratic candidates back current Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi? If so, they aren\u2019t saying. \u201cIn a survey of 20 Democratic House candidates, only one \u2013 a former Senate staffer from Orange County, California \u2013 would state support for the congresswoman staying on as leader of the House Democratic Caucus,\u201d Alex Roarty reports. \u201cOf the rest, 18 declined to say if Pelosi should keep her job, while one, a political newcomer from a culturally conservative Ohio district, said he would vote for someone other than Pelosi.\u201d More from McClatchy: http://bit.ly/2uqK7pv   ARRIVALS AND DEPARTURES \u2014 Nicole Hager, deputy press secretary for Sen. Jim Inhofe (R-Okla.) has a new gig starting later this month. Beginning on Aug. 21, Nicole will join the Senate Finance Committee as deputy press secretary. She\u2019s also starting law school at GW.   TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The House and Senate are out until September.   AROUND THE HILL \u2014 Interns anonymously editing their boss\u2019 Wikipedia page. Follow along: http://bit.ly/2uqsvdD   THURSDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Edward Rolwes was first to guess that a cotton blossom is the mystery item that appears in both the Grisaille Frieze and the George Washington Apotheosis in the U.S. Capitol Rotunda. It\u2019s also the name of the steamer in Show Boat.   TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 Ed with today\u2019s question: This former speaker of the House entered the Democratic convention with the most pledged delegates, yet failed to secure the necessary support to get the presidential nomination after losing the backing of the Williams Jennings Bryan-led wing of the party. Who is he, what state was he from and what year was the convention? The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
