aV 08/03/2017 07:48 AM EDT  By Heather Caygle (hcaygle@politico.com or @heatherscope)  GONE UNTIL SEPTEMBER \u2014 Good Thursday morning Huddle readers. The Senate could leave town as early as today, joining the House for a month-long break. But fear not, we\u2019re already looking ahead to battles in September.   Story Continued Below  Showdown looming? Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) and Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.), knowing they\u2019ll need Democratic votes anyway, are begrudgingly on board with the White House\u2019s request for a clean debt ceiling increase in September, Seung Min and Rachael report this morning. But some rank-and-file Republicans have other plans, calling for any debt ceiling hike to be accompanied by spending cuts or fiscal reforms. \u201cMeanwhile, Democrats, who time and again have coughed up votes to allow the GOP to avoid crises, are mulling their own demands with a Republican now in the White House,\u201d they report.   For now, House Republican leaders are looking to the Senate to move first with plans to push through the House whatever is first passed by the upper chamber. \u201cGOP leaders under their current strategy will, in essence, ignore conservatives because they can\u2019t give them what they want and expect it to clear the Senate\u2019s higher, 60-vote threshold.\u201d The state of play: http://politi.co/2umFCwk   FOR YOUR RADAR: MUELLER BILL \u2014 Sens. Thom Tillis (R-N.C.) and Chris Coons (D-Del.) plan to introduce a bill today that would give special counsel Robert Mueller recourse if he is fired by the White House. \u201cThe bill would allow any special counsel for the Department of Justice to challenge his or her removal in court, with a review by a three-judge panel within 14 days of the challenge,\u201d the AP reports. And the legislation would be retroactive to May 17, 2017 \u2014 the day Mueller was appointed to investigate Russian meddling and any potential involvement by the Trump campaign. Sens. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) and Cory Booker (D-N.J.) are also working on a similar bill, USA Today previously reported.   TRUMP SIGNS SANCTIONS BILL \u2014 President Donald Trump signed a sweeping Russia, Iran and North Korea sanctions package into law Wednesday, but not before saying he thinks parts of the bill are unconstitutional. The accompanying signing statement prompted a quick response from House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.), who said Trump\u2019s comments raise \u201cserious questions about whether his administration intends to follow the law, or whether he will continue to enable and reward Vladimir Putin\u2019s aggression.\u201d Matt Nussbaum and Elana with more: http://politi.co/2u51noU   Related read: \u201cCongress is moving to force the Pentagon to violate a nuclear arms treaty with Russia \u2014 in yet another effort to box in President Donald Trump on relations with Moscow,\u201d Bryan Bender reports. More: http://politi.co/2hqmhZU   RECESS, ALL I EVER WANTED. Welcome to Thursday, Aug. 3 and thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill.   WEDNESDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: Elana\u2019s story about Senate Republicans planning to pass a tax overhaul without bipartisan buy-in got the clicks.   OBAMACARE SUBSIDIES SAFE, FOR NOW \u2014 The White House has put the brakes on deciding whether to yank Obamacare subsidies that are critical to keeping the market functioning. Facing blowback from Republicans on the Hill, who are pushing to keep the cost-sharing reduction payments in place for now, the White House is not expected to immediately end the subsidies, despite previous threats. \u201cLawyers and some administration officials have raised questions about ending the payments but are expected to offer an analysis later in August, West Wing officials said,\u201d Josh Dawsey and Jen Haberkorn report. Another CSR payment is due approximately Aug. 22. More: http://politi.co/2umKa5D   Related: New bipartisan Obamacare push faces steep climb, via Jen Haberkorn and Adam Cancryn, http://politi.co/2umElFr.   McCAIN UPDATE: \u2018FEELING GOOD\u2019 \u2014 In his first interview since starting cancer treatment this week, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) said he\u2019s \u201cfeeling good\u201d and plans to return to the Senate in September. "It's a tough challenge, of course, but [I'm] getting the best care you can possibly have. I'm eating well and feeling fine, getting plenty of exercise," McCain said on Phoenix talk radio station KFYI. McCain said he\u2019s been keeping a regular schedule of meetings and plans to travel around the state during recess. He\u2019s also been touched by the outpouring of support since his diagnosis: "It's been very deeply moving to me, even those who have said, 'I hope you die, but you're still a good guy.'" Connor O\u2019Brien with more: http://politi.co/2un5mIL   BYE BYE BYE \u2014 National Security Adviser H.R. McMaster has fired a top White House intelligence aide who earlier this year secretly shared controversial \u201cunmasking\u201d information with House Intel Chairman Devin Nunes (R-Calif.). \u201cThe dismissal of Ezra Cohen-Watnick, confirmed by the White House, is the latest in a string of NSC staff members removed at the behest of McMaster, who has steadily shed aides that had been brought on by his short-lived predecessor Michael Flynn,\u201d report Eliana Johnson, Nahal Toosi and Ali Watkins. More: http://politi.co/2umUZon   GAVEL GRAB GETTING SERIOUS \u2014 Rep. Diane Black\u2019s entry into the Tennessee gubernatorial race will likely trigger serious jockeying between Republicans for her House Budget Committee gavel. Under GOP conference rules, Black must step down from her post to run for governor unless she gets a waiver, which doesn\u2019t look likely. Rep. Todd Rokita (R-Indiana) is the panel\u2019s vice chairman but he is eyeing a Senate bid. Rep. Bill Johnson (R-Ohio) has already started reaching out to Steering Committee members about the post, the Hill reports. \u201cIt's really wide open if Rokita does run for the Senate,\u201d said one member of the Steering panel. Niv Ellis and Scott Wong with more: http://bit.ly/2u53Dwv   \u2018HE OUGHT TO JUST DO IT\u2019 \u2014 Republican senators are unmoved by Trump\u2019s recent threats to ax subsidies for lawmakers' and their aides' health care, saying he should just follow through if he\u2019s going to keep talking about it. \u201cIf that\u2019s what he wants to do, he ought to just do it,\u201d Sen. Bob Corker (R-Tenn.) told Jen Haberkorn. But as \u201cprobably he\u2019s learned over the last couple of weeks, threats don\u2019t really go over particularly well. My advice would be to either do it or don\u2019t do it.\u201d   President Trump could follow through with his threat \u2013 although it would take months to actually enact \u2013 but given that the median net worth of a member of Congress is $1 million, the people who would feel the hurt are congressional staffers. Jen with more: http://politi.co/2ukfFxq   TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The Senate meets at 10 a.m. with roll call votes possible at 11 a.m., 12 p.m. and again during the day. The House is out for recess.   AROUND THE HILL \u2014 Senate Majority Whip John Cornyn (R-Texas), and Sens. John Barrasso (R-Wyo.), Ron Johnson (R-Wis.) and Thom Tillis (R-N.C.) hold a press conference on their border security bill at 11:30 a.m. in Senate radio/TV gallery.   WEDNESDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Kenny Kraft, a retired 37-year congressional staffer, was first to guess that Alabama Sen. Jeremiah Denton was also a POW in Vietnam alongside Sen. John McCain. Denton is remembered for blinking the word \u201ctorture\u201d in Morse code during a press conference with his North Vietnamese captors. Rep. Sam Johnson (R-Texas) was also a Vietnam POW.   TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 Kenny with today\u2019s question: This item can be found in both the Grisaille Frieze and the George Washington Apotheosis in the Capitol Rotunda. Hint: It\u2019s also the name of the boat in a famous Broadway musical. The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
