aV 08/02/2017 08:02 AM EDT  By Heather Caygle (hcaygle@politico.com or @heatherscope)  With an assist from Paul Demko and Daniel Lippman  Story Continued Below  OVER BEFORE IT STARTED \u2014 Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) has promptly shut the door on any major bipartisan effort to rewrite the tax code, saying Republicans plan to use a fast-track measure to bypass needing Democratic votes. \u201cWe will need to use reconciliation," McConnell told reporters Tuesday, saying Democrats are \u201cnot interested in addressing\u201d Republican priorities. His remarks came after Democrats sent a letter to the GOP leader Tuesday morning laying out their priorities for a tax rewrite.   One thing that will be different from the health care debate? Republicans plan to hold hearings in both chambers on tax reform after recess. But don't get your hopes up: \u201cI don\u2019t think this is going to be 1986, when you had a bipartisan effort to scrub the code,\u201d McConnell said. Elana with more: http://politi.co/2u3J6bS   HELLER UNDER FIRE \u2014 Sen. Dean Heller\u2019s gymnastics on the Obamacare repeal \u2013 first he\u2019s against, then he\u2019s for \u2013 haven\u2019t won him many fans on the right or the left. And Heller\u2019s latest effort, signing onto the Graham-Cassidy repeal bill that doesn\u2019t seem to be going anywhere, could hand critics even more ammunition. \u201cHeller's latest push may only exacerbate the notion that he has followed a too-complicated and contradictory path on health care, one that has infuriated conservatives and made Democrats privately cocky about their chances of snatching his seat next fall,\u201d Seung Min reports this morning. \u201cIf his intent is to get reelected, he\u2019s completely botched it,\u201d said Chuck Muth, a conservative activist in Nevada and former executive director of the state GOP. More: http://politi.co/2u3A26M   BLACK ENTERS GOV RACE \u2014 Rep. Diane Black made it official this morning, announcing her bid for Tennessee governor in 2018. The House Budget chairwoman enters the race as a frontrunner in a crowded GOP field. \u201cBlack, a staunch conservative from Sumner County who is in her fourth term representing Tennessee's 6th Congressional District, will formally announce her candidacy in an online video to be released Wednesday,\u201d Joey Garrison, Joel Ebert and Dave Boucher report for the Tennessean. More: http://tnne.ws/2u3twwE. And watch the video: http://bit.ly/2u3IUci   COMING TODAY: TRUMP MAKES ANTI-IMMIGRATION PUSH \u2014 President Donald Trump will unveil legislation later today that would dramatically scale back the number of legal immigrants entering the country. He\u2019ll be joined by Sens. David Perdue (R-Ga.) and Tom Cotton (R-Ark.), who have been working with top White House aides for months to develop the bill. Refresher: Eliana Johnson and Josh Dawsey wrote about the coming legislation a few weeks ago, http://politi.co/2thJWMJ  CAN I GET A WHAT-WHAT FOR WEDNESDAY? Welcome to Aug. 2 and thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill.   TUESDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: Paul Demko\u2019s story explaining the fallout if Trump scraps Obamacare subsidies for low-income enrollees.   SOMETHING TO WATCH: DEBT CEILING DIVIDE \u2014 Treasury Secretary Steve Mnuchin was up on the Hill lobbying congressional leaders for a clean debt ceiling increase Tuesday. But raising the debt ceiling will be a tough vote for both parties \u2013 Democrats will likely have to deliver a big chunk of the votes \u2013 and neither side is agreeing to Mnuchin\u2019s request to leave policy sweeteners off the bill, at least not yet. Mnuchin, who met with McConnell and Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.), wants a clean debt ceiling increase by Sept. 29, Bres and Seung Min report. More: http://politi.co/2u3BLJ1   YOU CAN GO YOUR OWN WRAY \u2014 The Senate overwhelmingly confirmed Christopher Wray as FBI director on Tuesday, showing strong bipartisan backing after Wray vowed to remain independent of any potential political pressure. Wray was confirmed 92-5. Five Democrats \u2013 Sens. Ed Markey and Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts, Jeff Merkley and Ron Wyden of Oregon, and Kirsten Gillibrand of New York \u2013 voted against him. Seung Min: http://politi.co/2u38M8o   THANKS BUT NO THANKS \u2014 Sen. Ben Sasse (R-Neb.) has recently swatted down overtures from the Heritage Foundation to lead the conservative group after the messy ouster of former Sen. Jim DeMint, Eliana Johnson reports. \u201cIn the Senate, DeMint was a leading antagonist of establishment Republicans, and at Heritage he suffered from the perception that the organization was becoming too political \u2014 and too reflexively pro-Trump,\u201d she writes. \u201cThe organization\u2019s interest in Sasse \u2014 sources say board members have been persistent to the point of irritating the senator \u2014 indicates that it is looking for a reset.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2u3ziOM   HAWKEYE STATE HOPES \u2014 Massachusetts Rep. Seth Moulton and Ohio Rep. Tim Ryan will join Illinois Rep. Cheri Bustos as the headliners of the annual Polk County Steak Fry of the Iowa Democratic Party in September, Gabe Debenedetti reports this morning. \u201cThe trips fuel speculation that Moulton and Ryan are considering White House runs.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2f7BrT9   MOMENTUM FOR MARKET STABILIZATION? \u2014 Members of the Problem Solvers Caucus say they think momentum is building for their bipartisan plan to stabilize the wobbly Obamacare markets, even if GOP leaders haven\u2019t embraced the idea. \u201cIt\u2019s not perfect for anybody, but finding a way forward is key, and that\u2019s what we got to here,\u201d said Rep. Josh Gottheimer (D-N.J.), a co-chair of the caucus, on a call with reporters Tuesday. Leaders of the group cited Sen. Lamar Alexander\u2019s announcement Tuesday that the Senate HELP Committee will hold bipartisan hearings on the issue as a sign that support is building for their approach.   But the blueprint put forth by the caucus faces major hurdles: There\u2019s no plan to pay for it and partisan gridlock on health care is deeply entrenched after nearly a decade of Obamacare wars. \u201cSome folks just want to kind of play the shirts and skins game and just move on from this issue,\u201d acknowledged Rep. Tom Reed (R-N.Y.), the other co-chair of the caucus.  ETHICS PANEL CLEARS LUJAN, ROGERS \u2014 The House Ethics Committee announced Tuesday it was dropping separate investigations into Reps. Ben Ray Lujan (D-N.M.) and Roger Williams (R-Texas). Lujan, who leads Democrats\u2019 campaign arm, was accused of violating the rules by fundraising off of Democrats\u2019 gun control sit-in. Williams, a well-known auto dealer, faced scrutiny after pushing an amendment to the 2015 highway bill that benefited car salesmen. \u201cThe ethics panel said neither Lujan nor Williams violated House rules, but cautioned that both lawmakers acted in ways where mistakes are possible,\u201d the AP\u2019s Matthew Daly reports. Full story: http://abcn.ws/2u3zXje   FLAKE\u2019S NEW BOOK ROILS THE SENATE \u2014 Sen. Jeff Flake's fellow GOP senators applauded him for writing his new book on conservatism, released Tuesday, Seung Min and Elana report. \u201cYet few were willing to endorse his central message: that their party has done little to push back against Trump.\u201d Case in point: I think Jeff\u2019s got a fairly strongly held view about where we are as a party and where we need to go, and I think it\u2019s fine for him to articulate that,\u201d said South Dakota Sen. John Thune. When asked whether many other Republicans subscribe to Flake\u2019s view, Thune added: \u201cHard to say.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2u3HUFd   Related: Seven things in the book that could haunt Flake\u2019s reelection, via Dan Nowicki with the Arizona Republic. Read: http://bit.ly/2u3vw8e. And don\u2019t miss Niels Lesniewski\u2019s review of the new Flake book, via Roll Call: http://bit.ly/2u3GjiI.   TREND ALERT \u2014 \u201cAbout a dozen Obama administration alumni have found a new calling in the early days of the Trump era: running for Congress,\u201d Elena Schneider reports this morning. \u201cShaken by Trump\u2019s surprising victory last November and motivated by his actions to undo parts of former President Barack Obama\u2019s legacy, former White House and agency staffers have moved home and jumped into crowded suburban House primaries, leaning on advice, endorsements and donations from former bosses and colleagues.\u201d Much more for Pros: http://politico.pro/2u3yrOk   OP-ED DU JOUR: \u201cMaine\u2019s two senators let us down,\u201d from Maine Gov. Paul LePage. The Wall Street Journal: http://on.wsj.com/2u3IVgw. (Related context from a few days ago: LePage rallies supporters against Collins\u2019 possible gubernatorial bid, via the Bangor Daily News: http://bit.ly/2u3CVEy)   TAR HEEL STATE TIFF \u2014 Normally, naming federal buildings doesn\u2019t cause this much controversy. But North Carolina Rep. G.K. Butterfield says two of his Republican colleagues are refusing to sign onto his bill renaming a courthouse after John H. Wheeler, a civil rights leader in the state and mentor to the former CBC chairman. Butterfield says Reps. George Holding and Robert Pittenger, the only two of the state\u2019s Republicans not to back the bill, are retaliating because Butterfield wouldn\u2019t support legislation to rename a different federal building after former Sen. Jesse Helms. \u201cSenator Jesse Helms was repugnant,\u201d Butterfield said. Colin Warren-Hicks with the Herald-Sun: http://bit.ly/2uhwbhB   WELCOME TO THE WORLD \u2014 Alison Schneider, comms director for Locust Street Group, and husband Andrew Shult, digital coordinator for House Majority Whip Steve Scalise, welcomed baby boy Cameron Burnley Schneider Shult on Tuesday. Pic: http://politi.co/2tXTuNZ  TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The Senate meets at 10 a.m. with a procedural vote at 11 a.m. related to Marvin Kaplan, National Labor Relations Board nominee. The House is out for recess.   AROUND THE HILL \u2014 Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) and Sens. Debbie Stabenow (D-Mich.), Tammy Baldwin (D-Wis.), Joe Donnelly (D-Ind.) and Bob Casey (D-Pa.) talk about the trade portion of their new agenda at 11:30 a.m. in the Senate swamp.   New Orleans Mayor Mitch Landrieu and several other mayors from across the country hold a press conference on the need for bipartisan approaches to health care, taxes and infrastructure at 2:45 p.m. in SVC-201.   OFF THE HILL \u2014 House Freedom Caucus Chairman Mark Meadows (R-N.C.) joins Americans for Prosperity to talk tax reform at the Newseum starting at 12 p.m.   Sen. Rob Portman (R-Ohio) meets with President Trump at 2 p.m. in the Oval Office.   TUESDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Chris Schuler was the first to guess that Sen. Robert Byrd holds the record for the shortest pro-forma session, at 23/30 of a second, measured in 23 frames of video.   TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 David with today\u2019s question: There's been a lot of recent focus on Sen. McCain, who everyone knows endured years as a POW in Vietnam. Name the other former POW held by Vietnam who later served in Congress and what he is most known for during his time in captivity. The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
