aV 08/01/2017 07:59 AM EDT  By Heather Caygle (hcaygle@politico.com or @heatherscope)  With an assist from Daniel Lippman   Story Continued Below  REPUBLICANS GIVE TRUMP REALITY CHECK \u2014 Senate Republicans have no plans to revive their Obamacare repeal effort this summer, despite Twitter taunts from President Donald Trump, who called them \u201ctotal quitters\u201d over the weekend. "Until somebody shows us a way to get that elusive 50th vote, I think it's over,\u201d said Sen. John Thune of South Dakota, the third-ranking Republican. \u201cMaybe lightning will strike and something will come together but I'm not holding my breath."  McConnell, notably, did not bring up health care in his opening floor remarks Monday afternoon. And Senate Majority Whip John Cornyn (R-Texas) pushed back on comments from OMB Director Mick Mulvaney, who said the Senate shouldn\u2019t do anything else until it votes on health care again. \u201cI don\u2019t think [Mulvaney\u2019s] got much experience in the Senate, as I recall,\u201d Cornyn said, reported the Washington Post. \u201cAnd he\u2019s got a big job. He ought to do that job and let us do our job.\u201d  The White House is still trying to rebuild momentum, pushing a proposal from Sens. Bill Cassidy (R-La.) and Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) to block grant health care funding for states. Cassidy met with top Trump aides, GOP governors and HHS Secretary Tom Price about the idea on Monday. But many Republicans are ready to move on, with \u201cthe idea of taking another heart-stopping vote with little chance of success\u201d not high on their priority lists, Burgess and Jen Haberkorn report. \u201cI don\u2019t think there\u2019s the appetite to have a vote in the next two weeks," said Sen. Shelley Moore Capito (R-W.Va.).   What\u2019s next: \u201cTrump is threatening to cut off health insurance subsidies for low-income people, which could spur Congress to act \u2014 though Trump could veto any bill providing funding for that assistance,\u201d Burgess and Jen report. Trump is expected to decide as soon as today whether to continue making the payments. More on the state of play: http://politi.co/2tZUqWo; And Paul Demko explores what would happen if Trump actually did cancel the Obamacare subsidies: http://politi.co/2ufp2hI   Related read: \u201cLessons for Trump: Hardball against senators is a game he can lose,\u201d via Carl Hulse (There\u2019s even a Roll Tide reference!). The New York Times: http://nyti.ms/2tZUJAw   GONE TIL NOVEMBER \u2014 Republican leaders are ready to pivot to something they feel is a little bit more in their control (albeit not much easier): tax reform. And the White House has its own ambitious agenda for overhauling the tax code, with legislative liaison Marc Short saying Monday the administration wants to see markups in September with floor action in the House and Senate finished by the end of November. That\u2019s an aggressive timeline to say the least. In September alone, Congress will have to keep the government running, lift the debt ceiling and reauthorize critical programs for flood insurance, children\u2019s health insurance and the FAA. Aaron Lorenzo has more: http://politi.co/2ufOgwn   Side note: Remember earlier this year when Republican leaders insisted they\u2019d have tax reform and health care finished by August? Those were the days.   Senate Democrats, meanwhile, are urging Republicans to go the bipartisan route on tax reform and are already laying out the conditions to secure their votes. \u201cIn a letter to Trump and GOP leaders Tuesday, 45 of the 48 members in the Senate Democratic caucus urged the GOP not to use arcane budget reconciliation procedures to shield any tax reform bill from a filibuster,\u201d Elana reports. More: http://politi.co/2ufTJ6h   SUMMER READING: \u2018MY PARTY IS IN DENIAL ABOUT TRUMP\u2019 \u2014 POLITICO has an except from Sen. Jeff Flake\u2019s new book and not only does he take on Trump, the Arizona Republican also criticizes his leaders and fellow Republicans for the \u201cFaustian bargain\u201d they made with president. \u201cIt was we conservatives who \u2026have maintained an unnerving silence as instability has ensued,\u201d Flake writes. \u201cTo carry on in the spring of 2017 as if what was happening was anything approaching normalcy required a determined suspension of critical faculties. And tremendous powers of denial.\u201d Much more: http://politi.co/2tZt171   WE MADE IT TO AUGUST, Y\u2019ALL. College football is so close. Welcome to Tuesday, Aug.1, and thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill.   MONDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: My story with Paul Demko on centrist lawmakers backing a bipartisan health care bill was the winner to start off the week.   IF YOU LEAD, WILL I FOLLOW? Democrats rolled out their 2018 agenda to much fanfare last week. But what remains to be seen is who in the party will go along and who will peel off and do their own thing. Not every incumbent wants to be associated with the party\u2019s message, Gabe, Elana and your Huddle host report. And many of the party\u2019s influential groups \u2014 including the Democratic National Committee and individual state party committees \u2014 are busy preparing their own, independent lines of messaging. \u201cJust as there isn\u2019t one kind of Democrat, there are not just one kind of message that works,\u201d said Rep. Jim Costa, a Blue Dog co-chair, who like several moderates endorsed the broader idea of an economic message without backing the progressive policies outlined so far. More: http://politi.co/2ufuAsG   BARLETTA PLANS SENATE BID \u2014 Pennsylvania Rep. Lou Barletta, one of Trump\u2019s biggest supporters on Capitol Hill, will challenge Democratic Sen. Bob Casey next year, the AP reports. \u201cA person familiar with the discussions told The Associated Press that Barletta began telling party officials of his decision last week, several months after he began considering it. \u2026In a text message Monday, Barletta said that his conversations have been \u2018very positive\u2019 and that he will announce his decision in a few weeks.\u201d More: http://bit.ly/2udtbmh   WATCHDOG WANTS WASSERMAN SCHULTZ PROBE \u2014 A right-leaning watchdog is pushing for an ethics probe into Rep. Debbie Wasserman Schultz (D-Fla.) after she kept an IT staffer employed for six months after he became the focus of a criminal investigation in February. The staffer, Imran Awan, was fired last week after he was arrested on one count of bank fraud during an attempt to leave the country. FACT, the watchdog, says Wasserman Schultz may have violated House rules by continuing to employ Iwan as an IT staffer over the last six months even though he was barred from using the House network. The Florida Democrat shot back, saying Awan did a variety of administrative duties and calling the complaint \u201centirely baseless.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2tZP3qa   RETIREMENT WATCH: DUNCAN OUT \u2014 Rep. Jimmy Duncan, the Tennessee Republican who has been in Congress since 1988, won\u2019t run for reelection next year, he told the local CBS affiliate Monday. But it's unlikely Duncan\u2019s Knoxville district will be a top target for Democrats. As Kevin points out, the seat has been in Republican hands since 1859.   BIG ISSUES IN THE BIG TENT? Rep. Ben Ray Lujan (D-N.M.), chairman of House Democrats\u2019 campaign arm, caused a little stir Monday when he told the Hill that the DCCC wouldn\u2019t shy away from financially supporting candidates who oppose abortion. The news shouldn\u2019t come as that big of a surprise \u2013 House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.) made clear earlier this year that there wouldn\u2019t be a \u201clitmus test\u201d for Democratic candidates. And the DCCC has been working closely with Blue Dogs, who already count three pro-life Democrats as members, on recruitment. But former DNC Chairman Howard Dean tweeted the news would prompt him to withhold support from the DCCC if true.   POLICE DIRECTED TO WRONG SITE IN SCALISE SHOOTING \u2014 The Capitol Police has opened an internal investigation after its officers initially responded to the wrong site during the congressional baseball practice shooting that severely wounded House Majority Whip Steve Scalise (R-La.) in June. The Capitol\u2019s elite tactical team was initially sent to House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi\u2019s house in Georgetown, several miles away, Billy House reports. \u201cThe tactical squad did make it to the Eugene Simpson Stadium Park in Alexandria, Virginia, where the shooting took place and it\u2019s unclear how much time the unit lost because of the mix-up. It also wasn\u2019t clear whether the squad arrived at Pelosi\u2019s house or was redirected en route.\u201d Bloomberg: https://bloom.bg/2tZU95H   MOVIN\u2019 ON UP \u2014 Natasha Hickman, longtime aide to Sen. Richard Burr (R-NC), has been promoted from legislative director to chief of staff today. Natasha started her Senate career with Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison and also served in the Bush Administration. Christopher Toppings, deputy legislative director, has been promoted to legislative director.   TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The Senate gavels in at 10 a.m. with weekly caucus lunches from 12:30 p.m. to 2 p.m. The House is gone for recess.   AROUND THE HILL \u2014 Senate Republican and Democratic leaders hold separate press conferences following their weekly party lunches, around 2 p.m.   MONDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Dave Bass, assistant sergeant at arms, was first to correctly guess that Nebraska Sen. Ed Zorinsky suffered a fatal heart attack in 1987, just hours after performing a song-and-dance routine poking fun at his decision to switch parties from Republican to Democrat.   TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 Dave with today\u2019s question: What senator holds the distinct honor for the shortest pro forma session and how long was it? The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
