aV \u000a            By HEATHER CAYGLE  07/31/2017 07:52 AM EDT  With an assist from Daniel Lippman   AIN\u2019T NO STOPPING US NOW \u2014 Sensing a window after the Senate\u2019s health care collapse, a bipartisan group of House lawmakers is moving quickly to unveil their own health care bill later today. The plan aims to stabilize Obamacare and make changes to the law backed by both sides, multiple sources told your Huddle host and Paul Demko. Roughly 40 centrist House Republicans and Democrats have signed onto the effort, which is being led by the bipartisan Problem Solvers Caucus.   Story Continued Below  The House plan: The most significant proposal is funding for Obamacare\u2019s cost-sharing subsidies. President Donald Trump has repeatedly threatened to cut off the payments, which could cause the insurance markets to implode. Trump is expected to decide this week whether to continue making the payments. Much more: http://politi.co/2uc1yu5   It ain\u2019t over til it\u2019s over: Trump fumed over the weekend about the Senate\u2019s failure to repeal Obamacare, taking to Twitter to vent his frustrations and calling on Senate leaders to change the chamber\u2019s longstanding filibuster rules. The president met with Sens. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.), Bill Cassidy (R-La.) and Dean Heller (R-Nev.) on Friday to talk about ways to revive the repeal push, including a block grant idea floated by Graham. House Freedom Caucus Chairman Mark Meadows (R-N.C.) also met with White House officials. Burgess, Josh and Rachael with more: http://politi.co/2ubDAim   That\u2019ll go over well: OMB Director Mick Mulvaney (a former House guy, mind you) said the White House is taking the official stance that the Senate shouldn\u2019t vote on anything else until Republicans revive their Obamacare repeal. \u201cIn the White House's view, they can't move on in the Senate,\u201d Mulvaney said Sunday on CNN. Remember, Congress has a long list of things to do come September, including funding the government, raising the debt ceiling, reauthorizing the FAA, renewing the children\u2019s health insurance program and more.   BRINGING OUT THE BIG GUNS \u2014 Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell is going all out to make sure one of two conservatives doesn\u2019t win the Aug. 15 GOP Senate primary in Alabama and make his life just a little tougher in the upper chamber. The Republican leader is trying to thwart Rep. Mo Brooks and former state Supreme Court Chief Justice Roy Moore, both of whom are campaigning against McConnell and recently appointed Sen. Luther Strange.   The deets: McConnell\u2019s super PAC is set to spend as much as $8 million to boost Strange. The Kentucky Republican has also \u201cactivated his sprawling donor network and pressed the White House for more resources.\u201d And the NRSC has warned consultants they'll be cut off in the future if they assist Strange\u2019s opponents. Alex Isenstadt: http://politi.co/2ubN7Wz   WELCOME TO MONDAY, JULY 31. Thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill. Things are quiet on the House side but still rocking in the Senate.  FRIDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: The NBC News video of Sen. John McCain giving the pivotal thumbs down, sinking the GOP\u2019s skinny repeal early Friday morning, was the big winner.   ON THE OTHER END OF PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE\u2026 Homeland Security Secretary John Kelly takes command of the West Wing today after Trump ousted chief of staff Reince Priebus on Friday. \u201cTrump enters a new phase of his presidency on Monday with a new chief of staff but an old set of challenges as he seeks to get back on course after enduring one of the worst weeks that any modern occupant of the Oval Office has experienced in his inaugural year in power,\u201d Peter Baker reports. The New York Times: http://nyti.ms/2ubKKmI   Help wanted: Kelly\u2019s move to the West Wing leaves a vacancy at the top of DHS, and could trigger a nasty confirmation fight depending on whom Trump nominates to replace the former Marine general. One name being floated is House Homeland Security Chairman Mike McCaul, who was passed over for the job the first time around. Ted Hesson and Andrew Restuccia report: http://politi.co/2ubuS3R   \u2018STICK THE LANDING\u2019 ON TAX REFORM \u2014 With the GOP\u2019s Obamacare repeal effort in the gutter (at least for now), House leaders are pivoting to their next big agenda item: tax reform. \u201cI feel much more confident that we\u2019re going to stick the landing on tax reform,\u2019\u2019 Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.) said on Fox News Sunday. But not so fast. Both Ryan and Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady (R-Texas) are already rejecting a 44 percent tax rate for people making more than $5 million per year, an idea being pushed by White House adviser Steve Bannon. Bloomberg\u2019s Benjamin Bain: https://bloom.bg/2ubObKo   Meanwhile, American Action Network, the outside group aligned with House leadership, plans to spend up to $20 million boosting its tax reform priorities. Katie Glueck with McClatchy: http://bit.ly/2ubAoDi   SHOW ME THE MONEY \u2014 The National Democratic Redistricting Committee, the group backed by former President Barack Obama and led by former Attorney General Eric Holder, brought in nearly $11 million in its first six months, Edward-Isaac Dovere reports this morning. \u201cMuch of the fundraising was through five briefings for donors conducted by Holder, House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi and Virginia Gov. Terry McAuliffe in New York, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Boston and Washington, but an event that Obama headlined in Washington earlier this month gave the efforts a significant boost.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2ubvvKy   AND SPEAKING OF WAR CHESTS\u2026 Senate Leadership Fund and One Nation, the main outside groups backing Senate Republicans, have nearly $22 million combined in their bank accounts after raising $17 million in the first six half of the year, Kevin Robillard reports. \u201cThe massive war chest, raised with Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell's help, should aid Senate Republicans as they try to win 10 Democratic-held seats in states President Donald Trump won last November, while playing defense for Nevada Sen. Dean Heller and Arizona Sen. Jeff Flake.\u201d More for Pros: http://politico.pro/2ubV0eZ   YOU CAN\u2019T ALWAYS GET WHAT YOU WANT \u2014 \u201cRep. John Delaney may not be the presidential candidate Democrats want. But the wealthy, low-profile congressman and newly minted 2020 hopeful believes he\u2019s what the country needs,\u201d Kevin writes in Huddle\u2019s favorite lede of the weekend. Kevin with more on what Delaney is thinking: http://politi.co/2ubvyWX   Dress rehearsal: And Gabriel Debenedetti reports on how Democrats are seizing on the 2018 midterms to distinguish themselves from the pack. \u201cTop contenders are making endorsements, picking sides in party primaries and aggressively working the fundraising circuit on behalf of 2018 candidates, all the while building their own name recognition.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2ubQ61y   McCAIN BEGINS CANCER TREATMENT \u2014 Sen. John McCain is back in Arizona where he begins treatment this week for an aggressive form of brain cancer. \u201cMcCain had hoped the Senate could quickly debate and pass the defense authorization bill once health care was completed. Senate Democrats said they would be willing \u2014 if Republicans dropped the repeal bid,\u201d CNN\u2019s Jeremy Herb reports. But in the end, Sen. Rand Paul (R-Ky.) objected to bringing NDAA up in the Senate, meaning the bill probably won\u2019t get addressed until September. It\u2019s unclear when McCain will return. More: http://cnn.it/2v6GLvJ   GRAPHIC DU JOUR \u2014 The moderate Blue Dog Coalition hopes to play a significant role in helping Democrats take back the House next year. But with only 18 members, the group is still working to rebuild its ranks after nearly half its members lost their seats in 2010. While Blue Dogs used to be primarily concentrated in the south, now their influence can be found more in the West and Midwest. More: http://politi.co/2ubBO0B   WELCOME TO THE WORLD \u2014 Rep. Trey Hollingsworth (R-Ind.) and his wife Kelly, who works in fashion, welcomed their first child, Joseph, on Thursday at 1:38 a.m. "Both Kelly and Joseph are doing well, and Trey is adjusting to fatherhood like a pro, already having taken hundreds of photos and videos of his new son." Pic: http://bit.ly/2haD96I  TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The Senate gavels in at 4 p.m. with one roll call vote at 5:30 p.m. The House is gone for recess.   AROUND THE HILL \u2014 Rep. Brad Sherman, (D-Calif.), TV host Marc Summers and others participate in a discussion on Americans with disabilities at 9 a.m. in 2168 Rayburn.   FRIDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Vince Magruder was first to guess that Ronald Reagan was the union leader later elected president. Reagan was president of the Screen Actos Guild from 1947 to 1952 and again in 1959.   TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 Vince with today\u2019s question: Last week yielded some pretty epic theatrics in the Senate. Fortunately, it did not involve a member of the body performing a song-and-dance routine, only to pass away within a few hours. Who was this senator and what were the circumstances? The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   Heather Caygle is a Congress reporter for POLITICO.  Before coming to POLITICO, Caygle was a congressional reporter for Bloomberg BNA, primarily covering transportation but also dabbling in Hill action on tax reform, agriculture, appropriations and the Postal Service. Her work has also been featured on the WashingtonPost.com and WAMU.  Caygle, an Alabama native, is a graduate of the University of Alabama at Birmingham and received her master's from American University in Washington. She loves rooting on the Alabama football team \u2014 Roll Tide \u2014 and spending time with her corgi/chihuahua mix named Biggie Smalls.  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
