aV 07/28/2017 08:07 AM EDT  By Heather Caygle (hcaygle@politico.com or @heatherscope)  SENATE REJECTS OBAMACARE REPEAL \u2014 In a dramatic floor vote that unfolded after midnight, three Senate Republicans joined with all 48 Democrats to sink the GOP's seven-year effort to repeal Obamacare. Sen. John McCain -- who returned after a cancer diagnosis to give Republicans the vote they needed to begin debate at the start of this week -- was the pivotal third GOP vote that killed the bill. McCain\u2019s no vote was met with audible gasps from colleagues inside the chamber. "I don't think we all knew until he actually did it," Sen. Shelley Moore Capito (R-W.Va.) said after. Sens. Lisa Murkowski (R-Alaska) and Susan Collins (R-Maine) also voted against the plan.  Story Continued Below  \u201cWatch the show,\u201d McCain told reporters as he was heading into the chamber. The unexpected turn of events capped at bizarre day that involved several Republicans only agreeing to vote for the \u201cskinny repeal\u201d after receiving assurances from Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.) that the House wouldn\u2019t pass the bill and instead would go to conference. "I do my job as a senator," McCain said after he left the Senate chamber, saying he voted against the Obamacare repeal bill "because I thought it was the right vote."   Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell reacts: \u201cYes, this is a disappointment. A disappointment indeed,\u201d he said after the vote failed around 1:40 a.m. Bres, Burgess, Jen and Seung Min with the play-by-play: http://politi.co/2tPdYfK   The video: Watch McCain give the pivotal thumbs down, via NBC: http://bit.ly/2tOU8Sb   THE MAVERICK IS BACK \u2014 McCain\u2019s decisive vote \u201cwas a shocking \u2014 yet fitting \u2014 coda for the Senate\u2019s health care battle, starring the veteran senator with a well-polished maverick streak. Within days he went from Obamacare repeal\u2019s savior to its executioner,\u201d Seung Min, Burgess and Jen write. Even a late night call from President Trump couldn\u2019t change the independent senator's mind. \u201cHe's now become a hero for Democrats, effectively voting to protect the chief legislative achievement of President Barack Obama, his opponent in the 2008 presidential campaign.\u201d Much more from our terrific health care trio (posted at 4:52 a.m.!): http://politi.co/2tOGOgq   OUR BUREAU CHIEF ON WHAT\u2019S NEXT: \u201cHealth-care fight is over, and it was a disaster for GOP. Now Rs will shift to tax reform. Open question whether they can pass anything,\u201d Bres tweeted this morning.  Speaking of tax reform\u2026 \u201cThe White House, the Treasury Department and congressional leaders issued a six-paragraph statement Thursday that tried to show off their commitment to pursuing tax reform without delving into any policy specifics,\u201d Nancy Cook and Aaron Lorenzo report. \u201cThe only problem? Tax overhauls live and die on details \u2014 and their absence, after months of weekly meetings aimed at achieving consensus, showed that the GOP\u2019s dream of achieving tax reform may be years from completion.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2tPpUhW   FINALLY FRIDAY, FREE AGAIN. Thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill. Welcome to July 28, where we couldn\u2019t be more ready for the weekend (and August recess). Happy hour starts early today!   THURSDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: You guys went gangbusters for the pic of former Speaker John Boehner (R-Ohio) and Sens. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) and John McCain (R-Ariz.) catching up at the neighborhood Italian restaurant.   HOUSE VOTES TO FUND BORDER WALL \u2014 The House passed a $789 billion defense spending package that includes what GOP leaders have dubbed a $1 billion \u201cdown payment\u201d for Trump\u2019s border wall. \u201cThe measure's passage also caps several weeks of sparring on other contentious items, such as Congress\u2019 war authorization power and the military\u2019s rules on transgender troops,\u201d Sarah Ferris reports. The four-bill package now heads to the Senate, where it doesn\u2019t stand a chance of passing as is. More: http://politi.co/2tHNNU8   Thursday in a nutshell: \u201cHouse GOP today approved a spending bill they know can't pass and Senate GOP wants to approve a health bill they hope won't become law,\u201d the New York Times\u2019 chief Washington correspondent Carl Hulse tweeted.   SANCTIONS BILL HEADS TO THE PRESIDENT \u2014 The Senate voted 98-2 Thursday to send a sweeping Russia, Iran and North Korea sanctions package to the White House, essentially daring the president to reject an accord that ties his hands on the Kremlin and has received overwhelming bipartisan support on the Hill. The White House has avoided taking any clear position on whether Trump will sign the bill into law but Congress has more than enough votes to override a presidential veto if needed. Elana with the wrap up: http://politi.co/2tPuxs3   Related: Russia retaliated to the sanctions vote by seizing two American properties and ordering the U.S. embassy in Moscow to reduce its staff by September. The New York Times: http://nyti.ms/2tPj1gw   PELOSI DEFENDS BRADY AMID INVESTIGATION \u2014 House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi defended Rep. Bob Brady (D-Pa.) on Thursday amid an ongoing federal investigation into whether his campaign illegally paid another candidate to drop out in 2012. Brady has not been charged with a crime. But the campaign manager for Brady\u2019s challenger pleaded guilty earlier this week to helping hide $90,000 in payments received from Brady\u2019s campaign in 2012. \u201cI know that Congressman Brady has fully cooperated with authorities and he has done nothing wrong,\u201d Pelosi (D-Calif.) told reporters during her weekly press conference Thursday. More from your Huddle host: http://politi.co/2tHO1e2   DELANEY HAS 2020 VISION \u2014 Rep. John Delaney (D-Md.) plans on bypassing runs for governor and reelection and has told associates he is seriously considering a bid for president in 2020, according to two Democratic sources, Kevin and yours truly report. Delaney, who could self-fund a run for governor, will skip a challenge against popular GOP Gov. Larry Hogan and will leave Democrats to defend his district, which he nearly lost in 2014. More: http://politi.co/2tPkJOE   Speaking of 2020 contenders, Michael Kruse profiles Rep. Seth Moulton (D-Mass.) for POLITICO Magazine today: Chatter about Moulton for president \u201cis precisely the type of talk that\u2019s currently causing disgusted eye-rolling among significantly more tenured Democrats in Massachusetts and Washington,\u201d Kruse writes. But Moulton, with three degrees from Harvard and four decorated tours as a Marine in Iraq, has top military allies on his side, who see him as the antithesis of Trump. Much more: http://politi.co/2tPidYL   \u2018HOLY HELL TO PAY\u2019 \u2014 Sen. Lindsey Graham wasn\u2019t mincing his words Thursday, telling reporters there would be \u201choly hell to pay\u201d if Trump fires Attorney General Jeff Sessions. The South Carolina Republican took it a step further when asked what the reaction on Capitol Hill would be to Trump firing special counsel Robert Mueller, calling it the possible \u201cbeginning of the end of the Trump presidency.\u201d Graham also outlined bipartisan legislation that would block Trump from firing the special counsel \u2014 by requiring a judicial review first, Darren Samuelsohn reports. More: http://politi.co/2tPnqzM   Related: Sessions says Trump\u2019s criticism of him over is \u201ckind of hurtful.\u201d Fox News: http://fxn.ws/2tPl2Jm   TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The House meets at 9 a.m. with votes around 10:30 a.m. Today\u2019s agenda: http://bit.ly/2tPj7Vi. The Senate is out, returning Monday at 4 p.m.   AROUND THE HILL \u2014  House Minority Whip Steny Hoyer (D-Md.), Rep. Luis Gutierrez (D-Ill.) and other members of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus hold an 11 a.m. press conference on their bill to establish legal status for undocumented immigrants brought to the U.S. as children.   THURSDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Peter Roff was first to guess that Ross Perot, whose candidacy split the Republican vote allowing Bill Clinton to be elected, appeared on all 50 states\u2019 ballots despite quitting the race mid-summer.   TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 Peter with today\u2019s question: Who is the national union president to also be elected to office in Washington, what was the office and what was the union? The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
