aV 07/26/2017 07:59 AM EDT  By Heather Caygle (hcaygle@politico.com or @heatherscope)  With an assist from Daniel Lippman   Story Continued Below  GOP LEADERS EYE \u2018SKINNY\u2019 REPEAL \u2014 With a tie-breaking vote by Vice President Mike Pence and a dramatic return from Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), Republicans finally agreed to open up debate Tuesday on their Obamacare repeal efforts. So now what? The leading idea is to roll back a small portion of Obamacare, called a \u201cskinny repeal\u201d by some, just to get a bill out of the Senate at the end of this week and into a conference with the House, Jen, Seung Min and Burgess report.   \u2018Whatever gets to 50\u2019: The skinny repeal would roll back three parts of Obamacare: the individual and employer mandates and the medical device tax, according to Republican sources. "Whatever gets to 50," said Sen. John Thune (R-S.D.). But there\u2019s still no guarantee the fractured GOP conference can unite around the plan.   Remember, there\u2019s still a lot of votes to get to that point. Late Tuesday night, nine Republicans joined with Democrats to oppose the GOP\u2019s latest repeal and replace plan, which had a controversial amendment from Rep. Ted Cruz (R-Texas) attached. Today, senators will vote on Sen. Rand Paul\u2019s (R-Ky.) \u201crepeal only\u201d idea \u2013 also expected to fail \u2013 and a long vote-a-rama on dozens of other amendments is expected Thursday. More: http://politi.co/2tJ7dMv   Related reading: \u201cWhat\u2019s next in the Senate repeal saga? Good question.\u201d Paul Demko breaks it down: http://politi.co/2tJagoa   SO HOW DID THEY GET TO YES? Just the fact that Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) was able to get 50 of his members to vote in favor of starting debate is a remarkable feat. The saga involved a tense floor exchange between the GOP leader and Sen. Ron Johnson (R-Wis.) \u2013 who has accused McConnell of a \u201cbreach of trust\u201d in negotiations \u2013 and a furious round of mid-flight texts from Sen. Mike Lee (R-Utah) Monday about leadership pressure. \u201cThis leadership line of pass something, anything, is dangerous and potent,\u201d Lee typed out during a flight from Salt Lake, according to an observer. Burgess, SMK and Jen again: http://politi.co/2tIFZG9   Bres keeps it real: McConnell got a huge win Tuesday but now he faces an even harder test \u2014 getting something passed. \u201cThere\u2019s no guarantee McConnell can pull an Obamacare repeal rabbit out of his hat by the end of this week. But at least the show has finally started after nearly two months of delays,\u201d Bres reports. \u201cI think his blood pressure\u2019s about 90 over 50, with about a 40 pulse, OK? He\u2019s very calm through the storm,\u201d Sen. John Kennedy (R-La.) said about the GOP leader. More on McConnell\u2019s work behind the scenes: http://politi.co/2tJcFPI   McCAIN\u2019S TRIUMPHANT RETURN \u2014 Sen. John McCain, recently diagnosed with brain cancer and now sporting a lengthy scar above his eye, was welcomed back with a standing ovation in the Senate chamber. And then he did the most McCain thing ever. Elana explains: \u201cMcCain waved spiritedly to a throng of reporters as he entered the chamber he\u2019s called home for 30 years, served as the crucial 50th vote to proceed to a repeal debate, and delivered a passionate speech undercutting the \u2018shell of a bill\u2019 he had just agreed to take up,\u201d she reports. "I have every intention of returning here and giving many of you cause to regret all the nice things you said about me," McCain said. More: http://politi.co/2tJ1c2D   And don\u2019t miss this other good McCain write up, from Paul Kane at the Washington Post: McCain \u201cdelivered a 15-minute excoriation of the modern Senate. \u2026A Senate so broken that the only way to even begin a health-care debate was to drag an 80-year-old man, diagnosed last week with brain cancer, 2,300 miles across the nation from Phoenix to cast that critical vote.\u201d   YES, IT\u2019S ONLY WEDNESDAY. Welcome to July 26 and thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill.   TUESDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: Rachael, Bres and Sarah\u2019s story about unhappy GOP House appropriators asking Republican leaders to delay recess was the winner.   GOP RALLIES BEHIND SESSIONS \u2014 \u201cCongressional Republicans and conservative activists rallied behind Jeff Sessions on Tuesday, as President Donald Trump continued his public humiliation campaign against the embattled attorney general,\u201d Austin, Seung Min and Kyle report. Sen. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) called Sessions \u201cone of the most decent people I\u2019ve ever met\u201d and several other GOP senators offered similar statements of support. But some Republicans, including Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.), had a different take. Ryan said it was Trump\u2019s \u201cprerogative\u201d who he hires and fires in the executive branch. More: http://politi.co/2tJeOL1   Some lawmakers are warning Trump not to fire Sessions, saying they fear it could be the first step in an attempt to kill the federal Russia investigation. "All hell would break loose," Rep. Mike Simpson, R-Idaho, told David Drucker with the Washington Examiner. More: http://washex.am/2eNiGUL  Sessions has been under fire from Trump over the last week for recusing himself in the Russia probe months ago, a move that led to special counsel Robert Mueller\u2019s appointment. The two men are not currently on speaking terms and Sessions has sent word to the White House that he has no plans to resign. Josh Dawsey: http://politi.co/2tYldNG   SANCTIONS BILL MOVES TO SENATE \u2014 The House overwhelmingly approved new sanctions on Russia, Iran and North Korea Tuesday, teeing up the bipartisan package to be cleared by the Senate before the August recess. The White House has yet to say if Trump will sign the bill, possibly triggering the first veto override of his young presidency. Elana with more: http://politi.co/2tJ1tTd   WASSERMAN SCHULTZ AIDE ARRESTED AT DULLES \u2014 A longtime staffer for Rep. Debbie Wasserman Schultz (D-Fla.) was arrested Monday at Dulles airport before boarding a plane to Pakistan. Imran Awan pled not guilty to one count of bank fraud Tuesday and was released with \u201chighly-supervised\u201d conditions. Awan and several of his family members, who were also House Democratic staffers, have been at the center of a criminal investigation on Capitol Hill for months. Other lawmakers cut ties with the staffers but Wasserman Schultz has kept Awan on her payroll until yesterday, even though he was barred from accessing the House computer network. Awan\u2019s lawyer said the case is a \u201cring-wing media driven prosecution\u201d because his client is Muslim. Your Huddle host and Bres: http://politi.co/2tXpEbx   JUDICIARY DROPS MANAFORT SUBPOENA \u2014 The Senate Judiciary Committee has dropped a subpoena compelling Paul Manafort to testify today about a meeting he, Donald Trump Jr. and Jared Kushner had with a Russian lawyer last year. Manafort, who along with Kushner was on the Hill Tuesday meeting with congressional investigators on the Intel committees, has agreed to a transcribed interview with Senate Judiciary members in the future. Josh Dawsey, Madeline Conway and Kyle with more: http://politi.co/2tIW3ri   WOMAN PLEADS GUILTY IN BRADY CAMPAIGN SCHEME \u2014 A Pennsylvania pastor pled guilty Tuesday to a federal felony for participating in a scheme that led a 2012 primary challenger to Rep. Bob Brady (D-Pa.) to drop out of the race, Josh Gerstein reports. Carolyn Cavaness admitted to helping create false FEC reports disguising the fact that Brady's campaign agreed to pay $90,000 in expenses for her boss, Jimmie Moore, who was challenging Brady. \u201cNo charges have been announced against Moore or Brady. However, one court filing made public Tuesday indicates prosecutors believe Brady attempted to influence the testimony of at least one witness in the investigation.\u201d More: http://politi.co/2tZ0PMA   NEW YORK STATE OF MIND \u2014 Democratic Rep. Louise Slaughter, dean of the New York congressional delegation, will host Gov. Andrew Cuomo today for a meeting with fellow Empire State Democrats on the Hill. On the menu: Obamacare and transportation funding, among other topics. Cuomo will meet with Transportation Secretary Elaine Chao later in the day, Shane Goldmacher reports for the New York Times.   IS IT TOO LATE NOW TO SAY SORRY? Sen. Susan Collins (R-Maine) has apologized after being caught on a hot mic Tuesday calling Rep. Blake Farenthold \u201chuge\u201d and \u201cso unattractive, it\u2019s unbelievable.\u201d Her remarks to Sen. Jack Reed (D-R.I.) \u2013 who colorfully said Collins could most certainly kick Farenthold\u2019s butt \u2013 came after the Texas Republican made a remark Monday about challenging Collins and other female GOP senators to an Obamacare-related duel, if only they were men. \u201cNeither weapons nor inappropriate words are the right way to resolve legislative disputes,\u201d Collins said in a statement, noting Farenthold also sent her a handwritten apology.   COMING TO A BOOKSHELF NEAR YOU \u2014 Sen. Jeff Flake, up for reelection next year and facing a possible primary challenge from the Trump-wing of the party, is writing a book, the New York Times reports. \u201cWorking privately, and largely without the knowledge of political advisers, he has written a book that amounts to an ideological manifesto for his own version of conservatism, according to three people briefed on the manuscript,\u201d Alex Burns reports. \u201cAll three said it would likely inflame debate about the direction of the Republican Party.\u201d No word on when it will be released. More: http://nyti.ms/2tXdgIE   WELCOME TO THE WORLD \u2014 Rep. Ryan Costello (R-Pa.) and Christine Costello, a finance consultant, on Monday welcomed Caroline Grace Costello, who weighed in at 9 lbs 6 oz. She joins big brother Ryan Jr. in the "overjoyed" Costello household. Pics of Rep. Costello with Caroline and Ryan Jr: http://politi.co/2tHB8VD and http://politi.co/2vG55CJ  TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The House gavels in at 10 a.m. with first votes at 1:30 p.m. and last votes at 10 p.m. Today\u2019s agenda: http://bit.ly/2tJ6085. The Senate meets at 9:30 a.m. with roll call votes at 11:30 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. related to the GOP\u2019s Obamacare repeal.   AROUND THE HILL \u2014 Sens. Bob Casey (D-Pa.), Chris Van Hollen (D-Md.), Tammy Duckworth (D-Ill.) and Maggie Hassan (D-N.H.) hold a 12 p.m. press conference in front of the Supreme Court about the potential impact the GOP\u2019s health care bill will have on the disability community.  TUESDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Emily Farnell correctly guessed that Georgia Rep. John Coffee was the Jacksonian Democrat who has the honor of being the first House member posthumously elected, according to the House historian. Coffee \u201cdied September 25, 1836, but was reelected posthumously on October 3, 1836, \u2018announcement of his death not having been received.\u2019\u201d  TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 Emily with today\u2019s question: In honor of the Harry W. Colmery Veterans Education Assistance Act passing out of the House 405-0 on Monday and its imminent move in the Senate, here is a tidbit of GI Bill trivia: When President Roosevelt signed the original GI Bill on June 22, 1944, who received the first pen? The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
