aV 07/25/2017 07:47 AM EDT  By Heather Caygle (hcaygle@politico.com or @heatherscope)  With an assist from Elana Schor  Story Continued Below  McCAIN COMING BACK TODAY \u2014 Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), diagnosed with an aggressive brain cancer just days ago, will make a dramatic return to the Senate today. McCain\u2019s decision to come back, announced Monday night, could help deliver GOP leaders enough votes to open up debate on their Obamacare repeal later today. The vote is expected some time after lunch.   "The whip count is still in question with several GOP senators publicly undecided, but Republicans feel a surge of momentum heading into the high-profile vote after a furious pressure campaign by President Donald Trump and Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell on Monday,\u201d Burgess, Seung Min and Jen Haberkorn report.   Fishing in the dark: The crazy thing is most Republican senators don\u2019t even know what they\u2019re agreeing to debate if today\u2019s vote is successful. \u201cRepublican leaders are being as vague as possible about what the final bill to replace Obamacare would include, after two recent drafts met fatal opposition. McConnell is reminding his members that there will be a price to pay for inaction after the GOP railed against Obamacare for seven years.\u201d  Quote du jour: \u201cThe sight of the gallows focuses the mind,\u201d said Sen. John Kennedy (R-La.). More from the team: http://politi.co/2uqDcQp   From the president\u2019s desk this morning: @realDonaldTrump: \u201cBig day for HealthCare. After 7 years of talking, we will soon see whether or not Republicans are willing to step up to the plate!\u201d  HOUSE SET TO PASS SANCTIONS AS WH DODGES \u2014The House will vote today on a bipartisan package of sanctions against Russia, Iran, and North Korea. The accord, which is expected to garner overwhelming bipartisan support, also empowers Congress to block President Trump from easing sanctions against Moscow. At first the White House appeared to nod to the political reality that any veto would get overridden by claiming that the bill\u2019s largely technical changes since last month assuaged its concerns, with press secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders telling ABC on Sunday that Trump supported the bill.   But Sanders backpedaled on Monday, telling reporters on Air Force One that Trump would have to \u201cstudy that legislation\u201d before weighing in definitively. \u201cHe has no intention of getting rid of\u201d sanctions on Moscow, Sanders said, \u201cbut he wants to make sure we get the best deal for the American people possible.\u201d Stay tuned.   DEEP BREATHS, IT\u2019S TUESDAY ALREADY. Welcome to July 25 and thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill.   MONDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: The DCCC polling memo, released in conjunction with Democrats\u2019 agenda rollout Monday, was the winner to start off the week.   DEMS SIDESTEP SOCIAL DIVISIONS IN NEW AGENDA \u2014 Democratic leaders descended upon the rural town of Berryville, Va., Monday to unveil their new agenda, a progressive-leaning economic plank that noticeably sidesteps the many social issues threatening to further divide the party. \u201cThere is not that divide on economic issues,\u201d Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) told reporters as Massachusetts Sen. Elizabeth Warren, whose anti-corporate agenda influenced Democrats\u2019 new strategy, worked a small but adoring crowd in a county that went for Donald Trump by more than 55 percent last year. Elana and yours truly with much more from Berryville: http://politi.co/2tVXAp9   'LYIN' TED' FOR AG? Trump went on another tweestorm this morning blasting his attorney general for being \u201cweak\u201d amid ongoing speculation the president is looking to replace Jeff Sessions just months into the job. Some of the names being floated, according to the Washington Post, are Sen. Ted Cruz (R-Texas), who Trump has frequently referred to as \u201cLyin\u2019 Ted\u201d in the past, and former NYC Mayor Rudy Giuliani. Giuliani dismissed reports he was being eyed for the job to CNN and Cruz reiterated his support for Sessions as AG in a Monday night statement. More from Sari Horwitz, Matt Zapotosky and Robert Costa: http://wapo.st/2gZ2roq   UNHAPPY APPROPRIATORS WANT RECESS DELAY \u2014 \u201cHouse Republican appropriators are pressing Speaker Paul Ryan to cancel the first week of recess and tackle a massive spending package full of goodies for the base \u2014 a strategy leadership rejected last week,\u201d Rachael, Bres and Sarah Ferris report. Some furious appropriators have even threatened to vote against the minibus \u2013 a package of four spending bills GOP leaders are bringing to the floor for a vote this week \u2013 unless the other funding bills are included. But Republican leaders still don\u2019t have the votes to pass a massive spending package, which is why they didn\u2019t bring it up this week in the first place. More: http://politi.co/2tWbIhX   KUSHNER INTEL INTERVIEW, TAKE TWO \u2014 House Intel Chairman Devin Nunes (R-Calif.) is expected to attend today\u2019s closed-door interview with Jared Kushner, Kyle reports. Nunes stepped aside from the House Russia probe earlier this year but has inserted himself into the investigation a few times since. Kushner denied any collusion with the Russians in the 2016 campaign during a brief statement at the White House Monday after he was interviewed by Senate Intel members. The president\u2019s son-in-law and adviser didn\u2019t take any questions. Annie Karni has more on how Kushner\u2019s statement actually raises more questions than answers: http://politi.co/2gWMRcF   PLEASE HOLD FOR WHIP SCALISE \u2014 House Majority Whip Steve Scalise (R-La.) surprised his colleagues Monday night by calling into the Republican whip meeting \u2013 his first time participating since he was nearly killed during a congressional baseball practice shooting in June. Scalise was in good spirits, according to sources in the room, and said he\u2019s getting ready to start rehab, a huge milestone in his recovery. Scalise told his colleagues he was eager to get back to work and jokingly asked: "Has the Senate passed the health care bill yet?" Rachael reports: http://politi.co/2tW2N0d   Startling stat: Ed O\u2019Keefe reports many lawmakers were unsettled about security even before the shooting due to a significant rise in threats against members this year. \u201cStill, this year, more than 1,650 threats have been made against lawmakers, or the U.S. Capitol or Congress, said senior congressional aides familiar with the figures who were not authorized to share them publicly. That figure for about the first half of the year is just short of the number of threats in all of 2016, the aides said.\u201d The Washington Post: http://wapo.st/2tVNwfK   HOUSE DEMS SINK TWO BILLS \u2014 Democrats sank two key bills on the House floor Monday night, \u201cembarrassing Republican leaders who were banking on the noncontroversial legislation sailing through \u2014 in a new sign of the opposition's party's frustration with the majority's approach,\u201d Connor O\u2019Brien reports. Democrats banded together to oppose an intelligence authorization bill \u2013 arguing GOP leaders were trying to sidestep debate over Trump and Russia \u2013 and a veterans\u2019 health care bill, with funding for the program set to run out in mid-August. Lawmakers are expected to revisit both bills. More: http://politi.co/2tVvxWY   BROOKS DEFENDS CONTROVERSIAL AD \u2014 Alabama Rep. Mo Brooks, who is running in the state\u2019s GOP Senate primary, is defending a controversial campaign ad using footage from the baseball practice shooting that severely wounded Whip Scalise. Brooks was also at the field during the shooting. Scalise's chief of staff, Brett Horton, tweeted that the spot made his "stomach turn.\u201d But Brooks said his ad is not out of line because Sen. Luther Strange has made the Second Amendment a major issue in their upcoming primary, Daniel Strauss reports. More: http://politi.co/2tGfzoh   ARRIVAL LOUNGE \u2014 Dominique McKay has been named press secretary for Sen. John Thune\u2019s leadership office, the Senate Republican Conference. She previously worked as deputy press secretary for the House Education Committee. The conference has also tapped Adam Scheidler as creative director starting July 31. He currently works as digital communications director for the House Financial Services Committee.   TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The House meets at 10 a.m. with first votes at 1:30 p.m. and last votes at 4:30 p.m. Today\u2019s agenda (which includes the Russia-Iran-North Korea sanctions package): http://bit.ly/2tVNJQh. The Senate meets at 12 p.m. with weekly caucus lunches until 2 p.m. The Senate will hold a roll vote post-lunch on whether to open debate on the GOP\u2019s health care bill(s).   AROUND THE HILL \u2014 The Faith & Politics Institute presents Sens. Tim Kaine (D-Va.) and Tim Scott (R-S.C.) with leadership awards during a ceremony in the Library of Congress\u2019 Jefferson building at 8:30 a.m. Reps. John Lewis (D-Ga.) and House Minority Whip Steny Hoyer (D-Md.) will present the awards.   Hoyer and Reps. Ruben Gallego (D-Ariz.), Luis Gutierrez (D-Ill.), Filemon Vela (D-Texas), Pete Aguilar (D-Calif.) and Adriano Espaillat (D-N.Y.) hold a press conference at 10 a.m. in the House triangle on the GOP plan to include border wall funding in the spending bill package this week.  House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.), Assistant Democratic Leader James Clyburn (D-S.C.) and Democratic Reps. Cheri Bustos (Ill.), David Cicilline (R.I.), Hakeem Jeffries (N.Y.), Scott Peters (Calif.), Judy Chu (Calif.), Mark Pocan (Wis.) and Tony Cardenas (Calif.) hold a press conference on Democrats\u2019 new agenda at 10:15 a.m. in HVC Studio A.   Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.) and other GOP leaders hold a 10 a.m. press avail in HC-8 after their weekly conference meeting. Hoyer holds his weekly pen and pad at 11:15 a.m. in H-144. Pelosi, Sen. Elizabeth Warren (D-Mass.) and Rep. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.) hold a press conference on GOP efforts to roll back Dodd-Frank at 11:30 a.m. in HVC Studio A.   Sens. Tom Udall (D-N.M.) and Richard Blumenthal (D-Conn.) hold a 12 p.m. press conference in the Senate swamp on banning dangerous pesticides. Pelosi and Reps. Rosa DeLauro (D-Conn.) and Eric Swalwell (D-Calif.) hold a meeting on ways to improve Obamacare at 1 p.m. in HVC 215. Rep. Bobby Scott (D-Va.) and Sen. Bernie Sanders (I-Vt.) hold a press conference on raising the minimum wage at 1 p.m. in the House triangle.  Senate Republican and Democratic leaders hold separate press conferences after their weekly caucus lunches, starting around 2 p.m. in the Ohio clock corridor.   MONDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Nobody got it. Let\u2019s try one more time.   TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 This southern lawmaker, who is sometimes confused with his first cousin (Huddle made the same mistake at first), served in his state\u2019s militia before being elected as a Jacksonian Democrat. He has a distinct honor in House history. Who is this person and what is he notable for in the House?  The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
