aV 07/24/2017 08:13 AM EDT  By Heather Caygle (hcaygle@politico.com or @heatherscope)  With an assist from Daniel Lippman  Story Continued Below  DEMS PROMISE \u2018BETTER DEAL\u2019 IN BERRYVILLE \u2014 Democratic leaders will unveil a broad economic agenda later today, hoping to unite the disparate wings of their caucuses and win back working-class voters who fled the party last year. Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.), House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.) and other top Democrats head to Berryville, Va., to roll out the package under the slogan \u201cA Better Deal\u201d in an afternoon press conference. Democrats chose the predominantly white, northern Virginia area represented by Republican Rep. Barbara Comstock because it\u2019s exactly the kind of district they need to win to take back Congress next year.  The deets: The agenda being introduced is \u201cquite different than the Democratic Party you heard in the past,\u201d Schumer said Sunday on ABC\u2019S \u201cThis Week.\u201d \u201cWe were too cautious, we were too namby-pamby.\u201d To fill that void, Democrats are adding pitches aimed at battling corporate overreach to an economic platform that already includes a trillion-dollar infrastructure plan and paid family leave. More from Elana and yours truly: http://politi.co/2tTAhfE   First in Huddle: The DCCC is out with a new polling memo showing the agenda is already testing well with Democratic and swing voters in battleground districts. Read the memo here first: http://politi.co/2tDpKdq   Counterprogramming: The GOP\u2019s Congressional Leadership Fund is launching digital ads in the 12 Democratic districts won by President Donald Trump, Kevin Robillard reports for Morning Score. \u201cThe 30-second ads link Democrats to the most radical elements of the so-called resistance to Trump and to unpopular House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi.\u201d Watch the ad here.  KUSHNER DENIES COLLUSION \u2014 Jared Kushner will deny colluding with Russia in the 2016 campaign during closed-door testimony before the Senate Intelligence Committee today. The president\u2019s son-in-law will also tell the Senate panel he was unaware of the topic when he arrived late to a meeting with Donald Trump Jr., Paul Manafort and the Russian lawyer claiming to have dirt on Hillary Clinton last year, according to prepared remarks released Monday. \u201cI had no improper contacts. I did not collude, nor know of anyone else in the campaign who colluded, with any foreign government,\u201d Kushner said in his prepared statement. The New York Times Matt Apuzzo and Maggie Haberman: http://nyti.ms/2tSZln6   -The House Intelligence Committee is set to interview Kushner Tuesday, the panel announced late last week. Austin: http://politi.co/2tCNPB5.  CRITICAL HEALTH CARE VOTE THIS WEEK \u2014 Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell is going ahead with a push to begin debate on the GOP's health care plan, even though it appears Republican leaders will fall short of the 50 votes needed to move forward. Some senior Republicans think the high-profile vote, which is expected Tuesday, could provoke enough backlash to bring senators back to the negotiating table. But senators don\u2019t even know what bill they\u2019d be moving on to \u2013 the 2015 repeal or the GOP\u2019s repeal and replace plan \u2013 if enough members agreed to start debate. With two senators on record against proceeding and Sen. John McCain\u2019s absence, the vote is on track to fail without last minute changes, Jen Haberkorn and Seung Min report. More: http://politi.co/2tDtFXD   Further complicating things, the Senate parliamentarian on Friday afternoon ruled against key provisions in the GOP\u2019s repeal and replace plan, including language targeting Planned Parenthood and restricting health care plans that provide abortion coverage, Jen and Seung Min report. The ruling against the abortion language is a huge hurdle in the House, report Jonathan Cohn, Laura Bassett and Matt Fuller for HuffPost. \u201cFreedom Caucus Chairman Mark Meadows suggested that, without that prohibition, the bill could not pass the House on the way back from the Senate.\u201d More: http://bit.ly/2tDgzcH   WE\u2019VE GOT A CASE OF THE MONDAYS TOO, Y\u2019ALL. Welcome to July 24 and thanks for tuning into POLITICO\u2019s Huddle, the play-by-play guide to all things Capitol Hill. And a very special happy birthday to my dad Ricky, who can give a wedding toast that's outta this world and cut a rug like you've never seen.   FRIDAY\u2019S MOST CLICKED: The latest on the Russia sanctions package, via Elana, was the winner.   DON\u2019T CALL IT A COMEBACK \u2014 The Blue Dog Coalition, a small group of conservative House Democrats, is eyeing an aggressive comeback in the 2018 election, arguing candidates that back their platform are the key to taking back the House next year. \u201cPeople want to purify,\u201d Rep. Henry Cuellar (D-Texas), one of the Blue Dog\u2019s three co-chairs, said about the Democratic base\u2019s surge to the left. \u201c[But] without Blue Dogs, we don\u2019t have a majority. That\u2019s the bottom line.\u201d With only 18 members, the group has a long way to go. But the Blue Dogs are working closely with House Democrats\u2019 campaign arm on recruitment, a relationship the group says hasn\u2019t been this good since Rahm Emanuel ran the DCCC a decade ago. My story: http://politi.co/2tDrm6L   SANCTIONS PACKAGE HITS HOUSE FLOOR \u2014 A package of sanctions against Russia, Iran and North Korea is set for a House vote Tuesday after lawmakers reached a final deal late Friday night following weeks of negotiations. The legislation, which does not include many of the changes sought by the White House to make it easier for Trump to ease penalties against Russia, is expected to pass by overwhelming majorities in both chambers. The accord \u2013 a remarkable thumb in the eye to Trump from a Republican-led Congress \u2013 gives GOP leaders a major bipartisan achievement to tout heading into August recess. Elana and your Huddle host with more: http://politi.co/2ujnDbH   Even with the sanctions deal, here\u2019s a helpful reality check from Playbook\u2019s Anna Palmer, Jake Sherman and Daniel Lippman: \u201cCONGRESS is likely to leave for August recess without passing a budget, spending bills, an infrastructure package, a bill to lift the debt ceiling and tax reform. 52 DAYS in session between now and the end of the year.\u201d  DEMS PROTEST CUTTING INTEL DEBATE SHORT \u2014 House GOP leaders moved late Sunday to sidestep a lengthy debate over the intelligence community's budget by teeing up the bill for fast-track passage. Republicans\u2019 decision to bring up the intel authorization bill under suspension of the rules, which requires two-thirds support for passage, \u201cprompted howling from Democrats that the GOP was attempting to limit discussion about \u2026 ongoing investigations into election interference by Russia,\u201d Kyle reports. House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi is urging Democrats to vote against the bill. More: http://politi.co/2gWPNWJ  CLYBURN MAKES HIS CASE \u2014 Assistant Democratic Leader James Clyburn turned 77 last week, but he\u2019s showing no signs of slowing down and says folks would do better not to focus too much on his birth date or the age of others in the top tier of leadership. \u201cWe\u2019d do much better up here as a party if people stop worrying how old [Nancy] Pelosi is, and [Steny] Hoyer, and yours truly, and start figuring out how they can be of service in these communities where we\u2019re trying to win elections,\u201d Clyburn told Emma Dumain with the Post and Courier. Much more from Emma on the gaping hole Clyburn will leave in South Carolina politics whenever he retires: http://bit.ly/2tTi7e5   TRUMP JR. AVOIDS PUBLIC HEARING \u2014 Senate Judiciary leaders have agreed to let Donald Trump Jr. and Paul Manafort avoid testifying publicly about a meeting they had with a Russian lawyer last year. The two will now be interviewed behind closed doors and not under oath. Committee leaders did issue a subpoena Friday for Glenn Simpson, founder of the firm that commissioned the dossier on President Trump, after Simpson's lawyer said he is on a lengthy vacation and can\u2019t testify. Austin and Josh Dawsey: http://politi.co/2tCy0tY   ARRIVAL LOUNGE \u2014 Heather Neilson has started as press secretary for Rep. Steve Womack (R-Ark.). She was previously at the Congressional Sportsmen\u2019s Foundation.  TODAY IN CONGRESS \u2014 The House meets at 12 p.m. with votes postponed until 6:30 p.m. Today\u2019s agenda: http://bit.ly/2tD9id1. The Senate gavels in at 4 p.m. with a confirmation vote on David Bernhardt, Trump\u2019s nominee to be Interior deputy secretary, at 5:30 p.m.   AROUND THE HILL \u2014 House Judiciary ranking member John Conyers (D-Mich.) and Reps. Steve Cohen (D-Tenn.) and Mark Sanford (R-S.C.) hold a bipartisan forum on press freedom at 3 p.m. in 2167 Rayburn.   FRIDAY\u2019S TRIVIA WINNER \u2014 Anthony Crisci was the first to guess that Ezra Taft Benson served as Agriculture secretary under President Eisenhower and was also leader of the LDS church from 1985 until his death in 1994.   TODAY\u2019S TRIVIA \u2014 This southern lawmaker, who worked as a land surveyor and fought in the War of 1812 before coming to Congress, has a distinct honor in House history. Who is this person and what is he notable for in the House? The first person to correctly answer gets a mention in the next edition of Huddle. Send answers my way: hcaygle@politico.com   GET HUDDLE emailed to your phone each morning.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson  \u000a                                            By Kel McClanahan 
