aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacqueline Klimas  EXCLUSIVE \u2014 MEMO: DLA LACKS DOCUMENTATION FOR FULL AUDIT, via our colleague Bryan Bender: \u201cThe Defense Logistics Agency will not be able to undergo a complete audit of its financial statements for fiscal 2017, in another setback for Pentagon efforts to finally undergo a scrub of its notoriously messy books.  Story Continued Below  \u201cIn an internal memorandum dated July 27, Lt. Gen. Darrell Williams, the agency's director, says that the outside accounting firm Ernst & Young has concluded after reviewing both the Working Capital Fund and General Fund that it cannot vouch for \u2018beginning balances,\u2019 the agency lacks \u2018accurate supporting documentation\u2019 and it is not possible to reconcile differences \u2018between the sub-ledger and the general ledger\u2026 \u2019  \u201cThe massive $44 billion agency has been leading Pentagon efforts to undergo a full audit, which Congress has been demanding for years. Experts have predicted that its experience will determine whether it is actually possible for DoD as a whole to ever get a clean opinion on its financial statements.\u201d  CONGRESS BACKS BUYING 747s ABANDONED BY RUSSIAN AIRLINE FOR AIR FORCE ONES, reports Bloomberg: \u201cThe Pentagon moved a step closer to buying two deeply discounted 747 jumbo jets from Boeing Co. for the next Air Force One fleet after four congressional panels approved a request to shift $195 million in funding, according to congressional aides.  \u201cThe deal to buy planes to be used by the U.S. president from Boeing has attracted attention because of the reason the company has them sitting in storage and available: They were originally built for Transaero Airlines, once Russia\u2019s second-largest airline. The carrier never signed for the humpbacked passenger jets before it dissolved in late 2015.  \u201cAir Force access to the $195 million was approved by the Senate and House defense appropriations and authorization committees as part of a Defense Department request to \u2018reprogram\u2019 $2.4 billion in previously approved defense funds for the current fiscal year, according to the aides, who asked not to be identified in advance of a formal notification to the Pentagon.\u201d  U.S. MAY EXPAND NORTH KOREA TALKS, reports Reuters: \u201cThe United States could shortly broaden talks on a push for stronger United Nations sanctions on North Korea to include all 15 Security Council members, signaling a likely deal with China on new measures, diplomats said on Thursday.  \u201cSince North Korea's July 4 launch of an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM), the United States has been negotiating with Pyongyang ally China on a draft resolution to impose new sanctions on North Korea, which fired a second ICBM last Friday.  \u201c\u2018We have been working very hard for some time and we certainly hope that this is going to be a consensus resolution,\u2019 China's U.N. Ambassador Liu Jieyi told Reuters on Thursday.\u201d  Meanwhile, Air France expands its no-fly zone after one of its jets flew past the location where an ICBM splashed down 10 minutes later, Reuters adds.  HAPPY FRIDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we\u2019re excited to welcome the newest member of POLITICO\u2019s defense team, Wesley Morgan. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  MD TRIVIA: The following question comes courtesy a long time reader in New Mexico: The following message, sent during the crisis of the Battle of Leyte Gulf caused an angry eruption from the admiral who received it: TURKEY TROTS TO WATER GG WHERE IS RPT WHERE IS TASK FORCE THIRTY FOUR RR THE WORLD WONDERS.  Who was the admiral who sent the message and who was the admiral who received it? For a bonus, why was the recipient enraged?  The first person to email the correct answer to Morning D (ghellman@politico.com) wins a mention in Monday\u2019s edition.  Pro subscribers: Are you getting all the content you want? Make sure your keywords are up to date and customized via your settings page at http://politico.pro/1iDALk9.  WAR REPORT \u2014 MCCAIN BACKS TOP U.S. COMMANDER IN AFGHANISTAN, via your Morning D correspondent: \u201cSenate Armed Services Chairman John McCain [Thursday] voiced his \u2018full confidence\u2019 in Gen. John Nicholson, the top U.S. commander in Afghanistan. McCain's statement follows a report from NBC News that President Donald Trump repeatedly suggested in a White House meeting last month that Nicholson should be fired because he was not winning the war.  \u201cThe Arizona Republican, however, pinned U.S. failures in Afghanistan on \u2018a lack of successful policy and strategic guidance from Washington over many years.\u2019\u201d  \u201c\u2018Our commanders-in-chief, not our commanders in the field, are responsible for this failure,\u2019 McCain said.\u201d  Meanwhile, Trump\u2019s top national-security advisers search for a way to overcome his reluctance to send thousands more troops to Afghanistan, officials say via The Wall Street Journal.  \u2014 NATO SOLDIER KILLED IN LATEST AFGHANISTAN ATTACK, reports The Washington Post: \u201cA NATO soldier was killed and six others, including a translator, were wounded when a suicide bomber attacked their patrol Thursday in eastern Afghanistan, marking the second incident in just as many days when insurgent attacks have killed Western troops.  \u201cThe U.S.-led mission in Afghanistan provided few details about the attack and did not release the nationality of the dead soldier. Navy Capt. Bill Salvin, a spokesman for U.S. forces in Afghanistan, said in an email that the bombing occurred in Kabul province\u2019s Qarabagh district and that the casualties\u2019 \u2018nationalities will be confirmed once we complete our notification procedures.\u2019\u201d  And the Pentagon identifies the two U.S. soldiers killed Wednesday in southern Afghanistan when their convoy was hit by a vehicle packed with explosives, via The Washington Post.  \u2014 U.S. BOMBS SUSPECTED ISIS CHEMICAL WEAPONS FACTORY IN SYRIA, reports The Washington Examiner: \u201cThe U.S. this week bombed a suspected chemical weapons factory in Syria in order to keep increasingly desperate Islamic State fighters from using them on the battlefield, as U.S.-backed Syrian rebels continue to gain ground in the battle to liberate Raqqa.  \u201c\u2018We know that ISIS has proven in Iraq that they are willing to use chemical weapons,\u2019 said Col. Ryan Dillon, a U.S. military spokesman in Baghdad.  \u201c\u2018We have not seen the use of chemical weapons in Syria, but we don't want to wait for them to use it either,\u2019 Dillon said at a Pentagon briefing Thursday.\u201d  Additionally, the U.S. is now supplying Syrian Kurds with armored bulldozers to defeat improvised-explosive devices as they continue the fight against ISIS in Raqqa, the Military Times adds.  And Russia announces the latest cease-fire in Syria, paving the way for the delivery of sorely needed humanitarian relief to rebel-held areas north of the city of Homs, writes the Associated Press.  TOP DOCS \u2014 HUMAN RIGHTS GROUPS PRESS FEDS ON TORTURE ALLEGATIONS, via Greg: \u201cA coalition of human rights organizations is asking the Pentagon, CIA and FBI to make public any reviews of alleged abuses by United Arab Emirates and Yemeni forces against men captured in counterterrorism operations, as well as alleged U.S. involvement in the abuse.  \u201cThe Pentagon began a review at the urging of Senate Armed Services Chairman John McCain (R-Ariz.) and ranking Democrat Jack Reed of Rhode Island. Their request followed a June report by the Associated Press that Emirati forces and their Yemeni partners tortured hundreds of men captured during operations against Al Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula.  \u201cThe AP report also alleged that U.S. military personnel provided questions to Emirati and Yemeni interrogators \u2014 although they were not directly involved in the abuse.  \u201cAccording to the human rights organizations, Defense Secretary Jim Mattis responded to Armed Services Committee in a classified letter. Now, the organizations want the content of the letter made public.\u201d  UAE\u2019s intervention in Yemen has proven a headache for the U.S., and its drive for influence has complicated the two countries\u2019 military relationship, adds The Washington Post.  \u2014 CBO SCORES SENATE NDAA: The Congressional Budget Office has scored domestic and mandatory costs of the Senate version of the National Defense Authorization Act S. 1519 (115).   The full CBO cost estimate is here.  \u2014 TRUMP\u2019S DEFENSE BUDGET COMES UP SHORT, CSBA SAYS, via our colleague Jacqueline Klimas: \u201cThe Trump administration\u2019s fiscal 2018 budget increase for defense is \u2018far short of an historic increase,\u2019 according to a new report released today by the Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments.  \u201cIn fact, the CSBA found the budget request would actually result in an annual 2 percent decrease in defense spending over the next five years after adjusting for inflation and the fact that the administration wants to phase out the use of Overseas Contingency Operations funding as a slush fund.\u201d  MCMASTER GETS NEW COVER, write Bryan and POLITICO\u2019S Josh Dawsey and Nahal Toosi: \u201cNational security adviser H.R. McMaster, who has waged a pitched battle with other senior staff for control over policy and personnel on the National Security Council, is taking advantage of the shield offered by the arrival of his old military colleague John Kelly as White House chief of staff.  \u201cKelly told McMaster this week that he wanted him to remain as national security adviser, said two senior White House aides, and has encouraged him to make any staffing changes he deems necessary. McMaster took that as a green light this week to oust top intelligence aide Ezra Cohen-Watnick \u2014 a Michael Flynn hire who has a warm relationship with Jared Kushner, President Donald Trump\u2019s senior adviser and son-in-law \u2014 after months of trying.\u201d  Kelly quickly moves to impose military discipline in the White House, adds The New York Times.  And Trump\u2019s generals try to save the world, starting with the White House, via James Kitfield in POLITICO Magazine.  INDUSTRY INTEL \u2014 TRUMP LAUNCHES DRONE EXPORT-POLICY REVIEW, reports Defense News: \u201cThe Trump administration has officially launched a review of an Obama-era drone export policy, with expectations in industry that the administration will make it easier to export U.S.-manufactured systems.  \u201cFor months, rumors have floated among both the defense industry and arms control communities that the Trump administration plans to change the 2015 export law that controls what unmanned aerial vehicles can be sold to allies.\u201d  MAKING MOVES \u2014 LT. GEN. HOOPER SET TO HEAD DSCA, reports Defense News: \u201cCharles Hooper, a longtime U.S. Army international affairs officer, has been promoted to rank of lieutenant general and named director of the Defense Security Cooperation Agency.  \u201cHooper was awarded his third star Monday as part of a batch of general officers promoted via voice vote in the Senate. He replaces Vice Adm. Joseph Rixey, who had lead DSCA since September 2013.  \u201cContacted by Defense News, a spokesman for the Pentagon confirmed Hooper\u2019s appointment and said he is expected to be in office come Monday.\u201d  \u2014 SENATE CONFIRMS VA DEPUTY SECRETARY AND NATO AMBASSADOR, reports our colleague Connor O\u2019Brien: \u201cThe Senate [Thursday] confirmed dozens of high-profile nominations, including Thomas Bowman to be the next deputy secretary of Veterans Affairs and former Texas Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison to be the U.S. ambassador to NATO.\u201d  SPEED READ  \u2014 Special counsel Robert Mueller impanels a grand jury in the Russia probe: POLITICO  \u2014 And what it means: POLITICO Magazine  \u2014 Trump rallies his base against the Russia investigation hours after news of the grand jury breaks: POLITICO  \u2014 Former White House National Security Adviser retired Lt. Gen. Michael Flynn files an amended federal financial disclosure report: The Washington Post  \u2014 U.S. approves A-29 Super Tucano sale to Nigeria: Defense News  \u2014 Congress approves the creation of a Global War on Terrorism Memorial in Washington: CBS Pittsburgh  \u2014 A majority of voters in military households think transgender people should be allowed to serve in the military, according to a new survey: The Hill  \u2014 Why has a military spy plane been flying over Seattle for more than a week? The War Zone  \u2014 The Pentagon is suppressing a book on interrogation techniques written by a former chief investigator at the U.S. military prison at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, the author says: Reuters  \u2014 How the Taliban is stymieing Western military efforts in Afghanistan: The Guardian  \u2014 Islamic State genocide against the Yazidis is still happening: Reuters  \u2014 The 2011 U.S. withdrawal from Iraq contains lessons for the president in Afghanistan: WSJ  \u2014 A Jordanian court upholds the life sentence of a Jordanian soldier in the shooting deaths of three U.S. military trainers: Military Times  \u2014 Video offers an inside look at an Islamic State suicide attack: The Washington Post  \u2014 Eyeing Russia, the U.S. military shifts toward more global war games: Reuters  \u2014 Iran\u2019s President Hassan Rouhani begins his second term with signs he\u2019s yielding to hard-liners: NYT  \u2014 Is it too late for the U.S. to arm Ukrainian troops? The Washington Post  \u2014 Syrian civil society tells the U.N. other countries are hijacking peace talks: The Guardian  \u2014 After six years, Al Qaeda frees a South African hostage in Mali: BBC  \u2014 Chinese army reform begins a new phase: The Economist  \u2014 VA Secretary David Shulkin will decide by November on adding Agent Orange-linked conditions: Stars and Stripes  \u2014 The Trump administration bolsters telehealth offerings for veterans: Military Times  \u2014 A bill to help veterans secretly exposed to mustard gas goes to the president\u2019s desk: NPR  \u2014 More than 400 Army units will get software upgrades over the next two years: Breaking Defense  \u2014 How the CIA came to doubt the official story of JFK\u2019s murder: POLITICO Magazine  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
