aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  08/02/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacqueline Klimas  DRIVING THE DAY \u2014 MATTIS AND TILLERSON TESTIFY ON AUMF, via our colleague Jacqueline Klimas: Defense Secretary Jim Mattis and Secretary of State Rex Tillerson are slated to testify in a closed Senate Foreign Relations Committee hearing about the need for a new Authorization for the Use of Military Force.  Story Continued Below  Asked about what Mattis will tell senators, Pentagon spokesman Capt. Jeff Davis said the Defense Department wants, but does not legally need, a new authorization.  \u201cWe don\u2019t require it legally, but it is in our view a signal of our national intent,\u201d he said. \u201cAs much as that\u2019s the case, we certainly support a new one, but we certainly wouldn\u2019t want to have a lapse from the old one before a new one came along.\u201d  WAR REPORT \u2014 ATTACKERS LAUNCH DEADLY STRIKE ON AFGHAN MOSQUE, reports Reuters: \u201cA suicide attack on a Shi'ite mosque in the western Afghan city of Herat killed more than 29 people and wounded more than 64 on Tuesday, officials said.  \u201cMore than 1,700 civilians have been killed in attacks in Afghanistan so far this year, hitting confidence in the Western-backed government of President Ashraf Ghani.  \u201cAbdulhai Walizada, a local police spokesman, said there appeared to be more than one attacker on Tuesday, with witnesses describing a suicide bomber who detonated explosives and at least one other, a gunman who threw grenades at worshippers.\u201d  \u2014 TWO INJURED IN HARD HELO LANDING, reports the Associated Press: \u201cA NATO statement says a U.S. Black Hawk helicopter encountered a mechanical problem that forced a hard landing in eastern Afghanistan. The region is where American troops are supporting Afghan security forces in a campaign against the Islamic State group\u2019s affiliate in Afghanistan.  \u201cThe statement says two soldiers received minor injuries during the hard landing early on Tuesday in the Achin district of eastern Nangarhar province.\u201d  And the USS Nimitz carrier group officially joins the fight against ISIS, launching strikes from the Arabian Gulf, writes Stars and Stripes.  IT\u2019S WEDNESDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we're always on the lookout for tips, pitches and feedback. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  ALSO TODAY \u2014 PENTAGON\u2019S SHANAHAN BRIEFS NEW ACQUISITIONS STRUCTURE: Deputy Defense Secretary Patrick Shanahan hosts a media roundtable to discuss the Pentagon\u2019s report on restructuring its Acquisition, Technology and Logistics Office.  MCCAIN SPEAKS OUT: Senate Armed Services Chairman John McCain (R-Ariz.) is set to give an interview on Phoenix radio station KFYI at 11:35 a.m. Washington time today \u2014 first since he began treatment for brain cancer Monday.  SENATE CONFIRMS NAVY SECRETARY AND PENTAGON ACQUISITION CHIEF, in a bloc of eight nominations, breaking a major defense personnel logjam, reports our colleague Connor O\u2019Brien: \u201cThe Senate [Tuesday night] quickly and quietly confirmed a slew of civilian Defense Department nominees, including President Donald Trump's picks for Navy secretary and Pentagon acquisition chief.  \u201cIn total, eight nominees were confirmed by voice vote. The group includes Richard Spencer to be Navy secretary and Ellen Lord as undersecretary of acquisition, technology and logistics.\u201d  Also confirmed were:  \u2014 Ryan McCarthy to be undersecretary of the Army.  \u2014 Matthew Donovan to be undersecretary of the Air Force.  \u2014 Robert Daigle for director of Cost Assessment and Program Evaluation.  \u2014 Elaine McCusker for principal deputy undersecretary in the comptroller's office.  \u2014 Lucian Niemeyer to be assistant secretary of Defense for energy, installations and environment.  \u2014 And Robert Hood to be assistant secretary of Defense for legislative affairs.  McCain hails the confirmations, but urges the White House to hasten nominations to the Pentagon.  \u201cI hope the White House will expeditiously send the Senate nominations for the many positions that remain unfilled at the Department of Defense,\u201d the senator said in a written statement. \u201cAt a time when the threats to our country continue to grow, neither the White House nor the Senate can afford to delay any further in giving [Defense] Secretary [Jim] Mattis the leadership team he needs to defend our national security.\u201d  \u2014 AND WRAY IS CONFIRMED AS FBI DIRECTOR, reports POLITICO\u2019s Seung Min Kim: \u201cChristopher Wray on Tuesday was overwhelmingly confirmed by the Senate to head the FBI, winning bipartisan support for his commitment to remain fiercely independent from any political pressure.  \u201cThe 92-5 vote installs Wray as FBI director at a consequential time. The bureau was rocked by President Donald Trump's abrupt dismissal of James Comey in May as Comey was overseeing the federal investigation into potential collusion between the Trump campaign and Moscow.\u201d  Meanwhile, Sen. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) says a report that President Donald Trump personally dictated his son\u2019s misleading statement regarding a meeting last summer in New York with a Russian lawyer \u201cbothers me a lot,\u201d via POLITICO\u2019s Louis Nelson.  And White House press secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders says the president \u201cweighed in\u201d on his son\u2019s misleading statement about the meeting in Trump Tower, Louis adds.  SENATE SENDS VA CHOICE FUNDING TO THE PRESIDENT: The Senate Tuesday night passed legislation replenishing the Veterans Choice Program for another six months, sending the measure to the White House, where Trump is expected to sign it.  The $2.1 billion legislation comes just in the nick of time for the program, which subsidizes outside medical care for vets who face long waits or distances to access the VA system. The VA predicts the emergency program will run out of cash later this month, far earlier than anticipated.   The bill also authorizes 28 leases for major VA medical facilities and includes provisions aimed at beefing up VA's recruitment and retention efforts.  ROMANIA PLEDGES $11.3 BILLION IN DEFENSE SPENDING, reports the AP: \u201cRomania\u2019s top defense body has approved a 9.8 billion-euro ($11.3 billion) spending plan for the next decade and has pledged to spend 2 percent of its GDP on defense as NATO requests of its members. The Supreme Defense Council met Tuesday and agreed to spend the money to upgrade the country\u2019s military from 2017-2026.  \u201cLast week Defense Minister Adrian Tutuianu said Romania would buy Patriot missiles worth $3.9 billion from the U.S.\u201d  But issues with capacity and interoperability still plague missile defense systems in Europe, writes Defense News.  Meanwhile, NATO intercepts Russian jets in Estonian airspace, reports Reuters.  And Vice President Mike Pence pledges support for the country of Georgia, his second stop on a European trip backing nations that feel threatened by Russian aggression, adds the AP.  COAST GUARD CHIEF WON\u2019T \u2018BREAK FAITH\u2019 WITH TRANSGENDER PERSONNEL, via your Morning D correspondent: \u201cThe head of the Coast Guard is pledging he \u2018will not break faith\u2019 with transgender personnel, marking the strongest rebuttal yet by a leader of the armed forces to President Donald Trump's declaration that he wants to ban all transgender troops.  \u201cCommandant Paul Zukunft, in remarks to a Washington think tank on Tuesday, cited the story of Coast Guard Lt. Taylor Miller, who was featured last week in The Washington Post, to express his support for transgender members of his service.  \u201c\u2018I told Taylor I will not turn my back,\u2019 Zukunft told the Center for Strategic and International Studies forum. \u2018We have made an investment in you and you have made an investment in the Coast Guard, and I will not break faith.\u2019\u201d  Additionally, 56 retired generals and admirals criticize Trump\u2019s planned ban, writing that it would \u201cdegrade readiness,\u201d adds Jacqueline.  \u2014 AND THE COMMANDANT IS \u2018VERY CONFIDENT\u2019 A NEW ICEBREAKER WON\u2019T BREAK THE BANK, also via Greg: Zukunft added at the CSIS forum he\u2019s \u201cvery confident\u201d American shipyards can build the Coast Guard\u2019s new icebreaker for less than $1 billion.  \u201cI am very confident we will drive the initial acquisition cost of this platform south of a billion dollars,\u201d Zukunft said. \u201cMake no mistake: This will be built in the United States with U.S. parts\u2026 That signal\u2019s been sent loud and clear.\u201d  The bill approved by the House Appropriations Committee would provide the Coast Guard $19 million towards acquisition of the icebreakers in fiscal 2018.  TOP BUDGET DOCS \u2014 CRS BREAKS DOWN DEFENSE APPROPRIATIONS, via Connor: \u201cA new report from the Congressional Research Service analyzes the House-passed fiscal 2018 defense appropriations legislation.  \u201cThe report breaks down the bill's ... level of regular base appropriations, war funding and the special National Defense Restoration Fund, which gives the Pentagon broad authority to spend $28.6 billion to implement a new defense strategy.\u201d  \u2014 TRUMP-ERA DEFENSE SPENDING MORE REAGAN THAN OBAMA, Avascent\u2019s Matt Valone writes in an analysis for The Hill: \u201cThe Trump administration came into office boldly promising a turnaround, if not an outright boom, in military spending.  \u201cDefense hawks remained hopeful for a return to fiscally bold Reagan-era outlays on new hardware and personnel. However, for all its potential, a sea change in Defense Department budgeting looks increasingly unlikely based on fiscal 2017 appropriations and the administration\u2019s fiscal 2018 budget request, which represents a high-water mark for possible defense budget outcomes.\u201d  TILLERSON: \u2018WE DO NOT SEEK REGIME CHANGE\u2019 IN NORTH KOREA, via The Washington Post: \u201cSecretary of State Rex Tillerson called Tuesday for a dialogue with North Korea and acknowledged that U.S. relations with Russia have worsened during the Trump administration.  \u201cDuring wide-ranging comments at the State Department marking six months since his confirmation, Tillerson told reporters that the United States does not aim to depose the government in Pyongyang or use military force.  \u201c\u2018We do not seek a regime change, we do not seek a collapse of the regime, we do not seek an accelerated reunification of the peninsula, we do not seek an excuse to send our military north of the 38th Parallel,\u2019 he said.\u201d  Meanwhile, a commercial jet came dangerously close to where last week\u2019s North Korean ballistic missile test landed, reports ABC News.  And here\u2019s how North Korea continues to get what it wants and needs, via the AP.  VENEZUELA\u2019S PRESIDENT CRACKS DOWN ON OPPOSITION, writes The New York Times: \u201cThe government agents barged into the homes of two prominent former mayors, hauling them off to jail in the dark. They dragged one of them into the street in his blue pajamas as witnesses screamed that he was being kidnapped.  \u201cThe two men, both vocal members of the opposition, had been arrested before. But as the doors shut and the cars sped away early on Tuesday, many Venezuelans worried that it marked the start of a new dictatorship in South America.  \u201cPresident Nicols Maduro and his leftist movement have seized control of the country, not through a coup, but through a contentious power grab that has gutted Venezuela\u2019s democratic institutions and effectively eliminated any official political challenges.\u201d  Maduro says he will soon convene an assembly to rewrite the constitution, via the AP.  And Trump \u201ccondemns\u201d his actions, including the arrests of opposition leaders Leopoldo Lopez and Antonio Ledezma.  \u201cThe United States condemns the actions of the Maduro dictatorship,\u201d Trump said in a statement. \u201cWe reiterate our call for the immediate and unconditional release of all political prisoners.\u201d  INDUSTRY INTEL \u2014 AIR FORCE EYES UNDELIVERED 747\u2019S FOR A FAILED RUSSIAN AIRLINE TO CUT AIR FORCE ONE COSTS, reports Defense One: \u201cPresident Donald Trump said the projected cost of new Air Force One aircraft was too high, so the U.S. Air Force found a way to lower it: by buying a pair of Boeing 747 jetliners abandoned by a bankrupt Russian airline.  \u201cAir Force officials are now finalizing a contract with Boeing for the two planes, according to three defense officials with knowledge of the deal. The Pentagon could publicly announce the deal as soon as this week.\u201d  \u2014 L3 AND AIR TRACTOR JOIN OA-X EXPERIMENT, writes Defense News: \u201cThe Air Force kicked off a demonstration of light attack aircraft on Monday as two companies \u2014 L3 and Air Tractor \u2014 made a last-minute announcement that they would participate in the experiment.  \u201cThe announcement injects a fourth aircraft into the Air Force\u2019s OA-X demo at Holloman Air Force Base, New Mexico. L3 and Air Tractor will put forward the AT-802L Longsword, the companies stated in a press release. The A-29, built by Sierra Nevada Corp. and Embraer, and two Textron aircraft \u2014 the Scorpion jet and Beechcraft AT-6 Wolverine \u2014 will also fly.\u201d  MAKING MOVES \u2014 MILITARY ACADEMIC TAPPED AS TOP NSC MIDEAST ADVISER, report Connor and Andrew Restuccia: \u201cRetired Army Col. Michael Bell has been promoted to the top Middle East adviser on the National Security Council, two White House officials said.  \u201cBell, who was most recently the NSC director of Persian Gulf affairs, is now senior director for the Near East. He succeeds Derek Harvey, who was dismissed last week by national security adviser H.R. McMaster, as the three-star Army general continues to overhaul an NSC he inherited from his predecessor, Michael Flynn.\u201d  SPEED READ  \u2014 U.S. Air Force successfully test launches an ICBM in California: NBC News  \u2014 Tillerson spurns $80 million to counter ISIS, Russian propaganda: POLITICO  \u2014 Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) urges Trump to block China from buying more U.S. companies to increase pressure on Beijing to rein in North Korea: POLITICO Pro  \u2014 How U.S. allies undermine NATO, writes Foundation for Defense of Democracies senior fellow Orde Kittrie: The Wall Street Journal  \u2014 Nuclear weapon contractors reported to repeatedly violate shipping rules for dangerous materials: The Center for Public Integrity  \u2014 The Trump administration sends conflicting signals on Russia sanctions: Reuters  \u2014 Iran calls U.S. sanctions a breach of the nuclear deal: Reuters  \u2014 TIllerson says he and Trump disagree over the Iran deal: Reuters  \u2014 Iran secures a new weapons transport path to Yemen\u2019s Houthi rebels: Reuters  \u2014 Tillerson consolidates his control of the State Department: Reuters  \u2014 While countries impose sanctions, the U.N. pays $18 million to Bashar Assad-linked companies: Bloomberg  \u2014 An Afghan asylum seeker in Germany is accused of killing a U.S. soldier in 2014: Stars and Stripes  \u2014 Top American and Chinese drone companies decide to partner: Quartz  \u2014 The Air Force uses Teslas as \u201cchase cars\u201d to help U-2 spy planes take off: Popular Mechanics  \u2014 The Navy plans to re-equip ships to reload missiles at sea: Military Times  \u2014 A sailor from the destroyer Stethem is missing in the South China Sea, triggering a search-and-rescue operation inside the contested waters: Defense News  \u2014 The USS Antietam\u2019s grounding in January was the captain\u2019s fault: Stars and Stripes  \u2014 The Pentagon faces a lawsuit over possibly revealing millions of service members\u2019 personal info: Military Times  \u2014 What does research indicate about military diversity and unity cohesion? The Washington Post  \u2014 Enrollees in the Veterans Choice Program face a higher risk of opioid abuse: WSJ  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
