aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  08/01/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacqueline Klimas  DRIVING THE DAY \u2014 PENTAGON SET TO UNVEIL NEW ACQUISITION STRUCTURE, reports Defense News: \u201cThe Pentagon is scheduled to deliver its new acquisition structure to Congress on Tuesday, a major step toward redesigning how the building researches and procures equipment.  Story Continued Below  \u201cThe 2017 National Defense Authorization Act instructed the Pentagon to devolve the undersecretary of acquisition, technology and logistics, or AT&L, into two separate jobs: undersecretary for acquisition and sustainment, or A&S; and a new undersecretary for research and engineering, or R&E, essentially a chief technology officer. Those changes are expected to be in place by Feb. 1, 2018.  \u201cCongress purposefully allowed time for the Department of Defense to come up with its own road map on how the split should occur, which the department is supposed to deliver to Capitol Hill on Aug 1.\u201d  PENTAGON AND STATE DEVELOP PLANS TO ARM UKRAINE, reports The Wall Street Journal: \u201cThe U.S. Pentagon and State Department have devised plans to supply Ukraine with antitank missiles and other weaponry and are seeking White House approval, U.S. officials said, as Kiev battles Russia-backed separatists and ties between Moscow and Washington fray.  \u201cAmerican military officials and diplomats say the arms, which they characterized as defensive, are meant to deter aggressive actions by Moscow, which the U.S. and others say has provided tanks and other sophisticated armaments as well as military advisers to rebels fighting the Kiev government.\u201d  And Senate Armed Services Chairman John McCain (R-Ariz.) tweets: \u201cIt\u2019s about time.\u201d  Meanwhile, Vice President Mike Pence reaffirms NATO\u2019s principle of collective defense following a meeting with the presidents of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, via The Associated Press.  And Russia urges the U.S. to show the \u201cpolitical will\u201d to repair ties between the two countries after slashing the number of U.S. diplomatic personnel allowed in Russia, the AP adds.  \u2014 RUSSIAN PLANS FOR MILITARY DRILLS NEAR NATO BORDER RAISE FEARS, writes The New York Times: \u201cRussia is preparing to send as many as 100,000 troops to the eastern edge of NATO territory at the end of the summer, one of the biggest steps yet in the military buildup undertaken by President Vladimir V. Putin and an exercise in intimidation that recalls the most ominous days of the Cold War.  \u201cThe troops are conducting military maneuvers known as Zapad, Russian for \u2018west,\u2019 in Belarus, the Baltic Sea, western Russia and the Russian enclave of Kaliningrad. The drills will feature a reconstituted armored force named for a storied Soviet military unit, the First Guards Tank Army. Its establishment represents the first time since the collapse of the Soviet Union that so much offensive power has been concentrated in a single command.\u201d  HAPPY TUESDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we're always on the lookout for tips, pitches and feedback. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  POLITICO Pro Policy Summit, Sept. 14: An all-day summit featuring deep-dive conversations and incisive interviews that explore policy trends inside and outside government. Space is limited to current Pro customers at the director level or above. Learn More.  HAPPENING TODAY \u2014 COAST GUARD COMMANDANT TALKS PRIORITIES AT CSIS: Coast guard Commandant Adm. Paul Zukunft discusses his priorities with the Center for Strategic and International Studies.  SELVA CONFIRMED FOR SECOND JOINT CHIEFS TERM: The Senate Monday evening confirmed Air Force Gen. Paul Selva for a second term as Joint Chiefs vice chairman. Altogether, the Senate briskly confirmed dozens of military nominations, including Defense Intelligence Agency Director Lt. Gen. Vincent Stewart to be deputy commander of U.S. Cyber Command.   MORE PENTAGON NOMINEES ON STANDBY: With no votes on health care and the pending National Defense Authorization Act likely before the Senate kicks off its August recess, Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) plans to hold confirmation votes on more Trump nominees this week. While no votes have been announced on defense picks yet, 12 civilian nominees are pending in the Senate, including Navy secretary nominee Richard Spencer and Pentagon acquisition chief pick Ellen Lord.  WAR REPORT \u2014 MCCAIN VOWS TO PRODUCE HIS OWN AFGHANISTAN STRATEGY, writes our colleague Connor O\u2019Brien: \u201cSenate Armed Services Chairman John McCain today vowed to write his own Afghanistan strategy, slamming the Trump administration for not producing one.  \u201cThe Arizona Republican said he would offer his own strategy as an amendment to annual defense policy legislation when the Senate takes up the bill in September ...  \u201c\u2018More than six months after President Trump's inauguration, there still is no strategy for success in Afghanistan,\u2019 McCain said in a statement. \u2018Eight years of a \u2018don\u2019t lose\u2019 strategy has cost us lives and treasure in Afghanistan. Our troops deserve better.\u2019\u201d  Meanwhile, Trump\u2019s plans for Afghanistan are missing as pressure builds in America\u2019s longest war, writes U.S. New & World Report.  And all four Islamic State attackers are killed during their attempt to storm the Iraqi Embassy in Kabul, adds the AP.  \u2014 TOP DOC \u2014 AFGHAN FORCES SUFFER CASUALTIES AT CONSISTENT RATE, via your Morning D correspondent: Afghan National Security forces lost 2,531 forces from the beginning of 2017 until May 8, according to the special inspector general for Afghanistan reconstruction\u2019s newest quarterly report.  Additionally, the forces reported 4,238 were wounded in action. Casualties have increased since Afghan forces took over operational control of security missions in 2015, the report notes.  \u2014 AL-SHABAB COMMANDER REPORTEDLY KILLED IN U.S. AIRSTRIKE IN SOMALIA, reports the AP: \u201cThe U.S. military said Monday it carried out a drone strike in Somalia that killed a member of the al-Shabab extremist group, while Somalia's government said it believes the strike killed a high-level al-Shabab commander responsible for several deadly bombings in the capital.  \u201cA U.S. Africa Command statement said the airstrike occurred Saturday near Tortoroow, an al-Shabab stronghold in Lower Shabelle region in southern Somalia.\u201d  FOR YOUR RADAR \u2014 U.S. TO TEST AN ICBM WEDNESDAY, reports our colleague Jacqueline Klimas: \u201cThe U.S. military will test launch an intercontinental ballistic missile Wednesday amid rising tensions on the Korean Peninsula.  \u201cCapt. Michele Rollins, a spokeswoman for Air Force Global Strike Command, said the test launch from Vandenberg Air Force Base in California will ensure the nation\u2019s stockpile of ICBMs is reliable. While the test launch will be unarmed, ICBMs can deliver a number of different kinds of weapons, primarily nuclear. Four test launches are done each fiscal year. The most recent was on May 3.\u201d  Meanwhile, analysts doubt North Korea\u2019s ICBM re-entry capability, writes the AP.  Still, the missile may be capable of hitting most of the U.S., officials say via Reuters.  CHINA OPENS FIRST OVERSEAS BASE IN DJIBOUTI, reports Reuters: \u201cChina formally opened its first overseas military base on Tuesday with a flag raising ceremony in Djibouti in the Horn of Africa, the same day as the People's Liberation Army marks its 90th birthday, state media said.  \u201cDjibouti's position on the northwestern edge of the Indian Ocean has fueled worry in India that it would become another of China's \u2018string of pearls\u2019 military alliances and assets ringing India, including Bangladesh, Myanmar and Sri Lanka.\u201d  INDUSTRY INTEL \u2014 HASC LEADERS BLAST SPACE ACQUISITION DELAYS, via your Morning D correspondent: House Armed Services Strategic Forces Subcommittee leaders Reps. Mike Rogers (R-Ala.) and Jim Cooper (D-Tenn.) are blasting delays in programs to acquire the new GPS Operational Control System and the Family of Advanced Beyond Line of Sight Terminals, both under development by Raytheon.   The OCX program has reportedly racked up an additional $630 million in costs, while the FAB-T program is behind schedule by a year, the congressmen said in a statement.  \u201cOur adversaries have already reorganized their space programs and are reaping the benefits,\u201d the congressmen said. \u201cThose who continue to oppose reform need to explain to the warfighter, the American people, and their elected representatives how the status quo is acceptable.\u201d  Bloomberg first reported the OCX program\u2019s delays here.  MAKING MOVES \u2014 TRUMP TAPS TWO FOR PENTAGON AND VA POSTS: The president has picked John Henderson as assistant secretary of the Air Force for installations, the environment and energy. He had been commander of the Omaha district in the Army Corps of Engineers and has more than 23 years of experience as an Army engineer officer.  Additionally, Trump announced his intention to nominate Melissa Sue Glynn as assistant secretary of Veterans Affairs for enterprise integration. She had recently led Alvarez and Marsal\u2019s public sector practice focused on improving the delivery of government programs. Earlier, she was a principal with PricewaterhouseCoopers, responsible for the firm\u2019s work with the VA.  \u2014 KELLY ANNOUNCES DHS MOVES IN FAREWELL EMAIL, via POLITICO\u2019s Ted Hesson: \u201cFormer Homeland Security Secretary John Kelly announced several department personnel moves in a farewell email sent to staff [Monday] morning. Kelly was sworn in as White House chief of staff [Monday], and the personnel changes reflect a shift in responsibilities after his departure. Deputy Secretary Elaine Duke will become acting secretary, a move DHS acknowledged July 28.\u201d  And he seizes control of a chaotic West Wing, dismissing embattled White Houe Communications Director Anthony Scaramucci, write POLITICO\u2019s Andrew Restuccia, Josh Dawsey, Tara Palmeri and Darren Samus   SURGEON GENERAL JOINS OPTUM: Retired Army Lt. Gen. Patty Horoho joined Optum to align the company\u2019s health care technology, operations and data analytics capabilities. She was the first woman and the first nurse to serve as Army surgeon general and also commanded the U.S. Army Medical Command.  SPEED READ  \u2014 Trump dictated his son\u2019s misleading statement about his meeting with a Russian lawyer during the 2016 presidential campaign: The Washington Post  \u2014 The U.S. imposes sanctions against Venezuelan President Nicols Maduro, saying his government abused human rights and organized an illegitimate vote: WSJ  \u2014 Inside the dismantling of the State Department: Foreign Policy  \u2014 Defense Secretary Jim Mattis learns how to play ball on Capitol Hill: CNN  \u2014 The White House reaches out to the Pentagon to begin drafting guidance to ban transgender troops from serving in the military: The Hill  \u2014 A top Iraqi general thinks wresting Tal Afar back from ISIS will be easy: Reuters  \u2014 Revealing Mosu \u2014 the last Islamic State stronghold: NYT  \u2014 Iraq and Afghanistan war veterans have better life outcomes than non-veterans: Task & Purpose  \u2014 Why the Middle East hated Barack Obama but loves Donald Trump: POLITICO Magazine  \u2014 North Korea promises retaliation against potential added sanctions: Stars and Stripes  \u2014 Trump awards a Vietnam veteran the Medal of Honor: The Washington Post  \u2014 The Air Force may extend the time frame for its \u201cup-or-out\u201d policy: Stars and Stripes  \u2014 Immigrant recruits are stuck in uncertainty: NBC  \u2014 The Pentagon moves to shore up a program proven susceptible to fraud: Federal News Radio  \u2014 In a Kentucky town that has lost several troops, the frequency of death in combat doesn\u2019t make it any easier: Stars and Stripes  \u2014 Algeria kills six in an Islamic State cell: Reuters  \u2014 A Kenyan election official is murdered, raising concerns about next week\u2019s vote: BBC  \u2014 Watch the new aircraft carrier USS Gerald R. Ford receive its first flight: Business Insider  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
