aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  07/31/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacqueline Klimas  WHITE HOUSE EYES AFGHANISTAN WITHDRAWAL, writes The Wall Street Journal: \u201cPresident Donald Trump\u2019s reservations about sending more troops to Afghanistan have triggered a new exploration of an option long considered unlikely: withdrawal.  Story Continued Below  \u201cUnable to agree on a plan to send up to 3,900 more American forces to help turn back Taliban advances in Afghanistan, the White House is taking a new look at what would happen if the U.S. decided to scale back its military presence instead, according to current and former Trump administration officials.  \u201c\u2018It\u2019s a macro question as to whether the U.S., this administration, and this president are committed to staying,\u2019 one senior administration official said. \u2018It doesn\u2019t work unless we are there for a long time, and if we don\u2019t have the appetite to be there a long time, we should just leave. It\u2019s an unanswered question.\u2019\u201d  A car bomb targets the Iraqi Embassy in central Kabul on Monday, followed by gunfire, Afghan police report, via the Associated Press  REP. BARBARA LEE: AN ARMY OF ONE, writes POLITICO\u2019s Austin Wright: \u201cIt\u2019s a recent Wednesday afternoon, and Barbara Lee\u2019s communications director is trying to find her. She\u2019s scheduled to give a speech in nine minutes, and she hasn\u2019t read it yet.  \u201cThe anti-war congresswoman \u2014 from an ultra-liberal congressional district that includes Berkeley, California \u2014 has somehow managed to spark an uprising, joined by rank-and-file Republicans, against House Speaker Paul Ryan. Their demand: Repeal the 2001 war authorization against Al Qaeda and begin debating a new authorization better suited for the wars of today. This strange alliance is all the more remarkable because Lee, one of the leftmost denizens of Capitol Hill, was famously the only member of Congress to vote against the original authorization of force, a vote held just three days after the 9/11 terrorist attacks.\u201d  COMING THIS WEEK \u2014 MATTIS AND TILLERSON BRIEF SENATE PANEL ON AUMF: Defense Secretary Jim Mattis and Secretary of State Rex Tillerson are slated to testify before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee Wednesday in a closed hearing on the administration\u2019s views on an AUMF.  IT\u2019S MONDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we're always on the lookout for tips, pitches and feedback. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  MD TRIVIA: Mark Kustra was the first to correctly answer that Iran has recorded the most air-to-air combat victories since 1975 using the F-14 Tomcat, compiling a 130-4-4 record during the Iran-Iraq War.  Tune in Friday for this week\u2019s question.  HAPPENING TODAY \u2014 TRUMP TO AWARD MEDAL OF HONOR TO VIETNAM VET, writes The Detroit News: Pfc. James McCloughan "is credited with saving the lives of at least 10 men in his company, despite being wounded on three occasions.  \u201cPresident Donald Trump will award McCloughan, now 71, the Medal of Honor at the White House on Monday for \u2018conspicuous gallantry,\u2019 recognizing his \u2018distinguished actions\u2019 during the battle 48 years ago in which an estimated 2,000 enemy forces vastly outnumbered the Americans.\u201d  \u2014 BROOKINGS MULLS \u2018NATO AT A CROSSROADS:\u2019 The Brookings Institution hosts a discussion about \u201cNATO at a crossroads: Next steps for the trans-Atlantic alliance.\u201d  U.S. THAAD HITS TEST TARGET MISSILE, reports Reuters: \u201cThe United States said it shot down a medium-range target ballistic missile in its latest test of the country's THAAD missile defense program, which is designed to protect the country against potential threats from countries such as North Korea and Iran.  \u201cThe test, conducted over the Pacific Ocean, comes amid heightened tensions with North Korea, which on Saturday said it had conducted its own successful test of a long-range intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM) that proved it has the capacity to strike American's mainland. The latest U.S. test of the Terminal High Altitude Area Defense (THAAD) system was planned well before North Korea's latest missile launch, but it comes at a time of rising tension with the country since Pyongyang launched its first-ever test of an ICBM on July 4.\u201d  And the Air Force flies B-1B bombers over the Korean Peninsula, the WSJ adds.  Meanwhile, the U.S. opens its new base in South Korea, moving its headquarters outside of North Korean artillery range, reports The Washington Post.  \u2014 NORTH KOREA TESTS MISSILE CAPABLE OF HITTING HOMELAND, reports our colleague Jacqueline Klimas: \u201cNorth Korea on Friday launched another ballistic missile that experts estimate had the reach to hit practically all of the major cities on the U.S. mainland.  \u201cPentagon spokesman Capt. Jeff Davis said the Defense Department detected the intercontinental ballistic missile launch at 10:41 a.m. Washington time. Launched from Mupyong-ni, he said, the missile traveled about 1,000 kilometers, or more than 600 miles, before coming down in the Sea of Japan.  \u201cFollowing the launch, Joint Chiefs Chairman Gen. Joe Dunford and U.S. Pacific Command chief Adm. Harry Harris called the South Korean Joint Chiefs Chairman Gen. Lee Sun Jin to discuss \u2018military response options,\u2019 Dunford spokesman Capt. Greg Hicks said.\u201d  South Korea announces it will build more powerful missiles to counter the North, via The New York Times.  Trump slams China, tweeting \u201cthey do NOTHING for us with North Korea,\u201d adds POLITICO\u2019s Brent Griffiths.  And China hits back, via Reuters.  TRUMP INTENDS TO SIGN RUSSIA SANCTIONS BILL, reports POLITICO\u2019s Madeline Conway: \u201cPresident Donald Trump intends to sign legislation that places new sanctions on Russia and empowers Congress to block him from scaling back the penalties on Moscow in the future, the White House press secretary's office said Friday.  \u201cWhite House officials had earlier left open the possibility Trump would veto the bill, though it was passed with veto-proof majorities in the House and Senate.\u201d  And Russian President Vladimir Putin orders U.S. diplomatic personnel cut by 755, escalating the sanctions fight, writes the NYT.  \u2014 U.S. ARMY EUROPE COMMANDER PUSHES A \u2018MILITARY SCHENGEN ZONE,\u2019 via Defense News: \u201cAs the U.S. Army Europe commander prepares to exit the military stage in September, he\u2019s pushing for better ways for militaries to move freely around the European theater. A military Schengen zone, he thinks, might be the best way to achieve that goal.  \u201cIn addition to improving the speed at which countries recognize an emerging crisis and make decisions on how to respond, the \u2018speed of assembly,\u2019 is also critical to get capability in place to prevent a crisis or react to a crisis, Lt. Gen. Ben Hodges said at the U.S. Army-led Saber Guardian exercise in Romania this month...  \u201c\u2018More than anything we need a military Schengen zone, something that would allow a military convoy to move across Europe as fast as a migrant is able to move across Europe,\u2019 Hodges said. \u2018Right now that is not the case.\u2019\u201d  \u2014 HOW ESTONIA BECAME A TOP U.S. DESTINATION, via our colleague Andrew Hanna: \u201cEstonia, a tiny Baltic nation dwarfed by neighboring Russia, isn\u2019t a premier American tourist destination. But when Vice President Mike Pence arrives there on Sunday he\u2019ll be just the latest in a parade of senior Washington officials to visit in recent months.  \u201cSen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) led a congressional delegation to Estonia in December and so did Sen. Lamar Alexander (R-Tenn.) in June. America\u2019s top NATO general dropped by in March, followed soon after by House Speaker Paul Ryan in April. President Barack Obama himself gave a September 2014 address in the Estonian capital of Tallinn.  \u201cWhy all the fuss over a nation of just 1.3 million with a landmass roughly half the size of Maine? The short answer is Russian President Vladimir Putin.\u201d  In Estonia, Vice President Mike Pence assures NATO's Baltic states: "We will 'hold Russia accountable for its actions,'" via POLITICO's Louis Nelson.  RAND PAUL PRESSES PAUSE ON SENATE NDAA, reports our colleague Connor O\u2019Brien: \u201cSen. Rand Paul blocked attempts to fast-track debate on the fiscal 2018 National Defense Authorization Act in an attempt to secure votes on amendments to bar indefinite detention and repeal the 2002 Iraq War authorization.  \u201cThe move early [Friday] morning drew an indirect rebuke from Senate Armed Services Chairman John McCain (R-Ariz.), who has been diagnosed with cancer and sought quick floor consideration today before he begins treatment\u2026  \u201cIn the wake of the late [Friday-] night dust-up, it's unclear when \u2014 or if \u2014 the Senate will consider the NDAA any time soon. Both McConnell and Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer support quick consideration of the defense bill to accommodate McCain's schedule.\u201d  The path forward on the must-pass NDAA is now up in the air as McCain begins radiation and chemotherapy today in Arizona. The Arizona Republican will maintain a work schedule during treatment and plans to return to Washington following the August recess, his office said.  TOP DOC \u2014 CBO SCORES MANDATORY COSTS OF SENATE NDAA, also via Connor: \u201cThe Senate Armed Services version of the fiscal 2018 National Defense Authorization Act ... would increase mandatory spending $621 million over the next decade, according to a CBO analysis. In a letter to Armed Services Chairman John McCain, CBO Director Keith Hall said a full cost estimate for the legislation would be released \u2018shortly.\u2019\u201d  TRUMP NAMES DHS SECRETARY JOHN KELLY NEW WHITE HOUSE CHIEF OF STAFF, write POLITICO\u2019s Bryan Bender, Ted Hesson and Stephanie Beasley: \u201cWhen President Donald Trump delivered the commencement address at the Coast Guard Academy in May, he was presented with a ceremonial sword \u2014 to which Homeland Security Secretary John Kelly, standing nearby, quipped, \u2018Use that on the press, sir.\u2019  \u201cNo one thought the retired Marine general, known for a single-minded focus on getting results, was being serious. But the swipe at the news media on which the president so often trains his ire showed how much Kelly has become a kindred spirit to his boss, who announced Friday he was tapping the DHS secretary for White House chief of staff.\u201d  His first task? Stabilize the West Wing, our colleagues Andrew Restuccia, Bryan, and Josh Dawsey also write.  To help out, he\u2019ll bring his DHS chief of staff, Kirstjen Nielsen, with him to the White House, Andrew adds.  WAR REPORT \u2014 U.S. HELICOPTER FIRES WARNING SHOTS AT IRANIAN SHIPS, reports the WSJ: \u201cThe U.S. and Iran on Saturday reported their second confrontation this week in the waters off the Persian Gulf, as political tensions between the longtime rivals flare. The U.S. Navy said several vessels operated by Iran\u2019s powerful Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps in the Gulf approached American ships at high speed on Friday.  \u201cAfter failing to contact the ships by radio, a Navy helicopter fired warning flares at a safe distance, according to the U.S. Naval Forces Central Command. The Iranian ships subsequently stopped moving toward U.S. ships, it said, describing the interaction as \u2018safe and professional.\u2019\u201d  \u2014 RUSSIA SHOWCASES MILITARY MIGHT OFF THE SYRIAN COAST, writes the NYT: \u201cRussia\u2019s global military ambition was on display Sunday when the country celebrated Navy Day with large military parades not only in St. Petersburg, but also on the banks of Syria.  \u201cThe parades of ships, submarines and aircraft were held at Russian naval bases in Sevastopol, which was annexed by Russia from Ukraine in 2014, and at Tartus in Syria, where Russia is expanding its military presence. The main parade took place in St. Petersburg, Russia\u2019s second-largest city and home of the navy\u2019s headquarters.\u201d  \u2014 IRAQI SECURITY FORCES REPORTEDLY FOIL ISIS ATTACK, reports the AP: \u201cIraqi intelligence officials said Sunday they foiled an attempt by the Islamic State group to attack revered Shiite shrines and the sect\u2019s spiritual leader. The IS plan was to launch a series of suicide attacks in Karbala and Najaf that house the shrines as well as the home of Grand Ayatollah Ali al-Sistani, two officers told The Associated Press.\u201d  INDUSTRY INTEL \u2014 LOCKHEED BAGS $3.69 BILLION F-35 CONTRACT, reports Breaking Defense: \u201cAfter the markets closed on a sleepy and rainy summer Friday afternoon, White House Chief of Staff Reince Priebus was ousted and DHS Secretary John Kelly named to take his place, and, oh, by the way, a $3.69 billion contract was awarded Lockheed Martin for 50 foreign F-35s and work on the Lot 11 LRIP. What\u2019s in play here?  \u201cMost of the money, $2.2 billion, goes to buy one British F-35B, one Italian F-35A, eight Australian F-35As, eight Dutch F-35As, four Turkish F-35As, six Norwegian F-35As aircraft, and 22 F-35As for Foreign Military Sales customers.\u201d  SPEED READ  \u2014 A foiled terrorist plot in Australia prompts heightened security measures: NYT  \u2014 McCain almost once left the GOP. What about Now?: POLITICO Magazine  \u2014 The Congressional Research Service tells Congress it has the authority to overturn any transgender military ban: POLITICO Pro  \u2014 The House approves the intelligence policy bill on its second attempt: POLITICO Pro  \u2014 The House passes legislation to replenish the Veterans Choice Program for another six months: POLITICO Pro  \u2014 Iran builds an armed network of young men across the Middle East, outstripping the U.S.: BuzzFeed  \u2014 Hezbollah takes journalists in Lebanon on a tour to prove Trump wrong: The Washington Post  \u2014 Ousted by his country\u2019s high court, Pakistani former Prime Minister Mian Nawaz Sharif paves the way for his brother to replace him in national elections: The Washington Post  \u2014 Confronting a pilot shortage, the Air Force tests out new career options: Military.com  \u2014 Ahead of Vice President Mike Pence\u2019s visit, Georgia starts military exercises with the U.S. and others: Reuters  \u2014 Chinese President Xi Jinping boasts of hard power with a massive military parade: NYT  \u2014 Four Arab countries say they\u2019re ready for a dialogue with Qatar to resolve their diplomatic row: Reuters  \u2014 Turkey detains more than 1,000 for suspected links to militant groups or last year's failed coup attempt: Reuters  \u2014 Nigeria plans to step up its anti-Boko Haram efforts: Reuters  \u2014 An al-Shabab ambush kills two dozen troops in Somalia: Reuters  \u2014 The Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System on the USS Gerald Ford, dissed by Trump, works in its first tests: Military Times  \u2014 Unexploded ordnance from the world wars complicates an underwater power channel in Europe: The Guardian  \u2014 Rep. Seth Moulton (D-Mass.) stirs presidential speculation: POLITICO Magazine  \u2014 Before the fall: a three-part examination of Michael Flynn\u2019s early years and military career: The Providence Journal  \u2014 An infantry without humans might not be far off: Military Times  \u2014 The Navy works on a new tool to identify iron sulfide in concrete: Military Times  \u2014 The new Navy destroyer\u2019s namesake has a complicated combat death story: Jalopnik  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                 