aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacqueline Klimas  TOP NEWS \u2014 HOUSE APPROVES DEFENSE APPROPRIATIONS BILL, our colleague Connor O\u2019Brien reports: \u201cThe House passed annual defense spending legislation Thursday after disposing of dozens of amendments.  Story Continued Below  \u201cThe vote was 235-192. Only five Democrats supported the measure, and only five Republicans broke with their party to oppose it. The defense appropriations were included in a broader national security-themed funding package, which also includes annual Energy, Legislative Branch and Military Construction and Veterans Affairs spending measures.  \u201cThe House bill now goes to the Senate, which has not yet taken up a defense appropriations bill.\u201d  The spending package also contains funding for President Donald Trump\u2019s border wall, POLITICO\u2019s Sarah Ferris adds.  NDAA ON HOLD IN THE SENATE AFTER HEALTH-CARE DEFEAT: Debate on the fiscal 2018 National Defense Authorization Act S. 1519 (115) is hold for now in the Senate, despite the efforts of Senate Armed Services Chairman John McCain (R-Ariz.) and leaders of both parties to consider it by the end of the week.  After the Senate narrowly defeated a so-called skinny repeal of Obamacare, with McCain casting the dramatic deciding "no" vote, Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) moved to open debate on the defense policy bill beginning at 10 a.m. today. But Sen. Rand Paul (R-Ky.) objected.  Instead, the Senate recessed until Monday afternoon. There's no timeline for the NDAA. But McConnell said Thursday he'd move to consider it once the health-care debate ended and urged senators to accommodate McCain, who has been diagnosed with brain cancer, "and give him an opportunity to finish that bill while he is here."  Earlier, on the Senate floor, McCain pressed his colleagues to take "a few hours" out to debate the massive defense policy bill today. And Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) added Democrats wanted to "move expeditiously" on the bill and that SASC ranking Democrat Jack Reed of Rhode Island had been working with McCain on a slate of amendments.   More on McCain\u2019s effort here.  Amendments roll in: At Morning D's last count, 131 amendments have been filed to the Senate NDAA.  The NDAA holding pattern follows McCain\u2019s dramatic \u201cno\u201d vote on the \u201cskinny repeal,\u201d write POLITICO\u2019s John Bresnahan, Burgess Everett, Jennifer Haberkorn and Seung Min Kim.  A behind-the-scenes POLITICO account of McCain's maneuverings is here. And his statement on it all is here.  PENTAGON BRACES FOR WHITE HOUSE TRANSGENDER GUIDANCE, writes our colleague Jacqueline Klimas: \u201cThe Pentagon is bracing for White House guidance on enforcing President Donald Trump's decision to ban transgender people from the armed forces \u2014 orders that military and legal experts say could kick out thousands of troops who just a year ago were told they could serve openly.  \u201cThe White House indicated Thursday that the president intends to carry out the decision he announced in a series of tweets that, taken at face value, would mean drumming out all service members who identify as transgender.  \u201c\u2018The White House will work with the Department of Defense and all of the relevant parties to make sure that we fully implement this policy moving forward and do so in a lawful manner,\u2019 press secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders told reporters.  \u201c\u2018They are going to have to work out the details,\u2019 she added.\u201d  A candidate for a top Homeland Security post withdraws because of objections to Trump\u2019s decision to ban transgender people from the military, POLITICO\u2019s Andrew Restuccia and Kyle Cheney add.  And a Coast Guardsman in transition fears the ban\u2019s effects, writes The Washington Post.  HAPPY FRIDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we're always on the lookout for tips, pitches and feedback. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  MORNING D TRIVIA: This week\u2019s question comes from last week\u2019s winner, Richard Streeter. Since 1975, what country has recorded the most air-to-air combat victories, and which airplane was responsible for most of those victories?  The first person to email the correct answer to Morning D (ghellman@politico.com) wins a mention in Monday\u2019s edition.  BREAKING OVERNIGHT \u2014 COURT ORDERS REMOVAL OF PAKISTAN\u2019S PRIME MINISTER, reports The New York Times: \u201cPakistan\u2019s Supreme Court on Friday ordered the removal of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif from office over accusations of corruption, delivering a historic ruling that is likely to shift the country\u2019s tumultuous political balance and deal a serious blow to the legacy of a man who helped define the past generation of Pakistani politics.  \u201cThe removal of Mr. Sharif, who was serving his third term in office, comes roughly a year before his term was to end.  \u201cThe verdict means the governing political party, the Pakistan Muslim League-Nawaz, must choose an interim prime minister to replace Mr. Sharif until the next general election, which is scheduled for mid-2018.\u201d  JAPAN\u2019S DEFENSE MINISTER RESIGNS, reports The Wall Street Journal: \u201cJapanese Defense Minister Tomomi Inada, a protg of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe who was once seen as having a chance to become the nation\u2019s first female prime minister, announced her resignation Friday over a dispute involving peacekeeping operations in South Sudan.  \u201cThe issues surrounding Ms. Inada have contributed to a sharp fall in support for Mr. Abe\u2019s cabinet, which was above 50% earlier this year but has fallen below 30% in some recent polls.  "Mr. Abe said he took responsibility for naming Ms. Inada to the job a year ago. \u2018I would like to apologize for the way this has turned out,\u2019 he told reporters at his office.  \u201cOpposition lawmakers accused Ms. Inada of trying to cover up an internal document that suggested Japanese peacekeeping forces in South Sudan had engaged in combat, something that is barred under Japanese laws reflecting the nation\u2019s post-World War II pacifism. Ms. Inada denied any coverup but acknowledged on Friday that she had handled the matter poorly.\u201d  Meanwhile, the head of Japan\u2019s main opposition party quits for failing to boost its election prospects despite Abe\u2019s unpopularity, the WSJ adds.  HAPPENING TODAY \u2014 ROUND TWO ON INTEL AND VETS BILLS: The House votes for the second time this week on annual intelligence policy legislation and a patch to keep the emergency Veterans Choice Program funded for the next six months. Both bills failed on the House floor Monday after Democrats opposed Republican leaders bringing up the legislation under expedited procedures that shorten debate and don't allow amendments.  \u2014 JAPAN-U.S. MILITARY STATESMEN FORUM WRAPS UP: The Japan-U.S. Military Statesman Forum, the only non-governmental military-to-military dialogue, is set to wrap up today after a week of discussions.  \u2014 PACOM CHIEF: MARAWI \u2018A WAKE-UP CALL,\u2019 via your Morning D correspondent: U.S. Pacific Command chief Adm. Harry Harris Thursday urged greater multilateral cooperation throughout the Asia-Pacific to combat the spread of ISIS.  The Philippines is set to receive two Cessna aircraft purchased by the Pentagon and modified for surveillance to assist in the battle against ISIS, he noted.  \u201cMarawi should be a wake-up call and a rallying cry for every nation in the Indo-Asian Pacific region,\u201d Harris said at the Japan-U.S. Military Statesmen Forum. \u201cOnly through multilateral cooperation can we eradicate ISIS ... before they spread.\u201d  \u2018TIME IS RUNNING OUT\u2019 ON NORTH KOREA, MILLEY SAYS, via Reuters: \u201c U.S. General Mark Milley, the chief of staff of the Army, said on Thursday that North Korea's July 4 test of an intercontinental ballistic missile showed its capabilities were advancing significantly and faster than many had expected.  \u201cMilley, in remarks to the National Press Club in Washington, said there was still time for a non-military solution to the crisis caused by North Korea's nuclear and missile programs, but cautioned that \u2018time is running out.\u2019  \u201c\u2018North Korea is extremely dangerous and more dangerous as the weeks go by,\u2019 he said.  \u201cU.S. media reported this week that the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA), the Pentagon spy agency, had assessed that North Korea would be able to field a nuclear-capable ICBM by next year, earlier than previously thought.\u201d  WAR REPORT \u2014 RUSSIA SIGNS HALF-CENTURY SYRIA AIR BASE DEAL, reports Reuters: \u201cPresident Vladimir Putin has signed a law ratifying a deal with the Syrian government allowing Russia to keep its air base in Syria for almost half a century, official documents show.  \u201cThe original deal, signed in Damascus in January, sets out the terms under which Russia can use its Hmeymim air base in Latakia Province which it has used to carry out air strikes against forces opposing President Bashar al-Assad. Putin approved the agreement on Wednesday, after the two chambers of the Russian parliament backed it earlier this month, according to the government's official information portal.  \u201cThe document says Russian forces will be deployed at the Hmeymim base for 49 years with the option of extending that arrangement for 25-year periods.\u201d  Meanwhile, U.S. deconfliction with Russia is \u201cworking quite well,\u201d Brett McGurk, the U.S. envoy to the Global Coalition to Counter ISIS, said Thursday, via Greg.  And McGurk discusses what happens to ISIS after the caliphate collapses in The New Yorker.  \u2014 TRUMP\u2019S TOP MIDDLE EAST AIDE OUSTED, reports POLITICO\u2019s Eliana Johnson: \u201cDerek Harvey, the president\u2019s top Middle East adviser, was dismissed on Thursday by national security adviser H.R. McMaster\u2014 further shrinking the ranks of White House aides hired by McMaster\u2019s ousted predecessor, Michael Flynn.  \u201c\u2018McMaster wants his own guy,\u2019 said a senior White House aide. The White House did not immediately announce a replacement for the job of National Security Council senior director for the Middle East.\u201d  CONGRESS DARES TRUMP TO VETO RUSSIA SANCTIONS, writes POLITICO\u2019s Elana Schor: \u201cThe Senate on Thursday delivered Donald Trump the first big bipartisan rebuke of his presidency, giving final approval to a package of sanctions on Russia, Iran, and North Korea that constrains his bid to defrost relations with Moscow.  \u201cThe Senate voted 98-2 to approve the sanctions bill that cleared the House earlier this week. Trump must now decide whether to sign a measure that allows Congress to block any attempt to ease or end penalties against Vladimir Putin's government and imposes new sanctions in response to a Russian electoral disruption campaign that the president continues to dispute.\u201d  On Friday, in response, Russia ordered a cut in the U.S. diplomatic force there and moved to close a U.S. recreation retreat on the outskirts of Moscow, The Associated Press reports.  INDUSTRY INTEL \u2014 RAYTHEON BOOSTS ANNUAL PROJECTIONS, reports Jacqueline: \u201cRaytheon announced [Thursday] a 4.2 percent increase in net sales during the second quarter of 2017, compared with the same period last year, leading the company to increase its full-year projections. The company reported $6.3 billion in net second-quarter sales, up from $6 billion in 2016.  \u201c\u2018Global customer demand for our advanced capabilities continues to drive growth, resulting in stronger than expected bookings, sales, EPS and operating cash flow for the quarter,\u2019 Raytheon CEO Thomas Kennedy said.  \u201cBecause of the performance so far this year, Raytheon increased its full-year net sales estimates by $200 million and its earnings for continuing operations by 10 cents per share.\u201d  TOP DOCS \u2013 STATE OFFERS PRIMERS ON ARMS SALES AND SECURITY ASSISTANCE: The State Department has released two fact sheets, one on U.S. arms sales and the defense trade, and a second on the role of the Bureau of Political-Military Affairs in U.S. security assistance.  MAKING MOVES \u2014 SASC ADVANCES FOUR PENTAGON NOMINATIONS, via your Morning D correspondent: The Senate Armed Services Committee Thursday approved by voice vote four nominees for key Pentagon civilian posts:  \u2014 John Gibson to be the Defense Department's deputy chief management officer.  \u2014 Ellen Lord to be undersecretary of Defense for acquisition, technology and logistics.  \u2014 Lucian Niemeyer to be assistant secretary of Defense for energy, installations and environment.  \u2014 And Matthew Donovan to be undersecretary of the Air Force.  All four nominations now must be approved by the full Senate.  \u2014 KING AIDE DEPARTS HILL: Today is Scott Ogden's last day as deputy communications director for Sen. Angus King (I-Maine). A Maine native who has worked for King since 2013, Ogden is returning to his home state. King\u2019s deputy press secretary and digital director, Jack Faherty, will take over as acting press secretary.  SPEED READ  \u2014 After McCain\u2019s cancer diagnosis, some veterans wonder about an Agent Orange link: Houston Chronicle/ProPublica  \u2014 The Marine Corps grounds its KC-130Ts after a fatal crash: Defense News  \u2014 A U.S. admiral says he\u2019d comply with a hypothetical nuclear strike order against China: NYT  \u2014 Britain plans to send a warship to the disputed South China Sea next year in a move likely to anger Beijing: Reuters  \u2014 China\u2019s air force will continue conducting sea drills regardless of interference: Reuters  \u2014 The Coast Guard lacks a vital strategy for funding and acquiring an aging fleet, the GAO reports: Defense News  \u2014 Trump instructs his national security aides to find a rationale for declaring that the Iran is violating the terms of the nuclear accord: NYT  \u2014 Al-Qaeda creates a new cell in Kashmir: The Guardian  \u2014 U.S.-trained Iraqi soldiers may have committed war crimes in Mosul: Newsweek  \u2014 Germany and Turkey gear up for a showdown: WSJ  \u2014 Some tensions ease but clashes continue after Palestinians are allowed to pray at a holy Jerusalem compound: The Washington Post  \u2014 How has Qatar managed to withstand the maelstrom so far? WSJ  \u2014 The story of a mysterious commercial ship hijacking in the Gulf of Aden: Bloomberg  \u2014 The Air Force and Navy plan cuts to AMRAAM missile purchases: Defense News  \u2014 Target-practice munitions from World War II are washing up on the North Carolina coast: The Washington Post  \u2014 France temporarily nationalizes a shipyard to scuttle an Italian company\u2019s incursion: WSJ  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
