aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  07/27/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacquelaine Klimas  DRIVING THE DAY \u2014 ALL ABOARD THE \u2018SECURITY-BUS:\u2019 After a late-night round of votes, the House aims to complete roll calls on amendments to the Legislative Branch, Milcon-VA and Energy-Water Appropriations bills today, clearing the floor to begin debate on the Defense Appropriations bill.  Story Continued Below  RULES PANEL APPROVES 54 DEFENSE AMENDMENTS, reports our colleague Connor O\u2019Brien: \u201cThe House Rules Committee [Wednesday] approved 54 amendments to annual defense spending legislation, with House Republicans blocking most controversial proposals from floor debate. The panel approved the rule 7-4 along party lines.\u201d  Here\u2019s a rundown of what did \u2014 and didn\u2019t \u2014 make the cut:  \u2014 CUTTING THE TOPLINE: The rule notably includes an amendment from Rep. Jared Polis (D-Colo.) that would cut the defense funding topline by 1 per cent, excluding personnel accounts.  \u2014 GITMO: An amendment from Rep. Jerry Nadler (D-N.Y.) that would strike provisions that bar the transfer of detainees from the military prison at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, to the U.S. and construction of facilities in the U.S. to hold Gitmo prisoners was also made in order.  \u2014 VIRGINIA CLASS SUBS: A proposal from Rep. Joe Courtney (D-Conn.) to permit multi-year procurement of up to 13 Virginia class submarines, reflecting a provision in the House-passed defense policy bill, was included.  \u2014 SPACE-BASED MISSILE DEFENSE: An amendment was also included from Rep. Bill Foster (D-Ill.) that would prohibit funding for testing and deployment of a space-based ballistic missile defense layer, which has been pushed by Republican defense hawks.  Some key amendments were also excluded, including cutting a $28.6 billion in broad "restoration" funds in the base and war budgets, targeting federal spending at Trump-owned properties and sunsetting the 2001 Authorization for Use of Military Force.  The House also won't debate a proposal from Rep. Scott Perry (R-Pa.) to block creation of a new Space Corps under the Air Force. HASC Strategic Forces Subcommittee Chairman Mike Rogers (R-Ala.), an architect of the Space Corps proposal, told Morning D that Perry elected to drop the amendment after the two lawmakers discussed the issue.   "Freight train's movin' baby!" Rogers said, leaving House votes Wednesday.  The panel also blocked proposals to bar funds for transition-related medical treatment for transgender troops as well as an amendment Rep. Scott Peters (D-Calif.) to block President Donald Trump's ban on transgender individuals serving in the military.  HOUSE BLOCKS BRAC, also via Connor: \u201cThe House [last night] quietly agreed to block a new round of military base realignments and closures for at least another year. Lawmakers adopted by voice vote an amendment from Reps. John Ratcliffe (R-Texas) and Bill Shuster (R-Pa.) to prohibit funding for a new BRAC as part of a massive national security appropriations bill. The amendment was adopted for the annual military construction and veterans affairs funding measure included in the bill.\u201d  FOR YOUR RADAR \u2014 RULES PANEL TO TURN TO INTEL AUTHORIZATION: The House Rules Committee is scheduled to meet this afternoon to consider a rule on the fiscal 2018 Intelligence Authorization Act. The meeting follows House Democrats rejection of the bill Monday after Republican leaders attempted to bring it up on the House floor under suspension, which requires a two-thirds majority for passage.  RYAN PROMISES BUDGET VOTE IN SEPTEMBER, reports POLITICO\u2019s Sarah Ferris: \u201cThe House GOP budget resolution is finally headed to the floor \u2014 just not until September. Republican Study Committee Chairman Mark Walker says he has struck a deal with House Speaker Paul Ryan to revive the fiscal blueprint, in exchange for dropping demands for a full GOP omnibus this week.\u201d  TOP DOC \u2014 CSBA: TRUMP DROPS BALL ON DEFENSE BUDGET REQUEST, via your Morning D correspondent: \u201cThe Trump administration made a \u2018strategic mistake\u2019 by not requesting more defense funding for its military buildup in its fiscal 2018 budget proposal, a new analysis says. The administration seeks to \u2018restore readiness\u2019 with its $667.6 billion request for discretionary defense spending in fiscal 2018, according to the analysis by the Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments. And it's expected to start its buildup in its fiscal 2019 request, once it's completed key strategic reviews, the analysis adds.  "\u2019Forgoing a request for additional defense spending in its first budget, when a new administration has the greatest chance of making big course corrections, was a strategic mistake,\u2019 Katherine Blakeley, the analysis' author, concludes.\u201d  IT\u2019S THURSDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we're always on the lookout for tips, pitches and feedback. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  HAPPENING TODAY \u2014 MILLEY MEETS THE PRESS: Army Chief of Staff Gen. Mark Milley speaks at a National Press Club luncheon, followed by a Q&A session.  \u2014 AND TRUMP COUNTER-ISIS ENVOY TALKS WITH MEI: Brett McGurk, the administration\u2019s envoy to the Global Coalition to Counter ISIS, joins several leading think tanks analysts at the Middle East Institute for a discussion about the administration\u2019s counterterrorism policy.  TRUMP BANS TRANSGENDER TROOPS, reports Louis Nelson: \u201cPresident Donald Trump announced on Twitter on Wednesday that the U.S. military will not allow transgender individuals to serve \u2018in any capacity,\u2019 reversing an Obama-era policy while sparking bipartisan criticism from some of the nation's most prominent lawmakers on military issues.  \u201c\u2018After consultation with my Generals and military experts, please be advised that the United States Government will not accept or allow Transgender individuals to serve in any capacity in the U.S. Military,\u2019 Trump wrote online, breaking his message up into multiple posts. \u2018Our military must be focused on decisive and overwhelming victory and cannot be burdened with the tremendous medical costs and disruption that transgender in the military would entail. Thank you.\u2019 ...  \u201cA Trump administration official said that the president\u2019s decision to announce the military\u2019s transgender policy shift was at least in part motivated by conservatives who had opposed government spending legislation that might put money towards transgender health services.\u201d  Rachel Bade and Josh Dawsey take us inside the president\u2019s decision, including his attempts to mollify House Republicans threatening to blow up the \u201csecurity-bus\u201d spending bill over a ban on Pentagon-funded sex reassignment operations.  \u2014 BUT A TWEET IS NOT POLICY, YET, writes our colleague Jacqueline Klimas: \u201cTrump's surprise announcement that he wants to ban transgender troops will have little practical effect in the short term for those who are already serving, according to legal experts...  \u201cBut without a formal modification to military regulations \u2014 a process that could take months \u2014 the decision does not constitute a change in policy.  \u201c\u2018A statement by a president is not the same thing as formal rule-making process,\u2019 said Tobias Wolff, a professor at the University of Pennsylvania Law School. \u2018None of the rules currently in place in the Department of Defense and the service branches have changed because of this statement.\u2019\u201d  The ban could turn into a legal landmine, John Culhane, co-director of the Family Health Law & Policy Institute at the Delaware Law School, writes for POLITICO Magazine.  And here\u2019s a primer on key issues surrounding the ban, via our colleagues Jacqueline, Matthew Nussbaum and Connor.  \u2014 SASC REPUBLICANS PUSH BACK: \u201cPresident Donald Trump's new plan to ban transgender people from the military is running into opposition from a key ally: Iowa GOP Sen. Joni Ernst,\u201d writes POLITICO\u2019s Burgess Everett.  \u201cIn a statement, a spokeswoman for the veteran said Ernst has served with people \u2018from all different backgrounds\u2019 and that gender is not a vital indicator of someone's military prowess.\u201d  SASC Chairman John McCain (R-Ariz.) urges patience while the Pentagon completes its review of transgender troops in the military, writing in a statement that \u201cthe president\u2019s tweet this morning regarding transgender Americans in the military is yet another example of why major policy announcements should not be made via Twitter...There is no reason to force service members who are able to fight, train, and deploy to leave the military \u2014 regardless of their gender identity.\u201d  Meanwhile, Trump\u2019s decision is ammunition for gay rights activists who have long doubted the sincerity of his professed support for lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender rights, adds POLITICO\u2019s Madeline Conway.  And tech industry leaders reject the ban: POLITICO Pro  GOP MOVES TOWARDS SANCTIONS BILL SOLUTION, writes POLITICO\u2019s Elana Schor: \u201cHouse and Senate Republicans clashed Wednesday over a bipartisan package of sanctions targeting Russia, Iran and North Korea before appearing to resolve a dispute that threatened to delay the bill's arrival on President Donald Trump's desk.  \u201cLess than 24 hours after the sanctions deal passed the House 419-3, Senate Foreign Relations Chairman Bob Corker (R-Tenn.) said Wednesday morning that his chamber would likely cut out the measure\u2019s North Korea provisions \u2014 which were added to the mix in the last lap of talks on the legislation at the behest of House GOP leaders \u2014 and send it back across the Capitol. House Republican leaders countered by urging the Senate to act quickly on the bill and warning that any changes would postpone Trump's looming decision on a veto until September.\u201d  Iran says it will reciprocate any sanctions, further endangering the nuclear accord reached between the country and the U.S., via Reuters.  And Russia says so, too, Reuters adds.  WAR REPORT \u2014 TALIBAN ROUTS AFGHAN ARMY OUTPOST, reports The New York Times: \u201cIn a bloody overnight attack in Afghanistan\u2019s Kandahar Province on Wednesday, the Taliban routed an Afghan Army outpost, killing dozens of soldiers and raising fears of a concerted insurgent offensive in the province, a former seat of Taliban power that took years of effort by coalition and Afghan forces to secure.  \u201cThe attack happened in Khakrez District, about 30 miles from Kandahar city, and the large number of casualties has raised concerns about new Taliban tactics against an Afghan force already losing men in record numbers.  \u201cOne senior security official said 39 Afghan Army soldiers were killed in the attack, which began at 10 p.m. on Tuesday and lasted for three hours. The official said 17 other soldiers were wounded, and another dozen have not been accounted for.\u201d  Meanwhile, Afghan forces rescue two Pakistani diplomats abducted last month, reports the Associated Press.  \u2014 ADVOCATES PRESS U.S. TO MOVE NUKES FROM TURKEY, writes Stars and Stripes: \u201cThe U.S. should move its nuclear weapons from Incirlik Air Base and start looking for alternatives to the longtime military hub in Turkey, a country that can no longer be fully relied on, analysts and former military officials said.  \u201cThe U.S. military maintains about 50 nuclear warheads at Incirlik, according to nuclear watchdog organizations.  \u201c\u2018It is the worst place possible to be keeping nuclear weapons,\u2019 said Joseph Cirincione, president of the Ploughshares Fund, a prominent nonprofit advocacy group.\u201d  \u2014 U.S.-BACKED FIGHTERS CONTROL NEARLY HALF OF RAQQA, reports the AP: \u201cA spokeswoman for a U.S.-backed Syrian opposition force and a monitoring group say opponents of the Islamic State group have captured nearly half of the extremists' de facto capital of Raqqa.  \u201cNisreen Abdullah of the Women's Protection Units, or YPJ, told The Associated Press on Thursday that the push into the northern Syrian city has slowed down because of massive amounts of explosives laid by IS fighters. She said fighters of the Syrian Democratic Forces, a coalition that includes the YPJ, now controls 45 percent of Raqqa.\u201d  Meanwhile, Syrian government forces capture Deir al-Zor, the last major town once-controlled by ISIS in Homs Province, reports Reuters.  And Hezbollah reaches a cease-fire with the Nusra Front at the Syrian-Lebanese border, Reuters adds.  INDUSTRY INTEL \u2014 BOEING AND GENERAL DYNAMICS REPORT REVENUE DIPS, BUT UPBEAT OUTLOOKS, via Jacqueline: \u201cBoeing announced [Wednesday] a more than $2 billion drop in revenues in the second quarter of 2017, compared with last year. The company reported $22.7 billion in second-quarter revenues this year, compared with $24.8 billion during the same period in 2016. Earnings per share, however, increased to $2.89. As a result, the company boosted its full year earnings guidance per share by 75 cents.\u201d  \u201cGeneral Dynamics' revenue dipped 1.3 percent in the second quarter of 2017, compared with last year, the company reported [Wednesday]. Second-quarter revenue was down to $7.68 billion this year from $7.77 billion in the second quarter of 2016. Diluted earnings per share, however, were up 6.5 percent to $2.45, compared to $2.30 a year ago. The increase led the company to increase its full-year earnings per share outlook by 20 cents. Net earnings were also up almost 5 percent to $749 million,\u201d Jacqueline also reports.  \u2014 NORTHROP REPORTS SALES UPTICK, via Jacqueline: \u201cNorthrop Grumman reported today a 6 percent increase in sales during the second quarter of 2017, compared with the same time last year. The company announced second quarter sales of $6.4 billion, compared with $6 billion in 2016. Net earnings also increased 7 percent to $552 million.\u201d  SPEED READ  \u2014 Iran reported to have successfully launched a rocket carrying a satellite: AP  \u2014 U.S. set to seek to test Iran deal with more inspections: AP  \u2014 The nuclear threat inside Secretary Rick Perry\u2019s Energy Department: Vanity Fair  \u2014 STRATCOM Chief Gen. John Hyten confirms plans for an overhaul: Breaking Defense  \u2014 Sen. Dan Sullivan (R-Alaska) predicts the fiscal 2018 NDAA finally approved by Congress would contain provisions strengthening ballistic missile defense: POLITICO Pro  \u2014 North Korea\u2019s army of hackers has a new target: bank accounts: The Wall Street Journal  \u2014 Secretary of State Rex Tillerson aims to slash dozens of special envoys within his department: POLITICO  \u2014 Multi-Domain Battle is \u201cactually becoming reality\u201d: Breaking Defense  \u2014 The WSJ and Institute of National Security Studies analyze suicide bombing in 2016: WSJ  \u2014 Egypt creates a national council to fight terrorism: Reuters  \u2014 Germany sentences an Islamic extremist recruiter to five and a half years in prison: NYT  \u2014 Islamic State militants\u2019 children worry about revenge attacks: The Guardian  \u2014 The top EU court keeps Hamas on the bloc\u2019s terror list: WSJ  \u2014 The European Court of Justice also tells the EU to redo its counterterrorism strategy of sharing airline traveler info with Canada: POLITICO  \u2014 China might soon be able to track foreign submarines with underwater drones: South China Morning Post  \u2014 The Philippines is set to receive two Cessna aircraft purchased by the Pentagon and modified for surveillance: Defense News  \u2014 Suicide attempts in an Army unit may spawn copycats: CNN  \u2014 What it took to work as a Navy chief engineer during the Cold War: The War Zone  \u2014 Lockheed Martin lands an $86.5 million missile contract with the Air Force and Navy: TheStreet  \u2014 The Senate Veterans\u2019 Affairs Committee advances bipartisan legislation that would expand the education benefits offered to veterans under the GI Bill: POLITICO Pro  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
