aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacqueline Klimas  TOP NEWS \u2014 DIA: NORTH KOREA COULD FIELD A NUCLEAR ICBM NEXT YEAR, via The Washington Post: \u201cNorth Korea will be able to field a reliable, nuclear-capable intercontinental ballistic missile as early as next year, U.S. officials have concluded in a confidential assessment that dramatically shrinks the timeline for when Pyongyang could strike North American cities with atomic weapons.  Story Continued Below  \u201cThe new assessment by the Pentagon\u2019s Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA), which shaves a full two years off the consensus forecast for North Korea\u2019s ICBM program, was prompted by recent missile tests showing surprising technical advances by the country\u2019s weapons scientists, at a pace beyond which many analysts believed was possible for the isolated communist regime...  \u201cThe finding further increases the pressure on U.S. and Asian leaders to halt North Korea\u2019s progress before it can threaten the world with nuclear-tipped missiles. President Trump, during his visit to Poland earlier this month, vowed to confront Pyongyang \u201cvery strongly\u201d to stop its missile advances.\u201d  And House Armed Services Committee Chairman Mac Thornberry (R-Texas) is \u201cincreasingly alarmed\u201d by North Korea\u2019s advancing capabilities, our colleague Jacqueline Klimas adds.  \u2014 INTERCEPTOR TEST ATTRIBUTED TO SAILOR ERROR, reports Defense News: \u201cA U.S. Missile Defense Agency review of a failed ballistic missile intercept test showed that a mistaken input into the combat system by a sailor on the destroyer John Paul Jones caused the missile to self-destruct before reaching the target.  \u201cA tactical datalink controller, in charge of maintaining encrypted data exchanges between ships and aircraft, accidentally identified the incoming ballistic missile target as a friendly in the system, causing the SM-3 missile to self-destruct in flight, according to a source familiar with the test.  \u201cThe head of MDA did not comment on the sailor error, but said in a statement that the ongoing review confirmed it wasn\u2019t an issue with the SM-3 Block IIA missile or the Navy\u2019s Aegis combat system.\u201d  MCCAIN RETURNS DRAMATICALLY TO THE SENATE, reports POLITICO\u2019s Elana Schor: \u201cIt was quintessential John McCain: a dramatic return to the Senate to salvage the GOP\u2019s Obamacare repeal effort \u2014 followed by a speech blasting the process his party used to get there\u2026  \u201cMcCain said he plans to remain [here] in the Senate in order to manage floor consideration of the annual defense authorization bill, part of his duties as Armed Services chairman, before returning to Arizona for further treatment of his glioblastoma \u2014 the same type of tumor that killed his friend, the late Sen. Ted Kennedy (D-Mass.).  "\u2019I have every intention of returning here and giving many of you cause to regret all the nice things you said about me,\u2019 he said.\u201d  McCain\u2019s statement and a video of his delivery of it on the Senate floor are here.  \u2014 NDAA STUCK BEHIND OBAMACARE REPEAL: Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) has teed up the fiscal 2018 National Defense Authorization Act S. 1519 (115) on the Senate floor, but Tuesday's successful vote to take up Republican Obamacare replacement legislation means the defense policy bill will have to wait its turn. The Senate could turn to NDAA later this week, or early next week.  IT\u2019S WEDNESDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we're always on the lookout for tips, pitches and feedback. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  HAPPENING TODAY \u2014 GOLDFEIN BREAKFASTS WITH THE AIR FORCE ASSOCIATION: Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. David Goldfein participates in the Air Force Association\u2019s Breakfast Series.  The talk comes as the service seeks to increase the range of its stand-off cruise missile in response to growing threats in Eastern Europe and the Western Pacific, writes Military Times.  \u2014 SENATE VA PANEL MARKS UP GI BILL: The Senate Veterans\u2019 Affairs Committee marks up a measure to expand education benefits offered under the GI bill. The full House passed a similar measure 405-0 on Monday.  HOUSE TEES UP FIRST BATCH OF 'SECURITY-BUS' AMENDMENTS: The House Rules Committee approved 72 amendments to a massive national security-themed spending bill, set to hit the House floor today. In all, amendments were made in order to three sections of the bill: the Legislative Branch, military construction-VA and energy funding measures. The Rules panel is expected to approve more amendments for the defense appropriations measure today.  For MilCon funding, an amendment from Rep.Jerry Nadler (D-N.Y.) would strike limits on constructing facilities in the U.S. to hold detainees from the U.S. military prison at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba. Another proposal by Reps. John Ratcliffe (R-Texas) and Bill Shuster (R-Pa.) would prohibit a new round of military base realignments and closures.   The full list of amendments set for floor votes is here.  And here are some key defense proposals we\u2019re keeping an eye on:  \u2014 KILLING SPACE CORPS: Rep. Scott Perry (R-Pa.) has an amendment to bar funding for the Pentagon to establish a Space Corps, reviving a debate on the House-passed NDAA H.R. 2810 (115) on the creation of a new space service under the Air Force.  \u2014 SLASHING \u2018RESTORATION\u2019 FUNDS: Rep. Keith Ellison (D-Minn.) filed two amendments (here and here) to cut $28.6 billion allocated for a new National Defense Restoration Fund. The funding is spread out by major defense accounts and gives Defense Secretary Jim Mattis broad authority to spend the extra cash \u2014 subject to congressional approval \u2014 to implement a new national security strategy, but gives little additional guidance on how the money may be spent.  Fiscal watchdog groups have slammed the account as a slush fund. And eight fiscal groups, \u2014 including Taxpayers for Common Sense, Concerned Veterans for America and Tea Party Nation \u2014 wrote to lawmakers Tuesday, backing Ellison's amendments. In a letter, the groups called the special account "a further step down the path of fiscal irresponsibility."  TRUMP BACKS THE 'SECURITY-BUS,' via Connor: \u201cPresident Donald Trump would sign a massive national security-themed spending bill set for a House vote later this week, though the White House takes issue with a handful of military provisions.  \u201cThe White House laid out its position on the massive appropriations bill \u2014 which combines annual defense, energy, Legislative Branch and military construction and veterans funding measures \u2014 in a Statement of Administration Policy. Chief among the administration's complaints about the defense appropriation is a prohibition on a new round of military base realignments and closures.\u201d  HOUSE HANDCUFFS TRUMP WITH RUSSIA SANCTIONS, reports Elana: \u201cThe House on Tuesday overwhelmingly approved new sanctions on Russia, Iran, and North Korea, with the GOP-controlled chamber advancing a significant new constraint on President Donald Trump\u2019s foreign policy.  \u201cThe sanctions legislation, which allows lawmakers to block Trump from any attempt to roll back sanctions against Moscow, is expected to pass the Senate in similarly bipartisan fashion before next month\u2019s recess.  \u201cThe White House has yet to say definitively whether Trump would sign the bill, which his administration had criticized for failing to give him necessary \u2018flexibility\u2019 to work on warmer relations with Russia. But it appears the votes would be there for Congress to override any veto from Trump.\u201d  But EU officials are still uneasy about the move, worried it might undermine the continent\u2019s energy independence, The New York Times writes.  WAR REPORT \u2014 TALIBAN WIELDS AMERICAN WEAPONS AGAINST U.S., reports the Military Times: \u201cWeaponry provided to the Afghan military over the last 16 years has slowly trickled down to the Taliban through corruption and battlefield losses. Armored vehicles, night vision devices, M-4s, laser illuminators and scoped optics have all found the way into Taliban hands over the years.  \u201cAnd at times the U.S. has been forced to combat its own armored vehicles and weapons.\u201d  \u2014 SIGAR PROBES AFGHANISTAN PROCUREMENT, writes your Morning D correspondent: \u201cThe Special Inspector General for Afghanistan Reconstruction [Tuesday] called for a review of the procurement of all organizational equipment and clothing by the Combined Security Transition Command\u2013Afghanistan. John Sopko told the House Armed Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations that his office will also undertake a criminal investigation related to uniform procurement for the Afghan National Army.\u201d  And Trump finds reason for the U.S. to stay in Afghanistan: minerals, adds the NYT.  \u2014 SYRIAN KURDS SEEK LONG-TERM U.S. SUPPORT, reports The Associated Press: \u201cThe Kurdish-led effort to secure Raqqa once it is liberated from the Islamic State group will require long-term U.S. political and financial support for the battered city\u2019s governance and reconstruction, a senior Syrian Kurdish official said Tuesday.  \u201cIn an interview with The Associated Press in the Kurdish-administered town of Kobani, Ilham Ahmed said the U.S. role in the fight against IS must not end with the liberation of the Raqqa but should continue as a guarantor of stability until a political future for the war-torn country is charted. Ahmed is the co-president of the Syrian Democratic Council, the political wing of the U.S.-backed Kurdish-led force currently fighting to liberate the Islamic State group\u2019s self-proclaimed capital of Raqqa from the militants.\u201d  Meanwhile, Assad hails Trump\u2019s decision to end covert CIA aid to Syrian rebels, via Reuters.  And an ex-Marine is killed battling ISIS after he secretly traveled to Syria to fight with a Kurdish militia group, the AP adds.  MATTIS ORDERS A MILITARY TRAINING REVIEW, via the Military Times: \u201cDefense Secretary Jim Mattis has ordered a review of all the administrative and training requirements that prevent trigger pullers and pilots alike from focusing on warfighting.  \u201cIn the memo obtained by Military Times, Mattis on Friday directed the services, the National Guard Bureau and the combatant commanders to determine what changes are needed to give each branch increased flexibility to organize, train and equip more ready and lethal forces.\u201d  ANALYST URGES NAVY NOT TO REINVENT WHEEL FOR NEW FRIGATE, via Jacqueline: \u201cIntroducing a new class of frigate into the Navy will be \u2018critical\u2019 to achieving its 355-ship goal, an analyst told Congress today \u2014 and a "clean-sheet design" is not necessary.  \u201cJerry Hendrix, a senior fellow at the Center for New American Security, told members of the Senate Armed Services Seapower Subcommittee that the new frigate should be based on an existing design, like Fincantieri\u2019s FREMM frigate used by Italian and French navies or the U.S. Coast Guard\u2019s national security cutter, built by Huntington Ingalls\u201d  CHINA FLEXES GLOBAL MUSCLES: \u201cRussian and Chinese naval warships are holding joint exercises in the Baltic Sea for the first time, underscoring deepening military cooperation between the two powers,\u201d Bloomberg reports.  \u201cChina\u2019s Hefei destroyer, Yuncheng frigate and Lomahu supply vessel are involved in drills with two Russian corvettes that include \u2018artillery fire at surface and air targets\u2019 in the Joint Sea-2017 maneuvers, Russia\u2019s Tass news service reported Tuesday. Helicopters and Su-24 bombers will also be involved in the \u2018anti-aircraft and anti-ship defense measures\u2019 coordinated from the Baltiysk base in Russia\u2019s Kaliningrad enclave, it said.\u201d  Meanwhile, President Xi Jinping is holding up China as a confident global power that can increasingly count on swelling national pride, writes The Wall Street Journal.  And for China\u2019s global ambitions, Iran is at the center of everything, adds the NYT.  MAKING MOVES \u2014 FORMER WITTMAN AIDE MOVES TO THE PENTAGON: Rep. Rob Wittman\u2019s (R-Va.) former chief-of-staff, Jamie Miller, began a new job Tuesday as deputy assistant secretary of Defense for House affairs. And Carolyn King has taken over as Wittman\u2019s chief of staff.  SPEED READ  \u2014 U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Nikki Haley touts North Korea sanctions progress with China: AP  \u2014 North Korea\u2019s elite use Gmail, Facebook, Amazon and other Western e-commerce companies: The Washington Post  \u2014 A close encounter with an Iranian warship prompts U.S. Navy warning shots: The Washington Post  \u2014 Iran will respond to any new U.S. sanctions, its deputy foreign minister says: Reuters  \u2014 Russia discusses supplying Iraq with battle tanks: Reuters  \u2014 Off-duty Oklahoma National Guardsmen save residents from a fire in Ukraine: Stars and Stripes  \u2014 How some Yazidi women and girls survived slavery at the hands of the Islamic State: The Guardian  \u2014 Afghan President Ashraf Ghani tries to focus on building a stable state system: WSJ  \u2014 An Afghan district governor dies in a roadside explosion: AP  \u2014 Trump and Lebanese Prime Minister Saad Harriri pledge to fight terrorism together during his visit to the White House: AP  \u2014 Libyan rivals reach an accord on a cease-fire and steps toward an election: AP  \u2014 Arab nations opposed to Qatar deepen the crisis by adding more names to their terror lists: WSJ   \u2014 Restarting the military draft after more than four decades of an all-volunteer force would be complicated: Military Times  \u2014 Israel removes the controversial metal detectors in Jerusalem, but Palestinians aren\u2019t mollified: Reuters  \u2014 The lone U.S. soldier who survived the fatal Jordan shootout tells his story: NYT  \u2014 Former Joint Chiefs Chairman retired Adm. Mike Mullen urges Congress not to legislate medical care for transgender troops: USA Today  \u2014 House Veterans\u2019 Affairs Chairman Phil Roe (R-Tenn.) is diagnosed with early-stage prostate cancer: Stars and Stripes  \u2014 Veterans\u2019 PTSD disability claims have tripled in 10 years: Military Times  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson  \u000a                                            By Kel McClanahan  \u000a                                            By Carrie Levine 
