aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacqueline Klimas  TOP NEWS \u2014 MCCAIN TO MAKE DRAMATIC RETURN FOR HEALTH CARE AND NDAA, report POLITICO\u2019s Burgess Everett, Seung Min Kim and Jennifer Haberkorn: \u201cSenate Republicans appear on the verge of having enough votes to start debate on Obamacare repeal, with the dramatic announcement Monday night that Sen. John McCain, diagnosed with brain cancer just a few days ago, would return to Washington for the Tuesday vote ...  Story Continued Below  \u201cEarlier Monday, McConnell also teed up the National Defense Authorization Act to come next on the Senate floor \u2014 a major priority for McCain, the Senate Armed Services Committee chairman.\u201d  McConnell offered a motion to proceed to the House-passed version of the defense policy bill. In previous years, the House NDAA has been used as a legislative vehicle, with the Senate version of the bill substituted as an amendment, our colleague Connor O\u2019Brien adds.  HOUSE PASSES GI EDUCATION EXPANSION, reports POLITICO Pro\u2019s Michael Stratford: \u201cThe House [Monday] overwhelmingly passed bipartisan legislation that would expand the education benefits offered to veterans under the GI Bill. Lawmakers voted 405-0 to pass legislation ... that would eliminate, for new enlistees, the current 15-year time limit veterans have to use their educational assistance under the GI Bill.\u201d  \u2014 BUT TURNS BACK INTEL AUTHORIZATION, FOR NOW, via Connor: \u201cHouse Democrats sank two key bills on the House floor Monday, embarrassing Republican leaders who were banking on the noncontroversial legislation sailing through \u2014 in a new sign of the opposition's party's frustration with the majority's approach.  \u201cKicking off a busy week in the House, most Democrats and a handful of Republicans joined forces to deny GOP leaders big-enough majorities to pass an annual intelligence policy bill and legislation to restore funding for a key veterans health care program.  \u201cBoth bills came to the House floor Monday under suspension of the rules, an expedited process that allows for less than an hour of debate and no amendments but also requires a two-thirds majority for passage ...  \u201cFirst, the House voted down the 2018 intelligence authorization bill, which sets policy for intelligence agencies and authorizes funding for classified programs.\u201d  \u2014 AND VA CHOICE FUNDING, Connor adds: \u201cNext, Democrats united to defeat a $2 billion bill to replenish for six months the emergency Veterans Choice Program, which subsidizes private medical care outside the Veterans Affairs Department for veterans facing lengthy wait times and is set to run dry in August.  \u201cDemocrats cited opposition from a large group of veterans organizations that called on Congress to reject the bill because it pays for the program through cuts in the VA.\u201d  HOUSE RULES MEETS FOR DAY TWO ON 'SECURITY-BUS:' The House Rules Committee meets for a second straight day to sift through the hundreds of amendments filed to the House GOP "security-bus," which includes the defense and military construction spending bills. The panel gaveled out after midnight last night without approving any amendments. So far, 325 have been filed.  HAPPY TUESDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we're always on the lookout for tips, pitches and feedback. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  HAPPENING TODAY \u2014 SASC PANEL MULLS OPTIONS FOR 355-SHIP NAVY: The Senate Armed Services Seapower Subcommittee hears from top naval analysts on options for building a 355-ship Navy.  \u2014 SENATE FOREIGN RELATIONS EYES MAXIMUM PRESSURE ON NORTH KOREA: The Senate Foreign Relations Committee hears from top officials to assess the maximum pressure and engagement policy for North Korea, featuring Acting Assistant Secretary of State of the Bureau of East Asian and Pacific Affairs Susan Thornton.  \u2014 AND HOUSE FOREIGN AFFAIRS TALKS AUMF: The House Foreign Affairs Committee holds a hearing featuring former government and military officials to discuss a new Authorization for Use of Military Force against terrorism.  \u2014 HASC PANEL EYES AFGHANISTAN AND IRAQ PROCUREMENT: The House Armed Services Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations hears from Special Inspector General for Afghanistan Reconstruction John Sopko, among other officials to evaluate equipment and uniform procurement Afghanistan and Iraq.  \u2014 TRUMP MEETS WITH LEBANESE PRIME MINISTER: The president meets at the White House \u2014 and holds a joint news conference \u2014 with Lebanese Prime Minister Saad Hariri, who is expected to make the case for increased U.S. security and humanitarian aid to his country. The president\u2019s proposed budget, though, would slash military aid to Lebanon from $103 million to $19 million.  \u2014 AND KUSHNER MEETS WITH HOUSE INTEL PANEL, via POLITICO\u2019s Kyle Cheney: \u201cHouse intelligence Committee Chairman Devin Nunes \u2014 who stepped aside from the House's Russia probe amid partisan infighting \u2014 is expected to attend Tuesday's highly anticipated closed door interview of Jared Kushner, according to a GOP source.\u201d  WAR REPORT \u2014 SYRIA STRATEGY HINGES ON COOPERATION WITH RUSSIA, writes The Washington Post: \u201cCooperation with Russia is becoming a central part of the Trump administration\u2019s counter-Islamic State strategy in Syria, with U.S. military planners counting on Moscow to try to prevent Syrian government forces and their allies on the ground from interfering in coalition-backed operations against the militants.  \u201cSyria\u2019s once-separate conflicts have moved into close proximity on the battlefield. Part of the plan essentially carves up Syria into no-go zones for each of the players \u2014 President Bashar al-Assad\u2019s fight, with Russian and Iranian help, against rebels seeking to overthrow him, and the U.S.-led coalition\u2019s war to destroy the Islamic State.\u201d  Meanwhile, Trump blasts The Washington Post\u2019s \u201cfabricated\u201d story about his decision to end a covert program aiding Syrian rebels fighting the government of Bashar al-Assad, The Washington Post adds.  \u2014 THE WHITE HOUSE WAR WITHIN, Susan Glasser writes for POLITICO Magazine: \u201cLast week, President Donald Trump\u2019s senior Cabinet officials and top national security advisers met for a contentious meeting to finally agree on a new strategy for America\u2019s longest war. After months of wrangling, they would ask Trump for a modest troop increase and a more intense commitment to the seemingly endless struggle in Afghanistan.  \u201cBut the session of the National Security Council Principals Committee, described by two sources briefed on it as a \u2018s*** show\u2019 that featured what a third source, a senior White House official, confirmed was a heated debate where \u2018words were exchanged,\u2019 proved no more successful than months\u2019 worth of previous Afghan policy debates.  \u201cTrump refused to sign off on the plan they approved, the sources said, instead sending it back to his national security team demanding more work.\u201d  Meanwhile, residents and analysts question if the government can protect Afghanistan's capital after the latest deadly bombing in Kabul, writes the Associated Press.  And Blackwater\u2019s founder defends his controversial proposal to expand contractors\u2019 role in the war in Afghanistan, via NPR.  \u2014 TALIBAN STRIKES IN PAKISTAN, reports the AP: \u201cA suicide bomber struck near a police team in the eastern city of Lahore Monday killing at least 26 and wounding another 54, many of them police officers. An outlawed Taliban faction claimed responsibility.  \u201cSenior police officer Haider Ashraf said a suicide bomber on a motorcycle targeted police guarding a demolition site at Kot Lakhpat's vegetable market on the outskirts of Lahore. Ashraf said it was believed earlier that the bomb was in a car, but it was later discovered that the vehicle belonged to a police officer, among the eight officers killed.\u201d  TOP DOCS \u2014 MATTIS CASTIGATES \u2018CAVALIER\u2019 AFGHAN UNIFORM BUYS, via your Morning D correspondent: Defense Secretary Jim Mattis asked Pentagon officials to act upon a Special Inspector General for Afghanistan report that found the Defense Department spent $28 million on ineffective uniforms for the Afghan National Army. SIGAR found the department failed to perform due diligence in approving a \u2018forest\u2019 pattern uniform, despite the fact that forests only cover 2.1 percent of Afghanistan's land area.  \u201cBuying uniforms for our Afghan partners, and doing so in a way that may have wasted tens of millions of taxpayer dollars ... must not been seen as inconsequential in the grand scheme of the Department's responsibilities and budget,\u201d Mattis wrote in a letter to the chairs of the Pentagon\u2019s Afghanistan Resource Oversight Council, which is comprised of three under secretaries of defense. \u201cIn my view, the key finding of the SIGAR report is not just that it exposes waste...but rather it serves as an example of a complacent mode of thinking.\u201d  \u2014 AND MCCASKILL DEMANDS ANSWERS, also via Greg: \u201cA senior member of the Senate Armed Services Committee is pressing the Pentagon on why it spent $28 million on ineffective uniforms for the Afghanistan National Army ...  \u201cSen. Claire McCaskill (D-Mo.) wrote [Monday] in a letter to Robert Karem, acting under secretary for policy, that she is concerned the uniform contract violated federal procurement law.\u201d  NATO WADES INTO TURKEY-GERMANY DISPUTE, via Reuters: \u201cNATO's secretary general is offering to broker a visit by German lawmakers to troops serving on a Turkish air base in an attempt to heal a rift between the two allies which is disrupting anti-Islamic State operations.  \u201cThe mediation offer by NATO chief Jens Stoltenberg, announced on Monday, came as Ankara itself sought to limit the economic fallout from the damaging row with Berlin, dropping a request for Germany to help it investigate hundreds of German companies it said could have links to terrorism.\u201d  The dispute threatens to disrupt NATO\u2019s counterterrorism mission, The Wall Street Journal adds.  U.S. AND CHINESE PLANES NARROWLY AVOID COLLISION, writes the WSJ: \u201cA U.S. Navy reconnaissance plane was forced to take evasive action to avoid a possible mid-air collision after a Chinese jet fighter came within 300 feet of the American aircraft over the East China Sea, U.S. officials said Monday.  \u201cCapt. Jeff Davis, a Pentagon spokesman, said a Chinese J-10 jet fighter rapidly approached under the U.S. EP-3 reconnaissance plane, slowed down and then flew in front of the American pilot, triggering the plane\u2019s collision alarm system and forcing it to take evasive action.  \u201cThe Chinese plane came within 300 feet of the U.S. plane, which was flying in international airspace, according to another defense official.\u201d  The near miss comes as a Chinese intelligence-gathering ship is spotted near a U.S.-Australian military exercise, reports Defense News.  And as Beijing opens its \u201csouthernmost cinema\u201d on the disputed island of Yongxing in the South China Sea, The Washington Post reports.  INDUSTRY INTEL \u2014 DEFENSE INDUSTRY RETURNS TO PROSPERITY? Defense News asks: \u201cOverall defense revenues for the Top 100 defense companies in the world increased in 2016, ending a five-year slide and signaling that the era of defense austerity may officially be at an end.  \u201cTotal 2016 defense revenues for the Top 100 companies came in at $364.8 billion, an increase of 3.6 percent over 2015 figures, according to numbers compiled by Defense News as part of the annual Top 100 Defense Companies list.\u201d  The 2017 Top 100 are listed here.  \u2014 TRUMP EXECUTIVE ORDER AIMS TO FULFILL DEFENSE BUILDUP PROMISE, a top U.S. trade official says via Defense News: \u201c The executive order President Trump signed Friday ordering a government-wide review of America\u2019s defense industry aims to help fulfill Trump\u2019s promise to \u2018rebuild\u2019 the military, a top U.S. trade official says.  \u201cWhite House Director of Trade and Industrial Policy Peter Navarro called the defense-industrial base \u2018a major priority,\u2019 for Trump. The order, he said, \u2018recognizes that the United States cannot be a global power without a preeminent military.\u2019\u201d  MAKING MOVES \u2014 FORMER VA SECRETARY JOINS RALLYPOINT BOARD: Former Veterans Affairs Secretary Bob McDonald has joined the board of directors of the military and veteran professional networking site RallyPoint. A former CEO of consumer product giant Procter & Gamble and a West Point graduate, McDonald led VA during the final years of the Obama administration.  \u2014 BRINKLEY AND GREENWALT LAUNCH NEW FIRM: Paul Brinkley, who as deputy undersecretary for Defense in the George W. Bush and Obama administrations led a Pentagon task force designed to boost U.S. and Western investment in Iraq and Afghanistan, is partnering with former SASC senior staffer William Greenwalt on a new investment firm to provide growth capital and expertise to private technology companies that primarily service the aerospace and defense markets.  SPEED READ  \u2014 Ukraine spots Russia moving more troops to the border: Newsweek  \u2014 For Trump and Russian President Vladimir Putin, sanctions against Russia are a setback both sought to avoid: NYT  \u2014 White House wavers on whether Trump would sign the Russia sanctions bill: Washington Examiner  \u2014 China prepares for a crisis along its border with North Korea, including the possibility of a U.S. military strike: WSJ  \u2014 Turkey fails to mediate the Qatar crisis: Reuters   \u2014 Russia is ready to step up to the Qatar plate next: Reuters  \u2014 The Navy tries out its amphibious up-gunned expeditionary strike group in Australia: Defense News  \u2014 A junior Navy officer dreamed up a wireless headset for gunnery sailors. Now the Navy\u2019s testing a prototype: Defense One  \u2014 Japan wraps up its probe into last month\u2019s fatal U.S. Navy collision with a commercial container ship: AP  \u2014 Hezbollah claims near-victory in an anti-jihadist campaign along the Syrian border: Reuters  \u2014 Al-Qaeda in Syria is close to snuffing out what remains of the country\u2019s uprising in the country\u2019s northwest: AP  \u2014 Israel agrees to remove metal detectors at the entrance to the Aqsa Mosque compound: The New York Times  \u2014 The Defense Department identifies the remains of a Marine killed in World War II: AP  \u2014 Mayor Sadiq Khan tries to usher London past a spell of terrorism: The New Yorker  \u2014 Trump takes action on veterans\u2019 affairs, but he stays quiet about it: Bloomberg  \u2014 Worries about privatization haunt VA Secretary David Shulkin: Military Times  \u2014 Watch footage of the SR-71 Blackbird recon jet at all stages of flight: Task & Purpose  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
