aV \u000a            By GREGORY HELLMAN  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Eli Okun, Connor O\u2019Brien and Jacqueline Klimas  BREAKING OVERNIGHT \u2014 TALIBAN CLAIMS DEADLY KABUL ATTACK, reports The Associated Press: \u201cA suicide bomber rammed his car packed with explosives into a bus carrying government employees in the Afghan capital early on Monday, killing 24 people and wounding 42 others, Kabul's police chief spokesman said. The Taliban claimed responsibility for the assault.  Story Continued Below  \u201cThe attack took place in a western Kabul neighborhood where several prominent politicians reside and at rush hour, as residents were heading to work and students were on their way to a nearby private high school, said Basir Mujahed, the spokesman.  \u201c\u2018The bomber attacked at one of the busiest times of the day,\u2019 the spokesman said. \u2018There were traffic jams with people going to work and to the university and schools. Many of the shops had just opened.\u2019\u201d  And the Taliban advances, taking over two more districts in Afghanistan, adds Stars and Stripes.  \u2014 AFGHANISTAN AUTHORITY IS TACTICAL, NOT STRATEGIC, MATTIS SAYS, via Military Times: \u201cSecretary of Defense Jim Mattis clarified on Friday that while the Defense Department now has authority to set troop numbers for Afghanistan, President Donald Trump is still setting the strategy that will drive those numbers.   \u201c\u2018What he delegated was a tactical decision about what forces to send,\u2019 Mattis said of Trump. \u2018He delegated not one bit of the strategy by the way. Not one bit. That is his and his alone.\u2019\u201d  Meanwhile, a U.S. airstrike in Helmand province kills several Afghan security forces, The New York Times reports.  KUSHNER DEFENDS HIS RUSSIA CONTACTS: \u2018I DID NOT COLLUDE,\u2019 reports POLITICO\u2019s Annie Karni: \u201cIn his first public defense of his meetings with Russian officials during Donald Trump\u2019s campaign and transition, Jared Kushner is presenting his encounters with those operatives as innocent interactions, according to testimony submitted ahead of a high-stakes, closed-door grilling session before the Senate Intelligence Committee on Monday.   \u201cIn an 11-page opening statement provided to reporters in advance of his 10 a.m. appointment with the panel, which is part of the ongoing investigation into possible collusion between Russian officials and the Trump campaign, Kushner \u2014 now a senior 7/24/2017 Kushner defends his Russia contacts: 'I did not collude, nor know of anyone else in the campaign who colluded, with any foreign government.\u2019\u201d  The full text of Kushner\u2019s prepared statement is here.  IT\u2019S MONDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING DEFENSE, where we're always on the lookout for tips, pitches and feedback. Email us at ghellman@politico.com, and follow on Twitter @greg_hellman, @morningdefense and @politicopro.  MORNING DEFENSE TRIVIA: Richard Streeter was the first to correctly recount that in World War II both the USS Tang and USS Tullibee were both sunk by their own torpedoes circling back on them.  Tune in Friday for this week\u2019s question.  DRIVING THE WEEK \u2014 HOUSE TAKES UP NATIONAL SECURITY APPROPRIATIONS PACKAGE: The House Rules Committee opens debate tonight on amendments to the \u201csecurity-bus\u201d package that combines four fiscal 2018 spending bills, including the Defense and Military Construction-Veterans Affairs measures. Last month, the House Appropriations Committee approved a $658.1 billion defense bill. Debate on the House floor will begin later this week. Here\u2019s a rundown of key amendments House Rules will consider for floor debate, including some that mirror those offered to the fiscal 2018 National Defense Authorization Act:  \u2014 PROHIBITING BRAC: Rep. John Ratcliffe (R-Texas) has offered an amendment that would prohibit the Defense Department from undertaking a new round of military base realignments and closures. The measure is in line with a provisions of the NDAA that would also prohibit a new BRAC.  \u2014 BORDER WALL: Rep. Ruben Gallego (D-Ariz.) has revived his amendment to reinstate a ban on funding President Donald Trump\u2019s promised border wall. The House Armed Services Committee adopted a ban in June in its NDAA markup, but in a procedural move the House Rules Committee stripped the provision without debate.  \u2014 GITMO: Rep. Jerry Nadler (D-N.Y.) has offered a proposal to strike a provision prohibiting DoD from building facilities in the U.S. to house detainees from the military prison at Guantanamo Bay, Cuba, and a second to prohibit their transfer to such prisons.  \u2014 PAKISTAN: Reps. Dave Trott (R-Mich.) and Ted Poe (R-Texas) each have amendments related to security aid to Pakistan. Trott\u2019s amendment would transfer $900 million for Pakistan to the Overseas Humanitarian, Disaster and Civic Aid account. And Poe\u2019s amendment would prohibit the department from using operations and maintenance funding in the country.  The amendments come following a Pentagon decision to withhold $50 million in \u201ccoalition support funds\u201d from Pakistan, potentially signaling a more hard-line approach by the Trump administration toward Islamabad, writes The Washington Post.  FURTHER READING: The House defense spending bill includes $28.6 billion in broad pots of money, known collectively as the National Defense Restoration Fund. Here's an earlier Pro Defense analysis on how appropriators use the unspecified funds to boost Pentagon spending and how that extra cash could be cut with a lower defense topline.  CONGRESS APPROACHES A DEFENSE BUDGET \u2018TRAIN WRECK,\u2019 our colleague Connor O\u2019Brien with a deep dive on the budget debate: \u201cCongressional defense hawks' efforts to boost military spending by tens of billions face a major problem: They run afoul of the law.  \u201cKey bills winding their way through the House and Senate would boost the Pentagon budget well beyond what they've been in recent years. They would even exceed proposals from President Donald Trump, who campaigned on a pledge to rebuild the armed forces.  \u201cBut the bills would exceed the limits imposed by a 2011 budget law that caps spending and mandated across-the-board cuts \u2014 known as sequestration \u2014 at the behest of fiscally conservative budget hawks seeking to rein in massive budget deficits.\u201d  ALSO THIS WEEK \u2014 SERVICE CHIEFS TALK SHOP: Air Force Chief of Staff Gen. David Goldfein takes part in an Air Force Association breakfast on Wednesday. And on Thursday, Army Chief of Staff Gen. Mark Milley speaks a National Press Club luncheon.  \u2014 HOUSE FOREIGN AFFAIRS COMMITTEE TALKS AUMF: The House Foreign Affairs Committee holds a hearing on Tuesday featuring former government and military officials to discuss a new Authorization for Use of Military Force against terrorism.  \u2014 SASC MULLS OPTIONS FOR 355-SHIP NAVY: The Senate Armed Services Seapower Subcommittee hears on Tuesday from top naval analysts on options for building a 355-ship Navy.  \u2014 SENATE FOREIGN RELATIONS EYES MAXIMUM PRESSURE ON NORTH KOREA: The Senate Foreign Relations Committee holds a hearing on Tuesday to assess the maximum pressure and engagement policy for North Korea, featuring Acting Assistant Secretary of State of the Bureau of East Asian and Pacific Affairs Susan Thornton.  And Americans should be prepared for the possibility of a military confrontation with North Korea, Joint Chiefs Chairman Gen. Joe Dunford suggests at a forum hosted by the Aspen Institute on Saturday, POLITICO\u2019s Nahal Toosi adds.  Meanwhile, the U.S.\u2019 next missile intercept test could come as soon as next weekend, the Coast Guard says, via the AP.  HAPPENING TODAY \u2014 HOUSE TAKES UP INTEL BILL, BUT DEMS COULD SINK IT: The House is set to vote today on annual intelligence policy legislation, but House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi is urging her fellow Democrats to kill the legislation.   In a letter to Democrats Sunday, Pelosi said the bill itself isn't problematic, but blasted Republicans for bringing the legislation to the floor under suspension of the rules, an expedited process without amendments that requires a two-thirds majority. Pelosi asked Democrats to defeat the bill "so that we can take it up under a rule" and amendments can be offered.  \u2014 KUSHNER FACES CONGRESS, via The Washington Post: \u201c[Jared] Kushner is scheduled to meet behind closed doors with the Senate Intelligence Committee [today], then be questioned \u2014 again in private \u2014 by the House Intelligence Committee the following day.\u201d  SENATE PANEL MARKS UP GI BILL EXPANSION WEDNESDAY, reports our colleague Michael Stratford: \u201cThe Senate Veterans\u2019 Affairs Committee will hold a vote [this] week on the bipartisan legislation to expand educational benefits under the GI Bill, according to Chairman Johnny Isakson\u2019s office.  "The committee will mark up the bill ... July 26 without making any amendments, Isakson spokeswoman Amanda Maddox said. The legislation is identical to the bill approved [last] week by the House Veterans Affairs Committee.\u201d  2016 PRIMARY RIVAL URGES MCCAIN TO STEP ASIDE, via The Washington Post: \u201cA day after news came out about Sen. John McCain\u2019s (R-Ariz.) brain cancer diagnosis, his onetime political opponent urged the ailing senator to think about his political future sooner rather than later \u2014 and expressed interest in the possibility of her taking over his Senate seat.  \u201c\u2018I hope Sen. McCain is going to look long and hard at this, that his family and his advisers are going to look at this, and they\u2019re going to advise him to step away as quickly as possible, so that the business of the country and the business of Arizona being represented at the federal level can move forward,\u2019 Kelli Ward, who lost to McCain in last year\u2019s Republican primary and is now running to unseat U.S. Sen. Jeff Flake (R-Ariz.), said Thursday during an interview with an Indiana radio station.\u201d  CONGRESS REACHES RUSSIA SANCTIONS DEAL, report POLITICO\u2019s Elana Schor and Heather Caygle: \u201cNegotiators in both parties on Saturday released a sweeping sanctions deal that does not include changes President Donald Trump's administration sought to make it easier for him to ease penalties against Russia.  \u201cThe accord on a package of sanctions against Russia, Iran and North Korea is set for a House vote on Tuesday, according to the announcement from Majority Leader Kevin McCarthy's office. To resolve a partisan clash over giving House Democrats the power to force a vote blocking Trump from easing sanctions on Moscow, the deal expedites House consideration of any anti-Trump vote that the Senate has already passed.\u201d  But the European Commission plans to hit back \u201cwithin days\u201d at the United States if possible new sanctions leave European energy and other companies vulnerable to U.S. interference, adds POLITICO\u2019s Ryan Heath.  WAR REPORT \u2014 U.S. SOUGHT YPG REBRAND, SOCOM COMMANDER SAYS, via your Morning D correspondent. The United States urged the Syrian Kurds\u2019 YPG, to rebrand themselves because of alleged links to the PKK, a designating terrorist group operating inside Turkey, Gen. Raymond Thomas, the commander of U.S. Special Operations Command, said at the Aspen Security Forum Friday.  The YPG currently fights under the umbrella of the Syrian Democratic Forces.  \u201cThey were formerly called the YPG, who the Turks would say equated to the PKK, you\u2019re dealing with a terrorist enemy of mine,\u201d Thomas said. \u201cWe literally replied back to them and said you got to change your brand,\u201d he added.  And Assad-aligned forces recapture territory outside Raqqa from ISIS, reports Reuters.  THE U.S. MILITARY IS \u2018BIGGER, BETTER, STRONGER,' the president says at the commissioning of the USS Gerald R. Ford, via CBS News: \u201cPresident Trump officially commissioned the U.S. Navy's newest and largest aircraft carrier, the USS Gerald R. Ford, in Norfolk, Virginia, on Saturday, applauding the military's strength.  "\u2019When it comes to battle, we don't want a fair fight. We demand victory, and we will have total victory, believe me,\u2019 Mr. Trump said of the powerful aircraft carrier \u2026  While Mr. Trump urged military members to call their members of Congress and ask them to support his budget, he noted the ongoing health care debate as well, telling service members, \u2018you can also call those senators to make sure you get health care.\u2019\u201d  Afterward, HASC ranking Democrat Adam Smith of Washington state blistered the president for politicizing the military.  \u201cI condemn President Trump\u2019s remarks. We need to be one-hundred percent clear that it is utterly beyond the pale for the commander-in-chief to publicly tell members of the armed services that they should lobby Congress on his behalf,\u201d Smith said in a written statement. \u201cDoing so, puts them in an untenable position and disrespects their longstanding professional practices as well as their duty to remain apolitical. President Trump has done this before, and he cannot be allowed to keep doing it.\u201d  Meanwhile, major questions remain about the Navy\u2019s newest aircraft carrier, CNBC adds.  INDUSTRY INTEL \u2014 TINY SATELLITES LAUNCH SPACE REVOLUTION, writes Bloomberg Businessweek: \u201cA good rocket launch site has a few important characteristics. An unpopulated patch of land near an ocean is preferable, so no one gets showered with wayward bits of flaming metal. It\u2019s also nice if it\u2019s on the equator\u2014like all spheres rotating on an axis, the Earth spins fastest in the middle, which provides rocket boosters with extra oomph. In other words, the best sites tend to be in remote, tropical locations. That such places are also often among the world\u2019s poorest gives many launches a counterintuitive feel: billions of dollars in futuristic machinery rising up over rainforests and shantytowns.\u201d  \u2014 TRUMP ISSUES INDUSTRIAL BASE ORDER, reports Greg: \u201cPresident Donald Trump today issued an executive order directing a "whole of government" review of the defense industrial base. The order directs Defense Secretary Jim Mattis, along with other cabinet departments, to produce a report within 270 days identifying the materials and goods critical to national security; threats to their supply; and assessing the resiliency and capacity of the manufacturing base.\u201d  SPEED READ  \u2014 Trump incorrectly accuses The New York Times of foiling an anti-Islamic State operation: NYT  \u2014 Countering China in the Indian Ocean proves a tall order for Japan and India: The Wall Street Journal  \u2014 China\u2019s Foreign Minister Wang Yi says his country wants to \u201cmaintain stability\u201d in the South China Sea and seeks alliances: Reuters  \u2014 Former spy chiefs John Brennan and Jim Clapper tear into Trump over Russia: POLITICO  \u2014 ISIS came dangerously close to getting a \u201cdirty bomb\u201d in Mosul: The Washington Post  \u2014 Exhaustion and discouragement proliferate among U.S. Marines in Afghanistan: CNN  \u2014 The fierce conflict against the Islamic State in Khorasan is scattering fighters across a wider swath of the mountainous east Afghanistan, ensuring a longer, more dispersed mission: The Washington Post  \u2014 The U.S. is hoping the fledgling Afghan Air Force will provide an advantage in the war against the Taliban: Reuters  \u2014 Iran and Iraq sign an agreement to boost their anti-terrorism cooperation: Reuters  \u2014 After its victory in Mosul, Iraq\u2019s leaders mull the future of Shiite militias who helped win the fight: AP  \u2014 Speed and range could be key for the Navy\u2019s next fighter jet: Defense News  \u2014 How soon could terrorists send armed drones across the Atlantic to the U.S.? Defense One  \u2014 The Justice Department charges an Army sergeant stationed in Hawaii with trying to provide equipment, training and classified military information to ISIS: NYT  \u2014 A deadly shooting at Israel's Embassy in Jordan further complicates Israel\u2019s efforts to find a way out of an escalating crisis over Jerusalem's most contested holy site: AP  \u2014 The U.S. special envoy to Ukraine pins blame for the conflict on Russia: Reuters  \u2014 Why Ukraine forces gave up Crimea without a fight - and NATO says it\u2019s on alert: Reuters  \u2014 A dozen U.S. paratroopers are injured in a night jump in Romania: AP  \u2014 Britain approves 283m of arms sales to Saudi Arabia in the six months after a Saudi airstrike on a funeral that killed scores of people: The Guardian  \u2014 In New Hampshire, health care providers blast the Veterans Choice Program for excess bureaucracy: New Hampshire Union Leader  \u2014 Air Force Secretary Heather Wilson objects to Yucca Mountain nuclear waste routes: Las Vegas Review-Journal  \u2014 Summit for Soldiers aims to save veterans from suicide through outdoors activity: Casper Star-Tribune  \u2014 Veterans\u2019 groups oppose a House plan to shore up the Veterans Choice Program through other VA cuts: AP  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
