aV \u000a            By THEODORIC MEYER  08/03/2017 02:00 PM EDT  With David Beavers and Aubree Eliza Weaver  SAUDI LOBBYING CONTRACT ENDED THE DAY CROWN PRINCE WAS DEPOSED: When the Saudi Ministry of the Interior signed a $5.4 million lobbying contract in May with SPG, a Washington lobbying firm, it was viewed as the latest move in a power struggle between Crown Prince Mohammed bin Nayef, who controlled the ministry, and King Salman\u2019s son, Deputy Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman. New documents filed with DOJ confirm that view. SPG\u2019s contract with the Saudi Interior Ministry ended on June 21, the same day Mohammed bin Nayef was ousted and just 38 days after it was signed, the filing shows. Because SPG\u2019s contract stipulated that the ministry pay the $5.4 million fee upfront, though, the firm gets to keep the money.  Story Continued Below  \u2014 \u201cSPG was excited about working with the Saudi Interior Ministry to help combat violent extremism,\u201d the firm said in a statement. \u201cDue to internal circumstances in the Kingdom our contract was truncated and SPG was unable to implement our unique strategic services \u2014 including our creative SPG Studios communications, branding, marketing and public relations offerings \u2014 on their behalf. We look forward to again working with our vital ally Saudi Arabia and bringing our global reach to the fold as we do for all our clients."  PODESTA GROUP NO LONGER LOBBYING FOR IRAQ: The Podesta Group is no longer representing Iraq in Washington, according to a DOJ filing. An Iraqi official who spoke on condition of anonymity told Al-Monitor, a Washington-based news outlet that covers the Middle East, that budget cuts had forced Iraq to scrap its contract with the Podesta Group as well as Brownstein Hyatt Farber Schreck. With \u201cthe glut in the oil crisis [and] the cost of war [against the Islamic State] the government took measures to reduce financing for certain activities for Iraqi ministries in general and that directly affected us," the official told Al-Monitor. "So we had to cut the spending for the lobbying efforts for the time being.\u201d Neither firm immediately responded to a request for comment.  BOCKORNY GROUP SIGNS TARGET: Target has hired the Bockorny Group to lobby on tax and labor issues. The hire appears to be part of a broader shakeup of Target\u2019s lobbying team. Target had previously retained Jochum Shore & Trossevin and Ogilvy Government Relations, according to disclosure records. But Target parted ways with Jochum Shore earlier this year and with Ogilvy at the end of June. The Minneapolis-based retailer spent $210,000 on Washington lobbying in the second quarter.  Good afternoon, and welcome to PI. I\u2019ve been writing PI for six months now. How can make I can make it better in the next six months? Send me your gripes, your suggestions, your ideas \u2014 and, as always, your tips: tmeyer@politico.com. You can also follow me on Twitter: @theodoricmeyer.  ADMINISTRATION WON\u2019T MAKE RULE CHANGE THAT ICAHN WANTED: \u201cThe Trump administration plans to reject a proposal that would let oil refiners off the hook for complying with the federal ethanol mandate, a senior administration official told POLITICO, dashing the hopes of billionaire Carl Icahn and a slew of independent companies,\u201d POLITICO\u2019s Eric Wolff reports. It\u2019s \u201ca severe blow for Icahn, a longtime associate and early supporter of Donald Trump who owns the refiner CVR Energy. He was once so confident that the obligation would be changed that he tried to strike a deal with a biofuels trade association.\u201d Full story.   GOLDMAN LOBBIES UP IN FLORIDA: \u201cGoldman Sachs is expanding its political footprint in Florida as its investment ties to Venezuela \u2014 and the broader business community\u2019s connections to the troubled Latin American nation \u2014 draw increasing scrutiny from state lawmakers,\u201d POLITICO Florida\u2019s Matt Dixon reports. \u201cThe firm has hired its first Florida contract lobbying firm and registered in-house lobbyists to advocate with the Scott administration and state Senate. And it\u2019s already met with Gov. Rick Scott to discuss brewing efforts to ban Florida business with the country.\u201d  \u2014 \u201cThe advocacy ramp-up comes as Venezuelan President Nicols Maduro \u2014 who has suppressed pro-democracy rallies and last weekend won an election White House officials called a 'sham' \u2014 faces increased pressure from Scott and others. Goldman purchased $2.8 billion in bonds issued by Venezuela\u2019s state-owned oil company in May, a move that received vocal criticism from both state and federal lawmakers, including U.S. Sen. Marco Rubio. But it was a July 5 announcement from Scott\u2019s office that the governor was mulling a plan to 'prohibit the state of Florida from doing business' with businesses that benefit the Maduro regime that caught Goldman\u2019s attention.\u201d Full story.  RUSSELL GROUP SIGNS ABBOTT: Abbott Laboratories has added the Russell Group to its stable of Washington lobbyists. Abbott, which spent $860,000 on Washington lobbying in the second quarter, also retains BGR Government Affairs, Chamber Hill Strategies, Forbes Tate, Mayer Brown, OFW Law, Polaris Government Relations, Thorn Run Partners and W Strategies.  ZUCKERBERG HIRES BENENSON: \u201cFacebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg and his wife, Priscilla Chan, have hired Democratic pollster Joel Benenson, a former top adviser to President Barack Obama and the chief strategist for Hillary Clinton\u2019s failed 2016 presidential campaign, as a consultant, according to a person familiar with the hire,\u201d POLITICO\u2019s Annie Karni reports. \u201cBenenson\u2019s company, Benenson Strategy Group, will be conducting research for the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, the couple\u2019s philanthropy. \u2026 Benenson\u2019s involvement in the group gives them access to someone who was one of the top lieutenants of Clinton\u2019s doomed campaign and Obama\u2019s longtime pollster, just as speculation about Zuckerberg\u2019s political ambitions is mounting.\u201d Full story.  DON\u2019T \u2018PARROT COMMANDS OF SPECIAL INTERESTS,\u2019 BERNHARDT WARNS: \u201cInterior Deputy Secretary David Bernhardt, a former [Brownstein Hyatt Farber Schreck] lobbyist, believes a few bad apples within the department have \u2018forgotten their oath\u2019 and \u2018choose to parrot comments of special interests rather than carry out their governmental duties to move the country forward,\u2019 he told employees in an introductory email sent after he was sworn in Tuesday,\u201d POLITICO\u2019s Esther Whieldon reports. \u201c\u2018By doing so, they often avoid grounding their views in the actual facts or the law. Such conduct is arbitrary. It is lazy. We must always refrain from taking such a path,\u2019 Bernhardt wrote in the email,\u201d obtained by POLITICO. Full story.  BIODIESEL TRADE GROUP LOSES TWO: \u201cThe National Biodiesel Board, which is based in Missouri, is losing two of its three Washington staffers,\u201d per Morning Energy. \u201cAnne Steckel, the head of the D.C. office, and Sandra Franco, the head of regulatory affairs and general counsel, are both leaving the group, NBB spokesperson Rosemarie Calabro Tully told ME. Chief Operating Officer Doug Whitehead will come to D.C. to run the office. The move comes at an awkward time, as lobbying is ramping up to get a biodiesel producers tax credit into any future tax overhaul bill, the group's members want EPA to increase the biodiesel requirements in the Renewable Fuel Standard, and they're looking to the Commerce Department to slap sanctions on Argentina and Indonesia.\u201d Steckel was the group\u2019s only registered lobbyist, according to disclosure reports.  JOBS REPORT  \u2014 The Clyde Group has promoted Aubrey Quinn to senior vice president. The firm has also hired Sasha Bennett as a senior associate and Daniel Cummins as a junior associate. Bennett previously worked for Edelman and Cummins previously worked for Hillary Clinton\u2019s campaign.  \u2014 LEVICK has promoted Jennifer Tong to vice president from director.  NEW JOINT FUNDRAISERS:  None  NEW PACs:  Redemption PAC (Leadership PAC: Rep. Clay Higgins)  NEW LOBBYING REGISTRATIONS:  A1.9 Strategies LLC: Analogic CorporationAtrio Consulting Group, LLC: National Border Patrol CouncilBarnes & Thornburg, LLP: Alcoa CorporationBockorny Group, Inc.: Job Creators NetworkBockorny Group, Inc.: Majestic Steel USABockorny Group, Inc.: Target CorporationCrossroads Strategies, LLC: Alitheon, Inc.Dentons US LLP: The CDL SchoolDowns Government Affairs: Delaware Technical Community CollegeFairvote: FairvoteFranklin Creek Consulting: Muscogee Creek NationFranklin Creek Consulting: Stockbridge Munsee Mohican CommunityHaka: RaytheonHenderson Strategies, Inc.: Wildlife ComputersJ M Burkman & Associates: Brightmind Labs Inc.Sagely Solutions LLC: King-Devick Technologies, Inc.Shumaker Advisors Florida, LLC: Regenerative Processing Plant, LLCSMW Partners, LLC: Marks and Sokolov, LLC on behalf of Igor KolomoiskyThe Glover Park Group LLC: John Hopkins UniversityThe Russell Group, Inc.: AbbottWilliams and Jensen, PLLC: US-Mexico Business Coalition  NEW LOBBYING TERMINATIONS:  Ott Bielitzki & O'Neill PLLC: Interlink Electronics, IncOtt Bielitzki & O'Neill PLLC: Secure SystemThe OB-C Group. LLC: Alliance of Marine Mammals Parks and Aquariums  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
