aV \u000a            By THEODORIC MEYER  08/02/2017 02:30 PM EDT  With David Beavers and Aubree Eliza Weaver  CHAMBER HILL ADDS WEINSTEIN: Anna Weinstein has left the Podesta Group for Chamber Hill Strategies, where she\u2019ll be a principal. Her clients at Podesta included the American Health Care Association, BMO Financial and Mylan, the pharmaceutical company, as a subcontractor to Hogan Lovells. Before joining Podesta, she worked as a lobbyist for the Biotechnology Innovation Organization.  Story Continued Below  NEW AD ATTACKS CORDRAY: A secretive group called Protect America\u2019s Consumers dedicated to opposing the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau is out with a new ad attacking Richard Cordray, the agency\u2019s director. The ad, posted on the group\u2019s YouTube page on Tuesday, says that Cordray is rumored to be running for Ohio governor next year, citing a POLITICO story. The ad\u2019s narrator accuses Cordray of using \u201chis power at the CFPB to issue a new regulation that will massively benefit potential donors: the trial lawyers.\u201d The ad directs viewers to cordray2018.com, a fake campaign site set up by the group. The group, which ran a similar ad last year, didn\u2019t respond to a request for comment on where and when the ad will be running. (The ad was spotted by Allied Progress, a liberal research group.)  \u2014 PI\u2019s Isaac Arnsdorf dug into who was behind the group last year when it first emerged. Here\u2019s what he found: \u201cThe campaign is being run by Lincoln Strategy Group, a political consulting firm in Tempe, Ariz. Its founder, Nathan Sproul, has been linked to several instances of suspected voter fraud and barred from Republican Party contracts. The company also worked with Steve Gates, the only person previously identified with Protect America's Consumers, on the American Coalition for Clean Coal Electricity's 2009 \u2018astroturf\u2019 campaign, when it was busted for sending fake letters to Congress.\u201d  \u2014 \u201cAt a field hearing on the CFPB's arbitration rule earlier this month in Albuquerque, N.M., a man who identified himself as Chuck Bowman rose to challenge the agency's director, Richard Cordray, on whether the policy would enrich trial lawyers and if he'll renounce support from trial lawyers in a future run for governor or attorney general. The moderator cut him off because the comment forum was not a Q&A. The outburst echoed Protect America's Consumers' talking points, replete with a website posing as Cordray running for office in Ohio. \u2026 \u2018Chuck Bowman\u2019 is most likely Chuck Coolidge, a partner at Lincoln Strategy Group, based on their likenesses.\u201d  MONUMENT SIGNS FRANCHISE ASSOCIATION: The International Franchise Association has added Monument Policy Group to its clutch of Washington lobbying firms. John Mulligan, T.A. Hawks and Ashley Hoy of Monument will lobby for the association, according to a disclosure filing. The association \u2014 which spent a relatively modest $110,000 on lobbying in the second quarter \u2014 also retains Geoffrey P. Gray, Mercury and Prime Policy Group.  Good afternoon, and welcome to PI. Tips: tmeyer@politico.com. Twitter: @theodoricmeyer.  COREY\u2019S NEW GIG: Corey Lewandowski has a new firm, The New York Times\u2019 Nicholas Confessore and Kenneth P. Vogel report. \u201cMr. Lewandowski started his new business, Lewandowski Strategic Advisors, in May, according to corporate documents filed in Delaware, eight days after he announced he would part ways with the Washington lobbying firm he helped found, Avenue Strategies. Mr. Lewandowski has recently discussed expanding the new firm by adding, among others, two more Trump insiders \u2014 the former Trump deputy campaign manager David Bossie and George Gigicos, who stepped down Monday as Mr. Trump\u2019s White House advance director \u2014 according to two associates.  \u2014 \u201cAmong the first new clients of Lewandowski Strategic Advisors is an Ohio-based company called Community Choice Financial. The company is a leader in the payday lending industry, which has faced heightened federal scrutiny in recent years.\u201d Full story.  TRUMP\u2019S CEO PANEL HASN\u2019T DONE MUCH: What has President Donald Trump\u2019s advisory panel of chief executives done since he took office? Elon Musk of Tesla and Bob Iger of Disney have quit in protest. But otherwise \u201cthere\u2019s been little activity for the strategy and policy forum and the manufacturing group, according to people familiar with the matter who asked not to be identified,\u201d Bloomberg News\u2019 Matthew Townsend, Shannon Pettypiece and Joe Deaux report. \u201cAfter initial meetings early in Trump\u2019s presidency \u2014 which the White House promoted with great fanfare \u2014 his administration hasn\u2019t convened the groups for months or set firm dates for future meetings, according to the people.\u201d Full story.  MORE BUSINESS FOR KIT: Former Sen. Kit Bond (R-Mo.) will lobby for the St. Louis Zoo Association, according to a disclosure filing. It\u2019s Kit Bond Strategies\u2019 first new client in more than a year.  WHAT OUTSIDE GROUPS ARE SPENDING ON TAX REFORM: \u201cConservative and business-aligned advocacy groups plan to spend millions of dollars boosting tax reform in August, part of a coordinated effort with the White House and lawmakers to avoid the mistakes made during the bruising attempt to repeal Obamacare,\u201d POLITICO\u2019s Nancy Cook reports. Consider the ad buys that have already been announced. \u201cThe American Action Network announced on Monday that it planned to spend $5 million in August alone \u2014 when lawmakers are usually back in their districts \u2014 and more than $20 million total on a tax push. The Business Roundtable, a group that represents CEOs of major companies, and the Koch-backed Americans for Prosperity have also pledged to spend millions on TV and radio ads and social media campaigns and ensuring grass-roots turnout at town halls over the congressional recess. They would not confirm the exact amounts they will spend.\u201d Full story.  MORE MONEY, FEWER LOBBYISTS: \u201cOverall spending for the first six months of 2017 amounts to $1.66 billion \u2014 the highest it has been since the first half of 2012, which was followed by a roughly $50 million drop in 2013,\u201d OpenSecrets Blog\u2019s Sara Swann reports. \u201cHowever, while money has been pouring in, the number of lobbyists has been dwindling. Since the first quarter of this year, approximately 940 stopped lobbying, but 605 new lobbyists entered the fray. This ebb and flow brought the total number of active lobbyists for the second quarter to 9,460 \u2014 335 less than the first quarter.\u201d Full story.   IF YOU MISSED IT: Sen. Ben Sasse (R-Neb.) isn\u2019t interested in quitting the Senate \u2014 at least not to run the Heritage Foundation, POLITICO\u2019s Eliana Johnson reports. \u201cSasse, who was elected to his first term in the Senate in 2014, has swatted down the overtures from Heritage\u2019s board of trustees, according to two sources familiar with the recruitment effort.\u201d Heritage\u2019s previous president, former Sen. Jim DeMint (R-S.C.), left the Senate in 2013 to take the helm at Heritage. Full story.  JOBS REPORT  \u2014 Sidley Austin has added Jim Lowe as a partner in its Washington office, where he\u2019ll be a member of the antitrust and competition practice. Lowe was previously a partner working in a similar capacity at WilmerHale and also worked in the Justice Department\u2019s antitrust division in the 1990s.  \u2014 ManattJones Global Strategies, a subsidiary of the law firm Manatt, Phelps & Phillips, is breaking away under a new name, Monarch Global Strategies. It\u2019s led by Jim Jones, a former U.S. ambassador to Mexico, and Michael Camuez, a former Commerce Department assistant secretary, and will have offices in Mexico City; Monterrey, Mexico; Los Angeles; and Washington.   NEW JOINT FUNDRAISERS:  Davidson Victory Fund (Rep. Warren Davidson, On Azimuth PAC, NRCC)  NEW PACs:  Dougle Eagle PAC (Leadership PAC: Rep. Steve Knight)Jersey Values PAC (Leadership PAC: Rep. Josh Gottheimer)  NEW LOBBYING REGISTRATIONS:  AWPC Federal Affairs: Oksana BrodovskaHealy Consulting Group: Huguley Consulting LLCHealy Consulting Group: Sixteen Thirty FundHobart Hallaway & Quayle Ventures, LLC: Techshot, Inc.Kit Bond Strategies: St. Louis Zoo AssociationLeBlanc Government Relations, LLC: Crossroads Strategies on behalf of Alitheon, Inc.McDermott Will & Emery LLP: IFO Group, LLCMonument Policy Group, LLC: International Franchise AssociationNorth South Government Strategies f/k/a JDM Public Strategies, LLC: Smiths GroupThe McManus Group: Horizon PharmaWilliams and Jensen, PLLC: Indivior, Inc.Wisconsin Hospital Association: Wisconsin Hospital Association  NEW LOBBYING TERMINATIONS:  Bockorny Group, Inc.: 21st Century FoxChamber Hill Strategies: Amag Pharmaceuticals (Formerly Known As Lumara Pharmaceutical)Chamber Hill Strategies: National Association for the Support of Long Term CareFranklin Creek Consulting: Hickory Ground Tribal Town of the Muscogee Creek Nation of Oklahoma  CORRECTION:  A previous version of PI misstated the list of fitms who lobby for the Interrnational Franchise Association. The Prism Group lobbies for the International Pizza Hut Franchise Holders Association.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
