aV \u000a            By THEODORIC MEYER  08/01/2017 02:20 PM EDT  With David Beavers, Aubree Eliza Weaver and Lorraine Woellert  FIRST IN PI \u2014 K&L GATES HIRES FORMER MURKOWSKI AIDE: K&L Gates is adding Amanda Makki, a former health policy adviser to Sen. Lisa Murkowski (R-Alaska), as a partner. Makki was previously a lobbyist for Novo Nordisk and before that worked for Murkowski for more than seven years. She was a top aide to Murkowski, a member of the Senate HELP Committee, during the fight over the legislation that became the Affordable Care Act. \u201cI would say that I know Alaska\u2019s health care landscape better than most,\u201d Makki said in an interview.  Story Continued Below  \u2014 Now that she\u2019s at K&L Gates, Makki said she expects to lobby on whatever \u201chappens with any kind of repeal-and-replace effort\u201d \u2014 a fight in which Murkowski, one of three senators who brought down Senate Republicans\u2019 \u201cskinny repeal\u201d bill last week, will almost certainly be a critical vote. She also plans to work on drug pricing, medical device reimbursement, Medicare Part D, health care appropriations and provider payment and audit issues.  FIRST IN PI \u2014 SPG SIGNS AFGHANISTAN: The Afghan government has hired a Washington lobbying firm. SPG, a firm that\u2019s worked to cultivate a reputation as a go-to for foreign governments in President Donald Trump\u2019s Washington, signed a three-month contract with Afghanistan on Monday worth $40,000 a month. SPG will provide \u201cExecutive Branch and legislative engagement,\u201d \u201cdefense consultation,\u201d \u201cstrategic advice pertaining to extremism/terrorism\u201d and \u201cpromotion of democracy and foreign direct investment,\u201d according to the contract. The firm appears to be the Afghan government\u2019s first registered lobbying firm in Washington, according to DOJ filings; an Afghan political party had previously hired two Washington firms in 2014.  \u2014 SPG has signed the Czech, Kenyan and New Zealand governments since it began an aggressive expansion in Washington after the election, as well as the Korea International Trade Association and a Saudi government ministry loyal to the now-deposed Crown Prince Mohammed bin Nayef.  Good afternoon, and welcome to PI. Today marks six months since I took over writing Influence. Thanks so much to everyone who\u2019s shared tips large and small, taken my phone calls and shared lobbying gossip over Manhattans. I couldn\u2019t write PI every day without you. Please keep the tips coming: tmeyer@politico.com. You can also follow me on Twitter: @theodoricmeyer.  \u2014 What do you want to see from PI in the next six months? What are we covering too much and what are we missing? What have we gotten wrong? I\u2019d love your feedback. Be brutal: tmeyer@politico.com.  HOW LOBBYISTS WROTE A MEDICAL-MALPRACTICE BILL: \u201cFor two years, lobbyists for doctors and their insurers met regularly around a conference table a few blocks from the Capitol to draft an overhaul of the nation\u2019s medical malpractice laws,\u201d The Washington Post\u2019s Kimberly Kindy reports. \u201cThe resulting legislation proposed strict limits on damages for some plaintiffs and sharply lower fees for their attorneys. Last month, with no public hearings and few modifications, the House voted to approve the measure \u2014 outraging victims\u2019 rights advocates, who accused lawmakers of acting in secret to slam the courtroom door on people who have been grievously injured by doctors.\u201d  \u2014 \u201cIt isn\u2019t unusual for industry stakeholders to draft legislation. But in this case, lobbyists were able to rapidly shepherd their bill to House passage with minimal input from the public or even members of Congress. Lobbyists then crowed about the achievement, boasting that the House-passed measure was nearly identical to one they provided to the House Judiciary Committee and that Rep. Steve King (R-Iowa) introduced on Feb. 24. \u2018There wasn\u2019t a dramatic change in how we wrote it,\u2019 said Mike Stinson, a lobbyist for the Physician Insurers Association of America. But, he added, \u2018there are always some tweaks.\u2019\u201d Full story.  TECH COMPANIES FIGHTING HUMAN TRAFFICKING BILL: \u201cThe likes of Amazon, Facebook and Google are about to go to war with the U.S. Congress over the most unlikely of causes: human trafficking,\u201d Recode\u2019s Tony Romm reports. \u201cA new bill by Republican Sen. Rob Portman \u2014 backed by 19 other lawmakers from both parties \u2014 would open the door for state attorneys general and victims alike to take legal action against social networks, review websites, advertisers and others that don\u2019t do enough to combat users who post exploitative content. But the proposal is already drawing opposition from Silicon Valley, where tech companies want to put an end to human trafficking \u2014 but don\u2019t want to do so in a way that also subjects them to new lawsuits.\u201d Full story.  CLARK HILL SIGNS UNITED LAUNCH ALLIANCE: The United Launch Alliance, a joint spaceflight venture between Lockheed Martin and Boeing, has added Clark Hill to its stable of lobbying firms. Kevin Kelly, Charlie Spies, Jasper Thomson and Lauren Lipin will lobby for the alliance on space-related legislation, policies and funding, according to a disclosure filing. The United Launch Alliance is a significant lobbying force in Washington, shelling out $460,000 in the second quarter. The alliance also has FTI Government Affairs, the Madison Group, the S-3 Group, Shank Public Policy and Theodore Kronmiller on retainer.  WHERE THEY ARE NOW: Roll Call\u2019s Kyle Stewart and Griffin Connolly have a rundown of what the 61 lawmakers who left the Hill after the 114th Congress are up to now. Just four have become lobbyists: former Sen. David Vitter (R-La.) and former Reps. Charles Boustany (R-La.), Ander Crenshaw (R-Fla.) and Jeff Miller (R-Fla.). Former House Speaker John Boehner is a senior strategic adviser at Squire Patton Boggs but hasn\u2019t registered as a lobbyist, and former Rep. Mike Fitzpatrick (R-Pa.) is a partner at the Pennsylvania law firm Obermayer Rebmann Maxwell & Hippel but isn\u2019t lobbying, either. Former Rep. Reid Ribble (R-Wis.) is the only former member to join a trade association. He\u2019s the chief executive of the National Roofing Contractors Association but isn\u2019t part of its lobbying team.  STOLEN EMAILS CAST UNFLATTERING LIGHT ON EMIRATI AMBASSADOR: \u201cYousef Al Otaiba, the United Arab Emirates ambassador to the U.S., is a high-profile power player in Washington, trying to shape American policy toward the Middle East and lobbying over a regional dispute with Qatar,\u201d The Wall Street Journal\u2019s Bradley Hope and Tom Wright report. \u201cHe\u2019s also being drawn deeper into a major global corruption scandal. Newly released stolen emails show a long-running relationship between Mr. Otaiba and Jho Low, a Malaysian financier who U.S. law-enforcement officials say is at the center of the misappropriation of $4.5 billion from a Malaysian state development fund.  \u2014 \u201cThat relationship is drawing new scrutiny from U.S., Swiss and Singaporean authorities, according to people familiar with the probes. The stolen emails show Mr. Otaiba and Shaher Awartani, his Jordanian partner, discussing inquiries from those countries about transactions they received from entities investigators say is connected to Mr. Low. In one email, Mr. Awartani suggested buying a Ferrari after what Mr. Otaiba described as a \u2018transfer from Jho.\u2019\u201d Full story.  FIRST FILINGS: Dickinson Wright\u2019s Teddy Eynon and Patrick Anderson, who joined the firm in May from Fox Rothschild, filed their first trio of registrations with their new firm. The pair will lobby for Firetrace International, an Arizona-based manufacturer of fire suppression systems, on defense authorization and Pentagon appropriations; for Gulf Coast Waste Disposal Authority on the Sustainable Water Investment Act; and for U-Wrap, a Miami-based luggage protection company, on Transportation Security Administration regulations, per disclosure filings.   JOBS REPORT  \u2014 Milan Dilal is leaving the Hill to join Brownstein Hyatt Farber Schreck as counsel. He was previously a senior economic adviser to Sen. Mark Warner (D-Va.).  \u2014 Jake Ward is stepping down as president and chief executive of the Developers Alliance, with Bruce Gustafson taking his place. Gustafson was previously a senior policy adviser to the alliance.   \u2014 The Government Affairs Industry Network has tapped Hannah Page-Salisbury of the Brunswick Group as its next secretary and chairwoman of the communications committee.  \u2014 \u201cWal-Mart hired Christian Gomez, Jr. as senior manager for global government affairs, with a focus on Latin America,\u201d per Playbook. \u201cHe was previously economic growth adviser at USAID and is a Council of the Americas alum.\u201d  NEW JOINT FUNDRAISERS:  Gillibrand McCaskill Senate 2018 (Sens. Kirsten Gillibrand and Claire McCaskill)  NEW PACs:  5th Wave (Unknown)People Over Party (Super PAC)  NEW LOBBYING REGISTRATIONS:  Clark Hill, PLC: United Launch AllianceClark Hill, PLC: University of Maryland, BaltimoreDentons US LLP: EchoStar CorporationDickinson Wright PLLC: Firetrace InternationalDickinson Wright PLLC: Gulf Coast Waste Disposal AuthorityDickinson Wright PLLC: U-WrapHogan Lovells US LLP: HeartFlow, Inc.Hogan Lovells US LLP: Lloyd's America, Inc.Key Impact Strategies: Hammack, Barry, Thaggard, & May, LLPKey Impact Strategies: Housing Assistance CouncilKey Impact Strategies: NVG, LLC (on behalf of The Reinvestment Fund)Key Impact Strategies: Renaissance Community Loan FundLungren Lopina LLC: The Conafay Group LLC (on behalf of the Antibiotics Working Group)Nancy Zirkin: The Leadership Conference on Civil and Human RightsPodesta Group, Inc.: 1890 Universities FoundationPodesta Group, Inc.: One Concern, Inc.Silent Majority Strategies LLC: Fountain Quail Energy Services, LLCZirkelbach Strategies: AMAG Pharmaceuticals  NEW LOBBYING TERMINATIONS:  Capitol Resources LLC: Tenax AerospaceChamber Hill Strategies: American Academy of Adoption AttorneysChamber Hill Strategies: GlaxoSmithKline, Inc.MoeVela LLC: DeVry Education Group Inc.Muzin Capitol Partners LLC: Biniatta Trade LPRuth White: Covenant HouseSubject Matter (fka Elmendorf Ryan): CTIA - The Wireless AssociationThe Russell Group, Inc.: Catfish Farmers of America  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
