aV \u000a            By THEODORIC MEYER  07/28/2017 02:25 PM EDT  With David Beavers, Aubree Eliza Weaver and Aaron Lorenzo  INSIDE THE LONG LOBBYING PUSH FOR TERRORISM VICTIMS' FAMILIES: Sharp-eyed PI readers might recall that three of the 10 biggest lobbying contracts of the second quarter that we compiled last Friday were for a single client, Victims of Terrorism - East Africa. McGuireWoods Consulting brought in $600,000 from its Victims of Terrorism work, making it the third-largest contract of the quarter, and Monument Policy Group and Morris J. Amitay each brought in $590,000.  Story Continued Below  \u2014 But the hefty sums are a little misleading. The payments are for more than two years of lobbying work on behalf of families of the victims of two terrorist attacks in Kenya and Tanzania in 1998, according to Frank Donatelli, the executive vice president and director of federal public affairs at McGuireWoods Consulting. \u201cWe looked at a variety of ways to get compensation to victims,\u201d Donatelli said in an interview. The firm started by trying to secure payments from a Justice Department fund. When that didn\u2019t work, McGuireWoods brought victims\u2019 families to Washington. \u201cWe fanned out over Capitol Hill and met a lot of members,\u201d Donatelli said. But \u201cthat didn\u2019t go anywhere.\u201d  \u2014 McGuireWoods and the other firms working for the families finally persuaded Congress in 2015 to tuck provisions into a giant spending bill creating a victims compensation fund stocked with money from the $9 billion that BNP Paribas, a French bank, paid in penalties for violating sanctions against Iran, Cuba and Sudan. Their clients received around $230 million in payments from the fund earlier this year \u2014 meaning McGuireWoods and the other firms could finally be paid as well. The firms will also receive a small cut of any future disbursements, Donatelli said. But their clients\u2019 advocacy work apparently isn\u2019t done. Victims of Terrorism - East Africa signed Kamins Consulting on Thursday to lobby for them. The firm did not immediately respond to a request for comment.  MILLER SIGNS THREE MORE: Former Rep. Jeff Miller, who joined McDermott Will & Emery as a lobbyist this spring after retiring from the House in January, has signed three more clients. Miller, a former chairman of the House Veterans Affairs Committee, will lobby only the executive branch for Ambrosia Treatment Centers, Lumina Analytics and Veterans Evaluation Services. He registered to lobby for Steve Cohen, the billionaire financier, on veterans issues earlier this month. Miller is working for each client alongside an old colleague, former Rep. Jim Moran (D-Va.), who served with Miller for more than a decade in the House, along with other McDermott Will & Emery lobbyists.  Good afternoon, and welcome to PI. Got a sensitive tip? I accept anonymous mail: Theodoric Meyer, POLITICO, Eighth Floor, 1000 Wilson Boulevard, Arlington, Va. 22209. For everything else, email should suffice: tmeyer@politico.com. You can also follow me on Twitter: @theodoricmeyer.  BUSINESS ROUNDTABLE READIES PUSH ON TAX REFORM: \u201cThe Business Roundtable is embarking on a multi-million-dollar national TV and radio campaign, beginning in early August, to give tax reform extra momentum over the congressional recess,\u201d POLITICO\u2019s Nancy Cook reports. \u201cDone in cooperation with White House, Treasury, and House and Senate leadership, this is BRT\u2019s effort to cast a potential tax overhaul as a once-in-a-generation opportunity. \u2018Members of Congress will hear from business leaders \u2014 and more importantly, their constituents \u2014 that tax reform is the single best way to increase investment in U.S. communities, create good jobs and promote a stronger economy,\u2019 said Joshua Bolten, President & CEO of Business Roundtable.\u201d  \u2014 \u201cThe ad campaign will kick off on Aug. 4. It comes on the heels of the \u2018Big 6\u2019 tax reform group releasing its six-paragraph set of principles on Thursday on broad tax reform goals including eliminating the controversial so-called border adjustment tax. The \u2018Big 6\u2019 includes National Economic Council Director Gary Cohn; Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin; Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell; House Speaker Paul Ryan; Senate Finance Chair Orrin Hatch; and House Ways & Means Committee Chair Kevin Brady, all of whom have been meeting weekly since the spring to negotiate on potential changes.\u201d Full story.  \u2014 But there\u2019s plenty of skepticism that the drive for tax reform will be any easier than Republicans\u2019 tortured efforts to scrap Obamacare, The Boston Globe\u2019s Victoria McGrane reports. \u201c\u2018No one knows what we\u2019re pushing for,\u2019 one lobbyist involved in the issue said. \u2018We get zero guidance from the White House, we get zero guidance from Treasury. They\u2019re not staffed up.\u2019 \u2026 \u2018To me, it\u2019s looking a lot like what happened with health care,\u2019 featuring an apparent lack of understanding about how to organize such a difficult undertaking, said Eugene Steuerle, a cofounder and fellow of the nonpartisan Tax Policy Center who was a key architect of the 1986 tax reform effort under President Ronald Reagan.\u201d Full story.  BUT WAIT, THERE\u2019S MORE: Top administration officials including Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin are set to talk tax reform with leaders from the Koch network at a newly scheduled event Monday at the Newseum. If this sounds familiar, it is: Team Koch had already set up a tax reform discussion Wednesday at the Newseum featuring Rep. Mark Meadows (R-N.C.), the chairman of the House Freedom Caucus, billed as a kickoff to a multimillion-dollar campaign on overhauling U.S. tax laws. The new event \u2014 which will include White House Director of Legislative Affairs Marc Short and Mnuchin as well as James Davis of Freedom Partners and Tim Phillips of Americans for Prosperity \u2014 will serve as a prelude of sorts. The influence groups are trying to help galvanize support around tax reform \u2014 and they see a clearer path forward now that the divisive border-adjustment tax proposal is off the table.  OUTDOOR RETAILERS MARCH IN PUBLIC LANDS CAMPAIGN: \u201cHundreds of outdoor industry representatives and their supporters took to the streets [in Salt Lake City on] Thursday for a rush-hour hike to the Utah Capitol\u201d as part of a protest against possible efforts to weaken protections for public lands, including the newly designated Bears Ears National Monument in the state, The Salt Lake Tribune reports. The march was part of a sustained lobbying campaign by companies include Patagonia, REI, the North Face and Adidas Outdoor. \u201cWe realized somebody had to start making their voice heard,\u201d Greg Thomsen, the managing director of Adidas Outdoor USA, told The New York Times. \u201cIn my 40 years in the industry I have never seen the industry galvanized in such a way before.\u201d  \u2014 REI is also lobbying on the issue in Washington, although it spent a relatively modest $60,000 in the second quarter. The company has Signal Group Consulting on retainer as well as an in-house lobbyist.   THE PERILS OF WORKING IN AFRICA: The Economist has an interesting piece on American and British firms working in African elections, including Cambridge Analytica, which worked for Donald Trump\u2019s campaign and is largely owned by the Mercer family of GOP megadonors. \u201c\u2018Those who succeed are the ones doing the dark arts,\u2019 says one consultant. Cambridge Analytica refuses to say what it is doing this year in Kenya, but many Kenyans suspect it is helping to craft a vicious campaign. In the 2013 Kenyan election, it claims its research made it \u2018able to draft an effective campaign strategy\u2019 for [President Uhuru] Kenyatta. That election was widely suspected of having been rigged.\u201d Full story.  NEW JOINT FUNDRAISERS:  None  NEW PACs:  84 Fund (Unknown)Fighting For Nevada (Super PAC)Grassroots North Shore (PAC)Key Wins PAC (Leadership PAC: Rep. Ruben Kihuen)Protecting Our Honor Veterans Action Committee (Super PAC)Taking America Back Fund (Super PAC)  NEW LOBBYING REGISTRATIONS:  Baker & Hostetler LLP: Hospital Association of Rhode IslandBaker Donelson Bearman Caldwell & Berkowitz: ResMed Corp.Cardinal Infrastructure: Spokane Transit AuthorityCassidy & Associates, Inc.: American Wind Energy AssociationCloakroom Advisors LLC: Statehouse Strategies on behalf of AECOMHance Scarborough: Global Aviation SolutionsHealth Policy Source, Inc.: HealthECJohnston Group, LLC: Madison Memorial HospitalKamins Consulting: Victims of Terrorism - East AfricaMcCaulley&Company: Village of Montpelier, OhioMcDermott Will & Emery LLP: Ambrosia Treatment CenterMcDermott Will & Emery LLP: Lumina AnalyticsMcDermott Will & Emery LLP: Veterans Evaluation ServicesNew Century Government Affairs (f/k/a Terrence C. Wolfe): Berkeley CollegeThe Aleksander Group: City of Belle GladeVeritas, LLC: Kidney Cancer Action Network  NEW LOBBYING TERMINATIONS:  Connecticut Board of Regents for Higher Education: Connecticut Board Of Regents For Higher EducationEdgepoint, LLC: Sabai TechnologyPareto Policy Solutions, LLC: Business Roundtable  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
