aV \u000a            By THEODORIC MEYER  07/25/2017 02:00 PM EDT  With David Beavers, Aubree Eliza Weaver and Daniel Lippman  HOW AMAZON IS ACTUALLY LOBBYING ON TAXES: President Donald Trump lashed out at Amazon in a trio of tweets on Monday night, wondering if the company was using The Washington Post \u201cas a lobbyist weapon against Congress to keep Politicians from looking into Amazon no-tax monopoly?\u201d It\u2019s not the first time Trump has attacked Amazon, and the basic contours of the fact-check are familiar by now. Jeff Bezos, Amazon\u2019s chief executive \u2014 not Amazon itself \u2014 owns the Post, and the company exercises no control over the newspaper. \u201cAmazon used to lobby to keep Internet sales free from state taxes, but no more,\u201d the Post\u2019s own fact-checker, Glenn Kessler, wrote this morning. \u201cAs of March, Amazon is collecting sales tax on purchases in every state that has one.\u201d  Story Continued Below  \u2014 While Amazon isn\u2019t pushing for a \u201cno-tax monopoly,\u201d it does do plenty of lobbying on taxes. The company spent $3.2 million on lobbying in the second quarter, according to a disclosure filing, and its roster of dozens of tax lobbyists includes three former members of Congress. They include John Breaux, Matthew Cutts, Trent Lott and Brandon Romn of Squire Patton Boggs; David Lugar, Ralph Hellmann and Nicole Mortier of the Lugar Hellmann Group; Vic Fazio, Ed Pagano and Hans Rickhoff of Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld; Elizabeth Frazee, Rachel Wolbers, Debra Dixon, Sarah Dumont-Merchak and Veronica O\u2019Connell of TwinLogic Strategies; Jonathan Talisman and Christopher Javens at Capitol Tax Partners; Amanda Armistead, Casey Duggan, Michael Drobac, Russ Sullivan, Frank Donatelli and Rob Wasinger of McGuireWoods Consulting; Brian Ballard, Sylvester Lukis, Dan McFaul and Rebecca Benn of Ballard Partners; and Stewart Verdery and a dozen other lobbyists at Monument Policy Group, as well as 10 in-house Amazon lobbyists, according to disclosure filings.  LOBBYIT LOBBYING ON CHILD ABDUCTIONS: Here\u2019s a registration that caught our attention last week: Lobbyit.com, a lobbying firm that charges clients as little at $995 per month, is lobbying for Henry Lyden of Wellesley, Mass., on \u201cForeign individual abduction of US citizens,\u201d per a disclosure filing. Lyden, an American living in Japan, is fighting for custody of his 9-year-old son, who lives in Japan with Lyden\u2019s estranged Japanese wife. There is a \u201cdifferent governmental mindset\u201d toward joint custody in Japan, according to John Gomez, the chairman of Kizuna Child-Parent Reunion, a group that advocates for parents like Lyden. The abducting parent is \u201cessentially rewarded\u201d with full custody by Japanese courts \u201cvirtually without exception,\u201d Gomez said.   \u2014 Lyden isn\u2019t the only American caught in a Japanese child-custody struggle, although he may be the only one who\u2019s hired a lobbyist. Japan signed the Hague Abduction Convention, an international treaty governing such disputes, in 2014, but the Japanese have \u201cthumbed their noses\u201d when it comes to enforcement, said Keith Nelson, one of the Lobbyit lobbyists working for Lyden. The Washington Post reported this month on a similar case involving a Minnesota man, noting that \u201cthe U.S. Embassy in Tokyo is dealing with about 70 child abduction cases, 42 of them filed since Japan signed the convention, and 10 of those seeking the return of children to the United States.\u201d Lobbyit will work to raise the profile of child abductions to Japan before the House Foreign Affairs Committee, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee and the State Department, Nelson said.  Good afternoon, and welcome to PI. Got a tip? Get in touch: tmeyer@politico.com. You can also follow me on Twitter: @theodoricmeyer.  AMAZON ADDS FIVE: Amazon has brought on five new public policy managers in its Washington office: Liz Garner, Dan O\u2019Connor, John Drake, Chris Wilson and Matthew McCardle. Garner was previously a senior vice president of policy and public affairs at the Merchant Advisory Group. O\u2019Connor was previously a vice president of public policy at the Computer and Communications Industry Association. Drake was previously a senior vice president of legislative affairs at the American Trucking Associations. Wilson was previously vice president of government affairs at 21st Century Fox. And McCardle was previously a senior director of federal affairs at Boeing.  SENATE CONFIRMS FORMER BROWNSTEIN HYATT LOBBYIST: The Senate confirmed Dave Bernhardt, a former Brownstein Hyatt Farber Schreck lobbyist, to the No. 2 slot in the Interior Department on Monday, POLITICO\u2019s Ben Lefebvre reports. The vote was 53 to 43, with just four Democrats \u2014 Sens. Michael Bennet of Colorado, Joe Donnelly of Indiana, Heidi Heitkamp of North Dakota and Joe Manchin of West Virginia \u2014 voting in favor, along with Sen. Angus King of Maine, an independent who caucuses with Democrats. \u201cBernhardt\u2019s confirmation came despite environmental and good governance groups criticizing him as having too many conflicts of interest to fill the position.\u201d Full story.  DeMINT WILL FIGHT \u2018POTOMAC FEVER\u2019: Former Sen. Jim DeMint (R-S.C.), who was ousted from The Heritage Foundation in May, will serve as chairman of a new conservative group called the Conservative Partnership Institute, POLITICO\u2019s Jake Lahut reports. \u201cThere\u2019s a missing piece that has proved costly: shepherding conservatives through the Washington swamps without being infected with Potomac Fever,\u201d DeMint said in a statement. \u201cThe Conservative Partnership Institute will fill this void by providing the resources, expertise and training needed for leaders and staff in Washington to succeed.\u201d Full story.  VENEZUELA, IN CRISIS, STILL SPENDING ON LOBBYING: Venezuela continues to shell out on \u201cWashington lobbyists through its subsidiary Citgo, a Houston-based oil company,\u201d even though its people are starving, McClatchy\u2019s Alex Daugherty and Franco Ordoez report. Three firms \u2014 Avenue Strategies, Cornerstone Government Affairs and VantageKnight \u2014 \u201ccurrently represent Venezuela in Washington, pushing Capitol Hill, the White House and Cabinet agencies on issues like \u2018fuel refining\u2019 and the \u2018potential impact of U.S. energy policies on CITGO\u2019s operation impacting U.S. consumers,\u2019 according to Senate lobbying records.\u201d  \u2014 \u201cCaracas sees its investment in lobbyists as a way to fight possible sweeping sanctions targeting Venezuelan oil. \u2026 \u2018The costs for representation is a drop in the bucket when compared to the potential economic loss\u2019 of oil sanctions, said C.J. Gimenez, the son of Miami-Dade [Mayor] Carlos Gimenez and a lobbyist who left Avenue Strategies, a firm started by Donald Trump\u2019s former campaign aides, after the firm decided to pick up Citgo as a client.\u201d Full story.  JOBS REPORT:  \u2014 Christina McGarry has joined HLP&R Advocacy as a policy adviser. She was previously a legislative assistant to Rep. Mario Diaz-Balart (R-Fla.).  \u2014 Chamber Hill Strategies is bringing on Melissa Bartlett as a principal. She was previously associate vice president for government relations at Sanofi.  \u2014 The Alliance for Health Policy has added Jenny Sullivan as director of policy and programs. She was previously vice president for programs at Enroll America.  \u2014 Rachelle Johnson started on Monday as director of government affairs for budget and appropriations for Motorola Solutions. She previously worked for the Podesta Group.  \u2014 Express Scripts has promoted Gary Kline to vice president of federal government affairs.  SPOTTED: At a TechFreedom reception at the CTA Innovation House last night, according to a PI tipster: Former SEC Chairman Chris Cox; Berin Szka and Austin Carson of TechFreedom; Katie Barr of Glen Echo Group; Nathan Leamer of the FCC; Kevin Bankston of New America\u2019s Open Technology Institute; Jesse Blumenthal of the Charles Koch Institute; Michael Hayes, Jamie Boone and Maya Sharma of the Consumer Technology Association; Nuala O'Connor of the Center for Democracy & Technology; Jeff Wieand of House Majority Whip Steve Scalise\u2019s office; Alex Kreilein of SecureSet; Richard Seiersen of Twilio; Hugh Gamble and Danielle Gilliam-Moore of Salesforce; Alex Wirth of Quorum; Rachel Wolbers of Engine; and Charles McCray of Amazon.  NEW JOINT FUNDRAISERS:  Committee to Protect Prosperity and Free Enterprise 2017 (Reps. Bruce Poliquin, Tom MacArthur, Claudia Tenney and Lee Zeldin)  NEW PACs:  Resolute Legacy (Unknown)Women Dems Political Action Committee (PAC)  NEW LOBBYING REGISTRATIONS:  Adtalem Global Education: Adtalem Global EducationAlston & Bird LLP: American College of Osteopathic Family PhysiciansAmerican Defense International Inc.: Nova Southeastern UniversityBroad and Cassel LLP: City of Belle GladeCapitol Advocacy Partners: Livermore Valley Joint Unified School DistrictGibson, Dunn & Crutcher LLP: TMK IPSCOHBW Resources: Sunnova Energy CorporationKing & Spalding LLP: Novelis Corp.Madison Law & Policy P.C.: FMR LLC ("Fidelity Investments"McAfee LLC: McAfee LLCMissy Edwards Strategies LLC: State Federal Strategies on behalf of WestfieldNational Association of Accountable Care Organizations: National Association Of Accountable Care OrganizationsNVG LLC: Somnology Inc.Oldaker Law Group LLP: Atlantis Healthcare GroupPowers Pyles Sutter & Verville P.C.: Swinomish Indian Tribal CommunityState Federal Strategies: Westfield CorporationTim Yehl LLC: Guide Strategies (on behalf of Alliance for Aviation Across America)Winn Strategies LLC: TwinLogic Strategies on Behalf of Dell USA LPWinn Strategies LLC: TwinLogic Strategies on Behalf of Lutron Electronics Co. Inc.  NEW LOBBYING TERMINATIONS:  Federal City Strategies: Davita Inc.Hobbs, Straus, Dean & Walker LLP: San Luis Rey Indian Water AuthorityNational Abortion Federation: National Abortion FederationNeighbors Health: Neighbors HealthThe Federal Group Inc.: National Association of Specialty PharmacyThe Federal Group Inc.: Solera Health Inc.The Federal Group Inc.: Unlimited Power Ltd.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
