aV \u000a            By THEODORIC MEYER  07/24/2017 02:21 PM EDT  With David Beavers and Aubree Eliza Weaver  CHARLIE BASS HAS A NEW FIRM: Former Rep. Charlie Bass (R-N.H.) has a new side gig. Bass joined Greenberg Traurig after losing reelection in 2012 and lobbied last quarter for clients including the American College of Rheumatology, Bayer, C&S Wholesale Grocers and Covanta. But Greenberg Traurig last week terminated its registration for C&S Wholesale Grocers, and the next day Bass registered to lobby for the company with a new firm, BASSGLP LLC. He also registered to lobby for Altria, the tobacco giant, which Greenberg Traurig has not represented. Bass wrote in an email that he was traveling and couldn\u2019t talk but that he hadn\u2019t left Greenberg Traurig.  Story Continued Below  END OF THE ROAD: Here are a few lobbying terminations that caught our eye amid the end-of-quarter deluge last week. Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld has parted ways with Intel and TripAdvisor (both of which recently signed McGuireWoods Consulting). Covington & Burling is no longer lobbying for Anheuser-Busch. ML Strategies has stopped lobbying for ExxonMobil, Lockheed Martin and Northeast Maglev, a politically connected firm pushing to build a maglev train between Washington and New York. (Northeast Maglev recently signed Brownstein Hyatt Farber Schreck.) And Qorvis MSLGROUP has parted ways with Yamal LNG, a proposed Russian liquefied natural gas plant for which Qorvis was lobbying on U.S. sanctions against Russia, among other issues.  TRUMP FRIEND ADDS ANOTHER CLIENT: Albert J. Pirro Jr., the New York lawyer and old friend of President Donald Trump\u2019s who served almost a year for a 2000 conspiracy and tax evasion conviction, has signed another client. He\u2019ll lobby for SHINE Medical Technologies Inc., a producer of medical tracers and cancer treatment elements, on \u201cmatch funding authorized by the American Medical [Isotopes] Production Act,\u201d according to a disclosure filing. It\u2019s Pirro\u2019s second registration in the health care space this year. The Greater New York Hospital Association, which Pirro signed in May, paid his firm, the Pirro Group, $122,517 in the second quarter. Pirro did not return a request for comment.   Good afternoon, and welcome to PI. Tips? Complaints? Angry, meandering rants about your lobbying rivals? Get in touch: tmeyer@politico.com. You can also follow me on Twitter: @theodoricmeyer.  MORE SECOND-QUARTER ANALYSIS: \u201cSeveral of the country's largest technology companies spent record sums on lobbying during the second quarter of the year as they beefed up their lobbyist rosters and began to navigate Washington under a new and often unpredictable administration, lobbying filings show,\u201d POLITICO\u2019s Steven Overly reports. \u201cGoogle had its single largest quarter ever with a lobbying bill that totaled $5.9 million. Oracle also posted a banner quarter with $2.79 million spent on lobbying. Apple shelled out a record $2.2 million, nearly double the amount it spent a year earlier. Amazon, Uber and Palantir also hit new heights between April and June.\u201d Full story.  \u2014 WilmerHale had a good quarter. The firm brought in $2.1 million in lobbying revenue, up from $1.2 million in the first quarter of 2017 and $1.3 million in the second quarter of 2016. The firm\u2019s revenue per lobbyist came in at more than $400,000, according to Jon Yarowsky and Rob Lehman, the co-chairmen of the firm\u2019s public policy practice. \u201cWe are thrilled at the rapid growth of our advocacy practice from its beginning three years ago,\u201d Yarowsky and Lehman said in a statement.   \u2014 While many firms saw upticks in their business and others saw declines, it\u2019s worth remembering that savvy companies don\u2019t ramp up or dial back their efforts just based on what\u2019s going on in Congress. They\u2019re here for the long haul. \u201cMost people who are playing at a meaningful level in Washington know that you don\u2019t just turn your efforts on and off like a light switch,\u201d said Hunter Bates, a former chief of staff to Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell who\u2019s now a partner at Akin Gump.   INSIDE MALLINCKRODT\u2019S INFLUENCE CAMPAIGN: \u201cAfter making meager donations in 2015, [the troubled drugmaker Mallinckrodt\u2019s] political action committee began raising its contributions for congressional campaigns last year,\u201d Kaiser Health News\u2019 Jay Hancock, Elizabeth Lucas and Sydney Lupkin report. \u201cLawmakers in both the House and Senate collected $44,000 from Mallinckrodt in 2017\u2019s first quarter, nearly nine times what they got from the company in the same period two years ago. Mallinckrodt also spent $610,000 lobbying Congress, triple the amount of 2015\u2019s first quarter.\u201d And the company is not unique. \u201cThis year, a critical and risky one for drug companies, the industry as a whole is ratcheting up campaign donations and its presence on Capitol Hill, a new database compiled by Kaiser Health News shows.\u201d Full story.  IF MISSED YOU IT: \u201cEmbattled former National Security Adviser Michael Flynn has opened a new consulting firm called Resilient Patriot LLC that is advising private equity firms, according to one of his brothers, who says Flynn is \u2018moving on with his life,\u2019\u201d the Associated Press\u2019 Michelle Smith reports. \u201cJoe Flynn said his family also is in the early stages of starting a fund to pay for the legal bills his brother is racking up as he sits at the center of multiple probes into Russia\u2019s interference in the 2016 presidential election. \u2018Mike\u2019s not a millionaire, not even close,\u2019 Joe Flynn told The Associated Press this week. \u2018This situation has put him in a tough spot financially. This is going to cost him a lot of money.\u2019\u201d Full story.  JOBS REPORT:  \u2014 The National Restaurant Association is bringing on Jessica Falborn as a senior adviser and Adam Hasley as director of advocacy research and insights. Falborn previously worked on the business side at The Hill. Hasley previously worked for a consulting firm in China.  \u2014 Tom Koonce will join Rich Feuer Anderson next month, per Morning Money. He was previously a lobbyist for JPMorgan Chase.  \u2014 District Mayor Muriel Bowser has tapped Kevin Bush as the city\u2019s first chief resilience officer. He was previously in community planning and infrastructure as supervisory resilience specialist at the Department of Housing and Urban Development.  \u2014 Hemal Shah has moved over to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce\u2019s Global Intellectual Property Center as a senior manager, focused on advocacy in markets including Brazil, India and South Africa. She previously worked for the Chamber\u2019s U.S.-India Business Council.  SPOTTED: At the Indiana Society Hoosier Beerfest (sponsored by the Brewers of Indiana Guild) at Baker Donelson\u2019s offices last week, according to a PI tipster: Doug Wasitis of Indiana University; Jan Powell of Baker Donelson; Jodi Richardson of Holland & Knight; Joel Riethmiller of Imperium Global Advisors; Stefan Bailey of Prime Policy Group (who\u2019s also president of the Indiana Society); Brad Queisser of Bose Public Affairs Group; Jennifer Pike Bailey of the Human Rights Campaign; Tom Jeffers of Hill-Rom; and Rob Ehrich of Slipstream Strategies.  NEW JOINT FUNDRAISERS:None  NEW PACs:Disability Voters (PAC)Draft Kamala Harris (PAC)Leadership For A Strong America (super PAC)Progressive Values (PAC)State Government Citizens' Campaign (super PAC)  NEW LOBBYING REGISTRATIONS:American Defense International Inc.: Hy5Pros ASBASSGLP LLC: Altria Client Services LLCBASSGLP LLC: C&S Wholesale Grocers Inc.BGR Government Affairs: American Family Mutual Insurance Company S.I.BGR Government Affairs: Western Digital CorporationBramer Group LLC: Spectrum Aero CorporationCapitol Counsel LLC: Two Canal Owner LLCCardinal Infrastructure: