aV \u000a            By ELENA SCHNEIDER  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With Zach Montellaro and Daniel Strauss  The following newsletter is an abridged version of Campaign Pro's Morning Score. For an earlier morning read on exponentially more races \u2014 and for a more comprehensive aggregation of the day's most important campaign news \u2014 sign up for Campaign Pro today. (http://www.politicopro.com/proinfo)  Story Continued Below  THREE WEEKS OUT \u2014 \u201cStrange pummels Brooks ahead of Alabama primary,\u201d by Campaign Pro\u2019s Daniel Strauss: \u201cRep. Mo Brooks is the center of attention \u2014 and not the good kind of attention \u2014 with three weeks to go until Alabama's special Senate primaries. Sen. Luther Strange and his allies have singled Brooks out of the crowded Republican primary to complete Attorney General Jeff Sessions' Senate term, highlighting inconsistencies in his record and airing ads making Brooks out as a flip-flopper and an opponent of President Donald Trump \u2014 a cardinal sin among Alabama Republican voters. One would be forgiven for thinking Brooks was Strange's only opponent given the intense blast of news, TV ads and other attacks targeting the congressman. But it's a reflection of the theory that while former state Supreme Court Justice Roy Moore's supporters are fairly locked in, Brooks is the other main competitor for a slot in a September top-two primary runoff, and one of Strange or Brooks is considered most likely to miss out.\u201d Full story.   \u2014 ICYMI \u2014 \u201cBrooks defends campaign ad on Scalise shooting,\u201d by Campaign Pro\u2019s Daniel Strauss: \u201cAlabama Rep. Mo Brooks on Monday defended a new ad from his Senate campaign that used footage of the aftermath of the shooting rampage that wounded House Majority Whip Steve Scalise last month. Brooks, who is running in the Aug. 15 special Republican primary for Senate in Alabama, told POLITICO that the ad, which features sounds of gunshots and shouts before playing clips of a Brooks interview, was meant to highlight his support for the Second Amendment. ... But Scalise's chief of staff, Brett Horton, tweeted that the spot made his \u2018stomach turn,\u2019 as Brooks faced criticism for politicizing a tragedy.\u201d Full story.  IDENTITY ISSUES \u2014 \u201cDemocrats sidestep social issues in new economic push,\u201d by POLITICO\u2019s Heather Caygle and Elana Schor in Berryville, Va.: \u201cCongressional Democratic leaders descended upon this rural Virginia town Monday to unveil a progressive economic package they say can win back working-class voters next November, even in red states. And noticeably missing, amid the talk of raising wages and reining in corporate interests, were the left-leaning stances on social issues that help form the backbone of the party, including immigration, abortion and LGBT rights. Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) vowed that his party's red-state incumbents would largely embrace the new agenda \u2014 which, he acknowledged, purposefully avoids the social issues that have already opened a rift this year between the party's liberal base and centrist bloc.\u201d Full story.   ON THE HILL \u2014 \u201cMcCain to make dramatic return for Obamacare vote,\u201d by POLITICO\u2019s Burgess Everett, Seung Min Kim and Jennifer Haberkorn: \u201cThe Senate GOP bid to kill Obamacare \u2014 itself left for dead as of Monday morning \u2014 saw a flicker of life late in the day after a furious pressure campaign by President Donald Trump and Mitch McConnell heading into a critical Tuesday vote. McConnell spent the day cajoling his members and meeting with Vice President Mike Pence to plot strategy. The majority leader was still short of the votes to even open debate, and Republicans still don't know what they'd be voting to allow debate on if they agree to go along with McConnell on the procedural vote. But Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), recently diagnosed with brain cancer and recovering from surgery, announced that he would return to the Senate on Tuesday, giving GOP leaders a critical vote in the up-and-down battle over repealing Obamacare. But the Senate leader isn't being counted out.\u201d Full story.  Days until the 2017 election: 104.  Days until the 2018 election: 468.  Thanks for joining us. You can email tips to the Campaign Pro team at sbland@politico.com, eschneider@politico.com, krobillard@politico.com, dstrauss@politico.com and mseverns@politico.com.  You can also follow us on Twitter: @politicoscott, @ec_schneider, @politicokevin, @danielstrauss4 and @maggieseverns.   Playbook Exchange Denver \u2014 Join POLITICO Playbook co-authors Anna Palmer and Jake Sherman for a special Playbook Exchange event in Denver with Colorado Gov. John Hickenlooper. Aug. 1 \u2014 5:30 p.m. MDT / 7:30 p.m. EDT \u2014 S&P Global, 1800 Larimer St., 2nd Floor, Denver. RSVP: Here. Watch it live: Here.  2020 WATCH \u2014 \u201cSherrod Brown thinks he could have helped Democrats win in 2016. But what about 2020?\u201d by The Washington Post\u2019s Ben Terris: \u201c...\u2018It\u2019s not out of the question that in 2020, if nothing changes, Democrats could win the popular vote by 5 million and lose the electoral college because of the Great Lakes states,\u2019 Brown said. So, because many of his constituents voted for Trump \u2014 and, frankly, because it seemed like a good reelection strategy \u2014 Brown\u2019s first instinct was to work with the president. ...He certainly is one of the Senate\u2019s most endangered Democrats. And if he loses, it could be the last anyone will hear from Sen. Sherrod Brown. But, if he wins ... \u2018We are constantly being asked by others if he\u2019ll run for president in 2020,\u201d Schultz said. \u2018In a way that we never have before.\u2019\u201d Full story.  MONEY, MONEY, MONEY \u2014 \u201cDemocratic House Freshmen Show Fundraising Edge Over GOP Classmates,\u201d by Roll Call\u2019s Sean McMinn: \u201cWith their first two fundraising deadlines behind them, Democratic newbies in the chamber are demonstrating their ability to out fundraise their Republican colleagues. Among first-term lawmakers in the chamber who will likely run for re-election next year, Democrats have taken in, on average, about 50 percent more in receipts per member than Republicans, according to a Roll Call analysis of Federal Election Commission filings. The margin between the two parties was largest during the first quarter of the year, when Democrats raised an average of $348,000 per freshman member, compared to $226,000 among Republicans. The disparity shrank slightly in the second quarter, but Democrats kept a sizable advantage.\u201d Full story.  \u2014 The RGA is donating another $2 million to Republican Ed Gillespie\u2019s campaign in Virginia: The cash infusion follows $1 million delivered to the campaign shortly after he won the GOP primary.   \u2014 POLLING DATA \u2014 Monmouth poll finds Gillespie 44, Northam 44: \u201cDemocratic Lt. Gov. Ralph Northam and Republican Ed Gillespie are tied in the latest poll of Virginia's race for governor, with President Donald Trump dragging voters away from the Republican, according to a new survey from Monmouth University. Northam and Gillespie each earned 44 percent of the vote in the survey. Libertarian Cliff Hyra got 3 percent and 9 percent were undecided.\u201d Full story.   FUNNY BEDFELLOWS \u2014 First Family lawyer keeps donating to Democrats: Jamie Gorelick, a Democratic lawyer who is representing Jared Kushner and Ivanka Trump (and getting some grief from Democratic friends for doing so), has continued to donate to a handful of congressional Democrats in 2017, even as those candidates heavily criticize the Trump administration. Gorelick gave $1,000 to one House candidate, Lindsey Davis Stover, who\u2019s running to take on GOP Rep. Barbara Comstock in northern Virginia. Gorelick also gave to Minnesota Sen. Amy Klobuchar and Montana Sen. Jon Tester.   SHOW-ME SHOWDOWN? \u2014 \u201cMissouri state rep eyes run against McCaskill after encouragement from Wagner,\u201d by the Kansas City Star\u2019s Bryan Lowry: \u201cMissouri state Rep. Marsha Haefner says she\u2019s weighing a run for U.S. Sen. Claire McCaskill\u2019s seat after being encouraged by U.S. Rep. Ann Wagner. Haefner, a St. Louis Republican, said she plans to travel to Washington, D.C., in the near future to meet with national party officials about her interest in a run. \u2018I would hope that the Republican Party would support someone who is not a white male,\u2019 said Haefner, a 66-year-old grandmother who owns a greenhouse and garden center. \u2026 Haefner had been planning to run for Wagner\u2019s congressional seat if Wagner had pursued a run against McCaskill, the incumbent Democrat, as most political observers in Missouri expected.\u201d Full story.   ADMINISTRATION SPEED READ \u2014 \u201cTrump tests the loyalty of the Ohio Democrats he won,\u201d by POLITICO\u2019s Annie Karni: \u201cDown-and-out Youngstown, Ohio, last year became emblematic of the power of Donald Trump\u2019s campaign. With his populist message targeting white working-class voters, he outperformed every GOP nominee since Richard Nixon won the Democratic stronghold of Mahoning County. Today, the blue-collar town represents one of the looming challenges of Trump\u2019s presidency, six months in: how to keep the support he won as a populist candidate, when he flipped disgruntled Democrats and independents to his side of the ledger, while in many cases governing like a plutocrat who has so far failed to deliver on many of his campaign promises. Trump will test the waters Tuesday night when he takes the stage in Youngstown at the Covelli Centre, a large arena that typically hosts events like ice hockey games, WWE wrestling matches, and monster truck tours. The campaign rally is designed to energize the president, excite his base, and offer Trump a chance to tack away from the Russia scandal that never stops brewing in Washington \u2014 one that his advisers claim no regular, outside-the-beltway Americans really care about.\u201d Full story.    CODA \u2014 QUOTE OF THE DAY: \u201cWho the hell wants to speak about politics when I\u2019m in front of the Boy Scouts?\u201d \u2014 President Trump, who later talked about politics, POLITICO reported.   Elena Schneider is a campaign pro reporter for POLITICO, where she focuses on House and Senate races. Before joining the 2016 politics team, Schneider was a news assistant and freelancer for the New York Times\u2019 D.C. bureau. Her work has also appeared in the Texas Tribune, Texas Monthly and Business Insider.  She earned a Master\u2019s and a Bachelor\u2019s in Journalism from Northwestern University\u2019s Medill School of Journalism. Schneider is a North Carolina native and an even-in-September Chicago Cubs fan.  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
