aV \u000a            By STEPHANIE BEASLEY and BRIANNA GURCIULLO  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Tanya Snyder  STRIKE TWO: The FAA bill was once again notably absent from the weekly schedule House Majority Leader Kevin McCarthydistributed Saturday. After raising expectations for a vote last week, and then having to pull back when the vote count wasn\u2019t in his favor, Rep. Bill Shuster (R-Pa.) has been hesitant to publicly target a specific timeframe for a floor vote. But clearly the failure to pass the bill before August recess would be a major blow for Shuster, and \u2014 assuming nothing else changes \u2014 will necessitate what\u2019s already been all but a foregone conclusion for the past few weeks: an extension.   Story Continued Below  Ray of hope: The fine print of McCarthy\u2019s schedule holds out a thin lifeline for Shuster. At the bottom of the list is the line, \u201cAdditional Legislative Items are Possible.\u201d That caveat frequently appears below the weekly schedule, but no doubt Shuster is hoping that this week it means the FAA bill still has a shot. As he told MT last week, \u201cwe\u2019re whipping it every single day; every minute,\u201d and no doubt once he has the 218th vote sewn up he\u2019ll be running to the floor.   Don\u2019t forget: The Senate doesn\u2019t have any air traffic control spinoff language, but a version championed by Sen. John Thune (R-S.D.) is still having trouble getting buy-in, due to language inserted at committee that would weaken the rule that pilots must have 1,500 hours of flight time before getting certified to fly commercially. Lawmakers are working toward a compromise, but so far nothing has emerged.  IT\u2019S THE MONDAY BEFORE RECESS: Thanks for tuning in to POLITICO\u2019s Morning Transportation, your daily tipsheet on all things trains, planes, automobiles and ports. Lauren will be back in the MT driver\u2019s seat with Steph, so please send along tips, feedback and lyrics to lgardner@politico.com or @Gardner_LM and sbeasley@politico.com or @Steph_Beasley.  \u201cI woke up driving my car / I couldn't see then what I see right now / The road dissolving like an empty vow.\u201d  GET LISTENING: Follow MT\u2019s playlist on Spotify. What better way to start your day than with tunes (picked by us and readers) that are all about flying, driving, commuting and sailing?  KICKING OFF JET FUMES WEEK: Zeke Miller (@ZekeJMiller) \u2014 \u201cSummer vacation: FAA says Trump is scheduled to be at Bedminster golf club from August 3-20.\u201d The FAA notice.  E-CIG BAN HERE TO STAY: A federal court of appeals Friday shot down arguments for lifting DOT\u2019s ban on using e-cigarettes on planes, our Tanya Snyder reported for Pros. Among the three judges, one \u201cruled in favor of DOT based on the principle of Chevron deference, which means that courts tend to defer to agencies\u2019 interpretations of the statutes that require them to take action,\u201d Tanya writes. \u201cAnother judge said that even without invoking Chevron deference, e-cigarettes are just similar enough to cigarettes to fall under the ban.\u201d  LYFT JOINS DRIVERLESS CAR RUSH: Lyft is developing its own driverless car technology and plans to hire hundreds of new workers to help with the project, Pro Technology\u2019s Li Zhou reports. The ridesharing company has created a new driverless car division that it says will compete with Uber and Alphabet\u2019s Waymo. Lyft has previously collaborated with Waymo and announced plans to test automated cars with nuTonomy in Boston later this year.   KATKO EYEBALLS CUBAN AIRPORT SECURITY: Rep. John Katko (R-N.Y.) introduced a bill that would require U.S. officials to examine security measures and equipment at Cuban airports. The legislation, H.R. 3328 (115), would also require TSA to create a standard process for signing agreements with the Cuban government to allow U.S. air marshals on scheduled flights between the two countries. The House Homeland Security Committee will mark up the bill on Wednesday.  THIS WEEK:  Tuesday \u2014 NTSB decides the probable cause of a 2015 train-SUV incident and reviews a study on accidents connected to speeding. A House Transportation subcommittee holds a hearing on the Coast Guard. A Surface Transportation Board task force hosts a listening session on regulatory streamlining. The Senate Appropriations subcommittee with jurisdiction over DOT and housing marks up its fiscal 2018 spending bill. A House Homeland Security subcommittee holds a hearing on \u201cthe current challenges to air cargo security.\u201d  Wednesday \u2014 The Senate Commerce Committee holds a hearing on Ronald Batory\u2019s nomination to be FRA administrator and Mark Buzby\u2019s nomination to be MARAD administrator. The full House Homeland Security Committee marks up multiple bills. A Senate Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs subcommittee holds a hearing on \u201coversight of federal infrastructure permitting and the Federal Permitting Improvement Steering Council.\u201dThe Association for Unmanned Vehicle Systems International holds a webinar with \u201cexamples of how successful companies use drones to inspect holdings and increase profits.\u201d  Thursday \u2014 The full Senate Appropriations Committee marks up the fiscal 2018 THUD spending bill.  MT MAILBAG: The American Trucking Associations wrote to FMCSA on Friday taking a stand against \u201cany effort to delay the December implementation of the fully litigated, widely debated and congressionally mandated use of electronic logging devices.\u201d Such \u201cefforts are misguided, are supported by misinformation, and are simply an attempt to evade compliance with the existing laws and regulations governing duty hours and driver fatigue,\u201d Bill Sullivan, executive vice president of advocacy for ATA, wrote to Deputy FMCSA Administrator Daphne Jefferson.  Remember: The House Appropriations Committee, in its report for the fiscal 2018 THUD spending bill, instructs DOT to studywhether there should be \u201ca full or targeted delay\u201d of the ELD requirement as small companies \u201cwill disproportionately bear new costs associated with the mandate.\u201d  Click: FMCSA has a nifty new website all about electronic logging devices. (h/t Eugene Mulero)  MUSK TWEETS AGAIN ABOUT HYPERLOOP: A day after saying he got \u201cverbal government approval\u201d for an underground hyperloop system connecting New York City, Philadelphia, Baltimore and D.C., Elon Musk tweeted Friday: \u201cVerbal approval was at Federal level. Still a lot of work before formal, written approval, but this opens door for state & city discussions.\u201d The White House said in a statement Thursday that it has \u201chad promising conversations\u201d with the Tesla and SpaceX executive. Hot take from Anthony Foxx, former Transportation secretary, who replied to one of Musk\u2019s tweets saying: \u201cUm \u2026 you might want to get that in writing!\u201d  And ICYMI: Democratic Rep. Joaquin Castro wants a hyperloop in Texas. (Musk did tweet on Thursday: \u201cFirst set of tunnels are to alleviate greater LA urban congestion. Will start NY-DC in parallel. Then prob LA-SF and a TX loop.\u201d)  NO THANKS, I\u2019M GOOD: Trump is passing over the opportunity to garner bipartisan support for his $1 trillion infrastructure idea just at the time when he most desperately needs a legislative win, reports Glenn Thrush on the front page of Sunday\u2019s New York Times. "In the White House, Mr. Trump has continued to dangle the possibility of 'a great national infrastructure program' that would create 'millions" of new jobs as part of a public-private partnership to rival the public works achievements of Franklin Delano Roosevelt and Dwight D. Eisenhower,\u201d Thrush writes. \u201cBut an ambitious public works plan, arguably his best chance of rising above the partisan rancor of his first six months in office, is fast becoming an afterthought - at precisely the moment Mr. Trump needs a big, unifying issue to rewrite the narrative of his chaotic administration. Infrastructure remains stuck near the rear of the legislative line, according to two dozen administration officials, legislators and labor leaders involved in coming up with a concrete proposal.\u201d  #SUMMEROFHELL UPDATE: Amtrak issued a second progress report on its repair work at New York City\u2019s Penn Station showing that the work remains on schedule.   THE AUTOBAHN:  \u2014 "Air Canada pilots reportedly didn\u2019t use normal navigation aids in close call at San Francisco." The Wall Street Journal.  \u2014 "Southeast Asia's Grab to get $2.5 billion extra firepower in battle with Uber." Reuters.  \u2014 \u201cU.S. to ban Americans from traveling to North Korea.\u201d The Associated Press.  \u2014 "Extreme commuting": More people are traveling two hours or more to work. The New York Times.    \u2014 \u201cAudi to update 850,000 cars as diesel recalls widen.\u201d The Associated Press.  \u2014 \u201cFord to petition to avoid U.S. recall of 2.5 million vehicles.\u201d Reuters.  \u2014 \u201cL.A. Metro wants to spend $138 million on electric buses. The goal: an emission-free fleet by 2030.\u201d Los Angeles Times.    \u2014 \u201cU.S. lawyers suing Volkswagen get $300 million in fees, costs.\u201d Reuters.  \u2014 "Regional leaders aim to launch Metro Safety Commission by end of year." The Washington Post.  \u2014 "Trump administration to replace Obama-era picks on Metro board." The Washington Post.  THE COUNTDOWN: DOT appropriations run out in 68 days. The FAA reauthorization expires in 68 days. Highway and transit policy is up for renewal in 1,164 days.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
