aV \u000a            By BENJAMIN WERMUND  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Michael Stratford, Caitlin Emma and Mel Leonor  TRUMP ADMINISTRATION SPARKS AGE-OLD AFFIRMATIVE ACTION FIGHT: News that the Justice Department may soon begin investigating whether colleges are discriminating in the way they use race in admissions set off a firestorm this week. The Supreme Court ruled just last year that colleges can use race in admissions, but experts say that doesn\u2019t preclude the administration from targeting colleges \u2014 and it doesn\u2019t mean that opponents of race-based admissions policies will stop working to end them. \u201cWe\u2019ve been in this fight for 40 years, at least,\u201d said Rachel Kleinman, an attorney with the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund, which defends affirmative action policies in court. \u201cWe\u2019re realistic that whenever you think something is settled, the challenges still pop up.\u201d Here\u2019s what you need to know about the issue.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 The Supreme Court has ruled multiple times that schools can use race as a factor in admissions. Most recently, the court ruled that the University of Texas at Austin\u2019s use of race was appropriate, because it was narrowly tailored and because the school proved that it needed to consider race in order to build a diverse student body. Those are the hurdles schools must clear to prove their use of race in admissions policies is legal.   \u2014 Still, the issue is likely to find its way back to the high court eventually \u2014 and could be decided by a very different set of justices. The group that challenged UT Austin\u2019s policies, Students for Fair Admissions, has sued both Harvard and the University of North Carolina. (Notably, Edward Blum, who heads that group, told the Boston Globe that he was \u201cbefuddled\u201d by the DOJ news and hadn\u2019t heard from anyone there.) While those lawsuits are still likely a long way from the high court, if they make it there, \u201cI am sure the issue will go back to the U.S. Supreme Court \u2014 the only question is when,\u201d said Vinay Harpalani, an associate professor of law at the Savannah Law School. The makeup of the court, which could change dramatically during President Donald Trump\u2019s term, will matter greatly on this issue. Justice Anthony Kennedy swung the court in UT\u2019s favor, and if President Donald Trump has a chance to replace him or one of the liberal justices \u201cthen that\u2019s a major change on this specific issue,\u201d said Jesse Choper, a law professor at the University of California Berkeley.   \u2014 It remains unclear what the Justice Department was, or still is, planning on this front. An internal Justice Department posting seeking lawyers for "investigations and possible litigation" relating to university affirmative action policies, first reported earlier this week by The New York Times, was actually a call for volunteers to work on a complaint alleging discrimination against Asian-American applicants at Harvard, not a sweeping policy change, the department says. But the groups that filed that complaint told Morning Education they haven\u2019t heard from the department and are only cautiously optimistic that their complaint will actually be taken up \u2014 especially after all of the backlash the news drew. \u201cWhat if upon all this political maneuvering the DOJ will back down,\u201d said Chunyan Li, a spokeswoman for the coalition that filed the complaint.   \u2014 If the department does begin to investigate college admissions practices, it will, at the very least, be sending a message to schools, advocates fear. \u201cIf you hear the Justice Department is coming after schools, whether or not you\u2019re doing the right thing under the law, that will certainly chill universities,\u201d Kleinman at the NAACP LDF said. For their part, colleges and universities have voiced strong opposition to any crackdown on affirmative action from the Trump administration. \u201cWe are deeply concerned by news reports about the Department of Justice\u2019s interest in exploring legal action against universities that would undermine schools\u2019 ability to use Supreme Court-sanctioned, race-conscious admissions practices as part of a holistic process,\u201d Peter McPherson, president of the Association of Public and Land-grant Universities, said in a statement.   \u2014 Also of note: Most Americans are opposed to the use of race in college admissions, according to a Gallup poll taken after last year\u2019s Supreme Court ruling. Seven in 10 Americans said merit should be the only basis for college admissions, and 65 percent said they disagreed with the Supreme Court decision. Some, meanwhile, have speculated that if the administration does seek to challenge race-based admissions, it will be a play to its base. \u201cAs they are doing with Kris Kobach\u2019s misguided efforts to prove voting fraud, this is a thinly-veiled effort to reach aggrieved whites who are looking for someone to blame and to demonize,\u201d said Michael A. Olivas, a law professor and higher education policy expert at the University of Houston. \u201cThere is no evidence that whites are displaced due to admissions for students of color, and SCOTUS has, since 1978, upheld modest uses of [affirmative action] for diversity.\u201d  HAPPY FRIDAY AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. I really like this take from The Ringer on Randy Newman, who has a new album out today: \u201cIn Newman\u2019s songs, we can see an American history with all its luminescence and hope, but mostly its pain and betrayal. Newman investigates the skeletons in our closets, the gunk between our toes, the hate that drives us to make bad choices. And sometimes he tells us how to be good friends.\u201d Tips? Feedback? Let me know: bwermund@politico.com or @BenjaminEW. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  Pro subscribers: Are you getting all the content you want? Make sure your keywords are up to date and customized via your settings page at http://politico.pro/1iDALk9.  STATES DIAL EDUCATION DEPARTMENT FOR ESSA FEEDBACK: Eight states are in the process of gathering federal feedback on their Every Student Succeeds Act plans, and at least three have had phone calls with federal officials in recent days. The calls come after the Education Department last week announced that it was changing the feedback process. This summer, the department had been publicly posting letters to states outlining initial comments or concerns, in addition to comments from a team of experts known as peer reviewers. Those letters got a lot of blowback from states and policy experts for being confusing, inconsistent or heavy-handed. Now, the agency is first discussing peer reviewer comments with states over the phone, giving them an opportunity to address any issues before a letter is posted publicly. After the phone call happens, the clock starts \u2014 states have 15 days to make changes, tweaks or clarifications to their plans. Some worry the process change could potentially shield from public view the back-and-forth between state and federal officials over the development of state ESSA plans.  \u2014 D.C. had its call with the Education Department on Tuesday. Maine and Michigan spoke to the feds Wednesday. Vermont is scheduled for a call early next week. D.C. Superintendent Hanseul Kang told Morning Education, \u201cWe appreciate the U.S. Department of Education\u2019s thorough review of D.C.\u2019s ESSA state plan. We are carefully reviewing the feedback we received from the department while keeping at the forefront the question of what will be most meaningful for our students, educators and schools, within our unique context.\u201d  \u2014 A spokeswoman for the Maine Department of Education declined to elaborate on where federal officials felt there was room for improvement in the state\u2019s plan. But she said, \u201cThe conversation highlighted a few areas that Maine\u2019s plan needed additional context, or further clarification, and there were a few sections that needed specific language to ensure that it aligned with the statute.\u201d  \u2014 Michigan Superintendent Brian Whiston told The Detroit News, \u201cWe were told that the secretary\u2019s determination will be based on compliance with the letter of the law only, and no subjective judgments on what is in the plan. This is in line with what Secretary DeVos promised about giving more flexibility and control back to the states on what they think is best for their state.\u201d Michigan initially submitted a plan this spring that included three options for grading schools. The state has since decided to use a \u201cdashboard\u201d of data approach. Whiston said federal officials want to see more information about how the dashboard will be designed and used to identify low-performing schools.   \u2014 Several weeks ago, Whiston said he was taken aback by a phone call that he had with Jason Botel, acting assistant secretary of elementary and secondary education. Botel reportedly questioned why Michigan\u2019s plan was incomplete, even though DeVos earlier this year said states could hand in their plans even if they still had to fill in some blanks. Whiston accused the Education Department of overreach after months of DeVos messaging flexibility to states.   SENATE CONFIRMS TRUMP EDUCATION NOMINEE: The Senate on Thursday confirmed President Donald Trump\u2019s nominee to be assistant secretary of education for legislation. Peter Oppenheim, an aide to Sen. Lamar Alexander (R-Tenn.), was confirmed to the post through unanimous consent in the Senate, as it approved dozens of Trump nominees in bulk as part of an agreement reached between Democrats and Republicans. POLITICO first reported in April that Oppenheim was a front-runner for the job.   \u2014 Oppenheim is the first Education Department nominee confirmed by the Senate since DeVos was confirmed earlier this year with Vice President Mike Pence casting the tiebreaking vote on her nomination. He was a key figure in drafting and passing the Every Student Succeeds Act, the Child Care and Development Block Grant Act of 2014 and the Workforce Innovation and Opportunity Act.  \u2014 Sen. Elizabeth Warren (D-Mass.) had previously signaled that she might put up a fight over the nomination, citing what she said was DeVos\u2019 lack of responsiveness to Democrats\u2019 inquiries. Warren wrote last week in a letter to Oppenheim that she was concerned that the Trump administration\u2019s Education Department had been \u201cnegligent in its duty to respond\u201d to congressional inquiries. But no senator objected to the nomination on the Senate floor on Thursday.  \u2014 Trump\u2019s sole other Education Department nominee \u2014 Florida attorney Carlos Muiz to be general counsel \u2014 remains pending before the Senate HELP Committee. Michael Stratford has more.   \u2014 DeVos said of Oppenheim\u2019s confirmation: \u201cPeter has spent his career working tirelessly on behalf of our nation\u2019s students, and I am thrilled he will continue that work here at the Department of Education. Peter\u2019s policy knowledge and expertise will be a tremendous asset to this Administration as we continue to fulfill the President\u2019s pledge to empower parents and ensure every child, no matter where they grow up, has access to a world-class education that meets their needs now and in the future.\u201d  IN TOWN TODAY \u2014 NAEP UPDATE: The National Assessment Governing Board \u2014 the body charged with overseeing the National Assessment of Educational Progress assessment \u2014 will be discussing what\u2019s ahead for NAEP at its quarterly meeting in Washington, D.C., today. Board members and stakeholders are planning to discuss the NAEP schedule and hold talks on the design and dissemination of the assessment. Peggy Carr, acting commissioner for the National Center for Education Statistics, will talk about what\u2019s ahead for the agency, and NCES staff will break down its High School Transcript Study. See the full agenda.  AFT JOINS ARMS WITH PUERTO RICO TEACHERS UNION: The American Federation of Teachers and the Asociacin de Maestros de Puerto Rico \u2014 which represents 40,000 teachers on the island \u2014 voted to affiliate Thursday. Both parties signed a trial affiliation agreement that will carry over through the next three years, as AFT works with AMPR and its locals to help with collective bargaining in the financially embattled U.S. territory. \u201cEvery country wants to improve its economic and social situation, but in Puerto Rico teachers haven\u2019t been treated fairly,\u201d AMPR President Aida Diaz said. \u201cWith the AFT, we can work hand in hand to improve our working conditions and reclaim all that has been denied to us.\u201d AFT President Randi Weingarten said she is looking forward to mobilizing AFT\u2019s new members for better working conditions and education opportunities on the island.   MOVERS AND SHAKERS  \u2014 Jonathan Butcher is joining The Heritage Foundation\u2019s Center for Education Policy as a senior policy analyst. Butcher was previously education director at the Goldwater Institute, where he worked on school choice policy.   REPORT ROLL CALL   \u2014 Teacher preparation programs often lack access to the right data to fully prepare teachers to meet the unique needs of their students, the Data Quality Campaign says in a new report.   SYLLABUS  \u2014 Rhode Island is the fourth state to make community college free: CNN Money.   \u2014 California State University is dropping algebra as a requirement for some students: EdSource.   \u2014 A mostly white Alabama city wants its own education system, highlighting a growing national trend as new districts reignite school segregation debates: The Wall Street Journal.   \u2014 \u201ciGen,\u201d the generation after Millennials, is on the brink of the worst mental-health crisis in decades \u2014 and it may be because of their smartphones: The Atlantic.   \u2014 An 8-year-old transgender girl in California is suing her private school for discrimination: BuzzFeed News.   \u2014 Last-minute donations from Eli Broad and others helped charter advocates gain power on the L.A. school board: L.A. Times.   \u2014 For the first time, Texas charter schools have outperformed traditional public schools in reading and are closing the gap in math: The Houston Chronicle.   \u2014 Young Americans are finding themselves stuck in their hometowns, even in economically depressed areas: The Wall Street Journal.   Follow the Pro Education team while you can, baby, don\u2019t look back. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
