aV \u000a            By MICHAEL STRATFORD  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Caitlin Emma, Kimberly Hefling, Mel Leonor and Benjamin Wermund  DOJ DENIES BROAD ATTACK ON AFFIRMATIVE ACTION, SAYS IT\u2019S INVESTIGATING COMPLAINT OF ANTI-ASIAN BIAS AT HARVARD: The Trump administration on Wednesday pushed back against news reports that it is seeking to curb affirmative action programs at colleges and universities \u2014 but confirmed that the Justice Department is investigating a complaint filed by Asian-American groups accusing Harvard University of racial bias in admissions.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 An internal Justice Department posting seeking lawyers for \u201cinvestigations and possible litigation" relating to university affirmative action policies was a call for volunteers to work on a complaint alleging discrimination against Asian-American applicants at Harvard, not a sweeping policy change, a department spokeswoman said Wednesday.  \u2014 The internal document, described in a New York Times report on Tuesday evening, set the higher education and civil rights worlds ablaze, as supporters of affirmative action worried that Attorney General Jeff Sessions was seeking to marshal the resources of the Justice Department against race-conscious university admissions policies.  \u2014 "The posting sought volunteers to investigate one administrative complaint filed by a coalition of 64 Asian-American associations in May 2015 that the prior Administration left unresolved," Justice Department spokeswoman Sarah Isgur Flores said in a statement. Those groups, led by the Asian-American Coalition for Education, filed complaints with both the Education and Justice departments alleging that Harvard discriminated against Asian-American applicants based on their race. The Education Department\u2019s Office of Civil Rights dismissed the complaint in July 2015, citing an ongoing lawsuit against the university over similar issues. But the complaint remains pending with the Civil Rights Division at DOJ.  \u2014 \u201cThis Department of Justice has not received or issued any directive, memorandum, initiative, or policy related to university admissions in general,\u201d Flores said in the statement. \u201cThe Department of Justice is committed to protecting all Americans from all forms of illegal race-based discrimination.\u201d Read more.   GOOD THURSDAY MORNING AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. Drop me a line with your tips and feedback: mstratford@politico.com or @mstratford. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  GI BILL EXPANSION HEADS TO PRESIDENT\u2019S DESK: A bill that would inject more than $3 billion in additional benefits over the next decade under the Post-9/11 GI Bill to veterans and their families to pay for higher education was sent to President Donald Trump, who is expected to sign it. The Senate on Wednesday cleared the bipartisan bill, which veterans groups have long sought, by unanimous consent. The legislation has been dubbed the \u201cForever GI Bill\u201d because one key component removes, for new enlistees, a requirement that the education benefit be used within 15 years. Purple Heart recipients and Reserve troops are among the groups of vets who see expanded benefits under the bill. It would also fully restore the GI Bill education benefits for veterans who were affected by the collapse in recent years of Corinthian Colleges and ITT Tech \u201cThis is what collaboration looks like, and this is what leadership looks like,\u201d said Jared Lyon, the president of Student Veterans of America. Read more here.   DEVOS, U.S. MARSHALS SERVICE TO RENEW SECURITY AGREEMENT: The U.S. Marshals Service and the Education Department plan to renew an agreement to continue providing protective services for Education Secretary Betsy DeVos, a spokesman for the Marshals Service tells Pro Education\u2019s Caitlin Emma. Earlier this year, the Marshals signed a memorandum of understanding with the agency to provide protective services for DeVos for up to four years, \u201csubject to the availability of funds and current threat assessments.\u201d The Education Department at the time agreed to reimburse the Marshals Service an estimated total of $7.78 million for services spanning mid-February through September 30, or the end of the fiscal year. Now, both parties \u201cplan to renew the reimbursement agreement beyond Sept. 30, which will continue the memorandum of understanding between the agencies for the protective detail for Secretary DeVos,\u201d a Marshals Service spokesman said. The spokesman could not provide details about the anticipated cost or length of the reimbursement agreement and could not discuss specifics about threats to DeVos\u2019 safety. The past four Education secretaries have been protected by the Education Department\u2019s own small security force.  JUDGE AGAIN SCOLDS DOJ ATTORNEYS IN EDUCATION DEPT. DEBT COLLECTION CONTRACTING DISPUTE: The federal judge overseeing a legal battle involving the Education Department\u2019s contracts with debt collection companies apparently isn\u2019t happy that she wasn\u2019t informed about DeVos\u2019 decision this week to scrap a planned loan servicing overhaul. In an order issued Wednesday evening, U.S. Court of Federal Claims Chief Judge Susan G. Braden appeared to chastise the DOJ attorneys representing the Education Department in the case for not informing her of the loan servicing announcement \u2014 and ordered them to produce a status report about the case by the end of tomorrow.  \u2014 \u201cOnce again, the Department of Justice has failed to inform the court of these developments,\u201d the Braden wrote in her order, citing POLITICO and Inside Higher Ed stories from earlier this week describing DeVos\u2019 change of course on student loan servicing.  \u2014 Braden did not explain in her order why she believes the debt collection and loan servicing contracts are connected. The Education Department has a set of contracts with debt collection firms that pursue borrowers who have defaulted on their federal loans; those are separate from the department\u2019s contracts with loan servicing companies, which manage the payments of federal borrowers whose student loans are in good standing.  \u2014 Braden earlier this year issued an order blocking the Education Department from assigning defaulted loans to any of its debt collectors as she resolves a dispute over whether the department acted unfairly in awarding contracts to some of the companies. In May, Braden extended her injunction against the department, criticizing DOJ attorneys for not informing her about the resignation of James Runcie as chief of federal student aid and a policy proposal reportedly under consideration that would shift the student loan program to the Treasury Department.  \u2014 A federal appeals court last month balked at the Trump administration\u2019s emergency request to reverse Braden\u2019s injunction, which the government says has prevented it from collecting defaulted student loans and deprived hundreds of thousands of borrowers of the ability to get their loans out of default.   COURT SAYS TITLE IX DOESN\u2019T PROTECT TEEN BECAUSE SHE WASN\u2019T A STUDENT: A recent ruling on Title IX addresses an odd wrinkle in the law: Does it require colleges to protect only their students, or also those, including high schoolers, on campus as prospective students? A federal appeals court said only the prior and tossed out a lawsuit by a 16-year-old high school junior who says she was assaulted at a fraternity party while visiting Culver-Stockton College in Missouri, because she wasn\u2019t a student at the college. The teen, who spent the night at the college as a potential athletics recruit, claimed the college violated Title IX by failing to prevent the assault. Inside Higher Ed has more.   \u2014 Meanwhile, the Education Department's civil rights office continues to open new investigations into allegations that colleges and universities mishandled sexual assault cases \u2014 including six just this week \u2014 despite the Trump administration's plans to change guidance for schools dealing with allegations of sexual violence. The Office for Civil Rights opened new investigations this week at Humboldt State University in California, the University of Florida, Michigan State, Ohio State, Ursinus College in Pennsylvania and the University of Texas at San Antonio. They bring the ever-growing list of Title IX probes to 350 at 246 colleges and universities.  \u2014 But the office this week also closed two cases \u2014 at Grinnell College in Iowa and Princeton \u2014 as investigators works to cut down on the lengthy backlog. They're under new marching orders from Candice Jackson, the acting head of the civil rights office, who told investigators to use a shorter scope than they previously had. Both of those cases were closed administratively without findings of wrongdoing. Benjamin Wermund has more.   ICYMI, GAVIN GRIMM\u2019S CASE SENT BACK TO TRIAL COURT: The case of Gavin Grimm, the Virginia teen at the center of a high-profile legal battle over transgender student rights, is back in federal district court. Grimm graduated high school in June. His attorneys argue that his case \u2014 in which he\u2019s suing for access to the boy\u2019s bathroom at his high school under Title IX \u2014 is still relevant because Grimm could return to school as an alumni and still be subjected to discrimination. Attorneys for the Gloucester County School Board in Virginia have argued that Grimm's graduation makes the case moot. Now, the three-judge panel on the 4th Circuit wants the trial court to decide if that\u2019s the case. Caitlin Emma has more.  COLORADO UNION STEPS UP TEACHER DEVELOPMENT: The Colorado arm of the National Education Association is partnering with professional development planform Edthena to deliver teacher-to-teacher professional support to its members. The union\u2019s partnership with Edthena will expand its professional development offerings by using video to connect teachers hoping to improve their skills, while fulfilling the training requirements imposed by their districts. \u201cUsing Edthena, teachers can record their classroom instruction and receive feedback from other educators who they respect and trust,\u201d the union said. \u201cVideo coaching also allows teachers to become an active part of the evaluation process.\u201d   BIPARTISAN PROPOSAL WOULD INCREASE AID TO STUDENT PARENTS: Bipartisan bills introduced in the House and Senate this week propose a boost in federal funding for on-campus child care tapped by student parents across the country. The bills would reauthorize the Child Care Access Means Parents In School program and quadruple investment in the program, which is now under threat of being axed under the House Labor-HHS-Education appropriations bill. The bills, titled CCAMPIS Reauthorization Act, were introduced by Reps. Katherine Clark (D-Mass.) and Don Young (R-Alaska) in the House, and Sens. Tammy Duckworth (D-Ill.), Patty Murray (D-Wash.), Kirsten Gillibrand (D-N.Y.), Bob Casey (D-Penn.) and Dick Durbin (D-Ill.) in the Senate.   \u2014 \u201cAs the costs of college and child care continue to climb, too many students and families are struggling to make ends meet,\u201d Murray, ranking member of the Senate HELP committee, said. \u201cWe must invest in student parents as they invest in their families\u2019 futures.\u201d   GAINFUL EMPLOYMENT REMINDER: Even as the Trump administration takes steps to delay parts of the Obama-era \u201cgainful employment\u201d and eventually re-write it completely, the regulation remains on the books. The Education Department on Wednesday reminded colleges and universities that they have until October 1 to submit a new round of data about their career college programs that are subject to the rules. Read the full announcement here.   SYLLABUS   \u2014 The Pennsylvania Department of Education is set to unveil a new school quality metric in 2018 that will be less focused on state standardized tests: Newsworks.   \u2014 DeVos defends Trump\u2019s proposed education cuts: Detroit News.   \u2014 Indiana\u2019s A-F grade overhaul now awaits approval from governor and the feds: Chalkbeat.   \u2014 Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens plans to boost education and job training for inmates in the state\u2019s embattled prison system: St. Louis Post-Dispatch.   \u2014 The Republican challenging New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio wants the city\u2019s anti-corruption watchdog to investigate contracts with a nonprofit retained by the education department to coach public school teachers and principals: amNewYork.   \u2014 New Hawaii schools chief says she wants to start her job by listening to as many people as possible: Civil Beat.   \u2014 Former Education Secretary John B. King Jr. says 'Alabama has a particular challenge' when it comes to closing achievement gap: AL.com.   The Wolf. Follow the Pro Education team. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
