aV \u000a            By BENJAMIN WERMUND  08/02/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Caitlin Emma, Mel Leonor, Kimberly Hefling, Josh Gerstein and Michael Stratford  OMAROSA MEETING WITH HBCU LEADERS THIS WEEK: White House aide Omarosa Manigault, who is spearheading the Trump administration\u2019s outreach to historically black colleges and universities, is meeting with several HBCU leaders this week \u2014 at a time when some of the leaders have become impatient with the Trump administration\u2019s approach to the schools.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 The leaders are still waiting on a couple of changes President Donald Trump promised when he signed a much-ballyhooed executive order designed to woo the schools. That order said his administration would move an initiative aimed at boosting HBCUs from the Education Department to the White House \u2014 a move that many college leaders hoped would give them a direct line to the president, but six months later, still hasn\u2019t happened, according to the Chronicle of Higher Education. The initiative, meanwhile, has no leader \u2014 marking the longest a president has gone without naming one, Inside Higher Ed reports.   \u2014 "There was a big display of love and support on the front end, and right now it\u2019s sort of like, \u2018OK, where are we?\u2019" Walter Kimbrough, president of Dillard University, told the Chronicle. He and other HBCU leaders have been skeptical of the administration from the start, blasting a \u201clistening session\u201d before the executive order signing as little more than a photo opp for the president. "There was very little listening to HBCU presidents today," Kimbrough wrote at the time.  \u2014 But Manigault, Trump\u2019s point person on HBCUs, told Morning Education that she is \u201cworking closely with the HBCU community in preparation for the official launch of the White House HBCU office.\u201d The administration has worked \u201cdiligently to interview and meet with all of the candidates that were submitted through our various HBCU channels,\u201d Manigault said in a written response to questions. She said they are now going through the final stages of the process and will have an announcement soon. \u201cIn terms of those who are frustrated that the government hiring and vetting process is taking too long all I can say to them is that \u2018we will not and CAN NOT cut corners,\u2019\u201d she wrote. \u201cBy law every candidate must go through the same process, the same screenings and the same background checks. That process takes time \u2014 plain and simple.\u201d  \u2014 Manigault said she is \u201cconducting nearly 20 different meetings over the next 4 days\u201d at a conference in Florida hosted by the umbrella organization of the nation's HBCUs, the National Association for Equal Opportunity in Higher Education.  MEANWHILE IN PENNSYLVANIA: The fight to save the country\u2019s oldest HBCU continues as Sen. Bob Casey and Rep. Dwight Evans, both Pennsylvania Democrats, wrote to the chancellor of state\u2019s system of higher education urging him to do anything he can to protect Cheyney University\u2019s accreditation, which the school is at risk of losing. The university has faced a financial crisis and dwindling enrollment. \u201cWhile Cheyney\u2019s path has been a rocky one, we believe they are committed to ensuring a strong path forward,\u201d the lawmakers wrote in a letter sent Monday. \u201cWe remain optimistic Cheyney will show they have taken the steps needed to ensure the viability of the institution and will ensure we pursue all federal options, as is our duty to the people who live in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.\u201d  GOOD WEDNESDAY MORNING AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. I\u2019m genuinely confused by how harsh the reviews of the new Arcade Fire album have been. It\u2019s not their best, but I really like it \u2014 especially the beautiful closer. Tips? Feedback? Let me know: bwermund@politico.com or @BenjaminEW. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  POLITICO Pro Policy Summit, Sept. 14: An all-day summit featuring deep-dive conversations and incisive interviews that explore policy trends inside and outside government. Space is limited to current Pro customers at the director level or above. Learn More.  TRUMP ADMINISTRATION MAY HAVE AFFIRMATIVE ACTION IN THE CROSSHAIRS: Colleges and universities that discriminate against white applicants appear to be the target of a new project by the Justice Department. The New York Times, citing an internal document, reported late Tuesday that the Trump administration is preparing to redirect resources from the Justice Department\u2019s civil rights division to investigate and sue universities over admissions policies that disadvantage whites. The division is seeking lawyers who want to work on \u201cinvestigations and possible litigation related to intentional race-based discrimination in college and university admissions," the Times reported. The Times did not publish a copy of the internal document. But the newspaper said it suggests the effort will be operated out of the division\u2019s front office, where the Trump administration\u2019s political appointees do business.  \u2014 The move would come just a year after the Supreme Court upheld that the University of Texas' program admitting some students based on consideration of their race is constitutional but cautioned that the university must continue to show that other means of addressing diversity have failed. An American Council on Education survey found in 2015 that about 60 percent of the most selective four-year schools consider race in admissions. Eight states ban race-based admissions for public institutions. Kimberly Hefling and Caitlin Emma have more.   \u2014 The news drew outrage from civil rights groups Tuesday night. The NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund said such a move would \u201cwaste taxpayer resources relitigating last year\u2019s Supreme Court ruling. Affirmative action is rooted in our nation\u2019s fundamental commitment to equality, a commitment this Administration woefully lacks and has expressed hostility towards.\u201d  \u2014 Vanita Gupta, the former head of the Justice Department's civil rights division under President Barack Obama who is now president of the Leadership Conference on Civil and Human Rights, told POLITICO that \u201cIt kind of is turning civil rights laws on their head and away from the purpose for which they were enacted, which is to ensure racial diversity and inclusion in higher ed institutions and prevent discrimination against marginalized, vulnerable or historically disadvantaged communities.\u201d She said she believes the administration \u201cwill likely be trying to set back the work schools and colleges are doing to try to ensure diverse student bodies.\u201d  DEVOS DROPS PLAN TO OVERHAUL STUDENT LOAN SERVICING: Education Secretary Betsy DeVos on Tuesday abandoned her plan to overhaul how the federal government collects payments from the nation\u2019s more than 42 million student loan borrowers after it faced growing resistance from congressional Republicans and Democrats. The Trump administration announced that it was scrapping plans to award a massive contract to a single company to manage the monthly payments of all student loan borrowers, and said it would come up with a new proposal aimed at improving customer service for student loan payments.  \u2014 \u201cBy starting afresh and pursuing a truly modern loan servicing environment, we have a chance to turn what was a good plan into a great one,\u201d DeVos said in a statement.  \u2014 The Education Department announcement came several hours after a bipartisan group of senators unveiled legislation that would have blocked DeVos\u2019 plans. The bill \u2014 sponsored by Sens. Roy Blunt (R-Mo.), Elizabeth Warren (D-Mass.), James Lankford (R-Okla.) and Jeanne Shaheen (D-N.H.) \u2014 would require the department to keep its current system of \u201cmultiple student loan servicers.\u201d  \u2014 Liz Hill, a department spokeswoman, told POLITICO that the announcement on Tuesday was not a response to the legislation. The changes, she said, had \u201cbeen under consideration\u201d since DeVos tapped A. Wayne Johnson as the new head of student aid in June and he \u201cbrought his fresh perspective and private sector experience\u201d to the project.  \u2014 Warren said in a statement that she\u2019s \u201cglad the Education Department is changing course, but it will be important to continue watching the department to evaluate whether its decisions are good for the millions of struggling federal student loan borrowers.\u201d  \u2014 Rep. Virginia Foxx, chairwoman of the House education committee, said she believes DeVos \u201cmade the right decision to cancel the single-servicer proposal,\u201d spokesman Michael Woeste said in a statement to POLITICO.   \u2014 Senate HELP Chairman Lamar Alexander also praised DeVos\u2019 change in plans, saying the department\u2019s new approach \u201cshould make it simpler for students to manage their loans\u201d and that he hopes it \u201cwill result in competition and better service."  \u2014 What\u2019s next? Department officials said they will solicit feedback from student loan industry groups and \u201cvarious stakeholders\u201d as they develop a new plan. That new approach will involve a single platform for back-end processing and data storage. But department officials said they haven\u2019t yet decided whether to hire a single company or multiple providers for the consumer-facing account servicing. Michael Stratford has more here.  STATES LOOK TO FEDS FOR TESTING FLEXIBILITY: Florida, Kentucky and New Jersey are all asking federal officials for flexibility when it comes to testing in their plans under the Every Student Succeeds Act. Florida and New Jersey both want more wiggle room for a provision of the law that allows eighth-grade students enrolled in advanced math to avoid "double testing," letting them take an advanced math test for accountability and avoid taking their grade-level test. In a waiver request, New Jersey says it wants to extend that rule to lower middle school grades, not just eighth grade. \u201cSince so many New Jersey middle school students have been successful in advanced-level mathematics coursework, it is in the best interest of students to administer end-of-course mathematics assessments that align with students\u2019 coursework rather than the grade-level exam,\u201d the state says in its request.   \u2014 Florida says in its waiver request that it wants to do the same, in addition to including science tests. The state is also asking for flexibility on how it tests English-language learners. POLITICO Florida reported early last month that the state wants an expansive waiver from federal requirements in order to preserve a school grading system developed under former Gov. Jeb Bush.  \u2014 Kentucky is seeking a waiver of an ESSA provision that caps at 1 percent the number of students with disabilities that states can test on alternate assessments.   \u2014 How Education Secretary Betsy DeVos handles the requests will be watched closely. DeVos has emphasized flexibility for states as they implement ESSA, while also stressing that her agency will ensure plans adhere to the letter of the law. Some education policy experts believe DeVos\u2019 Education Department is reading the law too narrowly. And the department has come under fire from state education officials, experts and members of Congress who've found federal feedback to states on their ESSA plans inconsistent, confusing or heavy-handed.  \u2014 Speaking of ESSA: Michigan sent the Education Department a plan in May that included three possible options for how it will hold schools accountable \u2014 and reportedly faced criticism from federal officials for not deciding on one, even though DeVos said earlier this year that states could hand in their plans even if they still had to fill in some blanks. Michigan has since decided to ditch an A-F approach to grading schools, instead opting for a \u201cdashboard\u201d of data. More.   \u2014 Acting Assistant Secretary of Elementary and Secondary Education Jason Botel has been working to schedule calls with D.C. and seven states \u2014 Arizona, Colorado, Illinois, Maine, Michigan, North Dakota and Vermont \u2014 after the Education Department announced last week that it\u2019s changing the way it delivers ESSA feedback to states. State education officials from Michigan and Vermont tell Morning Education that they haven\u2019t had their call with federal officials yet.   \u2014 ICYMI, DeVos said Tuesday night that she\u2019s approving Delaware\u2019s ESSA plan, months after her department questioned the ambitiousness of the state's long-term goals. Delaware in recent weeks posted a revised plan defending those goals. DeVos said in a statement that the plan "embraces ESSA\u2019s spirit of flexibility and creative thinking." Caitlin Emma has more.  \u2014 And finally, on \u201cevidence\u201d \u2014 The Education Department earlier this week set out new requirements to better align definitions of research and evidence on school improvement in grant-making with what\u2019s outlined in ESSA. The agency will be accepting public comment for the next 30 days. More.   MOVERS AND SHAKERS   \u2014 The Education Department earlier this year hired Christopher Rinkus as a special assistant in the Office of Elementary and Secondary Education, press secretary Liz Hill confirms. Rinkus is working with Botel on implementing the Every Student Succeeds Act, sources tell Pro Education\u2019s Caitlin Emma. He previously worked for D.C. Public Schools, according to LinkedIn.   \u2014 The Education Department has also tapped Nicholas Hahn as director of speechwriting in the Office of Communications and Outreach, Hill confirms. Hahn was previously chief opinion editor for The Hill and assistant editorial page editor for The Detroit News, according to LinkedIn.   \u2014 Roberto Rodrguez, former deputy assistant to President Barack Obama for Education, has been selected by the board of directors at the national nonprofit Teach Plus to be the new president and CEO. Teach Plus works to ensure that teachers have access to leadership training and that disadvantaged students have access to effective teachers.   REPORT ROLL CALL   \u2014 D.C.\u2019s effort to link teacher pay and retention to performance has led to higher rates of turnover among the lowest-performing teachers while boosting student achievement, researchers from Stanford University and the University of Virginia find in a new research article for Education Next.   SYLLABUS  \u2014 Ohio state funding for the online charter school ECOT will take another 12 percent cut for the upcoming school year because of ongoing attendance concerns: The Plain Dealer.   \u2014 Former Education Secretary Arne Duncan is disappointed he never got a call from Education Secretary Betsy DeVos: Chalkbeat.   \u2014 Washington Attorney General argues the state has fulfilled its constitutional requirement to fund education, and says the state supreme court should drop a contempt order against the state: the Associated Press.   \u2014 DeVos pushes \u2018multitude of pathways\u2019 to degree at first public stop in her hometown: MLive.   \u2014 A federal autism committee wants to see funding for research into the developmental disorder doubled by 2020: Disability Scoop.   \u2014 California plan to start school later gets mixed grades: the Associated Press.   \u2014 DeVos is part of a weekly White House Bible study: CBN.   \u2014 Guns now allowed at Texas community colleges: USA Today.   Put your money on the Pro Education team. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
