aV \u000a            By MEL LEONOR  08/01/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Aubree Eliza Weaver  ED LOOKS TO REINSTATE CHARLOTTE LAW LOAN ACCESS, A BOON FOR EMBATTLED FOR-PROFIT COLLEGES: Education Secretary Betsy DeVos' Education Department plans to reinstate federal funding for a for-profit law school cut off from aid by the Obama administration \u2014 the latest sign that the Trump administration is taking a friendlier view toward the for-profit education industry. The Education Department said this week it plans to reinstate the Charlotte School of Law\u2019s ability to award Title IV funds if it agrees to certain conditions. The Obama Education Department blocked the for-profit school\u2019s access to the Federal Direct Loan Program last December, a month after the American Bar Association placed the school on probation \u2014 a status the association has yet to lift.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 Charlotte School of Law could be reinstated as soon as the fall, according to CSL spokeswoman Victoria Taylor. \u201cThe Department has specified certain conditions, with which the school must agree to comply in order to allow eligible CSL students enrolling for the fall semester to receive Federal Direct Loans,\u201d Taylor said in a written statement. \u201cThe school has notified the Department of its willingness to abide by the necessary conditions, details of which are under discussion.\u201d   \u2014 Both the school and the Education Department declined to discuss the conditions when reached by POLITICO. But according to a letter obtained by the American Bar Association Journal, the school must supply the department with a letter of credit to the tune of $6 million to cover a \u201cteach-out\u201d plan, student refunds and fines under Title IV of the Higher Education Act. The school must also agree to tightened admissions criteria and submit itself to the department\u2019s Heightened Cash Monitoring 1 program. An Education Department spokesman told POLITICO that discussions on the conditions are ongoing. \u201cUntil the discussions reach a successful conclusion, CSL will remain ineligible to participate in the Title IV programs,\u201d he said.   \u2014 When the department announced its would block the school\u2019s access to federal student loans last year, it cited the school\u2019s \u201csignificantly\u201d low bar pass rates and high academic attrition. In February 2016, just under 35 percent of first-time test takers from CSL passed the North Carolina bar, compared to the 51 percent statewide rate. The department also alleged that the school misrepresented its standing with the ABA after its accreditation was put on probation, as well as its bar pass rate. The school has argued that the decision to withdraw its eligibility for funds was made "without proper cause, justification or the barest semblance of due process."  \u2014 For Charlotte School of Law, it could mean a comeback from what observers saw as almost-certain closure. The Education Department\u2019s decision could help its case before the University of North Carolina system, which gave the school until early August to prove its financial stability or face having its license to operate revoked. Still, hurdles remain for the school: It has yet to firm up its standing with the American Bar Association and faces an investigation by North Carolina\u2019s Attorney General under the state\u2019s civil consumer protection laws.   GOOD TUESDAY MORNING AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. I\u2019m still donning summer florals and believe the best part of the summer still lies ahead. If that\u2019s you, too, then send your thoughts to these kids in Georgia, who went back to school yesterday \u2014 the last day of July. Reach me at mleonor@politico.com or @MelLeonor. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  A WAITING GAME IN ILLINOIS: After weeks of back-and-forth, statehouse Democrats in Illinois have delivered their plan to fund the state\u2019s public schools to the desk of Republican Gov. Bruce Rauner. The governor, who repeatedly vowed to amend the bill by veto and hailed the legislation as an unacceptable \u201cbailout\u201d of cash-strapped Chicago Public Schools, said through his office late Monday he would review it and take \u201cswift\u201d action.   \u2014 It\u2019s unclear what came out of a series of closed-door meetings held in Springfield through the weekend and into Monday. The Chicago Tribune reports Democrats claimed progress toward a deal, while Republicans called the negotiation a \u201cpolitical charade.\u201d   \u2014 In the operating theater are Illinois\u2019 800-plus school districts, where officials still don\u2019t know if funds for the first day of school will come from Springfield. School districts are due for funding in early August, and a special provision inserted in the budget by Democrats will hold those funds until Illinois enacts a new "evidence-based" funding formula. The proposal at the center of the debate sets a target level of funding for each district and doles out money from the bottom up to work towards equity. Right now, Illinois schools draw most of their funding from local tax dollars, meaning districts in low-income areas often have the fewest resources to educate their students. But the dispute hinges on the dollars earmarked for Chicago, which is set to receive additional funding, on top of state block grants, to help cover teacher pension payments. (CPS is the only district that controls its teachers' pensions.) This is the part Rauner has said he would amend by veto.   \u2018NAACP HAS CHOSEN TO STAND AS AN OBSTACLE\u2019: Two charter school leaders and school choice proponents blasted the NAACP this week for its report highlighting a \u201cwide range of problems\u201d present in U.S. charter schools. David Hardy, founder and chair of Boys' Latin Philadelphia Charter School, and who is African American, said the NAACP campaign against charters is \u201cdetrimental and disrespectful to all parents who struggle to ensure a quality education for their children.\u201d   \u2014 \u201cRather than embrace, and work to expand, the opportunities that charter schools represent to America\u2019s disadvantaged, and to families of color across the nation, the NAACP has chosen to stand as an obstacle,\u201d Hardy said. Donald Hense, founder and chairman of D.C.'s Friendship Public Charter Schools said the NAACP\u2019s anti-charter efforts \u201care the antithesis\u201d of its \u201clong history of fighting for justice and individual rights.\u201d   PARENT DISCONNECT: While most parents still believe in the importance of a college education, worries over academics have taken a backseat to fears surrounding bullying, physical safety and even financing a college degree, according to a new report from Learning Heroes. Part of this may stem from many parents\u2019 belief that their child is already on track and performing at grade level. Nine in 10 parents of K-8 students think their child is at or above grade level in reading and math, while data from the National Assessment of Educational Progress indicates that only one in three 8th graders are proficient in these subjects. Read the full report here.  NASA LOOKS TO INVOLVE MORE WOMEN AND GIRLS: In response to the INSPIRE Women Act, signed into law by President Donald Trump in February, NASA is taking steps to encourage women and girls to study STEM, pursue careers in aerospace and play a part in advancing the country\u2019s space science and exploration efforts. As of 2012, NASA was the largest STEM employer of women; one-third of the agency\u2019s approximately 18,000 civil-service workers are women.  \u2014 A new report shows that in addition to astronaut appearances and other popular speaker events, the agency plans to invest in three programs: NASA GIRLS & BOYS, a program that pairs middle school students with NASA employees for a virtual mentorship; Aspire to Inspire, which offers content such as short films about career opportunities in STEM through the lives of early career women at NASA; and the Summer Institute in Science, Technology, Engineering and Research, which allows middle school students to take a deeper look at nontraditional career fields with female engineers, mathematicians and scientists. In the next year or so, NASA plans to consider other ways to reach and engage girls and women.   VETERANS GROUP URGES SENATE PASSAGE OF GI BILL EXPANSION: Student Veterans of America, one of the largest veteran organizations in the country, is urging the Senate to pass legislation that would expand the education benefits under the GI Bill (S. 1598 (115)) before the August recess. The measure \u2014 which also restores GI Bill benefits for veterans affected by the closure of ITT Tech and Corinthian Colleges \u2014 unanimously passed the House last week and has 57 bipartisan co-sponsors in the Senate.   \u2014\u201cIt\u2019s time for our senators to guarantee this benefit for those who serve our country today and in the future, and get this done,\u201d SVA President and CEO Jared Lyon said in a statement. \u201cVeterans should be a top priority, and [this bill] should be at the top of the to-do list.\u201d  STATES INCH FORWARD ON COORDINATED DATA SYSTEMS: Currently just 37 states and D.C. connect data between at least two educational systems and only 16 states plus D.C. have systems that share data across early learning programs, the K-12 system, postsecondary institutions and the workforce. That\u2019s according to a new study by the Education Commission of the States, which found that a handful of states considered legislation to improve data coordination in 2016.   \u2014California enacted legislation last year to improve data sharing between its department of consumer affairs and its community college system to monitor employment outcomes of students who participated in career technical education programs. Four other states considered legislation: Alabama, New Jersey, Rhode Island and Virginia. Proposals failed in all but New Jersey, where a bill remains in the pipeline. That proposal would connect available data from students in early learning programs through their outcomes in the workforce.   REPORT ROLL CALL   \u2014 Fear of deportation under Trump\u2019s immigration policy is causing children emotional stress and economic instability, according to a new report from the Center for American Progress \u2014 and that could ultimately affect their development and future successes. In cases of parental deportation, children without a guardian in the U.S. could be forced to return to their parents\u2019 home country and make a challenging transition, the report says. Children who are separated from their parent \u2014 or even those who face the idea of separation \u2014 may display signs of stress and trauma, such as anxiety, depression and difficulty in school.  \u2014 Food insecurity (or not having reliable access to sufficient amounts of healthy, affordable food) continues to be a leading public health concern across the country. When seen in college students, food insecurity is often associated with \u201cpoorer health, poorer academic performance and mental health symptoms,\u201d according to a new Urban Institute report. The report shows that as of 2015, food insecurity in households with students enrolled in four-year colleges was at 11.2 percent, versus 13.5 percent in households with students pursuing vocational education. The rate among households with students attending two-year colleges dropped to approximately 13.3 percent after reaching new highs following the 2008 recession.  MOVERS AND SHAKERS  \u2014 Daniel Hamburger, former president and CEO of Adtalem Global Education (formerly DeVry Education Group) will serve as CEO of Renaissance, a pre-K\u201312 learning analytics firm.   SYLLABUS  \u2014 Students bring political debates home for the summer: The New York Times.  \u2014 Dual-language program boom could leave Latinos behind: The Hechinger Report.   \u2014 West Virginia rolls out new accountability system: West Virginia Metro News.   \u2014 Hawaii enacts new bond requirements for higher ed institutions: Honolulu Civil Beat.   \u2014 Florida law allows parents to dispute textbooks: NPR.  \u2014 New Mexico explores alternatives to higher education system: Las Cruces Sun-News.  \u2014 Exit interviews with outgoing LAUSD board members: Los Angeles Times.   \u2014 California mulls later start times: The Sacramento Bee.    Hope the High Road. Follow the Pro Education team. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com), @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com) and @MelLeonor_ (mleonor@politico.com).   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
