aV \u000a            By MICHAEL STRATFORD  07/31/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Caitlin Emma  DEMOCRATS BLAST DEVOS\u2019 CHANGES TO STATE ESSA PLAN FEEDBACK PROCESS: Top Democrats on the House and Senate education committees are criticizing the Trump administration\u2019s changes to how it provides feedback to states about their plans under the Every Student Succeeds Act. The department last week confirmed that it would first hold telephone calls with state officials about each state\u2019s ESSA plan before publicly posting its feedback about the plans \u2014 a change that critics worry will shield the back-and-forth between state and federal officials from public view.  Story Continued Below  \u2014 Sen. Patty Murray and Rep. Bobby Scott wrote in a letter to Education Secretary Betsy DeVos being released today that the \u201cconcerning changes\u201d violated the law\u2019s requirement for public transparency surrounding the state plan review process. \u201cA verbal agreement in a nonpublic setting is not an appropriate substitute for publicly available discourse with states,\u201d the lawmakers wrote. \u201cPut simply, if your staff needs more information to better understand a plan\u2019s components, so do parents, teachers, civil rights advocates, members of Congress, and other stakeholders.\u201d They also said it would \u201ccreate an uneven playing field for states\u201d for the department to change its feedback process in the middle of its review of state plans.  \u2014 Murray and Scott asked DeVos to produce a written justification for the change in policy as well as other documents relating to the changes. Read their full letter here.  \u2014 The over-the-phone feedback is meant to \u201cprovide an informal opportunity to address any potential concerns prior to plans being submitted\u201d for DeVos\u2019 review, said Education Department spokeswoman Liz Hill last week. "Secretary DeVos looks forward to reviewing plans and approving every plan that complies with the law,\u201d she added.   GOOD MONDAY MORNING AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. After five years on Capitol Hill, I\u2019m moving into a new neighborhood in D.C. today \u2014 anyone have recommendations for some good spots in Navy Yard? Drop me a line with your tips and feedback: mstratford@politico.com or @mstratford. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  WEST VIRGINIA INVESTIGATES AUDIT DELAY THAT LED TO FEDERAL SANCTIONS: West Virginia Gov. Jim Justice\u2019s office says it expects that state budget officials will be able to advance hundreds of millions of dollars to the state\u2019s public colleges and universities for the upcoming school year, minimizing the financial hit of new federal sanctions. The Education Department earlier this month imposed \u201cheightened cash monitoring\u201d restrictions on West Virginia\u2019s public higher education systems after the state was late in submitting annual financial paperwork to the department for a third year. The state\u2019s congressional delegation has lobbied Education Secretary Betsy DeVos to reverse those restrictions.  \u2014 The federal restrictions, which are unusual for a public college and university system, require that schools must first use their own funds to disburse federal student loans and grants to students \u2014 and then later receive reimbursement from the Education Department. The state will float extra money to the college and universities \u201cto handle student loans for the Fall semester,\u201d Justice\u2019s chief of staff, Nick Casey, said in a statement on Friday.  \u2014 The governor\u2019s office is also \u201cthoroughly reviewing the circumstances that led to the delay of the final completion and filing of the State\u2019s single audit for the last three years to find out exactly who is responsible,\u201d Casey said in the statement. \u201cIt\u2019s become obvious that there is a systemic bottleneck that got in the way of a timely audit being filed for 2014, 2015 and 2016.\u201d  \u2014 Meanwhile, Moody\u2019s Investors Services is warning that the sanctions could negatively affect the credit ratings of the state\u2019s colleges and universities. Moody\u2019s said in a report that the restrictions were a \u201ccredit negative\u201d for the schools because of the strain they could create on their cash flows. Read more.   BETTER UNDERSTANDING BACK TO SCHOOL: Understood.org, an organization devoted to supporting parents of children with learning and attention issues, is making a back-to-school push in the coming weeks. The group will launch a campaign to alleviate some of the pressure and anxiety that comes with the start of a new school year by offering customized materials for families and teachers, said Kevin Hager, managing director of Understood.   \u2014 For example, depending on a child\u2019s age and learning or attention issue, the organization might design a homework contract to help manage expectations between a child and his or her parents. Or families might fill out a custom worksheet describing how a child learns best, which can then be shared with teachers. Understood is also offering advice on what not to say before the start of a new school year. For example, parents might want to avoid saying things like, \u201cThere\u2019s going to be more homework this year,\u201d Hager said. Rather, the organization is encouraging families to \u201ccreate a sense of excitement around getting a fresh start,\u201d he said.   \u2014 Understood is also the organization behind \u201cThrough Your Child\u2019s Eyes\u201d \u2014 a tool that allows parents of children with learning and attention issues to get a sense of their child\u2019s experience through simulations and interviews with real students. About 10,000 people a week use the tool, which was developed two years ago with input from more than 100 experts on learning and attention issues, Hager said. Millions of people have visited the organization\u2019s website, Hager said, \u201cbut nothing resonates as much as \u2018Through Your Child\u2019s Eyes does.\u2019\u201d   COLLEGE BOARD TEAMS UP WITH KHAN ACADEMY FOR AP TEST PREP: The College Board announced a partnership with Khan Academy on Friday to deliver preparatory courses for its Advanced Placement tests on the online learning portal. David Coleman, College Board\u2019s president and CEO, said the offering will bring personalized learning to test preparation for its 38 AP exams and make the courses more accessible to students from a wider range of academic backgrounds. Read more.   EDUCATION GROUPS URGE TEXAS TO DROP \u2018BATHROOM BILL\u2019 EFFORT: A handful of education groups are urging Texas lawmakers to ditch an attempt to restrict transgender students' bathroom and locker room use. The groups, which include the American School Counselor Association, American Federation of Teachers and the National Association of Secondary School Principals, said in a letter sent last week that the so-called bathroom bills would "put some of the most vulnerable children, transgender children, at risk for increased bullying and segregation from school activities." The Senate passed a bill earlier this week, but the effort faces an uncertain future in the House, where the Republican speaker is a vocal critic. Read more.   MOVERS AND SHAKERS  \u2014 Ellen Sherratt is now the vice president for policy and research at the National Board for Professional Teaching Standards; she previously worked at the American Institute for Research\u2019s Center on Great Teachers and Leaders.  SYLLABUS  \u2014 U.C. Irvine rescinds acceptances for hundreds of applicants: The New York Times.  \u2014 Urban colleges and universities move into K-12 schools to help the cities where they operate and boost the flow of local students to attend their schools: The Wall Street Journal.  \u2014 How university leaders should plan for another year of campus-speech protests: The Chronicle of Higher Education.  \u2014 The ongoing battle between science teachers and fake news: NPR.  Big Shot. Follow the Pro Education team. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
