aV \u000a            By MICHAEL STRATFORD  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Caitlin Emma, Benjamin Wermund and Mel Leonor  EDUCATION DEPARTMENT HIRING HITS A WALL: The task of staffing the Education Department with fresh political faces appears to have hit a wall. Dozens of individuals have dropped out, frustrated by the drawn-out, rigorous hiring process. Those in the pipeline are wondering what\u2019s taking so long. And fewer folks are throwing their hats in the ring, doubting whether the Trump administration\u2019s pledge to dramatically expand private school choice options for working class families will ultimately go anywhere, according to multiple sources plugged into the hiring process. \u201cThe White House looks so chaotic, I think people are starting to wonder if you will be able to do much\u201d on education, one source told Pro Education\u2019s Caitlin Emma.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 Amid the chaos, the Hill doesn\u2019t seem interested in funding the president\u2019s school choice budget proposals and it\u2019s unclear if the White House will get behind a plan to expand private school choice through tax reform \u2014 a huge lift for Congress and the administration. Folks who support private school choice are \u201cincreasingly pessimistic,\u201d the source said. \u201cThere still seems to be people in the pipeline that could get through. But it seems like no one new is getting in line.\u201d  \u2014 Education Department press secretary Liz Hill said, \u201cWe are making progress on staffing and more announcements on are on the horizon soon. The notion that the secretary doesn\u2019t have an agenda is ridiculous. The secretary is championing a robust agenda to reduce the federal role in education, expand school choice and empower parents, retool the Higher Education Act for the 21st Century, and modernize [Federal Student Aid] to better serve students and taxpayers. The secretary hears from those inside and outside the government who are excited about her agenda and are ready and willing to help advance it.\u201d   \u2014 Political vacancies will make it more difficult for Education Secretary Betsy DeVos to figure out and implement an agenda. At least a quarter of the Education Department\u2019s political vacancies have been filled, but a number of potential hires have been held up, thwarted or vetoed by the White House or Education Department, sources say. The Office of Government Ethics, in particular, has presented enormous hurdles. For example, the rigorous financial expectations set out by the Office of Government Ethics prompted Allan Hubbard, an economic adviser during both Bush administrations, to drop out of the running for the Education Department\u2019s No. 2 job in early June. Rumored names of a potential front-runner for that position have yet to surface.   \u2014 A lack of senior political hires has failed to attract other talent, compounding the problem, sources say. And the political hires now at the Education Department have way too much on their plate. President Donald Trump has only formally nominated two individuals for politically appointed, Senate-confirmable positions: Sen. Lamar Alexander aide Peter Oppenheim as assistant secretary for legislation and congressional affairs, and Florida attorney Carlos Muiz as general counsel. Jim Blew, director of the education advocacy group, Student Success California, is the front-runner to become the Education Department\u2019s assistant secretary of the Office of Planning, Evaluation and Policy Development \u2014 but has yet to be formally nominated.   \u2014 A White House spokesman declined to comment on personnel issues, but stressed the Trump administration\u2019s education accomplishments to date. For example, the spokesman pointed to the president\u2019s decision this week to donate his quarterly salary to the Education Department for a STEM-focused camp, among other things. \u201cUnder President Trump\u2019s leadership, Secretary DeVos has increased stakeholder engagement and rolled back harmful restrictions to ensure America\u2019s schools are helping students,\u201d the spokesman said.   GOOD FRIDAY MORNING AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. Drop me a line with your tips and feedback: mstratford@politico.com or @mstratford. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  WARREN PRESSES TRUMP NOMINEE OVER DEVOS\u2019 RESPONSES TO CONGRESS: Sen. Elizabeth Warren (D-Mass.) on Thursday signaled that she may put up a fight over President Donald Trump\u2019s nominee to be the Education Department\u2019s top liaison to Congress, citing what she said was Secretary Betsy DeVos\u2019 lack of responsiveness to Democrats\u2019 inquiries. Warren wrote in a letter to Peter Oppenheim, Trump\u2019s pick to be assistant secretary of education for legislation and congressional affairs, that she was concerned that the Trump administration\u2019s Education Department \u201chas been negligent in its duty to respond substantively, completely, and thoroughly to Members of Congress.\u201d  \u2014 The Trump administration \u201chas been either totally unresponsive to our oversight letters, or it has responded with paltry rhetoric and talking points that plainly ignore urgent document and information requests or do not completely answer our questions,\u201d Warren wrote, adding that it was impeding \u201cstrong\u201d congressional oversight of the department.  \u2014 Warren pressed Oppenheim, who is currently an aide to Sen. Lamar Alexander (R-Tenn.), on whether he would \u201ccommit to doing everything within your power to obtain substantive and complete responses\u201d to congressional Democrats\u2019 inquiries. Read the full letter here.  \u2014 What to watch next: The nomination for assistant secretary for congressional and legislative affairs is \u201cprivileged,\u201d which puts it on an expedited path to consideration on the Senate floor, bypassing a committee markup. But any Senator could object to that process and force a committee vote. The clock for making such an objection began on July 19, and lasts for 10 legislative days.   HIGHER ED GROUPS CALL ON IRAN TO RELEASE IMPRISONED STUDENT: A slew of American higher education groups are calling on Iran to release a Princeton graduate student who was accused of espionage while conducting research in Iran and sentenced to 10 years in prison. In a statement issued this week, several groups, led by the American Council on Education, write that Xiyue Wang described his research plans in advance to the Iranian authorities and the libraries and archives he planned to visit, and he only sought materials that he needed for his dissertation. His research was solely for the purpose of completing his academic work. \u201cMr. Wang\u2019s imprisonment can only have a chilling effect on historical research and scholarly exchange in Iran and throughout the world, and this, in turn, can only lead to diminished understanding and greater mistrust, to the detriment of all,\u201d the statement says. Read it here.   HOT DOCUMENTS: The Education Department has released the transcripts from the two hearings it held earlier this month to solicit public feedback on how to rewrite the Obama-era \u201cgainful employment\u201d and \u201cborrower defense to repayment\u201d rules. Read the hearing transcript from the Washington D.C. hearing here, and the Dallas, Texas one here.  \u2014 Next up in the process: The Education Department is expected to solicit nominations for the two negotiated-rulemaking panels that it has said it plans to convene later this year.   EDUCATION DEPARTMENT PLANS CHANGES TO ESSA FEEDBACK AMID BLOWBACK: The Education Department is changing the way it delivers feedback to states under the Every Student Succeeds Act. This summer, the department has been publicly posting letters to states outlining initial comments or concerns, in addition to comments from a team of experts known as peer reviewers. Now, the agency will first discuss peer reviewer comments with states over the phone, giving them an opportunity to address any issues before a letter is posted publicly.    \u2014 The change could potentially shield the back-and-forth between state and federal officials over the development of state ESSA plans from public view. It will likely raise transparency concerns from education policy wonks closely watching the implementation process. It comes after months of blowback from state education officials, education policy experts and members of Congress who've found the Education Department's feedback to states inconsistent, confusing or heavy-handed.   \u2014 Jason Botel, the acting assistant secretary of the Office of Elementary and Secondary Education, is now working to schedule calls with eight states: Arizona, Colorado, D.C., Illinois, Maine, Michigan, North Dakota and Vermont. Caitlin Emma has more here.   DEVOS BOOSTS STAKE IN NEUROCORE: Education Secretary Betsy DeVos has increased her financial stake in a \u201cneurofeedback\u201d company that says its technology treats attention deficit disorder and the symptoms of autism. DeVos reported a new investment of between $250,001 and $500,000 in the Michigan-based Neurocore, according to a financial disclosure form that was certified by government ethics officials on Wednesday.  \u2014 The June 13 purchase of new shares of Neurocore adds to DeVos\u2019 previously reported stake in the company that was valued at $5 million to $25 million on the disclosure form she filed in January. DeVos said earlier this year that she had stepped down from the Neurocore board but government ethics officials did not require her to shed her financial interest in the company.  \u2014 Neurocore, a \u201cbrain performance\u201d company, says its biofeedback therapies are aimed at improving the cognitive performance of children and adults and addressing a wide range of problems such as anxiety, stress, attention deficit disorder and autism symptoms. But some experts have questioned the company\u2019s methods and claims.  \u2014 DeVos also reported a new investment of between $50,001 and $100,000 in Move Systems, a company that makes high-tech and environmentally friendly food carts. She also purchased a $100,001 to $250,000 stake in the Orlando Solar Bears, a minor league professional hockey team. Read more here.   REPORT ROLL CALL   \u2014 Incidents of violence and reports of bullying are more prevalent in U.S. middle schools than in high schools, according to new data from the National Center for Education Statistics. In the 2015-16 school year, the survey found, middle schools reported 27 violent incidents per 1,000 students, compared to 16 incidents in high schools and 15 in elementary schools. As for incidents of bullying, 22 percent of middle schools reported incidents at least once a week, compared to 15 percent of high schools and 8 percent of elementary schools.  MOVERS AND SHAKERS  \u2014 Members of the National Association for Gifted Children, or NAGC, have elected Jonathan Plucker, the Julian C. Stanley Professor of Talent Development at Johns Hopkins University, as the organization\u2019s next board president-elect.   SYLLABUS  \u2014 Private colleges together hold more than $350 billion in endowments \u2014 more than twice all other groups combined: The Chronicle of Philanthropy.   \u2014 Ashford University notches win in GI Bill dispute: Inside Higher Ed.  \u2014 Measuring clicks, emotions, and brain waves: college recruitment keeps evolving: The Chronicle of Higher Education.  \u2014 Judge rules against charter schools in Florida funding case: The Tampa Bay Times.  \u2014 The latest filing in a Title IX lawsuit against Baylor alleges Ken Starr knew about a domestic violence allegation against a football player while he was president of Baylor \u2014 yet did nothing to rectify the matter for the alleged victim even after a personal meeting with the player: The Waco Tribune-Herald.   Blank Space. Follow the Pro Education team. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
