aV \u000a            By BENJAMIN WERMUND  07/27/2017 10:00 AM EDT  \u000a                    Updated 07/27/2017 10:25 AM EDT  With help from Caitlin Emma, Michael Stratford and Mel Leonor  CAMPUS SPEECH BACK IN CONGRESS\u2019 SPOTLIGHT: Republicans continue to ramp up pressure on colleges to preserve free speech on campus and do away with free speech zones and other policies they deem restrictive. Today, the House Oversight and Government Reform Committee's Intergovernmental Affairs Subcommittee and Health Care, Benefits and Administrative Rules Subcommittee will tackle the issue in a joint hearing featuring conservative comedian Adam Carolla and conservative commentator Ben Shapiro, who have both claimed college administrators have trampled their right to free speech.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 \u201cThe First Amendment is under attack on campuses across the country,\u201d Rep. Jim Jordan (R-Ohio), who chairs the House Oversight and Government Reform Committee, Health Care, Benefits and Administrative Rules Subcommittee, said in a statement. Jordan called Carolla and Shapiro \u201ctwo of the best defenders of free speech.\u201d  \u2014 In written testimony, Carolla rails against \u201csafe spaces\u201d on campuses. \u201cInstead of fostering the development of young adults, colleges are providing coloring books, play-doh, puppies, and stuffed animals,\u201d the testimony says. \u201cIt\u2019s basically your four-year-old daughter\u2019s bedroom where one can shut out the challenges and facts of the outside world. Providing this bubble wrapped type of education does not prepare the next generation for the challenges of life. It prepares them for failure.\u201d   \u2014 Shapiro, in written testimony, complains about the concept of \u201cmicro-aggressions\u201d \u2014 comments or actions seen as indirect or unintentional discrimination against members of a marginalized group \u2014 which he says have been used to justify violence against speakers who voice views that some find offensive. \u201cAll of this destroys free speech,\u201d he writes. \u201cBut just as importantly, it turns students into snowflakes, craven and pathetic, looking for an excuse to be offended so they can earn points in the intersectional Olympics and then use those points as a club with which to beat opponents.\u201d  \u2014 The hearing comes after Rep. Phil Roe (R-Tenn.) earlier this week said he would be open to cutting off federal funding for colleges that restrict speech. The House Education and the Workforce Committee member blasted colleges for carving out free speech zones and uninviting speakers with views that some find offensive. "If this, to me, offensive behavior continues to occur across the country, I would certainly be open to looking at how, maybe you don't need federal funding if you don't allow people to speak freely on your campus," Roe said. That sentiment appears to be shared by President Donald Trump, who earlier this year threatened the University of California-Berkeley in a tweet after administrators there canceled a speech by alt-right figure Milo Yiannopoulos following violent riots.  \u2014 Michael Zimmerman, a former provost and vice president for academic affairs at Evergreen State College who is set to testify today, will challenge the notion that government needs to intervene. \u201cWhat we don\u2019t need is additional legislation to be brought into the mix,\u201d Zimmerman says in written testimony. \u201cCollege administrators need the courage to do what is right, to stand for principles rather than expediency, and to risk alienating some in the name of those principles. On campuses where such strong leadership exists, conflict rarely escalates to crisis.\u201d Zimmerman recently criticized Evergreen State administrators for their handling of recent protests that embroiled the campus.  \u2014 Also testifying at today\u2019s hearing are Nadine Strossen, a law professor at the New York Law School, and Fred Lawrence of the Anti-Defamation League. The hearing begins at 9 a.m. in 2154 Rayburn House Office Building. Watch a livestream here.   GOOD THURSDAY MORNING AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. I\u2019m planning a trip to Philadelphia this weekend and want to do something outdoors. Any tips for good hikes or swimming holes not too far from town? Let me know: bwermund@politico.com or @BenjaminEW. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  TODAY: MICHELLE OBAMA VISITS WITH D.C. STUDENTS: Michelle Obama today is meeting with nearly three dozen students \u2014 all first-generation, rising college freshmen \u2014 at Dunbar High School in D.C. They\u2019ll talk about what it takes to succeed in college. The conversation is closed to the media, in part to keep the discussion candid, a spokeswoman told Morning Education. Obama will be joined by ESPN commentator Michael Wilbon. The discussion is part of the former first lady\u2019s Reach Higher initiative, aimed at inspiring all students to pursue and complete a postsecondary degree, particularly underserved students. Earlier this year, Obama surprised D.C. students at Ballou High School and Cardozo Education Campus, holding similar conversations. Reach Higher today is also launching a PSA encouraging students to commit to higher education, featuring celebrities like Allison Williams, Kelly Rowland, Connie Britton, Wale and Kal Penn. Watch the PSA.   TRUMP ADMINISTRATION HASN\u2019T APPROVED ANY DEBT RELIEF CLAIMS: Acting Undersecretary of Education James Manning said in a letter to senators earlier this month that the Education Department has not approved any borrower defense to repayment claims since President Trump took office \u2014 despite having received nearly 15,000 additional applications for such loan forgiveness over the past several months. \u201cNo borrower defense applications have been approved between January 20, 2017, and today,\u201d Manning wrote in a July 7 letter, which was released on Wednesday by Sen. Dick Durbin (D-Ill.). Durbin and other Democrats have been critical of the administration\u2019s decision to halt approvals of the claims.  \u2014 The Trump administration has carried out the loan forgiveness that was promised to some borrowers by the Education Department before the change in administration. The department, Manning said, has executed the loan forgiveness for 26,372 of the 31,773 claims previously approved by the Obama administration. The remaining 5,401 claims are \u201cin progress.\u201d  \u2014 Manning said in the letter that, in total, more 65,169 claims for loan forgiveness remain pending before the Education Department. The bulk of those pending claims, 45,092 of them, are from borrowers who claim they were defrauded by the now-defunct Corinthian Colleges. The others are from borrowers associated with ITT Tech (7,186 claims), Education Management Corporation (2,175 claims), DeVry University (1,872 claims) and University of Phoenix (1,306).  \u2014 Read the full letter from Manning here. See a state-by-state breakdown of new borrower defense claims received during the Trump administration here and the overall breakdown of all pending claims here.   FORDHAM\u2019S TAKE ON STATE ESSA PLANS: The Fordham Institute is out with its own review of state plans under the Every Student Succeeds Act. Some independent reviews have found the first 17 state plans submitted to the Education Department lacking, either in ambition or detail. But Fordham, a conservative education think tank, is assigning those states mostly \u201cstrong\u201d and \u201cmedium\u201d marks. The reviews are a little more positive because the think tank is only evaluating plans on three metrics, said Brandon Wright, Fordham\u2019s editorial director. Those metrics include: whether states are assigning clear, understandable ratings to schools; whether states are focusing on all students, not just low-performers; and whether state accountability systems fairly measure and judge all schools, including high-poverty schools. Arizona, Colorado and Illinois earn the highest marks in all three categories, followed by Connecticut, D.C. and Vermont, which also earned high marks. More.  SECRETARY DEVOS, YOU\u2019VE GOT MAIL: A bipartisan group of 20 lawmakers sent a letter to Education Secretary Betsy DeVos and her acting civil rights chief Candice Jackson urging them to continue publishing a list of colleges and universities under investigation for allegedly mishandling sexual violence claims. Jackson said last month that she may stop publishing the list, which she called a \u201clist of shame.\u201d The Obama administration began publishing the list in 2014 under pressure from sexual assault survivors. \u201cEnding sexual violence on our college campuses will never become a reality if college and university communities are kept in the dark,\u201d the letter, led by Reps. Jackie Speier (D-Calif.), Patrick Meehan (R-Pa.), Annie Kuster (D-N.H.), and David Joyce (R-Ohio), who all co-chair the Bipartisan Task Force to End Sexual Violence, says. The administration did release the list this week. It included 346 investigations at 243 institutions and showed the department had opened three new investigations into alleged violations of Title IX by colleges and universities \u2014 but also closed two probes as it seeks to cut down on the backlog. More on that here.   \u2014 A coalition of more than 60 members of Congress also sent a letter to DeVos Wednesday, urging her to work on reducing \u201cexcessive\u201d discipline in schools. The letter urges DeVos to continue the work undertaken by the Obama administration to reduce the number of out-of-school suspensions, specially among young students, and address the disproportionate disciplining of students of color and those with disabilities. The letter was signed by 68 members of Congress \u2014 all Democrats \u2014 including Sen. Patty Murray (D-Wash.) and Rep. Bobby Scott (D-Va.). In it, they point out the Education Department\u2019s \u201cobligation\u201d to work on the issue under the Every Student Succeeds Act, which calls on states to address the overuse of suspensions in the plans they\u2019re required to submit to the department. The review process, the letter reads, should ensure that state education agencies adequately \u201cdevelop proactive discipline approaches rather than suspensions, expulsions, seclusion and restraint.\u201d Read the letter.  \u2014 Another group of Democrats, also led by Murray, sent another letter to DeVos urging her to reverse course on a decision to delay an aspect of \u201cgainful employment\u201d rules that requires schools to disclose, such as how many students complete programs on time and how much graduates earn. The Trump administration is rewriting the Obama-era regulations, which would cut off funding for career colleges that produce graduates with more debt than income. Read that letter, signed by 59 members of the Senate and House, here.   TEXAS \u2018BATHROOM BILL\u2019 AGAIN FACES UNCERTAIN FUTURE IN HOUSE: As expected, Republicans in the Texas Senate again advanced efforts to restrict transgender bathroom use, as they did during the legislature\u2019s regular session, but those efforts now head to the House, where they face significant resistance from key lawmakers. House Speaker Joe Straus, a Republican, is a vocal critic of the so-called bathroom bills, which would force transgender students and athletes to use bathrooms and locker rooms associated with the sex listed on their birth certificates. The chairman of the House Committee on State Affairs, the first hurdle bathroom bills will have to clear in the lower chamber, meanwhile, criticized the efforts on Wednesday. More from the Dallas Morning News.   MOVERS AND SHAKERS   \u2014 Members of the National Association of Secondary School Principals have elected Christine Handy, principal of Gaithersburg High School in Gaithersburg, Md., as the organization\u2019s new president-elect.   REPORT ROLL CALL   \u2014 The majority of young people believe mental health is a very important priority, but more than a third of high school students say their schools don\u2019t cover mental health in any class at school. That\u2019s according to a new report from the Born This Way Foundation, led by pop star Lady Gaga and her mother, Cynthia Germanotta.   \u2014The Institute of Education Sciences, the Education Department\u2019s independent research arm, is seeking input on its education and special education research programs. IES wants to know whether some of its goals \u201care meeting the needs of the field, or whether changes should be considered to incentivize and support more replication and effectiveness studies.\u201d More.  SYLLABUS  \u2014 New York bans e-cigs in schools: CBS New York.   \u2014 Fifteen DACA recipients, protesters detained after pro-immigrant rights sit-in outside Texas Capitol: The Austin American-Statesman.  \u2014 Trump struggles to find a head for the White House initiative on HBCUs: The Chronicle of Higher Education.   \u2014 Facing a massive shortfall, Wyoming will explore new methods for funding education: Casper Star-Tribune.   \u2014 Oklahoma charter school applications could be a barrier to enrollment: The Oklahoman.   \u2014 Some rural Texas school districts can\u2019t get a single applicant for a teaching job: The Dallas Morning News.   The Pro Education team. Surrender to the sound. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  CORRECTION:  A previous version of Morning Education misstated the date of acting Undersecretary of Education James Manning's letter to Sen. Dick Durbin. The letter was written July 7.  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson  \u000a       