aV \u000a            By CAITLIN EMMA  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Benjamin Wermund and Mel Leonor  NAACP REPORT FINDS \u2018WIDE RANGE OF PROBLEMS\u2019 WITH CHARTER SCHOOLS: After calling for a moratorium on charter school expansion last year, the NAACP today is releasing a highly anticipated report that calls for the elimination of for-profit charter school operators. The report concludes that \u201cwhile there are certainly some charter schools serving students well, there are also a wide range of problems with the operation of charters across the country that require attention.\u201d And it stresses the need to "protect students from failing schools and create more high quality schools, regardless of the school\u2019s structure.\u201d   Story Continued Below  \u2014 \u201cAll children deserve the choice of a good neighborhood public school,\u201d the report says. \u201cPublic schools must be public. They must serve all children equitably and well. To the extent that they are part of our public education system, charter schools must be designed to serve these ends.\u201d   \u2014 The report comes as race has emerged as a focal point in ongoing sparring over the Trump administration\u2019s efforts to expand school choice policies. While those arguments have centered largely on private school vouchers, the NAACP\u2019s stance on charter schools is significant, in part, because charters \u2014 for which the Trump administration wants to boost funding \u2014 are very popular among many black parents. Approximately 837,000 Black students attended charter schools during the 2016-17 school year, according to the report. That\u2019s more than a quarter of charter school enrollment, while black students make up just 15 percent of the nation's overall enrollment.   \u2014 Those tensions were highlighted this week when Howard Fuller, a civil rights activist, former Milwaukee schools superintendent and founder of the Institute for the Transformation of Learning at Marquette University, blasted the NAACP's moratorium call. The NAACP has the right to express its opposition to charter schools, Fuller said, but thousands of parents have already shown their support for choosing to send their children to charter schools. \u201cI\u2019m a strong supporter of the NAACP," he said. "But the reality is, the NAACP doesn\u2019t represent all black people in this country.\u201d  \u2014 The report is the result of the work of the NAACP Task Force on Quality Education, which the NAACP formed after calling for the charter moratorium. The group was initially tasked with studying only charters, but its aim was expanded after President Donald Trump was elected. \u201cBased upon the United States President-Elect\u2019s campaign promise to expand privatization of public education, the officers were concerned that the 1954 Brown vs. Board of Education victory that promised a quality education for all was at risk,\u201d the report says. The task force held a series of listening sessions in cities across the country, including in New Haven, Memphis, Orlando, Los Angeles, Detroit, New Orleans and New York.   \u2014 Much of the report focuses on funding. It calls for \u201cmore equitable and adequate funding for all schools serving students of color\u201d and for an investment in \u201clow-performing schools and schools with significant opportunity to close the achievement gap.\u201d The report also says that school finance reform is needed and calls for states to model their funding formulas off of Massachusetts and California and for the federal government should fully enforce the funding-equity provisions in Every Student Succeeds Act. Benjamin Wermund has more.   \u2014 The task force will present its findings this afternoon at the NAACP National Convention in Baltimore. Watch a livestream here.   GOOD WEDNESDAY MORNING, JULY 26. I\u2019m REALLY invested in following the progress of Fiona, the Cincinnati Zoo\u2019s star baby hippo. If you\u2019re not familiar, Fiona was born six weeks premature in January. Zookeepers weren\u2019t sure she\u2019d make it, but she has since defied the odds, becoming the zoo\u2019s biggest attraction. Get your #FionaFix here. And here\u2019s a bonus video celebrating her 6 month birthday this week. (It might\u2019ve made me emotional.) Talk to me at cemma@politico.com or @caitlinzemma. Send events to: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  RIP \u2018EDIBLES\u2019 Bad news for Morning Education readers who love a good pun: the Education Department\u2019s cafeteria, once called \u201cEDibles,\u201d has been renamed \u201cMarketplace.\u201d But don\u2019t blame Education Secretary Betsy DeVos \u2014 the vendor that contracts with the General Services Administration to provide food services at the Education Department has decided to shake up its marketing and branding, said press secretary Liz Hill, which led to the demise of the pun-tastic name.   ON THE HILL TODAY: A House Education and the Workforce subcommittee will hold a hearing on \u201cExpanding Options for Employers and Workers Through Earn-and-Learn Opportunities.\u201d Lawmakers will hear about opportunities for workers to earn a paycheck while getting trained in a high-skilled job. They\u2019ll also hear about changes to the Labor Department\u2019s Registered Apprenticeship program aimed at increasing employer participation. Witnesses include Mike Bennett, vice president of Cianbro, a construction company in Pittsfield, Maine; Stacey Johnson Hughes, state chair of the Kentucky Federation for Advanced Manufacturing Education in Russellville, Ky.; Robert Peglow, a student with KYFAME; and Rob Hogan, vice president of manufacturing and material distribution for Newport News Shipbuilding in Newport News, Va. The hearing starts at 10 a.m. in 2175 Rayburn. Watch live.   \u2014 Also happening on the Hill: The Senate Veterans' Affairs Committee holds a markup of S. 1598 (115), bipartisan legislation that would expand the education benefits offered to veterans under the GI Bill. The House overwhelmingly passed an identical version of the bill on Monday. The markup starts at 11 a.m. in the Capitol, S-216.  \u2014 A House Science, Space, and Technology subcommittee will hold a hearing on \u201cSTEM and Computer Science Education: Preparing the 21st Century Workforce.\u201d Witnesses include: James Brown, executive director of the STEM Education Coalition; Pat Yongpradit, chief academic officer for Code.org; A. Paul Alivisatos, executive vice chancellor and provost at the University of California, Berkeley; and Dee Mooney, executive director of the Micron Technology Foundation. The hearing begins at 10 a.m. in 2318 Rayburn.  \u2014 And a report released today by Democrats on the U.S. Joint Economic Committee says that while more Americans are attending and completing degree programs, \u201csharp divisions\u201d in access remain \u201cby income level, race, ethnicity, and geography.\u201d The report calls on Congress to \u201cclose educational attainment gaps\u201d to make sure \u201call Americans have the ability to find a good job that pays well and provides a foundation for their family\u2026 Making college more affordable, giving students access to better information about their options, and better preparing high school students for the rigors of college are all goals that Congress must pursue.\u201d Read the report.   CHILDHOOD WELL-BEING: A new report from the Forum on Child and Family Statistics on the well-being of children found a decrease in the number of school-aged children who speak a language other than English at home and have difficulty speaking English. In 2015, according to the report, that number was 4 percent, compared to 5 percent in 2015. Researchers looked at a few dozen other indicators on childhood well-being in the U.S. and found a decrease in the number of eighth graders using illicit drugs from 8 percent in 2015 to 7 percent in 2016, and reported a decrease in the number of adolescent births from 11 per 1,000 live births in 2014 to 10 per 1,000 in 2015.   \u2014 Researchers also analyzed peer victimization in the third grade, and found that 6 percent of students in their sample were identified as perpetrators, meaning they frequently teased, hit or told lies about other students. Among these students, roughly one in ten reported they were also frequently victimized. Read the report here.  DEVOS, TRUMP AND THE SUMMER READING SLIDE: Education Secretary Betsy DeVos and Adviser to the President Ivanka Trump teamed up Tuesday for a STEM-focused reading event at the National Museum of American History. The event was aimed at raising awareness about the \u201csummer reading slide,\u201d or when students fall behind in reading over the summer. They took turns reading \u201cRosie Revere, Engineer\u201d by Andrea Beaty to a group of D.C.-area girls with the YMCA and the Boys & Girls Club. Trump said her daughter, Arabella, loves the book, which is about a girl who dreams of becoming an engineer. When one student noted that Rosie \u201cpersevered,\u201d Trump said, \u201cGood word!\u201d While DeVos and Trump didn\u2019t take questions from reporters, they entertained questions and comments from the students. \u201cYou are the next generation,\u201d Trump told the girls, encouraging them to grow up to be inventors, engineers and coders. After the reading session, DeVos and Trump worked on some STEM-focused projects with the students. Pictures here, here and here.   MOVERS AND SHAKERS   \u2014 Marjorie Hass, former chair of the board of directors of the National Association of Independent Colleges and Universities, has began her tenure as the 20th president of Rhodes College July 2017.   REPORT ROLL CALL   \u2014 The Education Trust, a nonprofit, is out with new case studies of high-poverty, high-performing schools that find the more \u201csystematic\u201d and \u201cpurposeful\u201d a school is about promoting access to Advanced Placement exams, \u201cthe more likely it is to achieve high levels of success.\u201d More.   SYLLABUS  \u2014 Student loan borrowers, herded into default, face a relentless collector: the U.S. Reuters.   \u2014 Texas Senate approves bills on "private school choice" and school finance study: The Texas Tribune.   \u2014 Alabama state board of education gives superintendent low marks on evaluation: AL.com.  \u2014 Who Is Betsy DeVos? And how did she get to be head of our schools? NYMag.   \u2014 Diana Rauner appears in new ad praising Illinois governor's support for education: Chicago Tribune.   \u2014 Utah unions, education advocates organizing march in response to Trump, DeVos policies: The Salt Lake Tribune.   \u2014 New Mexico student reading scores up, math stagnant: The Associated Press.   \u2014 D.C. looks to students for ways to address chronic absenteeism: The Washington Post.   \u2014 Robots, race cars and weather: Girl Scouts offer new badges: The Associated Press.   Break the silence and follow the Pro Education team: @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
