aV \u000a            By MICHAEL STRATFORD  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Caitlin Emma, Benjamin Wermund and Mel Leonor  THE SPARRING OVER VOUCHERS CONTINUES: Proponents of private school vouchers on Monday held a call with reporters to rail against a recent report backed by the American Federation of Teachers and Center for American Progress that describes the \u201cracist origins of private school vouchers.\u201d The rebuttal comes after days of pitched fighting in the education community sparked by the report, which looks at how Virginia\u2019s Prince Edward County sought to avoid racial integration more than 60 years ago through vouchers. Critics believe the report illustrates the potential consequences of the Trump administration\u2019s support for federal investment in voucher expansion.  Story Continued Below  \u2014 Derrell Bradford, executive vice president of 50CAN, an education reform advocacy organization, said the public school system is often \u201cthe biggest, most pernicious engine of segregation in American culture.\u201d New Jersey has \u201ca constitutional provision against school segregation, yet has among the most segregated schools in America,\u201d he said. Bradford said the American Federation of Teachers and the Center for American Progress should \u201cknow better and it's sad that they've elected to take this line of reasoning on this issue." More.  \u2014 Darrell Allison, president of Parents for Educational Freedom in North Carolina, an advocacy group, said thousands of low-income families in the state are applying for private school scholarships to escape failing public schools. \u201cYou know in our state we have 2,450 traditional public schools, and poor low-income, mostly minority children are disproportionately assigned to public schools with letter grade D or F. So when we make broad strokes statements that public schools are places of \u2018endless opportunities\u2019 \u2026 for that low-income parent in North Carolina, when faced with the reality of schools the system assigned their precious child to, there\u2019s nothing great about that. More.  \u2014 Catherine Brown, vice president of education policy at CAP, said in response to Monday\u2019s criticism that, \u201cIt\u2019s disappointing to see certain advocates of voucher programs trying to shout down a historically accurate account of the history of vouchers \u2014 a history that is rooted in racism and segregation, and a history that everyone in this country has a responsibility to acknowledge in order to not repeat the mistakes of past. While the silence on voucher program\u2019s racist history from DeVos and Trump is deafening, the swift defensiveness and hostility from some voucher advocates has been alarming. American students deserve reassurance that they will not face taxpayer funded discrimination and a government that believes in the importance of public education.\u201d Brown also penned an op-ed last week titled, \u201cThe History of School Vouchers Isn\u2019t Flattering.\u201d Read it.   GOOD TUESDAY MORNING AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. Drop me a line with your tips and feedback: mstratford@politico.com or @mstratford. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  DEVOS TODAY: Education Secretary Betsy DeVos will join Ivanka Trump for a summer reading event this morning at 10:30 a.m. at the Smithsonian\u2019s National Museum of American History. The summer reading initiative \u201cwill focus specifically on getting girls excited about science, technology, engineering and math,\u201d according to the Education Department. Watch live here.   HIGHER ED GROUPS SEEK EXTENSION OF AUTOMATIC PELL GRANT INCREASES: More than 300 advocacy groups and institutions of higher education today are urging Congress to extend annual increases in Pell grant funding that are pegged to inflation. For the past five years, a mandatory \u201cadd-on\u201d award has boosted the value of the Pell grant above what Congressional appropriators provide for the program each year. The amount of that \u201cadd-on\u201d is adjusted each year to account for changes in the Consumer Price Index \u2014 and it\u2019s funded through mandatory appropriations rather than being subject to the discretion of Congress each year.  \u2014 Mandatory \u201cadd-on\u201d increases in recent years have allowed the amount of the maximum Pell grant to increase even as Congressional appropriators kept their discretionary funding of the program at the same level. But the provision linking the amount of the \u201cadd-on\u201d to inflation each year \u2013 which was signed into law by President Barack Obama in 2010 \u2013 will expire at the end of the 2017-18 school year.  \u2014 \u201cAbsent Congressional action, the maximum Pell Grant award will no longer adjust with inflation after this upcoming school year,\u201d the groups write in a letter, which was organized by The Education Trust. \u201cAs costs for students continue to rise, ending the annual inflation adjustment is \u2014 in real terms \u2014 a cut to the value of the Pell Grant.\u201d Read it here.   RESISTANCE TO TEXAS BATHROOM BILLS GROWS: The Texas Association of Business has brought out the big guns in its effort to sink legislation that would restrict bathroom use for transgender students: Football. The group is behind a $1 million ad buy that focuses on the Dallas Cowboys\u2019 efforts to bring the 2018 NFL draft to Texas. The ad, which will begin playing on radio stations today, argues that if the \u201cbathroom bills\u201d pass, the NFL, which has voiced opposition to the bills, could reject the Cowboys\u2019 bid to host the festivities, the Dallas Morning News reports.   \u2014 Texas Republicans have proposed a handful of bills during the state\u2019s special session that would restrict bathroom use and would prohibit school districts, cities and counties from passing ordinances to \u201cprotect a class of persons from discrimination\u201d by allowing them to use the bathroom of their choice. Similar efforts failed during the regular session, but Gov. Greg Abbott revived them for the special session that he called. They have the support of Senate leadership, but the House speaker has vocally opposed them.   \u2014 Several police chiefs from major Texas cities, as well as the mayor of Austin, will protest the bill at the state capitol today. Those cities include Austin, Houston and San Antonio. The superintendent of a San Antonio school district is also slated to appear at the rally, a livestream of which can be found here at noon. The state\u2019s former education commissioner, Michael Williams, meanwhile, voiced opposition to the bathroom bills in a tweet he posted on Monday. \u201c35 years ago when I \u2018came out\u2019 as a Republican it never crossed my mind my party would some day worry about what bathrooms people used,\u201d he wrote.  ILLINOIS FUNDING SHOWDOWN CONTINUES: Uncertainty still clouds school districts in Illinois, where state lawmakers continue to clash over how to fund the state\u2019s public schools. On Monday, Illinois Democrats blew past a noon deadline set by Gov. Bruce Rauner to deliver the school funding bill to his desk, triggering a special session to start Wednesday.   \u2014 What\u2019s the hold up? Depends on who you ask. Rauner has repeatedly denounced the bill as a \u201cbailout\u201d for troubled Chicago Public Schools and promised to amend it by veto once it does reach his desk. Democrats have ignored Rauner\u2019s requests to send up the bill, asking the governor to meet with Democratic lawmakers before taking his pen to the legislation.   \u2014 Hanging in the balance is the start of the school year. School districts are due for funding in early August, and a special provision inserted in the budget by Democrats will hold those funds until Illinois enacts a new \u201cevidence-based\u201d funding formula. The proposal at the center of the debate sets a target level of funding for each district and doles out funds from the bottom up to work towards equity. Right now, Illinois schools draw most of their funding from local tax dollars, meaning districts in low-income areas often have the fewest resources to educate their students. It also gives cash-strapped Chicago Public Schools additional funding, on top of state block grants, to help it cover teacher pension payments. (CPS is the only district that controls its teachers' pensions.) This is the part Rauner hopes to amend by veto. More from the Chicago Sun-Times and the Chicago Tribune.   GI BILL EXPANSION SAILS THROUGH HOUSE: The House on Monday overwhelmingly passed bipartisan legislation that would expand the education benefits offered to veterans under the GI Bill. Lawmakers voted 405-0 to pass the legislation, H.R. 3218 (115), sending it to the Senate, where the Veterans Affairs\u2019 Committee is scheduled to markup an identical version of the bill on Wednesday. More here.  CHARTER SCHOOL LEADERS THANK LAWMAKERS FOR DREAM ACT: Charter school leaders are thanking Sens. Dick Durbin and Lindsey Graham for introducing the bipartisan DREAM Act of 2017, which aims to provide a legislative solution for "DREAMers" or undocumented immigrants brought to the U.S. as children. The bill that would give young undocumented immigrants a chance to become lawful permanent residents and eventually apply for citizenship.   \u2014 Nina Rees, CEO of the National Alliance for Public Charter Schools, writes in a letter that, \u201cSome of our students were born elsewhere and brought to our country as very young children, without going through the appropriate processes. For them, America is home, the only country they know and the only country to which they have allegiance.\u201d Rees stresses the importance of nurturing that allegiance. \u201cThe threat of deportation and limited access to the benefits of citizenship work against this goal and put students under tremendous stress, inhibiting their ability to learn,\u201d she writes. Read the letters here and here.  \u2014 Richard Barth, CEO of KIPP Public Charter Schools, says in a letter to Durbin that \u201cit is heartening to see such an illustrative group of senators reach across the aisle to work together to ensure immigrant children can continue pursuing the American dream \u2026 We have seen firsthand the positive impact that federal policy can have had on our undocumented students.\u201d Barth shares the experience of a student named Brandon, a DREAMer and alum of the KIPP network. Brandon says, \u201cI am currently thriving in my second year in college and am on track to graduate from one of the best business schools in the country \u2026 Everywhere I look I see good people doing good things \u2014 people in power advocating for students like me. That is what makes me hopeful. I believe in America, and I know, through nineteen years of experience, that Americans believe in me.\u201d Read the letter.   REPORT ROLL CALL   \u2014 The American Council of Trustees and Alumni is out with a new report today analyzing administrative spending at colleges and universities. Read it here.   \u2014 NewSchools Venture Fund, a nonprofit that invests in education reform, is out with a report stressing that diverse education organizations are stronger and more likely to retain staff and reach their policy goals.   SYLLABUS   \u2014 Undocumented suspensions persisted in D.C. schools despite repeated alerts: The Washington Post.  \u2014 Steven Salaita, whose revoked job offer inflated higher ed, says he\u2019s leaving academe: The Chronicle of Higher Education.  \u2014 Alabama, Ole Miss, Mississippi State offer football scholarship to eight-grader: ESPN.  \u2014 Judge plans to rule within weeks on challenge to Arizona law that prompted dismantling of a Mexican-American history program in Tucson\u2019s largest school district: The Associated Press.  \u2014 A teacher\u2019s solution to buy school supplies for her classroom is panhandling: The Washington Post.   Time. Follow the Pro Education team. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
