aV \u000a            By MICHAEL STRATFORD  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Caitlin Emma  SHOWDOWN OVER WEST VIRGINIA\u2019S FEDERAL STUDENT AID: West Virginia\u2019s Democratic governor and its bipartisan congressional delegation are urging Education Secretary Betsy DeVos to reverse her agency\u2019s decision to impose new restrictions on federal funding of the state\u2019s public colleges and universities. The Education Department last week imposed sanctions on West Virginia\u2019s public higher education systems after state officials were late in submitting annual financial statements to the feds for the third year in a row. The department ruled that, for at least five years, the colleges would have to distribute federal student loans and grants first using their own institutional funds \u2014 and then seek reimbursement from the department.  Story Continued Below  \u2014 It\u2019s unusual for the department to impose those restrictions \u2014 known as heightened cash monitoring \u2014 on the public institutions of an entire state. Most of the roughly 545 campuses currently facing those restrictions are for-profit institutions or private, non-profit schools that have failed the department\u2019s financial responsibility test or given officials some other reason to doubt their ability to manage federal funds.  \u2014 The sanctions are putting a \u201cbig financial burden on our colleges,\u201d which had already been facing budget cuts from the legislature, said Jessica Kennedy, a spokeswoman for the West Virginia Higher Education Policy Commission. \u201cWe\u2019re doing everything we can to make sure this doesn\u2019t have any impact on students,\u201d she said.  \u2014 West Virginia each year receives roughly $609 million in federal student loans and grants, according to Kennedy. Campus officials are working with state budget officials to make sure that the schools are able to float that amount money to students before being reimbursed by the Education Department, a process that could take as long as two weeks.  \u2014 State education officials say that they were late in submitting the financial paperwork because of a delay in the financial statements of the entire state government, which was out of their control. Gov. Jim Justice, a Democrat, said in a statement last week that \u201cheads will roll\u201d when he finds out who is responsible for \u201cthis disastrous mistake three years in a row.\u201d He said that West Virginia\u2019s \u201cschools and students are being penalized because of a mistake that\u2019s been brewing two years and ten months before I got here.\u201d  \u2014 The Education Department rejected that explanation last week. A department official wrote in a letter to West Virginia officials that \u201cthe failure to submit an acceptable complete audit and audited financial statements by the due date is a serious violation,\u201d noting that this year marks \u201cthe third annual submission that is late.\u201d  \u2014 The state\u2019s bipartisan congressional delegation on Friday sent a letter to DeVos urging her to reconsider the department\u2019s decision. \u201cThe people who will be harmed most by these sanctions are the low income students who rely on federal financial assistance to attend college,\u201d said the letter signed by Sens. Joe Manchin and Shelley Moore Capito and Reps. David McKinley, Alex Mooney and Evan Jenkins. They added: \u201cWe hope that you will put the needs of West Virginia students above bureaucratic technicalities while the state works to correct past mistakes.\u201d  \u2014 Scheduling note: President Donald Trump today is traveling to West Virginia, where he\u2019ll visit the Boy Scouts of America\u2019s 2017 National Scout Jamboree.   GOOD MONDAY MORNING AND WELCOME TO MORNING EDUCATION. Drop me a line with your tips and feedback: mstratford@politico.com or @mstratford. Share event listings: educalendar@politicopro.com. And follow us on Twitter: @Morning_Edu and @POLITICOPro.  HOUSE VOTES TODAY ON GI BILL EXPANSION: The House of Representatives is scheduled to vote today on legislation that would expand the educational benefits to veterans under the GI Bill. The bill, H.R. 3218 (115), would eliminate a 15-year time limit that veterans have to use their educational assistance as well as expand funding for veterans to enroll in non-traditional education providers like coding boot camps. It would also boost veterans educational assistance for National Guard and Reserve troops and for the dependents of fallen troops. In addition, the legislation would fully restore the GI Bill educational benefits of student veterans who were affected by the closures of Corinthian Colleges and ITT Tech.  \u2014 An identical companion bill was introduced last week in the Senate, where the Veterans Affairs\u2019 Committee has scheduled a markup for this Wednesday at 12 p.m.   SETTLEMENT TALKS IN LAWSUIT OVER PUBLIC SERVICE LOAN FORGIVENESS: Government attorneys representing the Trump administration said in court filings on Friday that they were in talks to settle an ongoing lawsuit over the Education Department\u2019s denial of applications in the Public Service Loan Forgiveness program. The American Bar Association and four attorneys working in public-service jobs have sued the department, accusing officials of reneging on promises that it would forgive their loans.  \u2014 The Justice Department attorneys representing the Education Department on Friday asked the federal judge overseeing the case for more time to file their next motion so that they could have \u201cadditional time to continue to discuss settlement\u201d with the plaintiffs in the case. But the American Bar Association pushed back, writing in its own filing that the department has not sought to settle all of their claims. The government, the attorneys for the ABA wrote, \u201chave merely purported to \u2018offer\u2019 to settle individual portions\u201d of the four attorneys\u2019 case but only as part of a \u201cpackage\u201d under which they agree to dismiss the entire lawsuit \u201cin exchange for piecemeal relief on a small set of claims.\u201d The ABA argued that the Education Department shouldn\u2019t be granted any more extensions in the case because borrowers were being harmed by the delay. A federal judge on Saturday split the difference, giving the department a one-week extension instead of the two-week reprieve it had been seeking.  \u2014 The lawsuit drew attention earlier this year because of an Education Department filing in which it said that borrowers could not rely on their loan servicers to determine whether they were actually on track to receive loan forgiveness under the federal program. The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau has also warned about problems with how the department\u2019s contracted loan servicers are carrying out the program \u2014 which the Trump administration has proposed eliminating.  ASHFORD UNIVERSITY LOSES BID TO KEEP GI BILL ELIGIBILITY: An Iowa judge last week upheld a decision by the state regulators to cut off GI Bill eligibility for Ashford University's online programs across the country. The Bridgepoint Education-owned for-profit school had sued to block the Iowa State Approving Agency\u2019s decision, which threatens the ability of thousands of student veterans to use their benefits at the school. The state regulators' decision stemmed from Ashford\u2019s closure in 2015 of its physical campus in Iowa. That decision had been stayed until last week when a judge issued a preliminary order against the for-profit school, which becomes final next month unless the company appeals.   \u2014 Curtis Coy, deputy under secretary of economic opportunity at the federal Department of Veterans Affairs, sent an email to affected student veterans last week, bracing for the court ruling to become final on August 16. After that point, Coy wrote, students will no longer be able to use GI Bill educational benefits at Ashford\u2019s online programs. \u201cVA does not have the legal authority to restore any GI Bill benefits you have used to attend Ashford University, even if you are not finished with your program,\u201d he wrote in the email. \u201cHowever, you are free to pursue your education goals at another approved school or training facility.\u201d  THE LAB-COAT LIBERALS MARCH ON WASHINGTON: \u201cDismayed by President Donald Trump\u2019s perceived hostility to climate science and other areas of research, a surge of scientists is entering the public arena and running for political office for the first time,\u201d reports POLITICO\u2019s David Siders. \u201cThey represent an evolving brand of Democrat that has been gaining steam for months. What began with rogue Twitter accounts and protest marches has graduated into candidacies in House races in places as varied as California, Texas, Pennsylvania and New York. The handful of scientists who have formally announced their candidacies so far \u2014 and the others who are preparing to join them \u2014 have cast themselves as a counterforce to the Trump administration\u2019s dismissal of climate science and de-prioritization of innovation funding.\u201d Read more.   EDU-PINION: John Schilling, chief operating officer at the American Federation for Children, penned a recent op-ed in the National Review defending the notion of a federal tax credit to help working class families access private school. AFC, an advocacy group formerly chaired by Education Secretary Betsy DeVos, is pushing for the creation of such a program, which reportedly has interest from the Trump administration.   \u2014 In the op-ed, Schilling pushes back on the Heritage Foundation and for concerns that the program would come with too many regulatory strings. \u201cA federal education tax credit would not be a federal program, no matter how anyone tries to spin it,\u201d Schilling writes. \u201cEducation Secretary Betsy DeVos has said that the administration has no intention of imposing anything on states \u2014 a view the majority in Congress shares \u2014 making it clear that the feds won\u2019t be doing any regulating of private schools, which is a state responsibility.\u201d   \u2014 The op-ed comes as groups supporting the creation of a federal tax credit scholarship program beat the drum on school choice during the summer months, hoping it will be included in a broader tax overhaul tackled by Congress. More.   REPORT ROLL CALL   \u2014 Nobel Prize-winning economist James Heckman is out with a new brief on the Nurse-Family Partnership program, which receives funding through the the Maternal, Infant, and Early Childhood Home Visiting federal grant program. The NFP provides low-income, first-time mothers with home visits from registered nurses during pregnancy until their babies reach age 2. Heckman finds the program can lead to greater educational achievement in boys through age 12 and better cognitive skills for both boys and girls by age 6. Find it here.  SYLLABUS  \u2014 Foster care as punishment: The new reality of \u201cJane Crow.\u201d The New York Times.  \u2014 Texas Senate revives school vouchers amid House opposition: the Associated Press.  \u2014 In D.C. rally, hundreds protest Trump\u2019s planned cuts to education: The Washington Post.   \u2014 University of Southern California received more than a year of questions about former medical school dean\u2019s conduct before scandal broke: the Los Angeles Times.   1983. Follow the Pro Education team. @caitlinzemma (cemma@politico.com), @khefling (khefling@politico.com), @mstratford (mstratford@politico.com) and @BenjaminEW (bwermund@politico.com).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
