aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Maggie Severns and Colin Wilhelm  HOW ABOUT ANOTHER TIMING ANNOUNCEMENT? There\u2019s less than five months left in 2017, and you can probably safely expect that there will be a lot of discussion here about whether a tax deal is on track to get done before 2018.  Story Continued Below  The latest installation: Key GOP senators stayed true to the reputation of their chamber, seeming to back a more deliberate timeline for tax reform. Marc Short, the White House\u2019s top person on the Hill, laid out a plan for tax reform markups in September, House passage in October and clearing the Senate in November.  But Finance Chairman Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), at least in his scripted remarks, only vowed a markup this fall. (Muddying the waters a bit, Hatch also told reporters that he did plan for the committee to consider a tax overhaul next month.) For his part, Senate Majority Whip John Cornyn (R-Texas) basically avoided the question when asked if tax reform could be wrapped up by November. \u201cThe hope is to do this through regular order,\u201d Cornyn told reporters, among other things.  One of the issues: Stop us if you\u2019ve heard this one before, but Obamacare might end up holding up other parts of the Republican agenda. The issue this time is that Sen. Lamar Alexander (R-Tenn.) is making noise about a bipartisan measure to stabilize the Affordable Care Act, while President Donald Trump, still angry that the GOP has fallen short on repeal, has threatened to revoke the cost-sharing reduction payments that help lower-income people afford insurance.  And that\u2019s got Hatch hopping mad, as your Morning Tax author and Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo report \u2014 eyeing a September full of legislative landmines, and believing that tax reform basically needs his committee\u2019s close-to-undivided attention. \u201cWe\u2019re not going back to health care. We\u2019re in tax now. As far as I\u2019m concerned, they shot their wad on health care and that\u2019s the way it is. I\u2019m sick of it,\u201d Hatch said this week.   But hey, assistant secretary for tax! Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin\u2019s team filled out quite a bit on Thursday right before the Senate skipped town, with David Kautter, now the assistant secretary for tax policy, among the nominees waved through. (The Senate filled more than five dozen positions in all, according to the Financial Services team\u2019s Zach Warmbrodt.) Other Treasury nominees confirmed: David Malpass as undersecretary for international affairs, Chris Campbell as assistant secretary for financial institutions, Brent McIntosh as general counsel and Andrew Maloney as deputy undersecretary for legislative affairs.  WELCOME TO MORNING TAX, first day of full congressional recess edition. Want to celebrate? It\u2019s also the 324th anniversary of when Dom Perignon invented champagne! (Well, actually, that\u2019s probably a myth. And the good monk probably didn\u2019t say \u201ccome quickly, I am drinking the stars.\u201d But don\u2019t stop on our account.)  Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  NO MIDDLING FIGHT: Mortgage interest deduction has been called one of the numerous third rails in American politics, but our Colin Wilhelm reports that the Trump administration sounds willing to put some serious limits on it. That was the message some officials from the real estate lobby took from a Monday meeting with two of Trump\u2019s top deputies on tax issues, Gary Cohn and Shahira Knight. (One potential idea \u2014 capping the deduction at $500,000, instead of a $1 million, a la former House Ways and Means Chairman Dave Camp\u2019s plan.)  It\u2019s a reminder that Republicans are going to need to search for revenue, after the implosion of the border adjustment, and that both liberals and conservatives have objected that the current incentive doesn\u2019t do much to help the working class. But as Colin notes, the deduction has proven durable in part because of the support from industry and the many, many homeowners who rely on it. And then there\u2019s the final wild card: the president\u2019s decades as a real estate developer.  NOW OFFERING DIGITAL BOUQUETS: Americans for Affordable Products, the coalition of retailers and others that relentlessly fought against the border adjustment, is now offering thank-yous to the GOP lawmakers who helped kill the proposal \u2014 or at least expressed some skepticism about it. The lawmakers receiving that appreciation include Cornyn, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), Sen. Tom Cotton (R-Ark.), Rep. Jim Jordan (R-Ohio), Rep. Mark Meadows (R-N.C.) and Rep. Pat Tiberi (R-Ohio).  REMEMBER, THEY STILL NEED A BUDGET: House Republicans left town without passing a budget, but GOP senators told reporters Thursday that they expected a budget markup in their chamber in September. Sen. Ron Johnson (R-Wis.) also noted that Republican senators are debating whether to use a current policy or current law baseline \u2014 an idea that could influence how generous a tax package can be.  FOXCONNED? Americans for Prosperity\u2019s Wisconsin chapter is breaking with Gov. Scott Walker over his proposed $3 billion in tax incentives to lure the Taiwanese manufacturer Foxconn to the state. \u201cAs much as we believe in Governor Walker\u2019s agenda that has turned this state around, as free market activists who staunchly oppose government tax incentives, we cannot support the expensive refundable tax credits in this package, which are not available to every other business in our state,\u201d Eric Bott, AFP\u2019s Wisconsin state director, said in a statement. But as the Associated Press notes, the decision from a key Koch organization isn\u2019t likely to trip up the incentive package that\u2019s winding its way through the GOP legislature. Foxconn is eyeing sites in southeast Wisconsin, between Milwaukee and Chicago, the AP added.  Still, it\u2019s pretty stunning for AFP to break with Walker. When Walker was running for president in 2015, Tim Phillips, AFP\u2019s president, raved that \u201cthe difference Scott Walker has made with his policy achievements is as transformative as any governor anywhere in a generation.\u201d  SPEAKING OF AFP: Mark your calendars, because AFP is breaking out the big guns. Vice President Mike Pence will address Americans for Prosperity\u2019s annual summit, set for August 19 in Richmond, Va. The summit, which offers AFP volunteers a chance to network, attend training sessions and hear from a battery of speakers, will focus this year on tax reform \u2014 the Koch network\u2019s main focus heading into fall.  FIRE WITH FIRE: Conservative and business groups have already started ramping up their advocacy campaigns for tax reform, and now they\u2019re getting a progressive foil, The Washington Post\u2019s Dave Weigel reports. The Not One Penny campaign, led by the Tax March, MoveOn and the Working Families Party, won\u2019t have nearly the resources as those other groups as it seeks to oppose any tax overhaul that lowers corporate tax rates or taxes on the wealthy. But organizers say their advantage will come from the energy generated by the GOP\u2019s failure so far to repeal Obamacare and the grassroots energy behind the Tax March on April 15. "In mid-July, as the fight to kill Obamacare repeal was underway, more than 50 organizers from the 'resistance' underwent training on best practices for organizing against tax cuts. They\u2019ve fanned out to create anti-tax-cut presences in congressional districts over the long August recess," Weigel writes.  COINS GOTTA STICK TOGETHER: Coin Center, a D.C.-based, digital currency-focused think tank, filed an amicus brief late Thursday on behalf of Coinbase, the largest digital currency exchange in the U.S. The IRS has pushed for two years\u2019 worth of comprehensive user records from Coinbase in an important case for the burgeoning technology. The government tax agency maintains that it has reasonable cause to suspect several of Coinbase\u2019s users based in America may have avoided paying taxes owed on Bitcoin-related trades, while Coinbase maintains that the IRS\u2019s request is unjustified and far too broad. No real shocker here, but Coin Center\u2019s with Coinbase. \u201cIf such a simple and sweeping statement of purpose is sufficient to qualify as a legitimate purpose, there would be no meaningful judicial check in place to stop the IRS from using the John Doe summons process to collect the personal records of every person who had bought or sold stocks on the New York Stock Exchange, art within a given time period from Sotheby\u2019s, rare books from City Lights Booksellers, or cash deposits or withdrawals at Bank of America,\u201d said Jerry Brito and Peter Van Valkenburgh, Coin Center\u2019s executive director and director of research, respectively.   INTERNATIONAL UPDATE  DOES THAT ADD UP? At first glance, Google\u2019s tax bill in Sweden seems to line up \u2014 an effective rate of 22 percent. But Business Insider Nordic reports that doesn\u2019t take into account how much of the online giant\u2019s business in the country was routed through Ireland, with one estimate finding that \u201cthe corporate tax Google paid in Sweden was less than one thousandth of its sales.\u201d  STATE NEWS  COMING TOGETHER: Thirteen states have banded together for a tax amnesty program for Amazon sellers, CNBC reports. Merchants selling through Amazon currently owe about $2 billion from sales taxes that have gone uncollected, but would be able to only be liable for taxes on future sales if they enlist in the program starting in the middle of the month. How is their $2 billion in uncollected taxes? Independent sellers can sign up to get access to Amazon\u2019s warehouses. But in doing so, those merchants might also make in-state sales from those warehouses that would force them to charge sales taxes \u2014 sometimes without their knowledge, because of the sprawling nature of Amazon\u2019s infrastructure.  WHAT NEXT? The future of the nuclear production tax credit is now in flux after a South Carolina provider decided to halt construction on a pair of nuclear plants, Tax Analysts\u2019 Asha Glover and Stephen Cooper report. The House passed a nuclear tax bill, but the Senate was seeking to combine that measure with a host of other energy provisions. \u201cBut the latest developments in South Carolina, combined with pessimism about the prospects for the projects in Georgia, have led some senators to question if the legislation is still necessary.\u201d  QUICK LINKS  The Financial Times examines why international tax rules will be such a challenge in tax reform.  DID YOU KNOW?  The first Chinese coins, dating to 2000 B.C.E., were made of shells.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
