aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Aaron Lorenzo  TURKEY WITH A DOLLOP OF DOMESTIC POLICY SUCCESS: Whether they like it or not, key Republicans are \u2014 of their own doing \u2014 basically making Thanksgiving almost a make-or-break moment for tax reform.  Story Continued Below  Rep. Mark Meadows (R-N.C.) said at a Wednesday event sponsored by Americans for Prosperity that tax reform just wouldn\u2019t make it if an overhaul wasn\u2019t on President Donald Trump\u2019s desk by Thanksgiving, becoming the second big-name Republican in just a few days to suggest November would be key for tax reform. Marc Short, the White House\u2019s top liaison to Capitol Hill, on Monday laid out what he called an \u201caggressive\u201d timeline for tax reform that included passing both the House and the Senate by November.   Other tidbits from Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo: Meadows called for a corporate tax rate into the teens, suggested that he was open to expanding the budget window beyond a decade and once more insisted he wanted deficit-neutral \u2014 not revenue-neutral \u2014 tax reform. (The Freedom Caucus chairman has for a while wanted to offset tax cuts with spending cuts.)  Those happen to be just several of the rather central details that Republicans still have to work through on taxes, after that very high-level statement that came out of the Big Six of senior administration officials and top GOP lawmakers last week.   That\u2019s not all: Mick Mulvaney, Trump\u2019s budget chief, became perhaps the most dismissive top Republicans yet of working with Democrats on tax reform Wednesday, telling Fox News that "my gut is that a tax bill looks a lot weaker \u2014 a lot less likely to get us to 3 percent economic growth \u2014 if we've got eight, 10, 12, 14 Democrats on it."  To be fair, the smart money has long been on tax reform being a partisan exercise. Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.) just this week dismissed the idea that the GOP could work with Democrats on the issue, and Axios reported that the White House hadn\u2019t reached out in a serious way on taxes to any of the 10 Democratic senators on the ballot next year in states won by Trump. But at the same time, Short was still selling the idea this week that bipartisanship was possible.  AND THEN: It's not like the Heritage Foundation releasing a study expounding on the benefits of full expensing should be all that surprising. Adam Michel and Salim Furth argue that nothing else is quite as good for the economy in their new paper, saying it helps to increase both employment and wages for American workers. Dropping the corporate rate and exempting companies\u2019 foreign income from U.S. taxes are both good ideas, the authors added \u2014 but not in the same league as full expensing when it comes to expanding economic growth. \u201cWhile lower tax rates are an important part of tax reform, expensing provides a larger economic gain because it is forward-looking, removing the current system\u2019s bias against new investment,\u201d they wrote.  Maybe it's the fact that Heritage released a new paper on the topic at all that is even more interesting than its findings. Michel and Furth released a similar paper not even two months ago, but a spokesman said the new release was aimed at pushing back on what the foundation believes is the \u201cwrong narrative\u201d \u2014 that robust expensing provisions aren\u2019t crucial to tax reform.  The Koch orbit, most notably Americans for Prosperity, and House Freedom Caucus members have been among those recently downplaying the importance of full expensing. In other words: expensing is also on that list of the very central details that the right is still not united on when it comes to tax reform.  Finally: Some Freedom Caucus members are grumbling that they don\u2019t have enough details on the GOP\u2019s tax reform path to sell it while they\u2019re back home, Bloomberg\u2019s Sahil Kapur reports.  And Sen. Jim Risch (R-Idaho), the chairman of the Senate Small Business Committee, and Sen. Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire, the panel's top Democrat, sent a letter to Finance Committee leaders urging them to take care of true small businesses in a tax revamp. The two senators added that lawmakers need to include protections against gaming along with any preference for pass-through income.  THANKS FOR HANGING IN with us here at Morning Tax. Today also marks 165 years since the first ever intercollegiate sporting event \u2014 what became known as the Harvard-Yale Regatta, of course.  Hit us up with your tips and feedback. What\u2019s going on out there? Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  IN THE HOLE: Three of Trump\u2019s political appointees have racked up some pretty extensive tax debts, the Center for Public Integrity\u2019s Dave Levinthal reports off an examination of financial disclosure forms. Two of the officials, Joe Alexander, a special assistant in the Agriculture Department, and Deborah Cox-Roush, White House liaison for the Corporation for National and Community Service, both are on IRS payment plans for tax debts of up to $50,000. Justin Clark, the White House director of intergovernmental affairs and a deputy assistant to the president, also owes up to $50,000 but doesn\u2019t seem to have a payment plan.  Lawmakers have proposed barring people with serious tax debts from holding government positions, but that idea hasn\u2019t gained much traction. Also of note, as Levinthal reports: Don\u2019t think this is just a Trump thing. \u201cTrump\u2019s appointment of federal debtors to his administration perpetuates a pattern that\u2019s dogged presidential administrations \u2014 including that of President Barack Obama \u2014 for decades.\u201d  ANYTHING YOU CAN DO, I CAN DO BETTER: Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) and several politically vulnerable members of his caucus unveiled a trade agenda that sounded downright Trump-y on Wednesday \u2014 an attempt "to put pressure on the White House to work across the aisle on trade or risk looking weak" on the issue, as Pro Trade's Megan Cassella put it. Among the proposals: Tax incentives for companies that bring jobs back to the U.S., and tax punishments for those that do the opposite.  ALL FITTING UNDER ONE UMBRELLA: The IRS is setting up an investigations unit to focus solely on international crimes, your Morning Tax author reported Wednesday. Don Fort, the new chief of the IRS criminal investigations division, said the unit will hopefully build on the agency\u2019s recent triumphs in the international sphere, including its partnership with the Justice Department in targeting Swiss banks that helped facilitate offshore tax evasion.   Fort added in a conference call with reporters that his division would be seeking to take fewer identity theft cases in the years to come. IRS Commissioner John Koskinen has made battling identity theft one of his central issues, following an explosion of new cases in recent years. But Fort noted that his division is responsible for more traditional tax enforcement matters \u2014 like tax evasion \u2014 and that declining resources means that it can only take the most far-reaching identity theft cases going forward.  INTERNATIONAL UPDATE  SOAK THE RICH TIME: The South Korean government is seeking to buck the current global trend on corporate taxes, Bloomberg reports \u2014 looking to increase its top rate from 22 percent to 25 percent. President Moon Jae-in has called tax hikes on both corporations and wealthy South Koreans key planks in the government\u2019s efforts to reduce income inequality. The new highest tax rate on corporations would hit companies with annual taxable incomes north of 200 billion won (around $178 million), while the government also wants to hike the top rate on individuals to 42 percent for those making more than 500 million won a year (around $445,000). The potential issue for a package that could raise around $5.5 trillion a year in won (about $4.5 billion), according to the government: Moon\u2019s party only has about 40 percent of the seats in South Korea\u2019s parliament.  STATE NEWS  WE SAID WHAT? Foxconn, the Taiwanese-based electronics manufacturer that makes devices for Apple, Sony and others, isn\u2019t commenting on Trump\u2019s assertion that it will invest as much as $30 billion in the U.S, the Associated Press reports. Trump said this week that Terry Gou, the company\u2019s chief executive, told him \u201coff the record\u201d that he would pour three times as much money as the expected $10 billion it plans for a Wisconsin plant. In a statement, Foxconn would only say that its Wisconsin facility would be just the first in a series of investments, and that it would offer an update on future plans whenever they were ready.  As for the Wisconsin plant, Republicans who control the legislature there are split over the $3 billion worth of incentives that Gov. Scott Walker is pushing to sew up the deal with Foxconn. Wisconsin\u2019s agreement with Foxconn says those tax breaks need to be in place by the end of next month, but there are questions about the size of the package that the state is offering in exchange for anywhere from 3,000 to 13,000 jobs.  QUICK LINKS  Like clockwork: First day of a new soda tax, this time in Cook County in Illinois, sparks some anger.  Newt watch! Former Speaker Gingrich predicts Nancy Pelosi could get the gavel back if Republicans fall short on taxes.  DID YOU KNOW?  Phobos, the larger of Mars\u2019 two moons, is expected to get \u201cpulled apart\u201d within 30 million to 50 million years, according to NASA.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
