aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  08/02/2017 10:00 AM EDT  \u000a                    Updated 08/02/2017 08:32 AM EDT  With help from Aaron Lorenzo  PIVOT UPDATE: Look at that \u2014 tax reform has reached the part of the proceedings where congressional leaders strive to set the markers for the debate.  Story Continued Below  Case in point: Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) and 44 of the other 47 Democratic senators sent a letter to the GOP demanding a few things that tax reform shouldn\u2019t be: a boon to the wealthy, a net tax cut or passed through budget reconciliation.  Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell\u2019s retort, via our Elana Schor: That letter proved exactly why Republicans need to use reconciliation \u2014 because Democrats are unwilling to work on the majority party\u2019s priorities, McConnell said, declaring that the bipartisan template that got tax reform across the finish line in 1986 just doesn\u2019t exist anymore.  And what about that trio of Democrats who didn't sign? Those three \u2014 Joe Donnelly of Indiana, Heidi Heitkamp of North Dakota and Joe Manchin of West Virginia \u2014 are definitely vulnerable next year, and their decision not to sign raised suspicions that they might be the three most likely to play ball with Republicans on tax reform. (Other Democrats who are also in danger, like Claire McCaskill of Missouri and Jon Tester of Montana, did sign the letter.) GOP senators on Tuesday did drop some hints about trying to reach out to Democrats who might be interested in their line of thinking. But as our Colin Wilhelm put it, Donnelly, Heitkamp and Manchin all \u201cplayed down the significance of their demurral from the letter, and it's certainly too early to read much into it other than political caution.\u201d (Also of note: It doesn\u2019t sound like President Donald Trump and the White House have done a ton of wooing of those vulnerable Democrats on tax reform.)  AND WHAT ABOUT PERMANENCE? One of the knotty big-picture questions that Republicans are still working on when it comes to taxes is how crucial it is to make any changes permanent.  To be fair, that\u2019s basically everyone\u2019s preference \u2014 though, in recent months, it certainly seemed like permanence was more of a priority for House Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.) and Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady (R-Texas) than other key negotiators. But now, there\u2019s increasing chatter that Republicans might have to rely on a mix of permanent and temporary tax changes in order to jump through all the requisite reconciliation hoops.  So how would that work? It wouldn\u2019t take any special procedural steps for the GOP to mix it up like that within a reconciliation bill, Rohit Kumar, a former top McConnell aide, told Morning Tax. (Recall, for instance, that Republican health care bills pushed the Cadillac tax on expensive employer-provided health insurance plans back until 2025.) But Kumar, now at PricewaterhouseCoopers, said there were other issues to watch out for as Republicans eyed that path.  Temporary can easily become permanent: The recent health care debate and even the fiscal cliff negotiations, which kept the vast, vast majority of the Bush tax cuts, show that it\u2019s tough to get rid of policies once you\u2019ve got them on the books. \u201cIt would be totally rational to think, \u2018here\u2019s some stuff that we can only afford to do for seven to 10 years,\u2019 but in the back of your minds have some confidence that not all of this will go away,\u201d Kumar said. \u201cIt turns out once the public has a benefit for several years, they react poorly when the government tries to take it away from them.\u201d  It could take some imagination: Remember how Ryan\u2019s office said that not even a three-year corporate tax cut would work under reconciliation rules, because it would cause deficits in the out years? No matter what, Republicans will likely need to find offsets either in the first decade or for the years outside the budget window to account for those kinds of reverberations, Kumar said. \u201cThere\u2019s lots of things that you can do. All of them would be unsatisfactory, and they\u2019re all things that people would later wish not to happen,\u201d he added. (In other words: Might you look for an offset that\u2019s unpopular enough that you don\u2019t expect it to get implemented?)  What would be temporary and what would be permanent? Probably too soon to say. But the policy change most likely to stay for the long-term would be a territorial system, Kumar said, because the Joint Committee on Taxation would likely score that like a years-long repatriation holiday \u2014 i.e., poorly.  THANKS FOR HEADING BACK for another installment of Morning Tax. Another taxiversary: It\u2019s 80 years to the day since the \u201cMarihuana Tax Act of 1937\u201d \u2014 yes, that\u2019s how it was spelled \u2014 was signed into law by then-President Franklin Roosevelt. (The law came out around the same time as the movie \u201cReefer Madness,\u201d and was later overturned by the Supreme Court in a case brought by the professor and activist Timothy Leary \u2014 leading to the current Controlled Substances Act.)  What\u2019s going on out there? Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  THE OUTSIDE GAME: There\u2019s been a lot of talk about how Republicans are going to step up their messaging campaign for tax reform, and our Nancy Cook found out some of the details. Outside groups like the American Action Network, Americans for Prosperity and Business Roundtable are going to spend millions of dollars on a campaign that won\u2019t focus much on how tax reform would help the corporate community. Instead, the spots will have the more populist tint aimed at Trump voters. \u201cThose ads will focus on how tax reform will hit consumers\u2019 pocketbooks, boost American jobs and help economic growth broadly, not on the benefits for the big businesses helping to fund the campaign,\u201d Nancy writes.  Speaking of which: Trump took to the East Room on Tuesday afternoon in his first real attempt to sell tax reform, this time at a small business event. The message at that meeting from Linda McMahon, the Small Business Administration chief, was that the Trump administration continues to believe tax rates should drop for all kinds of businesses, not just corporations, Matthew Haller of the International Franchise Association told Morning Tax.  That was a \u201cgood signal,\u201d Haller said. And yet, one of the attendees added to Morning Tax that he's still worried that Washington will fall short on a tax overhaul and instead fall back on simple corporate rate cuts. Matt Hefter, who owns a home and office painting franchise in Wisconsin, said that not giving pass-throughs and corporations equal treatment would cause business owners like him to waste time and money on accountants exploring whether to reorganize to secure lower rates.  The view from the left: Democrats like Sen. Ron Wyden of Oregon remain concerned that a steep reduction in taxes on pass-throughs could lead to a major loophole, as partners in lucrative partnerships could take advantage and mischaracterize capital gains income as wage income at a lower rate. Along similar lines, Americans for Tax Fairness said after Tuesday\u2019s meeting that the administration\u2019s 15 percent business rate is \u201ca massive tax giveaway for Wall Street hedge fund managers, big law firms, and real estate developers like Trump.\u201d  OH, MORE ON THAT TRUMP INTERVIEW: Our Josh Dawsey and Hadas Gold got their hands on the transcript of Trump\u2019s recent interview with The Wall Street Journal, and it turns out there was some more interesting stuff on taxes. The president, for instance, once again called the U.S. the highest-taxed nation in the world, and said American companies had as much as $5 trillion offshore. (Not really true in either case.) Meanwhile, Trump and what seems to be Gary Cohn, the director of the National Economic Council, went into further detail on the administration\u2019s hopes to make as many tax changes permanent as possible. (Another fun passage: Trump describing how George Steinbrenner\u2019s estate was taxed.)  Related: Reuters asks whether Trump is undercutting the case for tax reform by celebrating how much money corporations are making right now.  FAREWELL, MOOCH: Morning Tax made but one, brief reference to Anthony Scaramucci during his 10-day tenure as White House communications director \u2014 about how the former hedge fund executive was seeking to defer paying taxes on the sale of his company, SkyBridge Capital. And now as CNN reports, that\u2019s a no-go. \u201cMr. Scaramucci is going to pay the capital gains taxes once the sale goes through," Elliot Berke, Scaramucci\u2019s attorney, told CNN. "There was never an attempt to game the system \u2014 it was simply to adhere to what is allowable by law. His true and only purpose was to serve the country. And he will be back.\u201d  If you\u2019re interested in diving into waist-high weeds on this, David Herzig, a law professor at Valparaiso, wrote a primer on the tax provision itself and whether Scaramucci qualified before his lawyer sent the statement to CNN. (Short answer: it was a \u201copen and contentious\u201d question whether Scaramucci qualified.)  INTERNATIONAL UPDATE  ANOTHER GO-ROUND FOR INDIA AND APPLE: The world\u2019s second-most populated country and the mobile phone power continue to stare each other down over tax incentives for manufacturing iPhones, Reuters reports. Now, Apple wants India to give its suppliers tax breaks as well. \u201cThe two sides have been discussing a list of "prerequisites" that Apple submitted in October, including duty exemption on raw materials for manufacturing components and capital equipment for 15 years for it to make iPhones from scratch in India.The company has told the government it would be bringing in a host of these ancillary units when it sets up operations to cater to India, one of the world's fastest growing smartphone markets, a top government official said.\u201d  STATE NEWS  GIVE US THOSE TAX INCREASES: Seattle picked a pair of progressive women to face off this fall in a mayor\u2019s race that has focused a lot on taxes \u2014 and how the city needs more of them, the Associated Press reports. \u201cThe debate among candidates has focused on taxes and inequality among residents in a city that has seen median house prices double over the last five years to more than $700,000. Several leading candidates want to ask big corporations to pay more taxes and to invoke a city-wide income tax targeting rich residents \u2014 even though the legality of such a levy is in question for Washington state.\u201d (Reminder: For a liberal state, Washington relies rather heavily on the sales tax and other regressive levies.)  QUICK LINKS  Trump: Taiwanese manufacturer Foxconn could invest $30 billion in the U.S.  The Center for American Progress makes the case that the GOP rhetoric on taxes doesn\u2019t match its proposals.  The Tax Foundation tackles the difficulty of crafting a territorial system.  There will be no battle of the tax writers in Pennsylvania: Rep. Mike Kelly declines to challenge Sen. Bob Casey.  DID YOU KNOW?  Larry David, later to star in \u201cCurb Your Enthusiasm,\u201d provided the voice of George Steinbrenner on \u201cSeinfeld.\u201d  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
