aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  08/01/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Aaron Lorenzo  CHECK BACK AT THANKSGIVING: Who needs December?  Story Continued Below  Marc Short, the White House\u2019s top liaison to Congress, laid out a tax reform schedule on Monday that even he acknowledged was pretty aggressive \u2014 with September being for markups, October for House passage of a tax overhaul, and November the Senate\u2019s time, our Aaron Lorenzo reports. Short didn\u2019t get into whether the House and Senate bills would need to be reconciled at an event sponsored by Americans for Prosperity and Freedom Partners, a couple of groups in the Koch network, though Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin repeated yet again that tax reform would get done this year.  As for the budget that Republicans would need to move a tax overhaul using reconciliation? Short expects that to be checked off the list in either September or October, though he also floated the idea that there could be some bipartisan interest in taxes. (We\u2019ll see about that.)  Just how aggressive is that? Look at all the work Congress has to do in September beyond its familiar task of extending government funding, as ticked off by our Budget team of Jennifer Scholtes and Sarah Ferris \u2014 the National Flood Insurance Program, the FAA, CHIP and the debt ceiling.  So while top Republicans have said for a while that fall would be the time for tax reform, it\u2019s not like the calendar has been cleared of other obstacles. Something else to keep in mind: Congressional staff are going to have to put in a lot of work during the August recess for bills to be ready for September markups.  All about that coordination: Short added Monday that it looks like the administration and lawmakers will have a much more fruitful relationship with outside groups on tax reform than they did in their efforts to repeal Obamacare, Aaron also reports.Short said to expect a glut of events advocating for tax reform in the second half of August, and noted that the White House has had a better chance to build a coalition on taxes, given that the GOP push on Obamacare started before President Donald Trump was even inaugurated.  BREAK OUT THE BULLY PULPIT: Trump appears at a small business event in the East Room of the White House at 3 p.m. today.  WELCOME TO THE \u201cWow, it\u2019s August already?\u201d version of Morning Tax. It\u2019s also been 519 years since Christopher Columbus claimed something he called Isla Santa for Spain. (While Columbus clearly thought he was on an island, he\u2019d actually become the first European to make a recorded visit to mainland South America \u2014 Venezuela\u2019s Paria Peninsula.)  We\u2019re here for your tax tips and feedback. Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  BUT, BUT, BUT \u2026 : Gary Cohn, the director of the National Economic Council, told a roundtable of officials from the real estate industry on Monday that the Trump administration and congressional leaders were on the same page on the big-picture tax reform issues.  But the White House also didn\u2019t take long to suggest on Monday that there\u2019s still a lot of work to do on some of the central details of tax reform. For instance, Short said the White House still wants the 15 percent business rate that many tax observers believed was just an opening bid that was bound to sneak higher, the Washington Examiner\u2019s Joseph Lawler reports.  But hours earlier, Cohn didn\u2019t sound as dug in when addressing the real estate officials, saying simply that \u201ccutting the business tax to as low as possible is important to us.\u201d He added: \u201cWe\u2019ve proposed 15 percent. We\u2019re trying to work off a 15 percent base, and see if we can get there.\u201d Senate Finance Chairman Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), speaking to Reuters, sounded even more skeptical that Republicans would be able to pull off such aggressive rate cutting. "In fact, it would be kind of miraculous if we could get it down to 25 percent or less. I'd like to get it down to around 20 percent. I'd love to get it at 15 percent if we could," Hatch said. "But I think the odds are, we\u2019re going to be lucky to get it down at all."  REALLY, WE\u2019RE NOT DOING 44 PERCENT: Short also noted on Fox News that the White House wasn\u2019t interested in the 44 percent top rate for income over $5 million a year that\u2019s been floated by Steve Bannon, the chief White House strategist. \u201cI don\u2019t think that that\u2019s on the table right now, to be honest with you,\u201d Short said. Bannon was pushing the rate as a way to pay for tax cuts for the middle-class, Bloomberg reports.  But a couple corollaries there: The top statutory tax rate for individuals is 39.6 percent. But the actual top rate can be more like 44.6 percent when you add throw-ins like Obamacare\u2019s 3.8 percent tax on unearned income, the Pease limitation and the Personal Exemption Phaseout. The other question \u2014 how much money could that 44 percent tax rate, which some observers suspect grew more from political rather than policy considerations, actually raise?  Tough to say, actually. The Tax Foundation\u2019s Kyle Pomerleau estimates that new bracket could raise anywhere from $80 billion to $260 billion over a decade, based on IRS data for 2014 that found about 43,000 tax returns with adjusted gross incomes over $5 million. Why the wide variance? All depends on the design \u2014 a 44 percent rate on ordinary individual income that exempts pass-throughs would be the low end of the estimate, Pomerleau told Morning Tax in an email. The high end assumes that the 44 percent bracket would also sweep up capital gains and dividend income.  THE PUSHBACK FROM THE LEFT: Democrats are starting to step up their efforts to frame the GOP tax reform plans \u2014 and we\u2019re betting they might have a familiar ring to those who have heard the party\u2019s message about taxes and health care in recent years. For instance, Rep. Lloyd Doggett of Texas, the top Democrat on the House Ways and Means tax policy subcommittee, took the following shot at Monday\u2019s Koch event, as Aaron also reported: "Congress may have recessed for August, but billionaire special interests, who demand ever more tax breaks, never go into recess."  For its part, Freedom Partners decided not to let that kind of talk go unchallenged, saying it was \u201cfocused on eliminating the special carve outs that rig the economy in favor of the wealthy and well-connected.\u201d Bill Riggs, a spokesman for the group, added that \u201cwe\u2019re hopeful most lawmakers will give the false political smears a rest and work together to do something good for their constituents and the country.\u201d  AVOIDING THE BULLS-EYE: Rep. Mark Sanford (R-S.C.) is one of only a handful of House Republicans who have joined legislation that would mandate that presidential candidates release their last three years of tax returns. Why haven\u2019t more Republicans joined him? Well, Sanford told NPR: \u201cBecause nobody wants a bad tweet from Donald Trump,\u201d adding that getting called out by the president on Twitter wasn\u2019t atop his priorities, either. \u201cNobody's looking for a bad day. The president can be quite vigorous in his pronouncements. And you don't want to be at the receiving end of one of those,\u201d Sanford said. \u201cBut I think that, in this case, not letting a 50-year tradition die off or fighting if it is doing so is of greater importance.\u201d  INTERNATIONAL UPDATE  NOT GONNA DO IT: A post-Brexit United Kingdom won\u2019t seek to become a tax haven to undercut its new rivals in the European Union, Reuters reports. Philip Hammond, the chancellor of the exchequer, told Le Monde that there\u2019s no reason for Britain to shift away from its current setup \u2014 basically middle of the pack in Europe in the tax-to-gross domestic product ratio, as the BBC noted. But as the Labour opposition put it, Hammond seems to be taking a softer line on that question than he did six months ago, when the chancellor said \u201cyou can be sure we will do whatever we have to do.\u201d  STATE NEWS  ALL EYES ON RAHM: Chicago is facing a $114 million shortfall for 2018, but Mayor Rahm Emanuel isn\u2019t letting on whether he wants to rely on taxes to fill it, The Chicago Tribune reports. \u201cEmanuel did not respond Monday when asked whether he would consider another tax increase to fill next year's budget hole \u2014 one that could grow even further considering his pledge to open Chicago Public Schools on time and keep them open despite continued uncertainty over state funding for the cash-strapped school district that the city has contemplated helping out.\u201d  QUICK LINKS  Ukraine\u2019s finance minister denies tax evasion accusations.  Soccer star Cristiano Ronaldo to judge: I never tried to dodge taxes.  DID YOU KNOW?  The 1970s sitcom \u201cSanford and Son,\u201d starring Redd Foxx, was based on a British show called \u201cSteptoe and Son.\u201d  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
