aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  07/31/2017 10:01 AM EDT  IT\u2019S TIME: What has five letters, starts with \u201cp\u201d and rhymes with divot?  Yes, the time for the tax reform pivot has arrived. (Well, maybe. More on that later.) But in the meantime, key lawmakers and outside groups are definitely ramping up for tax to be perhaps the key issue in the fall. (Well, maybe for most of it. Debt limit, anyone?)  Story Continued Below  Making the case: House Speaker Paul Ryan (R-Wis.) and Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady (R-Texas), a.k.a. one-third of the Big Six, expressed confidence that tax reform would get done this year in Fox News interviews on Sunday \u2014 while pushing back on the idea from Steve Bannon, the chief White House strategist, to raise the top tax rate to 44 percent.  \u201cI feel much more confident that we\u2019re going to stick the landing on tax reform," Ryan said, via Bloomberg (which added \u201creferring to a successful end for a gymnastics routine.\u201d) As for Brady, he added: \u201cI don\u2019t intend on introducing a 44 percent tax rate in the Ways and Means Committee. We\u2019re going for growth, which means lower rates at every level.\u201d  That dovetails pretty nicely with what Ryan told conservative activists in his office on Friday, our Colin Wilhelm reports. (Remember: Conservative groups also met with White House officials last week to make sure that tax reform messaging isn\u2019t as much of a dud as the campaign to repeal Obamacare.) Ryan told the activists that the goal is a quick strike to lower tax rates and boost expensing provisions, in order to hopefully help the economy in time for the 2018 midterms. One of the big issues, as always: Can it be permanent?  Get that bully pulpit ready: President Donald Trump is going to make a first big attempt to stir up support for tax reform on Tuesday, Axios\u2019 Jonathan Swan reports, with an appearance at a small business event at the White House.  Who else? Add American Action Network to the list of outside groups willing to shell out big money \u2014 as much as $20 million \u2014 to shill for tax reform, McClatchy\u2019s Katie Glueck reports. The group joins the Business Roundtable and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, among others, in escalating efforts on taxes after the Senate\u2019s health care problems.  But yes, it\u2019s still difficult: The anti-tax activist Grover Norquist, within Colin\u2019s story, bumps Republican agreement on tax reform up to 97 percent with the death of the border adjustment from the House GOP blueprint \u2014 up from the 80 percent to 90 percent top Republicans had been saying. Whether that\u2019s true or not, Pro Tax\u2019s Brian Faler sought to explain the sheer scale of the challenge in front of the GOP, which has to sift through tax breaks helping everyone from bike riders to whale hunters. \u201cThey say it will be easier than dealing with Obamacare, because taxes are much more in their party's bailiwick, and promise to get legislation to President Donald Trump's desk by the end of this year. But most of the lawmakers weren't around for the last tax overhaul, in 1986, and many longtime tax aides say they are seriously underestimating the degree of difficulty that comes with uprooting hundreds of provisions. Many predict they will have no easier time undoing loopholes that have been in the code for decades than they've had rolling back Obamacare.\u201d  And yet, as Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo reports, GOP tax writers themselves have no illusions that this is going to be easy. \u201cIn regrouping, they'll look to salvage parts of past plans to overhaul tax laws and cobble together a bill they hope to pass this year for a much-needed political win after their latest efforts to upend the Affordable Care Act fizzled again,\u201d Aaron writes. But it might take awhile for Republicans to get their legs under them when both chambers are back in the fall. "I think we'll spend a fair amount of the month of September refocusing on what tax reform looks like going forward," said Rep. Kenny Marchant (R-Texas).  THANKS FOR JOINING US for another week of Morning Tax. By the way, where did July go?  This seems pretty exact \u2014 today marks 1,236 years since the first recorded eruption of Japan\u2019s Mount Fuji.  What\u2019s happening out there? Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  ABOUT THAT MAYBE: Even with Trump getting ready to hit the stump for tax reform, it doesn\u2019t look like the White House is prepared to let go when it comes to Obamacare repeal. Trump himself tweeted something to that effect a couple days back, and then his budget director, Mick Mulvaney, said it was administration policy that the Senate shouldn\u2019t vote on anything else \u2014 including the debt ceiling \u2014 before it tackles health care again. "In the White House's view, they can't move on in the Senate," Mulvaney said on CNN's "State of the Union,\u201d via Jacqueline Klimas. "You can't promise folks you're going to do something for seven years, and then not do it."  THE PEOPLE ARE READY TO MOVE ON: More than half of Americans want Washington to just throw in the towel on health care, a new Reuters poll found. \u201cWhen asked what they think Congress should do next, most Americans picked other priorities such as tax reform, foreign relations and infrastructure. Only 29 percent said they wanted Republicans in Congress to \u2018continue working on a new healthcare bill.'"  FRIDAY NEWS DUMP, 385 EDITION: The business community got some good news from the Treasury Department about those controversial Section 385 rules on Friday afternoon, Aaron also notes. No, it\u2019s not a full delay in the implementation of the rules, which would reclassify some debt as equity in an effort to put a crimp in earnings stripping. But businesses do get another year, until 2019, before they have to meet paperwork requirements on internal loans.  REQUIEM FOR A BAT: Safe to say that the border adjustment will be taking up less and less space here in the days to come, but Adam Looney of the Brookings Institution takes one last stab at how Ryan and Brady came up with a \u201cgenuinely good idea.\u201d For starters, Looney argues that former House Ways and Means Chairman Dave Camp\u2019s plan showed that a 1986-style \u201clower the rates, broaden the base\u201d approach wouldn\u2019t cut it when it comes to job growth or keeping U.S. companies from seeking new homes abroad. \u201cTaxing companies based on where their goods are consumed frees policymakers to retain or expand tax breaks for domestic investment, as in Chairman Brady\u2019s plan, and the rate can be set to bring in the revenues the federal government needs,\u201d Looney writes, adding: \u201cUnder a BAT, the U.S. would become an extremely desirable place to locate businesses and investment, and would reverse the shift of businesses abroad.\u201d  Meanwhile: Businesses in Arizona, whose GOP lawmakers were among the most strident critics of the border adjustment, are celebrating its death, the Arizona Republic reports.  GETTING PERSONAL: Gov. Scott Walker of Wisconsin is calling the state legislature into special session to consider a $3 billion package of incentives for Foxconn, the Taiwan-based manufacturer known for its work on Apple\u2019s iPhones. Republicans control both the governor\u2019s mansion and the legislature in Wisconsin, though The Associated Press notes there is some Democratic opposition to what would be the largest incentive package in state history.  As to that opposition, Walker took critics to task \u2014 but in a sort of Wisconsin Nice way. \u201cThere\u2019s a whole lot of people out there scrambling to try and come up with a reason not to like this. I can tell you, that\u2019s fine but I think they can go suck lemons,\u201d Walker said Friday.  INTERNATIONAL UPDATE  WE\u2019RE ON IT: Austria gets the European Council presidency for the last half of 2018, and Vienna is already hinting that it wants to make battling offshore tax gaming a core priority, Reuters reports. Hans Joerg Schelling, Austria\u2019s finance minister, has already come up with a strategy for cracking down on tax avoidance, his ministry said. "Tackling tax evasion more effectively will require European and international solutions. The European Union must finally come up with a joint strategy," Schelling said after meeting with Bruno Le Maire, the French finance minister, over the weekend.  STATE NEWS  ALL DRY: Hurricane Sandy might have been almost five years ago, but the storm is still having quite the impact on the property tax base of a lot of Jersey Shore communities, The New York Times reports. The big issue now is that federal aid that had been helping to fill the gap has run out, while Ocean County, N.J., is still about 8 percent short of its pre-storm property tax levels. \u201cIn Brick, that means the elimination of its Parks and Recreation Department. In Toms River, that means mandatory 10 percent budget cuts for every municipal department. In Seaside Heights, that means state monitors overseeing every expenditure,\u201d Nick Corasaniti wrote.  WATCH OUT, CHICAGO: The Cook County soda tax, which was supposed to go into effect July 1, will be up and running about a month late, The Associated Press reports. A judge on Friday threw out a lawsuit challenging the penny-per-ounce tax, filed by the Illinois Retail Merchants Association, which challenged the law for being too vague. Toni Preckwinkle, the president of the Cook County Board, says the tax \u2014 which the county projects will raise about $200 million in fiscal 2018 \u2014 will start on Wednesday.  QUICK LINKS  Taxes are now playing a role in Illinois\u2019 fight over school funding.  How a tax incentive for jobs in Michigan could leave out some new workers.  DID YOU KNOW?  The nation\u2019s oldest standing lighthouse, Sandy Hook, is in New Jersey.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
