aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Aaron Lorenzo   R.I.P., B.A.T.: And with that, the most controversial topic in the tax reform debate was swept aside.   Story Continued Below  That\u2019s of course the border adjustment, which the so-called Big Six of top lawmakers and administration bigwigs officially took out of the tax reform mix with their new statement on Thursday.   The glass half-full take on that: Taking away the central point of contention in tax reform, one that House Speaker Paul Ryan and Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady (R-Texas) had been clinging to pretty tightly, gives the process a jolt and policymakers the opportunity to unite behind the shared goals outlined in the new statement. (It might also allow Republicans to find a smoother path forward on tax reform than they ever have on the Obamacare replacement debate \u2014 though stay tuned on that.)   The glass mostly-empty take, from our Nancy Cook and Aaron Lorenzo: It\u2019s almost August, the window for actual legislating is getting smaller and smaller, and the central players in the tax reform debate just released something that was somehow less detailed than the much criticized one-pager from President Donald Trump\u2019s administration in April. \u201cTax overhauls live and die on details \u2014 and their absence, after months of weekly meetings aimed at achieving consensus, showed that the GOP's dream of achieving tax reform may be years from completion,\u201d Nancy and Aaron report. Also of note: Tax writers themselves now have to basically play the game perfectly from here with all the details left to be filled in: \u201cThat makes the conversation more difficult because we all now \u2014 50 out of 52 of us \u2014 have to agree on some number for short-term deficits,\u201d said Sen. Tim Scott (R-S.C.)   So what\u2019s next? You can expect that Senate Finance and House Ways and Means staffers will have a busy August starting to craft tax reform measures. And this likely wasn\u2019t the last hurrah either for the Big Six \u2014 Ryan, Brady, Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, Senate Finance Chairman Orrin Hatch (R-Utah), Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin and Gary Cohn, the director of the National Economic Council. But now, the six principals will be more like a central command system, as described by one person with knowledge of the next steps \u2014 still meeting regularly to make sure that the House, Senate and White House are moving in the right direction and in sync with one another.   Reading between the lines: It\u2019s fair to say the Big Six worded their statement fairly carefully, leading tax analysts to try and translate the intentions going forward. For instance: The statement calls permanent tax changes a priority, instead of a must \u2014 something that led some downtown observers to suggest that the Big Six was leaving itself some wiggle room in case Republicans are unable to craft something that isn't deficit-neutral, thus making it incompatible with Senate budget reconciliation rules. (To be fair, this wasn\u2019t a unanimous view.) There\u2019s definitely some fear among deficit hawks that Republicans will take the easier path of just cutting taxes in the end, but a couple of potential problems with that approach, via Ed Lorenzen of the Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget: the current House budget resolution and Senate pay-as-you-go rules.   Off the sidelines: Here\u2019s another potential positive point for tax reform following the new statement \u2014 the Business Roundtable is about to embark on a multi-million dollar national television and radio campaign in favor of tax reform, Nancy also reports. \u201cWe\u2019re taking the momentum created by the \u2018Big 6\u2019 and the unity going forward and taking advantage of the members being at home to hear about tax reform over the recess,\u201d said a BRT spokesperson. Why that\u2019s important: Trump\u2019s already supposed to hit the stump for tax reform next month. And before now, big national business groups like the Roundtable were largely sidelined in the tax reform debate, at least in part because the border adjustment divided their membership \u2014 suggesting the new statement will perhaps be bringing even more of those forces into the game.  About that budget: Remember how House Freedom Caucus members wanted the House budget to make a call on the border adjustment? That\u2019s not necessary any more, and yet Rep. Mark Meadows (R-N.C.), the Freedom Caucus chairman, says the votes for the House budget still aren\u2019t there, The Hill\u2019s Niv Elis reports.   MERCIFULLY, Friday has arrived. It\u2019s now been 151 years since Vinnie Ream became the youngest person ever, and the first woman, to get commissioned by the U.S. to create a statue. (She was 18. The statue is of Abraham Lincoln, and it currently stands in the Capitol Rotunda.)   Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  THAT HEALTH CARE PROCESS: Sorry tax nerds, but it doesn't seem that the Big Six statement will be making the front pages. Early this morning, a trio of GOP senators \u2014 Susan Collins of Maine, John McCain of Arizona and Lisa Murkowski of Alaska \u2014 brought down the so-called skinny Obamacare repeal that Republican leaders were pushing, which included a repeal of the medical device tax. (So what's it mean for tax reform? Give it a few more hours.)  It's not as important now, but the Senate also passed an amendment to permanently repeal the so-called \u201cCadillac tax\u201d on expensive employer-provided health insurance. The amendment, from Sen. Dean Heller (R-Nev.), passed mostly on a party-line vote \u2014 largely because Democrats didn\u2019t want to back a vote aimed at undercutting Obamacare, as the Health team\u2019s Paul Demko reports. In fact, the Cadillac tax, now scheduled to go into effect in 2020, is so unpopular in both parties that it isn\u2019t expected to be implemented.   BACK FOR MORE TAX RETURNS: Rep. Bill Pascrell of New Jersey, the House Democrat who\u2019s perhaps been the most steadfast in going after Trump\u2019s tax returns, is back with yet another approach \u2014 a resolution of inquiry seeking the president\u2019s tax returns from 2006 to 2016, as well as the returns of 515 of Trump\u2019s business entities. The hook this time: tax reform. \u201cWe know that the tangled web of the President\u2019s potential conflicts cannot be understood without a full picture of his business empire,\u201d Pascrell said in a statement, adding that lawmakers have to \u201cexamine Mr. Trump\u2019s network of businesses, and to understand the deductions and loopholes the President uses\u201d and to \u201censure that White House policy-making is not being done in service to the President\u2019s personal financial advantage.\u201d   It perhaps goes without saying, but this would seem to be the sort of measure that Democrats could use to make some noise at a tax reform markup.   WHAT DO YOU GET FOR THOSE TAX BREAKS? The Taiwanese company Foxconn, known for its role in assembling Apple\u2019s iPhones, has agreed to build a 20 million square foot factory in Wisconsin \u2014 as Trump, Ryan, Gov. Scott Walker and others all announced at the White House on Wednesday. In exchange, the company could get in the neighborhood of $3 billion in tax breaks from Wisconsin, as The Washington Post\u2019s Danielle Paquette explains. \u201cAs long as Foxconn keeps hiring U.S. workers at the new flat-screen manufacturing facility, Wisconsin would cut the company $200 million to $250 million a year for up to 15 years. That works out to a rough cost to the state of about $230,700 per worker, assuming the factory goes on to generate 13,000 jobs.\u201d   Walker himself told a Wisconsin radio station that the state was basically paying the going rate for job creation. \u201cWhat we\u2019re proposing is not outrageous,\u201d he said, via Reuters. Gov. Rick Snyder of Michigan, Wisconsin\u2019s next-door neighbor, wasn\u2019t so sure. \u201cYou have to ask what price is Wisconsin paying to get them to come there?" Snyder, a fellow Republican, said in a radio interview of his own. "I don\u2019t believe in buying companies into our states."   INTERNATIONAL UPDATE \u2014   WELCOME BACK, MARGRETHE VESTAGER: The European Commission has told France and Belgium to get rid of the tax breaks they offer for ports, saying that offers the two countries an unfair advantage over the other 26 European Union members, the Associated Press reports. Margrethe Vestager, the European antitrust czar, gave the countries until next year to revamp their systems for taxing ports, saying the current arrangements \u201cdistort the level playing field and fair competition.\u201d The E.C. gave a similar directive to the Netherlands last year.   STATE NEWS \u2014   NOT CHANGING NOW: Gov. Sam Brownback of Kansas, just nominated to a Trump administration position on religious freedom, has but one regret about the signature tax cuts that will be a big part of his legacy \u2014 that some of them were rolled back, the AP reports. In fact, the governor said that the legislature\u2019s decision to scrap a provision that zeroed out taxes on pass-through businesses was one of the biggest regrets of his six-and-a-half years in office, and blamed problems in the agriculture and energy sectors for the state\u2019s recent budget troubles. "We've opened up a new policy frontier," Brownback said. "I don't think that's going away in the country because the growth of small business is so critical."   MORE AND MORE TAXES: The Pennsylvania Senate went beyond raising taxes on natural gas drilling and utilities in its measure to close a $2.2 billion budget gap, the AP reports. \u201cGOP senators hope to raise another $43.5 million by requiring online marketplaces like Amazon and eBay to collect sales tax from third-party sellers using their sites. The Senate plan also counts on $200 million in revenue from another massive expansion of casino-style gambling in Pennsylvania, the nation's No.2 commercial gambling state, but it hasn't been approved and is still the subject of a disagreement with the House.\u201d (At first blush, that online sales tax proposal would seem to run afoul of the Supreme Court precedent that only allows states to collect from in-state retailers. Let us know if you think differently.)   QUICK LINKS    \u2014 Mark Mazur, former assistant Treasury secretary for tax policy in Obama administration: 15 percent corporate rate ain\u2019t happening.    \u2014 Trump\u2019s efforts to protect the U.S. steel industry have run into some hiccups.   DID YOU KNOW?   Yushan, a mountain in Taiwan that stands almost 13,000 feet above sea level, is the highest point crossed by the Tropic of Cancer.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
