aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  07/27/2017 10:01 AM EDT  With help from Colin Wilhelm   SOMETHING IS COMING: It was quite the buzzy Wednesday in D.C. tax circles, with all that discussion about Republicans having a further tax reform release before the week ran out.   Story Continued Below  So what do we know now? There\u2019s definitely something expected this week \u2014 so keep your eyes open today. The so-called Big Six of administration officials and top congressional types didn\u2019t offer up much after their latest meeting on Wednesday evening. What we don\u2019t really know is how much further substance Republicans will actually release, as they try to use August to gin up more momentum for tax reform. (In other words, how much will this be largely a messaging exercise?)   What else do we know? GOP tax writers in both the House and the Senate weren\u2019t getting any substantive updates out of the Big Six on Wednesday. House Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady (R-Texas) handed out pocket calendars with suggested tax reform messaging, mostly bashing the current system as too complicated and weighing down the economy. Rank-and-file Republicans also got a pocket card that outlines some basic areas of agreement within the party \u2014 killing the estate tax, for instance, while lowering tax rates and installing fewer tax brackets. (Left unmentioned: The controversial border adjustment in the House GOP blueprint. More on that in a bit.) So long story short: Brady wants to make sure that tax reform doesn\u2019t get lost in the messaging shuffle when members are back home next month.   On the other side of the Capitol, Senate Finance Republicans had a long meeting of their own Wednesday, with presentations on the various issue areas assigned to tax writers by Chairman Orrin Hatch (R-Utah). The meeting allowed Hatch \u201cto continue to seek input on how members want to move forward on comprehensive tax reform,\u201d a Finance spokeswoman said. \u201cThey discussed process and policy options, as members continue their efforts to overhaul the nation\u2019s broken tax code.\u201d   Also, there\u2019s a long way to go: And no matter what happens the rest of this week, Republicans still have a lot of tough questions to work their way through for tax reform to be successful. Case in point: Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin and Shahira Knight, the former Ways and Means staffer who\u2019s now the White House\u2019s most senior person on taxes, have been sparring over any number of tax proposals, Nancy Cook reports. Those disagreements have largely been over how to offset the sort of rate cuts the administration was after \u2014 Knight, for instance, is more into getting rid of the deduction for business interest than Mnuchin. But Knight also had to convince Mnuchin and Gary Cohn, the director of the National Economic Council, to back a territorial system over a pure worldwide system, Nancy notes. Oh, and this, too: Knight said in a recent meeting that attendees \u201cdid not need to spend much time talking about the border adjustment tax, leaving the impression that it was no longer on the table from the administration\u2019s perspective.\u201d   Other signs: White House officials are already considering a Plan B that would be a more straightforward tax cut in the event there\u2019s no agreement on full-scale reform, The Washington Post\u2019s Damian Paletta reports. The three main planks that are being pushed by outside advisers Larry Kudlow and Steve Moore \u2014 cutting the corporate rate to 15 percent, doubling the standard deduction and lowering the tax rate for offshore corporate profits, all for 10 years. (One question there: Top House GOP staffers have said that even a corporate rate cut that lasts three years would add to the deficit in the out years, running afoul of Senate budget reconciliation rules.)   And there\u2019s this, from The Intercept\u2019s Ryan Grim: \u201cTop White House adviser Steve Bannon is pushing for tax reform to include a new 44 percent top marginal tax rate, hitting people who earn more than $5 million a year, with the revenue paying for tax cuts for the rest, according to three people who\u2019ve spoken to him recently.\u201d   GET EXCITED FOR ANOTHER EDITION of Morning Tax, everybody. It\u2019s happy birthday time for one Bugs Bunny, whose formal name is apparently George Washington Bunny and who debuted on this day 77 years ago in an animated short called \u201cThe Wild Hare.\u201d   We\u2019re available for any and all bits of tax news. Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  HEALTH CARE INTERLUDE: The so-called \u201cskinny\u201d Obamacare repeal, which would roll back the medical device tax, among other things, doesn\u2019t have the votes yet, Burgess Everett, Jennifer Haberkorn and Seung Min Kim report.   HEY, DEMS \u2026 STOP FIDDLING AROUND THE EDGES: That\u2019s at least one takeaway that progressive tax analysts have about the current Democratic approach to taxes \u2014 especially after party leaders stopped barely short of avoiding the topic altogether in their new \u201cBetter Deal\u201d agenda. In short, some on the left believe that Democrats need to worry less about tax rates and loopholes and more about how capital is taxed if they really want to battle income inequality, The Washington Post\u2019s Max Ehrenfreund reports. Not only that: Many Democrats want expanded government programs for paid family leave and tuition assistance, among other things, but aren\u2019t willing to increase middle-class taxes to pay for it. \u201cThe only remaining option is to increase taxes on the rich, but without innovative capital taxes, their proposals will not really get at that money,\u201d according to David Kamin, a former economic adviser to former President Barack Obama, as paraphrased by Ehrenfreund. (A reminder that this was an issue with Sen. Bernie Sanders\u2019 presidential campaign, when he relied on tax increases on more than just the wealthy to pay for universal health care and other programs.)   LIVE TO SEE ANOTHER DAY: Republicans haven\u2019t had much problem knocking the Congressional Budget Office for their recent health care projections. But here was the step too far, as the Budget team\u2019s Jennifer Scholtes reports: A large chunk of House Republicans teamed with Democrats to turn aside a pair of amendments to cut CBO\u2019s funding, including a proposal to scrap its Budget Analysis Division, that were favored by conservatives. \u201cThis amendment is not the best way to accomplish our goal of obtaining better information and analysis from the CBO,\u201d said House Budget Chairwoman Diane Black (R-Tenn.)   The vote came after a range of outside groups called on the House to vote the amendments down, as did Brady and Rep. Richard Neal of Massachusetts, the top Democrat on the Ways and Means panel.   THE ADMINISTRATION AND ONLINE SALES TAX: Maybe it\u2019s just us, but Morning Tax isn\u2019t really used to Treasury secretaries weighing in on online sales tax matters. But that\u2019s exactly what Steven Mnuchin did on Wednesday, as Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo reports \u2014 telling a Senate hearing that \u201cthis is an issue that we've been looking at very carefully within the administration, and we expect to come out with a position shortly.\u201d The Treasury secretary also included some questions about the tax policies employed by Amazon, which has been known to be on the wrong end of some of President Donald Trump\u2019s tweets \u2014 most notably why the online sales giant charges taxes on items it sells directly to consumers, but not on items from third-party sellers on its marketplace.   Mnuchin has discussed the online sales tax issue with retailers, though only on the most surface of levels, according to someone with knowledge of those conversations. Trump himself has also seemed to suggest that he backs the idea of giving states more power to force out-of-state companies to collect sales taxes, the idea backed by retailers and Amazon.   Oh, so you\u2019re the one: One of the arguments that supporters of online sales tax legislation often rely on is that consumers almost never pay the use tax that they\u2019re frequently supposed to if they\u2019re not charged sales tax. But Mnuchin says he\u2019s not that kind of guy. \u201cI may be one of the few people in the world who actually file a use tax,\u201d he said.   More Mnuchin: A simpler tax code, coupled with improved technology, will help assuage concerns about the IRS\u2019s ability to offer quality taxpayer services, Mnuchin said, also via Aaron.   ANOTHER INTERLUDE FOR TAX REFORM MESSAGING: Grover Norquist\u2019s Americans for Tax Reform is breaking out the Huey Lewis and the News to remind people that it\u2019s been almost 31 years since the last tax overhaul.   INTERNATIONAL UPDATE \u2014   BANKERS\u2019 BOOT STATUS \u2014 SHAKING: British Labour Party leaders are warning London\u2019s financial sector that they\u2019ll be facing new taxes if Jeremy Corbyn gets to form a government, Reuters reports. John McDonnell, the likely Finance minister if Corbyn is prime minister, met with finance executives at London\u2019s stock exchange to get feedback on Labour\u2019s proposals. London\u2019s financial set had largely ignored Corbyn until recent months, but are now more interested in \u201cLabour's proposals to expand an existing tax on shares to include trading on other assets such as bonds and derivatives. Labour says the tax \u2014 proposed to be around half of a percentage point or less on the value of a trade \u2014 could earn 4.7 billion pounds a year.\u201d   STATE NEWS \u2014   ON YOU, DRILLERS: Pennsylvania\u2019s GOP Senate is considering a tax on natural gas drilling to help get the state\u2019s books in order, as well as new taxes on gas, electric and phone services, Philly.com reports. The $550 million those taxes would raise is more than a quarter of what\u2019s necessary to close a $2 billion budget gap.   QUICK LINKS    \u2014 The IRS still has a lot of work to do to shore up its cybersecurity operations, according to GAO.    \u2014 Trump nominates Gov. Sam Brownback of Kansas, whose tenure has become largely defined by his tax policies, to be an ambassador at-large for religious freedom.    \u2014 More sport: Brazilian soccer star Neymar cleared on tax charges, his dad says.   DID YOU KNOW?   Huey Lewis and the News and Celine Dion both had songs named \u201cThe Power of Love\u201d reach the top of the charts.  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
