aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Aaron Lorenzo and Colin Wilhelm   DUCKS FINDING THEIR ROWS: Tax reform might not be taking center stage yet, but know this: Republicans on both sides of Pennsylvania Avenue are already trying to figure out the best way to sell a tax overhaul to voters.   Story Continued Below  Cases in point: More than two dozen people from a range of grassroots conservative groups sat down with White House communications and political staffers on Tuesday to try to get on the same page on tax reform messaging, while House Republicans are gearing up to sell the idea back in their home districts next month.   The administration meeting was in part an acknowledgment that Republicans didn\u2019t cover themselves in glory on the public relations front when it came to repealing Obamacare, according to one attendee \u2014 no matter what the final outcome is on health care. \u201cThe general pitch of this meeting was to see how conservatives can make sure that the grassroots are energized on this and to make sure everyone is rowing in the same direction,\u201d the attendee said. (Among the groups involved: Americans for Prosperity, Americans for Tax Reform, Freedom Partners, FreedomWorks, the Heritage Foundation, the National Taxpayers Union and the R Street Institute.)   Conservatives are hoping that crafting a pitch for taxes will be easier than on health care, given that it\u2019s a bread-and-butter GOP issue. During Wednesday\u2019s meeting, attendees discussed a message that emphasized how tax reform could deliver lower taxes and a simpler system to voters in the middle parts of the income scale, with less of a focus on the wealthy.   The president\u2019s on message here! As it would happen, President Donald Trump sold his tax plan in just that sort of fashion in a Tuesday interview with The Wall Street Journal, while still pushing to bring the corporate tax rate down to 15 percent. \u201cThe people I care most about are the middle-income people in this country, who have gotten screwed,\u201d Trump said. \u201cAnd if there\u2019s upward revision it\u2019s going to be on high-income people.\u201d   Trump is also expected to hit the road next month to pitch tax reform \u2014 which, it should be noted, will come before administration and congressional negotiators are done with crafting an actual framework. It should also be noted that outside analysts have said that Trump\u2019s tax proposals would most help the wealthy, and that the math for doing all that the president wants without adding to the deficit would be challenging. (Those around Trump have started talking about how the rate for businesses will likely have to creep higher.)   As for the House: GOP leaders told the rank-and-file at a conference meeting Tuesday morning that they\u2019d be \u201creleasing plenty more about the party\u2019s tax plans in August,\u201d as our Budget team put it. House Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady (R-Texas) has stressed recently that GOP lawmakers need to make a hard sell on tax reform when their home in August, but told Pro Tax that there\u2019s more discussions to come on that front and no decisions have been made about giving colleagues explicit instructions on how to pitch tax reform. Still, Rep. Peter Roskam (R-Ill.), the chairman of the Ways and Means tax policy subcommittee, said there\u2019s no reason to overthink it. Republican lawmakers should tell voters back home to count on tax reform happening to set clear expectations, and count on it themselves too, Roskam said. \u201cCome back after Labor Day and be ready,\u201d he said.   The work going on: The Big Six hashing out a tax plan are scheduled to meet today, Brady said earlier this week, while the chairman will also be stopping by a meeting of the conservative Republican Study Committee to discuss tax reform. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin met with agriculture groups on Tuesday, The Hill\u2019s Naomi Jagoda reported.  WELCOME TO MORNING TAX, where what if we told you there\u2019s still 60 percent of this workweek left. It\u2019s also 272 years since the first recorded match of women\u2019s cricket, held near Guildford, England. (When was the first recorded match of cricket in general? Jan. 17, 1597, though it\u2019s thought the game had been around for perhaps centuries before that.)   Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  FEELING PRETTY GOOD: It\u2019s still far from certain where the GOP\u2019s effort to roll back Obamacare goes next, but it certainly seems that a so-called \u201cskinny\u201d repeal that scraps the medical device tax is on the table. And that\u2019s just part of the reason that industry believes that the end is near for a tax they\u2019ve railed against for well over half a decade. \u201cI feel confident it will come off the books at some point this year,\u201d Scott Whitaker, the chief executive for the Advanced Medical Technology Association (AdvaMed), told Morning Tax on Tuesday.   Whitaker didn\u2019t want to predict how Congress would repeal the tax, but said there were at least three other potential vehicles outside of rolling back Obamacare \u2014 reauthorizations for both FDA user fees and the children\u2019s health insurance program, as well as possible big spending or tax packages. He added that AdvaMed doesn\u2019t expect any Democrats from states with big device industries, like Massachusetts and Minnesota, to back repealing the tax within a measure undercutting Obamacare. But Whitaker insisted that \u201cwe haven\u2019t found any of them who\u2019ve said they would get in the way of getting this done\u201d in another vehicle.   HELLO, FLOOR: Rep. Morgan Griffith\u2019s amendment to end the Congressional Budget Office\u2019s Budget Analysis Division will get a vote on the House floor after it cleared the Rules Committee, our Colin Wilhelm reports. Rep. Tom Cole (R-Okla.), a Rules member, said the measure \u2014 which would cut 89 jobs and save around $15 million \u2014 deserved a full hearing on the floor, even as he said he\u2019d oppose it. \u201cI just don\u2019t think, in my view, it\u2019s wise policy, but that\u2019s what you have debates for,\u201d Cole told POLITICO. House Freedom Caucus leaders have also backed the amendment from Griffith, who said in a release this week that CBO too frequently miss the mark on fiscal projections to be trusted.   Donald Marron, an Urban Institute fellow and former acting CBO director, has also expanded on his argument for why this is a bad idea.   FIRST LOOK: Art Laffer, the father of supply-side economics who already called the House GOP\u2019s proposed border adjustment pretty dumb this year, is out with a new paper arguing that the provision would hurt the insurance and reinsurance industries. The Republican blueprint, Laffer writes, \u201ccould amount to considerable economic harm for both insurance and reinsurance companies, as well as consumers and the global economy at large.\u201d   \u201cFirst, the economic effects of denying tax deductions for only importing companies could be disastrous \u2014 as other countries responded with their own trade protectionist measures, we would soon find a market with much less choice. Second, the complicated and numerous transactions flows present in an insurance or reinsurance contract cannot be easily defined as an import or export, and any and all corporate tax reform proposals must take this fact into consideration,\u201d Laffer added.   LET\u2019S GET LEGISLATING: Rep. Vern Buchanan (R-Fla.), chairman of the Ways and Means oversight subcommittee, said Tuesday that he wants bipartisan legislation to overhaul the IRS in place by next year\u2019s filing deadline, Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo reports. Such a revamp would also help the agency\u2019s shoddy records-keeping procedures, the topic of a Tuesday hearing, Buchanan added. "We want to try to be helpful, in terms of the agency being more productive and effective long term,\u201d he said. One potential issue there: Brady likes to talk about how the House tax reform blueprint, not exactly bipartisan, seeks to \u201cbust up\u201d the IRS.   In better news for the IRS: The agency has overseen a pretty steep drop in the number of identity theft cases after teaming up with tax preparers on the issue, the Associated Press\u2019 Stephen Ohlemacher reports. John Koskinen, the IRS chief, said there had been around 107,000 identity theft victims through May of this year, compared to almost 700,000 for 2015 and 377,000 last year. Koskinen chalked the decrease up in part to more robust security of taxpayer data.   INTERNATIONAL UPDATE \u2014   IT WENT TO 11: Tanzania just escalated its quarrel with Acacia, a mining company that gets all of its gold from the African country \u2014 to the tune of $190 billion, Bloomberg reports. The Tanzanian government says that\u2019s the bill for 17 years worth of underreported revenues ($40 billion in taxes and $150 billion in interest and penalties.) The company denies that any underreporting has gone on. And as Bloomberg notes, the bill it just got from Tanzania would amount to \u201calmost two centuries worth of the gold producer\u2019s revenue.\u201d   STATE NEWS \u2014   SO ABOUT THAT BILL: It doesn\u2019t look like Congress will be finding common ground on online sales tax issues anytime soon, if a House Judiciary subcommittee hearing from Tuesday is any indicator. The Judiciary panel was examining a measure from Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner (R-Wis.), and supported by Chairman Bob Goodlatte (R-Va.), that bars states from collecting sales tax from out-of-state retailers and from making other regulatory actions on other states.   Opponents of the measure, including groups like the National Conference of State Legislatures that want to give states more latitude to collect sales tax revenue, said the bill was far too broad. But proponents, including Goodlatte, said the one size fits all nature of the measure was the right approach to limiting states from interfering with one another. Another point to remember: Republicans remain divided on the issue, with Rep. Doug Collins (R-Ga.) saying he couldn\u2019t support the measure, as The Hill\u2019s Ali Breland reported.   QUICK LINKS    \u2014 House Small Business chairman wants to make sure those companies are front-and-center in tax reform.    \u2014 Anthony Scaramucci, new White House communications director, seeks tax break on sale of his stake in SkyBridge Capital.    \u2014 FEC staffers contact with former IRS official Lois Lerner didn\u2019t break any rules, wasn\u2019t intended to single out conservatives, according to FEC watchdog.    \u2014 NYT headline: \u201cCanada Debates Whether Gift of Leibovitz Photos Is Also a Tax Dodge.\u201d  \u2014 New study: Cigarette tax increases lead to smokers spending less on food.   DID YOU KNOW?   Mount Kilimanjaro, the highest point in Africa, is located in Tanzania.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
