aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Aaron Lorenzo and Colin Wilhelm   SLOWEST. PIVOT. EVER.: Today\u2019s Senate vote on health care \u2014 which looked likely to fail for much of Monday \u2014 now seems to be in much better shape.   Story Continued Below  That sets up the possibility that congressional negotiations over replacing Obamacare could get even more protracted, continuing to keep tax reform in the on-deck circle. But for now at least, the top officials working on taxes say they still expect the issue to get Washington\u2019s full attention come fall. House Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady (R-Texas) told reporters Monday that the so-called Big Six from the House, Senate, and Trump administration will huddle again on Wednesday for their latest tax meeting.   Another issue to watch out for: Senate Republicans are still looking for ways to wiggle around the parliamentarian\u2019s guidance that several provisions run afoul of budget reconciliation rules, including a proposal to not allow tax credits to help buy plans that cover abortions. \u201cConservatives are also hoping the GOP can repair their abortion restrictions for plans on insurance exchanges by funneling those tax credits through other programs, like Medicaid or the Children's Health Insurance Program. Those are already barred from using taxpayer funds to cover abortion with some exceptions,\u201d Burgess Everett, Seung Min Kim and Jennifer Haberkorn report. Brady said Monday that the current abortion restrictions were very important to House Republicans, but stopped short of calling them a dealbreaker.   FAR FROM DONE WITH CBO: Conservatives are seeking to take some more whacks at the Congressional Budget Office in spending legislation the House is set to vote on this week, our Colin Wilhelm reports. And this time, the whacks could be more than just rhetorical. (Recall that President Donald Trump\u2019s administration has been particularly critical of how CBO\u2019s projections about proposed GOP Obamacare replacements.)   Rep. Morgan Griffith (R-Va.) has proposed an amendment to scrap CBO\u2019s Budget Analysis Division, tossing aside 89 employees and $15 million in government salaries. Rep. Scott Perry (R-Pa.), in another amendment backed by House Freedom Caucus leaders, would force CBO to incorporate budget projections from four outside groups \u2014 the American Enterprise Institute, the Brookings Institution, the Heritage Foundation and the Urban Institute.   Rep. Mark Meadows (R-N.C.), the chairman of the House Freedom Caucus, said Monday evening that only the Griffith proposal has a chance to get a floor vote this week. For what it\u2019s worth, Perry\u2019s amendment worried some outside budget wonks who believe it\u2019d be a mistake to replace CBO\u2019s work with outside aggregations. \u201cCBO's budget folks help Congress in myriad ways that think tanks can't replicate,\u201d tweeted Donald Marron, an Urban Institute fellow and former CBO acting director.   THANKS FOR JOINING US for another edition of Morning Tax. No anniversary like a tax anniversary (taxiversary?): It\u2019s a century to the day since Canada first got an income tax \u2014 which was meant to be temporary.   What\u2019s going on out there? Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  THE WOOLLY WORLD OF ONLINE SALES TAX: A House Judiciary subcommittee is holding a hearing today on a measure that would essentially codify the current Supreme Court precedent that only allows states to collect sales tax on online purchases from companies that have a physical location in that state. It\u2019s not the first time that Rep. Jim Sensenbrenner (R-Wis.) has offered a bill to officially put the so-called Quill precedent into law. But it is the first time that House Judiciary Chairman Bob Goodlatte (R-Va.) has signed on to the bill, which adds a little extra verve to this morning\u2019s proceedings. (Adding a little more oomph: Goodlatte released his own set of online principles not even a year ago.)   The battle lines for the hearing have already been drawn. Groups like the Retail Industry Leaders Association and the Marketplace Fairness Coalition both have statements blasting the legislation, with an extra eye roll for Goodlatte. (RILA noted that retailers, who want states to have more latitude to collect sales taxes on online purchases, have \u201cworked in good faith with Goodlatte. The Marketplace Fairness Coalition, meanwhile, maintains that Goodlatte\u2019s committee has been \u201cunable to fulfill\u201d its role on online sales tax issues.) On the other side of the issue, Steve DelBianco of NetChoice said the legislation is necessary to combat states finding increasingly novel ways to capture online sales tax revenue \u2014 like Massachusetts, which recently floated the idea that cookies on a mobile phone constituted enough of a physical location. (One last note: Retailers are hoping to the Supreme Court will reconsider the Quill precedent in the not-too-distant future.)   SACRED COW INDEED: The mortgage interest deduction is widely seen as one of the most entrenched tax breaks in the entire U.S. code. But there\u2019s long been one group that hasn\u2019t been a huge fan \u2014 academics, many of whom believe that the deduction subsidizes the buying of larger homes but doesn\u2019t do much to actually spur home ownership. The most recent installment of that genre: Three professors, using evidence from 1980s Denmark, found \u201cno effect of the tax policy change on whether households own or rent,\u201d as The Wall Street Journal\u2019s Richard Rubin reported. One of those professors, Jonathan Gruber of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology \u2014 who you might have heard of because of Obamacare \u2014 further suggested in an interview with the WSJ that a first-time homebuyer credit or a deduction capped at an area\u2019s median house price would be a better way to go. Industry groups said a study based on decades-old data from Denmark wouldn\u2019t offer much insight to America\u2019s mortgage interest break.   GIVE IT UP FOR THE COMPUTER SCIENTISTS: One of the problems in tracking the offshore flow of corporate money has been distinguishing between the final destinations and the stop-offs along the way. And now, Quartz\u2019s Tim Fernholz reports that computer scientists have found a better way to track the journey. \u201cUsing a global dataset that tracks the relationships between more than 98 million companies, the researchers used algorithms to build a network that identified the relationships between corporate subsidiaries, tracing the flow of tax-free money from country to country through these corporate chains.\u201d   The findings: Some of the top final destinations are usual suspects like the British Virgin Islands, the Caymans and Bermuda. More surprisingly, Taiwan is a pretty popular last stop, while Panama \u2014 for all the controversy engendered by the Panama Papers \u2014 really isn\u2019t. But Panama is a good conduit to those final destinations, along with Switzerland, the Netherlands, Ireland and others.   PRAISING THE NMTC: Rural America benefits greatly from a tax credit meant to spur economic development in such areas as well as urban cores, according to a group supportive of the incentive. Financing through the New Markets Tax Credit has led to $11.6 billion in total private investment in economically distressed towns and farming communities, said a study from the New Markets Tax Credit Coalition. Those investments created 49,940 full-time jobs and 21,706 construction jobs, the study found. The credit was established in 2000 in the Community Renewal Tax Relief Act, and supporters have been pushing to ensure it survives in tax reform. It is currently available through 2019.  INTERNATIONAL UPDATE \u2014   WHY CAN\u2019T THIS BE CIVIL? The French government is hoping that Google will sit down and negotiate a deal on back taxes, after a French court decided that the tech titan didn\u2019t owe Paris more than 1 billion euros. French officials had said they would appeal that decision, but Reuters reports that Budget Minister Gerald Darmanin is now saying that a long legal process wouldn\u2019t help either side.   THE VERDICT, THREE WEEKS IN: People are still confused by India\u2019s Goods and Services Tax that kicked off at the start of the month, Bloomberg reports. \u201cTraders, particularly in small towns, are struggling with their lack of knowledge of the new tax regime \u2014 compliance obligations, raising invoices and accessing input credits, said Praveen Khandelwal, secretary general of the Confederation of All India Traders. Small merchants and e-commerce companies are tripping over a dizzying array of documents and the complicated classification system that determines what percentage of tax will be charged. Thousands of small merchants have stopped selling on e-commerce sites because they can\u2019t meet these new requirements.\u201d   STATE NEWS \u2014   SEE YOU AT THE BALLOT BOX: Texas moved one step closer to force local governments to get voter approval if property taxes rise, the Texas Tribune reported. The Texas Senate passed a measure on Monday that would allow voters in larger cities to weigh in if property taxes grow by more than 4 percent a year on existing property, while smaller entities would get to go to the polls after an 8 percent increase.   QUICK LINKS    \u2014 Treasury official: The U.S. believes other countries aren\u2019t interpreting international transfer pricing guidelines correctly, allowing themselves to collect more revenue.    \u2014 President Rodrigo Duterte of the Philippines wants to stop exporting mineral resources and threatens to tax miners \u201cto death.\u201d    \u2014 The Tax Foundation examines Oregon\u2019s bike tax.    \u2014 Random story of the day: Ways and Means staffer gently informed the Kennedy Center that their Utah flag had a typo.  \u2014 Not Florida, but still New Jersey: 75-year-old man upset with property tax increase threatens to burn down the mayor\u2019s house.   DID YOU KNOW?   Lawyers appearing before the Supreme Court receives quills before every oral argument.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
