aV \u000a            By BERNIE BECKER  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Aaron Lorenzo  NOT QUITE PIVOT TIME YET: Health care will remain the dominant topic in Washington this week, as it has for months now. But fall \u2014 when GOP leaders say they want to move on tax reform \u2014 will be here before you know it, so here\u2019s some things to watch out for on taxes in what is scheduled to be the last full week that both chambers are in Washington until September.  Story Continued Below  A big one: Can the House pass a budget? That\u2019s the vehicle for tax reform, which Republicans plan to pass through budget reconciliation. But as of now, the math for GOP vote counters looks difficult, and House Majority Leader Kevin McCarthy (R-Calif.) hasn\u2019t put the budget on this week\u2019s floor schedule as of yet.  Meanwhile, Republicans are continuing to hash out the actual policies they want on tax reform. The House GOP\u2019s controversial border adjustment doesn\u2019t seem to have much life left, but Koch Industries \u2014 one of that provision\u2019s most vocal opponents \u2014 still wants the House to use its budget to finish off the job, Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo reports. (Whatever you say about the battle against the BAT, it hasn\u2019t been cheap: Bloomberg reported that the National Retail Federation spent close to $5 million on lobbying in 2017\u2019s second quarter, or almost three times as much as it did in those three months the previous year.)  In any event, Republicans remain at least outwardly confident on tax reform. House Budget Chairwoman Diane Black (R-Tenn.), who\u2019s also a Ways and Means member, told Bloomberg Television last week that the GOP was 85 percent on the same page on taxes, per our Budget team. (Black\u2019s giving the GOP even more of a nudge in the right direction than Speaker Paul Ryan and Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady \u2014 who usually say Republicans are in 80 percent agreement \u2014 usually do.)  Also to watch out for: Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin is scheduled to testify Wednesday before a Senate Appropriations subcommittee, for those seeking any more clues on tax reform\u2019s path. (Also on the docket for that hearing: IRS Commissioner John Koskinen, whose agency\u2019s records retention policies will be under the microscope at the Ways and Means oversight subcommittee on Tuesday.)  Who else wants to pivot? Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, the Job Creators Network and the American Legislative Exchange Council want the focus to shift from health care to taxes, stat \u2014 and they\u2019re more focused on tax cuts than reform, The Hill reports.  And so what about health care? Speaking of math, the Senate GOP\u2019s efforts on Obamacare repeal appear to be facing their own problems, with a key vote expected on Tuesday, Jennifer Haberkorn and Seung Min Kim report. There\u2019s still a lot of questions about what actual policy the Senate would consider if it votes to continue working on the bill on Tuesday. But there is this: Many GOP senators \u201care more than ready to turn to other priorities, like tax reform.\u201d  One last thing: The Senate parliamentarian released guidance on Friday that said that Republicans efforts to place \u201cantiabortion limits around tax credits that people could use to buy health insurance\u201d likely violate Senate rules, The Wall Street Journal reported.   IT\u2019S TIME FOR ANOTHER WEEK of Morning Tax, where your author is back and ready to wish a happy birthday to Lady Tax, also known as the mother of Toddler Tax. It\u2019s also been 106 years since the Yale lecturer Hiram Bingham III found the famous Inca site of Macchu Picchu in Peru, though plenty of people will tell you it was never really lost. (Bingham might also have been an inspiration for Indiana Jones.)  We\u2019re ready for another busy week, so send us all your tips and feedback. Email: bbecker@politico.com, teckert@politico.com, bfaler@politico.com, cwilhelm@politico.com, alorenzo@politico.com. Twitter: @berniebecker3, @tobyeckert, @brian_faler, @colinwilhelm, @AaronELorenzo, @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Tax.  THINK THIS WOULDN\u2019T COME UP IN TAX REFORM? Don\u2019t tell medical device makers that Obamacare\u2019s tax on them will live to see another day, even if the Affordable Care Act is here to stay, the Minneapolis Star-Tribune reports. \u201cBob Paulson and hundreds of other executives in the massive medical technology sector are planning business operations on the assumption that the device tax is dead,\u201d Jim Spencer wrote. \u201cThe current expectation,\u201d Paulson told the Star-Tribune, \u201cis that it is not coming back.\u201d  That might be misplaced optimism, but those comments also point to perhaps one of the overlooked reasons why a Republican failure on health care complicates their efforts on tax reform. Lots of people like to talk about how repealing Obamacare would also change the revenue baseline for tax reform. But falling short also means that there would likely be more taxes \u2014 on device makers, wealthy people\u2019s capital gains and even tanning salons \u2014 to sift through on tax reform, something that top Republicans have started to acknowledge.  INFRASTRUCTURE WAS SUPPOSED TO BE EASIER: The New York Times\u2019 Glenn Thrush detailed how President Donald Trump\u2019s efforts to revive American infrastructure have, at least so far, largely run aground. Among the takeaways for taxes: Gary Cohn, the director of the National Economic Council, believed that pairing tax reform and infrastructure was a winner, as did Trump. But Mnuchin has been telling people that\u2019s too big of a package to pass \u2014 perhaps in part because there\u2019s a fair bit of skepticism among GOP leaders about combining the two.  PRETTY SOON, TALKING ABOUT REAL MONEY: Sen. John Thune\u2019s proposal to put more structure around how the U.S. taxes the so-called \u201csharing economy\u201d \u2014 think Airbnb, Etsy and Uber \u2014 would add up to a decent offset in tax reform, Bloomberg reports. \u201cThis is easily a multibillion-dollar bill,\u201d Caroline Bruckner of American University\u2019s Kogod Tax Policy Center said about a measure that would, among other things, force companies to tell the IRS about far more vendors\u2019 income. Still, the revenue the bill raises would like only be able to finance a very small portion of the GOP\u2019s ambitions when it comes to cutting tax rates.  WHO\u2019S A WINNER? The liberal Institute on Taxation and Economic Policy broke down the numbers on Trump\u2019s tax plan, and found it would generally help richer states more than poor states. The losers: Alabama, Arkansas, Hawaii, Idaho, Kentucky, Maine, Mississippi, New Mexico, North Carolina, Oregon, South Carolina and West Virginia, two-thirds of which voted for Trump. (The biggest winners under the Trump plan, which include 11 states and Washington, D.C., split evenly between the president and Hillary Clinton.)  INTERNATIONAL UPDATE \u2014   STEP BY STEP: Ireland will be setting up a fund to manage the 13 billion euros (currently $15.2 billion) that it\u2019s due from Apple, following the European Commission\u2019s ruling almost a year ago that the tax advantages that Dublin offered the tech giant amounted to illegal state aid. Apple and Ireland will jointly appoint someone to look after that money, which will be held in escrow. But as Bloomberg notes, this doesn\u2019t necessarily mean that the end of this story is near. Ireland was supposed to have gotten the back taxes from Apple by January, and both Dublin and the company have appealed the ruling \u2014 which could tie up the case for years more.  STATE NEWS \u2014   \u201cTRUMP EFFECT?\u201d It seems like wealthy people\u2019s efforts to push off paying taxes wherever they can, in order to wait for a tax cut from Trump, dragged down state government revenues, The Hill reports. \u201cTotal tax collections in April fell 4 percent over last year, according to a Rockefeller Institute of Government of 41 state governments. The analysis suggests wealthy taxpayers likely shifted taxable income they could have collected in 2016 to 2017, when they expect rates on capital gains will be lower after President Trump\u2019s tax reform push.\u201d  POT TAXES ARE HARD: Stop us if you\u2019ve heard this one before, but officials in a state where voters just approved a recreational pot measure are grappling with how to tax marijuana purchases. The case in point this time: Maine, one of four states that saw a ballot measure pass in November. The Associated Press notes that the leaders of a legislative committee tasked with filling in the details are suggesting the tax rate might creep higher as they try to hit the \u201csweet spot\u201d between maximizing revenue and driving consumers to the black market. (Recreational marijuana advocates say a rumored 20 percent rate would definitely push people toward the latter.)  LOCAL TAX NEWS ON THE HORIZON: A Cook County circuit judge is expected to announce on Friday his ruling on a lawsuit challenging the county\u2019s penny-per-ounce soda tax, The Chicago Tribune reports. The tax was supposed to go into effect the first of this month, but retailers and others challenging the levy won a temporary restraining order.  QUICK LINKS  \u2014 The AP examines the GOP efforts to kill off the state and local tax deduction.  \u2014 New lawsuit from protesters involved in altercations at Trump rallies last year seeks the president\u2019s tax returns.  \u2014 San Francisco supervisor wants city to explore taxing large vacant buildings.  DID YOU KNOW?  Meat Loaf\u2019s 1993 single \u201cI Would Do Anything for Love (But I Won\u2019t Do That)\u201d reached No. 1 in 28 separate countries.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
