aV \u000a            By CATHERINE BOUDREAU  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from John Lauinger and Li Zhou  LOCAL FOOD AND RURAL AMERICA: The Federal Reserve is typically more likely to care about bank reserve ratios rather than fertilizer ratios. This week, however, monetary policy was not at the forefront of a book released by the Fed as well as a related forum in Washington. Instead, the Fed showcased how local and regional food systems can drive economic growth. There to deliver the keynote was Anne Hazlett, the newly appointed assistant to the secretary for rural development at the USDA. She said that supporting the growth of local and regional food supply chains could help address the top four challenges in remote areas of the country that she and Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue are working on: quality of life, workforce development, innovation and economic development.  Story Continued Below  "Whether it's through direct-to-consumer sales, farm-to-school programs or locally grown food in a grocery store, when I think about regional food systems, I see a strong tie to each of these four issues," Hazlett said to a room of regional food distributors, local and state policymakers, farming organizations, university researchers, bankers and investors. For example, local and regional food systems produce new job opportunities. For every job that is created in a farm-to-school program, another 1.67 jobs are created in the local community, she said.  A book authored by the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis in partnership with the system's Board of Governors and the Agriculture Department, arrived at a time when policymakers are trying to tackle the economic challenges in rural America. (You could argue that the controversy over Perdue eliminating the USDA undersecretary for rural development post, and instead establishing Hazlett\u2019s position, is an extension of that.)  While local and regional food systems are expected to grow substantially in the next few years \u2014 sales are estimated to increase to more than $20 billion by 2019, according to the USDA data cited in the Fed's report \u2014 there are many obstacles to scaling production and distribution. Read the full story from yours truly here.  HAPPY FRIDAY, AUGUST 4! Welcome to Morning Ag, where host is happy to report that she survived a week flying solo on the ag beat, and is now heading to greener pastures in her home state of Vermont! You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips? Send them to cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  USDA RECOGNIZES FARMERS MARKET WEEK: Speaking of local food, the USDA has recognized local farmers and vendors for the last 17 years. Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue kept the streak going, issuing a proclamation on Thursday designating Aug. 6-13 as National Farmers Market Week. Perdue highlighted that farmers markets and direct-marketing outlets contribute about $9 billion each year to the U.S. economy.   \u201cBuying directly from farmers and ag-entrepreneurs has an outsized impact by helping diversify farm incomes and supporting other businesses by keeping more money in the local economy. In addition to being good for the farmers and convenient for consumers, farmers markets are a gathering place that help build a sense of community,\u201d the department said.   PERDUE: FARM BILL SHOULD \u2018FOLLOW THE MARKET\u2019: Perdue on Thursday made his way around southeastern Wisconsin, the first stop of his \u201cBack to Our Roots\u201d R.V. tour across five states. In an interview with the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, Perdue said his main goal for the next iteration of the 2018 farm bill was to ensure that it would not direct farmers\u2019 planting decisions: \u201cMy principle for the farm bill is it should follow the market, not guide the market. I don\u2019t want people farming for the farm bill,\u201d he said, hitting on a long-held criticism of some subsidy programs in the farm bill -- that they give producers incentives to plant certain crops instead of allowing market conditions to dictate.  Perdue also echoed previous comments on SNAP. Just as he supports a safety net for farmers, Perdue said he supports one for people who don\u2019t have enough to eat. \u201cBut we don\u2019t want it to become a lifestyle for people who become dependent on a government program,\u201d Perdue told the Journal Sentinel.   Today, Perdue is heading north. The secretary is taking the Interagency Task Force on Agriculture and Rural Prosperity on the road, as well, hosting a listening session today at the Northcentral Technical College in Wausau, Wis., with local elected officials, broadband industry leaders, Wisconsin Farm Bureau members and students.  Take MA out to the ball game? Maybe some day. Tonight, Perdue and USDA staffers will take in a Twins game at Target Field in Minneapolis.   TRUMP TO DASH OIL REFINERS\u2019 DREAMS ON ETHANOL RULES: The Trump administration plans to reject a proposal that would let oil refiners off the hook for complying with the federal ethanol mandate, a senior administration official told Pro Energy\u2019s Eric Wolff, dashing the hopes of billionaire Carl Icahn and several independent companies. The EPA plans to formally announce the decision within the next two weeks, the official said.   The move is a severe blow for Icahn, a longtime associate and early supporter of Trump, who owns the refiner CVR Energy. Icahn, refining giant Valero and smaller refinery firms argued that purchasing compliance credits, called Renewable Identification Numbers, squeezed their bottom lines and, in some cases, threatened to put them out of business. Icahn's CVR lost $19 million in the second quarter of this year after guessing incorrectly that the administration would make the policy change.  Corn power. But Trump has turned away from one of Icahn's main policy goals, in large part because of pressure from corn state voters and ethanol organizations. Corn state residents and ethanol interests have been lobbying hard, arguing that the change would set back an ethanol industry that is vital to many communities that strongly backed Trump.  HOUSE DEMS CALL FOR TRANSPARENCY IN NAFTA TALKS: Democratic Reps. Bill Pascrell and Debbie Dingell are asking for their colleagues\u2019 support in requesting that the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative ramp up its engagement with Congress in the coming NAFTA negotiations, Pro Trade\u2019s Megan Cassella reports. Pascrell, ranking member on the House Ways and Means\u2019 Trade Subcommittee, and Dingell are circulating a \u201cDear Colleague\u201d letter, asking for signatures on a separate letter to U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer that calls for, among other things, access to negotiating texts for personal congressional staff of any member and not just those on the committees of jurisdiction; the public release of U.S. negotiating proposals; access to other documents that don\u2019t fall into the category of a U.S. proposals or the consolidated negotiating text; and the appointment of a chief transparency officer.  \u201cWith NAFTA negotiations beginning later this month, it is imperative that the Trump administration develop a process for sharing negotiating documents with Congress and the public,\u201d the two Democrats wrote. \u201cSuch a process is necessary to get Congressional and public support for any eventual agreement.\u201d  WELL, THAT WAS FAST: Hours before Al Almanza\u2019s four-decade career at FSIS drew to a close on Monday, he told Pro Ag\u2019s Helena Bottemiller Evich that \u201cit is a great thing to get to leave when people want you and want you to stay.\u201d People wanted him, all right. JBS SA announced Thursday that it hired the former FSIS administrator to be its global food czar, a newly created position. Almanza\u2019s title will be global head of food safety and quality assurance. He\u2019ll be based in Greeley, Colo., and be responsible for \u201censuring that JBS operations around the world implement the highest food safety, quality control and risk management systems,\u201d the company said in a release.  In many ways, Almanza\u2019s new job will be to use his experience and reputation to help JBS rebound from the food safety and corruption probes, which led to the company paying $3.2 billion in fines in a settlement this year. Pro Agriculture\u2019s John Lauinger has more on Almanza\u2019s new gig here.  Focus on the future: Now, the task falls to Perdue and the Trump administration to replace Almanza. \u201cWe have been at odds with Mr. Almanza with respect to many food safety policies and needed reforms,\u201d Thomas Gremillion, director of food policy at the Consumer Federation of America, told MA on Thursday. \u201cHe has been accessible and shown a willingness to hear our concerns, but I am hopeful that his successor, not to mention a new undersecretary for food safety, takes more aggressive action on behalf of consumers to improve the performance of the meat and poultry inspection system.\u201d   SENATE CONFIRMS 3 CFTC NOMINEES: In a rush to skip town for a four-week August recess, the Senate cleared a backlog of more than 60 nominees by voice vote on Thursday afternoon. Those confirmed included J. Christopher Giancarlo as CFTC chairman, and Brian Quintenz and Rostin Behnam as commissioners. The raft of approvals did not include CFTC commissioner nominee Dawn Stump, a former lobbyist for the derivatives industry who earned almost $400,000 in the last year working working for an industry association that has been critical of the agency's regulations. Giancarlo, a CFTC commissioner since 2014, had been serving as acting chairman. Quintenz is the founder of a hedge fund, and Behnam is a former aide to Sen. Debbie Stabenow, ranking member of the Agriculture Committee.  Greenlight for USAID Administrator. Also confirmed in the afternoon scramble was former Rep. Mark Green (R-Wis.) to be administrator of the U.S. Agency for International Development. Green served in Congress from 1999 to 2007 and was U.S. ambassador to Tanzania from 2007 to 2009. Most recently, he was president of the International Republican Institute.  Senate Flyaway: As the Senate takes its August leave of The Swamp, POLITICO\u2019s Elana Schor and Seung Min Kim put together this recap of how Senate Republicans passed their final days before vacation \u2014 they \u201cdelivered an unstated declaration of independence from their own Republican president.\u201d Read that here.   HATCH CALLS DEMS CORPORATE CRACKDOWN \u2018PARANOIA\u2019: Sen. Orrin Hatch on Thursday slammed congressional Democrats\u2019 new economic agenda and its call to crack down on corporate monopolies. The Utah Republican said on the Senate floor that the plan \u201camounts to little more than pseudo-economic demagoguery and anti-corporate paranoia.\u201d Hatch acknowledged that advances in technology could prompt authorities to reframe antitrust policy, but argued that there did not need to be a new \u201cprogressive standard\u201d on the issue.  \u201cTruth be told, the real trouble for the progressive standard is that it fails to grab the bigger picture of our history, economy and national character,\u201d he said, arguing that regulators should continue to use the existing consumer welfare approach to evaluate mergers like the Amazon-Whole Foods deal.  Dems\u2019 plan to hit corporate power. The Democrats unveiled their economic platform last week, which is packaged under the slogan \u201cA Better Deal.\u201d An anti-monopoly platform is part of the agenda, including targeting the agriculture and food and beverage industries. The pending mergers among six agrochemical companies \u2014 Dow with DuPont, Monsanto with Bayer AG, and Syngenta with ChemChina \u2014 are singled out as examples of the trend of concentration of power. Democrats want to establish new antitrust standards to limit large mergers and require federal regulators to review closed transactions more frequently, as well as create a new \u201ccompetition advocate,\u201d whose mission it would be to handle consumer complaints and recommend investigations to the FTC and the DOJ.  CANTWELL: NEW TECHNOLOGY NEEDED TO FIGHT FIRES: As forest fires this year have blazed through Western states like Kansas, Oklahoma, Texas, Montana, Utah, Arizona and Washington, senators are urging the Interior Department to use new technology to fight them and keep workers safe. During a Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee hearing Thursday, Rep. Maria Cantwell pressed Bryan Rice, an Interior Department official, on why the agency wasn't trying new systems, reports POLITICO\u2019s Luis Sanchez. The Washington state Democrat cited GPS tracking technology and unmanned drones as examples of new tools that could aid in the safety of firefighters during forest fires.  Rice, who directs the Interior Department\u2019s office of wildland fire, disputed Cantwell\u2019s assertion, and said staff in local areas were using such technology, and the department was examining ways to deploy it more broadly. Cantwell again impressed upon Rice that her state \u201cloves technology and it loves to keep pushing the envelope, so don't hold us back to getting solutions in the marketplace, this summer if we can."  MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 Intense drought in eastern Montana and North and South Dakota has forced ranchers to sell their cattle and farmers to harvest crops early, the AP reports.  \u2014 The FDA\u2019s decision to give food and beverage companies more time to adopt the new Nutrition Facts panel has led to inconsistency in the marketplace as some manufacturers press ahead anyway, The Wall Street Journal reports.  \u2014 Western Farm Press looks at Arizona to consider how the agricultural teacher shortage can negatively affect quality of instruction for students. That\u2019s here.   \u2014 Global food prices increased for the third straight month in July, powered mainly by higher cereal, sugar and dairy quotations, according to the U.N. agriculture agency. More here.   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
