aV \u000a            By CATHERINE BOUDREAU  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from John Lauinger, Megan Cassella and Annie Snider  FEDERAL RESERVE PROMOTES LOCAL FOOD: The Federal Reserve and USDA are unveiling a new report today to showcase how local and regional food systems can help the economies of rural and urban communities, as well as increase access to healthier food and create a more productive workforce. The report is intended to signal that local food is no longer just for \u201cfoodies,\u201d but instead is in high demand by consumers across the country and is ripe for investment and financing. Through a compilation of research, essays and case studies, the report highlights possibilities like: communities that used regional food strategies to meet economic goals; opportunities in the regional food system sector; systems that benefit low- and moderate-income households; and models of partnerships between policymakers, members of the community and the financial industry.   Story Continued Below  The report arrives at a critical time in light of the heightened attention to the condition of rural America, said Jen O'Brien Cheek, executive director of the Farmers Market Coalition. (A board member of the group contributed to the report).   \u201cWe want to bring in investors and institutions that offer loans and grants to make sure initiatives are supported, because it\u2019s been demonstrated that they have a lasting impact on economic prosperity,\u201d O\u2019Brien Cheek said. \u201cReally successful food systems respond to unique needs of a community.\u201d The report also lands just before the start of Farmers Market Week (Aug. 6-12).  The Federal Reserve Board of Governors, in partnership with the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis and the USDA Rural Development and Agricultural Marketing Service, is hosting a forum today to release the report, which explores \u201cunanswered research, policy and resources gaps,\u201d that need to be addressed. You can find the agenda for the forum here.  HAPPY THURSDAY, AUGUST 3! Welcome to Morning Ag, where your host has an addiction to mango mochi ice cream (you really ought to try it, too). You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips? Send them to cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  FOR CLOVIS, WHAT\u2019S OLD IS NEW (AGAIN): Sam Clovis, the nominee for USDA chief scientist, already was in trouble with Democrats. Writings the former Iowa academic made in 2011 and 2012 on a now-defunct blog during his conservative radio talk show days were unearthed yesterday by CNN \u2014 via the Internet Archive Wayback Machine. They reveal him calling progressives \u201cliars, race-traders and race-\u2018traitors\u2019\u201d and accusing labor unions of coming out of the \u201cCommunist closet\u201d to support \u201csocialist\u201d Barack Obama.   Clovis had already been facing opposition from Democrats and left-leaning advocacy and science groups. They assert that he does not possess the academic credentials legally required for the post of USDA undersecretary for research, education and economics. Critics have also attacked him for his climate skepticism. In addition, Senate Agriculture Chairman Pat Roberts recently issued a warning \u2014 albeit without mentioning Clovis by name \u2014 that his past position on the federally subsidized crop insurance program being unconstitutional simply would not fly with the committee.  Those controversies aside, Clovis has the backing of some 23 agricultural groups that regard the Trump administration official \u2014 he is currently USDA\u2019s liaison to the White House \u2014 as someone who has Trump\u2019s ear because of his campaign roots.  That said, Clovis\u2019 statements on race, in particular, are dangerous ground, especially because of USDA\u2019s history on that issue and reputation among critics as \u201cthe last plantation.\u201d In an August 2011 post, for instance, Clovis urged Republicans to call out progressives, saying they \u201chave done everything possible to keep minorities in this country enslaved to government.\u201d He said that was \u201cparticularly true in the African-American community," accusing progressives of attacking "the individual, the black family unit, the female and the black male to essentially eliminate people of color from the American landscape.\u201d More on the contentious issue here.  McKinney in committee: The White House announced on Wednesday that the nomination of Ted McKinney, Indiana\u2019s director of agriculture, for the new post of USDA undersecretary for trade and foreign agricultural affairs, had been sent to the Senate. He\u2019ll have company in waiting for a confirmation hearing: Clovis and Steve Censky, the nominee for deputy secretary, are also in a holding pattern.  MEXICO\u2019S NAFTA DREAMS AT ODDS WITH \u2018AMERICA FIRST\u2019: The first glimpse of Mexico\u2019s negotiating goals for NAFTA 2.0 revealed the U.S. may already be on a collision course with its southern neighbor ahead of the upcoming renegotiation, Pro Trade\u2019s Adam Behsudi reports. Mexico views the free trade deal as a cornerstone of its economy. It seeks a new version that would make the country an even bigger producer and exporter.   That goal, laid out in a statement of priorities submitted to the Mexican Senate and released this week, will likely not be well received by the Trump administration, which wants to revamp NAFTA in a way that reduces the U.S. trade deficit south of the border. Something\u2019s got to give.  More broadly, Mexico believes the new, NAFTA-promoted reality of an integrated North America must be accepted in order to have fruitful negotiations. \u201cAcross North America, thousands of workers, from those in the field to the engineers in charge of advanced manufacturing, depend in one form or another on the value chains that exist throughout the region,\u201d Mexican Economy Secretary Ildefonso Guajardo said in one of the documents, according to an unofficial translation. \u201cAccepting and understanding this reality is a fundamental step in properly evaluating NAFTA and identifying the areas in which we can work to strengthen the treaty.\u201d Pros, read the full story here.  Head south for Round 2: Guajardo said Mexico will host the second round of NAFTA talks sometime around Sept. 10, Reuters reports.  FALSE (CLIMATE) ALARM AT USDA? Some climate change information disappeared from the USDA website late last week before reappearing late yesterday, according to the Environmental Data & Governance Initiative. A USDA spokesman said the \u201coutages were the result of the site being migrated to a new server.\u201d The missing pages were from USDA\u2019s regional \u201cClimate Hubs,\u201d which are meant to provide tools to help farmers and land managers adapt to climate change.  Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue and Clovis, Trump\u2019s pick to be chief scientist, have both questioned human-caused climate change. But Perdue has also said he\u2019s committed to \u201cdigging ever deeper\u201d into research about agricultural production in light of a changing climate. EDGI, which is archiving public environmental data and monitoring changes to federal regulations and research to hold the Trump administration accountable, has seen no other changes to climate information on USDA\u2019s web pages.   SONNY PARKS HIS R.V. IN WISCONSIN TODAY: Perdue has a packed schedule in the Badger State today, beginning at 9:30 a.m. Central time, with the opening ceremony of the Wisconsin State Fair and a meeting with Gov. Scott Walker. Perdue will also discuss the 2018 farm bill with the Wisconsin Agriculture Secretary Ben Brancel and local farmers, including members of the Farm Bureau. Then it\u2019s on to Hunger Task Force Farm, which grows fruits and vegetables for food pantries and local meal programs. Perdue\u2019s last stop will be a meeting with House Speaker Paul Ryan, during which international trade, dairy farmers and immigration are likely to be topics du jour.   TRUMP ENDORSES BILL TO SLASH LEGAL IMMIGRATION: Trump came out Wednesday in support of a bill that would reduce legal immigration by one-half over the next decade. He joined Sens. Tom Cotton (R-Ark.) and David Perdue (R-Ga.) to present a reworked version of the so-called RAISE Act, S. 354 (115), originally introduced in February. Like the original measure, the revised bill would, over 10 years, reduce legal immigration to roughly 500,000 annually, down from the current level of about 1 million.   No help for U.S. agriculture. This isn\u2019t the kind of immigration legislation that the U.S. agriculture sector was pushing for. The RAISE Act would end petitioning by U.S. citizens and green-card holders to make extended family members lawful permanent residents, although spouses and minor children would still have preference. The bill doesn\u2019t address guest worker visas, including the H-2A program for temporary agricultural employees (a system that farmers say isn\u2019t meeting their labor needs).   But the Cotton-Perdue bill faces steep odds of becoming law, because of likely opposition from Democrats and pro-immigration Republicans. In a statement, Sen. Dianne Feinstein (D-Calif.) said that under the bill \u201chard-working immigrants in \u2018low-skilled\u2019 jobs can never have the opportunity to earn a green card. In California, that would mean farmworkers who have worked in the country for years would be permanently ineligible to apply for a green card.\u201d Read the full take from POLITICO\u2019s Ted Hesson here.  LARGEST DEAD ZONE TO DATE IN GULF: Federal scientists have measured the largest dead zone in the Gulf of Mexico ever recorded, with this year's oxygen-depleted area covering a space roughly the size of New Jersey. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, which lead the measurements, said the sprawling dead zone was being fed by nutrient pollution washing down the Mississippi River, primarily from farms, as well as urban and suburban runoff. Such "non-point pollution," in Clean Water Act parlance, is not federally regulated and is difficult to control. These nutrients spawn massive algae blooms that suck oxygen from the water as they decompose.  At 8,776 square miles, the dead zone continues to grow despite efforts in the 1990s to shrink it. A task force of state and federal agencies had set a goal in 2001 that aimed for the dead zone to be more than four and a half times smaller by now. Scientists estimate that to shrink the dead zone to the goal of 1,900 square miles would require a 45 percent reduction in nutrient pollution along the Mississippi River. In 2015, when the federal-state task force missed its goal, it said that it would take another two decades to reach those levels using voluntary, state-led efforts. The task force set an interim goal of cutting pollution by 20 percent by 2025.  Little interest from Trump. State and federal agencies have promoted voluntary efforts to measure and study nutrient pollution problems in the U.S. But the Trump administration, including EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt, has shown little interest in potentially controversial, more hands-on efforts to stanch nutrient pollution.  THUNE SEEKS SIMPLIFIED FOREST MANAGEMENT: Sen. John Thune (R-S.D.), a member of the Senate Agriculture Committee, introduced his fifth marker bill for the 2018 farm bill on Wednesday, with the newest proposal targeted at streamlining federal forest management. The legislation would: increase from 3,000 to 10,000 the number of acres that the U.S. Forest Service is allowed to categorically exclude from an analysis under the National Environmental Policy Act; expedite the environmental review process by allowing categorical exclusions for wildlife habitat, the thinning and salvaging of dead and dying trees (two activities that help prevent wildfires) and expanding designated insect and disease treatment areas; and provide alternative dispute resolution mechanisms for certain projects on a pilot basis.  \u201cThe U.S. Forest Service is excessively burdened with NEPA compliance obstacles and produces more environmental impact statements, which take longer to complete than those of most other federal agencies whose projects have longer-lasting impacts on the landscape,\u201d Thune said in a statement. \u201cThe changes I\u2019ve proposed would go a long way to provide relief from unnecessary and burdensome red tape and improve national forest management.\u201d Read a summary of the bill here.  \u2018CHARLOTTE\u2019S WEB\u2019 FARM IS FOR SALE: Perhaps the most famous saltwater farm in American literature \u2014 the 44-acre spread that inspired E.B. White to spin the beloved children\u2019s tale \u201cCharlotte\u2019s Web\u201d \u2014 is on the market. Asking price: $3.7 million. And, yes, the barn that was \u201chome\u201d to Charlotte and Wilbur still stands.   The farmhouse in North Brooklin, Me., dates to 1795. White and his wife, Katharine, bought it in 1933. He called it home until he passed away in 1985. The current owners, Robert and Mary Gallant, told the Portland Press Herald that it was not uncommon for passersby to stop and photograph the property. \u201cE.B. White would turn over in his grave if he knew how many people stop here,\u201d Mary Gallant said. \u201cBut to me, that\u2019s absolutely wonderful that he is so alive to the world.\u201d  NEW NUTRITION LEADER FOR UNITED FRESH: Mollie Van Lieu has been hired as senior director of nutrition policy for the United Fresh Produce Association, the group announced. She starts Sept. 5. Van Lieu, a former senior associate in government relations at the Pew Charitable Trusts, will work with both Congress and regulatory agencies, and dig into nutrition policy in the next farm bill.  MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 \u201cLobsterman\u201d may be the term for the profession, but Maine\u2019s lobster fleet has a growing number of women running their own boats \u201cand busting stereotypes along the way,\u201d NPR\u2019s The Salt blog reports.   \u2014 The Brazilian government\u2019s effort to raise taxes on fuels to increase federal revenue prompted truck drivers on Tuesday to demonstrate along roads critical to agricultural shipments, Reuters reports.   \u2014 Some 400,000 fewer Californians receive food stamp benefits today than during the later part of 2015, reversing a pattern of increases that held for a decade, The Sacramento Bee reports.   \u2014 Dirk Van de Put, head of Canada\u2019s McCain Foods Ltd., will take over in November for Mondelez chief executive Irene Rosenfeld, who is retiring, The Wall Street Journal reports.  \u2014 Researchers found that if every American substituted beans for beef in their diet, the country could come close to meeting its 2020 goals for cutting greenhouse gas emissions. The Atlantic has the story.  THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
