aV \u000a            By HELENA BOTTEMILLER EVICH  08/02/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Catherine Boudreau and Luis Sanchez  ALMANZA HAILS \u2018MODERNIZATION\u2019 IN EXIT INTERVIEW: Al Almanza has seen a lot change in nearly four decades at USDA\u2019s Food Safety and Inspection Service, the agency charged with overseeing the safety of meat and poultry in this country. It is where he climbed from front-line meat inspector to agency administrator and then acting deputy undersecretary. \u201cIt\u2019s been a great run,\u201d he said in a wide-ranging exit interview with POLITICO this week, emphasizing that FSIS staff bears responsibility for the successes under his leadership. \u201cEverybody has done their part,\u201d he added.  Story Continued Below  Poultry controversy: One of the things he\u2019s most proud of \u2014 revamping poultry inspection \u2014 is also perhaps the most controversial. The \u201cmodernized\u201d inspection system, known as the National Poultry Inspection System and finalized in 2014, pulled some FSIS inspectors off the line and away from looking for visible defects. The idea was to free up inspectors to focus more on pathogen testing and other activities aimed at pathogen reduction. The move, however, sparked a bitter public battle with the inspectors union and some consumer groups.   Need for speed? A provision allowing increased line speeds in slaughter plants was supposed to push poultry companies to opt in to the new inspection system, but the Obama administration ultimately backed off the increased speeds under intense criticism. FSIS initially estimated the vast majority of plants would opt in. Today some 60 of the 280 poultry slaughter plants have converted to the new system. Almanza said he was confident the poultry industry would eventually move toward adoption.   \u201cThe poultry industry is an industry that is very deliberate in what they do,\u201d he said. \u201cThey are going to watch how this plays out for the plants that are opting in and I would say most every big corporation that has poultry plants has one plant in. They want to wait and see how that is affecting production, wait and see what the data is showing them. \u2026 I do think that as they develop some history, they will invest the capital to modernize the majority of their facilities. I have no doubt whatsoever that is going to happen.\u201d   Brazilian beef mess: Asked about the recent suspension of Brazilian beef imports \u2014 a move that came after FSIS inspectors stepped up inspection and then rejected some 11 percent of product \u2014 Almanza said he\u2019s confident that bad Brazilian beef was kept out of the U.S. \u201cOur inspectors at those import facilities did their jobs right because they found things that caused us to be more aggressive in the action that we took,\u201d he said, adding: \u201cI would say that the chances that something got through that wasn\u2019t healthy or good are extremely remote, just on the diligence of the inspectors that we have out there.\u201d  What\u2019s in a recusal? Almanza said he doesn\u2019t know the status of talks with Brazil about resolving the issue. He\u2019s been recusing himself from the matter \u2014 something that has sparked plenty of scuttle in The Swamp about a possible private sector gig. Almanza said that as of Monday \u2014 his last day at FSIS \u2014 he hadn\u2019t committed to anything. Pros, read the full Q&A with Almanza here.  HAPPY WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 2! Welcome to Morning Ag, where your host is excited for a few days off in beautiful Bellingham, Wash. I hope you are all finding some time to unplug this August, while The Swamp is extra swampy! You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips? Send them to hbottemiller@politico.com  and @hbottemiller. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  TRUMP, FARMERS, KISSES AND TRADE BARRIERS: President Donald Trump said last week that farmers were hugging and kissing him because of the deal to open up China to U.S. beef exports, and that \u201cone of the reasons you see optimism is because people can actually use their land. They can farm their land.\u201d The statements are part of a long, meandering interview he gave The Wall Street Journal, a transcript of which was published by POLITICO on Tuesday. Here are some excerpts:  A protectionist EU: Trump was asked about what the important pieces of a potential trade deal with the U.K. would be. \u201cThere\u2019ll be certain pieces \u2026 I have a very good relationship with the EU people and all, but they are very, very protectionist,\u201d he said. \u201cYou know, our farmers and others can\u2019t even deal with \u2014 you know, you can\u2019t sell in. It\u2019s very unfair. And that\u2019s what I\u2019ve been talking about for a long time. It\u2019s so stacked against the United States.\u201d  No clarity on ag trade: When WSJ editor-in-chief Gerard Baker asked about an agricultural deal with the U.K., Trump said: \u201cWell, I\u2019ll tell you, you know, I did \u2014 I did thing [sic] that nobody even wrote about \u2014 although, you did. (Laughter.) But when I was with President Xi, who I have a very good relationship with, I said: Do me a favor. Would you allow cattle, please, to come in? I was last night in West Virginia, and I had farmers coming up to me and hugging me and kissing me because of the cattle stuff. They actually weren\u2019t from West Virginia; they were from other places. (Laughter.) But, you know, it was the Boy Scouts, so they came from all over the country.\u201d  No kisses for China: The Trump administration is preparing to take action against China over trade as soon as this week, two administration officials familiar with the issue told POLITICO. Andrew Restuccia and Doug Palmer have the details here.  BLUMENAUER\u2019S ALTERNATIVE FARM BILL: Rep. Earl Blumenauer (D-Ore.) voted against the 2014 farm bill \u2014 and now he\u2019s coming out with one more to his liking. He announced Tuesday plans to introduce an alternative farm bill this fall that would rein in commodity and crop insurance premium subsidies by capping them at $250,000 and $50,000 per year per farm, respectively, as well as make it easier for SNAP recipients and schools to purchase fruits and vegetables. Other reforms include creating incentives to help young and beginning producers gain access to land and equipment, establishing a food waste title, investing in local and regional food systems, and setting performance-based standards for conservation programs.   Blumenauer, a longtime critic of federal farm and nutrition policy, said the farm bill gives \u201ctoo much to the wrong people to grow the wrong food in the wrong places.\u201d Dissatisfied with the process, he conducted two years of outreach in Oregon to agricultural researchers, farmworkers, nutrition advocates, conservation groups, small and mid-sized farmers and ranchers and other interests \u2014 culminating in a report, published Tuesday, that serves as the basis of his alternative bill. Read a summary of the legislation here and the report, titled \u201cGrowing Opportunities: Reforming the Farm Bill for Every American,\u201d here.  SENATE DEMS REVIVE BILL TO LIFT CUBA EMBARGO: On Tuesday, just a few days removed from perhaps President Trump\u2019s roughest week in office, a group of senior Democratic senators moved to defy him on Cuba by introducing legislation to lift the economic embargo on the island nation. In mid-June Trump rolled back former President Barack Obama\u2019s historic opening to the island. The measure, submitted by Sen. Ron Wyden and known as The U.S.-Cuba Trade Act of 2017, would establish normal trade relations with the island nation, in addition to lifting the economic sanctions that go back to the White House days of Dwight Eisenhower and John F. Kennedy. It was co-sponsored by Sens. Patrick Leahy, Dianne Feinstein, Dick Durbin, Tom Udall, Patty Murray and Jeff Merkley.   \u201cDecades of experience have proven the embargo will never improve the lives of the Cuban people,\u201d Wyden, top Democrat on the Senate Finance Committee, said in a statement. \u201cInstead, this policy only serves to shut U.S. exporters out of a natural market for American agricultural and manufactured goods.\u201d  Political reality-check: The bill faces long odds of becoming law because of Republican party resistance.  You want numbers? The International Trade Commission has estimated easing U.S. restrictions on trade and business with Cuba could increase U.S. exports by $1.4 billion annually in the next five years, with even bigger gains possible.   ERNST TO EPA: PUMP UP ADVANCED BIOFUELS: Sen. Joni Ernst, Iowa Gov. Kim Reynolds and Nebraska Gov. Pete Ricketts asked EPA on Tuesday to ramp up the amount of biomass-based biodiesel and cellulosic ethanol in its final biofuels rule. During an all-day hearing on the agency\u2019s Renewable Fuel Standard proposed rule, the trio told a panel of EPA staff that companies had the capacity to produce 2.75 billion gallons of biodiesel in 2019, far more than the 2.1 billion gallons the agency proposed. The group also asked EPA to increase cellulosic volumes, which EPA proposed to lower by 23 percent in 2018 compared with 2017. \u201cReducing volumes for biodiesel and cellulosic would create uncertainty, especially as rural communities continue to experience a downturn in ag economy,\u201d Ernst said. The trio was pleased the agency kept conventional biofuels, typically filled by corn-based ethanol, at the maximum level.   Pruitt access: Ricketts and Reynolds told reporters after their testimony that they\u2019ve each spoken to EPA Administrator Scott Pruitt in person and on the phone on at least four occasions. EPA will take comment on the proposed volumes through Aug. 31.   HEALTH CARE OPIOID COMMISSION CALLS FOR CASH: In its interim report this week, the presidential commission on opioid addiction recommended a \u201cnational emergency\u201d declaration be made and more federal funding devoted to addressing the crisis. POLITICO New Jersey\u2019s Katie Jennings explains: The report proposes waiving a longstanding prohibition on using Medicaid funds to pay for residential substance-abuse treatment. That could cost the federal government between $40 billion and $60 billion over a decade, according to previous CBO estimates. \u201cThis is the single fastest way to increase treatment availability across the nation,\u201d the report states.  Backstory: Since the 1960s, the federal government has barred certain health care facilities with more than 16 beds \u2014 classified as Institutions for Mental Disease \u2014 from receiving federal matching funds to treat Medicaid patients. The ban was originally intended to force states to pay for the longterm institutionalization of psychiatric patients and limit Medicaid spending. But the commission\u2019s chief, New Jersey Gov. Chris Christie, says the prohibition \u201cis leaving thousands of beds empty across the country that could be occupied by folks who are in the midst of this disease to get the kind of treatment that could save their lives.\u201d  IRISH AG MINISTER PROMOTES GMO-FREE ISLAND: As the U.K. and Ireland continue talks on how to bring about \u201cfrictionless\u201d trade over the Irish border with Northern Ireland, Andrew Doyle, Ireland\u2019s Minister of State for Agriculture, has promoted the idea of having an \u201call-island status as GMO-free to maintain biodiversity.\u201d Doyle said, according to the Irish Times, that the island could be a \u201creservoir\u201d of safe genetically-modified-organism-free seed varieties. His view, however, does not reflect that of the country\u2019s Agricultural and Food Development Authority, which believes science should prevail in the argument over whether or not to cultivate GMO crops.  CLIMATE CHANGE AND MAGNUSON-STEVENS: The Magnuson-Stevens Act, the primary law regulating fisheries in federal waters, is in need of reauthorization, and Senate Commerce\u2019s Subcommittee on Oceans, Atmosphere, Fisheries and Coast Guard on Tuesday held the first in a series of hearings to guide that process. And, unsurprisingly, the issue of climate change made waves.  Chris Oliver, assistant administrator of NOAA\u2019s National Marine Fisheries Service, and John Quinn, chairman of the New England Fishery Management Council, pushed for a variety of changes, ranging from management of mixed stocks to more flexibility in how the Council Coordination Committee can monitor and collect data. But it was Sen. Richard Blumenthal who made the strongest case for change by criticizing the current system for failing New England\u2019s fishing fleet and leaving the region\u2019s fishermen \u201cangry and frustrated beyond words.\u201d  Because of climate change, Blumenthal said, fish that New England fishermen have traditionally sought were pushed north and fish from southern waters moved into New England. But catch limits for certain fish haven\u2019t been adjusted to meet the reality facing New England fishermen, forcing them to return quota-exceeding fish to the ocean. Billions of dollars in profits are being lost, Blumenthal said, while fishermen from southern states come to New England waters to catch their migrating fish. \u201cThere is something profoundly unfair and intolerable about the situation,\u201d he added. \u201cIn my view, it violates the present law.\u201d  Quinn responded by pointing out that parts of the New England fishing industry are booming but agreed that groundfish fishermen are struggling. While the CCC\u2019s process is to collect as much data as needed to produce accurate stock assessments, Quinn said they didn\u2019t have \u201ca simple solution for rising water temperatures or the ocean acidification,\u201d which are the roots of the shifting fish populations.  DASCHLE JOINS WORLD FOOD PROGRAM BOARD: Former Senate Majority Leader Tom Daschle is joining the nonprofit World Food Program USA's Board of Directors. One of the board\u2019s goals is to educate \u201cCongress and the administration about the importance of global food assistance for national security, economic development and global stability.\u201d The announcement is here.   MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 Retailers in Chicago have appealed a judge\u2019s decision this week to let the Cook County soda tax take effect today, The Chicago Tribune reports.   \u2014 A new trove of documents illustrates how Monsanto influences science and the media in the debate over glyphosate, The New York Times reports.  \u2014 Wall Street still thinks Amazon is going to be bad for Big Food companies, Bloomberg reports.  \u2014 Some Midwestern farmers are exploring raising livestock to meet consumer demand for meat raised on smaller operations closer to home, NPR\u2019s The Salt reports.  \u2014 California ranchers are suing the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service over the agency\u2019s process for designating 1.8 million acres in the state as critical habitat for three amphibians listed under the Endangered Species Act, Pro Ag\u2019s Catherine Boudreau reports.   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.  Helena Bottemiller Evich is a senior food and agriculture reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Before joining POLITICO, Helena spent four years reporting on food politics and policy at Food Safety News, where she covered Congress, the Food and Drug Administration and the U.S. Department of Agriculture.  Helena's work has also appeared in the Columbia Journalism Review and on NBC News. Her reporting has taken her to the Louisiana coast during the Gulf oil spill, Arizona lettuce fields, North Carolina hog farms and the occasional presidential turkey pardoning.  A native of Washington state and an alumna of Claremont McKenna College, she now lives in Washington, D.C., with her husband.  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson  \u000a                                            By Kel McClanahan  \u000a                                            By Carrie Levine 
