aV \u000a            By CATHERINE BOUDREAU  08/01/2017 10:01 AM EDT  With help from Eric Wolff and Adam Behsudi  PERDUE HITS THE ROAD IN SEARCH OF FARM BILL \u2018ROOTS\u2019: We\u2019ll spare you the Clark W. Griswold joke and get right down to it: Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue is set to depart on a five-state farm bill tour via RV, a journey that begins Thursday at the Wisconsin State Fair and signals the secretary\u2019s intent to be \u201cintimately\u201d involved in development of the 2018 measure. Perdue\u2019s summer road trip \u2014 dubbed \u201cBack to Our Roots\u201d \u2014 will also bring him to Minnesota, Iowa, Illinois and Indiana, USDA will announce this morning. His schedule is packed with listening sessions, to allow him to hear from producers and consumers across the country who are \u201con the front lines of American agriculture and \u2026 know best what the current issues are,\u201d Perdue said in a statement. He\u2019ll have some fun along the way, attending a Minnesota Twins game with USDA employees and popping in at Indianapolis Colts training camp for an event on the NFL\u2019s \u201cFuel Up to Play 60\u201d initiative.   Story Continued Below  \u201cUSDA will be intimately involved as Congress deliberates and formulates the 2018 Farm Bill,\u201d Perdue said in a statement. \u201cWe are committed to making the resources and the research available so that Congress can make good, facts-based, data-driven decisions. It\u2019s important to look at past practices to see what has worked and what has not worked, so that we create a farm bill for the future that will be embraced by American agriculture in 2018.\u201d  That would mark a significant departure from the USDA that Congress came to know under former President Barack Obama. While Obama included changes to crop insurance and other farm bill programs in his annual budget, former Agriculture Secretary Tom Vilsack largely stayed out of negotiations over the legislation.  Does Sonny do encores? Yup. A second RV tour is planned for later this summer, though details have yet to be announced. The trips will be documented on Perdue\u2019s Twitter account under #BackToOurRoots.  HAPPY TUESDAY, AUGUST 1! Welcome to Morning Ag, where your host would categorize this as a crime of passion. You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips? Send them to cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  TEXANS FRET ABOUT NEXT GENERATION OF FARMERS: Sticking with the 2018 farm bill for a moment \u2026 House Agriculture Chairman Mike Conaway said at the panel\u2019s field hearing in San Angelo, Texas on Monday that he wants to get a farm bill on the House floor by the end of this year \u2014 echoing a goal that his Senate counterpart, Pat Roberts, outlined last week. Over the course of three hours, some 80 farmers and ranchers, food bank employees, agricultural bankers and conservation groups discussed their concerns and suggestions on farm policy to Conaway, ranking member Collin Peterson and six other committee members.  Calls for returning cotton to Title I so it can qualify for commodity supports, improving livestock disaster assistance and strengthening conservation programs like CSP and EQUIP were plentiful, but the more passionate statements came from producers who fear the next generation won\u2019t be on the farm for a variety of reasons: the lack of equity needed to secure financing; the constant rise in the cost of pesticides, seeds, and equipment while commodity prices slump, which makes it difficult to make a profit; and the deteriorating economic condition of rural America.  \u201cI know five young growers who went out of business in the last three years,\u201d said Tony Dill of the Western Peanut Growers Association. \u201cThis is a very severe issue. I see no future in our country if we don\u2019t do something for younger farmers. A lot of us older farmers are living on equity, and younger farmers don\u2019t have that equity to get started.\u201d  THE ALMANZA ERA DRAWS TO A CLOSE: Al Almanza, administrator of the USDA Food Safety and Inspection Service, retired on Monday after 39 years at the agency. Secretary Perdue, in an email to staff, announced that two career employees will take on temporary leadership roles, beginning today: Paul Kiecker will be FSIS acting administrator, and Carmen Rottenberg will serve as acting deputy undersecretary for food safety \u2014 a post Almanza also held from September 2014 to December 2016.   In a farewell message to USDA employees last week, Almanza said highlights of his tenure include modernizing the poultry inspection system, reducing foodborne illnesses from listeriosis and E. coli and implementing stricter performance standards for campylobacter and salmonella in poultry.   The new line-up. Rottenberg has spent nearly six years in leadership roles at FSIS, including as deputy administrator and chief operating officer, overseeing the agency\u2019s $1-billion budget. Kiecker joined FSIS in 1988 as a food inspector and has held a number of positions since then, most recently as deputy assistant administrator for the Office of Field Operations.   MEXICO NAMES NEW CHIEF NAFTA NEGOTIATOR: Mexico is building out its negotiating team in preparation for the much-awaited renegotiation of NAFTA, naming Kenneth Smith Ramos on Monday to be its chief technical negotiator. Ramos, head of the trade and NAFTA office at the Mexican Embassy in Washington, will work just below Economy Secretary Ildefonso Guajardo and Undersecretary for Foreign Trade Juan Carlos Baker in leading the negotiations, a Guajardo spokesperson told our colleagues at Morning Trade.  Guajardo, speaking to reporters on Monday, highlighted Ramos\u2019 past work in Mexico\u2019s agriculture department as well as its economy ministry. \u201cHe is a man who has had a very, very long, intense and brilliant career in all foreign trade topics,\u201d Guajardo said in Spanish.  RFS HEARING BE POPPIN\u2019 LIKE CORN: EPA is throwing its annual Renewable Fuel Standard bash today, an all-day hearing for the agency to get feedback on its proposed rule, which will set the amount of biofuel that must be blended into the nation\u2019s fuel supply. The agency kept the ethanol mandate at the legal maximum of 15 billion gallons, but it dramatically cut the amount of advanced biofuels, and it will surely get an earful on that.   RFS A-listers: EPA will hear from: Iowa Gov. Kim Reynolds; Nebraska Gov. Pete Ricketts; Chris Bliley of Growth Energy; Bob Dinneen of the Renewable Fuels Association; Frank Macchiarola of the American Petroleum Institute; and Donnell Rehagen of the National Biodiesel Board. Reynolds, whose state leads the nation in ethanol production, will tell EPA she\u2019s glad it is on track for an on-time rule (they're actually a bit behind schedule), but wants the agency \u201cto raise the advanced biofuel, biodiesel and cellulosic volumes. The RFS is a bold policy, and Iowans and the industry as a whole have always risen to the challenge.\u201d  NMPF: PLANT-BASED FOOD PETITION \u2018INAPPROPRIATE\u2019: The Good Food Institute\u2019s effort to revive a 20-year-old soy industry petition that requested FDA allow plant-based products to be labeled as \u201cmilk\u201d is as \u201cinappropriate today as it was \u2026 in 1997,\u201d the National Milk Producers Federation said in response Monday. \u201cNothing has happened in the intervening time period to allow the combination of soy powder, water, emulsifiers, stabilizers, sugar, sodium and added vitamins to magically become milk,\u201d NMPF President Jim Mulhern said in a statement. \u201cRegardless of what food technologists might try, milk still only comes from mammals.\u201d   GFI also filed its own petition on Monday, asking FDA to codify its existing practice of allowing manufacturers to use common dairy names to broadly label plant-based foods and beverages. The FDA told MA in response on Monday that it is \u201creviewing the matter and takes action in accordance with public health priorities and agency resources.\u201d  THIS TAX REFORM TIMELINE IS \u2026 \u2018AGGRESSIVE\u2019: The White House expects tax reform legislation to move quickly through Congress this fall, clearing the House in October and the Senate in November, legislative director Marc Short said Monday. Markups will begin in September. \u201cSo that, I think, is an aggressive schedule, but that is our timetable,\u201d he said during an event hosted by a pair of conservative political groups backed by the billionaire Koch brothers \u2014 Freedom Partners and Americans for Prosperity.   Short\u2019s ambitious timeline is the most specific to be laid out by either the White House or Congress in recent months, reports Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo. It jives with a joint statement issued by administration and congressional negotiators last week, which said the expectation is that tax reform legislation will move through committees \u201cthis fall,\u201d followed by consideration on the House and Senate floor. Republicans are planning to use special instructions in a budget resolution \u2014 should it advance through Congress \u2014 to pass tax reform with a simple majority in the Senate in order to short-circuit a Democratic filibuster. But Short also suggested a Republican-only pathway isn\u2019t completely necessary. Some Democrats might get on board, particularly those up for reelection next year in states Trump carried, he said.  THE 2018 WATCH: CASEY, TESTER GET NEW CHALLENGERS: Senate Agriculture Committee member Bob Casey (D-Pa.) has a new challenger in 2018: GOP Rep. Lou Barletta, two Republican sources told POLITICO\u2019s Kevin Robillard. Barletta, an early supporter of President Donald Trump, is an immigration hard-liner serving his fourth term in the House. Trump has publicly suggested Barletta challenge either Casey or Democratic Gov. Tom Wolf. Barletta, a former mayor of Hazleton, Pa., is the biggest name in a large Republican field challenging Casey, a moderate who has emerged as a fierce Trump critic.  Tester territory: Montana State Auditor Matt Rosendale on Monday formally launched his campaign to challenge Democratic Sen. Jon Tester next year, and gave a heads-up to POLITICO\u2019s Elena Schneider. A handful of Republicans are already in the race, but Rosendale is the first statewide officeholder to jump in. Tester, an organic farmer and two-term incumbent, is one of the GOP\u2019s top Senate targets. Rosendale ran for Congress in 2014 and loaned his own campaign more than $1.1 million before losing to Interior Secretary Ryan Zinke in the Republican primary.   \u201cI\u2019ve always said that I will serve wherever Montanans feel I can be the most effective, and I\u2019ve gotten calls from across the entire state from people who are not satisfied with the job that Tester is doing. He acts like a farmer when he\u2019s here, but he goes back to Washington and votes just like Chuck Schumer,\u201d Rosendale said. \u201cWe recognize that even if you go into federal government well-intentioned, there comes a time when you have been there too long.\u201d  U.S., BRAZIL TO COMPETE FOR CORN CUSTOMERS: Brazil\u2019s corn production in the 2016-17 season is forecast to be a record 97 million tons, while U.S. farmers are predicted to harvest their second-biggest crop this fall \u2014 setting up intense competition for buyers in the second half of 2017, Bloomberg reports. Two decades ago, Brazil wasn\u2019t even on the United States\u2019 radar as a competitor in corn exports, but has since ramped up shipments. In 2016, the country ranked third in corn exports, while the U.S. was No. 1 and Argentina No. 2, according to USDA data. Japan and Mexico are the top buyers of the commodity.   U.S. corn shippers are seeing slow bookings for the coming marketing year, which starts in September, Bloomberg reported, citing USDA data. Corn shipments from Brazil are climbing, but they are projected to continue to pace behind those of the U.S. Whether Brazil can steal more market share from U.S. farmers depends partly on the value of the Brazilian real and how many growers are willing to sell crops at low local prices, one analyst told Bloomberg.  Another factor? Trump. Mexico is looking to diversify its corn supply amid the political uncertainty surrounding NAFTA 2.0 and President Trump\u2019s harsh rhetoric. But Secretary Perdue, after two days of bilateral meetings in Mexico last week with Mexican Secretary of Agriculture Jos Calzada, said the U.S. still has an edge.   \u201cI did not get any indication that they're seriously considering that,\u201d Perdue told reporters during a conference call on Friday. \u201cI think while they may talk ... as if they\u2019re having conversations, we have a corner store location for their supply," he added, highlighting the U.S. agricultural sector\u2019s competitive and logistical advantages in relation to its southern neighbor.  ERS: FARM PRODUCTIVITY KEY TO FOOD SECURITY: Growth in agricultural productivity is strongly connected to improvements in developing countries\u2019 food security status, according to a report published by the USDA Economic Research Service on Monday. Investments in agricultural research and technology are central to efforts to meet the challenge of feeding a world population north of 9 billion by 2050. \u201cOn average, the faster the growth in agricultural productivity, the larger the reductions in food insecurity,\u201d the report said.   ERS analyzed the role of trade, agricultural productivity, international aid, and better data and measurement in achieving food security gains in 76 low- and middle-income countries over the past 15 years. Since the U.S. provides about half of global food aid and support for agricultural development \u2014 between $6 billion and 7 billion annually over the last few years \u2014 the researchers said it\u2019s necessary to study factors that drive improvement if the U.S. is to reach its commitment of ending global food insecurity by 2030.  Cash is king? The report also found that for countries receiving aid, cash-transfer programs can be more cost effective than traditional methods like in-kind commodity donations, which represent the United States\u2019 largest form of food aid under the Food for Peace program. However, not all countries have sufficient food markets or the administrative capability to broadly implement cash programs. Advances in IT, personal identification, banking and mobile phones support the expansion of targeted cash-transfer programs. \u201cThese innovations can \u2026 reduce the market distortions associated with acquiring, distributing, and storing commodities found in traditional in-kind programs,\u201d the report said. Read it here.   FARM CREDIT ADMIN NAMES NEW IG: The Farm Credit Administration announced Monday that Wendy Laguarda will become its inspector general, effective today. Laguarda, who joined the FCA Office of General Counsel in 1990 and rose to become assistant general counsel and the designated agency ethics official, succeeds Elizabeth Dean, who retired Monday.   MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 New Food Economy has this deep dive on who owns America\u2019s farmland (hint: it\u2019s increasingly not farmers).  \u2014  The country\u2019s largest fresh-garlic producer solved its labor shortage by raising wages to $13. The Mercury News explores whether it\u2019s an isolated success story or a fix for U.S. agriculture more broadly.   \u2014 A group of leading crop scientists is calling for a coordinated approach to research to tackle global food security threats, Feedstuffs reports.  \u2014 Researchers found that providing a 50 percent discount on the price of fruits and vegetables doubled consumers\u2019 intake of the produce. Read the study here.   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
