aV \u000a            By CATHERINE BOUDREAU  07/31/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Jenny Hopkinson and Helena Bottemiller Evich   THE WAYBACK MACHINE HITS THE PLANT-BASED FOOD FIGHT: Twenty years ago the Soyfoods Association of North America filed a petition requesting FDA clarify that it allows soy-based beverages to be labeled as \u201csoymilk.\u201d FDA never acted on the petition. Now, in the midst of a simmering feud over naming of plant-based foods, the Good Food Institute is resurrecting that old petition. GFI, a nonprofit that promotes plant-based meat and dairy products, is today asking FDA to respond to the request, and petitioning the agency to codify its existing practice of allowing food producers to use common dairy names to broadly label plant-based items, such as almond milk, cashew cheese and coconut yogurt.   Story Continued Below  GFI says the need is urgent for FDA to clarify its position because of increased conflict over the issue. Last month a U.S. District Court judge in California stayed a case over use of the term \u201calmond milk,\u201d and referred the matter to FDA to settle the policy question. And the House Appropriations Committee, in non-binding report language attached to fiscal 2018 spending legislation, directed FDA to issue guidance on the standard of identity for dairy products.   The National Milk Producers Federation is pushing Congress to ban the practice of plant-based foods using the term \u201cmilk,\u201d arguing it is misleading to consumers from a nutritional standpoint. It\u2019s a fight that has taken on greater stakes for the dairy industry as it seeks to spur demand for its products amid a global oversupply of milk. On its side are Sen. Tammy Baldwin (D-Wis.) and Rep. Peter Welch (D-Vt.), who introduced the DAIRY PRIDE Act earlier this year, which would direct FDA to enforce standards of identity for milk, and effectively ban plant-based foods from being marketed with the term.   HAPPY MONDAY, JULY 31! Welcome to Morning Ag, where your host is now questioning every bake sale goodie she ate as a child. You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips? Send them to cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  HORMONE-TREATED BEEF: A TALE OF TWO TRADE DEALS: If U.S. beef producers want to realize the full potential behind the deal to open China\u2019s market to American beef, they must climb an all-too-familiar mountain: removing artificial growth hormones from production. The White House is hailing its deal with China, but it\u2019s important to note the agreement effectively disqualifies most beef produced in the states because it prohibits use of artificial growth hormones. But at the same time the administration is reviving a 1990s-era challenge of an EU measure that throws up the same roadblocks, creating a strange dichotomy for U.S. beef trade in the Trump era, Pro Trade\u2019s Doug Palmer reports this morning.   The Trump administration got China to lift its ban on U.S. beef by agreeing U.S. producers would ship only beef from cattle raised without hormones and also free of any trace of ractopamine or other beta agonists, a class of feed additives used to produce leaner meat. One analyst, who asked not to be identified, told POLITICO that forgoing those compounds would cost cattle producers upwards of $275 a head, a premium that isn\u2019t being offset by China. \u201cWe will still ship some small (niche) volumes to China, but the China deal is not commercially viable,\u201d the analyst said. U.S. meat industry groups expressed optimism, arguing exports to China will begin slowly and build over time.   A tipping point? It remains to be seen whether the opportunity for hormone-free exports to China proves to be a tipping point in U.S. agricultural trade policy after decades of fighting to keep overseas markets open to hormone-treated beef. The U.S. beef industry has every intention of pushing forward in its dispute with the EU. The WTO permitted the U.S. in the late 1990s to impose retaliatory duties on exports to the EU over the EU\u2019s ban on hormone-treated beef, which stayed in place until the Obama administration negotiated a settlement. As part of that agreement, a tariff-free quota for U.S. \u201chormone-free\u201d beef was created, but now Australia and Argentina are grabbing most of those sales. So the Trump administration is mulling whether to re impose retaliatory measures. Pros, read Doug\u2019s story here.  THIS WEEK: A FARM BILL TRIFECTA: Capitol Hill promises to be half as quiet as usual for the first week in August with only the Senate in town, trying to move past last week\u2019s momentous events in the Obamacare repeal effort (don\u2019t miss our colleagues\u2019 deep dive into Sen. John McCain's decisive vote). The farm world will largely be focused on House Agriculture Committee\u2019s trio of farm bill listening sessions. Chairman Mike Conaway, his staff, and other committee members will be racking up the airmiles as they go from San Angelo, Texas, on Monday to Morgan, Minn., on Thursday to Modesto, Calif., on Saturday. Today\u2019s hearing starts at 2 p.m. and will be livestreamed here.  Along with the changes in scenery will come huge shifts in the issues farmers are most concerned about. Expect the session in Texas to focus on the needs of cotton growers, including a commodity support program. Lawmakers also will likely hear calls from cattle ranchers for additional disaster-aid programs, especially following the prairie fires that burned in the northern part of the state this spring. The hearing in Minnesota is in ranking member Collin Peterson\u2019s stomping grounds, where the focus will likely be on dairy farmers and ways to fix their insurance program, as well as efforts to curb disease in poultry and hogs. Finally, the California hearing is undoubtedly going to feature a lot of specialty crop and organic production issues and calls for a federal fix to farm labor shortages.  Also this week:   Senate ENR tackles wildfires, water security: The full Senate Environment and Natural Resources Committee holds a hearing on Thursday to look at ways to use collaborations and technology to reduce wildfire risks and enhance firefighting effectiveness. Wildfires have become increasingly destructive as communities have expanded into traditionally forested areas, weather patterns have changed, and forest managers, including USDA\u2019s Forest Service, have not had sufficient resources to manage the land. While it seems like more money will be difficult to come by in the current political context, the hearing indicates that committee Chairwoman Lisa Murkowski is exploring other approaches to solving the problem. The committee\u2019s water panel will also meet Wednesday to consider methods to increase water security and drought preparedness.  Not on the schedule: Confirmation hearings. The Senate Agriculture Committee hasn\u2019t scheduled confirmation hearings on the three USDA subcabinet positions the White House has announced. The committee has received paperwork from the White House for Stephen Censky, for deputy secretary, and Sam Clovis, for undersecretary for research, education and economics. But the committee is still waiting for 1600 Pennsylvania to send over the goods on Ted McKinney, for undersecretary for trade.  AGGIE POPULARITY CONTEST: MA told you last week about how farm groups have supported Clovis serving as the department's chief scientist, even though he doesn\u2019t have the science credentials called for in the law that established the position. But Clovis has got nothing on Censky when it comes to farm-group support. Last Monday 23 groups signed onto a letter backing Clovis, and on Friday 44 groups wrote to Senate Ag calling for Censky to be confirmed.   In case you missed it, read Helena Bottemiller Evich\u2019s profile of Clovis here.   JUDGE GREEN-LIGHTS COOK COUNTY SODA TAX: Dear Chicago, your sugary drinks are going to get more expensive this week. On Friday, Cook County Circuit Judge Daniel Kubasiak dismissed a lawsuit brought by retailers and other industry groups that argued the county\u2019s penny-per-ounce soda tax was unconstitutional. An injunction against the tax, slated to kick in on July 1, was dropped, and the levy will now take effect on Wednesday, Aug. 2. It\u2019s not known if retail groups will appeal. Find more on the ruling from The Chicago Tribune here.   ICYMI: AGRIBUSINESS TOP LOBBYING POWER ON REG REFORM: Since House Judiciary Chairman Bob Goodlatte (R-Va.) introduced the Regulatory Accountability Act (H.R. 5) in January, it\u2019s become the sixth-most lobbied bill in Congress \u2014 and the agribusiness industry has been the most active. Out of the 109 companies and groups lobbying lawmakers this year, 23 represent agribusiness interests, according to an analysis conducted by the Center for Responsive Politics last week. For example, CropLife America, the trade group for pesticide manufacturers like Monsanto, Bayer AG and BASF Corp., has its own lobbyists on the bill and has also paid Jim Massie & Partners, LLC, $50,000 this year to work on the RAA and other issues (Lobbying disclosure forms don\u2019t break down the amount of money spent per issue or bill, but rather a total figure for all activity in any given quarter).   Other interests lobbying Congress on the RAA include National Grain and Feed Association; Dairy Farmers of America; farm bureaus in states like Michigan, Nebraska, Ohio, Texas and Pennsylvania; and the American Sugarbeet Growers Association.  The RAA, which is designed to overhaul the regulatory process, has passed the House, and a similar version was introduced in April by Sen. Rob Portman (R-Ohio) and Heidi Heitkamp (D-N.D.). It is all but guaranteed to be signed into law if it reaches President Donald Trump\u2019s desk. The legislation would require federal agencies to choose the lowest-cost rulemaking alternative that meets objectives outlined by Congress, would end judicial deference by courts and instead require them to decide all terms of an agency\u2019s actions, and prohibit regulations that cost more than $1 billion from taking effect until courts can resolve litigation challenging them, among other provisions.   JOHANNS\u2019 NEW GOAL: GET FARMERS USING THE R&D TAX CREDIT: Farmers have a lot on their wishlist for tax reform, should Congress ever get to it, but former Agriculture Secretary Mike Johanns says many in agriculture aren\u2019t taking advantage of a key credit already available to them. The former Nebraska governor, who led the USDA under President George W. Bush before serving a stint in the Senate, is on a mission to get farmers to use the federal R&D tax credit. That provision provides a dollar-for-dollar credit when a business tries something new in its operation, Johanns told MA.   The provision isn\u2019t just about work done in a lab, but also any efforts by a business aimed at \u201cimproving a process,\u201d the former secretary said, pointing to common farming activities such as selective breeding in livestock and to work being done by dairy processors, breweries and even ethanol plants to increase productivity. \u201cIt fits hand in glove with what\u2019s going on in agriculture,\u201d said Johanns, who added to his resume chairman of agriculture for the Houston-based tax consultancy alliantgroup. While many, if not most, farms could qualify for the credit, Johanns said only about 10 percent are taking advantage of it. \u201cIt\u2019s just something that the ag community hasn\u2019t put on their radar screen,\u201d he said.  President Trump and House Republicans have stated they would maintain the R&D tax credit in any overhaul of the tax code.   We\u2019d be remiss not to ask about the farm bill: Between his time at USDA and in the Senate, Johanns has both implemented a farm bill and written one. Here are his predictions for this one: \u201cIt\u2019s going to be a strained farm bill,\u201d he said, pointing to budget pressure from the White House and Republican leadership in Congress. However, he has some optimism because the House and Senate Agriculture committee leaders have started hearings early and are working on the legislation already. \u201cThat kind of preparation is very important,\u201d he said.  Recent comments from Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell that he wants to get the measure to the floor soon are also promising, Johanns said. \u201cThose dynamics are very helpful, and I continue to believe that they can get a farm bill done and on time. It's not going to get any easier the longer they wait.\u201d  NEW BILL ROUNDUP: SNAP E&T, HEMP PRODUCTION: Legislation introduced by Rep. Jim Costa (D-Calif.) would increase funding for employment and training programs for people who receive Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program benefits. SNAP E&T programs are an oft-forgotten element of SNAP, but creation of a major E&T pilot program to test how best to get people back to work ended up being key to passing the 2014 farm bill. Costa\u2019s bill would create a longterm competitive grant program for states starting in fiscal 2019 with $300 million, a discretionary spending level that would go up to $600 million by fiscal 2027.  \u201cFor years I have been following how pairing education and training programs with the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program has transformed people\u2019s lives in the San Joaquin Valley, and we have seen the success of programs that focus on helping individuals find longterm employment and start real careers,\u201d Costa said.  Legalizing hemp. Reps. Goodlatte, James Comer (R-Ky.), Thomas Massie (R-Ky.) and Jared Polis (D-Colo.) on Friday reintroduced legislation that would remove hemp from the Controlled Substances Act and legalize its cultivation in all 50 states. The 2014 farm bill authorized universities and state departments of agriculture to launch pilot programs to grow and research industrial hemp, and 31 states are participating. The Industrial Hemp Farming Act had 75 bipartisan co-sponsors in the House and 16 in the Senate during the last Congress, but never advanced beyond being introduced.   MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 An agricultural crisis is looming across Africa as its population increases but the amount of arable land shrinks, due to climate change, soil degradation, erosion and poaching, The New York Times reports.   \u2014 Chefs at farm-to-table restaurants should talk more about the inequalities in the U.S. food system, most notably cheap labor, opines Andrea Reusing in NPR\u2019s The Salt.  \u2014 Hundreds of libraries are now serving federally funded summer meals to children to ensure they don\u2019t go hungry when school is out, The New York Times reports.  THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.  CORRECTION:  An earlier version of this newsletter misstated the date of the House Agriculture Committee's farm bill listening session in Modesto, Calif. It will be held on Saturday, Aug. 5.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
