aV \u000a            By JENNY HOPKINSON  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Helena Bottemiller Evich and Catherine Boudreau  WHERE ARE THE GMO LABELING RULES? Saturday marks one year since former President Barack Obama signed the federal GMO ingredient disclosure law, ending the food industry\u2019s long struggle to preempt state labeling standards and short-circuiting Vermont\u2019s brief experiment with on-package disclosure. The law requires USDA to craft rules that set standards for what needs to be disclosed and that give companies options \u2014 on package or online \u2014 for informing consumers that GMOs are in their food.  Story Continued Below  Obama\u2019s ag chief, Tom Vilsack, worked to lay the groundwork for the rule in his last five months in office, but the effort seems to have been thrown off by the change in administration and the drawn-out vetting process and confirmation battles that have bedeviled President Donald Trump\u2019s executive branch buildout. The measure must be finalized in a year, but USDA appears to still be grappling with core details of the rule. A proposed rule is months away.  Tick tock: The average rulemaking takes about four years, but the clock for USDA on the GMO disclosure rules started with half that. A USDA spokesman tells MA that \u201cour goal is have a final rule ready for publication by the statutory deadline of July 2018,\u201d and that a proposal should be out this fall. That\u2019s a quick turnaround, given that officials are taking comments until Aug. 25 on what the rule should include. Once the regulation is proposed, USDA will have to take comment on the measure itself \u2014 a process that could take months \u2014 and review and update it before going final.   Industry groups are still optimistic USDA will wrap it up by next year. \u201cGiven this administration\u2019s support for U.S. manufacturing and farmers, we have every reason to believe that it will want to move ahead as quickly as possible to implement this rule by July 2018,\u201d Denzel McGuire, executive vice president of government affairs for the Grocery Manufacturers Association, said in a statement.  The sticky bits: The trickier parts of the rulemaking are basic questions that must be answered, including defining genetic modification. Some farm and food groups want disclosure to be required only for modifications that can\u2019t be achieved in nature, arguing that some technologies just speed up the process. But consumer advocates, including Just Label It, say the rule should apply to all biotech crops.   \u201cConsumers will expect the mandatory GMO disclosure standard to apply to all foods produced with or derived from genetic engineering, including foods which contain ingredients like highly refined sugars and oils, as well as foods produced with new forms of genetic engineering,\u201d pro-labeling group Just Label It said in its comments. Other issues likely to cause trouble for USDA include whether each GMO ingredient should be identified and how to provide broad access to online labels.   Patience is a virtue, but here\u2019s the thing: While USDA is trying to figure out how best to craft the rules, food companies are moving ahead with labeling in ways they hope will be covered by the rule. Campbell Soup Company has decided to add disclosures to all its products\u2019 packaging, and some companies that labeled to comply with Vermont\u2019s law appear to have left them in place \u2014 read your labels and you\u2019ll see them. Meanwhile, brands are signing up for GMA\u2019s SmartLabel program, a website for disclosure of GMO ingredients and other product info that can be accessed either online or through an on-package QR code. More than 10,000 products are already listed in the online database, GMA said, and the goal is to have 30,000 products enrolled by the end of the year.  HAPPY FRIDAY, JULY 28! Welcome to Morning Ag, where your Friday recommended reading includes news about franken-bagels, Bronze Age lunch boxes and rabbits that hitched a ride on sheep to flee rising floodwaters. Yep, it\u2019s that type of Friday. You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips, ways to stay dry in D.C. this weekend? Send them to jhopkinson@politico.com and @jennyhops. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  U.S. FROZEN BEEF EXPORTS TO JAPAN TRIGGER TARIFF HIKE: As if U.S. producers didn\u2019t have enough to lose in beef exports to Japan, Tokyo invoked a safeguard measure on imports of frozen beef from the U.S. and other countries, ratcheting up tariffs from 38.5 percent to 50 percent, per the U.S. Meat Export Federation. Under the terms of its Japan\u2019s WTO membership, it instituted a safeguard that would trigger if the quarter import volume exceeded the previous corresponding quarter by 17 percent. Imports during the first quarter of Japan\u2019s fiscal year (April 1-June 30) topped the threshold by a mere 115 metric tons, meaning the increased tariff will be applied for the remainder of Japan\u2019s fiscal year.About 45 percent of U.S. beef exports to Japan are frozen.  \u201cUSMEF recognizes that the safeguard will not only have negative implications for U.S. beef producers, but will also have a significant impact on the Japanese foodservice industry,\u201d USMEF President and CEO Philip Seng said in a statement. \u201cIt will be especially difficult for the gyudon beef bowl restaurants that rely heavily on Choice U.S. short plate as a primary ingredient.\u201d  For U.S. producers, it gets worse: The safeguard won\u2019t apply to imports of Australian beef, which will continue to enjoy a lower tariff of 27.2 percent and are not subject to safeguard tariffs per terms of a deal it signed with Japan in 2015. However, the USMEF argues the Japanese food service industry prefers U.S. short plate, a belly cut, which accounts for a majority of U.S. frozen beef exports to Japan. Still, the organization acknowledges the situation makes Australia\u2019s position even more advantageous.  PORK PRODUCERS PUSH FOR STAY OF CAFO REPORTING: The National Pork Producers Council is urging a federal judge to give EPA time to develop guidance for how livestock operations must report emissions, arguing that not doing so will create a haphazard \u201creporting fiasco.\u201d The motion in support of a stay requested by the agency, filed Thursday in the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, follows an April decision of the same court overturning EPA\u2019s exemption for animal waste emissions reporting requirements.   Not so fast: Environmental groups, in their own filing Thursday, said the court should reject the stay, since the agency has had plenty of time to figure out how to enforce the rule on CAFOs. \u201cEPA\u2019s motion ignores that CAFOs have been reporting releases without any guidance for over a decade,\u201d Waterkeeper Alliance and other groups argue. \u201cAnd EPA has been collecting and analyzing emissions data, similarly, for over a decade, for the purpose of developing guidance \u2014 but guidance still has not issued.\u201d  DONDE ESTA SONNY? Livin\u2019 la vida loca in Mrida, Mexico. Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue made his first trip south of the border for meetings Thursday and Friday with his Mexican counterpart, Agriculture Secretary Jos Calzada Rovirosa. The two officials are discussing trade issues, as well as hosting panel discussions with U.S. and Mexican farmers and ranchers.   The goal is to build personal relationships in Mexico so the two countries can collaborate on agricultural trade issues, USDA said. The U.S. agricultural industry has been trying to assure customers in Mexico that they are valuable partners and that preserving NAFTA is a top priority despite Trump\u2019s harsh rhetoric \u2014 a likely aim of Perdue\u2019s visit. The U.S. grain industry said it has already lost sales since the beginning of this year as Mexico pursues other buyers, particularly in South America, amid political uncertainty over NAFTA 2.0. Perdue and Rovirosa are set to hold a press conference this morning, so stay tuned for more.  BYE BYE, BORDER TAX: White House and congressional leaders officially acknowledged Thursday that the controversial border-adjustment tax would be dropped from the GOP tax reform plan, but they didn\u2019t provide any new details on the broader package they expect to start moving through Congress in the fall, reports Pro\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo and Colin Wilhelm. House Speaker Paul Ryan and Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady were pushing the border provision, which would tax imported goods but not exports, as a way to fund tax cuts. But the proposal prompted a fierce backlash from retailers and other import-dependent industries, and members of the Republican conference remain divided on the issue.   "While we have debated the pro-growth benefits of border adjustability, we appreciate that there are many unknowns associated with it and have decided to set this policy aside in order to advance tax reform," top negotiators, including Ryan, Brady, Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, Senate Finance Chairman Orrin Hatch, Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin and National Economic Council Director Gary Cohn said in a joint statement.   Regular order? The group\u2019s statement was largely symbolic, vowing to reduce tax rates, simplify the tax code and improve U.S. economic growth by changing tax laws. It added that "the time has arrived" for the tax-writing committees to produce draft legislation. "Our expectation is for this legislation to move through the committees this fall, under regular order, followed by consideration on the House and Senate floors," the statement added.  What about the estate tax? That was left unresolved. Lorenzo and POLITICO\u2019s Nancy Cook break things down further, here.   FOOD WASTE GETS A DAY ON THE HILL: A gaggle of chefs from across the country descended on Washington this week to talk to members of Congress about food waste, an increasingly hot topic that just might get some attention in the next farm bill.   The Food Policy Action Education Fund organized the fly-in on Wednesday that was part of the group\u2019s \u201cPlate of the Union\u201d campaign, a joint initiative with the Environmental Working Group. Dozens of chefs and other advocates met with no fewer than 65 offices, a full day that was capped off with a rooftop farm reception at Up Top Acres in Navy Yard. The day of action included chefs from all over, from South on Main in Little Rock, Ark., to Aziza in San Francisco and Dinette in Pittsburgh.   Spotted: Six members of Congress stopped by the rooftop farm shindig, including: Reps. Chellie Pingree (D-Maine) and Jim McGovern (D-Mass.) (no surprises there) as well as Reps. David Cicilline (D-R.I.), Marc Veasey (D-Texas), Joseph Crowley (D-N.Y.), and Filemon Vela (D-Texas).   SENATE AG STAFF SHUFFLE: Senate Agriculture Chairman Pat Roberts has some new faces leading the committee\u2019s legal staff, according to a notice from his office. Fred Clark, a former managing partner for Cornerstone Government Affairs and House Agriculture Committee staffer, is joining the majority\u2019s team as senior counsel, while DaNita Murray, previously senior counsel and policy director for the committee, is adding the title of chief counsel. The majority staff is also picking up two new staff assistants: former committee intern Haley Donahue and Future Farmers of America and Kansas State alumni Chance Hunley.  PHA NAMES ROMAN AS CEO: The Partnership for a Healthier America, the nonprofit launched to support former first lady Michelle Obama\u2019s Let\u2019s Move! initiative, has named Nancy Roman as president and CEO, the group announced recently. Roman is currently president and CEO of the Capital Area Food Bank, the largest food bank in the D.C. area.  \u201cAs President and CEO of the Capital Area Food Bank, Nancy brought the vision, fortitude, and focus on impact that will be essential to the future of PHA,\u201d said Melissa Winter, chief of staff to the former first lady. \u201cMrs. Obama is looking forward to working with Nancy.\u201d Roman will begin her new role Sept. 5.  MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 A new report from three EU agencies found that the consumption of certain types of antibiotics in hospitals is directly linked to people\u2019s resistance to them, while in other cases the use of antibiotics in animals ties with antimicrobial resistance, POLITICO EU reports.  \u2014 A new report from USDA\u2019s Economic Research Service has found that ending conservation compliance requirements for crop insurance premium subsidies would mean a significant reduction of soil erosion prevention measures on farms.   \u2014 Mexican officials are pushing back against claims that a Salmonella outbreak in the U.S. is linked to Mexican papayas, the AP reports.   \u2014 Thanks to more than a month without rain, Washington State\u2019s cherry crop is expected to be one of the largest ever, The Packer reports.   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
