aV \u000a            By JENNY HOPKINSON  07/27/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Annie Snider, Helena Bottemiller Evich, Patrick Temple-West and Catherine Boudreau  CROP INSURANCE AND THE NATURAL DISASTER PROBLEM: When historic floods hit South Carolina in 2015, crop farmers across the state relied on crop insurance payments to rebuild their farms. Payments averaged about 40 percent of premiums, but it was better than nothing, state Agriculture Commissioner Hugh Weathers told MA.   Story Continued Below  As lawmakers on both sides of the aisle discuss changes to crop insurance to lower costs in the next farm bill, Weathers warned they are missing a key point: The program is becoming more important because natural disasters are on the rise. \u201cIt\u2019s really the only safety net still available to farmers,\u201d he said after spending time on the Hill this week pushing lawmakers to spare the federal crop insurance program. \u201cCrop insurance is sort of the last line in the sand.\u201d  While livestock producers have disaster relief programs under the farm bill, crop farmers have no such safeguards to help them recover from weather events. When extreme weather hits, USDA can do little more than make available low-interest loans, so farmers simply must rely on their crop insurance. But weather events are getting more common, which has put more strain on the system. There were 13 significant flooding events that were not related to a tropical storm, hurricane or nor'easter between 2010 and 2016, FEMA records show. From 2000 until 2009, there were only seven. If that trend continues, any cuts to crop insurance could impair farmers\u2019 ability to recover from floods, droughts and other natural disasters, Weathers said.  Also on the farm bill wish list: Weathers made the case to his fellow South Carolinians in Congress to maintain the farm bill\u2019s credit provision and conservation programs, fix the dairy program, support and fund specialty crop block grants, and keep the nutrition title in the legislation. That\u2019s been a sticky subject for lawmakers from the Palmetto State, among whom Jim DeMint, the former senator from South Carolina, is still popular. DeMint previously led the conservative Heritage Foundation, which advocated for splitting the most recent farm bill. The nutrition title was \u201ca cause of a fair amount of angst\u201d among South Carolina\u2019s congressional delegation in 2014 as Heritage and then-Rep. Mick Mulvaney pushed for the legislation to include only farm programs, despite warnings from agricultural groups.   But this time around, with DeMint off on new ventures and Mulvaney at the White House, things could be a bit easier, Weathers said.   HAPPY THURSDAY, JULY 27! Welcome to Morning Ag, where the news that former White House spokesman Sean Spicer is being eyed by producers for a spot on Dancing with the Stars is making the team nostalgic about our favorite farmer contestant, Texas Agriculture commissioner turned governor turned Energy Secretary Rick Perry. You know the deal: Thoughts, news, dance tips? Send them to jhopkinson@politico.com and @jennyhops. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  SONNY IN A SEA OF BLUE: Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue has spent a lot of time touting the Future Farmers of America, hosting town halls with members and pointing out the navy-blue-jacket-clad youngsters in speeches and farm visits. Now the relationship is official. Perdue signed a memorandum of understanding between the USDA and FFA on Wednesday morning, agreeing to work to promote agricultural education and create internship opportunities and other resources to help young people develop careers in agriculture.   \u201cThe main objective is for USDA and National FFA to continue to have a dialogue on how we best build leaders and leadership programs, for how we prepare the next generation for careers in agriculture and agribusiness,\u201d FFA CEO Mark Poeschl told MA after the signing.   There is clear demand for assistance: A 2015 study from Purdue University and USDA estimated that for each year between that year and 2020, there would be an average of 58,000 skilled jobs available annually in agriculture \u2014 in areas like management, technology, sustainability and biomaterials development \u2014 but just 35,000 graduates qualified to fill them. \u201cWe need to and want to create an awareness among young people that while agriculture may not be as sexy as a Silicon Valley job, there are still a lot of opportunities available,\u201d Poeschl said.  The 800-acre gorilla in the room: The agreement surely could encourage some young people to fill high-skilled agricultural job openings, but it doesn\u2019t seem to do much to address the broader question of how to get young people into production agriculture. The average age of the American farmer is around 58 years-old, and more baby-boom-generation farmers retire with each harvest. FFA is an educational organization that works with middle- and high-school students on agriculture and leadership development, and under its charter it can\u2019t get involved in political issues and policymaking. As a result, it isn\u2019t involved in discussions on Capitol Hill about how to reduce burdens for people looking to get into farming \u2014 issues like access to land and capital for equipment, and student loan forgiveness for farm workers and managers.   The 2014 farm bill included money and technical assistance to help new and beginning farmers, but that has done little to encourage lenders or assist in land acquisition. Those are fixes, advocates say, that Congress will need to tackle next.  THE WOTUS AMONG US: EPA and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers will formally propose withdrawal of the Obama administration's controversial water rule today, marking the end of a yearslong effort by farm and other groups to scrap what they say is burdensome federal overreach. The proposed rule to withdraw the Waters of the U.S. rule, also called the Clean Water Rule, was unveiled in late June, but had yet to be noticed in the Federal Register, the formal step that triggers the beginning of the public comment period. The Trump administration has given the public 30 days to weigh in on the proposed rule, though critics of the repeal effort have called for more time.  A long way to December: The proposed rule would change little on the ground today, since the Obama administration's water rule only briefly went into effect before the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals put it on hold nationwide. The repeal rule is seen as a safety net in case the Supreme Court determines the 6th Circuit didn't have authority over the case and the hold is lifted. The repeal rule would remove the Obama-era rule from the books and cement the status quo while the Trump administration works on its own regulation to define which streams and wetlands are subject to federal protection under the Clean Water Act \u2014 an effort it has said it plans to unveil in December. More details here.   CFTC NOMINEE EARNED THOUSANDS LOBBYING AGAINST CFTC: Dawn DeBerry Stump, one of the Republicans who President Donald Trump nominated for a CFTC commissioner post, earned almost $400,000 in the last year working for an industry association that has been critical of the agency\u2019s regulations. On Thursday, Stump and two other nominees to be commissioner of the U.S. derivatives regulator \u2014 Republican Brian Quintenz, a former asset manager, and Democrat Rostin Behnam, a staffer for Senate Agriculture Committee ranking member Debbie Stabenow \u2014 will face their confirmation hearing before Senate Ag.   Stump is likely to face more attention than her fellow nominees. From January 2016 to May 2017, the Futures Industry Association paid her $198,902 in salary and bonuses, according to a financial disclosure form signed in May. Stump worked for FIA from 2012 to May 2016 as an executive. After she left, she made $197,586 lobbying at the firm she founded, Stump Strategic. FIA was her only client. She terminated the lobbying work in May. Stump declined to comment. More details on the nominees\u2019 financial disclosures here.   NCC HOPES TO GET POULTRY INTO CHINA SOON: The National Chicken Council is feeling optimistic about prospects for reopening China to U.S. poultry products after more than three dozen senators on Wednesday urged the Department of Agriculture to step up its efforts to get Beijing to lift its ban. \u201cWe are optimistic this will lead to the lifting of the ban in weeks, not months, and hopefully implementing regionalization soon after,\u201d Tom Super, a spokesman for NCC, tells MA.   In a letter to Secretary Perdue, the senators commended USDA for reopening the Chinese market to U.S. beef and urge that the same be done for U.S. poultry. China closed it market to U.S. poultry in 2015, citing concerns of highly pathogenic avian influenza that was detected in a wild duck. The letter, which was led by Sens. Mark Warner (D-Va.) and Thad Cochran (R-Miss.), notes that China has begun its animal health audit of the U.S. poultry industry \u2014 one of the crucial steps necessary for a resumption of U.S. imports.  CSPI RAILS AGAINST CLOVIS NOMINATION: Add the Center for Science in the Public Interest to the list of advocacy groups not pleased about Trump\u2019s nomination of Sam Clovis to be USDA\u2019s chief scientist.  \u201cSam Clovis has been a business school professor, a conservative talk radio host, an Air Force official, and, of course, a Trump campaign official. There are likely senior jobs in the administration that he would have been qualified to hold, but the job of USDA chief scientist is not one of them,\u201d Michael Jacobson, executive director of CSPI, said in a statement Wednesday. \u201cHe should not have been nominated, and the law requires that he not be confirmed.\u201d  AG INDUSTRY URGES SWIFT ACTION ON NAFTA TO AVOID FURTHER HARM: Most members of the House Agriculture Committee on Wednesday zeroed in on three issues related to the upcoming renegotiation of NAFTA, which starts August 16: expanding U.S. dairy exports to Canada and Mexico; balancing America\u2019s $5.3 billion produce trade deficit with Mexico; and ensuring NAFTA 2.0 is finalized as soon as possible \u2014 because the current political uncertainty has already hurt U.S. grain exports south of the border. Chairman Mike Conaway and Reps. Frank Lucas, Tom O\u2019Halleran and others emphasized the importance of wrapping up NAFTA 2.0 quickly, after officials from the U.S. grain industry testified that there\u2019s already been a 4-percent decline in sales of corn and 13 percent decline in sales of soybean meal to Mexico this year when compared with 2016.   Dairy dilemmas. Tom Vilsack, president and CEO of the U.S. Dairy Export Council, fielded a deluge of questions about what he described as tactics used by the Canadian government to block U.S. dairy exports \u2014 most recently with the establishment of a pricing program for ultrafiltered milk (a key ingredient in cheese). Any renegotiation of NAFTA needs to ensure more predictability and transparency, as well as reduce tariffs on U.S. dairy exports, he said at Wednesday\u2019s hearing.  But Canada is standing firmly in defense of both the Class 7 program for ultrafiltered milk and its supply management program, which sets production quotas and restricts imports to stabilize farmers\u2019 incomes. Canada argues these policies are not the cause of the U.S.\u2019s milk oversupply problem, and House Ag ranking member Collin Peterson (D-Minn.) predicted they could represent a potential rift in the coming talks, arguing the Canadians \u201care going to defend this no matter what.\u201d   IOWA FARMERS FLOOD INBOX OF WRITER WHO HIT BIOTECH MERGERS: It hadn\u2019t even been 36 hours and already more than 50 Iowa farmers had reached out to Austin Frerick to thank him. Frerick, who recently moved back to his home state after living in Washington, D.C., and working for the Treasury Department, had published an op-ed in the Des Moines Register last week that called for blocking the Monsanto-Bayer and Dow-DuPont mergers and breaking up other Big Ag corporations, to protect farmers from the potential combo of higher prices for seeds and pesticides and fewer alternatives that consolidation threatens to bring. Frerick\u2019s piece also criticized elected officials in Washington for not speaking up.   \u201cIt amazes me that no one has made a big deal about this wave of mega-mergers yet,\u201d Frerick told MA in an interview Wednesday. \u201cNo one is representing the actual farmer.\u201d  Frerick said that most of the e-mails he received from Iowa farmers were short thank-yous for raising a red flags on the issue when no one else has, including many industry groups that represent them. There also were expressions of frustration with Sen. Chuck Grassley (R-Iowa), chairman of the Judiciary Committee, he said. Grassley has been one of the more outspoken critics of the proposed agrochemical mergers, sending letters to the Justice Department to press for strict scrutiny to ensure markets are competitive, and holding a hearing last year where top executives from Monsanto, Bayer, Dow, DuPont and Syngenta all testified. But during his more than 30-year tenure as Iowa\u2019s senator, consolidation in the agriculture industry has only increased, Frerick said.   Some groups are making a stink. That includes the National Farmers Union, Food and Water Watch and the American Antitrust Institute, which on Wednesday sent a 17-page joint letter to DOJ analyzing how the proposed mergers would consolidate power among three companies and likely harm competition \u2014 and farmers and consumers along with it.   MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 Federal prosecutors in California have subpoenaed Chipotle for information on a suspected norovirus outbreak at its Sterling, Va., outlet, as part of an ongoing probe into the wave of foodborne illnesses that befell the burrito chain in 2015, Reuters reports.   \u2014 The University of California is trying to convince a federal judge that the federal patent appeal board ignored key evidence that proves it should be granted the patent for the gene-editing technology CRISPR, Science Magazine reports.   \u2014 Agricultural equipment maker AGCO Corp. is planning to buy Monsanto\u2019s equipment business, Reuters reports.   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
