aV \u000a            By CATHERINE BOUDREAU  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Helena Bottemiller Evich, Jenny Hopkinson and Anthony Andragna  CLOVIS\u2019 PAST STANCE ON CROP INSURANCE SPARKS CRITICISM: Senate Agriculture Chairman Pat Roberts put down a marker in what is expected to be a political battle to confirm Sam Clovis to a top USDA post. Although Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue\u2019s confirmation hearing didn\u2019t feature any real dustups, Clovis\u2019 pursuit to be USDA undersecretary for research, education and economics has drawn rebuke.  Story Continued Below  Roberts, during a hearing Tuesday on risk management programs in the farm bill, said that any USDA nominee who regarded crop insurance as unconstitutional "might as well not show up" to a confirmation hearing. Roberts' comments came after concerns raised by ranking member Debbie Stabenow, who mentioned that a USDA nominee who has questioned the constitutionality of crop insurance would be coming before the committee. She didn\u2019t mention Clovis by name, but his reputation preceded him.  Have Clovis\u2019 views evolved? In a 2013 interview with an Iowa talk radio host \u2014 when Clovis ran unsuccessfully to replace retiring Sen. Tom Harkin (D-Iowa) \u2014 he said crop insurance subsidies were federal spending that was unconstitutional. And in a 2014 interview with Iowa Public Radio, Clovis said: \u201c[M]ost of the Iowa farmers I talk to would just as soon have the government out of their lives and that includes the [crop] insurance program,\u201d adding that the government in some instances is supporting bad farming practices. His views resurfaced after POLITICO reported them in March, because he had since become a White House representative. But as recently as September, Clovis told reporters that crop insurance needs to be protected as a matter of national security.   Farm groups don\u2019t appear worried. Most major agricultural commodity groups cite crop insurance as one of the most important tools farmers have to manage risk, but they are still backing Clovis. In a letter this week to Roberts and Stabenow, they argue Clovis is qualified and will advocate for them.  He\u2019s officially the choice. President Donald Trump announced his intent to nominate Clovis earlier this month. It became official on Tuesday when the Senate Agriculture Committee received a formal notification from the White House.   HAPPY WEDNESDAY, JULY 26! Welcome to Morning Ag, where your host plans to bring this classy fish n' chips dish to the next party I'm invited to. You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips? Send them to cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  GRASSLEY REITERATES CALL FOR STRICTER FARM SUBSIDY LIMITS: Sen. Chuck Grassley (R-Iowa) wasn\u2019t shy about his frustration over the watering down of a provision he secured in a draft of the 2014 farm bill to cut off commodity subsidies to managers who aren\u2019t \u201cactively engaged\u201d in farming. Grassley had sought to limit to one the number of farm managers that a single operation could have, and cap their subsidies at $125,000. In the final version of the law, family farms (the majority of farm operations in the United States) were exempted from the new "actively engaged" requirements, which USDA finalized in 2015. Grassley has argued that this maintains a loophole allowing non-farming family members to receive subsidies.  \u201cPerhaps the most important thing I can do is explain why this issue is so important,\u201d Grassley said in a four-minute monologue during the Ag Committee hearing on Tuesday. \u201cGiving non-farmers subsidies is completely indefensible, especially when we have a $20 trillion debt. If bigger farmers are as efficient as they claim, they should not need unlimited subsidies to make their business model work.\u201d  Grassley added that he did not understand how the current $125,000-a-year cap on subsidies for a single farm operator (double that for married ones) wasn\u2019t enough to get a business through the year. \u201cWhat is the harm of supporting a policy that helps young and beginning farmers, gives us credibility against critics, and saves taxpayers money? Mr. Chairman, I\u2019m trying to help you, given the tight budget situation, as we try to help farmers that really are on the land doing the work,\u201d Grassley said to Roberts, who responded: \u201cMessage received.\u201d  McCONNELL GRACES AG HEARING WITH HIS PRESENCE: Also of note during Tuesday\u2019s hearing: A rare appearance by Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell. He briefly stopped in at the nearly four-hour hearing to introduce a witness from his home state, Mark Haney, president of the Kentucky Farm Bureau Federation. Roberts capitalized on McConnell\u2019s presence, urging him to bring the next iteration of the farm bill to the Senate floor this year, if the Agriculture Committee can deliver. It\u2019s a rather optimistic view considering all the political nominees senators need to vote on, not to mention the ongoing debate over a new health care law. \u201cThe sooner the better,\u201d McConnell told Roberts.  REPORT: RURAL WATER SYSTEMS HAVE HIGH NITRATE LEVELS: A new report from the Environmental Working Group looked at the 30 utilities with the distinction of having the highest nitrate contamination in tests between 2010 and 2015. All 30 exceeded the legal limit. And all 30 served small populations in rural, farm-based economies.   Nitrate in drinking water often stems from nitrogen runoff from fertilized fields. A larger system, like the Des Moines Water Works, has about half a million ratepayers to defray the costs to remove nitrates. But the largest one of the 30 that registered high levels served just 1,650 people. Many of the problematic ones are in rural western Texas, agricultural areas in California, and other farm-heavy communities.  EWG wants Congress to help those communities avoid having too much nitrate in their water in the first place. The report reviewed water data from roughly 50,000 utilities across the country.  VILSACK TALKS NAFTA IN FIRST HILL APPEARANCE SINCE LEAVING USDA: Tom Vilsack, president and CEO of the U.S. Dairy Export Council, will discuss trade issues between the U.S. and Canada during a House Agriculture Committee hearing on NAFTA this morning. It is to be Vilsack\u2019s first testimony before Congress since leaving his post as agriculture secretary. In his new role, Vilsack has repeatedly called for Canada to further open up its dairy sector. Canada has a supply management program that stabilizes incomes for its farmers by setting production limits and restricting imports. Other U.S. agricultural sectors that will be represented at the hearing today include beef, grains, poultry and eggs, and Florida fruit and vegetables. Watch the hearing live starting at 10 a.m. here.  WILDLIFE BILL SET FOR EPW VOTE: Senators on the Environment and Public Works Committee are expected today to clear legislation (S. 1514) to reauthorize through 2023 a number of popular conservation programs, including the North American Wetlands Conservation Act and Chesapeake Bay Program. \u201cThis bill is another example of how we can all work together, both Democrat and Republican, to help protect the environment and grow our economy,\u201d Chairman John Barrasso said at a hearing. While provisions in the package blocking Endangered Species Act protections for gray wolves in the Wyoming and Great Lakes region have drawn criticism from some Democrats, it\u2019s expected to clear the panel at a business meeting.  PERRY GETS TROLLED: The Energy Department has confirmed that Russian pranksters successfully got a 20-minute conversation with Secretary Rick Perry last week, Pro Energy\u2019s Darius Dixon reports. The trickery happened on July 19, but was only reported in a story on Tuesday in the Pravda Report, a Russian publication. (Cue the audio). Perry thought he was speaking with an Ukrainian official on behalf of Prime Minister Volodymyr Groysman. Topics discussed included the 2015 Paris climate agreement, the Nord Stream 2 natural gas pipeline and the possibility of a biofuel devised from home-brewed alcohol and manure.  RURAL TASK FORCE DOES ROUND TWO: Perdue on Tuesday morning hosted a second meeting with the principals of the Agriculture and Rural Prosperity Task Force, a group charged with "promoting agriculture and rural prosperity in America." It is supposed to come up with policy recommendations within 180 days. The group is planning to send a final report to the White House by late October, the USDA said. Those in attendance on Tuesday included Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross, Health and Human Services Secretary Tom Price, Transportation Secretary Elaine Chao, Housing and Urban Development Secretary Ben Carson and FCC Chairman Ajit Pai, the department said.  PERDUE MAKES NEWS AT FUTURE FARMER BREAKFAST: Perdue today will announce an agreement with the Future Farmers of America to support young farmers and prepare the future agriculture workforce. More than 100 FFA members from across the country are in Washington to chat with lawmakers about supporting technical education and programs for new and beginning farmers. The announcement will be livestreamed here.   Texas tour. Perdue also plans to travel to San Angelo, Texas, next week to attend the House Agriculture Committee\u2019s second field hearing on the farm bill, Chairman Mike Conaway announced Tuesday. The hearing is scheduled for July 21 at Angelo State University. More here.  PHILLY SODA TAX REVENUE SLIGHTLY BELOW PROJECTION: The Philadelphia soda tax has brought in just under $39.7 million, preliminary estimates for fiscal year 2017 indicate, with the most money per month coming in June, the end of the city\u2019s fiscal year. The figure is short of the $46 million that the mayor\u2019s office had predicted. More from the Philadelphia Business Journal here.   GMA, FOOD POLICY ACTION TEAM UP ON FOOD WASTE SURVEY: A new survey by strange bedfellows \u2014 the Grocery Manufacturers Association and the Food Policy Action Network \u2014 has found that nearly 60 percent of Americans have been confounded at home about what to make of date labels on food packages. About 40 percent said they\u2019ve had disagreements in their households about whether food should be kept or tossed by the date listed.   \u201cClarity on product date labeling will reduce confusion, cut food waste, and enable households to spend their time arguing about something other than what a date label means, like sports, politics, or what channel to watch on TV,\u201d said Meghan Stasz, GMA\u2019s senior director of sustainability.  The poll, conducted by Lake Research Partners, included more than 1,000 adults of various ages and political persuasions. The research comes after GMA and the Food Marketing Institute this year agreed to work together on standardizing date labels \u2014 which run the gamut from \u201cbest by\u201d to \u201cuse by,\u201d and \u201csell by\u201d and don\u2019t always mean the same thing.   WALMART, FFAR DISH OUT FUNDS TO REDUCE FOOD WASTE: The World Wildlife Fund has received a $1.3 million grant from the Foundation for Food and Agriculture Research and the Walmart Foundation to identify ways for farmers to increase the proportion of crops that are harvested and delivered. The intent is to prevent food from going to waste in the field. Researchers will look at maximizing the harvest of specialty crops and developing data on post harvest losses, among other things. The groups will announce the grant today.  MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 DuPont CEO Ed Breen said the company is on track to close its merger with Dow Chemical Co. next month, Bloomberg reports. The company also said it had an 11 percent increase in farm-related earnings during the second quarter.  \u2014 Tests found traces of glyphosate in Ben & Jerry\u2019s ice cream, The New York Times reports.   \u2014 Europe's largest farm lobby is urging the government to fight U.S. plans to impose anti-dumping measures against Spanish olive imports, POLITICO Europe\u2019s Emmet Livingstone reports.   \u2014 Brazil\u2019s federal food safety inspectors resumed their protest this week over what they say is a lack of employees to ensure the safety of the meat supply, Reuters reports.  \u2014 One of the founders of the food-delivery startup Blue Apron is stepping down from leadership a month after the company went public, The Wall Street Journal reports.  THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
