aV \u000a            By HELENA BOTTEMILLER EVICH  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Anthony Andragna, Catherine Boudreau and Jenny Hopkinson   HOW CLOVIS IS WINNING OVER HIS CRITICS: If you have been reading the headlines about Sam Clovis\u2019s lack of hard science experience and skeptical climate change views, you might think that his expected nomination to be chief USDA scientist was in jeopardy. But behind the scenes, Clovis has been winning over many ag folks, inside and outside the department.   Story Continued Below  At least that\u2019s what yours truly found after digging into Clovis\u2019s background over the past couple of days. He is among the most controversial subcabinet picks, largely because he lacks the credentials for the position laid out in federal law. He is also on the record questioning the scientific consensus on climate change.  But Clovis has political connections on his side. Even as the former professor\u2019s credentials have publicly drawn fire, he\u2019s been quietly winning over rank-and-file at the USDA. Unlike the chaos at the EPA after President Donald Trump picked Scott Pruitt to lead the agency, the USDA has been relatively even-keeled. Clovis has proven himself to be a steady hand and impressed career staff. Even some of his critics privately acknowledge that tanking his nomination could yield a pick whom they would view as much worse.  Trump whisperer? It was widely reported that Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue helped make the case for not pulling out of NAFTA by bringing a map to the Oval Office to illustrate precisely where the pain would be felt by such a drastic move. Guess who suggested he bring the map? Clovis.   Clovis, an Iowa Republican, is now known within the USDA as having a direct line to the president, a level of access far above that which is usually enjoyed by the USDA\u2019s head of research. That close rapport is not lost on agricultural groups. On Monday, nearly two dozen leading farm groups \u2014 including the American Farm Bureau Federation, the National Council of Farmer Cooperatives and the National Cattlemen's Beef Association \u2014 signed a letter urging the Senate Agriculture Committee to move swiftly on his nomination. Don\u2019t miss the full story on Clovis here.  HAPPY TUESDAY, JULY 25! Welcome to Morning Ag, where we your host could not be more excited to be heading to the Pacific Northwest on Friday. Oh summer weather sans humidity, I\u2019ve missed you so much! You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips? Send them to hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  DEMS PLEDGE CRACKDOWN ON CORPORATE MONOPOLIES: Democrats trekked on Monday to the small town of Berryville, Va., to unveil their new populist economic agenda packaged under the slogan \u201cA Better Deal.\u201d It\u2019s aimed at improving their chances of winning over voters ahead of the 2018 midterm elections. Within the party\u2019s plan is a pledge to crack down on corporate monopolies, including those in the agriculture and food and beverage industries.  The pending mergers among six agrochemical companies \u2014 Dow with DuPont, Monsanto with Bayer AG and Syngenta with ChemChina \u2014 were cited as examples of the trend in concentration of power. Consolidation in the agriculture industry will hurt family operations that will have to pay more for seeds and pesticides, as well as consumers paying higher food prices, the platform says. The beer industry was also targeted, as Dems noted that Anheuser-Busch InBev's purchase of SABMiller last year led to plans for job cuts.  NFU URGES \u2018NO\u2019 VOTE ON ACA REPEAL AND REPLACE: The National Farmers Union on Monday called on Senate lawmakers to drop their effort to \u201crepeal and replace\u201d the Affordable Care Act.  \u201cThe cost of health care has long been a primary concern of farmers and ranchers,\u201d NFU President Roger Johnson wrote in a letter. \u201cWhile there is certainly room for improvements to current policy, the Better Care Reconciliation Act (BCRA) and the Obamacare Repeal Reconciliation Act both ignore the needs of family farmers and ranchers. NFU urges you to vote no on either piece of legislation and to seek a common sense, bipartisan solution to improve our nation\u2019s health care system.\u201d The BCRA would leave many rural marketplaces without a single insurer, NFU argued. \u201cWorse yet, completely repealing the ACA would leave nearly three-quarters of the population without a single insurer in the non-group market,\u201d Johnson said.   Reality check: Any way you slice it, the rural health insurance market is lacking in competition. Roughly 41 percent of rural Americans have only one plan to choose from on the exchange. Nearly 32 percent of counties, many of them rural, only have only one provider offered. It doesn\u2019t take an economist to understand that less competition means higher prices. Pros can brush up on farmers\u2019 concerns on health care from yours truly here.   BYE-BYE RECESS?  House members and staffers, don\u2019t pack your bags just yet. House Republican appropriators are pressing Speaker Paul Ryan to cancel the first week of recess and tackle the extensive spending package full of goodies for the base.   Under the urging of financial services subcommittee chairman Tom Graves (R-Ga.), a few appropriators are urging the leadership to reconsider a $1 trillion spending bill before leaving for summer break. They were furious when the leadership decided last week to only pursue a smaller, scaled back version for national security priorities. The full story from Rachael Bade and John Bresnahan is here.   Late Monday night, another lawmaker, Rep. Mark Walker, started an effort to force a vote on all 12 spending bills by hijacking the slimmer package scheduled to hit the House floor this week. Pros can read about that here.   What that means for ag: The fiscal 2018 agriculture spending bill gives the USDA and the FDA more money than Trump\u2019s budget sought, so if the full House approves the bill before recess, it increases the likelihood that it will become the law of the land. It\u2019s still not clear what the Senate\u2019s timeline is, but aggies will certainly be watching closely. Senate Appropriations Chairman Thad Cochran and ranking member Patrick Leahy worked out a provision in the Senate bill to give $1 billion in support over 10 years \u2014 to be split evenly between the cotton and dairy sectors.  MEADOWS REITERATES SUPPORT FOR WORK REQUIREMENTS: Rep. Mark Meadows (R-N.C.), the ringleader of the House Freedom Caucus, doubled down on Monday on his tribe\u2019s insistence for stricter work requirements for able-bodied adults without dependents (known as ABAWDs) for them to receive SNAP benefits.   \u201cWe believe there should be a work requirement for able-bodied adults with non-dependent children,\u201d Meadows said, when asked about SNAP cuts at a National Press Club luncheon. \u201cWe\u2019ve got to put the value back in work once again. It\u2019s not fair to the American taxpayer for us to continue to give benefits if someone could work.\u201d  He noted the Freedom Caucus had taken a strong position on work requirements, but added that he was thinking beyond that: \u201cWe think we can find some common ground on the other part of the safety net.\u201d  Farm bill love? Meadows was a bit softer in his stance on the farm bill. He noted that he voted for the last iteration because agriculture is a major driver of the economy in his North Carolina district. \u201cAre there some good things in the farm bill? Yes. The less government involvement that we have generally the better off we are,\u201d he said.   FIRST STEP TOWARD CLIMATE \u2018RED TEAM\u2019? The Competitive Enterprise Institute\u2019s Myron Ebell says EPA might tap Steven Koonin, undersecretary for science at the DOE from 2009 to 2011, to run its "red team" review of climate science, Pro\u2019s Alex Guilln reports. Koonin, who wrote in 2014 that the science behind climate change \u201cis not settled.\u201d He floated the formation of a red team in a Wall Street Journal piece in April, arguing that such a review "would shine much-needed light on the scientific debates" surrounding the issue.  UDALL, BLUMENTHAL CALL FOR CHLORPYRIFOS BAN: Sens. Tom Udall (D-N.M.) and Richard Blumenthal (D-Conn.) will introduce a bill today to ban the use of the pesticide of chlorpyrifos \u2014 a move that follows a court order last week that kept in place the EPA\u2019s March decision not to pull the chemical from the market. Chlorpyrifos is a widely used agricultural pesticide, but has been linked to neurological problems in children in some cases, as well as to other health risks. The EPA under President Obama was on track to ban the chemical for agricultural uses, a move called for in a petition from environmentalists. However, the Trump administration has denied the petition, arguing that it needs more time to study the health risks of the chemical. EPA says it will make a decision by 2022 on whether to keep the pesticide on the market.  Udall and Blumenthal will layout their bill in a press conference Tuesday, according to a notice from their offices.   ANOTHER PANEL WADES INTO BIOFUELS DEBATE: Two House Science subpanels will dip their toes into the debate over biofuels policy. A hearing at 10 a.m. will \u201cexamine federal funding of biofuels projects and how it affects the private market.\u201d Witnesses include representatives from Oak Ridge National Laboratory and University of Michigan\u2019s Energy Institute, as well Growth Energy\u2019s CEO Emily Skor and the Heritage Foundation\u2019s Nicolas Loris. More info here.  AG SHAREHOLDER RETURNS TANK: The agribusiness sector is returning a whole lot less to its investors than in years past, according to a new study by the consulting firm Boston Consulting Group. The report looked at 40 of the top agribusiness companies from 2012 to 2016. It found that the industry\u2019s shareholder returns were among the lowest of the 34 sectors that the firm examined. Only oil and mining ranked lower. This was not always so, the report says. Between 2007 and 2011, the agribusiness sector was the best-performing industry in the ranking. Find the report here.   USDA BUMPS UP SUGAR QUOTA: The Agriculture Department said Monday that it would allow more imported raw cane sugar this fiscal year to meet domestic demand by increasing the tariff-rate quota by 244,690 metric tons.The USDA, in a Federal Register notice Monday, said that with the increase, the overall fiscal 2017 raw sugar TRQ would be 1.36 million metric tons."This action is being taken after a determination that additional supplies of raw cane sugar are required in the U.S. market," the department said.  FOOD POLICY ACTION NAMES MILLS AS NEW HEAD: Food Policy Action has named Monica Mills as the organization\u2019s new executive director. Mills, formerly director of government relations at the anti-hunger group Bread for the World, has previously been named a top grassroots lobbyist in Washington. Tom Colicchio, FPA co-founder and celebrity chef, praised the selection by saying: \u201cThis is a pivotal time for our food movement, and we are confident that Monica can build on FPA\u2019s historic successes and best prepare the organization to meet the enormous challenges ahead to protect and improve our nation\u2019s food and agriculture system.\u201d   MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 Sen. Cory Booker and other lawmakers in the Congressional Black Caucus are planning to push for greater scrutiny over Amazon\u2019s purchase of Whole Foods, Recode reports.   \u2014 The Senate confirmed former lobbyist Dave Bernhardt to the Interior Department's No. 2 spot, Pro Energy\u2019s Ben Lefebvre reports.  \u2014 Heinz is in court in Australia over the sugar content of some of its toddler foods, BBC reports.   \u2014 Inadequate funding for food safety oversight of imports is putting people at risk, Bill Marler argues over at The Hill.   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.   Helena Bottemiller Evich is a senior food and agriculture reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Before joining POLITICO, Helena spent four years reporting on food politics and policy at Food Safety News, where she covered Congress, the Food and Drug Administration and the U.S. Department of Agriculture.  Helena's work has also appeared in the Columbia Journalism Review and on NBC News. Her reporting has taken her to the Louisiana coast during the Gulf oil spill, Arizona lettuce fields, North Carolina hog farms and the occasional presidential turkey pardoning.  A native of Washington state and an alumna of Claremont McKenna College, she now lives in Washington, D.C., with her husband.  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
