aV \u000a            By JENNY HOPKINSON  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Catherine Boudreau, Luis Sanchez, Doug Palmer and Helena Bottemiller Evich   AG GROUPS RALLYING AROUND CLOVIS: Look for at least a dozen leading agriculture groups to go on the record today in support of Sam Clovis, President Donald Trump\u2019s controversial pick for USDA undersecretary for research, education and economics. The groups are expected to send a letter to Senate Agriculture Committee leaders today that outlines why they think Clovis, a climate skeptic who does not have a background in agricultural science, is a good choice to be USDA\u2019s chief scientist. \u201cThose researchers don\u2019t need a peer, they need an advocate,\u201d said Chuck Conner, president and CEO of the National Council of Farmer Cooperatives, who organized the letter.   Story Continued Below  Clovis and his critics: Conner and others MA has spoken to recently also contend that Clovis has started winning over critics inside and outside the department. \u201cTheir first instinct, given his background, was to not like this guy,\u201d Conner said, referring to rank-and-file USDA officials. \u201cBut he\u2019s won them over in a big way.\u201d Stay tuned later today for more on Clovis and the coming battle over his nomination.   HAPPY MONDAY, JULY 24! Welcome to Morning Ag, where we are reading about scientists rushing to get on the campaign trail, Cubans hoping President Trump won\u2019t follow through with his plans to reverse recent improvements in relations, and about Jay Leno\u2019s ride in a hemp car as we ease back into the work week. You know the deal: Thoughts, news, tips? Send them to jhopkinson@politico.com and @jennyhops. Follow the whole team at @Morning_Ag.  THIS WEEK: HOME STRETCH FOR THE HOUSE: House lawmakers are in their final week before August recess, and the Agriculture Committee is making its preparations for next month\u2019s start of the NAFTA 2.0 talks before it leaves. Chairman Mike Conaway will use a hearing on Wednesday to highlight the needs of farmers in the upcoming renegotiation. Farmers are worried that efforts to return manufacturing jobs to the U.S. \u2014 something Trump has long promised to do \u2014 could hurt provisions of the deal that have made it so successful for agriculture. The witness list has yet to be announced, but some grain and corn growers are likely to want to deliver their message directly to lawmakers. Details for the hearing are here.   Also happening this week:  The gang\u2019s all here: The Senate Agriculture Committee will meet Tuesday morning to hear from 17 farmers and farm group representatives, to get their take on existing risk management tools as lawmakers prepare to craft the 2018 farm bill. Yes, you read that right: There will be 17 witnesses! Some time will be devoted to discussion of farmers\u2019 access to credit, a big talking point for groups like the National Farmers Union and advocates for young farmers, both of which are expected to have representatives testify. The proceedings will also likely include calls to make sure the farm bill doesn\u2019t include cuts to crop insurance. Details.  Achin\u2019 for some bacon? National Pork Producers Council CEO Neil Dierks is set to testify before the House Judiciary Committee on Tuesday about state rules that affect entities outside of their borders. Also due to testify are representatives from Taxpayers for Common Sense and the National Conference of State Legislators. Details.   While we wait for USDA nominees to get their Senate spotlight: The Senate Agriculture Committee on Thursday will hold a confirmation hearing for three nominees to the Commodity Futures Trading Commission: Rostin Behnam, Brian Quintenz and Dawn DeBerry Stump. Quintenz, in particular, is no stranger to the committee; the hedge fund manager was nominated for the same job by former President Barack Obama in March 2016. Quintenz won bipartisan support from Senate Ag, but did not get a full Senate vote before the election, and his nomination withered on the vine. Trump nominated him anew in May. Details.  The hearing is a key step toward filling out the agency\u2019s leadership, which today consists of acting Chairman J. Christopher Giancarlo and Commissioner Sharon Bowen, who has announced plans to step down. Giancarlo has received Senate Ag\u2019s signoff but is awaiting the floor vote that will make him the CFTC\u2019s confirmed head.  Farm Credit leaders climb the Hill: More than 600 members of the Farm Credit Council \u2014 the organization that represents the agricultural banking network\u2019s interests in Washington \u2014 will be on Capitol Hill for two days, beginning Tuesday. Farm Credit System leaders plan to talk with lawmakers about their priorities for the 2018 farm bill and to advocate for increasing the USDA Farm Service Agency\u2019s $1.39 million limit on guaranteed loans. Members also want to ensure that funding for all FSA loan programs, both guaranteed and direct, remains at the same levels in fiscal 2018 as in the previous fiscal year.   SONNY GOES TO DELAWARE: Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue is headed to the Delaware State Fair today to spend some time with Sens. Tom Carper and Chris Coons, and Rep. Lisa Blunt Rochester, as well as state officials and farmers. Agriculture is the top industry in Delaware, contributing about $8 billion to the economy. Corn, soybeans, poultry and apples are the state\u2019s big crops. The state fair, in Harrington, is in its 98th year, and promises visitors a chance to hold a chick, drink Cheerwine and watch an extreme pogo stick demonstration. Details.   Scuse (is still) on the loose: Perdue will get a tour of the fair from Delaware Agriculture Secretary Michael Scuse, who was USDA\u2019s acting deputy for most of 2016 after several years as undersecretary for farm and foreign agriculture services.   IN DEFENSE OF POLLINATORS: A slew of food safety and environmental groups will demonstrate outside EPA headquarters today to voice support for a ban on all neonicotinoid pesticides \u2014 chemicals the groups believe are causing declines in pollinator populations. Friends of the Earth, Center for Biological Diversity, Earthjustice, Environment America and SumOfUs will also deliver what organizers said are thousands of letters to EPA from members of the public who back a ban. The event begin at 11 a.m.  SENATE APPROPRIATORS CALL FOR CONSERVATION DEPUTY: The Senate Appropriations Committee, in non-binding report language that was published Friday to accompany its fiscal 2018 agriculture spending bill, encouraged USDA to appoint a deputy undersecretary for conservation. The position would be second in command to the newly created post of undersecretary for farm production and conservation, which Secretary Perdue established as a part of a broader reorganization earlier this year. The undersecretary oversees three agencies: the Farm Service Agency, the Risk Management Agency and the Natural Resources Conservation Service.   Senate appropriators said they recognize that \u201cbetter coordination and data sharing between the three agencies can limit inefficiencies, improve conservation outcomes and enhance USDA\u2019s ability to serve its customers.\u201d A deputy undersecretary for conservation could facilitate those efforts and help ensure that each agency is supporting farmers\u2019 conservation objectives. The committee advanced the ag spending bill last week; the measure would allocate $20.5 billion in discretionary funding for USDA and FDA combined.  Additional committee recommendations on global food production, antibiotic research: Senate appropriators also said there needs to be an integrated approach at the federal level to address the food security and nutrition challenge of feeding more than 9 billion people around the world by 2050. Lawmakers urged the agriculture secretary to \u201ctake a leadership role\u201d in working with other federal agencies to meet that challenge and to \u201calign domestic and global programs related to food production.\u201d   The report language also said appropriators \u201cstrongly support\u201d research to develop alternatives to antibiotics used in animal production, and encouraged the USDA Agriculture Research Service to look into the role of \u201cnutritional alternatives/feed additives containing bioactives and prebiotics\u201d that may to lead reduced antibiotic use. Lawmakers requested a report on this effort as part of the department's fiscal 2019 budget.   Senate appropriators also want to be updated on imports of beef from Brazil after the scandal over federal food safety inspectors in that country taking bribes and allowing expired and unsanitary meat to be sold. (The U.S. banned all imports last month). Within 60 days of Congress enacting the ag spending bill, the agriculture secretary must send a report to Congress on any on-site trips USDA officials have taken to Brazil since March 18. The secretary must also notify lawmakers of when the next audit of the Brazilian meat inspection system will be conducted and provide results of the re-inspection system that Secretary Perdue implemented.  BILL INTRODUCED TO BOOST NUTRITION ED: Rep. Matt Cartwright (D-Pa.) late last week re-introduced a bill to promote nutrition education as a way to help combat the nation\u2019s crippling childhood obesity epidemic. The Nutrition Education Act would require schools participating in the National School Lunch Program to include 50 hours of nutrition education each year.  \u201cNearly one in three children is overweight or obese. This bill is an important step in ensuring our children are getting the health education they need to live healthier, longer lives,\u201d Cartwright said. \u201cIn addition, obesity and associated health problems take a toll on the nation\u2019s economy. Childhood obesity alone costs an estimated $14 billion annually in direct health expenses.\u201d More.   DOW\u2019S CHINA BIOTECH BLUES: As part of the Trump administration\u2019s 100-day plan to expand trade with China, the government of President Xi Jinping committed that it\u2019s National Biosafety Committee would hold a meeting by the end of May 2017 \u201cto conduct science-based evaluations of all eight pending U.S. biotechnology product applications to assess the safety of the products for their intended use.\u201d That wording suggested an agreement between the U.S. and China on the eight biotechnology products in question, even if it did not promise all eight would be approved by the end of the 100 days, which fell on July 16. But now it seems the U.S. and China may have been talking about two different groups of eight.   Dow AgroSciences said it previously understood that its \u201cEnlist\u201d variety of soybean was one of the eight pending biotechnology traits referenced under the 100-day plan. So, it was surprised when China\u2019s Ministry of Agriculture recently told the company that the herbicide-tolerant variety is not actually one of the eight products targeted for potential approval under the program. \u201cWe are seeking to clarify MOA\u2019s position related to Enlist soybeans,\u201d Dow said in a press release. \u201cWe will continue to work cooperatively with MOA to ensure this much-needed new technology will soon be available to farmers located in the U.S. and throughout the Americas.\u201d  The waiting list: China has approved four biotech varieties since the May 11 announcement of deliverables from the 100-day plan. One of those was Dow\u2019s Enlist corn. China also approved Monsanto's Vistive Gold soybean and its 87427 glyphosate-resistant corn, which is sold under the Roundup Ready brand, as well as Syngenta's 5307 insect-resistant corn, which is sold under the Agrisure Duracade brand.  MA\u2019S INSTANT OATS:  \u2014 Nutrition science drives everyone crazy not because it\u2019s fundamentally broken, but because it\u2019s really hard. The Washington Post explains.   \u2014 NPR goes behind the scenes to explore what it\u2019s like to work in a prison-run goat dairy. Read that here.   \u2014 University of Florida researchers are warning that recent weather fluctuations that have affected the state\u2019s strawberry crop are a harbinger of what climate change will do to all of the state\u2019s farms, the Tampa Bay Times reports.   \u2014 A class-action suit against Monsanto over dicamba-damaged crops alleges that company sales staff condoned use of older forms of the chemical on its new GMO crops, the St. Louis Post-Dispatch reports.   \u2014 Sen. Luther Strange is hoping that a focus on the farm bill will convince voters to keep him in office, AL.com reports.  THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MA! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop your host and the rest of the team a line: cboudreau@politico.com and @ceboudreau; jhopkinson@politico.com and @JennyHops; hbottemiller@politico.com and @hbottemiller; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Follow @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Ag on Twitter.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
