aV \u000a            By TIM STARKS  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Cory Bennett, Eric Geller and Martin Matishak   WHITE HOUSE CYBER SHAKEUP \u2014 Changeover on the National Security Council\u2019s cybersecurity team could disrupt work on President Donald Trump\u2019s cyber executive order, and all eyes are on cyber coordinator Rob Joyce to see how he manages the transition. Cheryl Davis, Daniel Melleby, and Heather King left the NSC cyber directorate in July, and Monica Maher is set to leave at the end of August, as Eric first reported on Thursday. King was filling in as one of two senior directors for cyber policy, while the other three were directors. A source familiar with the situation told Eric that at least two new people will be brought on to fill the gaps. The NSC cyber team has many responsibilities, but lately it has focused on overseeing the bevvy of reports from agencies that are spelled out in Trump\u2019s executive order. As those are submitted, the team will convene interagency meetings to distill the key takeaways and present policy options to senior officials.  Story Continued Below  Michael Daniel, who was former President Barack Obama\u2019s cyber coordinator, said he expected the departures to cause a short-term disruption in the NSC\u2019s work. \u201cWhen you have that much turnover in a short period of time, it inevitably affects your ability to operate,\u201d Daniel told MC in an email. \u201cYou lose people who know how to make the process work, the personal contacts at the agencies, and the perspective that comes with serving on the NSC.\u201d The fact that the departures came around the same time \u201cwill cause some temporary problems,\u201d he added, \u201cbut I expect Rob will be able to manage through it.\u201d  \u201cIt is a big loss for the NSC, administration and country,\u201d Ben Flatgard, who was an NSC director for cyber policy until January, told MC. \u201cWe're in a much better place as a nation because of their ideas, leadership and persistence.\u201d Andrew Grotto, who served as a senior director for cyber policy at the NSC until May, told MC that the impact might be felt in the \u201cquality of the work,\u201d because \u201cthe agencies won't lean in the way we want them to without [White House] leadership.\u201d NSC staffers, he said, are \u201ca vital conduit to the senior working experts doing the key work at the agencies.\u201d If the handoff to their replacements is not smooth, he said, there could be a \u201creal execution risk\u201d for the executive order.  Former officials noted that the four staffers\u2019 departures were expected, given the longevity of their service. Most NSC postings last only one or two years, and King had been working there since 2013, while the others joined in 2015 and 2016. \u201cIt's good to have some churn on the NSC staff as new people can come in with new ideas and energy to lead the interagency forward,\u201d said Flatgard, who is now a fellow at the Atlantic Council. Grotto, now a fellow at Stanford University, said he had confidence in Joyce \u2014 who he called \u201can experienced manager, with obvious depth in the substance\u201d \u2014 to serve as a steady hand. Joyce previously led the National Security Agency\u2019s elite hacking unit.  HAPPY FRIDAY and welcome to Morning Cybersecurity! Though this part-time boxing writer largely loathed his reign, Wladimir Klitschko dominated the heavyweight scene for freaking forever, is a class act and he retires after a rare (for him) thrilling pass-the-baton-style battle. Send your thoughts, feedback and especially tips to tstarks@politico.com, and be sure to follow @timstarks, @POLITICOPro, and @MorningCybersec. Full team info below.  WAGONS CIRCLED AROUND MUELLER \u2014 Senators are preemptively coming to the defense of special counsel Robert Mueller just as the former FBI is taking a step to accelerate his investigation into Russian meddling during the 2016 election and potential collusion with the Trump campaign.  Two pairs of bipartisan senators on Thursday proposed legislation that would protect special counsel Robert Mueller from potentially being fired by President Donald Trump. Together, the bills represent a warning shot for the president, who has expressed disdain for Mueller\u2019s investigation into possible collusion between the Trump campaign and Russia.   One measure, introduced by Senate Judiciary Committee members Thom Tillis and Chris Coons, would let Mueller challenge his firing to a panel of three federal judges after getting axed. The second proposal, from Sens. Lindsey Graham and Cory Booker, would force the Justice Department officials tasked with firing Mueller to first explain their rationale to the panel of judges. "Any effort to go after Mueller could be the beginning of the end of the Trump presidency unless Mueller did something wrong," Graham told reporters last week. Meanwhile, Sen. Jeff Flake suggested that Congress could hire Mueller if he\u2019s canned by the president. "I think that if he were to be removed, however it's done by the assistant attorney general or a new one, Congress would assert its prerogatives," Flake, a member of the Judiciary Committee, told MSNBC. "That would mean hiring a special prosecutor, and that might even be Bob Mueller."   The legislation dropped shortly before it was revealed that Mueller had impaneled a Washington grand jury for his Russia investigation, which our POLITICO colleague Darren Samuelsohn reported was \u201ca key procedural step.\u201d Mueller is expected to use the closed-door panel \u201cto present evidence and issue subpoenas as part of his expanding probe,\u201d Darren reported. And the investigation has been exploring financial ties, according to CNN.  WHITE HOUSE BIGFOOTING DHS ON CYBER? \u2014 The New York Times has some interesting details about what went down during the global ransomware outbreak earlier this year, in a story about new White House Chief of Staff John Kelly, who was at the time head of Homeland Security. "Mr. Kelly objected strenuously to the decision by Thomas P. Bossert, Mr. Trump\u2019s Homeland Security adviser in the White House, to take control of the response to a global cyberattack \u2014 a role traditionally played by Mr. Kelly and his department\u2019s cybersecurity division."  MUCH TO LEARN, YOU STILL HAVE \u2014 Universities, business groups and research organizations are sharing their thoughts on expanding and improving America\u2019s cyber workforce in comments sent to the technical standards agency NIST. Trump\u2019s cyber executive order tasked the Commerce Department with preparing a report on cyber education and training strategies, and NIST issued a request for comment to solicit feedback. The agency posted the submissions after the comment period closed on Wednesday. The technology trade group CompTIA stressed the need for \u201clow-cost cloud-based cybersecurity training and assessment tools\u201d to reach workers who can\u2019t take traditional certification courses. \u201cImprovements are needed for the effectiveness and scalability of cybersecurity education,\u201d CompTIA wrote. \u201cScalability can be met through cloud-based cybersecurity training, but a problem exists. At this point in time, cloud-based solutions tend to be expensive.\u201d  The SANS Institute, a private training organization, highlighted the importance of \u201chands-on experience, not just classroom instruction of hypothetical situations.\u201d It was important, SANS said, to use a variety of educational approaches, \u201csince some concepts are regrettably dry and are unlikely to normally generate much interest or excitement from students.\u201d And the University of Texas at San Antonio, \u2014 which the NSA has designated as a \u201cNational Center of Academic Excellence\u201d \u2014 said NSA and National Science Foundation scholarship programs were crucial to growing the workforce. The scholarships have \u201chelped to introduce individuals who may not have previously considered a career in the security field to the many rewarding jobs that exist,\u201d the university wrote.   POSITIONS FILLED \u2014 The Senate on Thursday confirmed dozens of Trump administration nominees, including several who will be involved in cybersecurity policy. The confirmed picks include Susan Gordon, Trump\u2019s selection for principal deputy director of national intelligence. For the Department of Homeland Security, the Senate confirmed David Glawe as undersecretary for intelligence and analysis and Claire Grady as undersecretary for management. The Senate also confirmed a number of overseas-oriented nominees, including Kay Bailey Hutchison as U.S. representative to NATO and Nathan Sales to be the State Department\u2019s coordinator for counterterrorism.  BOBBY DIGITAL \u2014 The Senate on Thursday also passed a bill that would order a federal working group to study the security of internet-connected devices. Under the legislation (S. 88), known as the DIGIT Act, the working group would make recommendations to Congress after examining what the federal government could do to \u201cenhance the resiliency of Federal systems against cyber threats to the Internet of Things.\u201d The overall goal of the bill, sponsored by Sens. Deb Fischer, Cory Booker, Cory Gardner and Brian Schatz, is to foster innovation and collaboration between the private sector and industry on internet-connected devices. Another bipartisan group of senators this week also introduced legislation aimed at securing such devices.  OPM GETS A CHECK, NO CHECK-PLUS \u2014 The Office of Personnel Management has more digital cleanup work to do, despite the bevy of digital reforms the agency has made since the data breach that exposed over 20 million sensitive government background files, concluded a new government watchdog report. While OPM has enacted 11 of the recommendations the Homeland Security Department made in the wake of the unprecedented intrusion and has worked to implement eight more, the agency is falling short on four of them, the Government Accountability Office found in a report issued on Thursday. \u201cGenerally, the recommendations pertained to strengthening activities and controls related to passwords, access permissions, patches, audit and monitoring, among other things,\u201d the examination states. Auditors submitted an accompanying report about the sensitive topics to Congress. "Until OPM completes implementation of government-wide requirements, its systems are at greater risk than they need be," GAO officials wrote in the report.  OPERATION DUMBO DROP \u2014 WikiLeaks released another batch of documents Thursday that appear to illuminate the CIA\u2019s hacking tools, with the latest dunno revealing a method of hacking into security cameras and turning them off, code-named Dumbo. \u201cDumbo can identify, control and manipulate monitoring and detection systems on a target computer running the Microsoft Windows operating system,\u201d according to WikiLeaks\u2019 summary of the 2012 and 2015 documents. The idea is to protect CIA personnel who have to physically access a location. The hack requires a USB stick to activate.  RECENTLY ON PRO CYBERSECURITY \u2014 \u201cA 23-year-old British cybersecurity researcher who helped stop a recent global malware outbreak has been arrested for allegedly creating a different piece of notorious malware.\u201d \u2026 Trump blamed Congress for an \u201call-time\u201d and \u201cvery dangerous low\u201d state of U.S. relations with Russia. \u2026 A Russian botnet operator received a 46-month prison sentence. \u2026 \u201cSen. Ron Wyden is urging the country's spy chief to consider new approaches to providing insight on the number of Americans incidentally vacuumed up by surveillance programs slated to expire at the end of the year.\u201d  TWEET OF THE DAY \u2014 \u201cThe Wire,\u201d but in cyberspace.  QUICK BYTES  \u2014 WannaCry hackers are cashing out their bitcoin \u2026 Quartz.  \u2014 \u2026 at a dangerous moment. Gizmodo.  \u2014 The Homeland Security Department\u2019s new chief information officer is already leaving, according to FedScoop.  \u2014 The proposed Kaspersky Lab Pentagon ban could spell trouble elsewhere for the Russian antivirus company. National Journal.  \u2014 Cybersecurity specialists are among the hottest jobs in China. South China Morning Post.  \u2014 Baltimore Cyber Range: open. Baltimore Business Journal.  \u2014 McAfee on its latest connected car security research.  That\u2019s all for today. Let\u2019s see what you can do, Anthony Joshua.  Stay in touch with the whole team: Cory Bennett (cbennett@politico.com, @Cory_Bennett); Bryan Bender (bbender@politico.com, @BryanDBender); Eric Geller (egeller@politico.com, @ericgeller); Martin Matishak (mmatishak@politico.com, @martinmatishak) and Tim Starks (tstarks@politico.com, @timstarks).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
