aV \u000a            By TIM STARKS  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Eric Geller and Martin Matishak   WHAT\u2019S THAT, NOW? \u2014 President Donald Trump\u2019s statement on his signing of Russian sanctions legislation went further than anything the president has personally said aloud about the Kremlin\u2019s digital meddling in the 2016 election. In the statement, released after Trump signed the bill (H.R. 3364 (115)) into law on Wednesday, the president said he supported \u201cmaking clear that America will not tolerate interference in our democratic process, and that we will side with our allies and friends against Russian subversion and destabilization.\u201d At the White House press briefing, press secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders said that the statement was consistent with Trump\u2019s previous comments on 2016 meddling \u2014 that he thinks other countries \u201cmay have been involved as well, but he doesn't dispute the fact that Russia was.\u201d But even in recent months, Trump has cast doubt on the situation, accusing Democrats of creating a \u201cscam\u201d and \u201cHOAX!\u201d around the alleged Russian hack of the Democratic National Committee.   Story Continued Below  WHAT PEOPLE THINK OF TRUMP AND RUSSIA \u2014 In a new Quinnipiac University Poll out Wednesday, 30 percent of U.S. voters said they believe Trump did something illegal with Russia during the 2016 elections, and another 30 percent believe he did something unethical but not illegal. Another group, 32 percent, believes he did nothing wrong. Among the same group of voters, 58 percent believe Trump has tried to \u201cderail or obstruct\u201d the investigation into Russia\u2019s election-year meddling and possible collusion with the Trump camp. And 63 percent believe Russia interfered in the 2016 elections. The numbers skew heavily by party lines. For instance, 88 percent of Democrats believe Trump behaved illegally or unethically, while 70 percent of Republicans say he did neither. Overall, Trump\u2019s approval ratings hit new lows in the survey.   HAPPY THURSDAY and welcome to Morning Cybersecurity! Because each week feels like an eternity of news, why not just have an oral history of every single week? Send your thoughts, feedback and especially tips to tstarks@politico.com, and be sure to follow @timstarks, @POLITICOPro, and @MorningCybersec. Full team info below.  ANOTHER ONE BITES THE DUST \u2014 Trump\u2019s pick to lead the Office of Personnel Management, George Nesterczuk, withdrew from consideration for the post, the White House announced. \u201cI have decided to withdraw because the prospect of my favorable confirmation has grown remote,\u201d Nesterczuk wrote in a letter to Trump, first reported by GovExec. \u201cRecent partisan attacks threaten to delay further the consideration of my nomination. These attacks are intended to prevent me, or anyone, from carrying out government reforms that the American people and you, Mr. President, are rightly demanding.\u201d   HOYER: HANDS OFF ELECTION COMMISSION \u2014 The No. 2 Democrat in the House is warning his Republican colleagues not to cut off funding for the federal agency that helps states administer elections. Given Russia\u2019s attempts to influence the 2016 presidential election and the constant threat of cyberattacks on the country\u2019s voting infrastructure, \u201cabolishing\u201d the Election Assistance Commission \u201cwould be downright foolish,\u201d House Minority Whip Steny Hoyer wrote in an op-ed. The House budget blueprint for fiscal 2018 initially suggested zeroing out funding the bipartisan agency, with supporters of the move arguing the agency is outdated and that its primary functions are carried out by the FBI and the Homeland Security Department. Hoyer wrote that none of the GOP\u2019s arguments \u201chold water\u201d and called on appropriators to fix the \u201cerror\u201d and infuse the EAC with $9.2 million, as the Trump administration requested in its budget. \u201cWith adversaries intent on undermining Americans\u2019 faith in our voting systems, Congress ought to be providing the Election Assistance Commission with even greater resources to meet these new threats, not pulling the plug,\u201d he wrote. Hoyer pointed to the recent DEF CON hacker conference, where researchers broke into voting machines, as evidence of the flaws that could be exploited by more nefarious actors. \u201cWe must not allow that to happen,\u201d he said.   CYBER BILLS ADVANCE \u2014 Two Senate panels, Commerce and Small Business, approved cybersecurity legislation without a single \u201cno\u201d vote Wednesday. The Commerce Committee-approved bill would expand the National Science Foundation\u2019s CyberCorps: Scholarship-for-Service program, which helps cyber-focused students pay for their education in exchange for a guarantee of post-graduation government work. And the Small Business Committee-approved measure would direct small-business development centers that receive federal grants to certify that a certain percentage of their personnel can offer cyber assistance. Both committees approved the bills amid a slate of broader legislation. \u201cThis diverse package of common-sense legislation will give small businesses a boost in areas where they need it,\u201d said Small Business Chairman Jim Risch.   THEY GROW UP SO FAST \u2014 A government-funded malware analysis program has left the research lab and become a startup company. REnigma, which records the activities of malware on a system so incident response teams can rewind its execution and study its code, began life at Johns Hopkins University as part of the Department of Homeland Security\u2019s Transition to Practice program, or TTP, which aims to turn leading research ideas into commercial products. On Wednesday, DHS announced that REnigma had left TTP and become part of the Oregon-based startup firm Deterministic Security. Nadia Carlsten, TTP\u2019s program manager, said REnigma\u2019s success reflected DHS\u2019s work funding tools that \u201ccan be applied to critical cybersecurity problems and developed into solutions that will help secure our nation\u2019s public and private networks.\u201d   SPYWARE SAGA CONTINUES DOWN SOUTH \u2014 Mexico\u2019s ongoing surveillance scandal grew on Wednesday after internet watchdog Citizen Lab found that a pair of high-profile human rights attorneys were targeted with spyware after they investigated execution-style killings. According to researchers, the lawyers, Karla Micheel Salas and David Pena, had their cellphones targeted by messages designed to infect them with the same spyware, dubbed \u201cPegasus,\u201d that the University of Toronto-based research facility previously concluded was sent to almost 20 other individuals and groups in the country. Pegasus is a product of NSO Group, an Israeli firm that has been accused of selling its digital snooping tools to repressive regimes. \u201cA pattern has emerged in a subset of these cases: lawyers and investigators working on targeted killings in Mexico have been targeted with NSO Group\u2019s spyware when their investigations questioned official accounts provided by the authorities,\u201d Citizen Lab researchers wrote.   RECENTLY ON PRO CYBERSECURITY \u2014 The Homeland Security Department says two states and six local governments have askedfor election cybersecurity scans since January. \u2026 DHS employees have confidence in acting Secretary Elaine Duke, a spokesman said. \u2026 The White House said national security adviser H.R. McMaster fired intelligence operative Ezra Cohen-Watnick. \u2026 \u201cAnother federal judge has turned down a request to prevent President Donald Trump's voter fraud commission from going forward with plans to collect information on about 200 million American voters.\u201d   TWEET OF THE DAY \u2014 What can you even say about this?   QUICK BYTES  \u2014 Taxpayers for Common Sense has created a cyber spending database.  \u2014 Russian Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev criticized the Trump administration\u2019s \u201cweakness\u201d over sanctions legislation.  \u2014 The Drug Enforcement Administration met with the NSO Group, makers of smartphone malware. Motherboard.  \u2014 A recent global malware outbreak is still hitting corporate profits. Reuters.  \u2014 That HBO hack might have been a lot worse than reported. Variety.  \u2014 A Canadian spy agency said Russian hackers were \u201cmorons.\u201d The Intercept.  \u2014 Adobe\u2019s Flash Player might not be gone anytime soon. Krebs on Security.  \u2014 Hackers who took over a Welsh digital street sign poked at Trump. The Register.  That\u2019s all for today. \u201cI think Pickle broke me.\u201d  Stay in touch with the whole team: Cory Bennett (cbennett@politico.com, @Cory_Bennett); Bryan Bender (bbender@politico.com, @BryanDBender); Eric Geller (egeller@politico.com, @ericgeller); Martin Matishak (mmatishak@politico.com, @martinmatishak) and Tim Starks (tstarks@politico.com, @timstarks).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
