aV \u000a            By TIM STARKS  08/02/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Eric Geller and Martin Matishak   FRIENDSHIP IS MAGIC \u2014 The Senate is sticking around longer than planned to wrestle with some thorny, politically divisive topics, but cybersecurity is uniting two panels today in bipartisan harmony.  Story Continued Below  \u2014 Senate Commerce Committee: The panel will mark up legislation that would expand the National Science Foundation\u2019s CyberCorps: Scholarship-For-Service program \u2014 which helps cyber-focused students pay for education costs in exchange for a guarantee of post-graduation government work \u2014 to include community college students. Under the potential expansion, 5 percent of the scholarship funds would also be devoted to career changers and military veterans in two-year programs. Additionally, students could, in some cases, serve government-affiliated elements of critical infrastructure, like a public power utility. Democratic Sen. Tim Kaine, who is sponsoring the legislation with Republican Sen. Roger Wicker, said the measure \u201cwill expand the federal cybersecurity workforce and strengthen national security.\u201d  \u2014 Senate Small Business Committee: Although it was missing a final time or location late Tuesday, the committee\u2019s planned markup features a bill that would require small-business development centers that receive Small Business Administration grants to certify between 5 percent and 10 percent of its employees to provide cyber assistance. \u201cEntrepreneurs \u2014 particularly in rural areas \u2014 depend on online sales and marketing to commercialize their businesses, leaving them incredibly vulnerable to cyber risks,\u201d said Chairman Jim Risch, who is co-sponsoring the bill with Democratic Sen. Gary Peters. \u201cWith many small businesses unable to recover after suffering a cyberattack, it is incredibly important that we address this threat head on.\u201d   HAPPY WEDNESDAY and welcome to Morning Cybersecurity! Your MC host is a longtime hater hating on Michael Jordan\u2019s \u201cI could still beat so-and-so\u201d grumpiness/mania, but Lavar Ball is annoying enough that MJ\u2019s slams here don\u2019t bother me. Send your thoughts, feedback and especially tips to tstarks@politico.com, and be sure to follow @timstarks, @POLITICOPro, and @MorningCybersec. Full team info below.  IN THE WAY OF WRAY \u2014 The Senate voted 92-5 Tuesday to confirm Christopher Wray as director of the FBI, but at least one senator voted \u201cno\u201d because he worries Wray poses a threat to cybersecurity. \u201cIn his public and private statements, Chris Wray failed to oppose government backdoors into Americans\u2019 personal devices, or to acknowledge the facts about encryption \u2014 that it isn\u2019t about liberty versus security, it\u2019s about more security versus less security,\u201d Sen. Ron Wyden said. \u201cWhile I appreciate his willingness to continue studying the issue, other officials who have talked about finding common ground have turned around and sought to fatally undermine the cornerstone of Americans\u2019 cybersecurity.\u201d While top Trump administration officials have backed off from trying to push for legislation that would force tech firms to decrypt data upon request, it has still vowed to work with the tech sector to come up with a way that would guarantee government access to locked communications, a prospect that cybersecurity experts and civil liberty advocates like Wyden say would inevitably erode online security.   KITT BY COMMITTEE \u2014 Rep. Ryan Costello has a new bill that would create a new panel inside the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration to make cybersecurity recommendations for testing, deploying and updating automated vehicles. The proposed Automated Driving System Cybersecurity Advisory Council would be made of 15 to 30 members from across a wide variety of sectors, offering technical advice and developing a framework for identifying and implementing vehicle recalls. Costello\u2019s measure (H.R. 3411) has been referred to the House Committee on Energy and Commerce, on which he serves.   CYBER DIPLOMACY AT AN 'INFLECTION POINT' \u2014 The Trump administration must not abandon U.S. leadership on international cyber diplomacy by diluting the work of the State Department\u2019s cyber office. That was the implicit message of the first public statement Tuesday from Christopher Painter, who left State at the end of July after serving for six years as the agency\u2019s first coordinator for cyber issues. Painter led countless U.S. delegations to other countries and international organizations, where he promoted the American view on issues like the protection of critical infrastructure, the prevention of cyber crime and the applicability of international law to cyberspace \u2014 all efforts that cyber policy watchers say have been vital to promoting global norms in the Wild West of the digital realm. \u201cI believe we are at an inflection point, where the work we do now and the choices we make will determine whether we can all continue to benefit from this amazing technology, or whether both growing policy and technical threats will undermine its incredible potential,\u201d Painter wrote in a Medium post. \u201cDiplomacy has and must continue to play a pivotal role \u2014 shaping the environment, building cooperation, and working to build coalitions to respond to shared threats, and we must continue to lead the international community.\u201d  Secretary of State Rex Tillerson reportedly plans to downsize Painter\u2019s old office, merge it into the economic bureau and downgrade the rank of the coordinator, who currently reports directly to the secretary. Painter did not directly address these plans in his post, but he appeared to take aim at a common argument in favor of merging the cyber office with a larger bureau: that its current setup as a \u201cspecial envoy\u201d office leaves it stranded in Foggy Bottom\u2019s vast bureaucracy. \u201cFar from being divorced from the expertise and resources of any single bureau at State,\u201d Painter wrote, \u201cwe have tapped into and used the expertise of every regional and functional bureau \u2014 each bringing their own unique perspective and experience \u2014 on a wide range of issues across the entire Department. In turn, we have been a resource for each of their growing cyber efforts.\u201d   STILL WAITING \u2014 The U.S. and China have yet to meet to discuss cyber issues during the Trump administration, Tillerson said Tuesday. Following President Donald Trump and Chinese President Xi Jinping\u2019s Mar-a-Lago meeting in April, the two countries established the U.S.-China Comprehensive Dialogue, which Tillerson described at the time as a \u201chigh-level framework for negotiations\u201d on thorny policy issues. Two of those issues is cybersecurity and law enforcement. But during a State Department briefing on Tuesday, Tillerson said that the two sides had yet to meet to discuss either cyber or law enforcement issues.  Digital security experts are closely watching how Trump handles cyber discussions with China, a longtime U.S. adversary that he frequently bashed during the campaign. Former President Barack Obama used the threat of economic sanctions to convince Xi to sign a landmark bilateral agreement prohibiting corporate cyber theft for domestic economic gain, and most experts say China has taken steps to comply with the agreement. Speaking to reporters, Tillerson said the new China dialogues had \u201cserved us well to this point.\u201d   TROOPS\u2019 INFO POSSIBLY EXPOSED \u2014 A veterans group is suing the Defense Department for potentially exposing the personal information of millions of former and current service members. The federal lawsuit by the Vietnam Veterans of America accuses the department of poor oversight of its Servicemembers Civil Relief Act website, which allows visitors \u2014 without any restrictions \u2014 to search through an individual\u2019s service records by providing a last name and either a Social Security number or birthdate. The suit \u2014 filed by the Civil Liberties and Transparency Clinic of the University at Buffalo School of Law \u2014 accuses DoD officials of violating the federal Privacy Act, the Federal Information Security Modernization Act and other industry best practices for personal information. It seeks $1,000 in damages for Thomas Barden, a retired Air Force master sergeant and a party in the lawsuit who says online scammers used the site to gain his trust and convince him to purchase fraudulent computer security software.   AS IF TAXES WEREN\u2019T ENOUGH OF A HEADACHE \u2014 The IRS wants tax professionals to watch out for ransomware attacks that could cripple their operations and disrupt the smooth reporting and collection of state and federal taxes. The IRS on Tuesday released the latest alert in its 10-week \u201cDon\u2019t Take the Bait\u201d cybersecurity awareness campaign, warning tax preparers not to click suspicious links, not to enable macros \u2014 a popular automated task feature \u2014 on downloaded Microsoft Office documents and not to pay ransoms if they get infected. The agency said it was \u201caware of a handful of tax practitioners who have been victimized by ransomware attacks,\u201d and it pointed to an FBI alert about how ransomware campaigns \u201care a growing and evolving crime.\u201d \u201cWe urge people to take the time to understand these threats and take the steps to protect themselves,\u201d said IRS Commissioner John Koskinen in a statement.   RECENTLY ON PRO CYBERSECURITY \u2014 The Government Accountability Office found both pros and cons to separating U.S. Cyber Command from NSA. \u2026 A bipartisan group of senators introduced legislation that would impose minimum security standards on internet-connected device manufacturers who want to become government contractors. \u2026 A Pew Research Center poll found that cybersecurity ranked third among global concerns.   TWEET OF THE DAY \u2014 There might be hope for Congress yet!   PEOPLE ON THE MOVE  \u2014 Christian Borggreen is taking the title of vice president at the Computer and Communications Industry Association, and will be the new head of office for CCIA Europe. Borggreen previously served as director of international policy for the Brussels office, and before that as a policy adviser to the U.S. Mission to the European Union, focusing on digital policy issues.   QUICK BYTES  \u2014 A Spanish court recommended extraditing a Russian computer programmer \u2014 accused of developing malware to steal financial institution information \u2014 to the United States. Associated Press.  \u2014 North Korean hackers went after Hillary Clinton\u2019s presidential campaign, according to CyberScoop.  \u2014 Apple CEO Tim Cook explained why his company pulled major VPN apps from China. TechCrunch.  \u2014 \u201cA court said CareFirst Inc. customers can proceed with a lawsuit they've filed against the Owings Mills, Md., insurer over a 2014 data breach that affected more than 1 million members.\u201d Washington Business Journal.  \u2014 Older Amazon Echoes can be hacked to record your \u201cmost intimate moments.\u201d Ars Technica.  \u2014 The NSA spied on Megaupload founder Kim Dotcom via illegally used technology, Dotcom alleged, citing New Zealand\u2019s Government Communications Security Bureau. New Zealand Herald.  \u2014 FireEye had better-than-expected quarterly revenue. Reuters.  That\u2019s all for today. The enemy of my enemy is my friend.  Stay in touch with the whole team: Cory Bennett (cbennett@politico.com, @Cory_Bennett); Bryan Bender (bbender@politico.com, @BryanDBender); Eric Geller (egeller@politico.com, @ericgeller); Martin Matishak (mmatishak@politico.com, @martinmatishak) and Tim Starks (tstarks@politico.com, @timstarks).  \u000a                                            By Joh