aV \u000a            By TIM STARKS  07/31/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Eric Geller, Martin Matishak and Andrew Hanna  FLIPPING THE SCRIPT \u2014 President Donald Trump\u2019s shock announcement that Homeland Security Secretary John Kelly would take over as his chief of staff, effective today, could do harm to DHS\u2019s cybersecurity mission, former department officials told your MC host for a story for Pros (with help from Cory and Eric). And they aren\u2019t alone in that opinion. Given the growing nature of the digital threat, \u201cDHS needs to be leading a full scale and comprehensive effort to protect our critical infrastructure as well as our election related and voter registration systems,\u201d John Cohen, a former acting undersecretary at DHS, told MC. \u201cChanging leadership now \u2014 especially at a time when there are so many senior leadership vacancies at the department \u2014 is highly disconcerting.\u201d  Story Continued Below  But it\u2019s not all bad. For one, Elaine Duke, the deputy secretary turned acting secretary, is highly regarded. \u201cDHS is fortunate to have an extremely competent deputy secretary,\u201d Bruce McConnell, a former DHS deputy undersecretary for cybersecurity, told MC. \u201cI expect DHS cyber won't miss a beat.\u201d And while Trump this month made two key widely-commended cybersecurity appointments at the department, DHS still has some major openings atop the National Protection and Programs Directorate, the main cyber wing at Homeland. \u201cThey have not yet named a cyber undersecretary, so that allows the next person to really put a stamp on the organization,\u201d James Norton, a former DHS deputy assistant secretary, told MC. It doesn\u2019t look like the NPPD undersecretary job will go to Kelly\u2019s DHS chief of staff Kirstjen Nielsen, the subject of on and off rumors as a leading candidate. She\u2019s expected to join Kelly in the White House.  So who\u2019s going to be the next DHS secretary? Speculation has veered toward House Homeland Security Chairman Mike McCaul, Kansas Secretary of State Kris Kobach, acting Immigration and Customs Enforcement Director Thomas Homan and Attorney General Jeff Sessions. McCaul is the most experienced cybersecurity hand among the group, but he faced opposition for the DHS job prior to Kelly\u2019s appointment from some conservatives who considered him weak on border security. Notably, over the weekend, McCaul introduced a border security bill that backs up key elements of Trump\u2019s plans.  HAPPY MONDAY and welcome to Morning Cybersecurity! [Game of Thrones commentary ahead] Euron Greyjoy may not win the game of thrones, but he sure is winning most episodes of the show. Send your thoughts, feedback and especially tips to tstarks@politico.com, and be sure to follow @timstarks, @POLITICOPro, and @MorningCybersec. Full team info below.  CYBER TRAINING, SCHOLARSHIPS ON SENATE AGENDA \u2014 Senate lawmakers will mark up bills this week aimed at boosting cyber skills among small businesses and expanding the cyber workforce more broadly. On Wednesday, the Small Business Committee will consider legislation that would require workers at small business development centers to be certified in cyber training, and the Commerce Committee will consider a bill to expand cyber scholarships to people pursuing associate\u2019s degrees. The scholarships bill would also create a National Science Foundation study on the success of the cyber scholarship recruiting program. Scholarships for young cyber professionals have emerged as a key tool to fill what experts say is an alarming and growing workforce shortage. Rep. Jim Langevin, co-chair of the Congressional Cybersecurity Caucus, recently introduced an amendment to the 2018 Pentagon funding bill that would add money to DoD\u2019s own cyber scholarship initiative.  NO OTHER CHOICE \u2014 President Trump will sign a sanctions bill targeting Russia, Iran and North Korea, the White House announced over the weekend, even as his administration remains concerned that it unwisely ties his hands in negotiations with foreign adversaries. Trump \u201cread early drafts of the bill and negotiated regarding critical elements of it,\u201d the White House claimed in a statement. \u201cHe has now reviewed the final version and, based on its responsiveness to his negotiations, approves the bill and intends to sign it.\u201d The Senate late last week passed the House-approved bill (H.R. 3364) by an overwhelming 98-2 vote. The measure cleared the House 419-3, meaning Congress would likely have overridden any Trump veto of the legislation.  The veto-proof margins in both chambers were seen as a rebuke of Trump\u2019s desire to improve relations with Russian President Vladimir Putin, but the administration tried to put a positive spin on the bill. The margins \u201crepresent the strong will of the American people to see Russia take steps to improve relations with the United States,\u201d Secretary of State Rex Tillerson said in a statement. \u201cWe hope that there will be cooperation between our two countries on major global issues and these sanctions will no longer be necessary.\u201d Tillerson, who had previously expressed reservations about the bill, promised that the Trump administration would \u201cwork closely with our friends and Allies to ensure our messages to Russia, Iran, and North Korea are clearly understood.\u201d  THIS AGAIN? \u2014 Trump may be willing to impose further sanctions on Russia, but he remains convinced that the Kremlin sought to aid his opponent, not him, in the 2016 presidential campaign. \u201cRussia was against Trump in the 2016 Election,\u201d he tweeted over the weekend, citing a Fox News article, \u201cand why not, I want strong military & low oil prices. Witch Hunt!\u201d The Fox story cited Senate testimony by Bill Browder, a financier and longtime Kremlin adversary. Browder claimed that the opposition research firm Fusion GPS \u2014 which commissioned ex-MI6 agent Christopher Steele to prepare the salacious and largely unverified Trump dossier \u2014 also worked for the Russian government \u201cin a smear campaign\u201d against Browder aimed at fighting U.S. sanctions. Trump\u2019s tweet, and the Fox story which he retweeted, implied a connection between Fusion GPS\u2019s work on the dossier and its separate work for the Kremlin.  The president\u2019s tweet marked the latest break between the commander-in-chief and the intelligence community he oversees regarding Russia\u2019s 2016 intentions. In a landmark assessment that Trump\u2019s top intelligence chiefs have said they support, the CIA, the FBI, the NSA and the Office of the Director of National Intelligence concluded that the Kremlin\u2019s cyberattacks on the 2016 election were aimed at undermining Hillary Clinton and, eventually, helping Trump get elected.  KASPERSKY IN THE SPOTLIGHT \u2014 Congressional fears about the reach of Moscow-based cybersecurity firm Kaspersky Lab are rising. Late last week, House Science Chairman Lamar Smith asked 22 federal agencies whether their computer networks rely on software from the popular Russian antivirus giant, which some lawmakers worry is cozy with the Kremlin. \u201cThe committee is concerned that Kaspersky Lab is susceptible to manipulation by the Russian government, and that its products could be used as a tool for espionage, sabotage or other nefarious activities against the United States," Smith wrote in a letter sent Thursday.   Meanwhile, with the Senate expected to soon turn to its version of the annual defense policy bill, Sen. Jeanne Shaheen has submitted an amendment that would expand her proposed Pentagon ban on Kaspersky products to cover the entire federal government. According to the provision\u2019s text, \u201cNo department, agency, organization, or other element\u201d of the U.S. government may use \u201cany hardware, software, or services developed or provided, in whole or in part\u201d by Kaspersky. And what does Eugene Kaspersky, CEO of the firm, think of all this scrutiny? He gave an interview where he vehemently denied his company has any ties to Russian intelligence.  DEFICIENCY STATUS: UNCORRECTED \u2014 From 2014 to 2017, overseas State Department inspector general reports repeated 18 different cybersecurity assessment recommendations, meaning the gaps went unfixed, according to an IG report released late last week. \u201cThese recommendations addressed weaknesses in information systems security officer programs, incomplete and untested IT contingency plans, noncompliant dedicated internet networks, and various physical, technical, and administrative cyber security control weaknesses,\u201d the report states. The report suggests that the Bureau of Diplomatic Security join forces with the Bureau of Information Resources Management and regional bureaus to develop a system for tracking how overseas posts comply with cybersecurity assessment recommendations.  SWEDEN MAKES CYBER HISTORY \u2014 A massive government data breach in Sweden has toppled two cabinet officials, perhaps the highest-ranking dismissals to ever result from a government cybersecurity incident. Two ministers resigned after a Swedish Transport Agency breach, exposing reams of highly-sensitive data in Eastern European countries. The reshuffling was seen as a bid by Prime Minister Stefan Lfven to avert new elections amid calls for his own resignation. \u201cI have to take responsibility for the country,\u201d he said late last week. \u201cIt wouldn\u2019t serve Sweden to throw the country into a political crisis.\u201d Comparatively, the largest U.S. government data breach led to the ouster of the head of the Office of Personnel Management.  TALLIN-TED \u2014 Vice President Mike Pence is visiting cyber-focused Estonia, and our POLITICO colleague Andrew Hanna exploredwhy the tiny nation has outsized influence in the United States. Among the reasons: \u201cIts skill in combating Russian cyber and intelligence operations. Russia targeted Tallinn with a huge cyberattack in 2007, targeting its parliament, banks, broadcasters and newspapers following a dispute with Moscow over the relocation of a Soviet war memorial. Since then, Estonia has bolstered its cyber defenses and know-how,\u201d he wrote. \u201cThe country is home to a NATO cyber center and hosts an annual cyber war game called \u2018Locked Shields,\u2019 which U.S. European Command participated in last year.\u201d  In fact, the Estonian government announced a new cyber defense exercise late last week, bringing together European Union defense ministers this September. The exercise, called EU CYBRID 2017, will be conducted in partnership with the European Defense Agency in Tallinn. \u201cThere are no borders between countries or organisations on the Internet, and when it comes to countering threats on the internet, barriers between European Union and NATO cooperation must be reduced,\u201d Estonian Minister of Defence Jri Luik said in a statement. The exercise aims to prepare governments to deal with the aftermath of cyberattack. EU defense ministers will gather in Tallinn for an informal meeting from Sept. 6 to 8, when the exercise will take place.  RECENTLY ON PRO CYBERSECURITY \u2014 Hackers descended on Las Vegas to expose voting machine flaws \u2026 Russian President Vladimir Putin ordered a 755-person cut in the U.S. diplomatic staff in Russia in retaliation for pending U.S. sanctions against his country \u2026 Rep. Adam Schiff\u2019s frequent TV appearances bother GOP members of the House Intelligence Committee the wrong way \u2026 Democrats members of the House Intelligence panel want President Trump to fill vacant slots on a critical privacy board \u2026 Rep. Terri Sewell introduced a pair of bills aimed at strengthening the cybersecurity of future state and federal campaigns \u2026 The so-called EU-U.S. Privacy Shield could be headed to court.  TWEET OF THE DAY \u2014 We\u2019d rather imagine almost anything else, thanks.  QUICK BYTES  \u2014 \u201cThe U.S. government\u2019s counter intelligence investigation into the so-called Shadow Brokers group is currently focused on identifying a disgruntled, former U.S. intelligence community insider, multiple people familiar with the matter told CyberScoop.\u201d  \u2014 Merck said a prominent malware campaign affected its revenue projections. Financial Times.  \u2014 A British hacker received a sentence from a German court for his role in knocking out the internet for Deutsche Telekom customers. Reuters.  \u2014 Apple removed major VPN apps from the Chinese app store. TechCrunch.  \u2014 Hacked car wash attacks car. Motherboard.  That\u2019s all for today.  Stay in touch with the whole team: Cory Bennett (cbennett@politico.com, @Cory_Bennett); Bryan Bender (bbender@politico.com, @BryanDBender); Eric Geller (egeller@politico.com, @ericgeller); Martin Matishak (mmatishak@politico.com, @martinmatishak) and Tim Starks (tstarks@politico.com, @timstarks).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
