aV \u000a            By TIM STARKS  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Eric Geller, Martin Matishak and Li Zhou  LAWMAKERS \u2018MEH\u2019 ON NSA-CYBER COMMAND SPLIT \u2014 House and Senate lawmakers are shrugging off reports that the Trump administration is closing in on a plan to separate the NSA from U.S. Cyber Command, saying, essentially, they\u2019ll believe it when they see it, Martin reports. \u201cIt would help the debate if they sent something up, because then we could look at their proposal,\u201d according to Sen. Jack Reed, the top Democrat on the Senate Armed Services Committee. Splitting the two agencies has been a topic of debate since Cyber Command was established in 2009, but has gained momentum in recent years as the Pentagon\u2019s stepped up its digital operations against threats around the globe.  Story Continued Below  \u201cI\u2019m open to it,\u201d said Florida Rep. Tom Rooney, who chairs the House Intelligence Committee\u2019s NSA and Cybersecurity subpanel. \u201cI\u2019m never a big fan of expanding bureaucracy, but we do have to do a better job with cybersecurity. And if splitting it off and ... having its own focus makes that better, then of course I would be interested in it.\u201d Lawmakers already used last year\u2019s annual defense policy bill \u2014 the National Defense Authorization Act \u2014 to legislatively mandate that the Pentagon elevate Cyber Command, putting it on equal footing with other combatant commands that oversee military operations in Europe, Africa and the Pacific. But the same measure also set up a number of conditions that must be met before any full NSA-Cyber Command split can occur, leading to a sense of caution on both sides of the aisle. A split \u201cmay happen some day,\u201d said Rep. Jim Langevin, the top Democrat on the House Armed Services emerging threats subcommittee. \u201cThey are not there yet. I\u2019m not ready to support such a move.\u201d  Questions about the fate of the two organizations is a positive thing, said John Schindler, a former NSA senior analyst. \u201cIf we don\u2019t do this very carefully, you\u2019re going to create a bigger furball than we have now,\u201d he said. But if lawmakers \u201cdo this slowly and patiently and understand this is a multi-year \u2014 not a one or two fiscal year project \u2014 this can be OK.\u201d Pros can read the full story here.  HAPPY FRIDAY and welcome to Morning Cybersecurity! Science is just too cool sometimes. Send your thoughts, feedback and especially tips to tstarks@politico.com, and be sure to follow @timstarks, @POLITICOPro, and @MorningCybersec. Full team info below.  TEACH A MAN NOT TO BE PHISHED \u2014 The federal government should encourage internet of things manufacturers to educate the public about ways to prevent their devices from being taken over by hackers, a leading cyber policy group said today. \u201cContextual customer notification may enable consumers to respond in the event their device is infected by malware,\u201d said the Coalition for Cybersecurity Policy and Law in comments filed with the National Telecommunications and Information Administration. \u201cNotifying consumers that their devices are infected by malware may not help consumers if they do not have the tools to remove the malware or are not able to distinguish between authentic notifications and fraudulent ones.\u201d  NTIA is leading a multistakeholder process to study ways to improve the security of the internet of things, and the cyber policy coalition\u2019s filing comes in response to an NTIA request for comment. The coalition said the Commerce Department, which houses NTIA, could help companies keep customers informed \u201cby bringing industry participants together to develop guidance for companies that choose to provide such notice to their customers.\u201d   SECOND TIME\u2019S THE CHARM \u2014 The House today is expected to take up, for the second time, its version of the annual intelligence authorization bill. Democrats successfully scuttled the measure earlier this week to protest it being brought to the floor under suspension of the rules, an expedited process without amendments that requires a two-thirds majority. This time the bill is coming to the chamber via a \u201cclosed rule,\u201d a procedural maneuver that bans amendments, unless they\u2019re recommended by the committee reporting the bill.   As for the measure itself, it directs the director of national intelligence to produce a report on past and present Russian plots to tamper with elections and would require that the DNI produce a publicly available report on foreign cyber threats to U.S. elections. Another part of the legislation would request an intelligence community report on the viability of a voluntary cyber exchange program between spy agencies and private companies, while another provision would direct the intelligence community\u2019s inspector general to produce a report on spy agencies\u2019 roles in the process of disclosing to tech companies the vulnerabilities that the government unearths.   MUCH-NEEDED BOOST \u2014 The Senate Appropriations Committee on Thursday approved a bill that would increase funding for Senate cybersecurity training and defenses. The 2018 fiscal year legislative branch funding bill \u201cprovides for investments in Senate cybersecurity capabilities and training to senators and their staff,\u201d the committee said in a statement. The bill adds money to the Senators\u2019 Official Personnel and Office Expense Account \u201cto support the increasing costs related to providing cybersecurity protections for senators\u2019 offices.\u201d Senators have focused more on their own offices\u2019 digital defenses in recent years as hackers have exploited weaknesses to breach numerous government agencies. In April, Sen. Ron Wyden pressed the Senate Rules and Administration Committee to mandate two-factor authentication for all congressional IT systems.   TICK TOCK \u2014 The State Department has yet to submit a required report on cybersecurity vulnerabilities related to its email policies that was due more than a month ago. Buried in the government funding bill that became law on May 5 is a provision requiring the State Department to report on changes to its email policies. One section of the report must address the department\u2019s efforts to \u201cstrengthen cybersecurity measures to mitigate vulnerabilities, including those resulting from the use of personal email accounts or servers outside the .gov domain,\u201d a nod to the Hillary Clinton private email server scandal. The report was due on June 19 to the congressional appropriations committees and to the National Archives and Records Administration \u2014 which oversees records retention policies \u2014 but the State Department has yet to submit it. \u201cWe have been working diligently to meet this requirement,\u201d a department official told MC. \u201cThe department is aware of the requirement and we will be forwarding a report to the requesting committees as soon as possible.\u201d   EYE ON THE SKY \u2014 The Transportation Department\u2019s inspector general said Thursday that it was initiating an audit, requested by lawmakers, of cybersecurity at the FAA. \u201cCyber-based threats \u2014 from both internal and external sources \u2014 are rapidly evolving and could threaten the connectivity of a complex aviation infrastructure,\u201d Matthew Hampton, assistant inspector general for aviation audits, wrote in a memo. \u201cFurthermore, FAA\u2019s current modernization efforts increasingly rely on integrated information systems, distribution of information, and satellite-based technologies,\u201d he added, referring to the FAA\u2019s transition to NextGen programs. \u201cAs a result, may put the air-traffic control system at greater risk for compromise.\u201d The audit stems from a request by leaders of the House Transportation Committee to determine how the FAA was complying with cybersecurity requirements from a 2016 law. The aviation industry has become an increasing target for hackers, and the FAA itself has been dinged by government watchdogs for poor cybersecurity practices.   GAO GETS GOING \u2014 The Government Accountability Office dropped a number of cybersecurity-related reports on Thursday. One determined that the SEC hasn\u2019t fully implemented 11 information security recommendations. A second report found that the Defense Department needs to take additional steps to secure internet-connected devices. And a third concluded that federal agencies aren\u2019t doing enough to reduce the use of Social Security numbers. Rep. Steve Chabot is also concerned about the number of State Department telecom device and software manufacturers identified by the GAO as having Chinese-headquartered suppliers.   HOUSE ELECTION SECURITY GROUP KICKS OFF \u2014 The House Democratic election security task force got its first informational briefing on Thursday. The Brennan Center spoke with the task force about its report, \u201cSecuring Elections From Foreign Interference,\u201d which focuses on hacking vulnerabilities in voting machines and voter registration databases. \u201cThe Brennan Center\u2019s expertise on election issues will lend us to our first public meeting in the coming weeks where we will hear from officials and experts with diverse backgrounds,\u201d said Reps. Bennie Thompson and Robert Brady, the task force\u2019s co-chairs. \u201cThis will be the first step towards forming solutions to protect our democracy and its cherished institutions from malicious actors and outside influence.\u201d   NEW ICPA BILL COMING \u2014 Per our friends at Morning Tech: Hot on the heels of the Electronic Communications Privacy Act reintroduction from Sens. Mike Lee and Patrick Leahy, Sens. Orrin Hatch, Chris Coons and Dean Heller are due to announce the return of the International Communications Privacy Act, according to a Hill aide. ICPA would provide a legal framework for U.S. law enforcement agencies to obtain electronic communication records of U.S. citizens that are stored overseas, which would include the use of a warrant. Google, BSA | The Software Alliance and SIIA are among those that have voiced their support for the return of the bill.    \u2014 Speaking of ECPA: Lee and Leahy on Thursday unveiled a new version of ECPA, which would require law enforcement to obtain a warrant for Americans\u2019 emails that are more than 180 days old. It would also create a warrant standard for tracking location information, including on cell phones. A previous version of the legislation got bogged down in the Senate last term, after Sen. John Cornyn added amendments that appeared to give the FBI more leeway for surveillance. Lee also introduced a companion to the House\u2019s Email Privacy Act. A range for groups, from BSA to the Consumer Technology Association and the Center for Democracy and Technology, quickly embraced the bill. Read the new version of ECPA here.   RECENTLY ON PRO CYBERSECURITY \u2014 \u201cThe Senate on Thursday delivered Donald Trump the first big bipartisan rebuke of his presidency, giving final approval to a package of sanctions on Russia, Iran, and North Korea that constrains his bid to defrost relations with Moscow.\u201d ... The Senate Intelligence Committee-approved 2018 fiscal year spy agency policy bill includes language meant to strengthen digital threat information sharing with election officials. \u2026 Federal and state officials agreed to the outline of a partnership for protecting the election system from hackers, according to the Election Assistance Commission. \u2026 New White House lawyer Ty Cobb thinks \u201cvery highly\u201d of special counsel Bob Mueller. \u2026 Russians reportedly tried to spy on Emmanuel Macron via Facebook during his candidacy for president. \u2026 \u201cAttorney General Jeff Sessions said he stood by his recusal from the federal probe into Russian election meddling and potential ties to the Trump campaign, despite President Donald Trump\u2019s repeated public rebukes of the move.\u201d  TWEET OF THE DAY \u2014 \u201cYou know the network access rules, and so do I\u2026\u201d   QUICK BYTES  \u2014 A South Korean report concludes that North Korea\u2019s cyber army is splitting up and stealing funds. The Wall Street Journal.    \u2014 Iranian hackers are using photographs of attractive women as lures. SecureWorks.    \u2014 Researchers determined that half of all kids\u2019 apps failed to protect data. The Washington Post.  \u2014 \u201cPutin derides sanctions and Trump investigations as \u2018boorishness.\u2019\u201d The New York Times.  \u2014 Trump\u2019s election commission renewed its request for state voter data and promised to keep it safe. The Washington Post.  \u2014 Sessions\u2019 remarks about the dark web spurred investors toward dark net intel firms. CyberScoop.  \u2014 A Naval War College assistant professor writes about lessons from war gaming for cyber defenses of critical infrastructure. War on the Rocks.  \u2014 Microsoft is amping up its bug bounties. The Verge.  \u2014 Android Security is taking steps to block a new spyware family.  \u2014 Access Now launched a campaign to convince the Blackstone Group not to buy a share in the NSO Group over its surveillance software. Reuters.   That\u2019s all for today. I mean, really: \u201cNearly half of the atoms that make up our bodies may have formed beyond the Milky Way and traveled to the solar system on intergalactic winds driven by giant exploding stars, astronomers claim.\u201d  Stay in touch with the whole team: Cory Bennett (cbennett@politico.com, @Cory_Bennett); Bryan Bender (bbender@politico.com, @BryanDBender); Eric Geller (egeller@politico.com, @ericgeller); Martin Matishak (mmatishak@politico.com, @martinmatishak) and Tim Starks (tstarks@politico.com, @timstarks).  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a   