aV \u000a            By TIM STARKS  07/27/2017 10:00 AM EDT  \u000a                    Updated 07/27/2017 10:08 AM EDT  With help from Eric Geller and Martin Matishak  REPLY HAZY, TRY AGAIN \u2014 What once appeared to be a sure thing \u2014 easy, bipartisan, bicameral legislation issuing new sanctions against Russia, partly motivated by its digital interference in the 2016 elections \u2014 now appears to have averted some minor jeopardy, although its fate beyond Congress is uncertain. One of the bill\u2019s leading original authors, Senate Foreign Relations Chairman Bob Corker, was temporarily balking at the last-minute decision in the House to add North Korea sanctions to the measure, which also included new penalties on Iran. \u201cWhat likely will happen is we will strip out the North Korea piece and send it back to them so that the two pieces that we\u2019ve negotiated together will remain intact,\u201d Corker said, noting that the Senate never got a chance to carefully negotiate the North Korea language the way it did on Iran and Russia. Late Wednesday, Corker announced that the North Korea language would be removed, with the Senate likely to later take up separate Pyongyang sanctions legislation from the House.  Story Continued Below  The White House was remaining noncommittal until it sees the final bill, said spokeswoman Sarah Huckabee Sanders. \u201cSen. Corker actually came out earlier today and said that he's not fully supportive of where the bill stands,\u201d she said at her briefing Wednesday. \u201cWe expect that there's a possibility that more changes take place. And so we're going to see what that looks like before we make a final decision.\u201d Overall, she said, \u201cI can tell you that the White House, the president, and the entire administration \u2014 as we've said many times before \u2014 strongly support sanctions against Russia, Iran and North Korea.\u201d  Other countries are developing heartburn over the U.S. legislation. Russia, naturally, isn\u2019t pleased, and vaguely raised the possibility of retaliation, while warning the bill (H.R. 3364) would do harm to international cooperation with the United States. The European Union is also vaguely threatening retaliation out of concern that the sanctions could have a negative impact on European corporations, although sources told our POLITICO Europe colleagues that recent changes to the bill have assuaged some of those concerns.   HAPPY THURSDAY and welcome to Morning Cybersecurity! Make no mistake. This will not get in the way of my forthcoming Super Mario Kart reign of terror. Send your thoughts, feedback and especially tips to tstarks@politico.com, and be sure to follow @timstarks, @POLITICOPro, and @MorningCybersec. Full team info below.  VEP, CISA \u2014 The House Homeland Security Committee on Wednesday approved a bill that would require the Homeland Security Department to produce a report on how the agency determines whether to disclose software vulnerabilities. The bill (H.R. 3202), sponsored by Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, seeks to shed light on the secretive Vulnerability Equities Process, amid a spree of leaks about purported vulnerabilities the government has hoarded. \u201cBecause vulnerabilities can be used by adversaries, it is important that the sensitive information is managed securely and the details are guarded against premature disclosure,\u201d Jackson Lee said. But, she added, the government must also work on \u201csolutions\u201d to the vulnerabilities it finds. The panel also approved legislation (H.R. 3359) renaming and elevating DHS\u2019s primary cyber wing, the National Protection and Programs Directorate. It would become the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency. The committee approved both bills by voice vote.   DHS BUYING BILLS CLEAR COMMITTEE \u2014 The Senate Homeland Security Committee on Wednesday easily approved two bills altering how the Homeland Security Department makes major purchases, which could affect future cybersecurity acquisition programs. The first measure would create a new review board to oversee the DHS acquisition process. The second bipartisan proposal would require DHS to notify Congress when one of the agency\u2019s buying efforts breaches its contract by failing to meet cost, schedule or performance benchmarks. Both bills were approved by voice vote.   WEDNESDAY NIGHT DOJ NEWS \u2014 \u201cA grand jury in the Northern District of California has indicted a Russian national and an organization he allegedly operated, BTC-e, for operating an unlicensed money service business, money laundering, and related crimes,\u201d the Justice Department announced Wednesday about indicted suspect Alexander Vinnik. \u201cThe indictment alleges that he received funds from the infamous computer intrusion or \u2018hack\u2019 of Mt. Gox \u2014 an earlier digital currency exchange that eventually failed, in part due to losses attributable to hacking.\u201d  GET ON THIS \u2014 The IRS has much more work to do to fix serious cybersecurity vulnerabilities and improve security policies, according to the Government Accountability Office. In a report released on Wednesday, GAO found that, while the IRS improved its security controls based on earlier recommendations, it still fell short in key areas. Among the problems that GAO identified: the IRS didn\u2019t consistently implement user authentication requirements; users had more permissions than they needed; some agency systems did not use the strongest possible encryption; and the agency failed to implement some of its auditing procedures, including logging who accessed certain databases. The IRS, according to GAO, is \u201cexposing financial and sensitive taxpayer information to unnecessary risk of unauthorized access, use, disclosure and modification.\u201d In a departure from standard agency responses to GAO reports, the IRS \u201cneither agreed nor disagreed\u201d with GAO\u2019s recommendations and maintained that its systems were secure.  The GAO\u2019s cybersecurity concerns about the IRS could come at an opportune time for the Treasury Department. In Senate testimony on Wednesday, Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin pressed Congress on the importance of the department\u2019s security upgrade program, which locates and fixes vulnerabilities in critical systems. The Trump administration has asked for \u2014 and the House Appropriations Committee has already approved \u2014 $27 million for the program, known as the Cybersecurity Enhancement Account. Last year\u2019s Treasury budget, however, funded the program at a much higher level, $48 million.   SWEDISH LEADERS COULD LOSE JOB OVER BREACH \u2014 Sweden\u2019s opposition party is trying to oust three government leaders they say are responsible for major data security mistakes that exposed sensitive information on the Swedish population. The move came after Swedish officials paid IBM\u2019s local division $100 million to manage vehicle registration and driver\u2019s license databases, but failed to implement proper safeguards, according to a New York Times story. As a result, IBM subsidiaries in Eastern Europe had unauthorized access to \u201cdetails about bridges, roads, ports, the subway system in Stockholm and other infrastructure,\u201d the Times reported.  Swedish Prime MInister Stefan Lofven said the breach was \u201cincredibly serious\u201d and \u201cput Sweden and its citizens in harm\u2019s way.\u201d The database contains information about undercover Swedish police and schedules for the movement of armored vans transporting valuables. The head of Sweden\u2019s transportation agency was fired and fined $8,500 for sidestepping privacy laws in setting up the contract, and the new agency chief estimated that it would take until the fall to repair the damage.   RECENTLY ON PRO CYBERSECURITY \u2014 A Facebook official said the company will donate $500,000 to a project to protect the American electoral system from cyberattacks \u2026 Partisan tempers flared on the House Intelligence Committee after Jared Kushner\u2019s testimony \u2026 Members of the Senate Judiciary Committee expressed bipartisan alarm over Russia\u2019s attempt to influence U.S. politics. \u2026 Despite days of badgering tweets, the White House insisted Trump wants Attorney General Jeff Sessions to stay on.   TWEET OF THE DAY \u2014 No firewall can keep out Fancy Bird.   PEOPLE ON THE MOVE  \u2014 Andrew Grotto, who served as senior director for cybersecurity policy at the National Security Council from late 2015 until May of this year, is joining Stanford University\u2019s Center for International Security and Cooperation. He\u2019ll be a fellow in the Stanford Cyber Initiative and research fellow at the Hoover Institute. During his time in the Trump administration, he was a driving force behind the White House\u2019s cybersecurity executive order. His past experience also includes serving as technology adviser to then-Commerce Secretary Penny Pritzker and as the lead cybersecurity staffer for then-Senate Intelligence Chairwoman Dianne Feinstein.   QUICK BYTES  \u2014 \u201cThe Trump administration's refusal to publicly accuse Russia and others in a wave of politically motivated hacking attacks is creating a policy vacuum that security experts fear will encourage more cyber warfare.\u201d Reuters.  \u2014 Hacker tools vulnerable to hackers. Motherboard.  \u2014 Ukrainian cyberattack victims were reluctant to disclose their damage to investigators. BBC.  \u2014 Kushner downloaded the private messaging app Signal. Splinter.  \u2014 Part 1: The State Department\u2019s cyber coordinator office is necessary. Slate.  \u2014 Part 2: Nah, not in this administration. Council on Foreign Relations.  That\u2019s all for today. Here we go. I\u2019m No. 1.  Stay in touch with the whole team: Cory Bennett (cbennett@politico.com, @Cory_Bennett); Bryan Bender (bbender@politico.com, @BryanDBender); Eric Geller (egeller@politico.com, @ericgeller); Martin Matishak (mmatishak@politico.com, @martinmatishak) and Tim Starks (tstarks@politico.com, @timstarks).  CORRECTION:  A previous version misidentified the DHS's primary cyber wing. It will be called the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency.  Tim Starks has written about cybersecurity since 2003, when he began at Congressional Quarterly as a homeland security reporter. While at CQ Roll Call, he mainly covered intelligence, but he also had stretches as a foreign policy reporter and defense reporter. In 2009, he won the National Press Club's Sandy Hume Memorial Award for Excellence in Political Journalism.  He left CQ Roll Call in March of 2015. Before coming to Politico he spent several months freelancing, writing for the Economist, the New Republic, Foreign Policy, Vice, Bloomberg and the Guardian.  He grew up in Evansville, Ind. and graduated from the University of Southern Indiana with a degree in print journalism. His first full-time reporting job was covering city hall for the Evansville Press, the former afternoon daily. He was a Pulliam Fellow at the Indianapolis Star, and participated in the Politics and Journalism Semester at the chain of newspapers anchored by the Las Vegas Review-Journal. He also was the Statehouse Bureau Chief at the Evansville Courier & Press and established the Washington bureau of the New York Sun. Some of his other freelance work has been for the Chicago Tribune, Glamour, Deutsche Welle, Ring and BookForum.  He is the founder of The Queensberry Rules, dubbed an "indispensable boxing blog" by the Wall Street Journal. He's also fond of fantasy basketball and real-life basketball \u2014 he is from Indiana, after all \u2014 and gets way too bent out of shape over people rooting against the home team or not walking on the right side of the sidewalk.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                           