aV \u000a            By TIM STARKS  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Eric Geller and Martin Matishak  EVERYWHERE, BUT NOT ALWAYS UP \u2014 The House this week begins floor consideration of a series of fiscal 2018 spending packages, and a search through the House Appropriations Committee\u2019s bill reports finds cybersecurity in every bill but one. But, as your MC host determined, that doesn\u2019t always translate to spending increases, as the GOP-controlled Congress wrestles with budget pressures. Overall, concluded the story for Pros, big cybersecurity hubs like the Defense and Homeland Security departments trended toward increases, while departments with smaller cyber footprints would often see decreases in their cyber funding.  Story Continued Below  The bill reports also give a sense of appropriators\u2019 policy priorities. For instance, the Financial Services and General Government report notes that while appropriators are \u201caware\u201d of legislative efforts to upgrade aging federal information technology programs, the bill allocates no money (yet) for the most prominent bill that would do so, the House-passed Modernizing Government Technology Act (H.R. 2227). The reports also sometimes reflect how cybersecurity has infiltrated less-expected corners of the federal government, with the Military Construction and Veterans Affairs bill report noting that since U.S. Cyber Command and others moved into the NSA campus at Fort Meade, parking has become a major headache. More for Pros here.   ANOTHER RUSSIA AMENDMENT BID, AMID SANCTIONS VOTE \u2014 Democrats are trying to throw Russia-related amendments at one of the House spending packages (H.R. 3219) due on the floor this week. Rep. Brendan Boyle proposed amendments to two different sections of the bill to prohibit the United States from sharing sensitive cybersecurity information with Russia, although one Republican, Rep. Leonard Lance, offered a similar amendment, too. Reps. Bill Pascrell and Anthony Brown offered amendments preventing the administration from returning compounds to Russia that President Barack Obama vacated in response to alleged Russian election interference. Not all of the proposed cybersecurity amendments are Russia-related, however: Reps. Jim Langevin and Marc Veasey want to add $10 million to a Defense Department cyber scholarship program. The amendment bid comes as the House is set to vote today on Senate-passed Russia sanctions legislation that is expected to be approved with broad bipartisan support.   HAPPY TUESDAY and welcome to Morning Cybersecurity! Apparently someone at the Cavs thinks there are never enough defenseless, aging point guards for one team. Send your thoughts, feedback and especially tips to tstarks@politico.com, and be sure to follow @timstarks, @POLITICOPro, and @MorningCybersec. Full team info below.  INTEL PUSH FAILS AMID RUSSIA PROBES \u2014 House Democrats scuttled an initial attempt to move the annual intelligence authorization bill Monday night, with lawmakers defeating the measure in a 241-163 vote. On Sunday, House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi blasted Republicans for their plan to bring the bipartisan legislation to the floor under suspension of the rules, an expedited process without amendments that requires a two-thirds majority. The move is \u201cunacceptable when critical intelligence decisions are being made that impact America's national security, and while the House and Senate Intelligence Committees are leading investigations into Russia's continued efforts to undermine our democracy,\u201d she wrote in a letter to her colleagues. The argument apparently worked. \u201cOn its merits, I believe the [intelligence policy bill] should and will become law," said Rep. Adam Schiff of California, the ranking Democrat on the House Intelligence Committee, said on the chamber floor. But he added that the bill \u201cshould go through regular order so that members may offer amendments.\u201d   RUSSIAN HACKERS TOO GOOD, PUTIN TELLS TRUMP \u2014 Trump has recently taken to saying Russian hackers are too smart to be detected, casting doubt on their culpability for the Democratic National Committee hack \u2014 an idea he reportedly got from Russia\u2019s president directly. After meeting with Vladimir Putin two weeks ago in Germany, according to The New York Times, Trump \u201cemerged to tell his aides that the Russian president had offered a compelling rejoinder: Moscow\u2019s cyber operators are so good at covert computer-network operations that if they had dipped into the Democratic National Committee\u2019s systems, they would not have been caught.\u201d It\u2019s a \u201claughable\u201d notion, according to cyber experts, and contradicts even his hand-picked intelligence and national security leaders, who say Russia was behind the election season attacks.   SOMEONE HAS TO DO SOMETHING \u2014 The Trump administration must work harder to ensure that law enforcement agencies can access suspects\u2019 data when it is stored abroad, according to a leading technology think tank. \u201cExisting legal processes and treaties are woefully out of date and needlessly complex. Countries have mismatched legal assistance treaties, conflicting laws, and differing norms,\u201d the Information Technology and Innovation Foundation said in a report released Monday. Cross-border data access has become a thorn in the side of American investigators, and the Justice Department is currently entangled in multiple lawsuits over its use of the Stored Communications Act to demand user information stored on overseas servers. ITIF said its report offered \u201ca path forward\u201d for U.S. policymakers to press other countries over access to foreign-stored data. \u201cSettling questions of jurisdiction over data will require global reforms,\u201d the report\u2019s authors wrote. \u201cHowever, the United States can and should lead the way on these reforms.\u201d   SOME 702 DOCS \u2014 Documents obtained this month by the American Civil Liberties Union via a Freedom of Information Act request detail numerous \u201ccompliance incidents\u201d related to how the NSA implements its procedures under Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act, a controversial surveillance program due to expire at year\u2019s end. The incidents include misuse of procedures for when the NSA destroys incidentally collected domestic communications, when it collects more information than it is supposed to and how it documents why it has targeted an individual. \u201cAmericans should be alarmed that the NSA is vacuuming up their emails and phone calls without a warrant,\u201d said Patrick Toomey, staff attorney for the ACLU\u2019s national security project. \u201cThe NSA claims it has rules to protect our privacy, but it turns out those rules are weak, full of loopholes, and violated again and again. It is time for Congress to embrace significant reforms that rein in this spying and give Americans the privacy protections they deserve.\u201d   A PEEK UNDER THE HOOD \u2014 The United States must be more transparent about its offensive cyber capabilities and its willingness to use them if it wants to deter cyberattacks and promote discussion of international norms, according to a former senior Pentagon official. \u201cBeing clear about U.S. capabilities would be a first step towards a more informed dialogue with the American people about the role they will and will not play in U.S. foreign policy,\u201d wrote Michael Sulmeyer, the former director of cyber policy plans and operations in the Office of the Secretary of Defense, in a blog post for the Council on Foreign Relations. When it comes to deterrence, he argued, \u201cthe problem is not the lack of definitions, but a lack of consensus about what bad conduct in cyberspace really needs to be stopped.\u201d Sulmeyer, now the director of the Cyber Security Project at Harvard\u2019s Kennedy School of Government, also said the U.S. needed to have \u201ca more holistic conversation\u201d about cyber defense. \u201cThe U.S. defensive posture against cyberattacks,\u201d he wrote, \u201cis often comparable to a man leaving money on his lawn overnight and being outraged the next morning to find it stolen.\u201d   RECENTLY ON PRO CYBERSECURITY \u2014 Christopher Krebs will serve as the Homeland Security Department\u2019s assistant secretary for infrastructure protection, a position expected to have a leading role in 2018 election security. \u2026 Trump\u2019s son-in-law and senior adviser Jared Kushner said he \u201cdid not collude\u201d with Russia during the 2016 elections, on the day he met with the Senate Intelligence Committee as part of its Russia probe. \u2026 House Intelligence Chairman Devin Nunes is expected to sit in on Kushner\u2019s session with his panel today, despite stepping aside from the Russia investigation. \u2026 Top Senate Judiciary Democrat Dianne Feinstein wants Attorney General Jeff Sessions to testify before the panel over a reported meeting with Russia\u2019s ambassador during the campaign where they discussed policy issues. \u2026 Trump continues to humiliate Sessions and might replace him.   A federal judge rejected a demand from the Electronic Privacy Information Center for Trump\u2019s election commission to conducta privacy assessment before gathering state voter data. \u2026 \u201cThe U.S. and Japan agreed during a meeting late last week to deepen their cybersecurity partnership on issues ranging from botnets to critical infrastructure, according to a joint statement.\u201d \u2026 The U.K. is pouring nearly $19 million into a cybersecurity innovation center.   TWEET OF THE DAY \u2014 Cyber nihilism!   QUICK BYTES  \u2014 A study found that 1 in 10 U.S. organizations were hit by the WannaCry bug. Security Week.  \u2014 A hacker admitted in court that he was responsible for an attack that knocked customers off German internet service provider Deutsche Telekom. Threatpost.  \u2014 \u201cJustice Dept. Nominee Says He Once Represented Russian Bank.\u201d The New York Times.  \u2014 John McAfee says there was an attempt on his life.  \u2014 Bobby Chesney writes for Lawfare about the legal and policy hurdles to separating NSA and Cyber command.  \u2014 Sweden\u2019s prime minister deemed \u201cunacceptable\u201d a cybersecurity mistake that made \u201ctop secret police databases available to foreign IT workers.\u201d The Local.  \u2014 The cyber arm of a U.K. spy agency was left without PGP encryption for months. The Register.  \u2014 \u201cHow Coders Hacked Back to \u2018Rescue\u2019 $208 Million in Ethereum.\u201d Motherboard.  That\u2019s all for today. Rose was really good for a while, though.  Stay in touch with the whole team: Cory Bennett (cbennett@politico.com, @Cory_Bennett); Bryan Bender (bbender@politico.com, @BryanDBender); Eric Geller (egeller@politico.com, @ericgeller); Martin Matishak (mmatishak@politico.com, @martinmatishak) and Tim Starks (tstarks@politico.com, @timstarks).  Tim Starks has written about cybersecurity since 2003, when he began at Congressional Quarterly as a homeland security reporter. While at CQ Roll Call, he mainly covered intelligence, but he also had stretches as a foreign policy reporter and defense reporter. In 2009, he won the National Press Club's Sandy Hume Memorial Award for Excellence in Political Journalism.  He left CQ Roll Call in March of 2015. Before coming to Politico he spent several months freelancing, writing for the Economist, the New Republic, Foreign Policy, Vice, Bloomberg and the Guardian.  He grew up in Evansville, Ind. and graduated from the University of Southern Indiana with a degree in print journalism. His first full-time reporting job was covering city hall for the Evansville Press, the former afternoon daily. He was a Pulliam Fellow at the Indianapolis Star, and participated in the Politics and Journalism Semester at the chain of newspapers anchored by the Las Vegas Review-Journal. He also was the Statehouse Bureau Chief at the Evansville Courier & Press and established the Washington bureau of the New York Sun. Some of his other freelance work has been for the Chicago Tribune, Glamour, Deutsche Welle, Ring and BookForum.  He is the founder of The Queensberry Rules, dubbed an "indispensable boxing blog" by the Wall Street Journal. He's also fond of fantasy basketball and real-life basketball \u2014 he is from Indiana, after all \u2014 and gets way too bent out of shape over people rooting against the home team or not walking on the right side of the sidewalk.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
