aV \u000a            By TIM STARKS  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Eric Geller and Martin Matishak  FOLLOW THE LEADER \u2014 The U.S. may have to follow European governments on encryption policy, the head of the Justice Department\u2019s national security division admitted over the weekend. \u201cThe terrorism challenges in Europe are really kind of tough, and they may lead the way and carry some of our water on this,\u201d said Acting Assistant Attorney General for National Security Dana Boente at the Aspen Security Forum in Aspen, Colo., over the weekend. \u201cWe\u2019ll have to see how that goes,\u201d he added during a panel on balancing security and liberty issues.   Story Continued Below  The Trump administration has pressed tech companies to come up with a method that let law enforcement access encrypted communications, but has withheld from pushing for a legislative mandate. European countries such as the United Kingdom, on the other hand, have moved to implement laws that force tech companies to hand over locked data. \u201cIf enough countries do that,\u201d Boente said, \u201cI\u2019m sure we\u2019ll find some technological brilliance that will provide the necessary security but still allow the government to do it.\u201d His comments represent the bluntest admission by a senior Trump administration official that Europe, which has been rocked by several deadly terrorist attacks in the past two years, is racing ahead of the United States to propose, debate and enact laws targeting locked data.  Boente denied seeking a \u201cbackdoor\u201d into encrypted products and services like Apple\u2019s iPhone, saying he only wanted to ensure that investigators could execute court-approved search warrants. \u201cTo say that we can\u2019t have a system that is secure [in which], with appropriate judicial oversight, [communications are] provided to the government in a criminal investigation \u2014 I just don\u2019t accept that narrative,\u201d he said. Security experts, though, describe any guaranteed-access scheme as creating vulnerabilities that hackers could exploit. But Boente noted that American technology companies would soon have to meet the European demands to hand over encrypted communications. \u201cWhen you have a number of large countries with large market shares that are going to require this, I think you\u2019ll find a change,\u201d he said.  Elsewhere at Aspen, current and former intelligence officials bluntly and obliquely criticized President Donald Trump\u2019s approach to cybersecurity issues, including:  \u2014 THAT RUSSIAN CYBER PARTNERSHIP: NSA Director Adm. Mike Rogers offered a veiled rebuke of his boss when asked what he thought of Trump\u2019s proposal to establish a cybersecurity partnership with the Russian government. \u201cNow is probably not the best time to be doing this,\u201d Rogers said during a panel where he and his British counterpart discussed security threats. Trump proposed and quickly walked back the idea shortly after his G-20 meeting with Russian President Vladimir Putin, but both Trump\u2019s homeland security adviser and a Russian official later said they were still interested in some form of dialogue. Rogers, who in addition to leading the NSA also oversees the military\u2019s cyber warfare unit, said a cyber partnership with Russia was \u201csomething that you might want to build over time\u201d if the Trump administration saw \u201cchanges in [Russia\u2019s] behavior.\u201d  \u2014 DISRESPECTING THE PROS: Trump\u2019s disparaging of the intelligence community and his continuing unwillingness to accept its Russian meddling conclusion are \u201cdisgraceful,\u201d former CIA Director John Brennan said at the conference. Brennan and former Director of National Intelligence James Clapper offered withering criticism of Trump for claiming that the intelligence community\u2019s Russia findings were politically motivated and that career staffers were part of a \u201cDeep State\u201d campaign to undermine his presidency. \u201cI was particularly distressed by, when in a foreign country Poland, he\u2019s disparaging his own intelligence community, which, to me, put him at a great disadvantage in the run up to the meeting with President Putin,\u201d said Clapper. Added Brennan: \u201cThese types of comments are just disgraceful, never should have happened and the person who said that should be ashamed of themselves.\u201d  HAPPY MONDAY and welcome to Morning Cybersecurity! Your MC host is joining Team Euron. Yeah, he\u2019s corny and I still think he dresses silly, but at least he\u2019s got a certain entertaining maniac quality. Send your thoughts, feedback and especially tips to tstarks@politico.com, and be sure to follow @timstarks, @POLITICOPro, and @MorningCybersec. Full team info below.  TRUMP STILL NOT SOLD ON RUSSIAN HACKING \u2014 Trump still doesn\u2019t accept the intelligence community's conclusion that Russia attempted to influence the 2016 election, according to his newly-installed White House communications director. \u201cHe basically said to me, \u2018Hey you know, this is, maybe they did it, maybe they didn't do it,\u2019\u201d Anthony Scaramucci said during an interview on CNN\u2019s \u201cState of the Union.\u201d The president\u2019s seemingly ingrained position contradicts that of his national security team. \u201cThere\u2019s a pretty clear and easy answer to this and it\u2019s 'yes,'\u201d White House homeland security adviser Thomas Bossert said just a few days ago when asked if Moscow tried to manipulate the election. Scaramucci said the president views the media\u2019s drumbeat of Russia election-meddling coverage as an attack on Trump\u2019s November win. \u201cThe mainstream media position on this, that they interfered in the election, it actually, in his mind, \u2018What are you guys suggesting? You are going to delegitimize his victory?\u2019\u201d he said.  RUSSIA SANCTIONS LEGISLATION DUE THIS WEEK \u2014 \u201cNegotiators in both parties on Saturday released a sweeping sanctions deal that does not include changes President Donald Trump's administration sought to make it easier for him to ease penalties against Russia,\u201d our POLITICO colleagues Elana Schor and Heather Caygle report. \u201cThe accord on a package of sanctions against Russia, Iran and North Korea is set for a House vote on Tuesday, according to the announcement from Majority Leader Kevin McCarthy's office. To resolve a partisan clash over giving House Democrats the power to force a vote blocking Trump from easing sanctions on Moscow, the deal expedites House consideration of any anti-Trump vote that the Senate has already passed.\u201d It\u2019s expected to pass by a broad bipartisan vote. Trump is reportedly now prepared to accept the bill.  ALSO THIS WEEK: THE NEW CISA \u2014 The House Homeland Security Committee is set this week to mark up legislation that would reorganize DHS\u2019s main cybersecurity wing. The draft legislation, sponsored by Chairman Mikel McCaul, would rename the National Protection and Programs Directorate as the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, elevating it from a headquarters component. Outgoing DHS officials who worked under President Barack Obama repeatedly identified the idea as the top thing Congress could do to bolster cybersecurity efforts at the department. The Wednesday markup also includes on its calendar a bill (H.R. 3202 (115)), sponsored by Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, that would require a DHS report on the federal government\u2019s procedures for disclosing software vulnerabilities it discovers.  ALSO ALSO THIS WEEK: GAO REPORT, COMMITTEE HEARINGS \u2014 Rep. Steve Chabot said late last week that a cyber-focused Government Accountability Office report critical of the State Department was coming down the pike. \u201cNext week, the GAO will release a report about suppliers to State Department\u2019s critical telecommunications infrastructure that will raise serious concerns about the security of foreign-purchased equipment,\u201d he said. \u201cIn light of the report, I will be making substantial recommendations to the State Department to strengthen its cybersecurity to help protect our national security.\u201d Chabot, chairman of the House Small Business Committee, is also holding a hearing of his panel Wednesday on cybersecurity insurance and how it can help protect small business.  Also Wednesday, the House Foreign Affairs Committee will hold a hearing on cyber diplomacy, featuring the State Department\u2019s outgoing cybersecurity coordinator, Christopher Painter. The week also brings three noteworthy committee meetings on Russia and election interference. The Senate Intelligence Committee is slated today to meet behind closed doors with Jared Kushner, Trump\u2019s son-in-law and a top adviser, and the House Intelligence panel will meet with Kushner the next day. Meanwhile, the Senate Judiciary Committee will hold its own hearing on election interference Wednesday. Donald Trump Jr. and former Trump campaign manager Paul Manafort are listed as witnesses, but panel leaders said they wouldn\u2019t appear at Wednesday\u2019s hearing after reaching an agreement to cooperate with the committee.  WHAT WE LEARNED \u2014 The technical standards agency NIST\u2019s cybersecurity framework has emerged as a key tool for promoting international cyber standards, according to an agency report published late last week. The report summarized what NIST learned from a May 16-17 workshop at its Gaithersburg, Md., headquarters, where industry, academia and government converged to discuss the framework\u2019s applicability to vulnerability disclosure, corporate governance, cyber insurance and the international environment.   \u201cMany private sector organizations engage foreign governments to encourage their consideration of the Framework or publication of complementary national frameworks,\u201d the agency said. \u201cNIST will continue reinforcing those private sector discussions with government-to-government dialogue.\u201d The agency also said in the report that it was expanding its focus on federal agencies\u2019 use of the framework, which is now a requirement under President Trump\u2019s cyber executive order.   WHY NOT US? \u2014 The Federal Trade Commission launched a series of cybersecurity blog posts late last week, with the inaugural edition focusing on why the FTC doesn\u2019t always pursue data breach cases. The commission said it takes into account whether a company took strong steps to protect information and whether the situation involved significant loss of sensitive information. It also considered whether other agencies have primary jurisdiction for specific circumstances. The blog post series emerges from industry demands that the FTC supply more guidance on when it decides to go after companies over digital intrusions. \u201cBusinesses have asked us to keep the guidance coming, which is why we\u2019re announcing a new initiative, Stick with Security,\u201d the agency said. Expect a new blog post every Friday for the next few months, according to the FTC.  CRACKDOWN ON INTERNET SERVICES \u2014 China and Russia are both stepping up their game against virtual private network, or VPN, software that allows people to circumvent their internet censorship systems, though for very different reasons. Beijing\u2019s actions are part of an effort to update its digital Great Firewall, a term used to describe the set of internet restrictions China imposes within its borders. Dozens of China-based VPN providers have already been shut down and some located overseas have experienced cyberattacks. Russia\u2019s parliament, meanwhile, outlawed VPN services in what they claim is bid to combat the spread of extremist material online. The measure still has to be approved by parliament\u2019s upper chamber and signed by Russian President Vladimir Putin before it can go into effect.  RECENTLY ON PRO CYBERSECURITY \u2014 The top Democrats on the House and Senate Intelligence committees are warning Trump against pardoning former campaign aides under investigation for alleged ties to Moscow. \u2026 A top Obama administration official defended how the former president responded to election interference. \u2026 Some Republicans are tying Russia to environmental groups, citing hacked documents as part of their evidence.  TWEET OF THE DAY \u2014 It never hurts to have another big-league set of eyes on the problem.  QUICK BYTES  \u2014 Microsoft is going after Russian hackers in court. The Daily Beast.  \u2014 Sen. Ron Wyden scolded the FCC over not providing an analysis of an alleged malware attack, with the agency saying in a Freedom of Information Act request that it has no such records. Ars Technica.  \u2014 Local governments are using Russia-based Kaspersky Lab products despite the recent federal action. The Washington Post.  \u2014 The Senate Judiciary Committee subpoenaed a co-founder of the company that produced that controversial Trump dossier. The Hill.  \u2014 Former Obama national security adviser Susan Rice met with the Senate Intelligence Committee as part of its Russia probe. CNN.  That\u2019s all for today. Just saying. Dat entrance tho.  Stay in touch with the whole team: Cory Bennett (cbennett@politico.com, @Cory_Bennett); Bryan Bender (bbender@politico.com, @BryanDBender); Eric Geller (egeller@politico.com, @ericgeller); Martin Matishak (mmatishak@politico.com, @martinmatishak) and Tim Starks (tstarks@politico.com, @timstarks).  Tim Starks has written about cybersecurity since 2003, when he began at Congressional Quarterly as a homeland security reporter. While at CQ Roll Call, he mainly covered intelligence, but he also had stretches as a foreign policy reporter and defense reporter. In 2009, he won the National Press Club's Sandy Hume Memorial Award for Excellence in Political Journalism.  He left CQ Roll Call in March of 2015. Before coming to Politico he spent several months freelancing, writing for the Economist, the New Republic, Foreign Policy, Vice, Bloomberg and the Guardian.  He grew up in Evansville, Ind. and graduated from the University of Southern Indiana with a degree in print journalism. His first full-time reporting job was covering city hall for the Evansville Press, the former afternoon daily. He was a Pulliam Fellow at the Indianapolis Star, and participated in the Politics and Journalism Semester at the chain of newspapers anchored by the Las Vegas Review-Journal. He also was the Statehouse Bureau Chief at the Evansville Courier & Press and established the Washington bureau of the New York Sun. Some of his other freelance work has been for the Chicago Tribune, Glamour, Deutsche Welle, Ring and BookForum.  He is the founder of The Queensberry Rules, dubbed an "indispensable boxing blog" by the Wall Street Journal. He's also fond of fantasy basketball and real-life basketball \u2014 he is from Indiana, after all \u2014 and gets way too bent out of shape over people rooting against the home team or not walking on the right side of the sidewalk.  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson  \u000a                                            By Kel McClanahan  \u000a                                            By Carrie Levine 
