aV \u000a            By DARIUS TAHIR  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from David Pittman (@David_Pittman) and Arthur Allen (@arthurallen202)  TRUMP AND VA UNVEIL TELEHEALTH INITIATVE: In an event at the Roosevelt Room Thursday, President Trump and VA Secretary David Shulkin promoted several new telehealth initiatives in the department:   Story Continued Below  \u2014 Big new reg: The most surprising for longtime readers is a new regulation allowing doctors to treat patients anywhere in the VA through telemedicine, regardless of location or state licensing laws. Shulkin called it "Anywhere to Anywhere VA Health Care."   Iowa Sen. Joni Ernst, Senate Veterans Affairs Chairman Johnny Isakson and others in Congress were pushing for the change through the VETS Act (S. 925 (115)). A patient in northwest Iowa\u2014 such as Ernst, herself a vet \u2014 couldn\u2019t see a doctor in nearby Omaha, Neb., for example, because of arcane licensing VA rules. But the legislation was opposed by the American Medical Association.   Shulkin, we\u2019re told by those close to the issue, pressed for change after taking over as secretary, after championing the cause while undersecretary for health. The VA drew upon the advice of the Justice Department to make sure it was on solid legal ground. The devil is in the details, since the regulation hasn\u2019t been published, but look for the text over the next couple of weeks.   Ernst was pleased with the announcement, as were groups pushing for changes in telemedicine licensing like the National Council of State Boards of Nursing. \u201cUnder the current law, VA-employed providers can practice in any state without needing to obtain additional licensure when delivering in-person care,\u201d the group wrote Shulkin last month. \u201cNCSBN supports extending that same license portability for VA-employed providers who deliver care via telehealth so long as they maintain a valid state license.\u201d  Read the VA\u2019s announcement of the plan here and watch the video of Shulkin and Trump here.   \u2014 And an app or two, too: Also announced was a new mobile app called VA Video Connect, making it easier for veterans to connect with providers by video on their phones or computers. There\u2019s also a nationwide rollout of an appointment scheduling app.  \u2014 Praise and a suggestion: The American Telemedicine Association was delighted by the licensure announcement, and encouraged the White House to go a step or two farther: \u201cWe encourage President Trump to issue an Executive Order to eliminate the state-by-state licensure model for all federal and private-sector health professional employees servicing federal government programs \u2014 notably agencies (such as the VA and the Department of Health and Human Services), health benefit programs (such as Medicare and TRICARE), federally-funded health sites (such as community health centers and rural clinics), and during federally-declared emergencies or disasters.\u201d  \u2014 Whether this would be legally possible is an interesting question.   Health IT Now also praised the decision; its director, Joel White, thanked \u201cPresident Trump and Secretary Shulkin for expediting this process.\u201d   \u2014 A little tidbit: Teladoc paid the law firm of Mehlman Castagnetti Rosen & Thomas $320,000 to lobby on issues \u2014 including telehealth expansion within the VA \u2014 from June 2015 until it dropped the issue from lobbying disclosure forms starting early this year. Could it see the VA was going to build its own system and not use a system like Teladoc\u2019s? The company didn\u2019t respond to our questions.   \u2014 From the White House event: Shulkin demonstrated the telemedicine technology to Trump during the White House event, patching him into a call with Albert Amescua, a 26-year Coast Guard veteran at a VA clinic in Grants Pass, Ore., and Brook Woods, a VA internist in Cleveland.   The Oregon clinicians attending to Amescua transmitted a photograph of his skin for Woods to review, although we didn\u2019t learn what Woods might have been looking for\u2026   \u201cI hope your skin is going to be in perfect shape,\u201d Trump said. \u201cLooks pretty good to me, but what do I know.\u201d Trump then instructed Watts to \u201cmake sure his skin is perfect.\u201d  eHealth tweet of the day: Donald J. Trump @realDonaldTrump Our GREAT VETERANS can now connect w/ their VA healthcare team from anywhere, using #VAVideoConnect - available at: http://mobile.va.gov/appstore .  FRIDAY: Your correspondent is gonna be biking to see sunflowers this weekend (possibly). How about you? Share weekend plans at dtahir@politico.com. Discuss sunflowers socially at @David_Pittman, @arthurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.  Pro subscribers: Are you getting all the content you want? Make sure your keywords are up to date and customized via your settings page at http://politico.pro/1iDALk9.  CONGRESS \u2014 NOMS NOMS NOMS (AND MORE): Congress went through a flurry of activity Thursday, which we\u2019ll helpfully recap for you:   \u2014 Nominees: Many, many nominees were confirmed for many, many positions. These included four HHS nominees (Lance Robertson, Assistant Secretary for Aging; Robert Kadlec, Assistant Secretary for Preparedness and Response; Elinore McCance-Katz for Assistant Secretary for Mental Health; Jerome Adams for Surgeon General); three FCC commissioners (Ajit Pai, Jessica Rosenworcel, Brendan Carr); and three VA nominees (Thomas Bowman, deputy secretary for Veterans Affairs; Brooks Tucker, assistant secretary of Veterans Affairs; and James Byrne, general counsel). Unclear if a partridge and a pear tree will get approval today. Morning eHealth is keeping an ear out for a voice vote to that effect.   \u2014 FDA user fees: The Senate approved the FDA user fee bill by a 94-1 margin, with Sen. Bernie Sanders voting against. The user fees are pretty big for digital health. The bill authorizes a new category of over-the-counter hearing aids, a victory for the bipartisan group of legislators \u2014 running the spectrum from Sen. Elizabeth Warren to Rep. Marsha Blackburn \u2014 who championed the measure.   The bill also gives new funding to a cadre of digital health employees. Given the agency\u2019s new digital health regulatory plan, those dollars could be quite important. \u201cThis measure will help ensure the agency has the funding needed to continue roll out of its Digital Health Innovation Action Plan and can set the stage for faster approval of health IT products, improved testing for preclinical innovation tools, and other reforms,\u201d said Joel White.   Finally, the funding will mean more dollars to the agency\u2019s surveillance programs, which rely on data from EHRs and claims forms.   \u2014 Jessie\u2019s Law: The Senate gave the thumbs-up \u2014 by unanimous consent \u2014 to Jessie\u2019s Law, which is intended to highlight patients\u2019 opioid addictions to doctors, so that they don\u2019t unwittingly contribute to an overdose. The bill directs HHS to come up with \u201cbest practices\u201d on the subject. There were some privacy concerns from Sen. Rand Paul, but they were solved.   \u201cWe didn\u2019t want to mess with HIPAA laws. We didn\u2019t want to violate any of that. We just thought there was a better way,\u201d Sen. Joe Manchin told POLITICO.   Despite passage, those supporting the change called it only a \u201cgood first step.\u201d  Manchin says he\u2019ll introduce legislation soon that will give substance abuse records the same level of protection as HIPAA provides. Today, patients must sign off on such doctors viewing those records. Jessie\u2019s law must still pass the House, but next-step legislation is already being touted by Rep. Tim Murphy, who has already authored such a bill (H.R. 3545 (115)).  \u2014 Behavioral health bill: Sens. Sheldon Whitehouse and Rob Portman introduced a bill Thursday for behavioral health providers seeking EHRs. The bill targets psychiatric hospitals, community behavioral health centers, residential and outpatient mental health and substance use treatment facilities, as well as clinical psychologists and social workers, and would get them EHRs through a CMS Innovation Center demonstration project.   FCC VOTES: The FCC unanimously approved three rural broadband items \u2014 one on a public notice for an auction of $2 billion over 10 years for providers interested in hard-to-service areas; the second an order helping to sort out which areas will receive the commission\u2019s Mobility Service Fund (for wireless); and a third concerning broadband data collections. You can see the full hearing here.   ONC UNVEILS NEW TESTING TOOL INITIATIVE: ONC is putting the call out for privately developed testing tools for the certification process. In general, such tools serve as ways to ensure EHR output is consistent and accurate \u2014 say, that the clinical measures reporting tool gives the same data every time.   ONC is describing the initiative as a way to harness the best of the private sector. The private sector has made major investment in the tools and "we don't want to make double investments," Posnack said in an interview.  Private sector tests may in some instances be better than the public tools, Posnack said, adding that by making a call for such tools, he hoped to encourage the best to emerge.  \u2014 GAO announces its part of the Health IT Advisory Committee roster: The Government Accountability Office announced its appointments for the Health IT Advisory Committee. They are: Michael Adcock, of the University of Mississippi Medical Center; Christina Caraballo of Get Real Health; Tina Esposito of Advocate Health Care; Brad Gescheider of PatientsLikeMe; John Kansky of Indiana Health Information Exchange; Kensaku Kawamoto of University of Utah; Denni McColm of Citizens Memorial Healthcare; Brett Oliver of Baptist Health; Carolyn Petersen, of Mayo Clinic\u2019s website; Terrence O\u2019Malley, of Massachusetts General Hospital; Raj Ratwani, of MedStar Health; Sasha TerMaat, of Epic; Andrew Truscott, of Accenture; Sheryl Turney, of Anthem Blue Cross Blue Shield; and Denise Webb, of Marshield Clinic. You can see a full list of these individuals\u2019 accomplishments here. Congressional leaders have announced four members: Anil Jain, of IBM; Patrick Soon-Shiong, of NantWorks; Steve Ready, of Norton Healthcare; and Steven Ready, of Sutter Health.   APPLICATIONS: Ever wanted to apply to stuff? Morning eHealth lives to serve. Here are some applications you can fill out:  \u2014 Hardship exceptions: CMS rolled out its application for hardship exceptions to the Quality Payment Program. Apply here. Also, if you are a first-time participant in the EHR incentive program, and want a one-year reprieve from MIPS, you can apply here by Oct. 1.   \u2014 Precision medicine studies: If you have a cool study on precision medicine, Health Affairs is requesting abstracts for its May 2018 issue. Submissions are due Aug. 14; more information here.   NOTES ON TELEMEDICINE: A few notes on telemedicine to share:   \u2014 Teladoc earnings call: The telemedicine company held its second-quarter earnings call Thursday. Its CEO, Jason Gorevic, wasn\u2019t giddy about the prospects of Medicare reimbursement. \u201cI think I would call it a long, gradual march,\u201d he said. \u201cWe continue to see positive steps, sort of one bill at a time that chip away at the barriers to larger-scale telehealth adoption and reimbursement, but I haven\u2019t yet seen a silver bullet come through in something that I think is going to change the game over night.  \u2014 Willis Towers Watson survey: A survey by the consultancy regarding employers\u2019 health care plans shows continuing enthusiasm for telemedicine. 78 percent of the 555 employers who responded said they offered telemedicine, and 16 percent are planning or considering adding the benefit in 2018.   WHAT WE\u2019RE CLICKING:   Kansas City Star finds Express Scrips contributed $10,000 to Eric Greitens\u2019s inauguration. (Greitens, of course, gave the company a $250,000 no-bid contract for the PDMP.)   Speaking of no-bid contracts, here\u2019s an op-ed critiquing the VA\u2019s Cerner decision.   The Economist\u2019s 1843 Magazine considers the period app.   Trump administration to rethink data procurement (with the help of Apple, Qualcomm, et al.?)   Oscar hires \u201cchief clinical officer\u201d   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
