aV \u000a            By DARIUS TAHIR  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from David Pittman (@David_Pittman)  CONGRESS \u2014 TAKING CARE OF BUSINESS: Congress took care of some items on its to-do list Wednesday, with some other important items coming up this morning. To wit:   Story Continued Below  \u2014 NOMINEES ADVANCED: A slew of HHS nominees got the Senate HELP Committee\u2019s thumbs-up on Wednesday: Lance Robertson (Assistant Secretary for Aging), Brett Grior (Assistant Secretary for Health), Robert Kadlec (Assistant Secretary for Preparedness and Response), Elinore McCance-Katz (Assistant Secretary for Mental Health and Substance Use) and Jerome Adams (Surgeon General).   Separately, the Senate Commerce Committee gave its blessing to Ajit Pai, Jessica Rosenworcel, and Brendan Carr \u2014 all nominees for the FCC.  \u2014 Mental health data bill tweaked before Senate vote: HHS will establish \u201cbest practices\u201d for sharing patients\u2019 opioid addiction histories rather than create a standard for them appearing in EHRs, according to the updated bill provided to POLITICO. A vote on the bill is expected by the full Senate. Jessie\u2019s Law, named after a woman who overdosed after being prescribed oxycodone by a doctor who didn't know she was once addicted to painkillers, is expected to pass the Senate as a stand-alone bill with the FDA user fee bill.   The original bill, first introduced last April and then refiled in March by West Virginia Sen. Joe Manchin, would direct HHS to create a standard that would display patients\u2019 opioid addiction history in electronic medical records. The updated bill has HHS \u201destablish best practices\u201d for sharing information about a patient\u2019s past opioid addiction, when that information is shared by the patient with his or her healthcare provider. Advocates of the change wanted to make it easier for doctors to know when a person with an addiction was sitting on the exam table before prescribing a drug that could cause a patient to relapse. The sharing of such information is currently barred by a 1970s-era law known as 42 CFR Part 2. A one-pager of the bill is here.   \u2014 Budget chair moving on? Tennessee Rep. Diane Black, a Republican often involved with a variety of health IT issues, announced she\u2019s running for governor Wednesday. The Republican primary is next August.   Black has been the lead sponsor of the CONNECT for Health Act (H.R. 2556 (115)), which would greatly expand telemedicine payments. She also pushed for relief from the ICD-10 coding update and helped gain exemption from meaningful use requirements for ambulatory surgical centers.   The Nashville Tennessean says Black is \u201cwidely considered a front-runner to an already-crowded Republican field.\u201d  \u2014 FDA vote today? Senate HELP Chairman Lamar Alexander signaled a vote on the FDA user fee bill might come today \u2014 a welcome turn of events for industry and FDA alike. There were jitters that Congress would be too slow to approve the uncontroversial (as it\u2019s turned out) user fee bill, and thereby deprive the agency of needed funds.   \u2014 Also today: The Senate Finance Committee will consider two HHS nominations: Matthew Bassett for Assistant Secretary of Health and Human Services, and Robert Charrow for HHS general counsel.   \u2014 Resolved: Sens. Roger Wicker and Brian Schatz introduced a resolution affirming support for 5G mobile broadband Wednesday.   KUSHNER ON VA: White House adviser Jared Kushner\u2019s pep talk to a swarm of Congressional interns got attention for the burning issues it contained \u2014 Israel-Palestine peace, for one example. But we at Morning eHealth, after taking a listen to the full audio (posted here by Wired), noted another interesting subject: the Cerner/VA deal.   Kushner explains that getting the deal done is \u201cone of the great successes we\u2019ve had so far\u201d in overhauling the department. Here\u2019s how, according to Kushner, the deal got done: He was \u201ctalking about the issue\u201d with David Shulkin, and they called Secretary of Defense James Mattis. Mattis and Shulkin convened the top five EHR guys from each department.   \u201cWe said, guys, we want a solution to get us on one system. This is absolutely crazy,\u201d Kushner said, and apparently, the group of EHR experts were given a deadline of two weeks to solve the problem. They managed to solve the whole thing in that time \u2014 when, by comparison, \u201cthey\u2019ve been holding Congressional hearings since 2000. Sixteen years and nothing\u2019s happened.\u201d  eHealth tweet of the day: Chinmay Singh @cagefreesingh [re: the Epic/Simon discussion on patient access to full medical records discussed in Wednesday\u2019s Morning eHealth] Faulkner is right. If laymen cd understand medical records then @Yelp reviews wd be full medical terms as opposed to "no one answers phone"[For a full perspective on that debate, we also enjoyed David Shaywitz\u2019s and Eric Topol\u2019s tweets on the subject.]  THURSDAY: Your correspondent fears he is getting old, as he has been complaining practically all week about a locked-up hip that twinges at odd moments. (All moments are odd moments, since again, your correspondent fears he is getting old. Such twinges were not present in his youth.) Why did this occur? This is the worst part: your correspondent doesn\u2019t really know, besides speculation about \u2014 and this sounds really quite lame \u2014 a kayaking jaunt. Tell your correspondent he\u2019s old at dtahir@politico.com. Tell your correspondent he\u2019s old on social media at @David_Pittman, @athurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.  BIG CMS RULE DROPS: CMS dropped its final hospital payments rule Wednesday evening. When it comes to health IT, it\u2019s just what the hospitals wanted: they\u2019ll only need to report over a 90-day period in 2018, as opposed to the entire year; and they won\u2019t have to do a full-bore switchover to 2015 certified EHRs for at least one more year.   Clinical quality measures reporting requirements will also be reduced. As is typical for final rules, the agency summarizes comments before discussing them. When it comes to clinical quality measures, we found this summary amusing: \u201cHospitals have had challenges with data mapping (aligning the information available in an electronic health record (EHR), particularly if the information is not located in a structured field (for example, PDF attachment, free text section) \u2026 \u201d   Or, to sum up: interoperability is hard and expensive. It\u2019s probably not surprising that the agency is still affirming its intention to reduce the quality reporting burden. It writes: \u201cOur goal for the future is to continue to align those quality measurement requirements and to adopt a more streamlined set of clinical quality measures \u2026 \u201d   Naturally, hospitals are pleased; the American Hospital Association specifically praised the \u201cagency allowing hospitals and critical access hospitals to report meaningful use modified Stage 2 in 2018, as well as implementation of a 90-day meaningful use reporting period in fiscal year 2018.\u201d   FIRST IN MORNING eHEALTH \u2014 VIRTA HEALTH SNAGS FORMER CMS HEAD FOR BOARD: Startup Virta Health \u2014 which is hoping to reverse patients\u2019 type 2 diabetes \u2014 announced today that it had snagged former CMS administrator Don Berwick to serve on its board of directors. The board also features luminaries like former Sen. Bob Kerrey, among a crew of prominent researchers and academics.   SUPERCOMPUTING: NIH got the second piece of a really fast computer Wednesday, the agency\u2019s prime contractor announced.   LAWSUIT STILL ON: A class action lawsuit regarding a 2014 data breach of CareFirst Inc. is still on, notes Business Insurance. At issue is whether the damages arising from a data breach are strictly hypothetical or likely to occur.   WHAT WE\u2019RE CLICKING ON:   Is medicine only getting more precise \u2026 for white people, asks 538?   An overview of Maryland\u2019s PDMP.   Would declaring a state of emergency on opioids help Pennsylvania?  Local news piece on Georgia schools getting telemedicine.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
