aV \u000a            By DAVID PITTMAN  08/01/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Darius Tahir (@DariusTahir)   OPIOID COMMISSION REFERENCES HEALTH IT: Health IT issues are mentioned several times by the White House opioid commission, led by New Jersey Gov. Chris Christie, which issued some preliminary recommendations on Monday. The panel wants to have state and federal prescription drug monitoring programs sharing information on patients\u2019 prescribing histories by July next year. That would include the Department of Veterans Affairs.   Story Continued Below  \u2014\u201cForty-nine states now have PDMPs but not nearly a majority of those are sharing their information,\u201d the 10-page report states. \u201cThis is unacceptable.\u201d  \u2014PDMPs need to be easier to use and include other data like overdose histories so doctors will be likelier to use them. But the report didn\u2019t offer ways to make this happen.   Update patient privacy protections: The report recommends \u2014 through regulation and law \u2014 alignment with HIPAA. Today, patients\u2019 addiction treatment professionals must obtain written patient consent before sharing information with the person\u2019s other providers. The report called 42 CFR Part 2 a \u201cparticular hindrance to comprehensive health care.\u201d The report even singles out Rep. Tim Murphy\u2019s recently reintroduced Overdose Prevention and Patient Safety Act (H.R. 3545 (115)), which would give substance abuse records the same level of protection as HIPAA, as a necessary step.   Other recommendations:   \u2014Use \u201cbig data analytics\u201d to devise targeted prevention messages   \u2014Develop CMS quality measures for substance use screenings and addiction treatment.   Not mentioned:   \u2014Using telemedicine to expand treatment options or changing the Ryan Haight Act to make prescribing anti-addiction drugs easier.   \u2014The full report. The final report is due Oct. 1.  eHealth tweet of the day: Steven J. Stack @StevenStackMD: Umm, or "This is a 43 year old man." Gotta love EHR voice recognition dictation![See the picture Stack, a former AMA president, tweeted to see the diction system\u2019s blunder.]  Welcome to Tuesday Morning eHealth and welcome to August, a time typically filled with slow-news days and out-of-office messages. But 2017 hasn\u2019t been a typical year in health care, so why should we expect August to be any different? Share tips and story ideas with dpittman@politico.com and connect with us on Twitter @David_Pittman, @athurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.   HOW TO MEASURE INTEROPERABILITY: Everybody in health care wants it easier to share patient records among doctors and hospitals, but how do we know how well providers or IT systems are hitting that goal? ONC floated a framework this spring based on measuring how widely interoperability standards were used by health IT vendors and providers. On Monday, public comments were due on that ONC draft. We summarize some notable responses below.   CHIME: Standards aren\u2019t to the point where they are worth measuring because each is used so broadly that together that don\u2019t offer a clear picture of information sharing.   HIMSS: Agrees, overall, that measuring standards adoption could help advance interoperability. \u201cMeasurement is critical to understanding how to improve efforts in this space.\u201d   EHR Association: A particular measure being widely used doesn\u2019t mean it\u2019s successful, but volume shouldn\u2019t be ignored while other analysis are developed. \u201cSuch insights can help clarify when standards are ready for national adoption and to be included in a widely-supported standards floor for sentinel use cases.\u201d  Health IT Now: Measuring is a tool to expedite information exchange. \u201cOver reliance on counting successful transmissions will devalue actual improvement on use of data in improving care and allow the mere capability to exchange information to remain the future goal for health systems.\u201d  American Medical Association: Over measuring can place an undue burden on providers. \u201cSignificant attention must be paid to the value/burden ratio when developing a participant reporting system.\u201d   For what it\u2019s worth: The Obama administration\u2019s suggestion last summer for measuring interoperability was simply to use data on the number of doctors and hospitals sending, receiving, querying and integrating that information into practice for decision-making.   COMING TODAY, THEN TOMORROW: The Senate HELP Committee will hold a confirmation hearing on five senior HHS officials this afternoon. But on Wednesday, the panel will vote on sending their nominations to the Senate floor, HELP announced Monday. Those being considered include, Jerome Adams for surgeon general; Brett Giroir for assistant secretary for health; Robert Kadlec for assistant secretary for preparedness and response; Elinore F. McCance-Katz for assistant secretary for mental health and substance use; and Lance Robertson for assistant secretary for aging.   HILL WANTS TV AIRWAVES FOR BROADBAND: A bipartisan group of forty-three House lawmakers wrote the FCC Monday urging it repurpose unused television airwaves to broadcast high-speed internet to underserved America. Microsoft draw attention to the matter last month when it announced it would use so-called TV white spaces to offer the internet to 2 million rural Americans. The lawmakers, led by Rep. Kevin Cramer, say TV white spaces "have strong potential to revolutionize broadband internet accessibility in rural areas" and create dependendable internet connections that are "extremely cost-effective requiring minimal infrastructure investments." Cramer secured sign-on from senior Republicans such as House Republican Conference Chairwoman Cathy McMorris Rodgers (Wash.) and Rep. Darrell Issa (Calif.), as well as tech-friendly Democrats including Reps. Peter Welch (Vt.), Suzan DelBene (Wash.) and Anna Eshoo (Calif.).   \u2014The letter drew the liking of the App Association, a supporter of telehealth and rural broadband expansion. They explain how repurposing unused television airwaves can help health care in this blog post.   FIRST IN MORNING EHEALTH: Eighty-two percent of health care executives say the never-ending battle to repeal Obamacare hasn\u2019t delayed their work on population health management. In fact, the survey of nearly 200 c-suiters from data analytics firm Health Catalyst found a small number \u2014 4 percent \u2014 are ramping up efforts on population health. Anecdotal evidence to this point had suggested hospitals were slowing their spending on health IT given the uncertainty in health care because of repeal-and-replace talk.   DON\u2019T BE AFRAID TO TAKE A CHANCE: If more Medicare ACOs operated in a model where they stood to lose money if they didn\u2019t sufficiently hold down costs, they\u2019d actually make money by taking on the risk, an analysis by Avalere Health found. In fact, 80 percent of such \u201cone-sided risk\u201d ACOs could have shared in $178 million if they had worked in a \u201ctwo-sided risk\u201d model and chanced losing money if they didn\u2019t hit Medicare-set spending targets.   \u2014\u201cFor those physicians who were dipping their toes in the water with low-risk ACO models, the incentives now make it advantageous for a majority of them to move more aggressively into greater accountability for population health,\u201d Avalere executive or former ONC official Josh Seidman said.   ON THE MOVE: Karen Groppe, who has been working part-time with HIMSS\u2019s government relations team in Washington for a couple of years, is joining the organization full-time as director of corporate communications. She\u2019ll be working with the HIMSS folks in Chicago more.   \u2014Former Army surgeon general, Lt. Gen. Patty Horoho, is joining Optum, the health services business of UnitedHealth Group, as chief executive of its military, veterans, and federal government group  WHAT WE\u2019RE CLICKING:  23andMe is recruiting customers for a study on depression and bipolar disorder.   Amazon\u2019s personal assistant Alexa incorporates WebMD information.   Hearing aid maker Cochlear to stream iPhone services through its devices.   Internet searches for \u201chow to kill yourself\u201d increased in wake of the popular Netflix series 13 Reasons Why.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Arthur Allen (aallen@politico.com, @ArthurAllen202), David Pittman (dpittman@politico.com, @David_Pittman) and Darius Tahir (dtahir@politico.com, (@DariusTahir).  David Pittman is an eHealth reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Before joining POLITICO in May 2014, Pittman served as the lone Washington reporter for the health news website MedPage Today, covering nearly all aspects of health policy from Medicare and Medicaid to the Affordable Care Act and Capitol Hill. He has also covered science and regulatory policy for trade newsletter company FDAnews and the weekly newsmagazine Chemical & Engineering News. Pittman got his start in journalism covering healthcare for the daily newspaper in the West Texas town of Amarillo.  Pittman holds bachelor's degrees in journalism and chemistry from the University of Georgia, where he graduated in 2006. While in Athens, Pittman worked as a staff writer of The Red & Black and eventually became editor-in-chief, pestering school administrators. Like any good Southerner, he prefers his tea sweet, chicken fried and fall Saturdays reserved for college football. He is also surviving as an Atlanta Braves fan in a town full of Washington Nationals supporters.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
