aV \u000a            By DAVID PITTMAN  07/31/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Darius Tahir (@DariusTahir)   OBAMACARE-REPEAL FAILURE: THE FALLOUT: Despite a series of failures in votes over health care in the Senate last week, efforts to thinker with or repeal Obamacare continue. POLITICO\u2019s Paul Demko and Heather Caygle scoop that a bipartisan group of 40 lawmakers will unveil a slate of Obamacare fixes today \u2014 including cost sharing reduction payments, state stabilization funds and repeal of the medical device tax \u2014 they hope will gain traction after the Senate\u2019s effort to repeal the law imploded. Meanwhile, partisan efforts on repeal continue, despite leadership saying it\u2019s time to \u201cmove on.\u201d   Story Continued Below  There are two other pressing health issues facing Congress; reauthorizing the FDA\u2019s collection of industry user fees and the Children\u2019s Health Insurance Program. Senate leaders haven\u2019t given an indication when the FDA user fees will get a floor vote. (It\u2019s already cleared the HELP Committee and the full House.) More on CHIP reauthorization below.   OTHER HEALTH LEGISLATIVE EFFORTS MOTOR ON:   Substance abuse records bill introduced: Rep. Tim Murphy on Friday introduced legislation that gives patients' substance abuse treatment records the same level of protection as HIPAA, making it easier to share information among providers. Under a federal law known as 42 CFR Part 2, patients must sign off on each individual provider who can view such records. Changes in regulations around the law that took effect this year do allow a patient to make a general disclosure that allows record-sharing among doctors but only within a health system. "You cannot treat the whole patient with half of their medical record,\u201d Murphy said in a release.   Murphy\u2019s Overdose Prevention and Patient Safety Act (H.R. 3545 (115)) is supported by the Partnership to Amend 42 CFR Part 2 Coalition, which includes the American Hospital Association and many others.   Policymakers are making progress on bringing Part 2 into the 21st century, recognizing the problem with opioid addiction and other behavioral health issues, said Kevin Scalia, executive vice president at behavioral health IT vendor Netsmart. If those concerned about their privacy want to opt out of having their data shared \u2014 let them, Scalia said. \u201cWe shouldn\u2019t, because of those minority of people, stop the majority of people who want to share.\u201d  Another week, another telemedicine bill: Reps. Doris Matsui and Bill Johnson have filed legislation (H.R. 3482 (115)) giving the HHS secretary power to waive Medicare restrictions on what telemedicine it covers if the service improves quality of care or reduces costs. The CMS actuary would have to certify that the move would save money. Since each measure would have to be signed by the secretary if it saves money, it's thought the Congressional Budget Office won't contend that it will actually cost the federal government much money and erase a longtime hurdle for getting more telemedicine payments.  What it means: Telemedicine advocates on and off Capitol Hill are frustrated by the lack of progress on getting more Medicare reimbursement, despite years of trying. But realizing the environment they live in \u2014 dominated by Obamacare-repeal work \u2014 pro-telemedicine offices are trying to maintain momentum by introducing bills and keeping talk alive. Quietly, Democrat and Republican offices are saying odds are slim that more substantive telemedicine changes will be attached to larger must-pass bill later this year like CHIP reauthorization \u2014 but they want to stay ready in case an opening appears.   eHealth tweet of the day: JacquiG @JacquiFromSheff: But can your smart phone and telehealth deal with a broken leg, a case of plague, cat stuck in a tree???Retweeted Kainos Evolve @KainosEvolve: Join us & @InTouchHealth 12 Sept to learn more about Telehealth & the benefits of \u201ccare anytime, anywhere\u201d.  Welcome to Monday Morning eHealth where our boss, Arthur Allen, is on vacation this week. We wish him adieu. But if he reads this, then maybe he\u2019d not really enjoying his time off as much as possible. Pass along your tips and story ideas to dpittman@politico.com and connect with us on Twitter @David_Pittman, @athurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.   CERNER EARNINGS CALL: Lost in all the FDA and repeal-and-fail mess last week was Cerner\u2019s earnings call \u2014 which provided some interesting color from executives of the Kansas City company:   \u2014 VA: President Zane Burke said he expected a contract to install the Department of Veterans Affairs\u2019 new EHR by the end of the year.   \u2014 The tech giants: In a wonderful dance of euphemism, one analyst asked Burke about unnamed \u201cnon-traditional players entering into the [EHR] space in some way, shape or form.\u201d Amusingly, neither Burke nor the analyst specifically mentioned \u201cApple\u201d or \u201cAmazon,\u201d but we all know what they meant.  Burke expects to beat the tech giants at the EHR game. \u201cThe core transactional EMR is a place where I think we have a significant moat built around us,\u201d he said. He believes that if a software company isn\u2019t focusing specifically on health care and IT, it\u2019ll fail.   \u201cI actually don't think that those that are rumored to be doing things in this space are thinking about how they're going to create the next EHR,\u201d he concluded. \u201cThey're thinking about how can they add value into the whole entire health care supply chain and how can they think about making the consumer experience a better one.\u201d   Full transcript here, for those who are interested.   MERCK CYBERATTACK: The Merck earnings call Friday was particularly interesting for our niche because of the cyberattack on the drug giant\u2019s computers last month, which reportedly kneecapped the company\u2019s operations.   The company\u2019s CEO said during the call that the attack halted the production of drugs which will hurt profits for the rest of the year. A full recovery from the cyberattack \u201cwill take some time.\u201d More here.   MARK YOUR CALENDARS: The FDA announced a workshop on incorporating real-world evidence into its decision making. The date is set for Sept. 13. Morning eHealth readers don\u2019t need to be reminded that it\u2019s hard to discuss real-world evidence for too long without drawing data from EHRs and other digital other tools. Find more info in the Federal Register notice.   HOW FOLKS REACTED TO RANSOMWARE: Despite FBI advice to not pay ransomware attackers to get them to release hostage data, that\u2019s exactly what 40 percent of surveyed health organizations are doing, according to a KPMG survey out today. Fewer than 20 percent actually worked with authorities on criminal action. The survey quizzed 100 c-suite executives at health care providers and health plans. More than a third said they were hit by ransomware in the past year.   Related: \u201cRansomware victims have paid more than $25 million in ransoms over the last two years, according to a study presented today by researchers at Google, Chainalysis, UC San Diego, and the NYU Tandon School of Engineering,\u201d The Verge reports.   WHAT TO WATCH TODAY:The presidential opioid commission chaired by Gov. Chris Christie is set to release its interim report today, our New Jersey colleague Katie Jennings reports. Among the recommendations will be more education for physicians about opioid prescribing. While the New Jersey governor didn\u2019t directly say prescription drug monitor programs would be mentioned, he did hint at it strongly while talking to reporters last week.   \u2014\u201c If you look at it, the amount of opioids that are being prescribed in this country would allow every adult to be medicated 24 hours a day for three weeks,\u201d Christie said, noting that four out of five heroin addicts start with prescription drugs. We\u2019ll be on the lookout.   LATER THIS WEEK:  Tuesday The Senate HELP Committee will hold a confirmation hearing for several HHS nominees, including Jerome Adams for surgeon general, Brett Giroir for assistant HHS secretary for health and Elinore F. McCance-Katz for the newly created position of assistant secretary for mental health.   WednesdayThe Senate Commerce will vote on three FCC nominations including two Republicans (FCC Chairman Ajit Pai and General Counsel Brendan Carr) and one Democrat (former Commissioner Jessica Rosenworcel).  ThursdayThe FCC\u2019s monthly meeting will focus on expanding rural broadband.   The Senate Finance Committee will hold a confirmation hearing on Matt Bassett to be HHS assistant secretary for legislation.   Got an event coming up? Send the details to ehealthcalendar@politicopro.com.   DEVICE TAX LEFT OUT OF SKINNY REPEAL: Within a matter of hours Thursday the medical device tax repeal went from a sure bet for being included in the Senate\u2019s \u201cskinny\u201d Obamacare repeal bill to being out. It\u2019s now back on the table in the aforementioned bipartisan offer, albeit as a three-year suspension. The full repeal of the tax was left out of the Senate package because it needed to save as much money as the House bill to be considered on the Senate floor, said Paul Van de Water, senior fellow at the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities. \u201cIt doesn\u2019t show any shortcoming on the part of the medical-device industry,\u201d he told Prescription Pulse. \u201cIn fact, they\u2019ve proven to be remarkably effective to this point.\u201d   ZUCK\u2019S BUCKS GO TO UCSF: Mark Zuckerberg and his wife, pediatrician Priscilla Chan, are donating $10 million to the University of California San Francisco. The cash will endow big data guru Atul Butte\u2019s chair, and supporting Butte\u2019s \u201cdata recycling\u201d efforts. As Butte imagines it, he\u2019ll be combining the University of California systems\u2019 disparate EHRs together for a massive ocean of data, which can be analyzed and probed for various insights into health care. More here.   WHAT WE\u2019RE CLICKING:  Amazon removed references to potential future health care work from web site and employees\u2019 LinkedIn profiles after CNBC reported on them.    The safety of voice dictation in EHRs.   Athenahealth uses its doctors\u2019 data to detect uptick in Lyme disease early.   eClinicalWorks chief wants to move on after Justice Department settlement, says his priority was his customers.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Arthur Allen (aallen@politico.com, @ArthurAllen202), David Pittman (dpittman@politico.com, @David_Pittman) and Darius Tahir (dtahir@politico.com, (@DariusTahir).  David Pittman is an eHealth reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Before joining POLITICO in May 2014, Pittman served as the lone Washington reporter for the health news website MedPage Today, covering nearly all aspects of health policy from Medicare and Medicaid to the Affordable Care Act and Capitol Hill. He has also covered science and regulatory policy for trade newsletter company FDAnews and the weekly newsmagazine Chemical & Engineering News. Pittman got his start in journalism covering healthcare for the daily newspaper in the West Texas town of Amarillo.  Pittman holds bachelor's degrees in journalism and chemistry from the University of Georgia, where he graduated in 2006. While in Athens, Pittman worked as a staff writer of The Red & Black and eventually became editor-in-chief, pestering school administrators. Like any good Southerner, he prefers his tea sweet, chicken fried and fall Saturdays reserved for college football. He is also surviving as an Atlanta Braves fan in a town full of Washington Nationals supporters.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
