aV \u000a            By DARIUS TAHIR  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from David Pittman (@David_Pittman) and Arthur Allen (@arthurallen202)  DEFEAT FOR OBAMACARE REPEAL IN THE SENATE: Late night drama. Sen. John McCain cast the deciding vote, killing the "skinny" fallback repeal legislation that the Senate had hoped would be the basis for negotiations with the House which had passed a far more expansive bill repealing much of Obamacare and fundamentally altering Medicaid. McCain put a stop to the Republicans' legislative priority -- and saved the top legislative achievement of Barack Obama, the man who defeated him for the presidency in 2008. What's next? Not yet clear. President Donald Trump tweeted "let Obamacare implode." There are also some whisperings of bipartisanship on the Hill.  Story Continued Below  FDA ANNOUNCES NEW DIGITAL HEALTH POLICY REGIME: FDA rolled out a new digital health policy Thursday. The announcement breaks down into two parts: a pilot \u201cpre-certification\u201d program and a broader policy road map. Let\u2019s consider each in turn:   \u2014 Pre-certification program: This is the pilot version of a long-discussed program: a strategy of certifying developers, rather than their products, as a way to deal with the nature of software development. Software, as anyone who\u2019s looked at the \u201cupdates\u201d queue in their iPhone knows, is frequently and iteratively constructed. New additions are processed all the time. That\u2019s long been a tough fit with FDA\u2019s medical device regulations, which allow manufacturers to make trivial updates without oversight (but still need agency approval for more substantive changes).   Hence the idea of certifying developers with sterling records. The pilot program will begin accepting applications Aug. 1, with a view to accepting nine developers Sept. 1. In a conversation with Morning eHealth, the agency\u2019s digital health director Bakul Patel told us that creating the specifics of the program \u2013 defining what a quality developer does, and perhaps whether and how to de-certify one-time good developers \u2013 would be built along with the developers who apply. From there, the agency is looking to unveil a draft version of the program in January.   \u201cCan we identify [a standard of] excellence that meets the small two-person company, and the large organization?\u201d Patel asked. \u201cThose are the goals.\u201d   \u2014 Roadmap: Separately, the agency also introduced a policy roadmap that includes a first-quarter 2018 timeline for anticipated guidance on subjects like clinical decision support and \u201cmulti-functional\u201d software. The clinical decision support software guidance is long awaited; it\u2019s been promised and never released for years now. While everyone Morning eHealth spoke with was upbeat about the policy maneuvers, we did hear some regret that the CDS guidance would be waiting for just a little bit longer. Patel said the delay allows the agency to align all its new policies.   \u2014 Reactions: We had several, and nearly all of them were happy. Let\u2019s start with the elected officials. Rep. Marsha Blackburn, the driving force behind the SOFTWARE Act, said the pilot program was a fulfillment of her goals. \u201cBy employing a light-touch regulatory approach and establishing a thorough pre-certification program, developers will be able to efficiently deliver the latest technology to those who stand to benefit most from it,\u201d she said in a statement.   Rep. Gene Green, an early co-sponsor of the SOFTWARE Act, said the program \u201cgives certainty to innovators so we can unleash the next generation of health information technology.\u201d  AdvaMed, the big medical device group, issued a nuanced but upbeat statement. It approves of the pre-certification pilot program, and while the group is happy with most of the proposed guidance, one in particular is concerning: the International Medical Device Regulators Forum\u2019s software-as-a-medical-device guidance. The Forum is an international collaboration of regulatory agencies intended to harmonize medical device regulations; one part of its work has been its software-as-a-medical-device product. FDA has been leaning toward introducing the Forum\u2019s work as a guidance, but AdvaMed believes it doesn\u2019t fit FDA\u2019s statutory framework.   And former FDA commissioner Robert Califf was quite pleased, tweeting, \u201cFDA is leading, not following-much appreciated in Silicon Valley. Digital tech can reinforce healthful behavior & ++ healthcare quality.\u201d  With the official reaction out of the way, let\u2019s take a brief break for tweets and stuff, and then give you some thoughts from distinguished observers.   eHealth tweet of the day: Mats Berggren @Sanktmickel Brilliant regulatory move. #FastTrack 4 #digitalhealth FDA announces pre-certification for digital health start-ups  FRIDAY: Apparently it\u2019s supposed to rain today and tomorrow, creating a reasonably distressing possibility that your correspondent must prepare two sets of weekend plans. We know, there are many worse fates, but you try coordinating disparate groups of people to agree to a plan and a backup plan. You can try coordinating two disparate groups of people to agree to a plan and a backup plan at dtahir@politico.com. You can also try social planning on social media at @David_Pittman, @athurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.  MORE REACTIONS: We also got some reactions from individuals outside official orbits. Bradley Merrill Thompson, a digital health lawyer with Epstein Becker & Green, told Morning eHealth that it was \u201crather unbelievable how fast FDA is moving in a positive direction.\u201d   \u201cThis stuff is really hard to figure out in the abstract, and it\u2019s really only by working with companies and tinkering and experimenting that we can truly identify the best model,\u201d he said, calling the plan \u201cbrilliant.\u201d He also praised the policy road map as \u201cwell-conceived.\u201d   But who will apply? FDA is hopeful it can select a representative cross-section of developers \u2013 that is, from small and big companies, as well as developers who aren\u2019t traditional medical device manufacturers. Stephen Kraus, a venture capitalist with Bessemer Venture Partners, is extremely excited about the program, calling it an \u201cexample of great market-driven policy,\u201d but isn\u2019t sure start-ups will rush to apply.   \u201cI doubt a lot of start-ups will have the time or capacity to be participants in the pilot here as they already have so much on their plate,\u201d he said. \u201cMy guess is most smaller companies will pass on being guinea pigs and will wait to see how the regulation and process develops before they engage.\u201d   Another venture capitalist, Vijay Pande of Andreessen Horowitz, said the decision demonstrated the agency was repeating the same sort of process with software as it had with drugs: accommodating new innovations with a balance of oversight.   Looking to the future, Pande suggested that the next area for regulatory adjustment would be machine learning algorithms with diagnostics. \u201cI would expect there\u2019ll be [agency] expectations how to run those clinical trials,\u201d he said, though the software would continue to adjust as it gets more and more data.   FTC HEARING ON INTERSTATE LICENSURE: The chair of the Interstate Medical Licensure Compact met with his home-state senator, Minnesota\u2019s Amy Klobuchar, and staff of the Federal Trade Commission to discuss ongoing issues with the FBI while in town for an FTC roundtable Thursday, he said.   \u201cMy message was, \u2018We need some help here,\u2019 \u201d Jon Thomas, head of the physician compact, told Morning eHealth following the FTC event on increasing professional license portability. Thomas is frustrated with the FBI, which continues to block access to its criminal background check system for doctors looking to gain approval to see patients in multiple states in the compact. The physician compact has tried \u2014 largely unsuccessfully \u2014 for months to get the FBI loosen its stance.   To date, 174 doctors have applied for a license through the compact, which would help doctors treat more patients through telemedicine. But it could be more, Thomas notes, if the FBI would stop objecting. The bureau says the compact commission isn\u2019t a state entity and therefore states can\u2019t share results of the background check among themselves.   \u2014 Remarks from the chair: FTC Chair Maureen Ohlhausen, in remarks to kick off the meeting, called convening an FTC task force on licensing one of her first tasks when taking over the commission in January. She wanted to shine a spotlight on the issue, which she called important for consumers and workers alike. \u201cWe plan to continue this dialogue in a number of ways,\u201d Ohlhausen pledged.   OTHER CONGRESSIONAL NON-REPEAL ACTIVITIES: Here are three tidbits on Congressional activities that don\u2019t involve Obamacare:   \u2014 Regulatory reigning-in: Pat Tiberi, chair of the Ways and Means health subcommittee, has no timeline for work on his committee\u2019s recently announced \u201cMedicare Red Tape Relief Project.\u201d Tiberi hopes to scale back regulations for doctors and hospitals, though there\u2019ll first be a public process of soliciting feedback.  \u201cTimelines always got us in trouble,\u201d Tiberi told Morning eHealth. HHS leadership is \u201cwildly interested\u201d in getting congressional feedback. (ONC brass say they\u2019ve already started regulation review around EHRs.) Tiberi is \u201copen-minded\u201d to all ideas and says \u201codds are good\u201d that legislation may result from this.   Remember, the American Hospital Association came up with nine pages of suggestions for the new Trump administration last December, including delays of Stage 3 meaningful use and use of 2015 edition EHRs.   \u2014 Behavioral health IT bill: Last week\u2019s legislation to help get EHRs into the hands of behavioral health providers is \u201ca key first step,\u201d members of the Behavioral Health IT Coalition wrote last week. In a letter made public Thursday, the group praised a bill (H.R. 3331) from Reps. Lynn Jenkins and Doris Matsui that would authorize a CMS Innovation Center project for psychiatric hospitals, community behavioral health centers, residential and outpatient mental health and substance use treatment facilities, as well as clinical psychologists and social workers to buy EHRs. The CMMI demo is a way around the billions the project would otherwise cost.   \u2014 Privacy: Rep. Suzan DelBene re-introduced her Birth Control Privacy Act Thursday, which would prevent wellness programs from disclosing personally identifiable information on birth control usage to employers. The bill was first introduced last session, after a Wall Street Journal report on employers\u2019 use of big data to keep an eye on their workers\u2019 health (and, perhaps, future pregnancies).   WHAT WE\u2019RE CLICKING ON:   The Joplin Globe raises more questions \u2014 including constitutional ones \u2014 about Missouri\u2019s new PDMP.   A back-and-forth between researchers and PhRMA on clinical trial data transparency.   CNBC has a round-up of thoughts on FDA\u2019s digital health move.   The Associated Press fact-checks Trump on VA\u2019s EHR conversion.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
