aV \u000a            By DARIUS TAHIR  07/27/2017 10:00 AM EDT  VA TO EMPLOYEES \u2014 ZIP YOUR LIPS ON EHRs: Some VA IT officials Arthur has spoken to this week got emails instructing them to sign a non-disclosure agreement regarding the Cerner deal with the agency. The emails were directed to people who \u201chave been selected to participate in the planning for an electronic health acquisition,\u201d and it prohibits them from discussing \u201call data, information and software\u201d related to the purchase.   However, many VA officials who got the email aren\u2019t working on the Cerner deal \u2014 yet, anyway. To date, a small group led by military officers who ran the DoD\u2019s Cerner purchase decision in 2015 has been overseeing this acquisition process. Some worried that the NDAs could make it hard for VA employees to give Congress straight dope on the Cerner implementation.   Story Continued Below  \u201cBefore, if VA employees spoke out against the Cerner deal they might have been worried about losing their jobs, but if they were ready to retire they might have taken the chance,\u201d said Nancy Anthracite, director of WorldVista, which commercializes VistA-based software. \u201cThis way they might not even be willing to do that.\u201d  ANNALS OF REPEAL \u2014 THE CONTINUING SAGA: Wednesday was another day slogging through another set of amendments to the Senate\u2019s repeal-and-TBD mystery bill. The Senate rejected a \u201crepeal-only\u201d proposal late in the afternoon, but also rejected a motion to send the process to relevant committees. Tune in today for more potential developments in the health care bill \u2014 including, perhaps, offerings of hundreds of amendments from Democrats.   eHealth tweet of the day: Greg Fulton @glfulton [on Arthur\u2019s open API piece] While the "specter"of regulation can be scary, ONC needs to align API so we don't repeat EHR exchange flaws and face closed API networks.  THURSDAY!: Your correspondent was recently shocked and appalled by news that rock band The War on Drugs is releasing a new album. You see, he\u2019s a fan. That\u2019s (sort of) the problem \u2013 he just learned today that the group had released, like, four or five songs from the album, and just fell down a rabbit hole listening to all of them. Why is this bad? Because your correspondent had no idea this was happening, in this, the epoch of the internet telling you about everything seconds after or even before it actually occurs. What kind of uninformed bozo (when it comes to music) is your correspondent? Tell him at dtahir@politico.com. Discuss socially at @David_Pittman, @athurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.  TODAY \u2014 FTC ON LICENSING: Today won\u2019t just be about a procession of votes to a health bill that may or may not ever become law. It\u2019s also about the Federal Trade Commission\u2019s event this afternoon on \u201cStreamlining licensing across state lines.\u201d You can see a description and agenda for the event here, but as you can probably guess, medical licensing will be a subject. Participants include Jon Thomas, of the Interstate Medical Licensure Compact Commission, and Katherine Thomas, of the Texas Board of Nursing.   The event provides the chance for comments; you can see the 22 comments collected so far (as of this writing) here. By our eye, the most notable is the American Medical Association\u2019s comment, which affirms the organization\u2019s support for the Interstate compact \u2013 with a specific shout-out to telemedicine.   \u201cProponents of telemedicine have often cited the time-consuming state licensure process for multiple-license holders as a key barrier to overcome in order for telemedicine to continue to grow and thrive,\u201d the trade group notes.   HABEMAS HIMSS CEO: HIMSS, the health IT organization, has a new CEO: Hal Wolf. The group announced the accession of the former Kaiser Permanente executive Wednesday.   Wolf has worked with HIMSS for the last four years, two as an advisor and two as a board member. (The last year was spent as vice board chair.) Given his familiarity with the organization, the chance to be CEO was too much to pass up, he told Morning eHealth.   One of his goals as CEO \u2014 aside from growing HIMSS\u2019 global footprint \u2014 is to dive deeper involved in polices around cybersecurity, interoperability and broader innovation. He recited the familiar line about how technology can help improve quality while providing better care at lower cost.    \u201cWhat the challenge [of health IT] has always been the development of information that comes out of EHRs,\u201d he told us. \u201cI think that\u2019s the maturity cycle that is picking up some steam now. It has been slower in its adaption than utilization than I would have hoped for. I think that\u2019s the light at the end of the tunnel that will start to add value.\u201d   Wolf got some attaboys from his peers in the health IT industry. CHIME\u2019s board chair, Liz Johnson of Tenet Healthcare, praised Wolf\u2019s \u201cdepth of experience and leadership skills\u201d in a statement.   INSTALLING EHRs IS COSTLY \u2014 FOR A YEAR: So concludes an analysis from Moody\u2019s of 39 hospitals and health systems. On average, during the year a hospital is converting to an EHR, it sees a 10 percent operating cash flow drop. Bad debt climbs by 4.3 percent in a conversion year, as opposed to 2.6 percent growth in the year after a conversion.   Nevertheless, the investment analysis service expects hospitals will continue to pour money into their EHRs. \u201cHospitals and health systems that enter into risk-bearing agreements with payors, or establish their own risk-bearing insurance products, will need sophisticated data analytics\u201d provided by EHRs, the analysis concludes.   MISSOURI PDMP DRAMA CONTINUES: Missouri continues to be a font of drama on PDMPs, despite Governor Eric Greitens\u2019s executive order:   \u2014 County-level program expands: The more comprehensive drug database offered by the county-by-county PDMP continues to expand. Earlier this week, Greene County elected to join; St. Louis County\u2019s executive \u2014 who\u2019s leading the project \u2014 cheered the decision, saying that about two-thirds of the state\u2019s population was now covered by their program.   \u2014 More questions on the order: The Missouri Times is questioning the process behind Greitens\u2019s order. To recap, Greitens established a state program primarily aimed at law enforcement through his executive order. The program\u2019s data derives from a contract with pharmacy-benefit management giant Express Scripts; the Missouri Times says the $250,000 contract was no-bid \u2014 an apparent evasion of the state\u2019s procurement regulations.   QPP SUBMISSION API PREVIEW: CMS sent around an email advertising a developer preview of its Quality Payment Program submission API Wednesday. (You can email QPP@cms.hhs.gov if you\u2019re interested in getting involved.)   Now, if this acronym pileup tickles your memory, it\u2019s probably because you\u2019re a longtime Morning eHealth reader. (Thanks!) We mentioned it in context with the US Digital Service\u2019s July 2017 report to Congress, in which the federal government\u2019s hacker conclave noted that it was developing the API \u2014 which would help software developers create apps and such allowing participants to submit or check up on data easily.   HITRUST COMMUNITY EXTENSION PROGRAM: The HITRUST Alliance rolled out a \u201cCommunity Extension Program\u201d Wednesday. The cybersecurity company is hoping to convene health care organizations at town halls in 50 cities over the next twelve months, which will help educate providers about upping their cybersecurity defenses.   WHAT WE\u2019RE CLICKING ON:   CNBC reports that Amazon has a secret EHR team called \u201c1492.\u201d We\u2019re not sure what this is supposed to imply about the, shall we say, indigenous EHR companies.   The Network for Excellence in Health Innovation has a report on the need for greater transparency for consumers.   Yelp is adding data on C-section rates (and more) for 250 California hospitals.   A radiologist pines (a little bit) for the good old days before digital radiology.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
