aV \u000a            By DAVID PITTMAN  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Darius Tahir (@DariusTahir) and Arthur Allen (@ArthurAllen202))  LIFE FOR OBAMA OFFICIALS IN A TRUMPIAN WORLD: For former ONC chief and Assistant Secretary of Health Karen DeSalvo, the meeting-packed days are gone along with the weekly trips to and from Washington. Since Donald Trump took office, she\u2019s just a private citizen with a familiar name. \u201cHonestly, you grieve a little bit because these things you\u2019ve been working on and the people that you\u2019ve grown to love, you\u2019re not with them every day, all the time anymore,\u201d DeSalvo told Morning eHealth in an interview from her New Orleans home.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 The first six months of the Trump administration have been trying for some senior Obama administration health care officials, who entered office with strong ideas about how to reform health care that have been largely marginalized by the new government. Few admitted to having expected posts under a President Hilary Clinton, but DeSalvo acknowledged she would have liked to have stayed on. Instead, she\u2019s still searching for her next opportunity during a \u201cself-styled sabbatical.\u201d  Vindell Washington, who took over as HHS\u2019s health IT lead last summer, only to lose the job in January, resurfaced in June as medical director of Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Louisiana. \u201cIt is clear that there\u2019s no other job you can go to where you are concerned about the wellbeing of the entire country,\u201d he said. Yet he didn\u2019t feel that the world was passing him by. \u201cWe all have a role to play. When you get tapped on the shoulder, you go and you play the role. Sometimes, you\u2019re the quarterback and sometimes a right guard,\u201d he said. \u201cThey\u2019re no less important.\u201d   Helping adjust: In the final days of the Obama administration, HHS Secretary Sylvia Mathews Burwell arranged for tours of the recently opened African-American History Museum on the National Mall. The message was clear for employees who worried their work would be undermined by the Trump administration: social progress had setbacks along the way \u2014 but the trajectory, like the museum\u2019s exhibits, was upward.   Pros get the full story here.   eHealth tweet of the day: liv @livyylove: everyones stressed about our go-live date for the new EHR system but its on my anniversary that I took off so [shrug emoji]  Welcome to Wednesday Morning eHealth where we\u2019re still in the dark as to when the Senate will vote on its FDA user fee bill. After health care (more on that later) comes the Defense reauthorization bill, and it\u2019s not clear yet where user fee fits in. Pass along your thoughts and news tips to dpittman@politico.com and connect with us on Twitter @David_Pittman, @athurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.   OBAMACARE UPDATE: It\u2019s hard to follow anything in health care these days that isn\u2019t impacted by the never-ending Obamacare repeal efforts in Congress. On Tuesday afternoon, the Senate GOP narrowly approved a motion to open floor debate on repeal efforts. In the evening, nine Republicans voted against the chamber\u2019s first-draft repeal effort (H.R. 1628 (115)). What happens next? POLITICO\u2019s Paul Demko has you covered.   MORE REACTION FROM THE ONC MEETING: Monday\u2019s ONC meeting on building a trusted exchange network raised a lot more questions than answers, according to self-described health information evangelist Adrian Gropper in a soon-to-be-published blog post. For example:   \u2014 Algorithmic patient identity matching has no solution in sight;  \u2014 Interoperability between HIPAA and non-HIPAA entities has no solution in sight;  \u2014 Different frameworks with different governance principles can only interoperate at a lowest common denominator, frustrating both clinicians and families;  \u2014 All agree that accountability is important but nobody proposed how patients can hold anyone accountable for anything;  \u2014 The 21st Century Cures goal of a Longitudinal Health Record was not mentioned by anyone.  HHS \u2018WALL OF SHAME\u2019 GETS A MAKEOVER: The website listing health care organizations that had patient information stolen or lost has had a bit of a facelift. The new site posts data breaches currently under investigation, listing events reported to HHS over the last two years. The site, overall, is easier to navigate, HHS says. Test drive it here yourself.   \u2014 The 2009 HITECH Act required organizations holding patient information to report to HHS \u2014 and then post online \u2014 when 500 or more patients\u2019 information is lost, stolen or hacked.   AND WE\u2019RE LOOKING TO PARE DOWN EHRS?: Social factors account for anywhere between 20 percent and 40 percent of our health. The rest is genetic, the care we receive or choices we make, like smoking. ONC, recognizing this, wants to better incorporate social, psychological, and behavioral factors into electronic health records. During a half-day webinar today, HHS\u2019s health IT office will take a step toward doing that. ONC has worked with standards development organizations on the issue, and during today\u2019s event health officials will discuss ways to make such tools more usable and interoperable. More information here.   PMI HANDS OUT SOME DOUGH: The NIH announced the first four community partners who will begin building its national network of recruiters for its All of Us Research Program, part of the Precision Medicine Initiative. This initial group of awardees will receive a combined $1.7 million this fiscal year.   CHECK BACK AT A LATER DATE: The House Veterans Affairs Committee has postponed its planned telemedicine roundtable that was set for Thursday. Morning eHealth told you about it Monday, but no rescheduled date has been set.   \u2014 A committee spokeswoman didn\u2019t respond when asked if the cancelation had anything to do with Monday\u2019s setback in a vote to extend the VA\u2019s Choice program, which allows veterans to seek VA-reimbursed care with private providers. The bill failed to obtain the two-thirds majority required under the rules that brought the bill to the floor. Funding for the program is expected to run out by mid-August.   TELEMEDICINE BILL PASSES HOUSE: House lawmakers used little drama in passing by a voice vote the Medicare Part B Improvement Act (H.R. 3178 (115)), which makes monthly, at-home kidney dialysis treatments through telemedicine reimbursable under Medicare despite the program\u2019s otherwise restrictive mandates for payment. The measure is expected to be attached to the CHIP reauthorization bill that must pass in September.   ADD THIS BILL TO THOSE YOU\u2019RE TRACKING: Mississippi Republican Gregg Harper and California Democrat Mike Thompson have quietly reintroduced their Telehealth Enhancement Act (H.R. 3360 (115)). The bill filed in 2015 would add urban critical access hospitals, sole community hospitals, home telehealth sites, and counties with fewer than 25,000 people as eligible for Medicare payments for telemedicine. Neither office got back to us in time to say whether the version filed Tuesday contained any changes.   TELLY-HEALTH UPDATE: Our colleague Arthur Allen has been attending the World Congress of Gerontology and Geriatrics in San Francisco this week and had the pleasure of learning about how they do tele-geriatrics in the wilds of northern British Colombia and in Queensland, Australia (they call it \u201ctelly-health.\u201d) Shannon Freeman of the University of Northern British Columbia (a France-sized region with 250,000 residents) described the growing telemedicine program in her region, which increased from about 1,000 to 24,000 teleconferences per year from 2012 to 2017, covering more than 40 specialties. Telemedicine is saving the state\u2019s sparse residents six million miles in travel and about $1.5 million a year, conservatively, reported Freeman. Meanwhile, Queensland University Professor Melinda Martin-Khan described how tele-memory clinics are replacing long drives to Brisbane.   MARK YOUR CALENDAR: The Senate HELP Committee will hold a confirmation hearing for five HHS officials next Tuesday, the panel announced. They include Lance Allen Robertson, assistant secretary for aging; Brett Giroir, assistant secretary for health; Robert Kadlec, assistant secretary for preparedness and response; Elinore McCance-Katz, assistant secretary for mental health and substance use; and Jerome Adams, surgeon general.   AMIA COMMENTS ON ONC INTEROPERABILITY STANDARDS FRAMEWORK: The American Medical Informatics Association is one of the first industry groups out of the gate on ONC\u2019s proposed interoperability standards framework, an April 2017 document outlining the agency\u2019s thoughts on how to measure progress towards interoperability. In the report, ONC separated out two objectives \u2014 measuring which standards are actually implemented in IT products and how (and how much) standards are used when they\u2019re actually used in the field.   AMIA has a few thoughts, but most intriguing is one bottom-line proposal: that ONC try retrospectively reviewing cases. The office could select specific types of care \u2014 say, congestive heart failure \u2014 in which coordination would be expected. In those instances, if care is being done well, there\u2019d likely be a high amount of data-sharing. To confirm, auditors armed with questionnaires could interview congestive heart failure patients about whether the interoperability, in fact, occurred.   Comments are due Monday and we\u2019ll be on the lookout for what others have to say.   WHAT WE\u2019RE CLICKING:  HIPAA is obstructing advanced genomics work on cancers like the one that struck Sen. John McCain, advocates of more data sharing argue in a Washington Post op-ed.   Traditional hearing aids are only slightly more effective than their over-the-counter counterparts, a new study found.   Data breaches in health care are up 30 percent in the first half of the year, according to a new report.   Trump\u2019s war on data hasn\u2019t materialized.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Arthur Allen (aallen@politico.com, @ArthurAllen202), David Pittman (dpittman@politico.com, @David_Pittman) and Darius Tahir (dtahir@politico.com, (@DariusTahir).  David Pittman is an eHealth reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Before joining POLITICO in May 2014, Pittman served as the lone Washington reporter for the health news website MedPage Today, covering nearly all aspects of health policy from Medicare and Medicaid to the Affordable Care Act and Capitol Hill. He has also covered science and regulatory policy for trade newsletter company FDAnews and the weekly newsmagazine Chemical & Engineering News. Pittman got his start in journalism covering healthcare for the daily newspaper in the West Texas town of Amarillo.  Pittman holds bachelor's degrees in journalism and chemistry from the University of Georgia, where he graduated in 2006. While in Athens, Pittman worked as a staff writer of The Red & Black and eventually became editor-in-chief, pestering school administrators. Like any good Southerner, he prefers his tea sweet, chicken fried and fall Saturdays reserved for college football. He is also surviving as an Atlanta Braves fan in a town full of Washington Nationals supporters.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
