aV \u000a            By DAVID PITTMAN  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Darius Tahir (@DariusTahir) and Arthur Allen (@ArthurAllen202)  SOME TRUSTED EXCHANGES: Monday at the Hubert H. Humphrey building, a conclave of health IT experts got together to help begin one of ONC\u2019s 21st Century Cures Act duties \u2014 defining a trusted exchange framework. The future of information exchange is widely perceived to be between networks. In order to accomplish those exchanges, different networks will need rules of the road \u2014 which is the purpose of getting all these folks together.  Story Continued Below  \u2014 Rucker talks new use cases: ONC head Don Rucker set out the broad agenda for ONC, which includes defining \u201ctechnical definitions of interoperability; technical definitions of information blocking; [and] technical definitions of API.\u201d Then he drilled into some of the specific use-cases of information exchange. Some of those will be familiar: exchanging data between providers, or consumers getting access to their data.  But Rucker included an interesting third category which isn\u2019t often dwelled upon: payer access to data. \u201cCan bulk payers get at the data and compare what they\u2019re getting?\u201d he asked. Later, in a brief chat with Morning eHealth, Rucker elaborated: because American health care involves large institutions negotiating against each other, accountability requires that each of the large entities have enough data. Including insurers. \u201cIt really goes beyond one provider sharing with another provider.\u201d   \u2014 Laying down markers: The emphasis from many of the big payers in information exchange was to reuse, repair, and not recreate existing capabilities in information exchange. David Kibbe, the Direct Trust CEO, and Mariann Yeager, of the Sequoia Project, circulated a statement to Morning eHealth urging ONC to \u201cleverage existing trust frameworks that have presence in the market and broad adoption nationally,\u201d \u201crecognize and appreciate the diversity of different data and information sharing approaches\u201d and note that the private sector was hard at work on trusted exchange already.   The Yeager and Kibbe tag team got a third partner during the public comment section of the meeting: Sasha TerMaat, an Epic executive speaking on behalf of the Electronic Health Record Association. She urges ONC to leverage \u201call of the effort\u201d that had gone into creating technical specifications and network-building.   That consensus was, to our ears, present on more than the floor. Kory Mertz, a former ONC staffer now with Audacious Inquiry, gave a presentation noting the diversity of approaches among different networks \u2014 for accountability, for the use of technologies like record locator services, and so on.   \u201cEach organization was founded at different time, with different set of stakeholders, for different purposes,\u201d Mertz said. At a later point \u2014 when emphasizing the multitude of paths different organizations traveled down \u2014 he noted that it wasn\u2019t as if \u201cone approach is better than another.\u201d   So a prescriptive approach in this area appears unlikely, at least by our ears.   IS THIS NOT CUTTING IT A BIT CLOSE?: Related to ONC\u2019s carrying out the 21st Century Cures Act, HHS is seeking applications for the newly-formed Health IT Advisory Committee. The HHS secretary appoints three people to the 25-member panel. But the GAO, which names 14 seats, issued a similar call early this spring, and congressional leaders have been busy naming their choices.   eHealth tweet of the day: Lucia Savage @SavageLucia: I wish refs to "local governance" in @ONC_HealthIT event today would distinguish between laws (change = hard) & org policies (change easier)  Welcome to Tuesday Morning eHealth where we are starting \u2014 finally \u2014 to watch Game of Thrones. Your author hadn\u2019t seen a single episode but watched the first two of Season 1 over the weekend. Only about six dozen more episodes to go. Reach out at dpittman@politico.com and connect with us on Twitter @David_Pittman, @athurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.   HEALTH IT LOBBYING PLUMMETS UNDER TRUMP: Morning eHealth has long suspected that debate around Obamacare repeal has sucked the preverbal oxygen out of the room. Now we have data to support that.   The number of groups lobbying Congress on MACRA dropped to 58 in the second quarter this year, more than a 25 percent drop from the 81 working on it in the same period last year, according to a POLITICO analysis of recent lobbying disclosures. Organizations lobbying on MACRA spent just over $18 million in the last three months, compared to more than $27 million in the same period in 2016. Those dropping the issue include Humana, AARP, Premier along with several state hospital associations.   \u2014Not only has Obamacare diverted attention, but the Trump administration\u2019s HHS is now run by folks more sympathetic to doctors and hospitals clamoring for a lighter legislative touch, lobbyists we spoke with said. HHS Secretary Tom Price, as a member of Congress last year, helped push HHS to lower the bar on MACRA. \u201cWith Dr. Price as the head of HHS, that congressional oversight is less critical. There is still public comment on the rule, but that technically would not require disclosure as its not direct lobbying,\u201d said Anders Gilberg, senior vice president of government affairs at the Medical Group Management Association.   Meaningful use: The number of groups listing \u201cmeaningful use\u201d fell nearly by half, from 64 last year to 34 this year. Since MACRA did away with the term for doctors, hospitals and Medicaid providers are the only ones left under meaningful use. As a result, lobbying on the topic was mostly done by hospitals.   Telehealth: The number of times \u201ctelehealth\u201d was listed in disclosure reports went from 82 this time last year to 64 in the quarter that just wrapped up. \u201cI\u2019m not sure why that would be, especially because there are more opportunities for progress on telehealth this year than there were last year,\u201d Krista Drobac, executive director of the Alliance for Connected Care, told Morning eHealth.   \u2014Groups like CVS Health, the ERISA Industry Committee, Intel and LeadingAge have all stopped lobbying Congress on the issue. The ERISA Industry Committee said telehealth legislation at the federal level has been in Medicare and Veterans Affairs, domains outside of the group\u2019s immediate focus. Intel said it was working more with the Alliance for Connected Care.   SECOND QUARTER LOBBYING NUMBERS FOR OTHER NOTABLE HEALTH IT GROUPS: Epic: $36,000Athenahealth: $180,000Cerner: $30,000Allscripts: $46,800McKesson: $212,000Siemens: $1,010,000CHIME: $15,000 West Health Institute: $20,000Health IT Now: $40,000Teladoc: $50,000 Alliance for Connected Care: $75,000Federation of State Medical Boards: $150,000  MEDICAL SCRIBES BILL PASSES HOUSE: The House passed a bill (H.R. 1848 (115)) that would create a two-year, 10-hospital pilot for using medical scribes in the Veterans Affairs health system. The pilot would cost $5 million and result in periodic updates to Congress and a \u2014 Congress would have more information to expand the program. There\u2019s no similar legislation in the Senate.   COMING TO THE HOUSE FLOOR TODAY: The House will vote on a bill (H.R. 3178 (115)) that, among other things, allows Medicare coverage of at-home end-stage renal disease treatment via telehealth. The overall bill would cut federal spending by $4 million over a decade, and the Congressional Budget Office has said previously that the measure is budget neutral.   Related: Members of the ultra-conservative House Freedom Caucus want to eliminate the CBO\u2019s budget analysis division \u2014 never a friend to the telemedicine world by its predictions covering the technology would balloon the federal budget \u2014 in amendments set to be offered to bills that fund the government.   THEY WANT TO HEAR FROM YOU: The House Ways and Means Committee wants to work with doctors, nurses and others to cut the red tape and regulatory burden around health care through an effort it\u2019s calling the \u201cMedicare Red Tape Relief Project.\u201d The first step involves fielding feedback from health care groups. Responses are due by Aug. 25. That will be followed by roundtables and finally action.   \u2014Washington\u2019s doctor and hospital lobbies are sure to have a long list of ways to change the EHR incentive program, Stark Law and other billing programs \u2014 all involving health IT \u2014 as possible suggestions for the committee.   IT EXPENSES ON THE RISE: Physician practices spent between $2,000 and $4,000 more per employee on IT between 2015 and 2016, according to an MGMA survey. The overall practices paid between $14,000 and $19,000 on average for their IT systems. While the survey didn\u2019t dive into reason for the increase, likely options include maintaining EHRs and patient portals. Also, MGMA\u2019s health IT policy guru Rob Tennant said doctors are being more aggressive with their practice management software.   ICYMI: HEALTH IT EXEC SENTENCED: Sreedhar Potarazu, the ophthalmologist-turned-health IT entrepreneur who at one point had Newt Gingrich and Tom Daschle on the board of his data analytics firm VitalSpring Technologies, was sentenced to nearly 10 years in prison. Potarazu defrauded investors of $49 million and committed $7.5 million in tax fraud, Justice Department officials said.  WHAT WE\u2019RE CLICKING:  eClinicalWorks tells clients of seven possible issues with its EHRs.  New Jersey considers allowing police access to state PDMP without court orders.   Amazon continues its ramp up in health care work.   The New York Times\u2019 Upshot\u2019s Austin Frakt finds a recent study on hospital quality mirrors other quality rankings fairly well.   ONC wades into genomic data.   A new \u201cvirtual hospital\u201d in Tacoma, Wash., is profiled in the local newspaper.   Tips, comments, suggestions? Send them along via email to our team: Arthur Allen (aallen@politico.com, @ArthurAllen202), David Pittman (dpittman@politico.com, @David_Pittman) and Darius Tahir (dtahir@politico.com, (@DariusTahir).  David Pittman is an eHealth reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Before joining POLITICO in May 2014, Pittman served as the lone Washington reporter for the health news website MedPage Today, covering nearly all aspects of health policy from Medicare and Medicaid to the Affordable Care Act and Capitol Hill. He has also covered science and regulatory policy for trade newsletter company FDAnews and the weekly newsmagazine Chemical & Engineering News. Pittman got his start in journalism covering healthcare for the daily newspaper in the West Texas town of Amarillo.  Pittman holds bachelor's degrees in journalism and chemistry from the University of Georgia, where he graduated in 2006. While in Athens, Pittman worked as a staff writer of The Red & Black and eventually became editor-in-chief, pestering school administrators. Like any good Southerner, he prefers his tea sweet, chicken fried and fall Saturdays reserved for college football. He is also surviving as an Atlanta Braves fan in a town full of Washington Nationals supporters.  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
