aV \u000a            By ARTHUR ALLEN  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from David Pittman and Darius Tahir  WHAT DOES \u201cWITHOUT SPECIAL EFFORT\u201d REALLY MEAN? The phrase deep inside the 21st Century Cures Act sets up a tricky little puzzle for ONC\u2019s new chief as he ponders the best way to get better usability and more interoperability into health care.   Story Continued Below  \u2014 With its budget slashed by a third, ONC\u2019s primary duty over the coming year is to fulfill the dictates of the Cures Act, including a section seeking to clear barriers to the flow of health data. On page 337, the law requires EHR vendors to make patient data accessible \u201cwithout special effort, through the use of application programming interfaces.\u201d Many EHR vendors are already developing the types of APIs required in Stage 3 of the meaningful use program. The question is, will these interfaces fit with the intent of the Cures Act? More than that, will they fulfill IT\u2019s promise to improve health care?  \u2014 They won\u2019t, some leading health IT advocates told me, unless the ONC regulates them. EHR vendors must create common, public APIs, in this view, writing the interfaces to specs that allow any eligible app to easily be popped onto any ONC-certified EHR. \u201cThe most useful form of interoperability is substitutability,\u201d says Harvard Medical School professor Kenneth Mandl, director of Boston Children\u2019s Hospital Computational Health Informatics Program.   \u2014 Others, such as Argonaut Project leader Micky Tripathi, are leery of too much government intervention in setting standards for exactly how the APIs should look.   \u2014 The final decision is in the hands of ONC director Donald Rucker, who seems to bel open to suggestions.   The whole story for pros here.  Tweet of the Day: Harlan Krumholz @hmkyale Nice explanation by @Atul_Gawande for why hard for #AI and #bigdata to make diagnoses; the art is in eliciting info.   Welcome to Monday Morning eHealth from glorious San Francisco, where the Giants suck this year, a fact that is satisfying the schadenfreude needs of non-Bay Area sports fans. Share your undignified glee with aallen@politico.com, or tweet something spicy @David_Pittman, @athurallen202, @DariusTahir, @POLITICOPro, @Morning_eHealth.   SPEAKING OF INTEROPERABILITY \u2026 ONC today is hosting the first of three events to gather information about successful network-to-network exchange of health information as outlined in the Cures Act. As part of the meeting, ONC will share a recent analysis of existing frameworks that support the flow of health information across various networks, and principles for enabling trusted exchange. More here.   \u2014 The info-sharing networks Sequoia and DirectTrust took the occasion to issue joint recommendations on ONC\u2019s effort. In a statement to POLITICO, Sequoia\u2019s Marian Yeager and DirectTrust\u2019s David Kibbe encouraged the agency to leverage existing trust frameworks so as to avoid disruption or duplication of the activities of existing national exchange networks, such as their organizations. They also discouraged ONC from seeking a \u201cone-size-fits-all\u201d approach to trust frameworks and urged the agency to recognize the diversity of different data and information sharing approaches.   \u2014 Genevieve Morris, ONC\u2019s principal deputy national coordinator, told Morning eHealth earlier this month that HHS was looking to resolve what she described as a roughly 20 percent difference among the various health information exchanges operating today. Our David Pittman asked Jitin Asnaani, executive director of the CommonWell Health Alliance, about that, but Asnaani wasn\u2019t sure what 20 percent Morris was referring to. \u201cI don\u2019t know what it is and I don\u2019t know if that 20 percent is something that is actually reconcilable or not,\u201d Asnaani told us. \u201cI\u2019m more excited than nervous, but I\u2019d like to know what those differences are.\u201d   \u2014 Sounds like it could be an interesting day for those of us deep in the weeds enough to understand what\u2019s being discussed.  GETTING EHRS TO MENTAL HEALTH WORKERS: Reps. Lynn Jenkins and Doris Matsui last week introduced a bill (H.R. 3331) that would authorize a CMS Innovation Center project to incentivize behavioral health providers to buy EHRs. The program would apply to psychiatric hospitals, community behavioral health centers, residential and outpatient mental health and substance use treatment facilities, as well as clinical psychologists and social workers. More EHR use in mental health would improve care for patients and collaboration with physical health providers, goes the reasoning. But expanding meaningful use to that segment of health care would cost billions that Congress won\u2019t spend. Creating a program within CMMI might be a way around that.   \u2014 On a related matter, CMS\u2019s Innovation Center last week announced a September summit to design a payment and delivery model for behavioral health providers. The Federal Register notice specifically calls out telehealth as an item that CMS wants to hear about.   HOUSE ACTION ON VETERANS TELEMEDICINE: The House Veterans Affairs Committee on Thursday will hold a roundtable on telemedicine, the committee confirms to Morning eHealth. The agenda wasn\u2019t announced, and such events are typically closed to the press, but we expect licensing to be one issue that arises. Congress has long dragged its feet on easing medical licensing requirements so doctors can see patients in multiple states more easily via telemedicine. But some in the industry are trying to rally support for the VETS Act (H.R.2123), which would allow doctors to treat veterans anywhere in the VA system regardless of location. The AMA has successfully suppressed congressional action on the bill, though Senate Vets Chair Johnny Isakson has voiced his support for it.   NURSING COMPACT GOES LIVE: North Carolina last week became the 26 state to enact the enhanced Nurse Licensure Compact, triggering it to take effect in six months, the group is announcing this morning. The FBI has raised legal issues with the interstate physicians\u2019 compact over the sharing of FBI files on doctors, but it hasn\u2019t created the same difficulty for the nursing boards, said David Benton, chief executive of the National Council of State Boards of Nursing. The licensing compact should enable more telemedicine visits because it allows nurse providers to be licensed more quickly and easily in multiple states.  EVERYBODY\u2019S HEARD ABOUT THE BYRD RULE: But did you know that a 60-vote Senate majority is needed to repeal a tiny eHealth section of the Affordable Care Act? The provision in the GOP bill would require HHS Secretary Tom Price to report to Congress recommending whether expenditure data from the Transformed Medicaid Statistical Information System (T-MSIS) is preferable to data from state CMS-64 reports for making certain Medicaid decisions. There. Now you know.   FCC IS ALL EARS: The Federal Communications Commission\u2019s Connect2Health Task Force on Friday announced that it will convene several virtual listening sessions, starting Aug. 7, to generate more input on broadband health issues. The agency will also keep the rural broadband expansion docket open for comment on its Website through Sept. 29. Four listening sessions will held: for health care providers, administrators and CIOs; rural advocacy groups; telecommunications carriers and manufacturers, and finally for lawmakers and state and local health officials. Get a message to the FCC by the end of this week if you want to participate. More details here.   THE ORACLE OF WATERTOWN: Athenahealth\u2019s latest earnings call didn\u2019t contain any direct reference to the big drama consuming the company \u2014 the stock purchases by activist investor Elliott Management \u2014 but CEO Jonathan Bush provided a few interesting tidbits:   \u2014 \u201cMIPS has been largely defanged,\u201d he said \u2014 echoing what our own David Pittman pointed out about a month ago \u2014 and as a result, doctors won\u2019t need to buy new EHRs to improve their performance.   \u2014 The Trump administration, Bush said, deserves credit for helping athenahealth gain designation as a qualified entity, which allows the company to access Medicare claims data and provide a more complete electronic health record for its clients. The government ships the data on \u201ca drive in a padded envelope by certified mail,\u201d Bush said. \u201cWe have people on eBay now looking for machines that can receive this drive.\u201d   \u2014 But CMS is \u201cearnestly trying,\u201d he said. Athena is also getting claims data from \u201call the commercial payers,\u201d he said. Full transcript here.  WHAT WE'RE CLICKING:  DotHealth is the new domain for matters Health, even for Taylor Swift   At SF Forum, docs discuss IT\u2019s ups and downs  Atul Guwande says robots won\u2019t replace doctors  Robert Califf describes life after FDA   Missouri governor defends his PDMP order   Arthur Allen is the eHealth editor for POLITICO Pro.  Becoming editor of eHealth at Politico marked Allen\u2019s return to the newsroom after 18 years of solitude (apologies to Gabriel Garcia Marquez). As a freelancer beginning in 1996, he wrote for publications and websites such as The Washington Post, The New York Times, The New Republic, Slate.com, Landscape Architecture, Global Health Matters, Science and Mother Jones. He also wrote three books, the last of which, \u201cThe Fantastic Laboratory of Dr. Weigl,\u201d comes out in July 2014 (buy your advance copy now!) Once upon a time, when the hairs on Allen\u2019s head were as numerous as pissants on a melon stalk, he was a wire service reporter. He toiled for The Associated Press for the better part of 13 years, including stints in El Salvador, Mexico and Germany. Allen is married to Margaret Talbot; their son heads off to college soon but for now they still have the company of a teenage daughter with impeccable taste in music and style. During Allen\u2019s non-wage earning hours, he may be found playing pickup basketball, studying Polish, reading 19th century novels, or hunting fruitlessly for morels and other edible mushrooms.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
