aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  08/04/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Marianne LeVine, Ian Kullgren and Mel Leonor   TRUMP (FINALLY) REACHES MILLION-JOBS MARK: President Donald Trump's claim that he's created a million jobs finally came true \u2014 months after he first made it. "We've added ... more than a million private sector jobs," Trump said on June 1, when the Labor Department's tally was about 600,000. On Monday White House Press Secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders said, "We've created over a million new jobs since [Trump] took office," when DOL's tally was 863,000. With the Labor Department reporting today that the economy added 209,000 jobs in July, Trump can finally say, truthfully, that he's created more than a million jobs since entering office. Trump tweeted shortly after the report's release "Excellent Jobs Numbers just released \u2014 and I have only just begun. Many job stifling regulations continue to fall. Movement back to USA!"  Story Continued Below  July\u2019s jobs number was a decrease from June, when the economy added 231,000 jobs. But unemployment ticked down to 4.3 percent, compared to June\u2019s 4.4 percent. Average hourly private-sector earnings were up 2.5 percent over the previous year, as they were in June. The pattern of job growth in 2017 remains essentially the same as in 2016. According to the Labor Department, an average of 184,000 jobs per month have been created this year, compared to 187,000 in 2016. If you eliminate January, when President Barack Obama was still in office, the monthly average is a somewhat lower 179,000.   Analysts reacted positively to today's jobs report. "Kind of all-around strong headline number," Tony Bedikian, head of global markets for Citizens Bank, told  CNBC. "More people are coming into the labor force and finding jobs. It's difficult to find anything really negative in the report." Economists surveyed by Bloomberg had predicted the creation in July of about 178,000 jobs, an unemployment rate of 4.3 percent, and an over-the-year increase in hourly earnings of 2.5 percent. The payroll company ADP estimated Wednesday based on its own records that private-sector job growth in July was 178,000. More here.   GOOD MORNING! It's Aug. 4, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.  Pro subscribers: Are you getting all the content you want? Make sure your keywords are up to date and customized via your settings page at http://politico.pro/1iDALk9.  SANDERS, PEREZ WEIGH IN ON NISSAN VOTE: Sen. Bernie Sanders (I-Vt.) took aim at Nissan Thursday as balloting began at its Canton, Miss., plant. In an op-ed published in the Guardian, Sanders accused the auto company of launching \u201cone of the most vicious, and illegal, anti-union crusades in decades.\u201d Nissan supervisors, Sanders wrote, \u201chave called workers off assembly lines for one-on-one interrogations. Anti-union videos are being run on a constant loop in employee break rooms. Groups of workers have been called into \u2018roundtable\u2019 meetings to hear management disparage the United Auto Workers (UAW).\u201d (These allegations surfaced in a lawsuit brought by an NLRB regional director and in complaints from the UAW.)   \u201cCorporations like Nissan know that if they stop workers in Mississippi from forming a union, wages will continue to be abysmally low in this state,\u201d Sanders wrote. \u201cFurther, if workers are unable to form unions and engage in collective bargaining, Americans throughout this country will continue to work for longer hours for lower wages. As Americans, our goal must be to raise wages in Mississippi and all over this country, not engage in a destructive race to the bottom.\u201d   DNC chairman and former Labor Secretary Tom Perez weighed in with an op-ed of his own in USA Today. \u201cThey\u2019ve intimidated workers by threatening plant closures, pay cuts and all-out retribution against those who vote yes,\u201d Perez wrote. \u201cThese threats aren\u2019t only immoral, they\u2019re illegal. In fact, the National Labor Relations Board has recently filed multiple charges against the plant for unfair labor practices." Polls are scheduled to close at 7 p.m. today. Read Sanders here and Perez here.   ACOSTA DEFENDS TRUMP ON IMMIGRATION: Labor Secretary Alexander Acosta on Thursday seconded Trump\u2019s endorsement of a bill that would halve the number of legal immigrants to the U.S. over a decade. Speaking at the Western Governor\u2019s conference in South Dakota, Acosta said immigration can be \u201clegal and appropriate\u201d when a business can\u2019t fill a job, but that \u201cso much immigration\u201d involves foreign workers taking jobs that U.S. workers could fill, the Associated Press reports.   Most economists disagree. A 550-page report published last year by the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering and Medicine found \u201clittle to no negative effects on overall wages and employment of native-born workers in the longer term.\u201d And in April, 1470 economists, Democrat and Republican, signed a letter by the nonprofit Center for a New American Economy that said "the benefits that immigration brings to society far outweigh their costs." More here.   AFT JOINS ARMS WITH PUERTO RICO TEACHERS UNION: The American Federation of Teachers and the Asociacin de Maestros de Puerto Rico \u2014 which represents 40,000 teachers on the island \u2014 voted to affiliate Thursday. Both parties signed a trial affiliation agreement that will carry over through the next three years, as AFT works with AMPR and its locals to expand collective bargaining in the financially-embattled U.S. territory. \u201cEvery country wants to improve its economic and social situation, but in Puerto Rico teachers haven\u2019t been treated fairly,\u201d AMPR President Aida Diaz said. \u201cWith the AFT, we can work hand in hand to improve our working conditions and reclaim all that has been denied to us.\u201d   BORDER WALL BLUES: Trump\u2019s campaign trail vision of a 35-foot concrete wall that spans half of the nearly 2,000-mile U.S.-Mexico border is starting to look a touch \u2026 unrealistic. (Did we mention Mexico would pay for it? More on that below.) \u201cSenate Majority Whip John Cornyn (R-Texas) and three other Senate Republicans rolled out legislation on Thursday making it clear that, in their view, a stand-alone wall running the length of the U.S.-Mexico border \u2014 a core Trump campaign promise \u2014 isn\u2019t the answer,\u201d report POLITICO\u2019s Seung Min Kim and Ted Hesson.   \u201cThe legislation, called Building America\u2019s Trust Act, would allot $15 billion over four years for what its backers call \u2018smart, multi-layered infrastructure\u2019 along the southern border,\u201d the pair write. \u201cThat may include a wall, fence, levees, technology or other barriers, according to a summary of the bill. \u2026 Trump may still insist that funding for the border wall be included in any must-pass government spending measure due by the end of September, provoking a potential government shutdown.\u201d   Cornyn appears to have done his homework. His legislation is backed by the National Border Patrol Council, Federal Law Enforcement Officers Association and the Southwest Border Sheriffs Coalition, among other law enforcement organizations, and he said he incorporated suggestions from DHS as well. \u201cThe Texas Republican stopped short of saying Trump backs the measure, but he sounded optimistic,\u201d POLITICO reports. \u201cWith this president in the White House, we think we have an ally who will help us,\u201d he said. More here.   PLEASE BABY PLEASE BABY PLEASE BABY BABY BABY: A transcript of Trump\u2019s call with Mexican President Enrique Pea Nieto in late January indicated that the newly elected American president was fretting about his campaign promise to make Mexico pay the cost of building the wall. The transcript, published by the Washington Post Thursday, showed Trump pleading with Pea Nieto \u2014 not unlike Mars Blackmon, the character Spike Lee played in his 1986 comedy, "She's Gotta Have It" \u2014 to stop saying Mexico wouldn't pay. "The fact is we are both in a little bit of a political bind," Trump said, "because I have to have Mexico pay for the wall \u2014 I have to. I have been talking about it for a two-year period, and the reason I say they are going to pay for the wall is because Mexico has made a fortune out of the stupidity of U.S. trade representatives." Trump told the Mexican president that he "cannot say [Mexico won't pay for the wall] to the press. The press is going to go with that, and I cannot live with that. You cannot say that to the press because I cannot negotiate under those circumstances."   Pea Nieto was unmoved ("My position has been and will continue to be very firm saying that Mexico cannot pay for that wall"), and even Trump conceded the dispute was, as a substantive matter, trivial. \u201cBelieve it or not, this is the least important thing that we are talking about,\u201d Trump said, \u201cbut politically this might be the most important [to] talk about.\u201d Read POLITICO's summary here and see the whole transcript here.   TILLIS OPTIMISTIC ON H-2B: The Homeland Security Department added 15,000 additional H-2B guest worker visas last month, far below what businesses had hoped for. Employers can use the visas to hire temporary foreign workers in non-agricultural sectors, such as landscaping, but the program hit its 66,000-visa cap in March.   Sen. Thom Tillis (R-N.C.), an advocate for more visas, says he thinks a legislative or regulatory solution can move forward. \u201cWe have people that recognize the need for [agricultural visas] and want to see reforms," he told Morning Shift, "but then they have an irrational objection to H-2B, which is a different kind of work. \u2026 This season, we\u2019re going to see some real business impacts [because of the visa shortage]. We\u2019ve got to communicate that.\u201d   NO MINER SAFETY WORRIES: The White House doesn't worry that injuries will increase as production ramps up in coal mines and regulations are eased, a spokesperson said during a briefing aboard Air Force One Thursday en route to Huntington, W.V. \u201cThe regulations that the president is doing are to help create jobs,\u201d said deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters in response to a press question. \u201cHe's not lowering any safety regulations. Safety is still a top priority, but as the president said, we need to create jobs, we need to bring jobs back to our shores, and send them to the people of West Virginia where coal mining is so prevalent.\u201d Trump hasn\u2019t nominated a chief for the Mine Safety and Health Administration, and Walters wouldn\u2019t comment on when he will.   STAYING PUT: The American tradition of leaving one part of the country to find a better job in another is dwindling, Janet Adamy and Paul Overberg report in the Wall Street Journal. The pair visited the town of West Branch, Mich., for some perspective. \u201cLike a lot of small towns in sparsely populated American counties, West Branch, population 2,067, is in an economic funk brought on by the decline of manufacturing and farm consolidation,\u201d they write. \u201cIn recent years, a handful of retailers, a flour mill and a carpet shop have all closed their doors.\u201d   \u201cWhat is troubling about this rural town and many places like it is that while lots of struggling residents see leaving as the best way to improve their lives, a surprising share remain stuck in place,\u201d they write. \u201cFor a number of reasons \u2014 both economic and cultural \u2014 they no longer believe they can leave.   \u201cIn rural America, which is coping with the onset of socioeconomic problems that were once reserved for inner cities, the rate of people who moved across a county line in 2015 was just 4.1%, according to a Wall Street Journal analysis,\u201d they write. \u2018That\u2019s down from 7.7% in the late 1970s.\u201d This is not a newly-identified trend; POLITICO's Timothy Noah wrote about it in the Washington Monthly in 2013 ("Stay Put, Young Man"). Others have, too. But the decline in job-related domestic migration remains an important, and still greatly under-appreciated, problem that plays havoc with the U.S. labor market and inhibits prosperity. More here.   ICE HITS LABOR HEARINGS: \u201cFederal immigration agents have shown up twice at California labor dispute proceedings to apprehend undocumented workers, in what state officials believe may be cases of employer retaliation,\u201d Natalie Kitroeff writes in the Los Angeles Times. \u201cThe Labor Commissioner\u2019s Office, the state\u2019s labor enforcement arm, said that since November U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents showed up at locations in Van Nuys and Santa Ana looking for workers who had brought claims against their employers.\u201d More here.   KUSHNER COMPANY HIS WITH SUBPOENA: \u201cKushner Cos., the New York property development business owned by the family of White House senior adviser Jared Kushner, has been subpoenaed by New York federal prosecutors regarding its use of an investment-for-immigration program, according to people familiar with the matter,\u201d the Journal\u2019s Erica Orden, Aruna Viswanatha and Byron Tau report.   The program in question is the EB-5 investor visa, which offers foreigners who invest at least $500,000 in a commercial project a path to a green card. The subpoena is tied to a least one residential high-rise financed through the visa program, the 66-story One Journal Square in Jersey City, the Journal reports.   \u201cIn early May, the company drew attention for a marketing campaign in Beijing and Shanghai that solicited Chinese investors for One Journal Square, saying that up to 300 individuals who put $500,000 each into the project could be eligible for green cards under the EB-5 program, according to marketing materials reviewed by The Wall Street Journal.\u201d More here.   COFFEE BREAK   \u2014\u201cFive things to watch in the July jobs report,\u201d from the Wall Street Journal   \u2014 \u201cTyson Foods settles lawsuit with Iowa workers for $5.8 million,\u201d from the Associated Press   \u2014\u201cJudge vacates steel bosses WTC-rebuild conviction,\u201d from Law360   \u2014 \u201cMicrosoft shifts from paying outside lawyers by the hour,\u201d from the New York Times   \u2014 \u201cTrump is considering Perry for Homeland Security chief,\u201d from Bloomberg   \u2014\u201cTrump\u2019s DHS ordered agents to block congressmen during travel ban,\u201d from the Daily Beast   \u2014\u201cLinking public works to local hiring faces a Trump challenge,\u201d from the New York Times   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson  \u000a                                            By Kel McClanahan 
