aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Marianne LeVine, Ian Kullgren, Seung Min Kim and Timothy Noah   WHAT'S SO GREAT ABOUT ECONOMIC GROWTH?: President Donald Trump has a new target: legal immigration. On Wednesday he endorsed the Raise Act, which would halve, over a decade, the number of lawful permanent residents admitted to the U.S. Sponsored by Sens. Tom Cotton (R-Ark.) and David Perdue (R-Ga.), the bill would limit immigration through extended family ties and assign green-card "points" based on education, English-language ability, prospective salary, age, entrepreneurship, and past achievements.   Story Continued Below  White House Senior Adviser Stephen Miller said at a press briefing that the bill would "add to the economy." But most economists would disagree, write POLITICO's Timothy Noah and Marianne LeVine. "Economic growth, as measured by gross domestic product, is an increase in the quantity of goods and services produced by workers," they write. "The more workers, the more goods they can produce. And with U.S. population growing at its slowest pace since the Great Depression, the only way the workforce can expand is through immigration. Economists therefore tend to worry not about there being too much immigration, but rather not enough."   Economists aren't the only ones worried about slowing the workforce's growth. Sen. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) said Wednesday that while he's "always supported merit-based immigration," the bill's dramatic reduction in legal immigration "would be devastating to my state\u2019s economy." Randy Johnson, a senior vice president at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said that although the bill had "many interesting concepts," its halving of legal immigration "won\u2019t raise the standard of living for Americans" but "likely accomplish the opposite, making it harder for businesses, communities, and our overall economy to grow."   Cotton, weirdly, seemed to concede at a Wednesday press briefing that his bill would reduce overall economic growth. GDP "is an important measure, to be sure, but it\u2019s not the only measure of well-being in our society," he said, mentioning GDP per capita as an alternative metric. "We could increase our GDP if we imported the entire population of Bangladesh ... But would that really be in the best interests of the American people?"   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Chuck Grassley (R-Iowa) said he supported the bill, but might not take it up in his committee. It's "a procedural issue," he told Morning Shift, because if the bill acquires too many amendments "Cotton and Perdue aren\u2019t going to get what they want anyway.\u201d Read more from POLITICO's Timothy Noah and Marianne LeVine here and Ted Hesson here.   GOOD MORNING! It's Thursday, August 3, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.   SENATE CONFIRMS KAPLAN: The Senate on Wednesday confirmed Marvin Kaplan, one of Trump's two nominees for the NLRB, on a 50-48 party-line vote, with Sens. John McCain (R-Ariz.) and Richard Burr (R-N.C.) absent. Democrats Elizabeth Warren (Mass.), Sherrod Brown (Ohio), and Patty Murray (Wash.), had some harsh words for Kaplan. Warren, in her floor speech, accused GOP leaders of trying to "sock it to workers one more time" before summer recess. Kaplan, she said, had "no experience practicing labor law," and spent his time while working for Republicans on the House Education and the Workforce Committee "actively stripping workers of their right to organize."   Republicans have high hopes that Kaplan and (when confirmed) NLRB nominee William Emanuel will use the board's new Republican majority to reverse Obama-era decisions. Both the International Franchise Association and National Restaurant Association said they hoped Kaplan will reverse the NLRB's 2015 Browning-Ferris decision, which made it easier for corporations to be held liable for labor violations committed by their franchisees and contractors.   "We are glad the Senate moved quickly on this timely confirmation, which will help move the board in a new direction," House Education and the Workforce Chairman Virginia Foxx (R-N.C.) said in a joint statement with Rep. Tim Walberg (R-Mich). "Hopefully, our Senate colleagues will act swiftly to fill the remaining vacancy so we can have a full slate of board members that puts workers \u2014 not special interests \u2014 first." ("Special interests" in this context means "unions.")   FISCHER INTRODUCES PAID LEAVE: Sen. Deb Fischer (R-Neb.) introduced a voluntary paid family leave bill yesterday along with Sen. Angus King (I-Maine) and Reps. Mike Kelly (R-Pa.) and Terri Sewell (D-Ala.). The Strong Families Act would give a 25 percent tax credit to companies that offer between two and 12 weeks' paid leave. It would cover women and men who need to care for a new child or a sick family member. The tax credit would apply only to wages at or below $72,000 and would be pro-rated based on the level of wage replacement.   Fischer and King introduced similar legislation previously and it went nowhere. To advance, it will likely require a nod from Ivanka Trump, but it's unclear that she will back the proposal; a spokesperson didn't respond to Morning Shift's request for comment. Fischer's bill doesn't offer the mandatory eight weeks' paid parental leave proposed in the president's budget proposal, but the White House may be getting desperate for a legislative victory. More here.   TODAY: NISSAN VOTE BEGINS: More than 3,500 Nissan workers at a plant in Canton, Mississippi, will begin voting today on whether to join the United Auto Workers, in the most closely-watched union election in years. "Caught among an administration that is frequently hostile to labor, a long-term decline in membership, and a steady shift in jobs to the lightly unionized South, the United Automobile Workers long ago settled on this Mississippi town as a key to rebuilding its ranks and energizing the entire labor movement," writes the New York Times' Noam Scheiber. More here.   ACOSTA TO SOUTH DAKOTA: Labor Secretary Alexander Acosta today heads to Sioux Falls, South Dakota, where he'll join Gov. Dennis Daugaard (R) at the Western Governors\u2019 Workforce Development Initiative, an effort to connect workers and employers. They'll hold a joint press conference at 9:30 a.m. EDT, and Acosta will speak about workforce development at 1:30 p.m. EDT.   GREEN CARD LOTTERY, OUT OF LUCK?: The immigration bill endorsed by Trump Wednesday would eliminate the diversity visa lottery, which extends 50,000 visas each year to people from countries with low rates of immigration to the U.S. While the program these days tends to serve African and Eastern European immigrants, its origins date to the 1980s, when Irish immigrants sought a way to live in the U.S. legally, writes Michael Miller in the Washington Post. More here.   FACEBOOK LEANS IN: Facebook's efforts to recruit female workers appear to be working, Yoree Koh reports Tn the Wall Street Journal. "Women now account for 35 percent of global employees, up from 33% the previous year, Facebook said Wednesday. In technical roles\u2014positions where there are typically the fewest female, black and Hispanic employees\u2014the percentage of women has increased from 17 percent to 19 percent." More here.   WORKERS LINE UP TO WORK AT AMAZON: Thousands lined up around the country Wednesday to apply for jobs at Amazon fulfillment centers as the online retailer sought to fill 50,000 positions. The company said "it made scores of job offers on the spot at a dozen locations from Buffalo, N.Y., to Oklahoma City," according to the Washington Post's Abha Bhattarai. More here.   GO MIDWEST, YOUNG MAN: Wichita has plenty of factory jobs, but it can't find workers to fill them, Shayndi Raice writes in The Wall Street Journal. "The problems in Wichita mirror those in other manufacturing areas, where a skills gap has emerged due in part to aging workers and changing technology," Raice writes. "But the turbulent aviation industry \u2014 which is easily affected by economic cycles \u2014 adds another wrinkle to the challenge." More here.   (We can't run an item like this without noting that we at Morning Shift remain less than convinced that a skills gap actually exists. So does the New York Times's Scheiber. Peter Cappelli of the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business is quite brutal on the subject; he says the skills gap is utter hooey.)   EPN: BORDER CALL DIDN'T HAPPEN: Mexico denied Wednesday that Mexican President Enrique Pea Nieto ever praised Trump's border enforcement policies, according to the Wall Street Journal. On Monday Trump gushed over his new chief of staff, former DHS chief John Kelly, by saying "Even the president of Mexico called me" and "said their southern border, very few people are coming because they know they\u2019re not going to get through our border, which is the ultimate compliment." But "a spokesman for [Pea Nieto] said on Wednesday that the last time the two presidents spoke was at the G-20 summit in Germany on July 7," the Journal reported. "The subject of migration was addressed by both leaders at that meeting, but the discussion was informative and not congratulatory, the spokesman added."   Tempting though it is to presume any given Trump statement false until proven otherwise, the president may very well have spoken truthfully in this instance. The two quotations, on examination, are not really contradictory, and arrests at the border really are down. More here.   COFFEE BREAK   \u2014 "Dow passes 22,000, fueled by broad global growth," from The Wall Street Journal   \u2014 "Rosengren: Tight labor markets justify Fed plans to keep rates rising," from The Wall Street Journal   \u2014 "Appeals court won't block Kobach deposition," from POLITICO   \u2014 "Border agents test facial scans to track those overstaying visas," from The New York Times   \u2014 "He went to ICE to tell agents he had gotten into college. Now he and his brother have been deported," from The Washington Post   \u2014 "The good news about the hollowing out of America\u2019s middle class," from Quartz   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.    \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
