aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  08/02/2017 10:01 AM EDT  With help from Marianne LeVine and Ian Kullgren   DOWNSIZING IMMIGRATION: Sens. Tom Cotton (R-Ark.) and David Perdue (R-Ga.) head to the White House this morning to roll out a reworked bill to slash levels of legal immigration and shift the immigration system's emphasis away from family ties and toward skills, Anna Giaritelli reports in the Washington Examiner.   Story Continued Below  The senators first introduced a version of the legislation, S. 354 (115), in February. The bill sought to cut legal immigration in half over a decade (from roughly a million legal immigrants per year down to 500,000) and to limit to spouses and unmarried children the categories of family member who could be sponsored for a green card. In addition, the measure would have ended the diversity visa lottery, which offers 50,000 visas each year to people from nations with low rates of immigration to the U.S.   The pair met with President Donald Trump to discuss the bill in March. While the White House didn't endorse the measure, Cotton said Trump was engaged. \u201cThe president is interested in pursuing those reforms, but also a broader set of reforms that would examine some of the work-related [programs] that are being abused,\u201d he told POLITICO's Seung Min Kim at the time.   POLITICO's Eliana Johnson and Josh Dawsey reported last month that Trump planned to back the reworked bill, but officials stopped short of a confirmation to the Examiner's Giaritelli. More from the Examiner here.   GOOD MORNING! It's Wednesday, August 2, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.  POLITICO Pro Policy Summit, Sept. 14: An all-day summit featuring deep-dive conversations and incisive interviews that explore policy trends inside and outside government. Space is limited to current Pro customers at the director level or above. Learn More.  TODAY:   KAPLAN CLOTURE VOTE: The Senate will hold a cloture vote today on NLRB nominee Marvin Kaplan, POLITICO's Ian Kullgren reports. "The vote is expected to take place as soon as an hour after the Senate convenes at 10 a.m.," according to a leadership source. A vote on the nomination itself will likely occur tomorrow, though it may occur today.   "Kaplan is currently counsel for the Occupational Safety and Health Review Commission," writes Kullgren. "He has held jobs on the House Education and the Workforce and Oversight and Government Reform committees, as well as the Labor Department's Office of Labor-Management and Standards. Senate leadership has not scheduled a vote on President Donald Trump's other NLRB nominee, William Emanuel, meaning it probably will be delayed until after the August recess." Once both nominees are confirmed, the five-member NLRB will flip from majority-Democrat to majority-Republican, allowing it to roll back precedents established under President Barack Obama. More on today's vote here.   PIZZELLA NOMINATION VOTE: The Senate HELP Committee is scheduled to consider the nomination of Patrick Pizzella to become deputy secretary of Labor. During a committee confirmation hearing in July, Pizzella faced sharp questioning from Sen. Al Franken (D-Minn.) over lobbying work he had done decades ago to keep federal labor laws out of the Northern Mariana Islands. The hearing takes place at 11 a.m. in S-216, the President's Room. Watch it here.   LAPAN EYED FOR WHITE HOUSE ROLE: Newly installed White House chief of staff John Kelly may bring his former Homeland Security colleague David Lapan to Pennsylvania Avenue as communication director, CNNMoney's Dylan Beyers reported Tuesday evening. "Lapan, who has worked with Kelly for over a decade, is at the top of a short list to serve as the White House's top official on messaging and communications," wrote Beyers, citing two senior administration officials.   The move would be a significant change in terms of experience from ten days' wonder Anthony Scaramucci. Lapan previously led press shops for the Marine Corps and the Defense Department, and brought a workmanlike professionalism to the DHS role while handling thorny policy issues like the travel ban and the border wall. Kelly has already recruited his former chief of staff at DHS, Kirstjen Nielsen, to assist with his transition to the new role.   Would Lapan take the job? "Obviously I've known [Kelly] for a long time," Lapan told Beyers. "I would take seriously anything he asked. But I would also have to understand more about what it would be and all of those things. So I couldn't say today what my answer would be." Lapan would of course have to take into account that under Trump, White House communications directors turn over faster than Defense Against The Dark Arts teachers in the Harry Potter series. Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry, you'll recall, could never keep anyone teaching Defense Against The Dark Arts more than one school year. But the White House can't keep anyone in the communications director job more than three months. Three people have come and gone just since January (Sean Spicer; Mike Dubke; Sean Spicer, acting; the Mooch). More here.   WHAT ABOUT KOBACH? Who will replace Kelly as Homeland Security secretary? The Great Mentioner is talking up Kansas Secretary of State Kris Kobach \u2014 a vigorous opponent of illegal immigration and vice chair of President Donald Trump's much-criticized panel on alleged voter fraud. Kobach helped draft a controversial law in Arizona, much of it later overturned by the Supreme Court, that required immigrants to carry proof of legal status). Now he seems intent on a bigger role. (At the moment he's running for Kansas governor.) The problem with giving Kobach DHS is that he'd be a highly controversial choice \u2014 "radioactive," in the words of one former DHS official. And there's a decent chance Kelly would oppose putting Kobach in his old job.   SPEAKING OF WHITE HOUSE JOBS: "Bill Shine, a former co-president of Fox News and top lieutenant to the network\u2019s founder, Roger Ailes, has spoken with White House officials about taking a position on President Trump\u2019s communications team, according to several people briefed on the discussions," Michael Grynbaum writes in the New York Times. "Mr. Shine has no political experience outside of producing cable news, and he was forced out of Fox News in May after his name surfaced in lawsuits that accused him of abetting Mr. Ailes\u2019s harassing behavior toward women. (Mr. Shine has denied all wrongdoing, as did Mr. Ailes, who died in May.)" More here.  WIN FOR UBER UNION BACKERS: A federal judge on Tuesday dismissed a court challenge to a Seattle law that allowed drivers of rideshare services to unionize. In late 2015, Seattle became the first city where drivers for companies like Uber and Lyft could join unions, but the U.S. Chamber of Commerce (representing Uber and Lyft) argued in court that the ordinance violated and preempted the National Labor Relations Act. U.S. District Court Judge Robert Lasnik blocked the law from going into effect while the court considered the case.   In an order issued Tuesday, Lasnik granted the city's motion to dismiss, a tentative victory for proponents of the measure. But the injunction against the law will remain in place until the court resolves a separate motion to dismiss in a companion case, Clark v. City of Seattle, brought by 11 drivers. Uber plans to appeal the decision, according to a written statement from Brooke Steger, Uber\u2019s general manager for the Pacific Northwest. "This ordinance was never about benefiting drivers or the community but really about helping Teamsters and protecting taxi companies,\u201d she said. Read more from the AP here and read the order here.   NISSAN HIT WITH RIGGING CLAIM: The UAW is accusing Nissan of taking extreme measures to influence a union election at the Canton, Mississippi plant this week \u2014 including threatening to fire employees and close the plant if they vote to organize. The union points to a consolidated complaint in which an NLRB regional director cites nearly two dozen instances, from 2014 to 2017, in which company officials allegedly intimidated workers.   "After seeing threats and intimidation escalate this month, it\u2019s now clear that Nissan has no intention of letting employees vote in a free and fair election," Gary Casteel, the UAW secretary-treasurer, said in a statement. \u201cNissan is running one of the nastiest anti-union campaigns in the modern history of the American labor movement."   The UAW says that Nissan stepped up its anti-union rhetoric this month after the election dates were set, delivering "threatening" messages in meetings and broadcasting anti-union videos. "Nissan has also prevented a fair campaign by denying Canton workers equal access to arguments in favor of a union," the UAW wrote in press release. "Since the election petition, Nissan has used each day to deliver its threatening anti-union messages in repeated, mandatory meetings with workers, all in order to pressure them to follow Nissan\u2019s instructions to 'VOTE NO.'"   Nissan officials told the Associated Press, which first reported the amended complaint, that it had done nothing wrong. \u201cWe\u2019re staying within the law,\u201d Rodney Francis, the plant's human resources director, told the AP. \u201cWe have the right to communicate our positions.\u201d More here.   COURT OVERTURNS NLRB DECISION: The U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit overturned an NLRB decision Tuesday, saying that managers of a grocery store in a Portland, Oregon, suburb did not violate federal labor laws when they called the cops on union organizers \u2014 and a local lawmaker \u2014 in 2009. The court found that the union organizers, accompanied by an Oregon state representative, took things too far by lingering in the store and arguing with managers \u2014 and police.   "Under these circumstances \u2014 where the individuals arrested had broken with prior practice and then failed to obey the officers\u2019 commands despite repeated opportunities to comply and avoid arrest \u2014 we can hardly say the arrests amounted to a violation on the part of Fred Meyer," the court wrote. "In short, the Board\u2019s actions in this matter are more consistent with the role of an advocate than an adjudicator." More here.   HATCH HAILS END OF MYRA: Senate Finance Chairman Orrin Hatch (R-Utah) praised the Treasury Department Tuesday for ending its myRA program. Created under the Obama administration, the myRA program provided a savings option to employees without a retirement plan at work, offering investments only in government savings bonds.   The Treasury Department said last week that it would shut down the program because of "extremely low" demand. In a letter to Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin, Hatch wrote that "while perhaps well intended, the scheme has not been a net benefit to savers and American taxpayers, and was set up through executive overreach to sidestep the Congress." Hatch argued that employers who promoted the myRA program were "at risk" of becoming a fiduciary under the Employee Retirement Income Security Act. He added that the Treasury Department only had about 30,000 myRA account holders and spent $70 million on the program. "The myRA Roth scheme clearly fails on a cost-benefit basis, and is a failed program," he said. Read the letter here.   CHIPOTLE: HOLD WORKER IN CONTEMPT: Lawyers for Chipotle requested Tuesday that a Texas district court hold in contempt workers who filed a lawsuit against the company. In June, Chipotle workers filed a class action lawsuit, alleging that the company withheld wages owed to them under the Obama administration's overtime rule, even though the rule never took effect because the same Texas court issued an injunction against it.   The workers argued the injunction applied to the Labor Department and not to private parties. But Chipotle disagreed. In its motion for contempt, Chipotle's lawyers argued that the workers' interpretation of the order was incorrect. "This court possesses the inherent authority to enforce its own injunctive decree and to punish those who disobey it," Chipotle argued, adding that the plaintiffs' "dismissive attitude towards this court and disregard for the sanctity of its order \u2014 at Chipotle's expense \u2014 cannot be condoned." Read the motion here.   BARLETTA FOR SENATE? Rep. Lou Barletta (R-Pa.), a long-time opponent of illegal immigration and Trump backer, plans to run for a Senate seat currently held by Sen. Bob Casey (D-Pa.), Marc Levy writes in the Associated Press. "Barletta won his House seat during the Republican midterm wave of 2010, catapulted by the attention he received while mayor of the small city of Hazleton for cracking down on immigrants in the country illegally," Levy writes.   "Casey plans to seek a third six-year term in next year's election," the AP reports. "Democrats' 4-3 ratio registration edge over Republicans gives him a built-in advantage, though that did not stop Trump from becoming the first Republican since 1988 to capture Pennsylvania's crucial electoral votes in the presidential race." The Democrat senator holds very different views from Barletta on immigration. Casey made an impassioned public plea on Twitter in May for then-Homeland Security Secretary John Kelly to halt the deportation in progress of a Honduran woman and her son \u2014 both of whom hoped to seek asylum in the U.S. Kelly preceded with the deportation and contended that the woman had parroted certain phrases to establish an asylum claim when she entered the U.S. More on Barletta's possible challenge here.   ICE PICKS UP 'COLLATORALS': "An Immigration and Customs Enforcement operation to arrest people who entered the country without authorization as kids or as families ended up mostly sweeping up other people who officers encountered along the way," Elise Foley writes in the Huffington Post. "Of 650 arrests carried out during the operation last week, 70 percent of those detained were not the targets, ICE officials said Tuesday. One-fifth of the total arrested had criminal convictions."   "The Trump administration is carrying out what its officials promised: sweeping arrest efforts that do not exempt anyone, regardless of their criminal records or whether they\u2019re the person ICE set out to detain," writes Foley. More here.   MUSLIM OUTREACH OFFICIAL RESIGNS: "George Selim, the federal counterterrorism official who works most closely with the organized American Muslim community, tendered his resignation on Friday," reports Peter Beinart in the Atlantic. Selim had been director of the DHS Office for Community Partnerships and the lead on the department's Countering Violent Extremism Task Force. \u201cThere were clearly political appointees in this administration who didn\u2019t see the value of community partnerships with American Muslims,\u201d Selim told Beinart. More here.   OUTSOURCERS TOP LIST OF H-1B USERS: A newly released trove of visa data from U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services shows "the widely made complaint about the visa program is true: a small number of IT outsourcing companies get a disproportionately high number of H-1B visas and pay below-average wages to their workers," Youyou Zhou writes in Quartz. More here.   COFFEE BREAK   \u2014 "Hiring seafood workers in Bristol Bay has been tough for years. This summer, it\u2019s even worse," from the Alaska Dispatch News   \u2014 "Minimum wage, paid leave questions proposed for 2018 Mass. ballot," from CBS Boston   \u2014 "Border lawmakers call for Paxton to rescind DACA letter," from the El Paso Times   \u2014 "Senators pressure retailers to root out \u201cshameful\u201d labor abuse of truckers," from USA Today   \u2014 "Uber's search for new CEO is a bumpy ride," from the Los Angeles Times   \u2014 "Worried sick about losing a job," from The Wall Street Journal   \u2014 "U.S. manufacturing activity continued to expand in July," from The Wall Street Journal   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
