aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  08/01/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Marianne LeVine and Ian Kullgren   WHITE HOUSE QUASHES SESSIONS-TO-DHS SCENARIO: DHS employees are still wondering who will get the top job now that former Homeland Security Secretary John Kelly has taken the White House chief of staff post.   Story Continued Below  A source close to Kelly told POLITICO on Friday that it's unclear who will replace him. But one scenario that circulated among Homeland Security staffers involved Attorney Jeff Sessions swinging from the Justice Department to DHS, a move that would extricate Sessions from the Russia investigation and allow Trump to put someone else into the attorney general role.   That option isn't being discussed, according to White House press secretary Sarah Huckabee Sanders, who took over the lead spokesperson position when Sean Spicer resigned earlier this month. (In case you've lost track, Spicer reportedly quit over the hiring of Anthony Scaramucci as communication director. After 10 days on the job, Scaramucci was pushed out on Monday as Kelly assumed the chief of staff role.)   At a press conference mainly dominated by questions about Scaramucci's abrupt departure, Huckabee Sanders poured cold water on the possibility that Sessions could move over to DHS. \u201cThere are no conversations about any Cabinet members moving in any capacity,\u201d she said during the press conference. \u201cThe president has 100 percent confidence in all members of his Cabinet.\u201d   GOOD MORNING! It's Tuesday, August 1, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.   FORMER ICE BOSS ON DHS VACANCY: A former head of U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement can envision Trump sticking with a military leader to helm the Homeland Security Department, she told Morning Shift. Julie Myers Woods \u2014 who oversaw ICE from 2006 to 2008 and is currently the CEO of Guidepost Solutions \u2014 said Kelly was liked and respected at DHS, which could set the stage for someone else from the armed forces.   On her list? Retired U.S. Coast Guard Adm. Thad Allen, who now works as an executive vice president at Booz Allen Hamilton (Morning Shift couldn\u2019t immediately reach him for comment). Allen was involved in the response to Hurricane Katrina and served as \u201ca rare reassuring presence in the troubled federal efforts to control the Gulf oil spill,\u201d according to Time, which highlighted his work in 2010. \u201cI think he\u2019s really seen as a strong leader and someone the department could look up to,\u201d said Myers Wood. She added that \u201cDHS is about to implement some highly controversial policies,\u201d from so-called extreme vetting to an expansion of expedited removal, and could use an experienced hand on the wheel.   The former ICE official also said Rep. Michael McCaul (R-Texas) would be an \u201cexcellent choice\u201d for secretary. \u201cHe has provided very thoughtful oversight \u2026 and been a strong advocate for the department,\u201d she said. And what about that #NeverMcCaul hashtag immigration restrictionists (who think the Texas Republican would be too soft) have been circulating on Twitter? \u201cAnyone that is nuanced on immigration in any way is criticized on both sides,\u201d she said.   MILLION JOBS? NOT QUITE: Trump's White House likes to say he has created a million\u2014even more than a million \u2014 jobs since he's been in the Oval Office. Problem is, it's been wrong the whole time. When Trump made the claim June 1 during remarks announcing the U.S. withdrawal from the Paris climate agreement, the economy had actually added 600,000 jobs from February through May.   Sarah Huckabee Sanders repeated the million-jobs assertion during Monday's press briefing. This time it was slightly less wrong, since the economy had added 222,000 more jobs in June. But she was still 200,000 short. If Trump gets a good July jobs report on Friday, he might be able to correctly argue he's created a million jobs \u2014 but that's after months of missing the mark.   GADE TAPPED FOR EEOC: Trump plans to nominate Daniel Gade to the remaining part of a five-year term on the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, the White House announced Monday night. Gade is a veteran of the Iraq War and former official in the George W. Bush administration. He taught political science and public policy at West Point from 2011 until he retired from the Army earlier this year, according to the White House. The EEOC term would expire July 1, 2021.   OSHA LAGS ON PRESS RELEASES: Trump's OSHA continues to lag behind Presidents Barack Obama and George W. Bush in putting out press releases on safety fines given to companies, according to Jordan Barab, a former Obama OSHA official who runs the workplace safety blog Confined Space. "OSHA has issued two ... enforcement-related press releases this month, out of probably 50 cases that exceeded $40,000," Barab writes in a post published Monday. "In the first three weeks of July there were 13 cases above $70,000, the press release threshold during the Bush administration, and 7 cases over $100,000 during that time.   "I\u2019m hoping that Loren Sweatt, OSHA\u2019s new political deputy assistant secretary (the acting head of the agency) will have the courage to re-instate press releases, recognizing that press releases are not primarily about embarrassing employers," he wrote. "They are about making sure that employers and workers know that there is a law that requires employers to provide a safe workplace, and that OSHA inspectors are out there inspecting workplaces and enforcing the law." OSHA didn't immediately respond to requests for comment. More here.   GUILTY VERDICT FOR ARPAIO: "A federal judge in Arizona found former Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio guilty of criminal contempt on Monday for violating an order in a racial-profiling case," POLITICO's Ted Hesson reports. "U.S. District Court Judge Susan Bolton said the evidence in the case showed a 'flagrant disregard' for a 2011 court order that required the sheriff to stop detaining people unless they were suspected of a crime."   "The 85-year-old Arpaio, who lost a reelection bid last year, earned a reputation during his tenure for his tough stance against illegal immigration and headline-grabbing approach to criminal justice, dressing inmates in pink underwear and operating an open-air 'tent city' jail in the scorching Arizona heat," POLITICO reports. "But his renegade approach to law enforcement also attracted litigation. One class-action lawsuit that began a decade ago accused the sheriff\u2019s office of racial profiling of Hispanics during traffic stops."   The order issued Monday by Judge Bolton found that Arpaio had \u201cwillfully violated\u201d an order for his office to stop detaining people (i.e., suspected undocumented immigrants) if they couldn't be charged with a crime. "The former lawman, who is scheduled for sentencing Oct. 5, faces a maximum of six months in jail for the misdemeanor offense," Hesson writes. Read the story here and the judge's order here.   HOTELS BOOM, EVEN WITH $15 WAGE: The $15 minimum wage is not stopping hotel developers from investing in SeaTac, Washington, Julie Weed reports in The New York Times. Nine hotels are under construction, and develops appear unfazed by the 2013 wage hike. Michael Mahoney, president of Western International, a Dallas-based development company, said that the $15 minimum wage was not a determining factor in his decision to build a Marriott Residence Inn.   "We are competing for quality people seeking the best jobs, so would likely have been at that threshold anyway,\u201d he told the Times. Jeff Robinson, SeaTac's director of community and economic development, said "hoteliers had adapted to the ordinance, which requires any hotel with at least 100 rooms or 30 full-time employees to pay the $15 minimum wage." He added that "nobody eliminated rooms to get under it." More from the Times here.   DEMS: AFFIRM BARGAINING RIGHTS: Democrats urged Trump last week to affirm the collective bargaining rights of workers at a Nissan facility in Canton, Mississippi. In a letter led by Rep. Mark Pocan (D-Wis.), the lawmakers requested that Trump tell Nissan to "shift its posture towards the organizing drive at the facility in Canton to neutral." They said the Canton plant, along with two facilities in Tennessee, are Nissan's "only plants in the world without unions and meaningful representation."   Workers at the Canton plant will vote Thursday and Friday on whether to join the United Auto Workers union, which has tried since 2012 to unionize the facility. According to the Huffington Post's Dave Jamieson, last week managers called workers off the floor and into large meetings. "Using slides to make their case, they tried to show employees all the bad things that can happen after unionizing," Jamieson writes. Read the letter here.   7TH CIRCUIT DECLINES TO REVIVE ADA CASE: The 7th Circuit Court of Appeals declined Monday to revive a case that addressed whether the city of Evanston violated the Americans with Disabilities Act when it fired an employee after he experienced a brain injury. When the employee returned from temporary disability, the employer alleged that he was unable to perform the tasks and fired him. In response, the employee sued, arguing that he was fired because of his disability. A lower court sided with the employee and the appeals court agreed. Read the opinion here.   OIG: 15,000 IMM AGENTS ISN'T EASY: A report released Monday by the DHS Office of Inspector General lays out the challenges the Trump administration will face if it wants to hire 15,000 additional Border Patrol agents and ICE officers, as the president directed in a pair of executive orders signed in January. The report suggests that getting Congress to approve funding for the extra personnel would only be part of the battle.   One major concern is whether people will be interested in the jobs. For some perspective: Trump's executive order calls for 5,000 additional Border Patrol agents. To reach that level, the agency would need to attract 750,000 applicants, according to a U.S. Customs and Border Protection estimate cited in the report. "DHS needs to gather better data on attrition and understand why employees are leaving so it can potentially improve the use of incentives, both monetary and nonmonetary, for human resource and law enforcement positions," the report reads.   Rep. Bennie Thompson (D-Miss.), ranking member on the House Homeland Security Committee, said the report shows a hiring surge would "only exacerbate underlying problems" at CBP and ICE. Thompson said the administration "should understand that skimping on workforce planning is an irresponsible waste of limited resources." More here.   POLL: BORDER WALL, MEH: A majority of likely voters don't want a wall along the U.S.-Mexico border, according to a survey released Monday by Rasmussen Reports. The poll found 56 percent opposed the wall construction, while 37 percent thought it was a good idea. House Republicans passed a spending package last week that included $1.6 billion for 74 miles of border fence and wall, but dodged a risky floor vote to get the wall dollars approved. See the poll here.   CALIF FACTORY JOBS, FOR NOW: "Warehouses have hired tens of thousands of California workers over the last five years to help fuel the fast-rising industry of online retail," Mike McPhate writes in The New York Times. In the past year, Amazon has announced four new fulfillment centers in California's inland cities "where real estate is cheaper and the labor force is plentiful," McPhate writes. One researcher found the addition of 10,000 new warehouse jobs in San Joaquin Valley slashed the unemployment rate nearly in half over five years, a pretty impressive boost to the local economy.   "Still, the good economic news has been shadowed by questions over the growing role of automation in the retail business," the Times reports. "Amazon says robotic machines work in tandem with humans at its warehouses, rather than replacing them. But the industry is pushing hard to expand the frontiers of such technology, raising doubts not just about warehouse jobs but delivery work that could be made obsolete by driverless cars and drones." More here.   TEXAS SHERIFFS JOIN 287(G): Federal immigration officials on Monday announced agreements with 18 Texas counties that will allow local police to enforce immigration laws, Dianne Solis and Ray Leszcynski write in the Dallas News. The president signed an executive order in January that calls for the Homeland Security department to engage with state and local officials to broker what are known as 287(g) agreements. In addition to the aforementioned counties, the city of Carrollton has also agreed to cooperate with federal officials. "With 19 local entities on board, Texas accounts for almost one-third of the 60 pacts nationwide," the Dallas News reports. More here.   COFFEE BREAK   \u2014 "Bernie Sanders' campaign isn't over," from The New Yorker   \u2014 Opinion: "Why India\u2019s ban on self-driving cars is misguided," from The Washington Post   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
