aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  07/31/2017 10:00 AM EDT  JOB OPENING AT DHS: John Kelly will leave his leadership role at Homeland Security today and decamp to the White House, where he'll take over for Reince Priebus as President Donald Trump's chief of staff. The Cabinet shakeup rocked Washington through the weekend and effectively serves as a coda to the president's turbulent first six months in office. (Just how turbulent has it been? Peter Baker wrote in the New York Times that presidential historians had to look back more than 100 years to find examples of presidents who experienced such a "combination of internal warfare and external legislative troubles.")   The move means the top post at Homeland Security \u2014 a key administration position given Trump's central focus on illegal immigration and counterterrorism efforts \u2014 will be up for grabs. A person close to Kelly told POLITICO that it's unclear who will replace him, but Deputy Secretary Elaine Duke will become acting secretary today and gives the department a steady hand following Kelly's abrupt transition.   Story Continued Below  One leading contender is House Homeland Security Chairman Michael McCaul (R-Texas), POLITICO's Ted Hesson and Andrew Restuccia wrote Friday. "The Texas Republican competed for the secretary role in November," POLITICO reports. "He introduced an immigration bill on Friday that would provide $10 billion for Trump\u2019s border 'wall,' a pot of funds that would pay for a mix of wall, fence, technology and aerial surveillance over four years, while boosting Border Patrol by 5,000 agents \u2014 the level Trump called for in a January executive order."   Still, McCaul would face intense opposition from some groups that seek to reduce immigration. Mark Krikorian, executive director of the Center for Immigration Studies, tweeted "NOOOOOOOOOOOOO!" to the suggestion that McCaul could see an easier path to confirmation than other candidates, and the hashtags #NoWallMcCaul and #NeverMcCaul made the rounds on Twitter over the weekend.   Other names that surfaced were Thomas Homan, acting director of U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement, Kansas Secretary of State Kris Kobach and Duke. The confirmation fight for any secretary will likely be heated, but Homan and Kobach in particular could encounter fierce resistance from Democrats. Homan has been the face of ICE's broad immigration crackdown; Kobach is helping to lead Trump's controversial commission on alleged voter fraud.   Rumors circulated among DHS staffers that Attorney General Jeff Sessions could swing over to the Homeland Security Department, a move that would let Trump appoint a new official to head the Justice Department and lead the Russia investigation. Sen. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) doesn't like that idea, however, and voiced his opinion over the weekend. "AG Jeff Sessions has a good ring to it. Highly qualified, committed to the rule of law, tough on crime, and fiercely independent," he said in a two-part tweet Saturday. "DHS Secretary Jeff Sessions doesn't sound right, doesn't feel right. Bad idea."   The Trump administration doesn't need to rush to fill the position, as James Norton, founder of the consulting firm Play-Action Strategies and a former DHS official during the George W. Bush administration, told Morning Shift. Duke has "enough experience to guide the ship," Norton points out. And Congress is heading into its August recess, which means the confirmation likely wouldn't take place until the fall. More on possible candidates here.   GOOD MORNING! It's Monday, July 31, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.  NIELSEN TO THE WHITE HOUSE: John Kelly will bring DHS chief of staff Kirstjen Nielsen with him to the White House, POLITICO's Andrew Restuccia reports. Sources told Restuccia her title is still in flux, but CNN reported Saturday that she was expected to become deputy chief of staff. More from POLITICO here and CNN here.   TRUMP'S RUST BELT PUSH: The president has made a point of highlighting positive economic news in the Rust Belt states that helped hand him the election, Eli Stokols and Eric Morath write in the Wall Street Journal. "This week\u2019s announcement that the Chinese iPhone manufacturer Foxconn Technologies has committed to building a $10 billion plant continued the pattern," the pair write. "It was delivered in Wisconsin, a Democratic stronghold for three decades where Mr. Trump bulldozed through Hillary Clinton\u2019s firewall on Election Night."   But some analysts see the job creation announcements as more braggadocio than substance. \u201cThe White House calling out Carrier and other employers is more about public relations than great economic impact,\u201d Adam Kamins, senior economist at Moody\u2019s Analytics, told the Journal. \u201cThe amount of taxpayer money being thrown at these firms to attract them to certain states is pretty exorbitant. That creates a high bar in terms of the number of jobs that need to be created for the investment to pay off.\u201d   Foxconn agreed to hire 3,000 workers when the factory opens in 2020 and may eventually expand that number to 22,000, the Journal reports. At the same time, however, the company will receive $3 billion in tax breaks from the state of Wisconsin. More here.   WISCONN VALLEY?: When Wisconsin Gov. Scott Walker and Foxconn founder and chairman Terry Gou signed a memo of understanding last week over the factory deal, badges distributed to attendees read "Welcome to Wisconn Valley." The Badger State is only the latest state or city to promote itself as the next tech hub, but it has a long way to go, as Sarah Kessler writes in Quartz. "Large factories alone do not a Silicon Valley make, partly because they\u2019re expensive," Kessler writes. She quotes Christopher Balding, a professor of economics at Peking University in China. \u201cWisconsin can only have so many $10 billion plant investments before they face a real budgetary problem,\u201d he said. More here.   HOW ABOUT CANADA?: President Trump's immigration crackdown has inspired Canada to vie for tech businesses that might have otherwise come to the U.S., David George-Cosh and Jacquie McNish write in The Wall Street Journal. "The pitch: Come to Canada, where there are cosmopolitan cities, affordable health care and, most important, more certainty around work permits and entrance requirements that many executives feel is lacking under the Trump administration," The Journal reports. "Ben Zifkin, chief executive of Hubba Inc., tells potential employees currently in the U.S.: 'You don\u2019t have to stay in Canada forever, just the current presidential term.'" More here.   EMPLOYERS LOOK TO EX-CONVICTS: The tight labor market has encouraged employers to consider former inmates to fill vacant positions, Jeffrey Sparshott writes in The Wall Street Journal. Karen Hellman, the director of inmate programs and re-entry at the Arizona Department of Corrections said more companies in the state are trying to hire ex-convicts this year, The Journal reports. "National data on hiring of ex-offenders isn\u2019t available, but other state correctional systems across the U.S. and training programs for ex-offenders report similar experiences."   From the Journal: \u201cI\u2019ve never dealt with employers who are more willing to hire ex-felons,\u201d said John Nally, who started working at the Indiana Department of Correction in 1967 and is now its director of education. \u201cIt is a totally different landscape when you have an unemployment rate of 3.6 percent. We have all these people in construction who are literally begging for workers.\u201d More here.   STEELWORKERS, GOODYEAR STRIKE DEAL: "The United Steelworkers and Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. have reached a tentative contract agreement that covers about 7,000 workers at five plants," the Associated Press reports. "Goodyear says the five-year agreement covers workers at plants in Fayetteville, North Carolina; Akron, Ohio; Danville, Virginia; Gadsen, Alabama; and Topeka, Kansas. The agreement was reached late Saturday night, just before union officials said workers were ready to go on strike." More here.   GET YOUR ACT TOGETHER: The president's criticism of Attorney General Jeff Sessions (whom he's called "beleaguered" and blasted for a "VERY weak position on Hillary Clinton crimes") has exasperated at least one immigration restrictionist group. \u201cThe administration is having a hard time getting out of its own way,\u201d Ira Mehlman, a spokesman for the Federation for American Immigration Reform, told the New York Times. \u201cThe seeming disarray in the White House obviously makes it hard for the administration to carry out its policies.\u201d More here.   TRAVEL BAN STRANDS ORPHANS: A 16-year-old Eritrean orphan remains stuck in an Ethiopian refugee camp as a result of Trump's travel ban, the Washington Post's Justin Moyer reports. "On July 19, the Supreme Court allowed the Trump administration\u2019s travel ban to stand, leaving about 100 unaccompanied minor refugees stranded overseas," he writes. "The decision comes after months of judicial back-and-forth over the ban, casting doubt on the children\u2019s plans to live in the United States. \u2026 The result: M.T., an orphan who fled child labor in Eritrea two years ago and was approved by the State Department to live in the United States, remains in legal limbo." More here.   UNION RIGHT TO WORK WIN: "A union-led attempt to dump Missouri\u2019s new \u201cright to work\u201d law scored a victory in court Friday," the St. Louis Post-Dispatch reports. "The Missouri Court of Appeals Western District overturned a lower court decision that said the language of a proposed ballot initiative seeking to nix the new law was unfair and insufficient." More here.   COFFEE BREAK   \u2014 "U.S. companies post profit growth not seen in six years," from The Wall Street Journal   \u2014 Opinion: "While Boeing touts profits, workforce shrinks," from the Seattle Times  \u2014 "Fast food chains are coping with their labor cost problem," from Yahoo Finance   \u2014 \u201cWho is Elaine Duke, the deputy at Homeland Security?\u201d from CNN   \u2014 "Activists decry latest attempt to force out the Dreamers," from the Washington Times   \u2014 "Trump's battle over LGBT discrimination is just beginning," from the Atlantic   \u2014 "Growers rely on dwindling immigrant workforce to harvest onions," from the Spokesman-Review   \u2014 "Jesus Lara Lopez prays for a miracle after deportation to Mexico," from Cleveland.com   \u2014 "Guest worker visas a complex cure for vineyard labor shortage," from the San Francisco Chronicle   \u2014 "Border mayors talk trade, border crossings and the wall," from the San Diego U-T   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
