aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Marianne LeVine and Ian Kullgren   TRUMP TO LONG ISLAND: President Donald Trump will travel to Suffolk County, L.I., today, where he'll talk about the street gang that his administration is determined to make the most famous in America, MS-13. Is MS-13 scary? You bet. Is it growing? Not so's anybody can tell; its numbers have been estimated at around 10,000 for more than a decade. But MS-13 is Salvadoran, and that's what makes the gang useful to Trump.   Story Continued Below  "The president will use his Friday speech to urge Congress to back his border wall with Mexico and to greenlight funding for new Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents and immigration judges," writes POLITICO's Andrew Restuccia. At the same time, the emotionally bruised Attorney General Jeff Sessions will be in El Salvador, meeting with President Salvador Snchez Cern to discuss efforts against crime and illegal immigration.   The Trump speech is part of a larger push to link crime and immigration, and make the case for more enforcement funding. \u201cI think it\u2019ll be very hard for Democratic lawmakers to vote against hiring ICE officers and the other resources we need to remove some of these dangerous and violent people, like MS-13, from our country, who are quite literally terrorizing communities, committing the most heinous kinds of crimes imaginable,\u201d an administration official told Restuccia.   But that's assuming Democrats buy the idea that undocumented immigrants cause more crime than anyone else, which researchers consistently say isn't true. On top of that, alleged gang members \u2014 not just MS-13, but all gang members \u2014 make up a tiny proportion of ICE's arrest total. And the gang members ICE does arrest are usually \u2026 uh \u2026 U.S. citizens. Back in May, the agency announced it had picked up 1,378 suspected gang members and their affiliates. Of those, 933 were citizens. Fewer than one-third were in the country illegally.   Democrats have taken a hard line against Trump's deportation agenda, and it's hard to imagine this trek to Long Island will change their minds. During Trump's first 100 days in office, ICE arrests of non-criminals climbed 157 percent compared to the same period a year earlier. More from POLITICO's Restuccia here.   GOOD MORNING! It's Friday, July 28, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.  JOINT EMPLOYER PATH FORWARD: House Republicans who want to rewrite the joint employer standard got a boost Thursday when Rep. Bradley Byrne (R-Ala.) introduced a bill supported by at least one Republican leader and a pair of Democrats.   House Majority Leader Kevin McCarthy (R-Calif.) signaled the House leadership would support his effort to roll back the NLRB's 2015 Browning-Ferris decision, which made it easier to hold corporations liable for workplace violations committed by their contractors and franchisees. "[The bill] will treat American businesses fairly again so they can go back to what they do best \u2014 hiring workers and providing quality products and services for their customers," McCarthy said in a written statement.   Is the bill a priority? House Education and the Workforce Chairwoman Virginia Foxx (R-N.C.) told reporters she hadn't received word from leadership on when she might bring the bill to the floor. But Byrne insisted the bill would win over enough Democrats to get a filibuster-proof 60 votes in the Senate, noting that Reps. Henry Cuellar (D-Tex.) and Lou Correa (D-Calif.) are cosponsors. "We are dead serious about not just passing it out of the House," Byrne said, "but getting it over to the Senate and getting 60 votes."   Some on the left are determined not to let that happen, saying the legislation, H.R. 3441, would allow employers to shirk workplace protections. \u201c[The bill] immunizes joint employers from liability, even if they share contractual control of wages, benefits, scheduling, or discipline," Rep. Bobby Scott (D-Va.), the ranking member on House Ed and the Workforce, said Thursday in a written statement.   HOUSE PASSES BORDER WALL FUNDS: The House passed a defense spending package on Thursday afternoon that included $1.6 billion in funding for Trump's border wall. The bill, H.R. 3219 (115), doesn't technically fund a wall -- it would pay for 60 miles of new bollard-style fence and levee wall in South Texas and 14 miles of replacement fence in the San Diego area \u2014 but it spares House Republicans the embarrassment of giving Trump nothing at all, which seemed a real possibility this week.   The border funding was attached to the defense portion of the \u201cminibus,\u201d which also included funding for energy, veterans' affairs and the legislative branch. But despite what Democrats conceded was a tough vote \u2014 against military funding \u2014 they largely rejected the package. Five Democrats voted in favor: Reps. Sanford Bishop (Ga.), Charlie Crist (Fla.), Josh Gottheimer (N.J.), Tom O'Halleran (Ariz.) and Kyrsten Sinema (Ariz.). Likewise, five Republicans opposed the measure: Reps. Justin Amash (Mich.), John Duncan (Tenn.), Walter Jones (N.C.), Thomas Massie (Ky.) and Mark Sanford (S.C.).   The big question: Can Republicans convince any Senate Democrats to fund a similar border boost? Minority Leader Chuck Schumer called the border wall a "poison pill" rider before it was rejected from an earlier appropriations bill, and he isn't likely to change that opinion this time. Morning Shift spoke with a pair of Democratic aides who similarly said, "Hell no" and "No way." Read more about the House spending package from POLITICO's Sarah Ferris here.   Meanwhile, construction of border wall prototypes "has been delayed until winter at the earliest after bidders who were passed over filed protests about the decision," CNN's Tal Kopan reports. "The delay pushes back construction of the potential wall designs months beyond when the administration had hoped to break ground."   Earlier this year DHS reprogrammed $20 million in existing funds to develop border wall prototypes. Hundreds of companies bid on the project, but this latest delay wasn't the first. "The plan had originally been to build in June, and in recent weeks the Department of Homeland Security has insisted it was still on track to begin work on prototypes this summer," writes Kopan. Read more here.   KING BACKS OUT: "Retired Jones Day Lawyer G. Roger King has withdrawn his name for consideration for National Labor Relations Board general counsel," Chris Opfer reports for Bloomberg BNA, citing an anonymous source. King, who works for the HR Policy Association and is a usual suspect on the D.C. labor-policy circuit, was thought a shoo-in to succeed Richard Griffin when his term ends in November. King didn't respond to requests for comment. More from BNA here.   TODAY: DEM DREAMER BILL: Rep. Luis Gutierrez (D-Ill.) will introduce the American Hope Act, "a permanent legislative solution" for undocumented immigrants covered by the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program, along with other immigrant youth, according to a related announcement. He'll be joined by Democratic leaders and members of the Congressional Hispanic Caucus at a press conference today at 11 a.m. in Studio A of the House Radio/TV Gallery, House Visitor\u2019s Center. Watch it here.   MOST TOXIC WORKPLACE IN AMERICA: That would be the White House, where communications chief Anthony Scaramucci, with Trump's apparent blessing, was quoted yesterday in two news outlets saying exceptionally vicious and otherwise unhinged things about his coworkers Reince Priebus and Steve Bannon. An interview the Mooch gave the New Yorker's Ryan Lizza was the more outrageous (that's where he said "\u201cReince is a fucking paranoid schizophrenic" and "I\u2019m not Steve Bannon, I\u2019m not trying to suck my own cock"), but Scaramucci's interview with CNN was no slouch either ("I don't know if this is repairable or not," the Mooch said, with breathtaking presumption, of his relationship with Priebus. Also: "The fish stinks from the head down. But I can tell you two fish that don't stink, and that's me and the president"). David Mamet, call your office.   APPLE IN A PICKLE: Earlier this week, Trump put Apple in an awkward position when he told the Wall Street Journal that the company planned to build three plants in the United States. Although Foxconn Technology (Apple's largest contract manufacturer) said Wednesday that it would invest $10 billion in a display-panel factory, that investment was not part of the "three potential Apple facilities to which the president had referred," Tripp Mickle reports in the Wall Street Journal.   "Supply-chain experts and analysts say the prospect of Apple building one plant in the U.S. \u2014 much less three \u2014 is highly unlikely," Mickle writes. "Apple has built a sophisticated supply chain in China because that is where component suppliers are located, and manufacturing workers are abundant there. Shipping iPhone or iPad materials to the U.S. for production would cut into Apple\u2019s profit margins, observers say." More here.   SPEAKING OF FOXCONN: Wisconsin Gov. Scott Walker has offered up to $3 billion in state tax breaks for Foxconn to build a factory, Danielle Paquette reports in the Washington Post. "As long as Foxconn keeps hiring U.S. workers at the new flat-screen manufacturing facility, Wisconsin would cut the company $200 million to $250 million a year for up to 15 years," she writes. "That works out to a rough cost to the state of about $230,700 per worker, assuming the factory goes on to generate 13,000 jobs." More here.   AND SPEAKING OF FACTORIES: "Economic reports Thursday offered encouraging signals about U.S. factories, jobs and underlying demand in the economy ahead of a much-anticipated report on national output Friday," Josh Mitchell writes in the Wall Street Journal. More here.   DHS CANDIDATE WITHDRAWS: "A candidate for a senior position at the Department of Homeland Security withdrew from consideration on Wednesday, citing President Donald Trump\u2019s decision to ban transgender people from serving in the military," POLITICO's Andrew Restuccia and Kyle Cheney report. "John Fluharty, a former executive director of the Delaware Republican party, informed a DHS official in an email Wednesday morning that he was pulling out of contention to be the assistant secretary of partnership and engagement at the department." More here.   REUTERS: REFUGEES IN MILLER'S HANDS: The president can set the number of refugees the country should accept in the coming fiscal year \u2014 and White House policy adviser Stephen Miller, an impassioned opponent of legal and illegal immigration, will take the lead on the decision, Arshad Mohammed and Yeganeh Torbati report in Reuters.   The White House Domestic Policy Council, which reports to Miller, "is taking the lead on a decision about how many refugees to admit to the United States next year \u2026 a move that may empower those who wish to reduce immigration," according to Reuters. The council appears to be "adopting a role traditionally handled by National Security Council and State Department officials." More here.   PROVOST PROFILE: The New York Times' Ron Nixon profiled Border Patrol Acting Chief Carla Provost, "the first woman to lead the Border Patrol in its 93-year history," he writes. "When Ms. Provost joined [in 1975], agents patrolled wide-open borders with just their weapons and a few vehicles," Nixon reports. "Today\u2019s Border Patrol operates with drones, high-tech sensors, surveillance cameras, military-style body armor and high-powered rifles."   "What hasn\u2019t changed is the ratio of women to men," he continues. "Ms. Provost cites a number of reasons, among them the remote, rugged locations. It\u2019s often solitary duty, with large stretches of time patrolling alone, facing constant threats from dangerous drug and human smuggling organizations." More here.   COFFEE BREAK   \u2014"Charlie Baker drafting legislation to honor ICE hold requests," from the Boston Herald   \u2014"New Hampshire may delay opening of $48 million prison over staffing challenges," from the Wall Street Journal   \u2014"Justice Department says no LGBT protection in federal sex-discrimination law," from POLITICO   \u2014"Violence can be as powerful as economics in driving immigration," from the Wall Street Journal   \u2014"Inside the minimum wage data war," from Seattle Weekly   \u2014"American Airlines workers protest over pay, outsourcing," from the Associated Press   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.    \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
