aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  07/27/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Marianne LeVine and Ian Kullgren   IT'S JOINT EMPLOYER DAY: Republicans on the House Education and the Workforce Committee will introduce their much-anticipated "joint employer" bill at a 10 a.m. press conference. Republicans loathed the Obama NLRB's 2015 Browning-Ferris decision, which made it easier to hold corporations liable for workplace violations committed by their contractors and franchisees \u2014 and therefore, for instance, to sue McDonald's Corp. in an ongoing administrative law proceeding brought by NLRB general counsel Robert Griffin. (Griffin, an Obama appointee, is still there. Trump is stuck with him until Griffin's term expires in November.) The legislation to be introduced today will reverse Browning-Ferris, and more.   Story Continued Below  A discussion draft obtained by POLITICO's Marianne LeVine on Wednesday night indicated that the new bill will narrow the definition of joint employment under not only the National Labor Relations Act (the law that the NLRB enforces) but also the Fair Labor Standards Act (which is enforced by the Labor Department and was unaffected by Browning-Ferris). "The discussion draft, which may differ from [the] final version \u2026 would allow a company to be classified a joint employer with another business (typically a franchisee or contractor) only if the company exercised direct control over that other business's employees," LeVine writes. "Under the conditions outlined in the draft bill, 'a person may be considered a joint employer \u2026 only if such person directly, actually, and immediately, and not in a limited and routine manner, exercises significant control over the essential terms and conditions of employment.'"   "These conditions, according to the draft bill, would include determining employee pay, hiring and firing employees, and setting employee scheduling. Billed as a return to the joint employer standard established under two Reagan-era NLRB rulings that governed NLRB decisions until Browning-Ferris, the statutory language in the discussion draft may be more restrictive even than those earlier rulings," writes LeVine. The press conference will take place at the House Triangle and will include Chairwoman Virginia Foxx (R-N.C.) and several lawmakers, including Rep. Henry Cuellar (D-Texas). Watch it here and read LeVine's story here.   GOOD MORNING! It's Thursday, July 27, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.  BORDER BUCKS HEAD TO HOUSE FLOOR: The House is expected to pass a spending package this week that includes $1.6 billion in border wall funding \u2014 all while dodging a vote that might have ended in an embarrassing failure.   The House Rules Committee approved a rule Wednesday that will attach that $1.6 billion to the so-called "minibus," a four-part spending bill that covers defense, energy, veterans\u2019 affairs and the legislative branch \u2014 but not, one can't help noticing, the Department of Homeland Security, which would do the actual spending. The appropriation would pay for 74 miles of \u2026 well, not wall exactly, but a combination of fence and wall (60 miles of new fence and levee wall in South Texas and 14 miles of replacement secondary fence in the San Diego area) \u2014 the same amount requested in President Donald Trump's proposed budget.   In a strange twist, the border wall/fence faced a threat from House Republicans who wanted the minibus to include a ban on Pentagon-funded sex reassignment operations \u2014 "something GOP leaders wouldn\u2019t give them," POLITICO's Rachael Bade and Josh Dawsey report. "They turned to Trump, who didn\u2019t hesitate" to ban transgender troops altogether, causing the predictable ruckus that dominated the news Wednesday.   "After consultation with my Generals and military experts, please be advised that the United States Government will not accept or allow \u2026 Transgender individuals to serve in any capacity in the U.S. Military. Our military must be focused on decisive and overwhelming \u2026 victory and cannot be burdened with the tremendous medical costs and disruption that transgender in the military would entail. Thank you," Trump wrote in a three-part tweet on Wednesday. This was, Bade and Dawsey write, all about saving "a House proposal full of [Trump's] campaign promises that was on the verge of defeat." Including what Morning Shift is tempted to start calling the border wence.   \u201cThis is like someone told the White House to light a candle on the table and the WH set the whole table on fire,\u201d a senior House Republican aide told Bade and Dawsey in an email. More here.   FED LEAVES RATES UNCHANGED: The Federal Reserve said Wednesday that it would leave interest rates unchanged, Binyamin Appelbaum writes in the New York Times. The Fed is expected to raise rates one more time before the end of this year, but that won't likely occur before December, the Times reports. The Federal Reserve acknowledged that inflation was not as robust as officials had hoped. More here.   WATERED-DOWN ETHICS: David Apol, Trump's choice to lead the Office of Government Ethics, tried to ease up on ethics requirements for federal employees when he worked at the agency, Eric Lipton reports in The New York Times. "As recently as this spring, Mr. Apol had a disagreement with Walter M. Shaub Jr., the departing director, when Mr. Apol suggested that Derek T. Kan, then a general manager at Lyft, the car-sharing service, should not be required to sell his vested stock options in the company before he accepted a job at the Department of Transportation as the head of policy." More here.   IT'S THE ECONOMY, DONALD: In the past Trump has posted favorable poll results about his ability to handle the economy, but don't be surprised if he goes quiet on that subject. The public's faith in Trump's economic policies appears to be eroding, Heather Long reports in the Washington Post. She cites a Fox News poll that found Trump's approval rating on the economy fell to 45 percent \u2014 "the first time in his presidency [that] more Americans disapproved of how he was managing the economy than approved." Reality check: The U.S. economy hasn't changed very much, for good or for ill, since Trump assumed office. More here.   WANT A TOP TECH JOB? MOVE HERE: A recent tally by the job-search website Indeed found that eight cities accounted for more than a quarter of all tech jobs posted to its platform, the Wall Street Journal reports. The cities \u2014 Seattle, San Francisco, San Jose, Austin, Raleigh, Washington, Baltimore and Boston \u2014 had an even bigger footprint with high-paying tech jobs. Nearly 40 percent of tech job postings paying $100,000 or more were in those cities. More here.   LACK A DEGREE? MOVE HERE: There are 30 million jobs in the U.S. that pay $35,000 or more but don't require a college degree, Lauren Weber writes in The Wall Street Journal. The downside? There are 75 million workers without degrees, which creates a lot of competition for those jobs.   Where are these jobs? "In 2015, Wyoming had the highest share of noncollege good jobs thanks to a boom in mining and other natural-resource industries, coupled with a low overall population," the Journal reports. "It was followed by New Jersey and Maryland, densely populated states with more diverse economies." More here.   AMAZON'S JOB FAIR: Amazon "aims to fill 50,000 new positions in the U.S. by hosting a giant job fair next week, where it will be making offers on the spot," Laura Stevens writes in the Wall Street Journal. "The event, scheduled for Aug. 2 in a dozen locations around the country including 10 of its warehouses, shows how Amazon is pushing to make good on its pledge to hire 130,000 full- and part-time employees, as it competes with other logistics companies for hard-to-find workers." More here.  SANCTUARY SUSPECT BACK IN COURT: The death of Kate Steinle in San Francisco has come to symbolize the dangers of sanctuary cities \u2014 and her alleged killer is due back in court Friday, the Wall Street Journal reports. The suspect, Juan Francisco Lopez-Sanchez, is an undocumented Mexican immigrant who was released by local police despite a request by federal immigration officials to hold him.   Trump spoke about Steinle's case on the campaign trail, and even mentioned her in his speech at last year's Republican National Convention. "Of all my travels in this country, nothing has affected me more deeply than the time I have spent with the mothers and fathers who have lost their children to violence spilling across our border," he said. "My opponent will never meet with them, or share in their pain. Instead, my opponent wants sanctuary cities. But where was sanctuary for Kate Steinle?"   The sanctuary debate has remained heated since Trump took office. In the latest salvo, the Justice Department announced this week that it would place conditions on a grant program, and now require localities to give federal immigration officials access to jails and 48-hour notice before the release of a suspected undocumented immigrant. More on the Steinle case here.   NRA'S JOINT EMPLOYER CARTOON: The National Restaurant Association released an animated video on Wednesday night arguing that the NLRB's joint employer standard under Browning-Ferris is all wet. Watch it here.   ASYLUM BILL CLEARS JUDICIARY: The House Judiciary Committee approved H.R. 391 (115) Wednesday, a bill that would toughen standards for asylum seekers and curtail the use of parole to allow people to enter the country on humanitarian grounds or for the public interest. One core provision would require asylum seekers to prove during a so-called "credible fear" interview that their fear of persecution in their home country is "more probable than not."   The measure was introduced by former Rep. Jason Chaffetz, who left Congress in June, and is now sponsored by Rep. James Michael Johnson (R-La.). The Louisiana congressman said in a written statement that the bill "ensures our asylum programs are used not for the ill-intent of bad actors." Immigrant supporters, however, were outraged. David Bier of the libertarian Cato Institute entered a statement for the record that said the bill would "undermine the individual rights of people fleeing persecution and violence" and "obliterate the current asylum standards." Read Bier's full statement here.   SNYDER SIGNS JOBS BILL: "[Michigan] Gov. Rick Snyder on Wednesday signed into law a package of bills aimed at fostering job creation in the state," the Detroit News reports. "To receive the tax incentives, companies must create at least 250 jobs that pay 125 percent or more of the region's average annual wage, or at least 500 jobs that pay the region's average annual wage or more. Certain industries, such as retail and jobs at sports stadiums, are exempt." More here.   DREAM PROTESTERS ARRESTED IN TEXAS: "Fifteen immigrant rights supporters were arrested Wednesday outside the Texas Capitol after they blocked traffic in an effort to defend existing immigrant protections and demand permanent legal status," the Texas Observer reports. "The hourlong demonstration was led by so-called Dreamers \u2014 recipients of Obama\u2019s Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA) \u2014 and came on the heels of Texas Attorney General Ken Paxton\u2019s urging the Trump administration to end the program." More here.   Speaking of Dreamers, Reps. Lucille Roybal-Allard (D-Calif.) and Ileana Ros-Lehtinen (R-Fla.) on Wednesday introduced a version of the DREAM Act, which would offer an eventual path to citizenship to DACA enrollees and other undocumented immigrants brought to the U.S. at a young age. The bipartisan bill is a companion to S. 1615 (115), legislation introduced last week by Sens. Lindsey Graham (R-S.C.) and Dick Durbin (D-Ill.).   COFFEE BREAK   \u2014 "Texas Senate passes bill targeting public employee union dues," from the Texas Tribune   \u2014 "Who wants to run that mom and pop market? Almost no one," from The New York Times   \u2014 "Four migrants die trying to cross the Rio Grande into the U.S.," from The New York Times   \u2014 "Illinois lawmakers back in session \u2014 and clashing with the governor," from The Wall Street Journal   \u2014"Everything wrong with that New York Times profile of Uber\u2019s Bozoma Saint John," from Quartz   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.    CORRECTION:  A previous version of Morning Shift incorrectly reported the asylum bill included a provision related to unaccompanied minors. An amendment during Wednesday\u2019s markup removed that provision before it was approved by the committee.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
