aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Ian Kullgren, Marianne LeVine and Josh Gerstein   GOP TEES UP JOINT EMPLOYER: After months of talk, Republicans are set to unveil a bill Thursday that would rewrite the legal definition of joint employment as laid down under the NLRB's 2015 Browning-Ferris decision. Corporations hate Browning-Ferris because it made it easier to hold them jointly liable for workplace violations committed by their franchisees or contractors. Republicans are expected to impose a stricter standard in which only a business that wields direct control over another company\u2019s employees can be classified a joint employer jointly accountable for that other company\u2019s overtime and other violations.   Story Continued Below  What else might the GOP bill include? Roger King of the HR Policy Association, testifying before the committee last month, asked lawmakers to include a "safe harbor" provision that would preempt state laws and allow companies to remove the threat of joint-employer lawsuits through the adoption of certain social-responsibility standards.   Supporters of a safe harbor clause point to Microsoft, praised by President Barack Obama in 2015 for requiring its contractors to offer its employees paid leave \u2014 a decision that, by demonstrating Microsoft\u2019s influence over the contractors\u2019 labor practices, arguably left the software giant vulnerable to joint-employer litigation. In an appellate court brief, Microsoft said the Browning-Ferris standard "will cause companies to question whether [social responsibility] initiatives will contribute to findings of joint employment relationships, and ultimately deter adoption of such initiatives."   Will the idea of promoting corporate responsibility convince Democrats to join the cause? Probably not in most cases, but Rep. Henry Cuellar (D-Texas) \u2014 who typically leans right on labor issues \u2014 is set to join House Education and the Workforce Chairwoman Virginia Foxx (R-N.C.), along with Reps. Tim Walberg (R-Mich.) and Bradley Byrne (R-Ala.) at the Thursday press conference. It's unclear who will sponsor the bill; Walberg and Byrne are both strong contenders.   GOOD MORNING! It's Wednesday, July 26, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com, and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.  BORDER WALL WORKAROUND: "House Republicans are poised to fund $1.6 billion for President Donald Trump's border wall through a procedural maneuver designed to avoid a floor vote that might fail," POLITICO's Ted Hesson reports.   "The House Rules Committee is expected to attach funding for the wall that Trump has proposed building along the Mexican border to the so-called minibus, a downsized spending package for the Pentagon, the Energy Department, the Department of Veterans Affairs and the legislative branch \u2014 but not DHS, the Cabinet agency responsible for the wall," Hesson writes. "If an amendment to fund the wall is adopted by the Rules Committee, this line item can circumvent a floor vote, sparing GOP immigration moderates and fiscal hawks from being pressed to approve a project that their constituents might view as xenophobic, misguided and wasteful \u2014 and sparing GOP leaders possible defeat." The committee is expected to report out the border-related part of the spending package today. More on the maneuvers here.   TODAY:   FED WATCH: "Federal Reserve officials are likely to hold monetary policy steady at the conclusion of their two-day meeting Wednesday," Harriet Torry writes in The Wall Street Journal. "With no press conference scheduled after the meeting and no new economic forecasts to be released, any changes in their policy statement will be scrutinized for clues about the path for interest rates and when they might start shrinking the Fed\u2019s portfolio of Treasury and mortgage bonds." For a list of things to watch, read the Journal's story here.   WALMART TALKS MANUFACTURING: Walmart will host a public discussion on U.S. manufacturing beginning at 9 a.m. today. Business leaders from the company and elsewhere will be joined by members of Congress, including Rep. Tom Reed (R-N.Y.). The event takes place at 300 New Jersey Avenue NW, Suite 800.   TRUMP: APPLE PROMISED PLANTS: President Trump told the Wall Street Journal Tuesday that Apple CEO Tim Cook promised him that the company would build "three big plants, beautiful plants" in the United States.   \u201cI said you know, Tim, unless you start building your plants in this country, I won\u2019t consider my administration an economic success," Trump told the Journal. "He called me, and he said they are going forward.\u201d The president did not specify the location of the plants, and Apple declined to comment. More here.   SANCTUARY CRACKDOWN: "The Justice Department announced Tuesday that it will impose new grant conditions in a bid to make sure that federal money does not flow to so-called sanctuary cities," writes POLITICO's Josh Gerstein. "Localities receiving funds through one of Justice's most popular grant programs will have to meet two new conditions: allowing immigration authorities access to local jails and prisons, and giving the feds 48-hour notice before an illegal immigrant wanted by the feds is released."   In a written statement, Attorney General Jeff Sessions sought to tie a recent case of human smuggling \u2014 in which 10 migrants died after sitting in a scorching-hot tractor-trailer \u2014 to sanctuary policies. "These policies also encourage illegal immigration and even human trafficking by perpetuating the lie that in certain cities, illegal aliens can live outside the law," he said. "This can have tragic consequences, like the 10 deaths we saw in San Antonio this weekend."   The logic, presumably, is that people would risk their lives to travel to the relative safety of a so-called sanctuary city (although San Antonio's police chief has contested that label). But that argument could just as easily be used to blame harsh enforcement policies that send desperate migrants further underground. More from POLITICO's Josh Gerstein here.   TRUMP TO LONG ISLAND: President Trump will head to Long Island Friday to talk about steps to eliminate MS-13, a street gang with roots among Salvadoran immigrants, the New York Times reports. The administration has flagged the gang\u2019s horrific violence to link illegal immigration to violent crime. But studies have indicated that overall, immigrants are incarcerated at a much lower rate than U.S.-born individuals. Attorney General Jeff Sessions, who visited Long Island in April for the same purpose, will not accompany the president due to other travel plans, a Justice Department official told POLITICO. (Sessions and Trump are not exactly besties right now.) More from the Times here.   LOCAL TIES: At least one of the victims in the tractor-trailer case was a 19-year-old Guatemalan immigrant who grew up in Northern Virginia and graduated from a Fairfax County high school, the Washington Post's Maria Sacchetti, Moriah Balingit and Fenit Nirappil report.   "Frank G. Fuentes was one of at least six Guatemalans packed into a poorly ventilated truck with scores of other migrants who had crossed the border illegally, said Cristy Andrino, the consul of Guatemala in McAllen, Texas," according to the Post. "U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement said he had been brought to this country before his third birthday and was deported on March 2 after being convicted of assault and battery by a mob. He was suspected of having ties to Mara Salvatrucha, the deadly street gang also known as MS-13." More here.   DEMS MAY END NOMINEE BLOCKADE: Senate Democrats pledge to lift a blockade against Trump nominees if the GOP's Obamacare repeal effort fails, POLITICO's Seung Min Kim and Burgess Everett report.   "In recent weeks, the Senate has slowed to a crawl, taking days to process nominees such as a federal judge from Idaho and the second-ranking official at the Pentagon as a protest of sorts against the Republicans' secretive health care drafting process," Kim and Everett write. "But Democrats plan to work with Republicans for a deal on the dozens of nominations lingering on the floor once the GOP's partisan health push ends, according to Democratic senators and aides." More here.   WORK FROM HOME NO MORE: Fewer businesses are allowing their employees to work remotely full-time, John Simons reports in The Wall Street Journal. In 2016, 22 percent of employees said that they did some or all of their work at home, down from 24 percent in 2015.   IBM, Aetna, Bank of America, Best Buy, Honeywell and Reddit "are among employers that have ended or reduced remote-work arrangements recently as managers demand more collaboration, closer contact with customers \u2014 and more control over the workday," the Journal reports. More here.   EMPLOYEES WANT ... MICROCHIP IMPLANTS?: Starting next week, employees at a technology company in Wisconsin will have the option to inject a chip into their body so that manual tasks like swiping into a building or paying for cafeteria food "can be accomplished with a wave of the hand," Maggie Astor reports in the New York Times.   But the program (as you probably guessed) could create health and privacy concerns. "A microchip implanted today to allow for easy building access and payments could, in theory, be used later in more invasive ways: to track the length of employees\u2019 bathroom or lunch breaks, for instance, without their consent or even their knowledge," the Times reports. More here.   FACEBOOK CAFETERIA WORKERS JOIN UNION: "More than 500 cafeteria workers who serve food at Facebook have unionized to push for higher wages and more affordable health benefits," the Mercury News reports, citing an announcement Monday from UNITE HERE Local 19. "The move to unionize comes as thousands of contract workers such as janitors, security guards and shuttle bus drivers at other major Silicon Valley tech firms, including Apple, Intel and Google, have done the same." More here.   JUDGE BLOCKS IRAQI DEPORTATIONS: "A federal judge in Detroit temporarily blocked the deportation of more than 1,400 Iraqi immigrants with criminal records who were detained by federal immigration agents last month," Kris Maher reports in the Wall Street Journal. "U.S. District Judge Mark Goldsmith granted a preliminary injunction sought by attorneys for a group of Iraqis until they can make their case in immigration courts that their deportation would be illegal." More here.   COMPARE TECH SALARIES: A new tool from the pay-tracking website PayScale allows users to compare pay and employee engagement at a range of tech companies, from Airbnb and Amazon to Twitter and Uber.   "Twitter, LinkedIn and Facebook top the list among all tech companies when it comes to early-career median pay, coming in at $112,000, $110,000 and $110,000 respectively," the company found. "When employees reach mid-career, however, these social media giants become somewhat less attractive; only Twitter makes it into the top-10 of the 52 companies we surveyed, sneaking in at number 10 with mid-career median salary of $157,000." Try it for yourself here.   CITIZENSHIP GRANTS: U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services will provide up to $10 million in grants to aid citizenship and assimilation, the agency announced Tuesday. More from USCIS here   COFFEE BREAK   \u2014 "Maybe we've been thinking about the productivity slump all wrong," from The New York Times   \u2014 "Company whose trailer was used in human smuggling case has history of complaints, legal problems," from The Washington Post   \u2014 "Lawsuit challenges secrecy of White House advisers on infrastructure plan," from The New York Times   \u2014 "Court officers can\u2019t hold people solely under ICE detainers, Massachusetts justices rule," from The New York Times   \u2014 "Economy needs workers, but drug tests take a toll," from The New York Times   \u2014 "Detroit automakers downshift workforce, lineups," from the Detroit News   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
