aV \u000a            By TED HESSON  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Marianne LeVine and Ian Kullgren  BACKDOOR BORDER BOOST: The House Rules Committee is expected to slip $1.6 billion in border-wall funding into the \u201cminibus\u201d spending package that\u2019s headed to the House floor this week. Why in a rule? Why not just amend the bill once it\u2019s on the floor? Probably because the wall doesn\u2019t have enough Republican support to pass there.   Story Continued Below  Back in April, the Wall Street Journal\u2019s Laura Meckler and Kristina Peterson surveyed border lawmakers from both parties and couldn\u2019t find any backers of a similar fiscal year 2017 proposal from the Trump administration. \u201cNot a single member of the House or Senate representing the region expressed support for the funding request,\u201d they wrote, and \u201csenior congressional Republicans have long indicated that they prefer to leave it out.\u201d GOP budget hawks are wary of the wall, too. So are Republicans who are immigration moderates.   The Rules Committee began consideration Monday night of nearly 300 amendments to the \u201cminibus,\u201d which would fund military construction and veterans' affairs; the legislative branch; energy and water; and defense. Border wall funding falls under the Department of Homeland Security, which isn\u2019t covered by the minibus, but no matter. The $1.6 billion will likely be attached via an amendment by Rep. John Carter (R-Texas). The amendment would fund 60 miles of new bollard-style fence and new levee wall in the Rio Grande Valley ($1.3 billion); 14 miles of secondary fence in the San Diego area ($250 million); and \u201cplanning for border wall construction\u201d ($40 million) \u2014 all, Carter says, \u201cnecessary to gain operational control of the border.\u201d  Democrats blasted Republicans for avoiding a floor vote. Rep. Louise Slaughter (D-N.Y.), ranking member on the Rules Committee, called the border wall \u201coffensive, expensive and ill-conceived,\u201d and said funding it through a rule would be \u201cundemocratic.\u201d Earlier in the day, Rep. Ruben Gallego (D-Ariz.) said the expected maneuver was a \u201csneaky gimmick\u201d and that the border wall spending was \u201cdeeply unpopular, especially in the border communities.\u201d The committee meets again today (2 p.m. in H-313 of the Capitol) and is expected to vote on the spending package. Watch it here.   GOOD MORNING! It's Tuesday, July 25, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com, and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.  TODAY:  DEMS CONTINUE WAGE PUSH: House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi and eight Democratic colleagues will hold a press conference this morning to promote their \u201cbetter deal\u201d to \u201cboost wages, lower costs and unrig the economy.\u201d  POLITICO\u2019s Marianne LeVine reports the Democratic plan includes a $15 minimum wage, an expansion of registered apprenticeships and work-based educational programs, a tax credit for employers who train and hire new workers, and more partnerships between businesses, community colleges and technical programs. Although everybody\u2019s labeling the plan \u201cpopulist,\u201d we haven\u2019t heard a whisper, as President Donald Trump and the Senate prepare to eliminate the NLRB\u2019s pro-union majority, about strengthening organized labor\u2019s hand in collective bargaining. That didn\u2019t escape attention from the Democrats\u2019 Sanders faction. In a CNN commentary, Jonathan Tasini, who challenged then-Sen. Hillary Clinton in the 2006 Democratic primary and campaigned for Sanders in 2016, called it \u201cperhaps the most glaring omission.\u201d The press conference will take place at 10:15 a.m. in the Capitol Visitor Center. Watch a livestream here and read more from LeVine here.  SCOTT PITCHES WAGE BILL: House Education and the Workforce Committee ranking member Bobby Scott (D-Va.) hopes to revive his moribund Raise the Wage Act, a bill that would increase the hourly federal minimum wage to $15 over a seven-year period (it\u2019s currently $7.25 an hour). Scott and 16 fellow Democrats will send a letter today to Committee Chairwoman Virginia Foxx (R-N.C.) that requests a legislative hearing on the bill, which would also gradually eliminate the separate minimum wage for tipped workers.   Scott will also join Sens. Bernie Sanders (I-Vt.) and Patty Murray (D-Wash.) to promote the legislation at a press conference today, POLITICO\u2019s Ian Kullgren reports. The press conference is scheduled for 1 p.m. in the House Triangle. Read the letter here and the bill here.  WAITING ON THE OVERTIME RFI: Morning Shift is still waiting on the Labor Department to publish its request for information on the overtime rule. We hear the request will likely solicit comment on how (and whether) to index the threshold to inflation. Have more info? Let us know!  YOU TALK, DOL LISTENS: The Labor Department posted a notification recently that said the department will consider comments on the fiduciary rule even after the deadline for public comment passes. The rule, part of which took effect in June, required that broker dealers consider only their client\u2019s best interest (and not commissions or fees) when providing retirement advice.   Earlier this month, the department issued a request for information that gave the public until Aug. 7 to comment about the rule\u2019s effect. But according to the new notification, \u201cif commenters submit thoughtful comments \u2026 after August 7, 2017, the department will endeavor to consider those comments,\u201d at least for awhile.  DOL GETS DEPUTY COS: Molly Conway was appointed deputy chief of staff at the Labor Department, a spokesperson tells Morning Shift. Conway came to the department in February from the Senate HELP Committee and has worked for the House Committee on Education and the Workforce.   SHERROD BROWN\u2019S RUST BELT TEST: Ohio Democratic Sen. Sherrod Brown\u2019s re-election campaign will likely be one of 2018\u2019s most closely watched races, and it may signal that the Democratic party is doing better than some think, Ben Terris writes in the Washington Post. Brown\u2019s success in Ohio could be a model for Democrats hoping to roar back in the Rust Belt.   \u201cPeople keep asking me how I\u2019m going to win back the Trump voters\u201d Brown told the Post. \u201cWell, I don\u2019t think I\u2019ve ever lost them.\u201d Terris writes that Brown retains his appeal to union members. \u201cHe\u2019s fluent in pension plans, overtime work rules, and what he calls the \u2018myths\u2019 of free trade. \u2026. In an alternate universe where Hillary Clinton picked Sherrod Brown as her vice-presidential candidate, which she almost did, the Democratic ticket could have won Ohio, Wisconsin, Michigan and the White House.\u201d More here.  SPEAKING OF THE RUST BELT: Rust Belt states diverged from a national trend of growth in blue-collar jobs and lost 5,700 manufacturing jobs in June, according to the left-leaning Center for Economic and Policy Research. \u201cPennsylvania continues to be the leading job loser in manufacturing since President Trump took office, with a loss of 8,300 jobs since January, or 1.5 percent of the manufacturing jobs in the state,\u201d the read reads. \u201cOhio comes in second with a loss of 5,400 jobs, 0.8 percent of total employment.\u201d More here.  WHY THE FED IS WORRIED ABOUT LOW INFLATION: The Federal Reserve is expected to fall short for the sixth straight year on a goal to keep inflation rising at 2 percent, the New York Times reports. And that has economists worried (seriously).   Conventional wisdom suggests that inflation is bad, and in most respects it is. We want money to retain its buying power. But Fed economists say the expectation of higher wages and greater profits can motivate people to work harder \u2014 giving the economy a boost. And that depends on there being enough inflation to make that expectation seem plausible.  \u201cA little inflation can brighten the economic mood, causing wages and corporate profits to rise more quickly,\u201d Binyamin Appelbaum writes for the Times. \u201cEconomists like to point out that this is an illusion. If everyone is making more money, then no one can buy more stuff. Prices just go up. But the evidence suggests people enjoy the illusion and, importantly, they respond to the illusion by behaving in ways that increase actual economic growth, for example by working harder.\u201d More here.   On the other hand, Harriet Torry writes in the Wall Street Journal, not that many people are paying attention. \u201cAlmost half of Americans surveyed, 44 percent, said they didn\u2019t know when the Fed most recently [raised] short-term interest rates, according to the survey by the personal finance website WalletHub,\u201d the Journal reports. \u201cFor the record, the Fed has raised its benchmark federal-funds rate twice this year, in March and in June, bringing it to a range between 1% and 1.25%. It is likely to leave the rate unchanged Wednesday.\u201d More here.  JUDGE OKAYS LEGAL HELP FOR IMMIGRANTS: \u201cA federal judge in Seattle said Monday that nonprofit legal groups around the country can keep assisting immigrants facing deportation, after a Justice Department decision threatened to curtail much of that work,\u201d the Associated Press reports.  \u201cIn April, the Justice Department told the Seattle-based Northwest Immigrant Rights Project that it cannot provide certain legal assistance to immigrants unless it undertakes full, formal representation of them in court,\u201d according to the AP. \u201cThe organization \u2014 and similar groups around the U.S. who could be hindered by such a rule \u2014 said they don\u2019t have the resources to do so, and that the order would force them to give up preparing motions and other documents on behalf of immigrants who represent themselves.\u201d   U.S. District Judge Richard Jones had temporarily blocked the policy but issued a preliminary injunction on Monday, citing First Amendment concerns. More from the AP here.  FOXCONN PLOTS BADGER STATE INVESTMENT: \u201cTaiwan\u2019s Foxconn Technology Group, which assembles Apple Inc.\u2019s iPhones, is nearing a decision to invest in Wisconsin and could hold an event in Washington, D.C., as soon as this week to discuss U.S. investment plans,\u201d the Wall Street Journal reports, citing people familiar with the matter.   \u201cIn Wisconsin, Foxconn is looking at producing display panels that can be used in large-screen television sets, three people briefed on the plans said,\u201d according to the Journal\u2019s Yoko Kubota and Takashi Mochizuki. \u201cThe investment, if confirmed, would be the latest by Asian manufacturers in the U.S. as [Trump] seeks to revive manufacturing there.\u201d More here.  FEINSTEIN WORRIES ABOUT ASYLUM SEEKERS: The top Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee sent a letter Monday to Homeland Security Secretary John Kelly that urges him to issue guidance to U.S. Customs and Border Protection officers about how to handle asylum seekers. The letter, from Sen. Dianne Feinstein (D-Calif.), follows a lawsuit filed in California earlier this month that argues asylum seekers were wrongly turned away at the border.  \u201cRecent complaints and reports have raised concerns about whether CBP officials are following proper procedures in cases involving asylum seekers arriving at the U.S.-Mexico border,\u201d Feinstein writes. \u201cFor instance, there are claims that the agency\u2019s officials have falsely informed asylum seekers that there is a \u2018daily quota for asylum cases\u2019 and that they need a visa to seek asylum. In some cases, it has been reported that officials have coerced individuals to withdraw their credible fear assertion.\u201d Read the letter here.  DISNEY UNION WANTS WAGE TALKS: A union that represents 38,000 Disney World workers wants to reopen wage negotiations this year, Paul Brinkmann writes in the Orlando Sentinel. \u201cThe last time [the Service Trades Council Union] held talks with Disney World was in 2014, and the company agreed to raise wages gradually to at least $10 an hour starting in 2016,\u201d Brinkmann reports. \u201cShortly after, the raises were extended to all Disney's approximately 70,000 Orlando employees, not just those represented by unions.\u201d More here.  COFFEE BREAK  \u2014 \u201cFormer Attorney General Holder calls Kobach a 'fact-challenged zealot,'\u201d from POLITICO  THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.   \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
