aV \u000a            By MARIANNE LEVINE  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Ted Hesson  THIS WEEK \u2014 OVERTIME RFI: The Labor Department is expected to release this week a request for information on the Obama administration\u2019s overtime rule. The White House Office of Management and Budget completed its review of the request last week. Issued last year, the rule doubled (to $47,476) the salary threshold under which virtually all workers are guaranteed time-and-a-half pay if they work more than 40 hours in a given week. But the rule never took effect because a judge issued a preliminary injunction against it. Last month, the Trump administration defended its legal authority to set a salary test to determine whether an employee qualifies for overtime pay. But it did not defend the Obama administration rule. The request for information is the Trump administration\u2019s first step in reviewing the regulation. Labor Secretary Alexander Acosta acknowledged at his confirmation hearing in March that the salary threshold for overtime pay, which hadn\u2019t been updated since 2004, was due for an update. But he questioned the Obama administration\u2019s legal authority to double it. He suggested that a threshold of $33,000 would be more in line with inflation.   Story Continued Below  The request for information will likely offer some clue as to what changes the Trump administration has in mind. But don\u2019t expect a proposed rule anytime soon. In its court filing last month, the administration said it would not propose a new rule until the court affirmed its authority to set a salary test.   GOOD MORNING! It's Monday, July 24, and this is Morning Shift, POLITICO's daily tipsheet on employment and immigration policy. Send tips, exclusives, and suggestions to thesson@politico.com, ikullgren@politico.com, mlevine@politico.com, and tnoah@politico.com. Follow us on Twitter at @tedhesson, @marianne_levine, @IanKullgren and @TimothyNoah1.  JOINT EMPLOYER BILL THURSDAY: Morning Shift hears that House Republicans will introduce legislation Thursday to roll back the National Labor Relations Board\u2019s broadened joint employer standard under Browning-Ferris. The 2015 decision made it easier to hold large companies liable for labor law violations by contractors or franchisees. Last week, House Education and the Workforce Chairwoman Virginia Foxx (R-N.C.) wrote in The Hill that congressional action \u201cis the most logical and straightforward way to undo the damage that\u2019s been done and protect local employers and their employees from future bureaucratic overreach. To fall short of this objective is to shirk our congressional responsibilities."  SECOND QUARTER GDP OUT FRIDAY: The Commerce Department will release Friday its first cut at estimating real Gross Domestic Product growth for the second quarter of 2017. Last month, the Commerce Department reported that GDP increased 1.4 percent in the first quarter, up from an initial estimate of 0.7 percent and a second estimate of 1.2 percent, but down from the fourth quarter of 2016\u2019s 2.1 percent and the third quarter\u2019s 3.5 percent. Economists are more optimistic about second quarter GDP. According to a Bloomberg survey, analysts predict that GDP will have grown 2.6 percent. That\u2019s still well below the Trump administration\u2019s stated goal to expand the economy by 3 percent.   TODAY: DEMS RELEASE PLAN TO IMPROVE THE ECONOMY: Democrats will announce today their agenda to improve the economy, entitled \u201cA Better Deal: Better Jobs, Better Wages, Better Future.\u201d Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer (D-N.Y.) and House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi (D-Calif.) will discuss the plan at 1 p.m. at Rose Hill Park in Berryville, Va. Watch it here.  TRUMP\u2019S NATIONAL INFRASTRUCTURE PLAN ON HOLD: President Donald Trump\u2019s \u201cgreat national infrastructure program\u201d isn\u2019t happening anytime soon, Glenn Thrush reports in the New York Times. According to Thrush, it must wait its turn behind budget negotiations, the debt ceiling, tax reform, immigration reform, and the repeal and replacement of the Affordable Care Act. Trump said in April that he would provide more details about his plan \u201cvery soon,\u201d but he has \u201cyet to even name any members to a new board he claimed would green-light big projects.\u201d AFL-CIO President Richard Trumka told the Times that \u201cthe president doesn\u2019t know what his own party wants, and he\u2019s not sure what he wants ... he can\u2019t get his own party to pony up the money for infrastructure.\u201d  Sean McGarvey, president of the North America\u2019s Building Trades Union, said that he\u2019d like to see \u201ca detailed proposal that can make it through committee, and be voted on through regular order by the end of the year.\u201d But that\u2019s optimistic. Sen. John Thune (R-S.D.) said that lawmakers might not consider a proposal until 2018. \u201cWe\u2019re sort of waiting on the administration to tell us what it is exactly they want to do,\u201d he told the Times. More here.  ACOSTA: OCCUPATIONAL LICENSING CREATES BARRIERS: Labor Secretary Alexander Acosta encouraged state lawmakers Friday to eliminate requirements for occupational licenses where they\u2019re unnecessary. In a speech at the American Legislative Executive Council\u2019s annual meeting, Acosta said that \u201cthe growth of occupational licensing is part of a nationwide trend where we regulate, and regulate, and regulate.\u201d He noted that in 1950, 1 in 20 jobs required an occupational license. But today \u201cmore than 1 in 4 Americans need a license to legally perform their work,\u201d he said. Acosta added that \u201cexcess licensing hinders the American workforce\u201d by creating barriers for workers who have less money; who want to move to another state; or who want \u201cto leverage technology and to expand their job opportunities.\u201d  CHRISTIE VETOES PAID LEAVE BILL: New Jersey Gov. Chris Christie vetoed legislation Friday to expand paid family leave to 12 weeks, up from the state\u2019s current six. The program, funded by employee payroll contributions, allows workers to take time off for numerous reasons, including the birth of a child or a sick family member. In a statement, Christie described the bill as a \u201ccostly expansion\u201d that would \u201cresult in increased taxes to be paid by working citizens in New Jersey." He recommended that lawmakers amend the bill \u201cto focus directly on raising awareness of the benefits currently available.\u201d According to NJ.com\u2019s Samantha Marcus, \u201cthe Democrat-controlled Legislature can override his veto, something it lacks the votes to do without Republican support, or it can accept Christie\u2019s recommendations.\u201d More here.  ICE TARGETS TEENAGERS IN RAIDS THIS WEEK: U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement will target this week teenagers who came to the U.S. without a guardian or who are suspected gang members, Julia Edwards Ainsley reports in Reuters. According to an internal memo, the raids began Sunday and will go through Wednesday. They will focus on 16 and 17-year-olds. \u201cU.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement said in a statement that a person can be identified as a gang member if they meet two or more criteria, including having gang tattoos, frequenting an area notorious for gangs and wearing gang apparel,\u201d Ainsley writes. \u201cThe agency said it does not comment on plans for future law enforcement operations, but that it focuses on individuals who pose a threat to national security and public safety.\u201d More here.  THE RESURGENCE OF THE BORDER WALL: House Republicans are expected to include funds for a border wall in the smaller-scale spending bill they plan to vote on this week, POLITICO\u2019s Jennifer Scholtes and Sarah Ferris reported last week. Republican lawmakers, who had hoped to pass a broader range of spending measures, downsized their ambitions last week, instead opting to focus on a four-bill \u201cminibus\u201d that includes military construction and veterans\u2019 affairs; the legislative branch; energy and water; and defense.   The House Rules Committee will meet today at 5 p.m. to set up floor debate for the package. \u201cMajority Leader Kevin McCarthy has warned that \u2018late-night votes are likely\u2019 once the legislation hits the floor next week, since hundreds of amendments are expected to be filed,\u201d Scholtes and Ferris reported. \u201cStill no word on when \u2014 or if \u2014 the Senate would/could follow suit.\u201d Over the weekend, newly installed White House Communications Director Anthony Scaramucci said that the Trump administration is on \u201cmissile lock\u201d to build the border wall, and a House Appropriations Committee aide told Morning Shift the funds would be added as an amendment.   EPI: MINIMUM WAGE VALUE DOWN 12.5 PERCENT: The purchasing power of the federal minimum wage \u2014 now at $7.25 \u2014 is down 12.5 percent from 2009, the last time it increased, according to the left-leaning Economic Policy Institute. According to EPI\u2019s David Cooper, the decline in the buying power of the minimum wage over the past eight years is not even half the overall decline in the minimum wage\u2019s value since the late 1960s ... At its high point in 1968, the federal minimum wage was equal to $9.90 in today\u2019s dollars.\u201d More here.  PENCE TOUTS JOB CREATION IN OP-ED: Vice President Mike Pence touted the number of jobs created under the Trump administration, in a Fox News op-ed published Sunday. \u201cPresident Trump inherited an economy that would barely budge \u2014 but under his watch, American businesses small and large have already created more than 800,000 new jobs since January,\u201d Pence wrote. Although Pence got the number of jobs created right, the pace of job creation is actually  slower under Trump than it was last year under President Barack Obama. Since the start of the Trump administration, the economy has added about 172,600 jobs a month. In 2016, the economy added about 187,000 jobs a month.   SMUGGLING TURNS FATAL: At least nine people died after being packed into a tractor trailer outside a Walmart during a scorching hot day in San Antonio, Texas, a tragedy officials described as a failed smuggling attempt, Eric Gay and Will Weissert report for the Associated Press. San Antonio Police Chief William McManus called it \u201ca human-trafficking crime\u201d and \u201ca horrific tragedy.\u201d   \u201cAuthorities were called to the San Antonio parking lot late Saturday or early Sunday and found eight people dead inside the truck,\u201d the AP reports. \u201cA ninth victim died at the hospital, said Liz Johnson, spokeswoman for U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement. \u2026 Based on initial interviews with survivors of the San Antonio tragedy, more than 100 people may have been packed into the back of the 18-wheeler at one point in its journey, ICE acting Director Thomas Homan said.\u201d A least four people in the truck were children, Homan said.  DHS Secretary John Kelly said in a written statement that the deaths show the \u201cbrutality\u201d of smugglers, who \u201chave no regard for human life and seek only profits.\u201d The sweltering temperatures in cramped trucks have led to similar tragedies in past years, including a case in 2003 where 19 migrants died while trapped inside a truck in Victoria, Texas. More here.  NON-DISPARAGEMENT AGREEMENTS PROLIFERATE: Non-disparagement clauses in employment contracts are growing in popularity, Katie Benner reports in The New York Times. \u201cTheir use has become particularly widespread in tech employment contracts, from venture investment firms and start-ups to the biggest companies in Silicon Valley, including Google.\u201d  \u201cNondisparagement clauses have become so common that the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, which enforces federal discrimination laws, and the National Labor Relations Board, a federal agency that protects workers\u2019 rights, have been studying whether they are having a chilling effect on workers speaking up about wrongdoing or filing lawsuits, said Orly Lobel, a law professor at the University of San Diego.\u201d More here.  CALENDAR   Noon:  Pew Charitable Trusts, the W.K. Kellogg Foundation, and the Senate Economic Mobility Caucus \u201chold a discussion on \u2018Economic Mobility, Economic Security, and the Future of Employment,\u2019\u201d according to Washington Daybook. Location:  G-11 Dirksen Senate Office Building  COFFEE BREAK  \u2014 \u201cWithout visas, carnival workers are trapped at home in Mexico,\u201d from The New York Times  \u2014 \u201cTraveling in the wake of immigration arrests,\u201d from The New York Times  \u2014 \u201cBBC women demand action to close pay gap with men,\u201d The New York Times  \u2014 \u201cSibley Memorial Hospital plans to cut staff through buyouts,\u201d from The Washington Post  \u2014 \u201cAs California\u2019s labor shortage grows, farmers race to replace workers with robots,\u201d from the Los Angeles Times  \u2014 \u201cTrump administration seeks to sidestep border wall environmental study: sources,\u201d from Reuters  \u2014 \u201cTrump\u2019s immigration crackdown is stressing out deployed U.S. troops,\u201d from McClatchy   \u2014 \u201cCulinary backs effort to extend temporary-status immigration program,\u201d from the Las Vegas Sun   THAT\u2019S ALL FOR MORNING SHIFT.   Marianne LeVine is an Employment & Immigration reporter for POLITICO Pro. Prior to joining POLITICO, LeVine interned at the Los Angeles Times\u2019 bureau in Washington, D.C. She graduated from Stanford\u2019s Graduate Program in Journalism this past June. While at Stanford, LeVine covered affordable housing and gang violence issues in East Palo Alto. She also graduated from Stanford undergrad in 2013, with degrees in International Relations and French. Originally from California, LeVine is looking forward to having actual seasons and bracing herself for the snow. She enjoys running, traveling and meeting new people.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
