aV \u000a            By MEGAN CASSELLA  08/03/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Adam Behsudi, Doug Palmer and Luis Sanchez  TRUMP\u2019S PLANNED TRADE PROBE PUTS BEIJING IN THE HOT SEAT: If President Donald Trump moves forward Friday with launching an investigation into Chinese industrial policies surrounding forced technology transfer, it wouldn\u2019t launch a global trade war right of the bat.   Story Continued Below  It would, however, broadcast to Beijing that the United States is not afraid to limit imports or block Chinese investment \u2014 and it tarnishes Chinese President Xi Jinping\u2019s preferred portrayal of China as a champion of the rules-based international system, Pro Trade\u2019s Doug Palmer reports.  \u201cI would expect the Chinese to be critical of the announcement and defend their practices, but also sharpen their pencils to prepare to retaliate in the event that the investigation concludes with penalties against China in some manner,\u201d said Scott Kennedy, director of the Chinese business and political economy project at the Center for Strategic and International Studies.  The anticipated announcement would likely launch a so-called Section 301 probe that would last somewhere between six months and a year. The U.S. pledged in the mid-1990s to settle disputes through the World Trade Organization\u2019s dispute system, but as long as Washington is trying to curb an action not covered by a WTO agreement, it could move outside of the global trading body to impose unilateral sanctions.   IT\u2019S THURSDAY, AUG. 3! Welcome to Morning Trade, where your host is wondering if maybe it\u2019s time to watch \u201cSharknado 3: Oh Hell No\u201d to find out how many parallels the plotline has to today\u2019s reality. Got any trade news or tips to share? Let me know what you\u2019re hearing: mcassella@politico.com or @mmcassella.  MEXICO\u2019S NAFTA DREAMS AT ODDS WITH \u2018AMERICA FIRST\u2019: The U.S. may already be set on a collision course with its southern neighbor ahead of the upcoming renegotiation of NAFTA, after the first official glimpse of Mexico\u2019s negotiating goals this week shows a government focused on using the talks to further bolster the country\u2019s production and export platforms, Pro Trade\u2019s Adam Behsudi reports.  That goal, laid out in a statement of priorities submitted to the Mexican Senate and released this week, is unlikely to be well received by the Trump administration, which wants to revamp NAFTA in a way that reduces the U.S. trade deficit south of the border.  From Adam: \u201cThose conflicting views are balanced by the fact that many of the objectives laid out by [Mexican Economy Secretary Ildefonso] Guajardo square with what the U.S. wants out of a deal. But some of Mexico's priorities could be anathema to the Trump administration's \u2018America First\u2019 agenda, including demands for easing movement of workers across the border, ensuring opportunities for Mexican firms in U.S. government procurement and defending a NAFTA dispute settlement process that the U.S. has been clear it wants to jettison.\u201d  U.S. LUMBER INDUSTRY HATCHETS CANADIAN ASSERTIONS: The U.S. lumber industry is pushing back against reports that the United States and Canada are close to reaching a new agreement managing the cross-border trade in softwood lumber.  \u201cWe should be able to reach an agreement,\u201d Canadian Ambassador David MacNaughton said in a Canadian press report. \u201cThe ball is in their [U.S.] court. We have made clear we are prepared to manage to a market share \u2013 which is what they asked. We\u2019re just waiting for them to come back, and say yes.\u201d  MacNaughton said the U.S. and Canada have already agreed to cap Canadian imports at around 30 percent and major disagreement only remains on whether Canada or other countries would get first right to supply the market if the U.S. industry can\u2019t reach its domestic demand. Canada in 2016 committed to cap its supply to the U.S. \u201cat or below\u201d an agreed upon market share.  But U.S. Lumber Coalition Executive Director Zoltan van Heyningen said the industry\u2019s understanding \u201cis that the latest Canadian proposal would result in an \u2018at or above market share\u2019 agreement, which the industry will not accept.\u201d He added that the U.S. industry is working with the U.S. government toward a final deal that contains a \u201cclean quota\u201d for capping imports as a way to help a potential expansion of U.S. production.  MacNaughton\u2019s favorable attitude toward reaching a deal is a shift from the assessment at the end of June, when officials from both sides said the two sides were nowhere close to an agreement.  \u201cIt is disappointing that Canada continues to negotiate through the media,\u201d van Heyningen said.  GARRETT SPEAKS: REFORM EX-IM, BUT DON\u2019T KILL IT: Former Rep. Scott Garrett this week finally divulged his plans for the Export-Import Bank if he were confirmed as its head, telling the top senator in charge of vetting his nomination that he supports policies that would keep the agency operational.  In a letter to Senate Banking Chairman Mike Crapo (R-Idaho) after the pair met Tuesday, Garrett said he fully appreciated the role the bank plays in "aiding the global competitiveness of a number of manufacturers," including the U.S. aerospace industry. "I support the president's policy of having a fully staffed EXIM board and having EXIM functional as a U.S. export credit agency," Garrett said.  \u2014 Not so fast: "I also believe that EXIM must be reformed and modernized as outlined by Congress," Garrett wrote in the letter. He also pledged to pursue regular Export-Import Bank board meetings "to transparently and thoroughly review transactions that will help create American jobs and provide maximum value to the U.S. taxpayer."  \u2014 The Trump perspective: Amid mounting opposition from major corporations, business groups and lawmakers who support the bank, Trump had privately questioned whether to stick with Garrett just a few weeks ago. But the president has now decided to give the New Jersey Republican an opportunity to save his own nomination, POLITICO\u2019s Zachary Warmbrodt and Andrew Restuccia report. Trump has also underscored his support for Garrett in conversations with conservative lawmakers, a White House official said.   "He's looking to get a reformer in there," the official said, adding that Trump hopes Garrett can change the agency. The administration is developing a plan to make sweeping changes to the bank, officials said, but it's unclear when it will be unveiled publicly.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: The JET Program celebrates 30 years of strengthening educational and cultural ties between Japan and the United States. Through JET, the Japanese Government has sponsored 32,000 young Americans to live and work in communities across Japan. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **   DEMS\u2019 TRADE PLAN \u2018EVEN TOUGHER\u2019 THAN TRUMP\u2019S, SCHUMER SAYS: In many respects, the seven-step trade plan that Senate Democrats outlined on Wednesday felt almost Trumpian: It seeks to crack down on currency manipulators, toughen enforcement, punish companies that move jobs overseas and tighten \u201cBuy America\u201d provisions for all taxpayer-funded projects. But to Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer, the proposal goes further \u2014 and is \u201ceven tougher\u201d on China and other bad trade actors.  \u2014 A prosecutor to combat cheating: One section of the bill calls for creating a new trade prosecutor that could work outside the constraints of the WTO to revamp the U.S. trade enforcement system. Schumer highlighted the proposal as a more effective method to punish China than the Section 301 action the administration is expected to take that would examine Chinese policies that force U.S. companies to hand over valuable technology to do business there.  "We're tougher than Section 301 action," Schumer told POLITICO. "Our proposal with the new trade prosecutor is even tougher."  \u2014 Blocking foreign investment for economic security reasons: Another provision calls for the creation of an American Jobs Security Council, a panel that could block foreign purchases of U.S. companies for economic security reasons \u2014 similar to the way the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States can block sales on the basis of national security.  "CFIUS has to certify that the proposed deal doesn't harm our national security, but no one ever checks if it hurts our economic security," Schumer said. "We're not opposed to foreign investment, but we're opposed to foreign investment that only benefits the bottom line and leaves workers out in the cold."  Read the full plan here, and more from Schumer here.  WYDEN TO USTR: INVESTIGATE CHINA\u2019S FORCED TECH TRANSFER POLICIES: Sen. Ron Wyden, ranking member of the Finance Committee, sent a letter to U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer on Wednesday urging USTR to investigate Chinese policies that force U.S. companies to transfer technology in order to do business \u2014 the same policies Trump is expected to take action on as soon as this week.   "I write to urge you to investigate China's forced technology transfer policies and take appropriate action to ensure that U.S. manufacturers and service providers are no longer pressured to sacrifice critical intellectual property and operational freedom as a condition for accessing China's market," Wyden wrote.  Wyden detailed in the letter ways that China forces U.S. companies to transfer valuable technology, such as by requiring or pressuring foreign firms that want to do business in China to establish a joint venture with a Chinese partner. The Chinese government also has created tools that provide Chinese agencies with broad authority to intervene in the daily operation of companies to enable the transfer of U.S. and other foreign technology, he said.   Noting that the administration had made little progress on these issues during the Comprehensive Economic Dialogue this year, \u201cI urge appropriate additional steps be taken promptly to counter China's attempts to strong-arm U.S. innovators into giving up their intellectual property and drive U.S. firms further out of the Chinese market,\u201d Wyden said.  USTR\u2019S ENFORCEMENT AGENDA EXCLUDES ALUMINUM CASE: A case filed late in the Obama administration against Chinese government subsidies for primary aluminum producers did not receive a mention in USTR\u2019s congressionally mandated report this week on its 2017 enforcement priorities.   However, two other late Obama-era cases challenging China\u2019s domestic support for farmers and its administration of agricultural tariff-rate quotas did make the cut in a section titled, \u201cRobust Pursuit of Ongoing WTO Dispute Settlement Actions and Continued Enforcement Against Traditional Trade Barriers.\u201d   There was no explanation as to why the aluminum case was excluded, but the main industry group, the Aluminum Association, has been lukewarm on the litigation. In addition, the Commerce Department has been exploring the idea of restricting both aluminum and steel imports in the name of national security.  USTR VOWS \u2018AGGRESSIVE DEFENSE OF U.S. TRADE REMEDIES LAWS\u2019: Aluminum did get a mention elsewhere in the report, which USTR posted on its website without publicizing its release. In a section labeled \u201cAggressive Defense of U.S. Trade Remedies Laws,\u201d USTR noted the U.S. steel and aluminum industries are suffering from \u201cexcessive and uneconomic capacity in China,\u201d which it said is one reason why the United States will aggressively defend its trade remedy laws at the WTO.   Two other sections of the 11-page report promised \u201crigorous enforcement of intellectual property rights\u201d and a continued emphasis on \u201censuring foreign product standards do not create unnecessary obstacles to trade.\u201d USTR zeroed in on a number of Chinese measures, such as its new cybersecurity law, which it said \u201cappear to discriminate against foreign technologies in the name of protecting information security.\u201d China\u2019s draft Standardization Law also raises market access concerns, USTR said.   CHINA EXPERT: \u2018ONE BELT, ONE ROAD\u2019 IS ABOUT GROWING INFLUENCE: China\u2019s \u201cOne Belt, One Road\u201d initiative isn\u2019t solely for infrastructure and economic development, as Beijing says \u2014 it\u2019s also for expanding China\u2019s global influence, Nadge Rolland, a senior fellow at the National Bureau of Asian Research, said on Wednesday.  Currently, \u201cthe Chinese don\u2019t have the material and military capacities to change things on the ground through military power,\u201d Rolland said Wednesday at an event hosted by the Center for Strategic and International Studies. They want to increase their influence through these investments so that they can serve their own interests, he said.  For Beijing, the initiative is also a way for China to continue to grow its wealth without having to reform its economic or governmental structure, argued Rolland, who wrote a book on political and strategic implications of the initiative. Outside of the country, it sets the groundwork for a Eurasian continent where all roads lead to China.  \u201cWhen you put together all the puzzle pieces, you ... get China\u2019s vision of itself, for itself, as a great power and the preponderant power of the region,\u201d Rolland said. \u201cAnd when I say region, it\u2019s from China\u2019s eastern shores to Portugal, the Middle East, central Europe, central Asia and to the eastern shores of Africa. It is a big landmass that the [initiative] is supposed to serve.\u201d  TRUMP SIGNS, BUT CRITICIZES, RUSSIA SANCTIONS BILL: Moscow is facing new sanctions from Washington for its interference in the 2016 election after Trump signed the bill into law on Wednesday. But Trump, angered by provisions in the law that limit his power to lift the sanctions without congressional approval, protested in a signing statement what he saw as congressional encroachment on the president\u2019s power in foreign affairs.  In Brussels, officials had been on alert \u201cto launch countermeasures within days\u201d if it found that European companies were affected by the new sanctions coming out of Washington. After Trump signed the legislation, however, the European Commission said it was pleased the bill calls for close coordination with allies \u2014 though the bloc will \u201cremain vigilant\u201d to ensure European firms are not hit.  NORTH AMERICAN OIL AND GAS INDUSTRY UNITED ON NAFTA: The major oil and gas industry organizations in the U.S., Canada and Mexico are presenting a united front on what they want to see out of the renegotiation of NAFTA. The American Petroleum Institute, Canadian Association of Petroleum Producers and the Mexican Association of Hydrocarbon Companies outlined priorities that include the preservation of tariff reduction or elimination in energy trade, better market access, a modernized system of certificates of origin and regulatory cooperation. The groups also support a strong investor-state dispute settlement system. Read the full joint position paper here.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 Mexican Economy Secretary Ildefonso Guajardo said Mexico will host the second round of NAFTA talks around Sept. 10, Reuters reports.  \u2014 To make up for its lack of negotiating experience as it prepares for Brexit, the United Kingdom has set aside 2.5 million pounds to pay for training of new trade negotiators and has already spent 1.2 million pounds on headhunting, Bloomberg reports.  \u2014 Russian Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev called Washington\u2019s new sanctions against Russia a \u201cfull-scale trade war,\u201d the BBC reports.  \u2014 Vietnam has begun to rebound after its export-driven economy was jolted earlier this year when the United States discarded the Trans-Pacific Partnership, VOA reports.  THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
