aV \u000a            By MEGAN CASSELLA  08/02/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Adam Behsudi, Doug Palmer and Andrew Restuccia  SOURCES: TRUMP TO TAKE ACTION AGAINST CHINA FOR IP THEFT: President Donald Trump will soon call on U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer to open an investigation against China under Section 301 of the Trade Act of 1974 for violations of U.S. intellectual property rights and forced technology transfers, two administration officials told POLITICO.   Story Continued Below  An announcement is expected late this week, but an official cautioned it could slip into next week. U.S. companies have complained they are often forced to share valuable technology with Chinese counterparts as a condition of doing business in the country. Section 301 allows the U.S. to impose unilateral duties against countries that impose barriers to U.S. exports.  The action would give Lighthizer a leading role in a lengthy investigation that could peer into all aspects of Chinese industrial policies and potentially result in unilateral U.S. trade sanctions. As talk of the possible move circulated this week throughout the trade community, USTR\u2019s press office has remained mum.   Frustration that China is not doing more to persuade North Korea to rein in its nuclear program seems to be motivating the administration to fire a shot across the bow on the trade front, one source said. Many in the business community are likely to silently cheer the action as long overdue, but others may be worried about a further souring of the business environment and possible Chinese retaliation, a second source said.   Read Andrew Restuccia and Doug Palmer\u2019s story here.  SCHUMER ALSO SETS SIGHTS ON CHINA: Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer and other Democrats are set to roll out new trade legislation today with a special emphasis on stopping China and other countries from cheating on trade rules and manipulating markets for an unfair advantage.   Schumer has repeatedly goaded Trump to make good on campaign promises to get tough on China. On Tuesday, he urged the president to punish Beijing for its failure to stop North Korea by blocking it from making any further purchases of U.S. companies. \u201cIf China does not change its posture, the U.S. should take clear and firm action to seek to ensure China\u2019s cooperation," Schumer said.   The Democrats\u2019 new bill is part of their effort to convince voters they can offer \u201ca better deal\u201d for the middle class than the Republicans can under Trump. Look for a story on the new legislation later this morning.   IT\u2019S WEDNESDAY, AUG. 2! Welcome to Morning Trade, where your host is thinking that weekly oral histories might be the best way to help us remember what happened each day in this crazy news cycle. Any trade tips or news out there to shake up today? Let me know: mcassella@politico.com or @mmcassella.  NAFTA VISA ISSUES COULD PIT BIG BUSINESS AGAINST CAPITOL HILL: Businesses and major companies across North America are clamoring for reforms in the upcoming renegotiation of NAFTA that would ease the cross-border movement of workers and reduce the hassle Mexican and Canadian professionals face when trying to secure visas to work in the United States. But longheld views on Capitol Hill that free-trade agreements should not be used to negotiate immigration provisions make it unlikely anything will be changed in the updated trilateral deal, Pro Trade\u2019s Adam Behsudi reports this morning.  But frustration over the agreement's outdated labor provisions runs high: A new survey of 87 of some of the largest companies in the United States and Canada found that more than 90 percent said they want a NAFTA redo to make it easier for workers in today's high-tech economy to move across the border. The survey, which was conducted by the Canadian Employee Relocation Council and is set to be released later this week, reflects frustrations from businesses that differing interpretations and inconsistent decision-making at the border costs millions of dollars each year in lost production.  In Congress, however, lawmakers have been staunchly opposed to broaching the visa issue in the context of trade deals at least as far back as 2003, when the George W. Bush administration negotiated agreements with Singapore and Chile that set aside a specific number of work visas for professionals from those countries. At the time, leaders of the House Judiciary Committee warned USTR "in the strongest possible terms to never again agree to negotiate immigration provisions in bilateral or multilateral free trade agreements."  \u201cAnything that looks like a backdoor into the immigration system is going to be a challenge,\u201d said Daniel Ujczo, a lawyer based in Columbus, Ohio, who specializes in cross-border business issues between the U.S. and Canada. Plus, with the White House aggressively pushing \u201cBuy American, Hire American\u201d policies, there\u2019s even less of a chance that NAFTA 2.0 will lead to a major overhaul or clarification of provisions. Read the full story here.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: The JET Program celebrates 30 years of strengthening educational and cultural ties between Japan and the United States. Through JET, the Japanese Government has sponsored 32,000 young Americans to live and work in communities across Japan. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **   MEXICO WANTS LABOR MARKET INTEGRATION: One of Mexico\u2019s top priorities in NAFTA negotiations is better labor market integration, according to a Reuters report that cited an economy ministry document circulating in the Mexican Senate. It\u2019s unclear from the report if that will cover work visa issues.  "Our objective is to have an expedited negotiation that maintains the benefits that we have achieved during the lifespan of NAFTA, but which at the same time serves as a platform for the modernization of the treaty," the document says.  Mexico will seek to retain unimpeded access for goods and services in the NAFTA region, promote greater integration of North American labor markets and establish rules of origin to guarantee NAFTA's regional benefits, the document says.  GETTING BACK TO NORMAL ON JAPANESE BEEF: Negotiating a solution to the recent setback for U.S. beef producers from Japan\u2019s decision to raise tariffs on U.S. frozen beef could help pave the way to a bilateral trade deal, the U.S. Meat Export Federation is arguing this week in visits with senior trade officials in Washington.  Japan last week put in place a safeguard on imports of frozen beef after U.S. export volume exceeded a certain level. The move ratcheted up tariffs from 38.5 percent to 50 percent in U.S. producers\u2019 most lucrative foreign market. The higher tariff will remain in place until the end of March 2018 and doesn\u2019t apply to Japan\u2019s free-trade agreement partners, like Australia, a major beef exporter that already has cheaper access to the Japanese market.  USMEF President Philip Seng told Morning Trade he\u2019s pitching a solution the two countries could aspire to when officials meet again for the broader economic dialogue that launched earlier this year. One possibility is eliminating the annual 200 metric ton tariff-rate quota the U.S. places on imports of Japanese beef. By comparison, the U.S. exported 1.2 million tons of beef to Japan in 2016. The move to eliminate the TRQ could play well with Japan, which is seeking to boost exports of high-value agricultural products like Wagyu beef. Japan already hit its limit on June 16 and now faces a steeper tariff of 13.2 cents per kilogram as opposed to the 4.4 cents per kilogram that was paid for in-quota beef shipments.  He said the goodwill gesture on the part of the U.S. could be offered as a motivation for Japan to ease its safeguard measure. However, it could present a challenge for Japan since any changes would have to be approved by the Diet, but Seng said the move is unlikely to generate a major political controversy.  \u201cThat to me is an area for creativity,\u201d said Seng, who is traveling to Japan to present that option to Japanese officials. \u201cThe FTA approach is going to take a long time.\u201d  TECH GROUP PUSHES TRADE WISH LIST: U.S. technology companies face an increasing number of trade barriers around the world, including in several countries that have trade agreements with the United States, the Information Technology Industry Council said this week in comments filed with the Trump administration, which asked for input on how U.S. trade pacts are being abused and violated.   However, ITI also stressed how the tech industry has benefited from existing trade agreements, even if they could be better enforced. \u201cThey have created new commercial and investment opportunities for U.S. companies, reinforced the rule of law in U.S. trading partners, given U.S. stakeholders new tools to address difficult trade problems, allowed U.S. firms to participate in the development of regulations, and created greater global economic certainty and predictability,\u201d the group said.   Trump ordered USTR and the Commerce Department to conduct the investigation, with results expected to be delivered to the White House by the end of October. ITI urged the agencies to focus on technology-related trade barriers that prevent U.S. companies from selling their goods and services overseas or impede cross-border data flows that are vital to the economy.   A partial list of ITI\u2019s concerns includes data localization and restrictions on cross-border data flows in China, Colombia, the European Union, Indonesia, South Korea, Russia, and Vietnam; restrictions on the ability of cloud-computing companies to compete in China and South Korea; and rules that treat foreign firms and local companies differently in China, Colombia, India, Indonesia, South Korea, Russia and Vietnam.  AFL-CIO: GET TOUGHER ON CHINA: The AFL-CIO, in its comments, zeroed in on the labor provisions of trade agreements, which they said experience has shown are obviously inadequate. \u201cThe United States has never imposed trade sanctions, or even a fine, as a response to labor violations by FTA partner countries, even though U.S. trade partners include the world\u2019s worst violators of trade rights,\u201d the group said.   A big chunk of the AFL-CIO\u2019s relatively short submission was focused on China, which it said should be the target of much more aggressive U.S. trade action.  It called on the Trump administration to go after China in areas including currency misalignment, the exploitation of workers, unfair and predatory practices by state-owned and state-supported enterprises, illegal government subsidies, non-tariff barriers such as onerous licensing and certification requirements, forced technology transfer, intellectual property theft and overproduction.  TEXTILE GROUP: TIME FOR OTHERS TO CATCH UP WITH U.S.: The National Council of Textile Organizations, which has seen its industry shrink dramatically over the past several decades, also weighed in with criticism of trade deals.   The WTO, in particular, \u201chas fostered an entitlement mindset among many of its members, leading to a belief that industrialized countries, such as the United States, should grant ever increasing access to their markets, while being satisfied with unfair and nonreciprocal treatment on the part of other WTO trading partners,\u201d the group said.   As result of WTO commitments, the average U.S. bound tariff is 3.5 percent, compared to the WTO member average of 39 percent, the group said. \u201cClearly, the United States should not make any additional tariff concessions until other WTO members reduce their tariffs and border-adjusted taxes to our level,\u201d the NCTO said.   DEMOCRATS NOT CONVINCED BY GARRETT\u2019S EX-IM PLEDGE: Senate Democrats who have criticized Trump\u2019s decision to nominate Scott Garrett to lead the Export-Import Bank aren\u2019t letting the former congressman off easy in his quest to convince them that, if confirmed, he would support the bank he previously wanted to shut down.  After a meeting with Democrats on Tuesday, Garrett struck a far different tone than he did while in Congress, telling Pro Financial Services\u2019 Zachary Warmbrodt that as president of the agency he would work to advance the administration\u2019s pro-manufacturing agenda. The comment marks a stark difference from his time on Capitol Hill, when he worked to shut down the agency that he said embodied \u201cthe corruption of the free enterprise system.\u201d   "My job would be to fulfill the administration's agenda of creating more jobs and helping manufacturing in this country," Garrett said Tuesday. "That's our agenda."  But Senate Democrats walked away unconvinced, branding the meeting \u201cbizarre\u201d and criticizing Garrett for his refusal to share his personal thoughts about the bank and its mission. In a joint statement following the meeting, eight senators including Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer also said Garrett refused to say whether he would \u201cunequivocally support\u201d the bank\u2019s reauthorization and said \u201che clearly knew very little about the critical work the bank is doing to support small businesses and expand opportunities for U.S. manufacturers, which was both surprising and concerning.\u201d  \u201cSo we\u2019re supposed to trust that someone who has extensive history undermining and disparaging the bank will now support and lead it even though he doesn\u2019t seem to believe his own words?\u201d the group of lawmakers, including Sen. Sherrod Brown, the ranking member of the Banking Committee, and Sens. Heidi Heitkamp (D-N.D.) and Joe Donnelly (D-Ind.).   Brown, in a brief interview after the meeting, said Garrett has a "ways to go" before he wins the support of groups like the National Association of Manufacturers. "I think there will be difficulty for Scott Garrett,\u201d he said. Read more here.  PASCRELL LEADS CALL TO REFORM VISA PROGRAM TO PROTECT WORKERS: A bipartisan group of lawmakers is calling on the president to put his money where his mouth is when it comes to protecting U.S. workers, asking him to back legislation that would reform existing visa programs and crack down on companies that abuse current law to use significant numbers of foreign workers to displace American employees.  Led by Rep. Bill Pascrell (D-N.J.), the ranking member on the House Ways and Means Subcommittee on Trade, the five lawmakers from both sides of the Capitol urged Trump to support the Visa Reform Act of 2017 that would help close loopholes in the H-1B and L-1 visa programs and provide more oversight.  Sen. Dick Durbin (D-Ill.) and Reps. Dave Brat (R-Va.), Ro Khanna (D-Calif.), and Paul Gosar (R-Ariz.) also signed the letter.  \u201cIn your remarks in Kenosha, Wis., you identified the issue with current law when it comes to \u2018allowing American workers of all backgrounds to be replaced by workers brought in from other countries to fill the same job for sometimes less pay,\u2019\u201d they wrote. \u201cTo address that issue, our legislation provides protections for American workers and visa holders and requires more transparency in the recruitment of foreign workers.\u201d Read more here.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 U.S., Canadian and Mexican officials will hold a dinner to mark the start of NAFTA talks later this month, The Canadian Press reports.  \u2014 Canada is dispatching a senior trade official to Washington as deputy ambassador to provide support for upcoming NAFTA talks, The Canadian Press reports.  \u2014 Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross vows in a Wall Street Journal op-ed to go after China and the European Union for hypocrisy on protectionism, POLITICO Pro reports.  \u2014 British finance minister Philip Hammond says the U.K. is interested in pursuing a free trade deal with Brazil once it completes its exit from the European Union, according to a Euronews report.  \u2014 India\u2019s minister of state of commerce and industry is pushing Beijing to provide a level playing field for Indian IT, pharmaceutical and agricultural products to reduce the trade deficit between the two countries, the Hindustan Times reports.  THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
