aV \u000a            By ADAM BEHSUDI  08/01/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Megan Cassella and Doug Palmer  BUSINESS GROUPS HAVE LITTLE TO SAY FOR TRUMP TRADE DEAL REVIEW: Some of the biggest cheerleaders of free trade, including the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and National Foreign Trade Council, aren\u2019t biting on a Trump administration request for comments on its review of trade agreement violations and abuses.  Story Continued Below  The Chamber\u2019s 18-page submission is primarily focused on the opportunities that trade deals have created for the U.S. economy as opposed to their drawbacks. The organization does note that enforcement of trade agreement rules is \u201cessential.\u201d   But when it comes to addressing the core question of identifying trade agreement violations per President Donald Trump\u2019s executive order, the business group makes it clear that reports like the National Trade Estimate Report on Foreign Trade Barriers are already in place to do that.  \u201cPreparation of this annual report is required by statute,\u201d the Chamber said in its comments. \u201cU.S. Chamber member companies and associations have long contributed extensively to the preparation of this report, which is and should be the default resource for the administration as it considers the next steps in its trade policy actions.\u201d  The NFTC reminded the administration in its 12-page submission that the U.S. International Trade Commission published an economic impact analysis just last year that looked at all U.S. free trade agreements since 1984, as well as the 1994 Uruguay Round world trade agreement. That largely positive report was requested by Congress in the 2015 trade promotion authority bill.  The business group also stressed the geopolitical benefits of trade deals. \u201cIt is undeniable that one of NAFTA\u2019s most important benefits is the existence of a more prosperous, stable and democratic neighbor on our southern border than was the case prior to the agreement,\u201d while other deals have helped improve ties with countries in Latin America, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, the NFTC said.   IT\u2019S TUESDAY, AUGUST 1! Welcome to Morning Trade, where your host is quite sure where the summer is going. It\u2019s August already and we\u2019re hoping upcoming NAFTA talks don\u2019t send a cold wind our way. Got any news to share? Let me know: abehsudi@politico.om or @abehsudi.  MNUCHIN WON\u2019T RULE OUT BLOCKING VENEZUELAN OIL IMPORTS: After taking the dramatic step Monday of slapping sanctions on Venezuelan President Nicols Maduro, the Trump administration kept open the possibility of also shutting down oil trade with the South American country to punish Maduro\u2019s government.   \u201cWe very much believe that sanctions do work,\u201d Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin told reporters at a White House briefing to announce the action, which came one day after what U.S. officials called a sham election to give the government sweeping new powers. \u201cWe will continue to monitor the situation and consider additional sanctions.\u201d   Mnuchin kept to that script in the face of repeated attempts by reporters to pry out more details, including whether the Trump administration could impose an embargo on oil imports from Venezuela or shut down U.S. oil exports to the country. \u201cThis president is not going to advertise what he\u2019s going to do in the future. So all options are on the table and we will consider everything,\u201d Mnuchin said.   The United States imports about 700,000 to 800,000 barrels per day of Venezuelan heavy crude oil to refineries in Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi. It also exports about 30,000 barrels per day of oil to Venezuela for blending with the heavier product.   Shutting down that trade would require oil companies in both countries to scramble to find other suppliers and customers. But unless the Trump administration persuaded other countries to follow along, the move might not have much impact beyond increasing transportation costs and gasoline prices, said Adam Sieminski, a former National Security Council official now at the Center for Strategic and International Studies.   Still, the Trump administration keeps \u201ctalking about energy dominance, using our oil as a way to look strong on a geopolitical stage,\u201d Sieminski noted. \u201cSo, yes, it sounds to me like they could do something. But it\u2019s not without its complications. I think the best word for this is messy.\u201d   ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: The JET Program celebrates 30 years of strengthening educational and cultural ties between Japan and the United States. Through JET, the Japanese Government has sponsored 32,000 young Americans to live and work in communities across Japan. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **   MEXICO NAMES NEW CHIEF NAFTA NEGOTIATOR: Mexico is building out its negotiating team in preparation for the much-awaited renegotiation of NAFTA, naming Kenneth Smith Ramos on Monday to be its chief technical negotiator. Ramos, the head of the trade and NAFTA office at the Mexican Embassy in Washington, will work just below Economy Secretary Ildefonso Guajardo and Undersecretary for Foreign Trade Juan Carlos Baker in leading the negotiations, a Guajardo spokesperson told Morning Trade.  Guajardo, speaking to reporters on Monday, highlighted Ramos\u2019 past work in Mexico\u2019s agriculture department as well as its economy ministry in announcing his appointment. \u201cHe is a man who has had a very, very long, intense and brilliant career in all foreign trade topics,\u201d Guajardo said in Spanish.   SCARAMUCCI\u2019S FALL FROM GRACE MAY INCLUDE AN EX-IM EXIT: It remains somewhat up in the air whether Anthony Scaramucci, who was ousted from his position as White House communications director on Monday after 10 days on the job, will now return to his previous role in the administration as senior vice president and chief strategy officer at the Export-Import Bank.   Scaramucci does not have any administration role \u201cat this time,\u201d White House press secretary Sarah Sanders told reporters on Monday, though she refused to elaborate on the circumstances surrounding his departure. \u201cI\u2019m not going to get into the process tick-tock. Look, as we\u2019ve said several times before, what matters most to us is not who\u2019s employed in the White House but who\u2019s employed in the rest of the country.\u201d  The financier and Trump loyalist joined Ex-Im on June 19, though he had been on leave from the day he started and gave up his $172,100 salary. The Ex-Im gig had been seen as a \u201cvery temporary move,\u201d a way to get Scaramucci to Washington before a more prominent role could be found, one White House adviser told POLITICO.  A spokeswoman for the bank said officials there were looking into the matter, and she did not respond to a further request for comment. Read more on the Mooch\u2019s exit here.  CANADA\u2019S STATE OUTREACH EFFORT EXTENDS TO MICHIGAN: Amid ongoing efforts in Canada to ramp up economic ties with individual U.S. states before NAFTA renegotiation begins, officials in Ontario and Michigan are pledging to enhance collaboration and further integrate the Great Lakes region\u2019s automobile sector.   The memorandum of understanding signed between Michigan\u2019s Department of Transportation and Ontario\u2019s Ministry of Transportation \u201cperfectly illustrates Ontario\u2019s commitment to strengthening our partnerships across the United States,\u201d Brad Duguid, Ontario\u2019s minister of economic development and growth, said in a statement announcing the deal. The partnership will focus in part on creating self-driving technology and enable \u201cjob-creating growth\u201d for both regions.  \u201cThe deep integration of the Great Lakes auto cluster helps foster industry-leading innovation and allows companies on both sides of the border to be competitive around the globe,\u201d Duguid said. \u201cWe\u2019re proud to be leveraging our shared ties to enhance a crucial, growing sector, and ensure a good future for workers in Ontario and Michigan alike.\u201d  TAI MOVES UP TO TAKE DEMS\u2019 CHIEF COUNSEL SLOT ON WAYS AND MEANS: Veteran trade attorney Katherine Tai will become the new chief trade counsel for Democrats on the House Ways and Means Committee, taking the place of Jason Kearns, who resigned late last week as he awaits confirmation to become a commissioner at the International Trade Commission.  Tai, who has worked with the Ways and Means Democrats as a trade counsel since 2014, also has eight years of experience at the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative. From 2007 to 2014, Tai worked in the general counsel\u2019s office at USTR and, in her later years there, as chief counsel for China trade enforcement.  "Throughout her service in two administrations at USTR and years with our committee, Katherine has proven she has the knowledge and experience to tackle and understand our nation's most pressing trade issues," Ways and Means ranking member Richard Neal (D-Mass.) said in a statement announcing the move. "I am happy to welcome her to this new role, and I am confident she will play an important part in helping Democrats improve our nation's trade policy in the years ahead."  EU-U.S. PRIVACY SHIELD HOBBLES ALONG: A year-old data-sharing deal between the European Union and the United States has managed to survive despite expectations that it was doomed from the start. But the EU-U.S. Privacy Shield faces an uncertain future as policymakers start planning for the first annual review of the agreement in mid-September in Washington, D.C.  \u201cAs long as there\u2019s no definitive voice from regulators on Privacy Shield\u2019s future, there will be a sword of Damocles hanging over the agreement,\u201d said Wim Nauwelaerts, a data protection lawyer at Hunton & Williams in Brussels. \u201cA lot of companies have taken the trouble to get certified, but there are still so many uncertainties.\u201d  Discussions between European and American officials are focused on small tweaks to the agreement, and the upcoming review looks unlikely to solve that uncertainty. Instead, how companies move digital data \u2014 everything from social media posts and search queries to companies\u2019 payroll and pension data \u2014 is expected to be resolved eventually by legal challenges and other disagreements that still swirl over the data-transfer agreement. POLITICO Europe\u2019s Mark Scott has the full story here.  WHITE HOUSE EYES SPEEDY TAX REFORM TIMELINE: The Trump administration expects tax reform legislation to move quickly through Congress this fall, advancing through the House in October and clearing the Senate in November, legislative director Marc Short said Monday. Markups will begin in September, he said during an event hosted by a pair of conservative political groups backed by the billionaire Koch brothers \u2014 Freedom Partners and Americans for Prosperity.   Short's ambitious timeline is the most specific laid out by the White House or Congress in recent months, reports Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo. It tracks with a joint statement issued by administration and congressional negotiators last week, which said the expectation is that tax reform legislation will move through committees \u201cthis fall,\u201d followed by consideration on the House and Senate floor. Republicans are planning to use special instructions in a budget resolution -- should it advance through Congress -- to pass tax reform with a simple majority in the Senate in order to short-circuit a Democratic filibuster. But Short also suggested a Republican-only pathway isn't completely necessary. Some Democrats might get on board, particularly those up for reelection next year in states Trump carried, he said.  WTO RELEASES A PUBLIC-FORUM PREVIEW: Sustainability, fisheries subsidies, Buenos Aires and inclusive trade will all be in the spotlight at various points next month when the World Trade Organization kicks off its annual public forum in Geneva, Switzerland. A provisional schedule released on Monday shows that the three-day conference, entitled \u201cTrade: Behind the Headlines,\u201d will feature more than 100 sessions exploring topics ranging from potential outcomes for the upcoming ministerial conference in December to Trump\u2019s trade policies and why such protectionist views are on the rise in developed countries. Check it out here.  SOUTH KOREA TRADE MINISTER PICK DEEPENS WTO TRADE-CASE STRAIN: South Korea\u2019s appointment of Kim Hyun-chong as trade minister punches another hole in the WTO\u2019s Appellate Body, where Kim had recently begun a four-year term. Kim will have to resign his position on the Appellate Body, bringing to three the number of current and expected vacancies on the critical seven-member board. His pending departure would increase the burden on the overworked judicial panel, which has become a de facto last stop for almost every trade case filed at the WTO, and add to heated debate over how to fill the vacancies without further delaying pending cases.  Delays at the Appellate Body are already seen as normal as the judicial panel strains under the buildup of ever-more complex cases, including a long-running fight between the U.S. and the European Union over commercial aircraft subsidies. In June, Appellate Body member Ricardo Ramirez-Hernndez's second and final term ended, and on Dec. 11, the same will be true for another member, Peter Van den Bossche. Ramirez-Hernndez is staying on to handle some of the pending appeals in which he is involved. Read the full story here.  FLAKE TAKES A STAND AGAINST TRUMP: Sen. Jeff Flake, in an excerpt from his book published in POLITICO Magazine, reflects on his party\u2019s role in Trump\u2019s presidency and advises his GOP colleagues not to lose sight of conservative ideals, including free trade.   \u201cSo, where should Republicans go from here?\u201d the Arizona Republican writes. \u201cFirst, we shouldn\u2019t hesitate to speak out if the president \u2018plays to the base\u2019 in ways that damage the Republican Party\u2019s ability to grow and speak to a larger audience. Second, Republicans need to take the long view when it comes to issues like free trade: Populist and protectionist policies might play well in the short term, but they handicap the country in the long term. Third, Republicans need to stand up for institutions and prerogatives, like the Senate filibuster, that have served us well for more than two centuries.\u201d Read the full piece here.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 Qatar files a wide-ranging WTO challenge of a trade boycott from Saudi Arabia, Egypt and the United Arab Emirates, Reuters reports.  \u2014 Trump keeps President Barack Obama\u2019s Mexico ambassador in place as envoy south of the border, Bloomberg reports.  \u2014 China\u2019s services trade deficit rises to its highest since the end of 2013 as the Chinese spend more abroad, Reuters reports.  \u2014 Top Iowa officials fear that tensions with Beijing over North Korea could wipe out agricultural gains with China, The Waterloo Courier reports.  THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  Adam Behsudi is a trade reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Prior to joining POLITICO, he covered international trade policy for Inside U.S. Trade, where he tracked down the latest news on the Trans-Pacific Partnership from exotic locales such as Auckland, New Zealand; Kota Kinabalu, Malaysia; and Leesburg, Va.  Before writing about anti-dumping, export controls and other trade subjects, Behsudi covered city hall for the Frederick News-Post. He got his start in journalism chasing crooked sheriffs and other crime-related news in the mountains of western North Carolina for the Asheville Citizen-Times.  Behsudi earned his bachelor\u2019s degree in 2005 from the University of Missouri. With the hope that journalism could return as a growth industry within his lifetime, he earned a master\u2019s degree in interactive journalism from American University in 2010.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
