aV \u000a            By MEGAN CASSELLA  07/31/2017 10:01 AM EDT  With help from Doug Palmer  TRUMP ADMINISTRATION\u2019S CHINA PLAN COULD COME THIS WEEK: President Donald Trump and his administration are considering a handful of economic measures meant to punish China, with a final decision coming as soon as this week, administration officials told POLITICO.  Story Continued Below  Trump\u2019s aides met over the weekend to discuss options, including trade restrictions or economic sanctions, and they will continue those conversations today. It remains too early, however, to say what the president might decide, the officials said.  While the latest discussions come as the Commerce Department continues to conduct a review examining whether to limit imports of steel and aluminum for national security reasons \u2014 an investigation aimed largely at China \u2014 this week\u2019s talks are not solely centered on that, officials said.  The decision may come as the president grows increasingly frustrated with Beijing over its handling of the North Korea missile situation, including Friday\u2019s latest intercontinental ballistic missile test. "I am very disappointed in China. Our foolish past leaders have allowed them to make hundreds of billions of dollars a year in trade, yet they do NOTHING for us with North Korea, just talk. We will no longer allow this to continue. China could easily solve this problem!\u201d Trump said on Twitter over the weekend.  On the trade front, Trump has also long complained about what he sees as unfair trade practices by Beijing, and he has been encouraged particularly by some of the harder-line aides in his administration \u2014 like chief strategist Steve Bannon and Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy Director Peter Navarro \u2014 to crack down on China. Read more from POLITICO\u2019s Andrew Restuccia and Josh Dawsey here.  IT\u2019S MONDAY, JULY 31! Welcome to Morning Trade, where we highly recommend reading this first-person article in POLITICO magazine by a transgender veteran who served six combat tours in Iraq and Afghanistan. Got any other first-person stories about politics and policy? Let me know: mcassella@politico.com or @mmcassella.  TOUGH HURDLES IN THE CHINA BEEF DEAL: In other China news, Trump's deal to reopen China's market to U.S. beef exports could turn out to be something less than a blockbuster -- unless a large portion of the U.S. cattle industry weans itself off its reliance on artificial growth hormones, which are not allowed in shipments to China under the terms of the pact.   In exchange for Beijing dropping a ban on U.S. beef that was imposed after a few cases of mad cow disease were found in U.S. stock nearly 14 years ago, the Trump administration agreed that U.S. producers would ship only beef that came from cattle raised without artificial growth hormones. It also promised the beef would be free of any trace of ractopamine or other beta agonists, a class of feed additives used to produce leaner meat.  \u201cThose compounds are used widely in the U.S. and to forgo them would cost cattle producers and feeders upwards of $275/head,\u201d one analyst, who asked not be identified, told POLITICO in an email. \u201cThat premium is not being offset by China. We will still ship some small (niche) volumes to China, but the China deal is not commercially viable.\u201d  In a sign of the mountain U.S. producers must climb, the U.S. sold just 130 metric tons of beef to China in the one month since beef trade resumed, compared with 37,000 tons to Japan \u2014 its largest export market \u2014 over the same period. To read Doug Palmer\u2019s full story, click here.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: The JET Program celebrates 30 years of strengthening educational and cultural ties between Japan and the United States. Through JET, the Japanese Government has sponsored 32,000 young Americans to live and work in communities across Japan. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **   DEADLINE FOR TRADE \u201cVIOLATIONS AND ABUSES\u201d COMMENT TODAY: One of the flurry of executive orders President Donald Trump signed this spring called for a \u201cperformance review\u201d of all U.S. trade agreements to identify \u201cviolations and abuses.\u201d Interested groups and individuals have until midnight today to submit comments to help the USTR, the Commerce Department and other government agencies in their review of how well the World Trade Organization pact and various bilateral and regional free agreements are working. The results of that inquiry are due to Trump by Oct. 26, although many other trade-related deadlines have come and gone in recent months.   You may recall Trump signed another executive order on March 31 asking for an investigation into the causes of significant trade deficits. That report was due to the White House by the end of June, but has not yet been released. Two other reports looking into whether the White House should restrict steel and aluminum imports to protect national security are also still under wraps, even though Trump, at one point, indicated they would be out by June 30.   STEWART AND STEWART WEIGHS IN ON WTO WOES: Terry Stewart, managing partner at the law firm of Stewart and Stewart, sent us his comments on trade agreement violations and abuses by email. He focused most of his attention on the World Trade Organization, which he argued is much harder to reform than bilateral free trade or investment pacts.  That\u2019s because \u201cthere is no agreement amongst the major economic powers on their relative responsibility for moving the system forward,\u201d Stewart said in an email. \u201cMembers, unfortunately, appear to be pursuing short term interests versus protecting the importance of a balanced system for all members in the longer term.\u201d   One big problem that hurts U.S. export competitiveness are WTO rules that treat direct and indirect taxes differently, Stewart said. Every country that runs a significant trade surplus with the United States has significant indirect taxes that are assessed on imports and rebated on exports, putting U.S. goods at a price disadvantage, he said.  Stewart also argued the WTO has inadequate rules for dealing with large state-directed economies like China. In addition, it is unable to fix errors made by its dispute settlement panels or the WTO Appellate Body. Both problems, he said, hurt the United States.   KEARNS SAYS GOODBYE, FOR NOW: Jason Kearns, the longtime chief international trade counsel for House Ways and Means Democrats, stepped down from his job on Friday while he waits for Senate action on his next gig: judging anti-dumping and countervailing duty cases as a member of the International Trade Commission. Right now, he\u2019s in a queue with several other trade nominees, waiting for the Senate Finance Committee to announce a date for a hearing.   Kearns joined the Ways and Means staff in 2006 and became chief international counsel for the subcommittee in 2012. During his tenure, he worked particularly closely with Rep. Sander Levin, the former top Democrat on Ways and Means. \u201cHis knowledge and work ethic have been indispensable to the committee as the U.S. has considered specific trade deals from CAFTA to TPP and now, the renegotiation of NAFTA. The ITC will only benefit from his experience and talents once he is confirmed,\u201d Levin said.  Current ranking member Rep. Richard Neal also wished Kearns continued success. \u201cJason has been an outstanding leader and asset to the Ways and Means Committee for more than a decade, providing insightful analysis and knowledge on a range of trade issues for staff and members alike,\u201d Neal said.   U.S. BEEF PRODUCERS COULD HAVE BEEN SPARED NEW DUTIES: Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue is taking Japan to task for its decision to raise tariffs on U.S. frozen-beef exports. The situation could have been prevented if the administration had moved forward with the Trans-Pacific Partnership earlier this year.  The move to increase tariffs an additional 11.5 percentage points \u2014 a level that will stay in place until Japan\u2019s fiscal year ends in April 2018 \u2014 has renewed tensions between the two nations and led the secretary to warn on Friday that the bilateral relationship was at risk of moving backward.  "I am concerned that an increase in Japan's tariff on frozen beef imports will impede U.S. beef sales and is likely to increase the United States' overall trade deficit with Japan," Perdue said.  Japan's action applies to all countries with which it does not have a free trade agreement. But it does have a deal in place with Australia, so that country will benefit by not being hit by the higher duty. U.S. producers would have been spared if Trump had not withdrawn from the TPP on his third day in office and if it had ultimately been approved by Congress. But for now, the administration can only complain.  "This would harm our important bilateral trade relationship with Japan on agricultural products," Perdue added. "It would also negatively affect Japanese consumers by raising prices and limiting their access to high-quality U.S. frozen beef. I have asked representatives of the Japanese government directly and clearly to make every effort to address these strong concerns, and the harm that could result to both American producers and Japanese consumers." Read more from Doug Palmer here.  DEATH OF THE BAT LEAVES CONSERVATIVES NEAR CONSENSUS ON TAX REFORM: With Republicans still reeling from last week\u2019s failed Senate vote on health care, party leaders have set their sights on tax reform for a much-needed legislative win. To that end, House Speaker Paul Ryan is working on a plan to mix permanent changes with some temporary ones in order to comply with budgetary rules and write a bill that could get passed, POLITICO\u2019s Colin Wilhelm reports.  Grover Norquist, president of Americans for Tax Reform, said that conservatives were at \u201c97 percent\u201d agreement on tax reform after the tax on imports, known as \u201cborder adjustment,\u201d was tabled last week.  The top priority is to lower overall business and individual tax rates as quickly as possible, Ryan told conservative activists during a closed-door meeting in his office, according to multiple individuals present. Cuts to business and individual rates will likely be permanent, as will some sort of carrot-and-stick approach to prevent companies from offshoring revenues and other assets. Read more here.  SCOTT GARRETT\u2019S EX-IM WOES PILE ON: As former Rep. Scott Garrett faces an increasingly uphill battle in his quest to earn Senate confirmation to lead the Export-Import Bank, two prominent business and manufacturing groups in Texas are protesting his nomination.  The heads of the Texas Association of Manufacturers and the Texas Association of Business are calling on Trump to withdraw Garrett\u2019s nomination, saying that his history of anti-Ex-Im views and his record of voting against the bank undermine promises to create jobs and boost the U.S. manufacturing sector.   \u201cWe cannot support a nominee who is flatly opposed to the existence of the bank - one who would destroy the Texas jobs the bank helps create and unilaterally disarm American businesses on the global stage out of misguided ideology,\u201d Tony Bennett and Chris Wallace wrote in an op-ed in the Houston Chronicle. \u201cPutting such a committed opponent of the bank in charge of its operations will only yield more of the dysfunction and gridlock that the American people rejected when they voted to change business as usual in Washington by electing Trump.\u201d   Their calls are the latest in a growing chorus of bank supporters who fear that Garrett, if confirmed, would use his position atop the agency to try to hamstring it from within. They also signal the extent to which a Washington debate is filtering down to the state level, which could ultimately put pressure on the lawmakers charged with voting on his confirmation. Read the full piece here.  MARCHANT\u2019S NAFTA ADVICE: PUSH FOR MORE TRADE In other news from the Lone Star State, Rep. Kenny Marchant (R-Texas) is urging the administration and the USTR to abide by its own stated principle for the NAFTA talks to \u201cfirst, do no harm.\u201d In a Dallas Morning News op-ed, the congressman, who sits on the House Ways and Means Committee, touted a series of benefits Texans have reaped from the trilateral deal. He called on negotiators to maintain the original framework of the deal while modernizing it to allow for more trade, not less.  Rules governing digital trade should be a top priority in the coming talks, Marchant said, adding that the \u201crapidly expanding digital economy\u201d was \u201cin its infancy\u201d when the nearly quarter-century-old agreement came into effect. Read the full piece here.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 Trade ministers of the BRICS nations \u2014 Brazil, Russia, India, China and South Africa \u2014 are meeting in Shanghai this week amid rising tensions between the Asian members primarily over the border, Bloomberg reports.  \u2014 South Korea's president on Sunday appointed a new trade minister as the nation gets ready to modify its free trade agreement with the U.S., Reuters reports.  \u2014 Qatar\u2019s imports slumped 40 percent in June, official data show, after the embargo imposed by neighboring countries took a toll, the Financial Times reports.  THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
