aV \u000a            By ADAM BEHSUDI  07/28/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Doug Palmer, Megan Cassella and Catherine Boudreau  STEEL TARIFF THREAT COOLS DOWN: President Donald Trump\u2019s plans to hit steel and aluminum imports with tariffs and/or quotas will be put on ice for a while longer, according to House lawmakers briefed Thursday afternoon by Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross.  Story Continued Below  Ross, speaking to members of the House Ways and Means Committee, \u201csaid that the current forums that we have \u2014 the WTO and the global steel forum \u2014 have not been adequate in addressing this over-dumping issue, and that he is hoping for some way to negotiate in a dialogue with these countries to resolve the problem,\u201d said Rep. Judy Chu, a California Democrat.  Ross had initially been expected to deliver reports investigating the national security threats posed by steel and aluminum imports to the White House by the end of last month. But Trump, who will ultimately decide on how to proceed and has previously promised a crackdown on steel dumping, told The Wall Street Journal earlier this week that "we don't want to do it at this moment." The president added that the administration would most likely take action "fairly soon."  Ross read the president's recent statements out loud during the briefing and said that those are the orders he is following, Rep. Sander Levin, a Michigan Democrat who was previously ranking member of Ways and Means, told reporters afterward.  "I think the secretary, given his druthers, is up to being part of a negotiating team with other countries," said Rep. Bill Pascrell, the top Democrat on W&M\u2019s Trade Subcommittee. Get Megan Cassella\u2019s full rundown on the briefing here.   IT\u2019S FRIDAY, JULY 28! Welcome to Morning Trade, where your hosts wishes he might be cool enough to be jamming with a funk band when he turns 84. Got any cool trade news to help us on this hot day? Let me know: abehsudi@politico.com or @abehsudi.  U.S. FROZEN BEEF EXPORTS TO JAPAN TRIGGER TARIFF HIKE: As if U.S. producers didn\u2019t have enough to lose in beef exports to Japan, Tokyo invoked a safeguard measure on imports of frozen beef from the U.S. and other countries, ratcheting up tariffs from 38.5 percent to 50 percent, per the U.S. Meat Export Federation. Under the terms of its Japan\u2019s WTO membership, it instituted a safeguard that would trigger if the quarter import volume exceeded the previous corresponding quarter by 17 percent. Imports during the first quarter of Japan\u2019s fiscal year (April 1-June 30) topped the threshold by a mere 115 metric tons, meaning the increased tariff will be applied for the remainder of Japan\u2019s fiscal year. About 45 percent of U.S. beef exports to Japan are frozen.  \u201cUSMEF recognizes that the safeguard will not only have negative implications for U.S. beef producers, but will also have a significant impact on the Japanese foodservice industry,\u201d USMEF President and CEO Philip Seng said in a statement. \u201cIt will be especially difficult for the gyudon beef bowl restaurants that rely heavily on Choice U.S. short plate as a primary ingredient.\u201d  For U.S. producers, it gets worse: The safeguard won\u2019t apply to imports of Australian beef, which will continue to enjoy a lower tariff of 27.2 percent and are not subject to safeguard tariffs per terms of a deal it signed with Japan in 2015. However, the USMEF argues the Japanese food service industry prefers U.S. short plate, a belly cut, which accounts for a majority of U.S. frozen beef exports to Japan. Still, the organization acknowledges the situation makes Australia\u2019s position even more advantageous.  FINANCE SETS KAPLAN CONFIRMATION HEARING: The Senate Finance Committee will hold a hearing Thursday on the nomination of longtime trade attorney Gilbert Kaplan to be undersecretary of Commerce for international trade, nearly four months after Trump tapped him for the job.   Kaplan is a partner in the international trade group at King & Spalding, a law firm that often represents companies seeking anti-dumping and countervailing duties on imports. He served as deputy assistant secretary and acting assistant secretary of Commerce for import administration during the Reagan administration, where he supervised over 500 trade remedy cases, according to a White House bio.   Kaplan also was a key negotiator of the United States-Japan Semiconductor Agreement, an example of \u201cmanaged trade agreements\u201d that many think could come back into fashion in the Trump administration. In 2010, Kaplan represented U.S. paper producers in a countervailing duty case against China, where the petitioners asked that Beijing\u2019s policy of undervaluing its currency be treated as an illegal subsidy under U.S. trade law.  The Commerce Department decided against taking that step, but Kaplan could soon be in a position to shape its views on such matters.   In other nomination news: The White House on Thursday officially sent to the Senate its nomination of C.J. Mahoney for deputy U.S. trade representative. Mahoney\u2019s nomination as deputy in charge of investment, services, labor, environment, Africa, China and the Western Hemisphere was announced last week.  R.I.P., BORDER ADJUSTMENT TAX: White House and congressional leaders agreed to drop a controversial border adjustment tax proposal as they try to move forward with a broader tax reform effort. The proposal, which would have placed a blanket tax on all imports, had been an integral part of House Republicans\u2019 tax reform blueprint as a way to pay for a corporate tax cut.   "While we have debated the pro-growth benefits of border adjustability, we appreciate that there are many unknowns associated with it and have decided to set this policy aside in order to advance tax reform," House Speaker Paul Ryan, House Ways and Means Chairman Kevin Brady, Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin, Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, Senate Finance Chairman Orrin Hatch, and National Economic Council Director Gary Cohn said in a statement.  "[W]e are now confident that, without transitioning to a new domestic consumption-based tax system, there is a viable approach for ensuring a level playing field between American and foreign companies and workers, while protecting American jobs and the U.S. tax base," they said.  The BAT could rise again: Brady, who along with Ryan was a big supporter of border adjustability, told reporters that "in order for us to unify it was important to set it aside, for now. Perhaps there will be study in future years on it."  \u201cWe\u2019ve been actively exploring with the Senate and the White House a viable alternative," he added. "[We] still have work to do but I like the path we\u2019re going.\u201d Read the full story from Pro Tax\u2019s Aaron Lorenzo and Colin Wilhelm.  The view from Canada: Canadian Foreign Minister Chrystia Freeland took to Twitter soon after hearing the tax would be dropped: \u201cCanada is pleased to see the border tax proposal dropped by the U.S. We know our people and economies prosper together.\u201d  DONDE ESTA SONNY? Livin\u2019 la vida loca in Mrida, Mexico. Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue made his first trip south of the border for meetings on Thursday that will continue today with his Mexican counterpart, Agriculture Secretary Jos Calzada Rovirosa. On Thursday, Perdue toured a pork plant and dressed in matching shirts with Rovirosa.  More broadly, the two officials are discussing trade issues, as well as hosting panel discussions with U.S. and Mexican farmers and ranchers. The goal is build personal relationships in Mexico so the two countries can collaborate on agricultural trade issues, the USDA said. The U.S. agriculture industry has been trying to assure its customers in Mexico that they are valuable partners and that preserving NAFTA is a top priority following Trump\u2019s harsh rhetoric -- delivering such a message is likely the aim of Perdue\u2019s visit. The U.S. grain industry has already lost sales since the beginning of this year as Mexico pursues other buyers, particularly in South America, amid political uncertainty over NAFTA 2.0. Perdue and Rovirosa will hold a press conference today at 10:40 a.m., so stay tuned for more.  BEEF INDUSTRY: DON\u2019T WRECK KORUS, PLEASE: Trump may not think much of the U.S.-Korea Free Trade Agreement, but folks in the beef industry are pretty big fans. They\u2019re also worried sales to their second-biggest export market could be collateral damage as the Trump administration pushes for changes to the pact in its quest to return manufacturing jobs to the United States.  "Under KORUS, the U.S. beef industry has seen an 82 percent increase in annual sales to South Korea, from $582 million in 2012 to $1.06 billion in 2016," top officials at the National Cattlemen's Beef Association, North American Meat Institute and U.S. Meat Export Federation said in a letter to U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer and Perdue.  "Simply put, KORUS created the ideal environment for the U.S. beef industry to thrive in South Korea," the groups said. "We would not support any changes in the terms of the KORUS that would jeopardize either our market share or the significant investment that has been made in rebuilding Korean consumer confidence in the safety, quality and consistency of U.S. beef." To read Doug Palmer\u2019s story, click here.   LAWMAKERS WANT TO MAKE AGOA EVEN BETTER: House Foreign Affairs Chairman Ed Royce (R-Calif.) and ranking member Eliot Engel (D-N.Y.), along with Reps. Chris Smith (R-N.J.) and Karen Bass (D-Calif.), introduced legislation on Thursday that would modernize the African Growth and Opportunity Act and the Millennium Challenge Act.  The bill would require a new website to collect and share information on AGOA, including information on AGOA benefits in eligible countries, available technical assistance and the outcome from meetings of the U.S.-Sub-Saharan Africa Trade and Economic Cooperation Forum. The bill would also call on the president to develop and implement policies to encourage trade cooperation among eligible sub-Saharan African countries. Read more here.  FOX ON THE RUN (IN MEXICO): United Kingdom Secretary for International Trade Liam Fox isn\u2019t just talking up a bilateral with the U.S. On Thursday, he gave a speech in Mexico City on the U.K.\u2019s desire for a free-trade agreement with Mexico after it completes its exit from the EU.   Toward that goal, Fox said he and Mexican Economy Minister Ildefonso Guajardo Villarreal launched \u201can informal trade dialogue\u201d to discuss how the U.K. can maintain the preferential arrangements it currently has with Mexico as an EU member. They also reaffirmed their support for quickly finishing talks to expand and modernize an existing EU-Mexico free-trade agreement, he said.   \u201cGoing forward, our priority must be to ensure stability, continuity and transitional agreements that minimize disruption for businesses,\u201d Fox told the group. \u201cIn the same way, the U.K. wants the closest possible relationship with our European neighbours, with no interruption of our trading relationship. This will provide the most stable platform for those companies from other countries, such as Mexico, who use Britain as an access point to Europe.\u201d   WTO MEMBERS AGREE TO NEW TRADE POLICY REVIEW SCHEDULE: World Trade Organization members agreed to adjust the frequency in which countries undergo trade policy reviews \u201cto ensure the effectiveness of TPRs amid the rising number of WTO members.\u201d  The changes to the trade policy review mechanism, which regularly analyzes trade policies and practices of each WTO member, will space out the reviews that take place every two, four or six years, depending on economy size, to frequencies of three, five and seven years. The new review schedule will be phased in starting in 2019.  Consensus was reached fairly quickly by WTO standards, given that the proposed changes were first introduced last June. The 2018 schedule for TPRs, which is not subject to the new rules, was also released this month, with 23 members getting reviews, including the U.S. for the 14th time.  BELL TOLLS FOR SCOTT GARRETT: Former Rep. Scott Garrett has a growing litany of questions he must answer \u2014 and answer \u201csatisfactorily\u201d \u2014 before lawmakers will feel comfortable approving his nomination to lead the Export-Import Bank. In a letter to Senate Banking Committee Chairman Mike Crapo (R-Idaho), whose panel will lead the confirmation process, four House Democrats urged their colleagues on the other side of the Capitol to push Garrett to repudiate his previous anti-Ex-Im statements and to commit to support the bank\u2019s full reauthorization before they vote to approve his nomination.  The four lawmakers \u2014 House Democratic Whip Steny Hoyer and Reps. Maxine Waters, Gwen Moore and Denny Heck \u2014 also asked senators to ask Garrett whether he would commit to immediately scheduling a board meeting to approve transactions waiting in the backlog. A fourth request involved asked Garrett to \u201ccommit to aggressively using the bank\u2019s tools on a going-forward basis to counter the expansion of Chinese and other foreign export credit agency financing as a means of supporting U.S. production,\u201d as well as to make sure he would not use his position to block consideration of transactions.  \u201cIf confirmed as chairman of the board, Mr. Garrett would have wide latitude to control the board\u2019s agenda and substitute his personal views for the statutory mission of the bank, destroying it from within after failing in his efforts to persuade his colleagues to legislate its demise,\u201d the four lawmakers wrote. \u201cIf he were to do so, those supporting his confirmation would be complicit in off-shoring thousands upon thousands of American jobs.\u201d Read the full letter here.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 Mayors from border towns in the U.S. and Mexico were singularly focused on NAFTA renegotiations during a meeting this week, the Associated Press reports.  \u2014 New Department of Transportation data found that trucks carry 63.4 percent of U.S.-NAFTA freight, Trucker News Services reports.  \u2014 Canada faces the uphill battle of improving labor mobility in a NAFTA redo, The Canadian Press reports.  THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  Adam Behsudi is a trade reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Prior to joining POLITICO, he covered international trade policy for Inside U.S. Trade, where he tracked down the latest news on the Trans-Pacific Partnership from exotic locales such as Auckland, New Zealand; Kota Kinabalu, Malaysia; and Leesburg, Va.  Before writing about anti-dumping, export controls and other trade subjects, Behsudi covered city hall for the Frederick News-Post. He got his start in journalism chasing crooked sheriffs and other crime-related news in the mountains of western North Carolina for the Asheville Citizen-Times.  Behsudi earned his bachelor\u2019s degree in 2005 from the University of Missouri. With the hope that journalism could return as a growth industry within his lifetime, he earned a master\u2019s degree in interactive journalism from American University in 2010.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
