aV \u000a            By ADAM BEHSUDI  07/27/2017 10:01 AM EDT  With help from Megan Cassella, Doug Palmer, Catherine Boudreau and Zachary Warmbrodt  HOUSE REPUBLICAN FRESHMEN SHOW THEIR NAFTA LOVE: President Donald Trump got elected last year railing against NAFTA and other trade agreements. But a new letter from the 32 Republicans who were elected to the House for the first time last year shows that is a lonely position within the party.   Story Continued Below  "We recognize that a 23-year-old agreement needs updating, and commend your desire to make improvements and ensure strict enforcement," the freshman lawmakers said in a letter to U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer. "We are also keenly aware of the potential for damage to U.S. farmers, businesses, manufacturers, service providers and workers if long-standing agreements are suddenly vacated. Canada and Mexico are our largest export markets, and our $3.5 billion in daily trade with these two countries supports 14 million American jobs."  The letter came as the U.S., Canada and Mexico are preparing to hold the first round of talks to renegotiate NAFTA beginning Aug. 16. in D.C. Trump has repeatedly threatened to pull out of NAFTA if the other two countries don't agree to new U.S. terms.   Twenty-seven of the 32 signatories are from parts of the country that Trump won in last year\u2019s election, including Rust Belt states like Pennsylvania and Michigan where his anti-NAFTA message seemed to resonate the most. The letter was led by Reps. Roger Marshall of Kansas and Mike Gallagher of Wisconsin, whose states Trump also won.   The lawmakers told Lighthizer they were concerned that U.S. industry and farmers are already being hurt as other countries negotiate trade agreements without the United States. \u201cThis creates a sense of urgency that makes us glad our predecessors provided you with Trade Promotion Authority, empowering you to launch, negotiate and conclude trade agreements," they said.   IT\u2019S THURSDAY, JULY 27! Welcome to Morning Trade. Be sure to stay connected: abehsudi@politico.com or @abehsudi.  LAWMAKERS, AG INDUSTRY AGREE: WE NEED SWIFT ACTION ON NAFTA: While we\u2019re on NAFTA, most members of the House Agriculture Committee on Wednesday zeroed in on three issues related to the upcoming renegotiation of the trade deal: expanding U.S. dairy exports to Canada and Mexico; balancing America\u2019s $5.3 billion produce trade deficit with Mexico; and ensuring the updated pact is finalized as soon as possible, because the current political uncertainty has already hurt U.S. grain exports south of the border. Chairman Mike Conaway and Reps. Frank Lucas and Tom O\u2019Halleran, among others, emphasized the importance of expeditiously wrapping up the trilateral talks after officials from the U.S. grain industries testified that there\u2019s already been a 4 percent decline in sales of corn and a 13 percent decline in sales of soybean meal to Mexico this year when compared with 2016.   Dairy dilemmas: Former Agriculture Secretary Tom Vilsack, now president and CEO of the U.S. Dairy Export Council, fielded a deluge of questions about what he described as tactics used by the Canadian government to keep U.S. dairy exports out on a whim -- most recently with the establishment of a pricing program for ultrafiltered milk (a key ingredient in cheese). Any renegotiation of NAFTA needs to ensure more predictability and transparency, as well as reduce high tariffs on U.S. dairy exports, he said.   But Canada is standing firmly in defense of both the Class 7 program for ultrafiltered milk and their supply management program, which sets production quotas and restricts imports to stabilize farmers\u2019 incomes, arguing that these policies are not the cause of the United States\u2019 milk oversupply problem. Rep. Collin Peterson (D-Minn.), the ranking member of the Agriculture Committee, said during the hearing that the Canadians \u201care going to defend this no matter what,\u201d highlighting a potential rift in the coming negotiations.   U.S. produce growers want level playing field with Mexico: Lawmakers in key agriculture states like Reps. Al Lawson (D-Fla.), Darren Soto (D-Fla.) and Austin Scott (R-Ga.) are also searching for ways to help the U.S. fruit and vegetable sector deal with what one industry official said is unfair trade practices by Mexico. Reginald Brown, executive vice president of the Florida Tomato Growers Exchange, said U.S. produce growers will face economic ruin if the renegotiation of NAFTA doesn\u2019t secure a way for regional industries to bring anti-dumping and countervailing cases against Mexico. The country prices fruits and vegetables below the cost of production, employs a web of subsidy schemes to boost production, and pays farm workers about 10 percent of what U.S. agricultural workers earn, Brown added.  BRITISH COLUMBIA PREMIER PUSHES PROVINCIAL LUMBER INTERESTS WITH ROSS: New British Columbia Premier John Horgan is the latest top Canadian provincial official to meet with Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross on the issue of softwood lumber trade, but U.S. industry sources say the meeting doesn\u2019t signal that any meaningful progress has been made on reaching a new softwood lumber agreement.  \u201cWe are not aware of any uptick in the negotiations process,\u201d an industry source told Morning Trade. \u201cCanada appears still unable to have a cohesive position that is consistent with their prior commitment to an \u2018at or below market share\u2019 or quota agreement construct.\u201d  British Columbia is the largest exporter of softwood lumber to the United States. Lumber producers in the province have been opposed to a new deal that would impose a straight quota. Instead, they want to see a deal similar to the one that expired in 2015, which restricted exports through a mix of quotas and export taxes. Producers in the eastern provinces, which produce and export less lumber, are less opposed to a straight quota.  Prior to his trip to Washington this week, Horgan, a New Democrat Party member who succeeded embattled former Liberal premier Christy Clark after she failed to form a majority government in elections earlier this year, said his goal is \u201cto fight for B.C. jobs in the softwood lumber dispute.\u201d  Despite the U.S. industry\u2019s misgivings, Horgan said in an editorial earlier this week that \u201ca deal is in the making \u2013 a 10-year agreement to assure Canadian producers a fair portion of U.S. market share, based on export performance since implementation of the last softwood lumber agreement, and adjusted to ongoing market conditions.\u201d  AFL-CIO PROMISES NAFTA OFFENSIVE SIMILAR TO TPP: The AFL-CIO\u2019s Executive Council issued marching orders to members on Wednesday promising to \u201cmobilize with the same level of intensity as our campaign to defeat the TPP.\u201d  The labor group body laid out a comprehensive campaign to push its demands in the NAFTA talks, which will include lobbying of elected officials; reports on the impact of NAFTA on jobs, wages and negotiating power; and joint actions with labor allies in Canada and Mexico.  \u201cWe will work to advance a set of positive and forward-looking trade rules through a comprehensive public campaign on the ground, online and over the air,\u201d the council said in its statement.  STEELWORKERS DEVASTATED BY 232 DELAY: The United Steelworkers union says Trump\u2019s decision to delay action on steel imports could have \u201cdevastating\u201d consequences as foreign trading partners rush to export steel to the U.S. under a long-delayed threat of tariffs.  \u201cSince the president announced an investigation in April, attacks on the U.S. steel sector have skyrocketed, with imports up 18 percent,\u201d USW President Leo Gerard said in a statement Wednesday. \u201cTrading partners have targeted the U.S. market for fear that the United States will finally stand up for its producers and workers and protect our national security.\u201d  Trump pushed for a report into the national security threat of steel imports and a similar one on aluminum imports to be concluded by the end of June. However, the reports have become subject to intense internal administration debate on the implications a broad tariff might have on U.S. trade relations and downstream industries. The European Union has already threatened swift retaliation if it is hit with tariffs.  Gerard acknowledged that trading relationships in the steel sector are \u201ccomplex.\u201d   \u201cBut enough time, attention and investigation have passed to know what needs to be done,\u201d he said in the statement. \u201cSteel, the foundation of our national security, is crumbling under the onslaught of foreign imports. Much of that is illegally traded.\u201d  SENATORS PRESS CHINA ON CHICKEN ACCESS: More than three dozen senators signed a letter pressing Agriculture Secretary Sonny Perdue to step up USDA\u2019s efforts to get China to end its ban on American poultry. U.S. poultry has been banned in China since 2015 over concerns of a highly pathogenic avian influenza that was detected in a wild duck.  "We encourage you to remain focused on the next steps to officially reopen the Chinese market as soon as possible," they write. "Expanding market access in growing regions in the Asia Pacific, especially China, is essential for our poultry producers and will result in the creation of new jobs and higher wages in rural communities."  The letter, which was led by Sens. Mark Warner (D-Va.) and Thad Cochran (R-Miss.), notes that China has begun its animal health audit of the U.S. poultry industry \u2014 one of the crucial steps necessary for China to resume acceptance of U.S. poultry imports.  Going forward, the lawmakers urge USDA to "remain diligent in seeking final Chinese approval for U.S. poultry\u2019s first successful shipment as quickly as possible" \u2014 preferably before Chinese New Year celebrations, as "our farmers would very much like to be able to offer their products during that time."  TRUMP ADMINISTRATION HAILS A JOBS WIN: The self-proclaimed \u201cgreatest jobs president that God ever created\u201d claimed a win on Wednesday in his bid to revive the U.S. industrial sector, announcing a $10 billion investment from Taiwanese company Foxconn to open a new plant in Wisconsin and create between 3,000 and 13,000 jobs.  A senior White House official told reporters that the electronics manufacturer, whose Chinese factories supply parts for Apple\u2019s iPhones, chose to invest in Wisconsin because of \u201cconfidence\u201d in the Trump administration\u2019s business policies, including efforts to roll back regulations and overhaul the tax code.  And while it\u2019s a politically beneficial move for Trump, it might not come cheap: The deal to lure the company could include a $1 billion to $3 billion package of local, state and federal incentives including tax breaks and infrastructure improvements, the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel reported this week. Read more from Pro Technology\u2019s Steven Overly here.  LIGHTHIZER PLEDGES TO \u2018TAKE ON\u2019 CHINA\u2019S INDUSTRIAL POLICY: The Trump administration is focused on confronting Beijing over its industrial policy \u201cone way or another,\u201d including by holding the country accountable to the rules of the World Trade Organization, Lighthizer said in a rare media interview this week.  \u201cThere\u2019s no question that China has an industrial policy that is designed to create jobs and wealth in China, and in many cases there are things that are outside of the norm of the WTO,\u201d Lighthizer told conservative talk-show host Kevin McCullough. He acknowledged that some actions were in violation of the WTO, whereas others simply weren\u2019t covered by the rules of the global trading body.   \u201cThere are examples of them subsidizing and dumping and doing other things that we would find to be noneconomic,\u201d he added. \u201cOur objective is not to let that go on in an unfair way, and that\u2019s really where the president is focused.\u201d  \u2014 No near-term demise for NAFTA: Asked during the same interview what the president\u2019s current thinking is on NAFTA and whether he still believes the deal should be \u201cscrapped,\u201d Lighthizer tamped down the idea. \u201cScrapped is too strong,\u201d he said. \u201cBut the president wants very, very substantial changes.\u201d Listen to the full interview here.  A \u2018NO\u2019 FOR GARRETT: Sen. Catherine Cortez Masto plans to vote against former Rep. Scott Garrett\u2019s nomination to lead the Export-Import Bank because of his views on LGBT issues and his record of trying to shut down the bank, a spokesman for the Nevada Democrat told POLITICO on Wednesday. That comes just hours after the National Association of Manufacturers and the Nevada Manufacturers Association ran an ad designed to persuade Cortez Masto and her Republican Senate colleague, Dean Heller, to oppose Garrett\u2019s confirmation.   A spokeswoman for Heller did not respond to a request for comment. Cortez Masto and Heller sit on the Senate Banking Committee, which is vetting Garrett's nomination.  Sen. Bob Corker, another committee member, is keeping more of an open mind. \u201cWho knows,\u201d the Tennessee Republican told POLITICO, "someone like that who\u2019s opposed it but now knows they\u2019re going to lead it could end up being an inspired choice.\u201d Corker said he wanted to sit down and talk with Garrett, whom he described as a \u201cvery knowledgeable guy."  TREASURY ANNOUNCES MORE VENEZUELA SANCTIONS: The Treasury Department on Wednesday announced a new round of sanctions on Venezuelan officials, the latest in a string of Trump administration restrictions aimed at the beleaguered Latin American country before a pivotal election on Sunday.  Sanctions were levied on nine current and former government individuals and four people connected to the state oil company PDVSA. As a result of these actions, all assets of these individuals that are subject to U.S. jurisdiction are frozen, and Americans are prohibited from dealing with them.   The sanctions focus on current and former officials associated with the elections or the undermining of democracy, the Treasury said.  "Anyone elected to the National Constituent Assembly should know that their role in undermining democratic processes and institutions in Venezuela could expose them to potential U.S. sanctions," Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin said in a statement. Read more here from Pro Financial Services\u2019 Patrick Temple-West.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 Mexico\u2019s Congress backed a non-binding resolution defending NAFTA\u2019s Chapter 19 dispute settlement mechanism, Reuters reports.  \u2014 Thousands of Mexican farmers and farm workers marched in Mexico City demanding that agriculture be exempted from NAFTA talks, teleSUR reports.  \u2014 Iowa Gov. Kim Reynolds and a contingent of ag industry representatives talk about various trade issues on their trip to China, Radio Iowa reports.  \u2014 The EU warns that it would act swiftly to counter proposed new U.S. sanctions on Russia, Reuters reports.  THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  Adam Behsudi is a trade reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Prior to joining POLITICO, he covered international trade policy for Inside U.S. Trade, where he tracked down the latest news on the Trans-Pacific Partnership from exotic locales such as Auckland, New Zealand; Kota Kinabalu, Malaysia; and Leesburg, Va.  Before writing about anti-dumping, export controls and other trade subjects, Behsudi covered city hall for the Frederick News-Post. He got his start in journalism chasing crooked sheriffs and other crime-related news in the mountains of western North Carolina for the Asheville Citizen-Times.  Behsudi earned his bachelor\u2019s degree in 2005 from the University of Missouri. With the hope that journalism could return as a growth industry within his lifetime, he earned a master\u2019s degree in interactive journalism from American University in 2010.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
