aV \u000a            By MEGAN CASSELLA  07/26/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Doug Palmer and Zachary Warmbrodt  EU PLACES A TARGET ON CHINESE INVESTMENT: Washington is no longer the only international capital aiming to impose strict new regulations on foreign direct investment \u2014 particularly when it comes from Beijing. The European Commission, aiming to strengthen its hand in limiting Chinese takeovers of some of the bloc\u2019s most strategic and valuable companies, is weighing plans to implement a radical new rulebook governing how the European Union treats FDI, five senior EU diplomats told our POLITICO Europe colleagues.   Story Continued Below  The new regulations, which are likely to be unveiled during a \u201cstate of the European Union\u201d speech in September, could mandate that all EU member countries introduce strict investment screening. It would also create a common legal base for states to stop certain investments on the basis of principles of \u201cnational security\u201d and \u201cpublic order\u201d laid down in the WTO\u2019s General Agreement on Trade in Services, though trade diplomats in Brussels cautioned there is still heated debate over the legal scope of the plan.  The move to screen and potentially limit foreign dollars from flowing into EU countries comes as Chinese buyouts of critical European infrastructure and high-tech businesses have emerged as one of the bloc\u2019s most contentious political issues, particularly in France and Germany.  At the same time, on this side of the Atlantic, lawmakers led by Sen. John Cornyn, the No. 2 Republican in the Senate, are exploring methods to revamp the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States to make it harder to sell companies that have advanced technology to China. Read the full story from POLITICO Europe here.  IT\u2019S WEDNESDAY, JULY 26! Welcome to Morning Trade, where your host is wondering if there might be something to the theory that Anthony Scaramucci got the job of White House communications director because of how well he has learned to mimic President Donald Trump\u2019s own hand motions. Any trade tips or news floating around out there? Let me know: mcassella@politico.com or @mmcassella.  TRUMP HITS THE BRAKES ON 232 REVIEWS: The Trump administration is unlikely to make any decisions regarding whether to limit imports of steel and aluminum for national security reasons any time soon, after the president himself told The Wall Street Journal on Tuesday that \u201cwe don\u2019t want to do it at this moment.\u201d  The administration had already missed its initial deadline of wrapping up the pair of Section 232 reports by the end of June, and Trump indicated Tuesday that was in part because of various regulations regarding any decisions. \u201cYou can\u2019t just walk in and say I\u2019m going to do this,\u201d he told the Journal. \u201cYou have to do statutory studies \u2026 It doesn\u2019t go that quickly.\u201d  Back of the queue: Trump was confident that his administration would eventually be \u201caddressing the steel dumping,\u201d which he called \u201ca very unfair situation.\u201d He did not, however, indicate the action would be imminent: He started by saying it would come \u201cvery\u201d soon, but then backed off and said it would be \u201cfairly soon.\u201d  It will also likely come after other high-profile items on his policy agenda are completed. \u201cWe\u2019re waiting \u2018til we get everything finished up between healthcare and taxes and maybe even infrastructure,\u201d he said. Read more here.   CANDIDATE TRUMP RETURNS TO THE STUMP IN YOUNGSTOWN: The White House had branded Trump\u2019s return to Ohio on Tuesday night as a campaign event, and in many ways, it felt like one, with the president returning time and again throughout his speech to trade. Over the course of nearly an hour, he pledged several times to bring back manufacturing jobs, promising that \u201cthey\u2019re all coming back.\u201d  \u201cDon\u2019t move,\u201d he told the crowd of about 7,000. \u201cDon\u2019t sell your house.\u201d  In a roughly 15-minute speech just before the rally to American veterans, Trump mentioned that he heard \u201cwe\u2019re doing better in the polls\u201d because \u201cthey see what we\u2019re doing with jobs.\u201d  He promised that audience that \u201cwe\u2019re doing trade deals\u201d and, with an apparent reference to the various regulations wrapped up in Trade Promotion Authority legislation, he defended the fact that nothing concrete has happened yet on trade. \u201cYou know, we have statutory length problems where you have to wait statutorily before you do them,\u201d he said. \u201cBut everybody has been put on notice.\u201d Read more from the rally here.  FOX: HARD TO SAY HOW LONG U.S. FTA TALKS WOULD TAKE: Free-trade talks between the United States and the United Kingdom haven\u2019t even officially started, and already folks are asking how long it will take to reach a deal. That\u2019s hard to answer, but a lot will depend on how much progress is made in preparatory talks over the next two years, U.K. Secretary of International Trade Liam Fox told Bloomberg TV at the Capitol on Tuesday.   The U.K. cannot formally negotiate with the United States until it completes its exit from the EU, which is currently expected in March 2019. So the further the preparatory talks with the United States get, the faster the two sides can become FTA partners, Fox said.   However, the British official indicated he expects the U.K. will negotiate its new trading arrangement with the EU at the same time it is negotiating with the United States on a free-trade agreement. \u201cWe can\u2019t be making concessions or agreements on one of those agreements, but not on the other one. They need to proceed at around about the same pace,\u201d Fox said.   He sidestepped a question about whether the U.K. would have to lower its regulatory standards in areas like agricultural food safety to strike a deal with the United States. \u201cUltimately, we\u2019re setting U.K. conditions. We\u2019re setting U.K. standards. We\u2019re neither going to be members of the European Union, nor are we going to be totally bound to the United States,\u201d Fox said.   To read Doug Palmer\u2019s story on Fox\u2019s comments at a Capitol Hill reception Tuesday, click here.   MORE LAWMAKERS SQUEEZE SCOTT GARRETT: Three Democratic members of Congress are joining the push for Trump to withdraw his nomination of former Rep. Scott Garrett to lead the Export-Import Bank, arguing that putting a critic of the bank atop the agency \u201cmakes no sense.\u201d  \u201cGiven your expressed intention of making the U.S. more competitive, the nomination of Mr. Garrett makes no sense,\u201d Reps. Steny Hoyer, the House Democratic whip; Gwen Moore, the ranking member on the Monetary Policy and Trade Subcommittee; and Denny Heck wrote in a letter to Trump on Tuesday.   \u201cIf confirmed as chairman of the board, Mr. Garrett would have wide latitude to control the board\u2019s agenda and substitute his personal views for the statutory mission of the Bank, destroying it from within after failing in his efforts to persuade his colleagues to legislate its demise,\u201d they added.  On the other side of the Capitol, Garrett is beginning to make the rounds among Senate Banking Committee members who ultimately will have the responsibility of vetting their former colleague\u2019s nomination. Chairman Mike Crapo (R-Idaho) and Sen. Richard Shelby (R-Ala.) both said Tuesday they had plans to meet with Garrett in the coming weeks, while Sen. Heidi Heitkamp (D-N.D.) said she was working with Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer to set up a time for him to speak with Democrats.  POLITICO reported last week that Trump is reconsidering his decision to nominate Garrett, who has become a political headache for the White House amid opposition against his appointment from manufacturers and major corporations. Rep. Chris Collins (R-N.Y.), a close Trump ally and a supporter of the bank, told Morning Trade this week that Garrett \u201cis facing a pretty bumpy road.\u201d  Collins, who worked alongside Rep. Mike Kelly (R-Pa.) to convince Trump to appoint nominees to revive the bank and offered him a list of potential names to fill the empty slots, added that he currently has \u201ca couple\u201d of names \u201cthat could be a good fallback\u201d if Garrett\u2019s nomination falls through.  \u2014 Manufacturers take the fight to print: The National Association of Manufacturers is also working to hinder Garrett\u2019s path to the agency, running full-page newspaper ads today in South Carolina and Nevada pressuring the state\u2019s two senators to oppose his nomination. The ads, slated to run in the Charleston Post and Courier and the Las Vegas Review-Journal, warn that Garrett would be "a terrible trade deal for the American manufacturing worker."  "He sent American jobs and wealth overseas," read the ads, which feature a photo of Garrett at a podium adorned with an "#EndExIm" sign. "He spread misinformation without regard to the impact it would have on the jobs of thousands of Americans."  The ads urge readers to reach out to Sens. Tim Scott (R-S.C.), Dean Heller (R-Nev.) and Catherine Cortez Masto (D-Nev.), who sit on the Senate Banking Committee tasked with vetting the nominees.  \u2014 A Republican divide: Sen. Tim Scott (R-S.C.) threatened on Tuesday to oppose Garrett\u2019s confirmation \u201cabsent a clear, public statement that ensures he will not dismantle the bank,\u201d he said in a statement. But Shelby, meanwhile \u2014 who as chairman of the Banking Committee hindered the bank by refusing to move on any of then-President Barack Obama\u2019s nominees \u2014 has emerged as one of Garrett\u2019s staunchest supporters.  \u201cIf they were to drop him and send somebody else up, they\u2019ll have a fight on their hands,\u201d Shelby said in an interview Tuesday.  SENATORS PUSH FOR \u2018REAL RELIEF\u2019 IN LUMBER DISPUTE: Seven members of the Senate Finance Committee are pushing the administration to bring its ongoing softwood lumber dispute with Canada to a close, calling for a resolution that would provide \u201creal relief\u201d for U.S. industry and support American jobs, particularly those in the rural sector.  In a letter sent to Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross and U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer on Tuesday, the bipartisan group of lawmakers said that "the American economy depends on a vibrant domestic lumber industry" and emphasized the need for close consultations with Congress throughout any negotiations.  Led by Sens. Ron Wyden (D-Ore.) and Crapo, the lawmakers called for an enforceable clean quota agreement that maintains Canadian exports at or below an agreed market share, adding: \u201cAny long-term agreement must stop the harmful effects of subsidized and unfairly traded Canadian lumber on fair competition with the U.S. producers.\u201d  The two countries remain closely engaged on the issue, but senior-level officials warned late last month that it was unlikely they will reach a deal to manage cross-border trade ahead of the start of NAFTA talks on Aug. 16.  Still, officials on both sides have said they would like to resolve the issue before negotiations, and Canadian officials, including Ontario Premier Kathleen Wynne, expressed optimism earlier this month that such a deal might be possible.  \u2014 Fueling the speculation: John Horgan \u2014 the newly sworn-in premier of British Columbia, which is Canada\u2019s largest exporter of lumber into the U.S. \u2014 is traveling to Washington to meet with Ross today and press him on a potential deal, a Commerce spokesman confirmed to Morning Trade.   WTO OFFICIAL: NEED TO \u2018SIGNIFICANTLY ACCELERATE\u2019 AG TALKS BEFORE DECEMBER MEETING: World Trade Organization member countries must ramp up their current talks surrounding agricultural issues and narrow the number of topics they would like to address if the global trading body wants to see any concrete outcomes settled by its ministerial conference in December, one ambassador is warning.  Stephen Ndung'u Karau, Kenya\u2019s ambassador to the WTO and the chairman of the committee on agriculture in special session, said in a report summarizing the current status of talks that member countries need to prioritize discussions and begin to move into a \u201creal intensive negotiation mode\u201d ahead of the year-end event in Buenos Aires, Argentina. After holding a series of meetings with member countries on specific proposals and areas for negotiation, the most likely areas for achievable outcomes this year are public stockholding for food security purposes, domestic support, export restrictions, and cotton, he said.  \u201cI am of the view that we will need to significantly accelerate the rhythm of our discussions after the summer break, if we are committed to progress on substance and achieve convergence on the negotiating issues in time for MC11,\u201d Karau said in the report.   TRADE REMEDY CORNER \u2014 SPANISH OLIVES CASE SETS OFF EU FARM LOBBY: Europe's largest farm lobby is urging the European government to fight back against Washington's plan to impose anti-dumping measures against Spanish olive imports, POLITICO Europe\u2019s Emmet Livingstone reports.   Copa & Cogeca boss Pekka Pesonen said Tuesday that such a move would eliminate thousands of Spanish jobs and that "imposing protectionist measures against our products without justification" is "unacceptable." The remarks come after the Commerce Department decided earlier this month to launch an investigation into whether Spanish olive were being dumped illegally in the United States and whether Spanish olive farmers were receiving subsidies under the EU\u2019s Common Agricultural Policy that gave the Spanish industry an unfair advantage.  A European Commission spokesman confirmed that U.S. authorities had received the request from domestic producers to investigate Spanish olives on June 21. He said the Commission is intervening to defend the rights of the Spanish producers to export to the U.S. in line with World Trade Organization rules.   Brussels has already registered as an interested party in the investigations, the spokesman added.  MEMORY LANE: ITC RELEASES REVIEW OF 2016 TRADE YEAR: The International Trade Commission released on Tuesday its annual report on the year in trade, which dives deeply into everything from import and export data and analysis of all of the U.S.\u2019s existing free-trade agreements to policy developments with countries the U.S. does not currently have a deal with, like Taiwan and Cuba. The full report, which totals nearly 300 pages, is available here.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau said that \u201ca fair dispute resolution system is essential\u201d for NAFTA 2.0, setting up a possible conflict with the U.S. over Chapter 19, Reuters reports.  \u2014 Some European leaders are warning that sweeping sanctions against Russia that the House passed overwhelmingly on Tuesday could backfire, hindering transatlantic efforts to curb Moscow\u2019s aggression against Ukraine, the Washington Post reports.   \u2014 A pending decision in the trade case brought by U.S. solar manufacturer Suniva has led U.S. solar companies to purchase large amounts of cheap imported solar panels out of worry the prices could soon skyrocket, Reuters reports.  \u2014 Quartz writes an explainer piece on the United States\u2019 chlorinated chicken and whether the U.K. will accept imports of it under a new trade deal.   THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  \u000a                                            By Joshua Zeitz  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
