aV \u000a            By MEGAN CASSELLA  07/25/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Doug Palmer and Adam Behsudi  TRUMP RETURNS TO THE RUST BELT: President Donald Trump is heading back to the heartland that elected him to give a speech this evening in Youngstown, Ohio, a city he visited twice as a candidate. The White House branded the sold-out 7 p.m. rally as a campaign event, and it remains unclear what, if any, policy announcements the president might make when he returns to the stump.  Story Continued Below  But his freewheeling, improvisational style leaves open the possibility he\u2019ll touch on any number of trade-related topics that would likely resonate in Ohio, from ongoing reviews of steel and aluminum imports to his efforts to push \u201cBuy American, Hire American\u201d policies. Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross is expected to brief the House Ways and Means Committee on the Section 232 reviews on Thursday, suggesting that Trump is unlikely to announce any final decisions at the event this evening.  Democratic Ohio Sen. Sherrod Brown on Monday called for Trump to address the administration\u2019s Buy America initiative during the event, writing on Twitter that \u201csteelworkers in Youngstown would love to hear your plan to enforce Buy America rules.\u201d  \u201cI want to help,\u201d Brown added in the three-tweet thread. \u201cMy Buy America bill w/ @senrobportman requires American infrastructure tax $ to be spent on American iron & steel. That means jobs in Ytown.\u201d The senator attached a photo of a letter he sent to Trump shortly after the election \u2014 which the president signed and sent back \u2014 and added: \u201cYou said you'd never let our workers down\u2014w/ my bill, we can work together to support what they make in the USA.\u201d  Stay tuned for more from POLITICO\u2019s Annie Karni, who is on the ground in Youngstown, later today.  IT\u2019S TUESDAY, JULY 25! Welcome to Morning Trade, where your host, who is moving across town this weekend, just learned how difficult it is to book a moving truck on the busiest moving day of the year for the District. Any trade tips or news out there to keep me busy in between packing boxes? Let me know: mcassella@politico.com or @mmcassella.  FOX BLASTS BRITISH MEDIA\u2019S CHICKEN \u2018OBSESSION\u2019: U.K. International Trade Secretary Liam Fox accused the British media of trivializing preparations for free-trade talks with the United States by narrowly focusing on whether London would open its market to U.S. poultry that has been treated with a chlorine solution to kill pathogens.   He made the comment at the American Enterprise Institute after being asked by a British reporter if he was prepared to eat \u201cchlorine-washed chicken\u201d and thereby signal his acceptance of a U.S. industry practice banned in the EU. That\u2019s a sensitive issue on both sides of the Atlantic. While many European consumers are repelled by the idea of eating \u201cchlorinated chicken,\u201d U.S. industry complains the EU ban is not based on sound science.  \u201cIn a debate which should be about how we make our contribution to global liberalization and increase the prosperity of both the U.K., the U.S. and our trading partners \u2026 the British media are obsessed with fully washed chickens,\u201d Fox said. He added the issue would only be addressed at the \u201cvery end stage\u201d of free-trade talks with the United States, which can not formally begin until the U.K. completes it exit from the EU in two years.   Back home in London, a food fight is looming over the idea that a U.S.-U.K. trade deal could align the U.K. more closely with U.S. food safety standards. To read more about that, click on Charlie Cooper and Adam Behsudi\u2019s story.  FOX URGES PUSH TO FINISH SERVICES TRADE TALKS: Fox also called for countries to finish talks on the Trade in Services Agreement \u201cas soon as practicable,\u201d which he said would be good for both the United States and the U.K. since the strength of their economies depends so much on the services sector.   Those negotiations have been on ice since November, when Trump was elected. However, U.S. Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer recently made positive noises about starting them up again. "That certainly is an important one, and I don't expect it to fall by the wayside," Lighthizer told Congress in June. "We're doing an evaluation right now across the aboard, and when that is done we'll move forward where appropriate."  Asked Monday for an update, a U.S. trade official added: \u201cUSTR is still evaluating the status of these negotiations. However, given that this was only the first session of the Working Group, I think it's a bit premature to speculate. I imagine that this, among a myriad of other issues, will continue to be [an item for] discussion in future sessions of the Working Group.\u201d  The United States, the EU and 21 other WTO members have already held 21 rounds of talks on the TiSA pact. Fox said concluding those talks would be an important step toward modernizing the international trade architecture, while shifting away from a 20th-century preoccupation with \u201cgeographical\u201d trade arrangements. To read Doug Palmer\u2019s story on Fox\u2019s speech at AEI, click here.   U.S., U.K. TAKE FIRST STEPS TOWARD \u2018AMBITIOUS FREE TRADE DEAL\u2019: The main event of Fox\u2019s visit was the official start of preliminary bilateral trade talks under the newly established U.S.-U.K. Trade and Investment Working Group, which the two nations will use to eventually create an \u201cambitious free trade agreement,\u201d the top trade officials from each country said.  \u201cThe immediate priority is to give businesses on both sides of the Atlantic certainty and confidence," Fox said in a statement released after the first meeting. "Early discussions will focus on providing commercial continuity for U.S. and U.K. businesses as the U.K. leaves the EU."  Lighthizer added in the joint release that the working group would be a "key mechanism to deepen our already strong bilateral trade" and will help "lay the groundwork" for a bilateral trade deal once the U.K. completes its exit from the European Union sometime around April 2019. Read more here.  SOUTH KOREA PUSHES BACK AGAINST REOPENING KORUS: South Korea\u2019s newly installed trade minister is pushing back against the Trump administration\u2019s request to convene a meeting in Washington on possible amendments to the Korea-U.S. free trade agreement, writing in a letter to Lighthizer on Monday that the two countries should first examine the bilateral trade deficit \u2014 and its causes \u2014 before looking to make changes to the deal. Multiple South Korean news outlets reported that South Korea's new minister of Trade, Industry and Energy Paik Ungyu also suggested the talks be held in Seoul, not Washington, \u201cat an appropriate date in the near future.\u201d  The letter to Lighthizer comes less than two weeks after USTR wrote to Seoul with a formal request to make changes to the five-year-old agreement, with a focus on reducing the trade deficit.  232 TUG OF WAR: BEVERAGE INDUSTRY PUSHES FOR ALUMINUM CAN EXCLUSIONS: Leading food and beverage companies and industry associations are adding their voice to the chorus of groups chiming in on the administration\u2019s ongoing review into whether to limit imports of aluminum, arguing that tariffs or other restrictions could lead to \u201chundreds of millions in costs\u201d for companies that rely on the material to make aluminum cans.  In a letter sent to Trump on Monday, heavyweights like the Coca-Cola Company and Anheuser-Busch argued that the administration should make an exception for can sheet aluminum because it is not widely available in the United States, so American companies that use it are dependent on imports. \u201cAny import restrictions or tariffs,\u201d they wrote, would \u201cdetrimentally affect over 82,000 American manufacturing jobs in industries that rely on these products.\u201d  Steps to restrict imports of the material would also invite retaliatory actions on U.S. exports, further damaging the industry, they wrote in the letter, which was also signed by industry associations like the American Beverage Association and the Can Manufacturers Institute.  The letter comes on the heels of a separate note sent to the administration last week by the main aluminum industry group that argued against allowing any exceptions, including for aluminum can sheet and related products used for food and beverage containers.  China does not deserve any exclusion because it subsidizes its aluminum industry and blocks foreign producers from lower-priced Chinese inputs, Aluminum Association President Heidi Brock said in a letter to Ross. Granting one exception would open the door for other products to get through because of the potential for misclassification, she wrote.  OHIO SENATORS CELEBRATE ALUMINUM EXTRUDERS\u2019 WIN: In other aluminum news, Brown and fellow Ohio Sen. Rob Portman are lauding the Commerce Department\u2019s recent finding that aluminum extruders in the United States are being harmed by unfair trade practices by foreign competitors.  \u201cI applaud Commerce\u2019s decision to fight back against Chinese efforts to avoid our trade laws and protect American jobs,\u201d Portman, a former U.S. trade representative, said in a statement. \u201cOhio aluminum producers can compete and win against anyone if they get a fair shake, and I will continue to work to ensure they are protected against those who refuse to play by the rules.\u201d   \u201cWe\u2019ve got to hold cheaters accountable,\u201d Brown added. This ruling will help crack down on China\u2019s trade abuses and support American workers.\u201d  The bipartisan pair wrote to Ross last month to argue in support of the Aluminum Extruders Fair Trade Committee, pushing for the agency to rule against Chinese producers\u2019 steps to circumvent anti-dumping and countervailing duties.  MINISTERIAL ON THE MIND AT THE WTO: It may be the dog days of summer in Washington, but officials at the World Trade Organization are focused squarely on December, ramping up plans for the global trading body\u2019s ministerial conference in Buenos Aires, Argentina. WTO Director-General Roberto Azevedo is set to brief the organization\u2019s full membership later this week on ongoing preparations ahead of the biennial event, where members are hoping to achieve concrete outcomes on areas including e-commerce, fisheries subsidies and agriculture.  Azevedo and Susana Malcorra, the chairwoman of this year\u2019s conference, held a meeting with the heads of all WTO negotiating group chairs on Monday to discuss their plans.  \u201cMinister Malcorra and I are working closely together to prepare the ground for a successful Ministerial Conference in Buenos Aires which puts the multilateral trading system on a strong footing for the future,\u201d Azevedo said after the meeting. \u201cThe discussion with Negotiating Group Chairs was constructive, but it highlighted again what is very clear to all WTO members \u2014 there are still significant gaps between positions in many key areas. Continued engagement will be essential in the coming months in order to make progress in closing these gaps.\u201d   ENERGY DEPARTMENT LOOKS AT NEW GAS EXPORT REGS: ICYMI, the Energy Department kicked off a rulemaking to determine whether it can or should establish a special application process for the export of \u201csmall\u201d quantities of natural gas to countries the U.S. doesn\u2019t have free-trade agreements with.  According to an updated list of federal rules posted Thursday, the agency opened a new docket aimed at improving \u201capplication procedures related to natural gas exports, reduce the administrative burdens associated with the small-scale natural gas export market, and result in more efficient processing of applications for small-scale natural gas exports.\u201d  Finalizing the rulemaking, which seeks to \u201cclarify\u201d DOE\u2019s interpretation of its public interest responsibilities, would allow the agency to \u201cissue an order upon receipt of any application that seeks to export natural gas to non-FTA countries, provided the application meets the criteria for small-scale exports.\u201d  TRADE REMEDY CORNER \u2014 SOLAR INDUSTRY WINS CASE AGAINST CHINA, TAIWAN: The solar industry is celebrating a pair of appeals this week after the U.S. Court of International Trade decided to uphold the scope of anti-dumping and countervailing duty orders brought against China and Taiwan. The rulings, which were handed down on Friday, upheld the Commerce Department\u2019s decision that the duties should apply to all solar modules assembled in China, including those from cells produced in any other country.  The U.S. company SolarWorld, which participated in both appeals, was \u201cextremely pleased with the court\u2019s decision,\u201d Timothy Brightbill, a partner in Wiley Rein\u2019s International Trade Practice and lead counsel to the company, said in a statement. \u201cThese broad-scope definitions were necessary to address the injury to U.S. solar manufacturers caused by the unfair trade practices of solar producers and exporters from China and Taiwan and, in particular, from Chinese producers\u2019 attempts to change their operations and sourcing patterns in order to evade duties.\u201d  Parties will have 30 days to appeal the decisions.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 Sen. Sherrod Brown, a onetime favorite to be the vice presidential candidate on the Democratic Party\u2019s ticket, gears up for his 2018 bid for reelection with an eye toward the 2020 presidential campaign, The Washington Post reports.  \u2014 Chamber of Commerce CEO Tom Donohue writes in an op-ed that while the organization feels that most of its recommendations for NAFTA \u201chave been largely heeded so far\u201d by the administration, the focus on the trade deficit is a mistake.  -- U.S. and U.K. union leaders voice skepticism about the benefits of a U.S.-U.K. free trade agreement, and complain they haven\u2019t been consulted on preparatory talks, the Huffington Post reports.  \u2014 An increase in factories does not lead to as many jobs as it used to, nor does it bring higher wages, and factory closures do not always lead to a loss of prosperity, Quartz reports in an extensive data analysis project.  THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Jack Shafer  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By Daniel H. Wilson 
