aV \u000a            By ADAM BEHSUDI  07/24/2017 10:00 AM EDT  With help from Megan Cassella and Doug Palmer   24 REASONS TO LOVE U.S.-U.K. TRADE RELATIONS: The Office of the U.S. Trade Representative and British trade officials will begin their Trade and Investment Working Group today, with the hope that it could lead to a bilateral trade agreement after the United Kingdom officially exits the European Union. However, the two days of talks are likely to focus on a raft of near-term measures the two sides could achieve, according to business sources briefed on what to expect.  Story Continued Below  \u201cOur exit from the European Union offers an unprecedented opportunity to reshape our independent trading ambitions and build on the already strong trading relationship with our single largest trading partner \u2014 the U.S.,\u201d U.K. Secretary of State for International Trade Liam Fox said in a statement, ahead of the meeting with USTR Robert Lighthizer and members of the USTR\u2019s European office.   Fox is expected to arrive with a list of as many as 24 \u201cconfidence-building measures\u201d that fall well outside the EU\u2019s purview, business sources said. The British government is keeping the specifics on those items close to the chest, but sources said they didn\u2019t expect them to be controversial. Separately, the two sides are also planning to review existing U.S.-EU regulatory deals on issues like air travel and mutual recognition agreements.  The other items on the agenda will dabble in longer-term prospects, such as an early effort to scope out what an eventual free trade agreement might cover, sources said.  \u201cAlthough it\u2019s too early to say exactly what would be covered in a potential deal, the working group is the means to ensure we get to know each other\u2019s issues and identify areas where we can work together to strengthen trade and investment ties,\u201d Fox said.  A U.S. trade official told Morning Trade the talks will lay the groundwork for \u201ccommercial continuity,\u201d adding that early discussions will also explore ways to strengthen trade ties that are consistent with the U.K. trade obligations as an EU member.  IT\u2019S MONDAY, JULY 24! Welcome to Morning Trade! Please, forgive us for the easy wordplay, but as we look toward the U.K. minister\u2019s visit, we have a certain ditty and video from a few years ago stuck in our heads: \u201cWhat Does the Fox Say?\u201d As that song so beautifully reminded us, the secret of the fox is an ancient mystery. Somewhere deep in the woods, we know he\u2019s hiding. If you know what this Fox has to say \u2014 or have any other news tip \u2014 let me know: abehsudi@politico.com or @abehsudi.   FOX ON THE RUN, D.C. STYLE: Fox\u2019s schedule includes a speech at the American Enterprise Institute at 8:30 this morning; then separate meetings with Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross, House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Kevin Brady and other members of Congress; and finally dinner with U.K. and U.S. business representatives.  He will also host a breakfast with members of Congress on Tuesday to highlight a new report showing the strong ties between the U.K. and each of the 435 U.S. congressional districts. That is the companion to a previous study on trade and investment relationship between each of the 50 U.S. states and the U.K.  South of the border: Fox will then travel to Mexico for talks with Economy Minister Ildefonso Guajardo Villarreal about how the two countries can maintain their trade relationship after the U.K. leaves the EU. He will also meet with U.K. and Mexican companies and explore opportunities for U.K. companies to participate in Mexico City\u2019s new airport project, which is the biggest infrastructure project in Latin America, the British Embassy said.   Deep in the heart of Texas (industry): Fox will complete his visit by traveling to Houston to hold meetings with the chemical, oil and gas sectors. Texas exported $3.8 billion in goods in 2016 to the U.K. with nearly 900 U.K. subsidiaries operating in the state, according to the embassy. More than 53,000 Texas jobs are supported by exports to the U.K., it said.  DOW\u2019S CHINA BIOTECH BLUES: As part of the 100-day plan between the Trump administration and China, the government of President Xi Jinping pledged that its National Biosafety Committee would hold a meeting by the end of May 2017 \u201cto conduct science-based evaluations of all eight pending U.S. biotechnology product applications to assess the safety of the products for their intended use.\u201d  That wording suggested an agreement was reached between the United States and China on the eight biotechnology products in question --even if it did not promise all eight would be approved by the end of the 100 days on July 16. But now it seems that the United States and China may have been talking about two different groups of eight.   Dow AgroSciences said it previously understood that its Enlist variety of soybeans was one of those referenced under the 100-day plan. Therefore, it was surprised when China\u2019s Ministry of Agriculture (MOA) recently told the company that the herbicide-tolerant variety was not actually one of the eight products on the list for potential approval under the plan.  \u201cWe are seeking to clarify MOA\u2019s position related to Enlist soybeans,\u201d Dow said in a press release. \u201cWe will continue to work cooperatively with MOA to ensure this much needed new technology will soon be available to farmers located in the U.S. and throughout the Americas.\u201d  The U.S. grain industry does not want to produce and export biotech varieties that have not been approved in China because of the potential for cargoes to be rejected. However, China does not even begin its approval process for a biotech variety until it has been cleared in another country, such as the United States. That creates an avoidable lag that frustrates the introduction of new genetically modified crops around the world.   China has approved four biotech varieties since the May 11 announcement of the 100-day plan. One of those was Dow\u2019s Enlist corn. China also approved Monsanto's Vistive Gold soybean and its 87427 glyphosate-resistant corn, which is sold under the Roundup Ready brand; as well as Syngenta's 5307 insect-resistant corn, which is sold under the Agrisure Duracade brand.  Morning Trade has asked the Trump administration whether Enlist soybeans was one of the eight varieties it expected China to evaluate under the 100-day plan, but has not heard back yet. MT has also asked the administration to provide a list of the four varieties not yet approved under the 100-day plan.   MCLARTY EXPERT SEES DIFFICULT NAFTA TALKS: The Trump administration\u2019s insistence on reducing bilateral trade deficits with Canada and Mexico in the new NAFTA negotiations could make those talks impossibly difficult, Nelson Cunningham, president of McLarty Associates said Friday during a discussion hosted by the McDonough School of Business at Georgetown University.   \u201cI see three ways you can adjust a bilateral trade deficit: one is tariffs, one is quotas and one is managed trade. If those are put on the table, I don\u2019t see how either of our trading partners are going to continue. I look at the impending NAFTA negotiations and I see some very rough sledding coming up,\u201d Cunningham said.   That\u2019s particularly true for Mexico, since the United States had a $63.2 billion trade deficit with that country in 2016. \u201cYou take $60 billion of the Mexican economy, that is hugely significant,\u201d Cunningham said.   FORMER HILL AIDE: TRADE POLICY CAN\u2019T FIX TRADE DEFICIT: During the same discussion, former Ways and Means Republican aide Stephen Claeys spilled what he called the \u201cdirty secret\u201d about trade policy. (To be honest, it\u2019s a similar to the argument that a number of economists have made since Trump\u2019s election.)   \u201cYou want to get rid trade deficits? It\u2019s not trade policy that gets rid of trade deficits. It\u2019s tax policy, it\u2019s education policy, it\u2019s health care policy, it\u2019s labor policy. Those are the real things that are going to drive whether U.S. workers or U.S. companies are competitive globally,\u201d Claeys said.   Claeys went on to add that the fact the National Retail Federation ran an ad on \u201cSaturday Night Live\u201d against the Republicans\u2019 proposed border adjustment tax -- but failed to run any in favor of the Trans-Pacific Partnership \u2014 \u201cshows they recognize what actually drives their competitiveness and affects them the most.\u201d   CANADA GETS READY TO RUMBLE: Canada\u2019s priorities for NAFTA 2.0 haven\u2019t been formally laid out in a convenient document, as the U.S. had to recently do under domestic fast-track legislation. But we hope to get a better sense of its goals when Canadian Foreign Minister Chrystia Freeland addresses her Parliament\u2019s trade committee on Aug. 14, just two days before the first round of talks start in Washington. In a recent tweet, Freeland said she would be discussing Canada\u2019s NAFTA priorities when she appears before the committee.  It\u2019s no secret what Canada \u201cpines\u201d for during the talks \u2014 and no, we\u2019re not talking softwood lumber. Ottawa has had a long-held interest in cracking open government procurement markets in the U.S. at the federal, state and local levels. In addition, Canadian firms want better mobility for professionals back and forth across the border.   The question of whether Canada should publicly outline its negotiating objectives has been the source of internal debate in Ottawa, said Lawrence Herman, a former Canadian trade official and current adviser to the government on NAFTA issues.  \u201cIt\u2019s strategically important for Canada to set down its negotiating agenda rather than just be reactive to the U.S.,\u201d he said.  PERSONNEL SWAP: ITA\u2019S SINGH TO KPMG: Vinay Vijay Singh, an Obama-era appointee at the Commerce Department\u2019s International Trade Administration, is headed to KPMG to work as a director in the Global Infrastructure practice. As former deputy assistant secretary at the ITA, he oversaw more than 90 export assistance centers while also focusing on trade and investment policy as well as promotion efforts.  TRADE REMEDY CORNER: COMMERCE HITS TAIWAN ON REBAR: The U.S. has come after at least one country over steel this year. The Commerce Department on Friday set final anti-dumping duties, ranging from 3.5 to 32 percent, on imports of steel rebar from Taiwan, which totaled $53 million in 2016.  The decision is a victory for the Rebar Trade Action Coalition, which includes Byer Steel Group, Commercial Metals Company, Gerdau Ameristeel, Nucor Corporation and Steel Dynamics. The coalition filed a petition last year asking for import relief. The U.S. International Trade Commission still has to give final approval for the duties. That vote is scheduled for Sept. 5.  INTERNATIONAL OVERNIGHT  \u2014 Congressional trade leaders send comments to the U.S. International Trade Commission ahead of next month\u2019s final Miscellaneous Tariff Bill report.  \u2014 Mexican Economy Secretary Ildefonso Guajardo said there could be six to nine rounds of NAFTA talks in the event a quick deal can be reached, Reuters reports.  \u2014 Mexico\u2019s solution for rebalancing trade with the U.S. is more cross-border trade, the Wall Street Journal reports.  \u2014 The Wall Street Journal editorial board defends the choice of Scott Garrett to lead the Export-Import Bank.  \u2014 The leaders of auto worker unions in the U.S. and Canada urge a major rethink of NAFTA.   THAT'S ALL FOR MORNING TRADE! See you again soon! In the meantime, drop the team a line: abehsudi@politico.com and @abehsudi; mcassella@politico.com and @mmcassella; dpalmer@politico.com and @tradereporter; jlauinger@politico.com and @jmlauinger; and P.J. Joshi, at pjoshi@politico.com and @pjoshiny. Also follow us @POLITICOPro and @Morning_Trade.  ** A message from the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program: This week celebrates the 30th anniversary of the Japan Exchange & Teaching (JET) Program. One of the largest educational and cultural exchange programs of its kind, the JET Program has sent 32,000 young Americans to live and work in local communities. Founded in 1987 by the Government of Japan, JET builds strong educational and cultural ties between the United States and Japan. Participants are chosen through a competitive selection process and sponsored by JET to work in Japanese schools and government offices.   JET Program participants are not only teachers and public servants during their time in cities, towns and villages throughout Japan \u2013 they become cultural ambassadors and forge deep bonds with local communities. Learn more: jetprogramusa.org. **  Adam Behsudi is a trade reporter for POLITICO Pro.  Prior to joining POLITICO, he covered international trade policy for Inside U.S. Trade, where he tracked down the latest news on the Trans-Pacific Partnership from exotic locales such as Auckland, New Zealand; Kota Kinabalu, Malaysia; and Leesburg, Va.  Before writing about anti-dumping, export controls and other trade subjects, Behsudi covered city hall for the Frederick News-Post. He got his start in journalism chasing crooked sheriffs and other crime-related news in the mountains of western North Carolina for the Asheville Citizen-Times.  Behsudi earned his bachelor\u2019s degree in 2005 from the University of Missouri. With the hope that journalism could return as a growth industry within his lifetime, he earned a master\u2019s degree in interactive journalism from American University in 2010.  \u000a                                            By John A. Farrell  \u000a                                            By Brian Murphy  \u000a                                            By