aV The leaders of America\u2019s cities have serious concerns about race relations, minority communities and policing issues as the nation approaches the one-year anniversary of last year\u2019s unrest in Ferguson, Missouri, a POLITICO Magazine survey finds. And urban public schools\u2014widely identified by experts as the key to improvement of neighborhood conditions, racial equity and social mobility\u2014won\u2019t offer a solution anytime soon, according to large majorities of mayors who also expressed deep dissatisfaction with the state of their city\u2019s public education systems, citing lack of funding, high drop-out rates and racial segregation as their leading causes of concern.    Fully nine out of 10 mayors surveyed expressed concern about the state of race relations and police in their city, according to the survey, with nearly a third describing themselves as \u201cdeeply concerned\u201d about race and policing in their cities. The revelation illustrates the intensity and seriousness with which mayors have taken up the issue, as cities from Baltimore to New York City to Ferguson have dealt with public unrest over the last year.   Story Continued Below   The findings were part of POLITICO Magazine\u2019s second quarterly national Mayors\u2019 Survey, conducted over the course of July as part of the magazine\u2019s award-winning \u201c What Works\u201d series, which heard from 31 mayors spanning the country from Philadelphia to Tampa to San Francisco to New Orleans to Anchorage. While not scientific\u2014the large majority of respondents were Democrats, 77 percent, as well as three independents and four Republicans\u2014the survey represented a diverse range of cities from across the nation and showed clear trends across cities of varying sizes, political traditions and geographic regions.    Debates and flare-ups around alleged police misconduct have seized cities as disparate as Philadelphia, Madison and Houston\u2014each governed by mayors who participated in the POLITICO Magazine survey\u2014and across the nation, mayors have begun to lead efforts to repair community trust and broach policy discussions about department conduct.    Still, experts have suggested that the most fundamental improvement departments can adopt still remains the simplest: creating a police force that resembles the citizens it\u2019s sworn to protect. However a majority of the mayors surveyed\u201456 percent\u2014said that their police departments did not accurately reflect the racial makeup of their cities, and fully 13 percent said their force was \u201cextremely\u201d different than the racial makeup of their cities, underscoring that communities like Ferguson\u2014which received harsh criticism in the wake of last year\u2019s protests for its largely white police force overseeing a majority black city\u2014are nationally less the exception than the rule.    Yet even as they reported their concern over race and policing issues and expressed that their own police departments did not adequately reflect the racial diversity of their cities, the mayors surveyed say they believe their own police departments have solid relationships with local minority communities. Three-quarters of those surveyed\u201476 percent\u2014said they believed their police had \u201cgood\u201d or \u201cexcellent\u201d relationships with local minority communities, suggesting perhaps the recognition of a national problem coupled with an apprehension to apply it to their own departments. Indeed, the same contradiction is borne out in social science: In a recent New York Times poll in which a historic low number of respondents positively described national race relations, an overwhelming 77 percent described race relations in their own community as generally good\u2014a trend that has held true for 20 years. Mayors, it would seem, are hardly themselves immune from this phenomenon.    The mayors are enthusiastic supporters of the federal government taking a larger role in issues of police and criminal justice reform. One much desired area of reform: The surveyed mayors, themselves uniquely positioned to feel the brunt of the federal drug policies, overwhelmingly encouraged the decriminalization of marijuana, with 79 percent of the mayors suggesting that the federal government follow the lead of an increasing number of cities like Washington, D.C., and even whole states like Colorado.    Mayors expressed strong approval of President Barack Obama\u2019s speeches and actions in the wake of the unrest in Ferguson and the other policing controversies of the last year; 86 percent described the president\u2019s handling of the national debate over race and policing generally as \u201cwell\u201d or \u201cvery well.\u201d The mayors also broadly supported the president\u2019s decision this year to end the transfer of certain military surplus to local police departments like theirs\u2014the same Pentagon program that endowed the Ferguson police with military-grade equipment, with 57 percent supporting the president\u2019s ban. (The next largest response was \u201cNot Sure,\u201d at 29 percent; only 13 percent of mayors said they would have preferred the program to continue.)    The warm feelings for the federal government quickly dissipated, however, when the survey turned to matters of public education. Most mayors were cool to the legacy of No Child Left Behind; a plurality, 45 percent, said the measures had hurt their school districts, and 31 percent said it had no effect. A strong majority\u2014nearly three-fourths\u2014expressed approval for the controversial Common Core standards.    SURVEY PARTICIPANTS (in alphabetical order): Mayor AC Wharton, Jr., Memphis, TN; Andrew Gillum, Tallahassee, FL; Mayor Andy Berke, Chattanooga, TN; Mayor Anthony Silva, Stockton, CA; Mayor Bao Nguyen, Garden Grove, CA; Mayor Betsy Hodges, Minneapolis, MN; Mayor Bob Buckhorn, Tampa, FL; Mayor Carolyn G. Goodman, Las Vegas, NV; Mayor Dan Clodfelter, Charlotte, NC; Mayor Edwin Lee, San Francisco, CA; Mayor Eric Jefferson, Jackson, MS; Mayor Ethan Berkowitz, Anchorage, AK; Mayor Garrad Marsh, Modesto, CA; Mayor Hardie Davis, Augusta, GA; Mayor Harry LaRosiliere, Plano, TX; Mayor Jesse Molina, Moreno Valley, CA; Mayor Jorge Elorza, Providence, RI; Mayor Libby Schaaf, Oakland, CA; Mayor Marni Sawicki, Cape Coral, FL; Mayor Mary Casillas Salas, Chula Vista, CA; Mayor Annise Parker, Houston, TX; Mayor Michael A. Nutter, Philadelphia, PA; Mayor Mitch Landrieu, New Orleans, LA; Mayor Mayor Paul R. Soglin, Madison, WI; Mayor Ralph Becker, Salt Lake City, UT; Mayor Rick Kriseman, St. Petersburg, FL; Mayor Sam Liccardo, San Jose, CA; Mayor Steve Hogan, Aurora, CO; Mayor Tom Tait, Anaheim, CA; Mayor William Peduto, Pittsburgh, PA.    Indeed, probing into the mayors\u2019 views on school reform revealed a roughly even philosophical split in the school reform wars, even among the survey\u2019s large cache of Democratic respondents. Asked to identify the greatest challenges facing their school districts, many mayors expressed an outlook consistent with nationwide concerns for lack of funding and recourse. \u201cOverall funding\u201d topped the list of concerns, garnering 27 percent, with racial segregation coming in fourth (10 percent) and poor facilities coming in fifth (7 percent). But another contingent voiced concerns typically associated with a focus more on school performance: 16 percent of responses cited the student drop-out rate, coming in second overall; and clocking in at third was \u201cteacher pay\u201d at eleven percent.    Only 30 percent of the mayors said that they were satisfied with the performance of their school districts, and some mayors shared stern words for their city\u2019s school administrators. \u201cThe central administration is a relic of the past,\u201d griped one Democratic mayor. Others described their school systems as \u201cpoorly managed\u201d and another Democratic mayor complained, \u201cteachers unions [have] too much influence on local elected officials.\u201d But regardless of their feelings for administrators, these mayors don\u2019t abide any fantasies for changing the leadership. Some 93 percent said they have no control over hiring their public school\u2019s superintendent, and 90 percent said they\u2019ve never attempted to get such authority.    POLITICO Magazine also asked about the broader political landscape in the United States, and according to the mayors\u2019 surveyed, the rising U.S. economy appears to also be making a difference at the local level, as fully 70 percent of the mayors said that they were more optimistic their local economy is improving than they were at the beginning of the year. (Another 27 percent said they felt the saying they felt the \u201csame\u201d; only one mayor reported being less optimistic about the economy than at the beginning of 2015.)    On the question of which presidential contender they\u2019d most like to see elected for president in 2016, mayors provided a wide panoply of options, including several candidates who aren\u2019t in the race, like Cory Booker and Elizabeth Warren. One mayor offered only: \u201cNot Donald Trump.\u201d But it seemed that the heavily Democratic set of mayors had caught Clinton fever\u2014or, perhaps, Clinton fever had caught them. While a narrow majority thought Hillary Clinton should become president, at 52 percent, when asked who would win the election, nearly 70 percent of responses went to Clinton.    Strikingly, only two of the 31 mayors predicted that a Republican would win next year\u2019s presidential race, with one vote going to Jeb Bush and one vote going to Marco Rubio.    \u2014    The next POLITICO MagazineMayors\u2019 Survey will be published in October. Kristen East, Aaron Mak, Maya Park and Isabelle Taft contributed research to this article.     Ben Wofford is a researcher at Politico Magazine.  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Joshua Zeitz