aV Opening night for the Houston Astrodome\u2014April 9, 1965\u2014couldn\u2019t have gone better. The newly renamed Houston Astros (they had been the Colt .45s from their inception in 1962) hosted the mighty New York Yankees in an exhibition baseball game\u2014the first Major League game played indoors. Yankee slugger Mickey Mantle hit the first home run as President Lyndon Johnson and Lady Bird looked on from an air-conditioned luxury suite\u2014a novelty at that time. (The Astros won the game, 2-1.)     The next 50 years were just as eventful for the world\u2019s first domed stadium. Judy Garland was the first entertainer to play the Dome, with the Supremes as her opening act. Elvis Presley performed there six times. The Rolling Stones, Paul McCartney, the Jacksons, Pink Floyd and dozens of country superstars played there. Muhammad Ali fought there. And it was in the Astrodome where Evel Kneivel jumped over 13 cars on his motorcycle; where the University of Houston beat UCLA in 1968\u2019s \u201cGame of the Century\u201d\u2014the first college basketball game that aired on prime time TV; where tennis queen Billie Jean King, in her prime, whipped 55-year-old Bobby Riggs in the \u201cBattle of the Sexes.\u201d And, of course, it was for a time home to the Houston Oilers football team, baseball\u2019s Astros and the world-renowned Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo.   Story Continued Below   The official name of the Astrodome, which was built with $35 million in local taxpayer dollars, was the Harris County Domed Stadium, but nobody called it that. It was the Astrodome, known as the Eighth Wonder of the World, a remarkable, imaginative structure for its time that immediately became the symbol of the city, right along with America\u2019s pulse-pounding space program.    Today, the Astrodome sits there, wasting away, abandoned and unloved, declared an uninhabitable fire trap by the Houston Fire Department. The Oilers left in 1997, relocating to Nashville and becoming the Tennessee Titans. The Astros left in 1999 for new digs, Enron Field, in downtown Houston. The Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo left in 2002, moving to Houston\u2019s new football palace, NRG Stadium, built next door to the vacant Astrodome. The Houston Texans are now the local NFL favorites.    It is also a political mess that has Houstonians\u2019 emotions at the boiling point. In 2013, voters rejected a $213 million proposal to convert the Astrodome into a multipurpose event facility. The vote went 53 to 47 percent against the Dome. Essentially, voters said they no longer wanted their tax dollars spent on anything to do with the Astrodome. The Houston Texans want the Astrodome demolished to make way for parking. Livestock Show and Rodeo officials favor tearing down the Dome, too.    ***    So why is the Astrodome still there?    Harris County chief executive Ed Emmett, 65, can\u2019t seem to say goodbye to the Astrodome. Emmett\u2014whose formal title is \u201cjudge\u201d due to quirky Texas nomenclature\u2014presides over the five-member Commissioners Court that runs Harris County, which is the third largest in the United States with just over 4 million residents.    Emmett, a Republican, spent nearly a decade in the Texas legislature and some three years as a George H.W. Bush-appointed commissioner on the Interstate Commerce Commission before becoming the elected head of Harris County. His argument to save the Astrodome is simple: The stadium is paid for, and owned by county taxpayers; to him, it makes no sense to tear down a building that he insists is \u201cstructurally sound.\u201d He desperately wants to save the Dome, even though to many he looks like a wacko chaining himself to the building to thwart the inevitable bulldozer.    In 2005, Emmett's predecessor, Robert Eckels, was instrumental in opening the Astrodome to 25,000 Hurricane Katrina evacuees from Louisiana. He arranged for cots and clothing and meals for the mostly women and children, giving them a chance to dry out and catch their breath before figuring out their new lives. The evacuees stayed in the Dome two weeks. It was the last time the Dome had people inside it in an official capacity.    Emmett became county judge in 2007. One year later, Houston was hit by Hurricane Ike, and Emmett gained the confidence of Houstonians and a national reputation for his calm, mature leadership. As rain and wind pelted Houston, Emmett went on TV, standing shoulder to shoulder with Houston Mayor Bill White, a Democrat, and helped residents stay safe with a steady statesman\u2019s hand.    Emmett gained the nickname \u201cHunker Down Ed,\u201d possibly the most respected and well liked politician in South Texas.    Emmett may find that weathering Ike and Katrina was a breeze compared to the fire storm gathering on what to do with the Astrodome.    After the 2013 bond proposal was rejected, Emmett went back to his Dome drawing board. Now he\u2019s promoting a $242 million plan to turn the Astrodome into an indoor park that will have free admission and free parking. He wants green space for picnics and concerts, also museums and sporting events. He thinks a biking and hiking trail would be popular, especially during hot Houston summers. There are dozens of festivals in Houston each year. He\u2019s sure many of them would love to relocate indoors.    Emmett says most of the money will come from the private sector, but admits that taxpayers will have to kick in an undetermined portion.     Emmett recently visited Germany to tour an indoor water park that was converted from an abandoned zeppelin hangar several times bigger than the Astrodome. He wanted to check out the building, meet the architects, and get gardening tips from the Germans, who grow lush tropical plants inside a building 50 miles from Berlin.    This new plan has many taxpayers fuming. \u201cDidn\u2019t we already vote on this?\u201d    The anger seems to come from conservative Republicans in Houston\u2019s suburbs. A conservative radio talk host rails against Emmett and his obsession with saving the Dome. The Houston Press, an alternative weekly, ran a major story: \u201cWhen it comes to the Dome, Ed Emmett thinks you\u2019re an idiot.\u201d    Letters pour into the Houston Chronicle:    \u201cHe\u2019s sticking us taxpayers with a bill for his free vacation in Germany.\u201d    \u201cWhen will his madness stop?\u201d    \u201cI\u2019m a fiscally conservative Republican. Emmett is wasting millions on his \u2018pet project.\u2019 He\u2019s turned into an arrogant political hack who pays no attention to voters.\u201d    \u201cI guess Emmett learned a valuable lesson from his Democratic counterparts when he denied the results of Harris County voters on the future of the Dome.\u201d    So much for avuncular, admired \u201cHunker Down Ed.\u201d    ***    Emmett fumes that Houstonians are buying a lot of misinformation about his new Astrodome plan, while they\u2019re not willing to pay to save Houston\u2019s once-defining structure.    \u201cWe are not proposing a $242 million expense of public money,\u201d he says. \u201cWe\u2019re talking about a public-private partnership. I would hope that only a fraction of that would be public money to build the park itself. We have an Astrodome that is fully paid for, and it would cost tens of millions of dollars to tear it down. So I\u2019d rather spend that amount, or less, to turn it into something useful, and give it to the people who have already paid for it once.\u201d    He is emphatic. The public did not vote to tear down the Astrodome.    \u201dThe polls that I\u2019ve seen say people overwhelmingly support saving the Dome. They just don\u2019t want to use their money to save it. The bond election in 2013 was poorly presented to voters. To this day, people still think they were voting for a convention center. That\u2019s what failed. People did not vote to tear it down, that wasn\u2019t on the ballot.\u201d    And he did not use taxpayer money on his trip to Germany, he notes. He expensed it to his private campaign fund.    One reason that some think they were voting to tear down the Astrodome was this 2013 warning from Emmett himself: \u201cIf we can\u2019t spend tax dollars to repurpose the Dome, and there are no private dollars to repurpose the dome, then the only thing at that point is we can\u2019t leave it sitting there. So it would have to come down.\u201d    Emmett now admits that \u201cI did say something similar to that.\u201d    Not similar\u2014word for word.    There\u2019s another wrinkle that could work in Emmett\u2019s favor: The push to designate the Astrodome as an historic landmark. The Texas Historical Commission has yet to act, largely because officials with the commission said they worried that such a designation could hamper efforts to raise money to rehabilitate the stadium. But Emmett is still hopeful. \u201cWhat people don\u2019t realize is, we couldn\u2019t tear it down now, anyway,\u201d he says. \u201cThe Texas Historical Commission has to approve everything we do with the Astrodome, and I don\u2019t see them approving that.\u201d    So the Astrodome sits, forlorn, depending on its hero Ed Emmett to make it pretty again.    \u201cWhen it\u2019s time to make a proposal, if there is a bond attached to it, I will be front and center, along with other people, to sell it,\u201d he says. \u201cWere there lessons learned from the 2013 election? Absolutely. Whatever we present, we will present in a much more vigorous fashion. The taxpayers have to realize that whatever we do, it\u2019s going to cost.\u201d    Correction: an earlier version of this story incorrectly stated that Ed Emmett was involved in the decision to open the Astrodome to Katrina refugees. It was in fact his predecessor who made that decision.     Ken Hoffman is a columnist for the Houston Chronicle.  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Joshua Zeitz\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By John A. Farrell\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Brian Murphy\u000a  A reported series from Politico Magazine, featuring innovative ideas from cities across the United States at a time of unprecedented urban reinvention. 
