aV The first time Madelinne Gomez journeyed from San Pedro Sula, Honduras, to Houston it was 2008 and she was 8 years old. Madelinne\u2019s father had been killed when she was four and she hoped to rejoin her mother, who\u2019d been in Texas for several years. So, she trekked into Guatemala with the coyote her mother hired, took the train they call La Bestia through Mexico, spent a month ransomed in Reynosa before her mother could pay more, and was set free, alone, in the South Texas wilderness where she was found by the Border Patrol. After seven months with her mother, a judge ordered Madelinne back to Honduras.    She tried to cross again at age 12, but was caught on the train and deported from Mexico. By then San Pedro Sula was known as the most dangerous city in the world and her mother worried about Madelinne\u2019s future as a young woman in the city ruled by the brutal Maras gangs. Madelline had seen death and violence on her journeys to the U.S., but faced great danger too if she remained in Honduras. Early last summer, at age 14, she set out again.   Story Continued Below   On one of the last legs of the trip, she watched the current of the Rio Grande pull an old man from her boat. Madelinne survived, and today she lives in an apartment with her mother and two American-born sisters. She is an eighth-grade student in Houston\u2019s public schools.    She tells me her story at a table at Las Americas Newcomer School, a special Houston program designed to soften the adjustment into the American education system. A world map hangs on the wall behind Madelinne along with the words \u201cwelcome home.\u201d In another corner sits Sarah Howell, a social worker hired last year to help students like Madelinne who arrive from Central America, Afghanistan, Burma, Congo and other parts of the world that have been ravaged by violence or poverty. \u201cNobody came here for fun,\u201d Howell tells me. \u201cYou left because you didn\u2019t have another option.\u201d    That may not be the most glowing endorsement a school or a city could ask for, but it is a point of pride for Las Americas, and for Houston generally. Houston will soon be America\u2019s third-largest city\u2014its metro area grew more than any in the country from 2000 to 2010\u2014and the Houston region is already the nation\u2019s most diverse. According to the Houston Refugee Consortium, the city has been nation\u2019s top destination for refugees, popular for its relatively low cost of living, strong job market, warm weather and well-established ethnic pockets. That Houston is where so much of the world makes its American arrival is the city\u2019s great challenge and its great opportunity. Nowhere is that more evident than in the city\u2019s schools, and no school embodies it more than Las Americas.    In a city with such wealth and promise, and more Fortune 500 companies than anywhere but New York, the school system preparing the next generation of Houstonians is performing a delicate dance of highs and lows: a reputation for bold, impressive innovation, and a student body that\u2019s increasingly poor and challenging to teach.    Eighth grader Sabrin Haile,second from left, chats with a friend between classes at Las Americas; she once lived in an Ethiopian refugee camp. Last year's wave of migrant children fleeing from Central America has balooned Las Americas' enrollment this year to triple capacity. | Mark Peterson/Redux    Two years ago, the Houston Independent School District (HISD) became the first two-time winner of the Broad Prize for Urban Education. The prize is a high honor for school districts, often called the Nobel Prize of school reform, and comes with $550,000 in college scholarships for the winner\u2019s graduating seniors. The Council of Great City Schools\u2014a consortium of the largest urban school districts\u2014named Houston\u2019s superintendent, Terry Grier, its urban educator of the year for 2014. Onstage at a recent school district event, Grier recalled a visit to the White House, when President Obama told him, \u201cYou know, I don\u2019t think anyone innovates quite like HISD.\u201d    Principal Marie Moreno says that nothing in her first nine years at Las Americas could have prepared her for the challenges of this year. "It's not just teaching them English," she said. "It's teaching them a way of life and how to live in a western society." | Mark Peterson/Redux    It\u2019s hard to disagree. HISD, for example, has 52 \u201cdual language\u201d schools, where students spend at least half of the school day learning in Spanish; the district boasts more such schools than Dallas, San Antonio, Austin and El Paso combined. HISD also has one dual language school for Arabic and another for Mandarin Chinese and soon plans to open Texas\u2019s first Hindi dual language school. Through its fledgling \u201cEmerge\u201d program, Houston public schools last year sent 64 low-income, minority students to Ivy League or top-tiered schools; it\u2019s on track to matriculate 91 this year. The district began \u201cHome Field Advantage\u201d recently after it realized that 13 of its schools had mobility rates of 40 percent or more with students changing schools multiple times throughout the year because of family financial stresses. To maintain continuity and stability, students are provided free transportation to the school where they started the year, regardless of where they currently live.    In the schools as in the city, the free market rules: Teachers who are deemed effective receive bonuses; principals are paid to take marketing classes at Rice University to better pitch their schools to prospective students who can choose to go to any school in the district, space permitting. There are also\u2014as in most school districts\u2014teacher/edu-preneurs and Teach for America grads like Adeeb Barqawi and Rick Cruz who go beyond their classroom lessons to build new systems to support students.    As a result, the district has achieved some impressive results: The \u201cachievement gap\u201d in high school math and science between white and minority students has been cut in half; HISD has the country\u2019s highest rate of minority participation in SAT and Advanced Placement tests; passage rate for AP exams has increased by 80 percent since 2007, according to Grier.   \u000aOPTICS: Click here to see the faces of the Las Americas Newcomers School. | Mark Peterson/Redux   But the district\u2019s long history of concerted school improvement efforts hasn\u2019t altered the reality of poverty and economic segregation in Houston. And while it\u2019s nave to expect any new school management strategy to have that kind of impact, some around the district worry that the attention to discrete innovations and improvement strategies\u2014the sort of things that win awards and create good buzz in policy circles\u2014has come at a cost to the stable support network students desperately need their schools to be.    \u201cHouston\u2019s always been the city of the future,\u201d says Houston school trustee Juliet Stipeche, \u201cbut if we don't make meaningful change we\u2019re gonna be left behind.\u201d    Superintendent Grier all but acknowledged that point in a February speech. \u201cThe truth is,\u201d he said, \u201cthe list of Houston schools that most of us in this room would refuse to send our own children to, is longer than the list of schools we consider acceptable for our own children.\u201d     Patrick Michels\u2014a former teacher\u2014is a staff writer for the Texas Observer.  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Brian Murphy\u000a  Law And Order  \u000a\u000a                        By Kel McClanahan\u000a  Swamp Diary  \u000a\u000a                        By Jack Shafer\u000a  A reported series from Politico Magazine, featuring innovative ideas from cities across the United States at a time of unprecedented urban reinvention. 
