aV Matt Popola\u2019s family has owned Paddy\u2019s Service Station in Newark\u2019s Ironbound neighborhood for more than 80 years. Popola\u2019s father was part of a generation of men who manned the rooftops of their homes and businesses, some of them armed, to save the neighborhood from destruction during the 1967 riots that scarred Newark. Now 48 years old, Popola looks to another son of the post-\u201967 generation to save Newark in another time of crisis. Spoiler: It\u2019s not Cory Booker.    \u201cWhen Cory Booker came around, I said to myself \u2018Here\u2019s a guy who believes in us. He\u2019s young. He\u2019s good looking. He\u2019s a rock star,\u2019\u201d Popola says. \u201cBut he\u2019s no better than any other politician. He left Newark high and dry. As soon as something better came along, he was gone.\u201d Popola also hasn\u2019t forgotten the hikes in commercial property taxes and cuts in the police force that occurred during Booker\u2019s watch. \u201cNow, Cory Booker comes off like a playboy,\u201d Popola adds, \u201cand Ras Baraka seems more like a businessman.\u201d   Story Continued Below   To which some people might respond, Ras Who?    Baraka succeeded Booker\u2014he of the golden resume, with boxes checked for Stanford, Yale, Rhodes Scholar. After serving almost two terms as mayor of New Jersey\u2019s largest city and garnering more than 1.5 million Twitter followers, Booker moved politically up and out of the city, winning the 2013 special election to replace the late U.S. Senator Frank Lautenberg (D-N.J.).    Baraka may not be the media darling that his predecessor was, but he\u2019s slowly emerging from Booker\u2019s shadow. And he has some in this city betting he\u2019ll be the better mayor.    Baraka is the son of the late poet and activist Amiri Baraka, an iconic figure of the 1967 Newark civil disturbances, which were termed a race riot by some and a socioeconomic rebellion by others. Baraka is a published poet himself and has contributed a spoken-word intro to the critically acclaimed album The Score by the hip hop group The Fugees. While building a career in education that led to the principal\u2019s spot at Newark\u2019s Central High School, Baraka honed his political chops by serving on the city council.    Poet. Principal. Pol\u2014not exactly the typical trajectory for those seeking public office.    But in other ways, aspects of Baraka\u2019s career are familiar to students of the American political game. Ras Baraka has a strong personal and political bond with his brother, Amiri Baraka, Jr., who served as his campaign manager in the fiercely fought 2014 Newark mayoral race that brought the brothers to power. Now, Amiri is Ras\u2019 chief of staff, an urban New Jersey version of Bobby Kennedy as fraternal enforcer to Ras\u2019 Jack.    If Baraka is to turn Newark into Camelot, he faces problems endemic to many American cities\u2014high violent crime and unemployment rates among them. And, as he closes in on the end of his first year in office, he also faces problems related to another New Jersey politician who, like Booker, has sought the national spotlight: Republican Gov. Chris Christie.    Newark Mayor Ras Baraka at an environmental event in Newark in March. | Mark Peterson/Redux for Politico Magazine    Newark has been at the center of an ongoing battle stemming in part from Christie\u2019s education policies. Christie stood alongside then-Mayor Booker and Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg in 2010 when the social media magnate pledged $100 million to revamp Newark\u2019s schools, which were placed under state control in 1995. It is unclear whether the dramatic attempt to jump-start school reform in Newark has had any lasting effect. Even more unclear in the ultimate impact of the controversial \u201cOne Newark\u201d school reorganization scheme, put in place by Newark Schools Superintendent Cami Anderson in September. (But a lengthy piece in The New Yorker last year certainly casts doubt on the program\u2019s success.)     Christie\u2019s decision to appoint Anderson to head Newark\u2019s public schools in 2011 has created what many see as an educational standoff. The \u201cOne Newark\u201d plan, meant to improve the city\u2019s public education system by increasing students\u2019 school choices and expanding charter schools, has left many parents frustrated and confused. Despite widespread community protests, including from Baraka, the Christie administration recently renewed Anderson\u2019s contract\u2014and rewarded her with a pay raise.    Although somewhat stymied on education issues, Baraka has found opportunity in another Christie-generated crisis.   What Works  By JASON NARK   While the governor has travelled the nation and the world to drum up support for a potential 2016 presidential run, New Jersey\u2019s fiscal situation has grown so dire that \u201cTaps\u201d could serve as its soundtrack. New Jersey is staring down long-term budgetary woes such as the troubled state pension and benefit system and an evaporating transportation fund, with the result that cities around the Garden State are recognizing that the funding stream once provided by the state has all but run dry.     Mark Bonamo is a staff writer at the website PolitickerNJ.   History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Joshua Zeitz\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By John A. Farrell\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Brian Murphy\u000a  A reported series from Politico Magazine, featuring innovative ideas from cities across the United States at a time of unprecedented urban reinvention. 
