aV Office of Management and Budget Director Shaun Donovan said on Wednesday that although the chances of a government shutdown are \u201clow,\u201d he still has his eye on his office\u2019s shutdown countdown clock.    \u201cI believe [the chance] is still low, but \u2026 it is important that members of Congress know that this is the most important thing they can do in the next eight days,\u201d Donovan said during POLITICO Magazine\u2019s \u201cWhat Works Summit,\u201d which was moderated by POLITICO Editor Susan Glasser.   Story Continued Below   Donovan called the possibility of a shutdown \u201cnerve-wracking\u201d and said setting a budget is \u201cthe most basic job of government.\u201d    \u201cWe need to get this done, and I am hopeful that we\u2019ve heard from the leadership on both sides of the aisle that that\u2019s recognized that we need to keep moving, but we\u2019ve just heard that before,\u201d Donovan said. \u201cCongress needs to do its job and we need a funding bill for the rest of the year.\u201d    About sequestration, Donovan said it limits the federal government\u2019s ability to invest in infrastructure, education and housing.    \u201cThe sequestration and budget cuts that we\u2019ve been seeing are devastating for cities, and I\u2019ve made it very clear as budget director to say that we ought to end sequestration,\u201d Donovan said.    Donovan also announced on Wednesday a new set of grants for \u201cClimate Action Champions\u201d around the country.    \u201cThe federal government is in a unique position to help cities understand what\u2019s happening to the climate, how that\u2019s going to affect not just a whole city, but block by block,\u201d Donovan said.    The municipalities designated as \u201cClimate Action Champions\u201d are the Blue Lake Rancheria Tribe, California; Boston; Broward County, Florida; Dubuque, Iowa; Knoxville, Tennessee; the Metropolitan Washington Council of Governments in Washington, D.C., Maryland and Virginia; the Mid-America Regional Council of Kansas and Missouri; Minneapolis; Montpelier, Vermont; Oberlin, Ohio; Portland, Oregon; Salt Lake City; San Francisco; Sault Ste. Marie Tribe of Chippewa Indians, Michigan; Seattle; and The Sonoma County Regional Climate Protection Authority in California.    \u201cThese are communities that are leading already, but they\u2019ve been clear with us, saying, \u2018We need the federal government, and the federal government is relevant here,\u2019 and we\u2019re going to do everything we can to help these communities,\u201d Donovan said.    D.C.\u2019s Mayor-Elect Muriel Bowser said at the event that \u201cany grant funds that can help us use data to help improve is welcome.\u201d    \u201cWe know that we can do more in our lower income communities to improve energy efficiency and we want to make sure we do that,\u201d Bowser said.    The new round of grants will focus on identifying and recognizing local climate leaders and providing those areas with targeted federal support, according to OMB press aide Melanie Roussell Newman.    Shaun Donovan announces 'Climate Action Champions'    \u201cThe selected communities will benefit from facilitated peer-to-peer learning and mentorship and targeted support from a range of Federal programs,\u201d according to a statement. \u201cFurthermore, a coordinator will be provided to each Climate Action Champion to foster coordination and communication across the Federal agencies, national organizations, and foundations in support of the Champions.\u201d    Salt Lake City Mayor Ralph Becker, who also spoke at the event and whose city is set to receive benefits from the grant, called addressing climate change \u201cincredibly important,\u201d and spoke of the grant as \u201canother example [of] this administration\u201d focusing federal dollars on helping specific communities.    The \u201cplace-based\u201d grants come after President Barack Obama ordered a 2009 review of federal programs and found that \u201cleveraging federal investments in an integrated way, on a regional scale, and in a particular place \u2026 [has] the most transformative impact\u201d in revitalizing cities, according to the White House website. The policy takes into account \u201cplace-specific triggers,\u201d existing systems and community growth to target specific cities, neighborhoods and regions where federal dollars will show the most impact.    \u201cThrough this place-based agenda, we can really be a different kind of partner to communities on this incredibly pressing issue of climate change,\u201d Donovan said.    Some of the cities set to receive the new grant already benefit from other place-based funding programs, such as the Sustainable Communities Initiative and Strong Cities, Strong Communities.    POLITICO Magazine\u2019s \u201cWhat Works Summit,\u201d sponsored by JPMorgan Chase & Co. and held at D.C.\u2019s Longview Gallery, took place before an audience of about 70, including mayors from around the country. The event was a culmination of a yearlong series of discussions focused on the future of cities and innovative ways that urban areas are tackling a range of issues.   History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Joshua Zeitz\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By John A. Farrell\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Brian Murphy\u000a  A reported series from Politico Magazine, featuring innovative ideas from cities across the United States at a time of unprecedented urban reinvention. 
