aV It was January 2013 when Milwaukee County Sheriff David A. Clarke Jr. issued a call to arms\u2014not for his own dwindling troops, but to law-abiding citizens.    \u201cWith officers laid off and furloughed, simply calling 911 and waiting is no longer your best option,\u201d the sheriff said in a public service announcement. \u201cYou can beg for mercy from a violent criminal, hide under the bed or you can fight back. But are you prepared? Consider taking a certified safety course in handling a firearm so you can defend yourself until we get there. You have a duty to protect yourself and your family.   Story Continued Below   \u201cWe\u2019re partners now,\u201d he concluded. \u201cCan I count on you?\u201d    Clarke was incensed by what he saw as a spike in violent crime and by weak-kneed responses from his counterparts in the Milwaukee area. No secret that Clarke, a former veteran of the Milwaukee Police Department, was not a fan of MPD Chief Ed Flynn\u2014Clarke has been very publicly mulling a run for mayor, a job that would make him Flynn\u2019s boss. The sheriff\u2014whether on local conservative talk radio or on CNN\u2014seldom leaves any doubt about what he thinks.    Milwaukee Mayor Tom Barrett and others rebuked him, calling his TV spot irresponsible. They accused the sheriff of undercutting confidence in law enforcement and promoting a vigilante mindset in a city already struggling with violent crime. Clarke\u2019s response: doubling down. Big time.    Two months after the PSA, in an interview posted on the conservative Project Veritas website, he instructed law-abiding citizens about what to do if they encountered a \u201cclown\u201d breaking into their house.    \u201cKnow who and what your target is. Point that barrel center mass and pull the trigger,\u201d Clarke directed. He went on to talk about calling 911 to \u201cget this dead guy out of my house. He\u2019s bleeding out and messing up my carpet.\u201d    What right-minded law-enforcement official urges citizens to take crime-fighting into their own hands?    This black Rush Limbaugh with a badge is who. Clarke is a very public doubter when it comes to all the newfangled, data-driven, community-policing experiments embraced by Flynn. Whether Clarke\u2019s approach is effective is tough to determine: He refuses to produce an annual report with data on his department, although the county board directed him to do so three years ago. \u201cAll they are, they\u2019re fluff pieces, anyway,\u201d Clarke scoffs. \u201cEverybody\u2019s annual report says we\u2019re saving the world.\u201d    But saving the world\u2014and getting his fair share of publicity in the process\u2014is exactly what Clarke seems intent on doing.    ***    Clarke\u2019s been the sheriff since 2002, when he was named to the post by Republican Gov. Scott McCallum, and he\u2019s won four elections since then. As sheriff, he has ultimate authority for law enforcement in the county, but in reality, his jurisdiction is limited\u2014the freeways, the courts, the airport and the jail.    Over his tenure, the sheriff\u2019s office closed a drug-investigation unit and a gun-reduction program and other investigation units. His number of sworn deputies has been cut from 647 in 2002 to 245 in 2014. Cops in the county\u2019s 19 municipal police departments do the heavy lifting, the kind of street-level policing Clarke favors and performed for two decades as a patrol officer, homicide detective and commander in the Milwaukee Police Department.    He ordered a deputy who criticized him to go out, by bus, as a one-man patrol in a crime-ridden neighborhood.    The bully pulpit is not just his favored weapon. It may be his only one, a tool he has used to outsize his stature from the start.   What Works  By ERIK GUNN   In press releases and on talk radio, the African-American sheriff has called black legislators race hustlers \u201cpromoting the cult of victimology.\u201d He ordered a deputy who criticized him to go out, by bus, as a one-man patrol in a crime-ridden neighborhood. He threatened to arrest the supervisor of the House of Corrections and warned that gun control would lead to a second American Revolution.    All the political theatrics have made him a celebrated figure on the right: He was named sheriff of the year by the Constitutional Sheriffs and Peace Officers Association in 2013, and featured at the National Rifle Association Leadership Forum in 2014. After a combative appearance on CNN\u2019s Piers Morgan Show, gun rights groups touted a video of Clarke: It shows the sheriff in his favorite pose, on a horse, wearing a cowboy hat and dark glasses; then follows him to a shooting range where he fires his handgun like an action figure.    \u201cI saw 24 years of futility from this criminal justice system,\u201d Clarke told me. \u201cA cop\u2019s biggest complaint is that they can\u2019t get cases charged; we keep putting guys out on the street. Now, I get to talk about it. It angers me, because we\u2019re losing generations of kids to crime, violence, lives of poverty and unemployment.\u201d    In a four-hour interview in his bunker-like office, with Fox News rolling on a big-screen TV, Clarke often fell back into the jargon of a street cop, calling criminals goofs and clowns and using \u201cfrickin\u201d as a softer version of a familiar obscenity. Now 58, Clarke still looks ready to battle bad guys. He\u2019s a commanding figure: six feet, four inches tall, with a strong jaw line and authoritative posture, much like a military man, like his father, who served as a paratrooper in Korea and taught his son discipline. The cowboy look, he says, harkens back to his boyhood, when he sought to emulate his uncle, a wide receiver for the Dallas Cowboys.     Tom Held, a former staff writer at the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel, is a freelance writer and blogger at www.theactivepursuit.com.  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Joshua Zeitz\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By John A. Farrell\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Brian Murphy\u000a  A reported series from Politico Magazine, featuring innovative ideas from cities across the United States at a time of unprecedented urban reinvention. 
