aV Writing about Boston\u2019s adventures in mobile technology, Ben Schreckinger profiles its crowning achievement to date\u2014Citizens Connect, a cell phone app that empowers Bostonians to report municipal problems to city officials\u2014and get them fixed in record time. See a pothole? Graffiti? A broken streetlamp? Just use your smartphone to tag the location and submit a report. In many cases, it takes the city just a day to respond.    Citizens Connect has imitators in cities across the United States: In Philadelphia, it\u2019s Philly 311; in New Haven, it\u2019s SeeClickFix; Oakland\u2019s got Mobile Citizen. But this isn\u2019t the only type of app seeking to provide a public service. From addressing crime to turning us all into citizen scientists, smartphone apps are increasingly being designed not only to make urbanites\u2019 lives more convenient, but also to improve, inspire and empower entire communities. Here are just a few examples:   Story Continued Below   LiveSafe        Co-founded in 2012 by Shy Pahlevani and Virginia Tech-shooting survivor Kristina Anderson with the initial goal of promoting safety on college campuses, LiveSafe, lets its users report any kind of security concern to local police\u2014and provide photographic, video and audio evidence to corroborate. It\u2019s not just on college campuse It\u2019s especially useful in cases such as sexual assault, bullying or concerns about someone\u2019s mental health, when the reporter might wish to remain anonymous or be hesitant to call 911. The app also lets a user send emergency messages (tagged with a GPS location) to selected contacts\u2014or simply post safety tips. LiveSafe is now used at several colleges, such as Virginia Commonwealth University, University of New Hampshire and Washington College, and has expanded to cities. In March, the app raised $6.5 million in venture capital.    Visibility        Air Visibility Monitoring, or just \u201cVisibility,\u201d monitors local air pollution. Users snap a photo of the sky, which is tagged with relevant data (location, time and orientation). The app, developed by researchers at the University of Southern California in 2010, then runs an algorithm comparing the intensity of the image to a pre-established model of the sky\u2019s luminance\u2014all to tell the user just how many pollutants are in the air. With enough data, it can generate a regional pollution map. Unfortunately, it\u2019s not so easy to use: The photo must be properly cropped and taken in the right direction in clear skies (on cloudy days, the accuracy of the visibility data is compromised).    iCitizen        iCitizen, a startup founded by Duncan Dashiff and Rodney Massey in 2013, aims to alleviate voter apathy and increase civic engagement\u2014and not just around election time. The app provides users with information from several different media outlets about a range of political issues\u2014from women\u2019s rights to budget ceilings\u2014and publishes politicians\u2019 voting records and polling data. It\u2019s meant to be nonpartisan, serving as a fact-based database that exposes the public to points of view across the political spectrum. There\u2019s another app called Textizen that functions in the opposite way, providing city planners with public survey data; the app builds a \u201cconversation-based\u201d survey with users about issues involving planning, development and other areas of municipal government\u2014all in hopes of enabling citizens to influence decision-making in their own cities.    Cycle Atlanta        Developed in 2012 by a group of researchers at the Georgia Institute of Technology, Cycle Atlanta lets cyclists automatically track their routes and, once they\u2019ve reached their destination, manually upload feedback about road conditions and safety issues. In doing so, it\u2019s promoting more effective, less bureaucratic communicationbetween cyclists and the City of Atlanta. Ideally, these bikers will be able to voice their need for certain infrastructural changes, including the creation of new bike lanes and the construction of conveniently-located repair shops, without having to attend a public meeting. In the words of co-developer Christopher Le Dantec, who calls this new civic hacking movement \u201cdigital democracy,\u201d apps and data are the new bullhorn and soapbox.     Jordana Cepelewicz is a researcher atPolitico Magazine.  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Joshua Zeitz\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By John A. Farrell\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Brian Murphy\u000a  A reported series from Politico Magazine, featuring innovative ideas from cities across the United States at a time of unprecedented urban reinvention. 
