aV \u000a                Mark Black  \u000aWhat Works  \u000a            By LUCY MCCALMONT  April 09, 2014  Chicago Mayor Rahm Emanuel said he brings the lessons of working in a certain executive office in Washington to his own in the Windy City.    \u201cI do come out of President [Bill] Clinton\u2019s philosophy where I\u2019ll look at different ideas and my question isn\u2019t, \u2018Where does this sit on the ideological prism?\u2019\u201d Emanuel said Wednesday during POLITICO Magazine\u2019s \u201cWhat Works: Chicago\u201d event in Chicago.   Story Continued Below   \u201cIt\u2019s, \u2018Does it move you forward?\u2019 Or, \u2018Does it just keep you trapped in the past?\u2019\u201d he added. \u201cChange is difficult. The goal is to make change your friend, not your foe.\u201d    Citing his own experience working with labor unions, Emanuel said he doesn\u2019t find himself at odds when trying to implement reforms.    \u201cChange is hard, but I do believe if you give people a sense of where you\u2019re going, and what you\u2019re trying to accomplish and how you can make them winners of that, that is a better option than the certainty of what you have today,\u201d Emanuel said, \u201cbecause it\u2019s replaced for the certainty of what you\u2019re going to get tomorrow.\u201d    Emanuel described how he spoke with trade unions while trying to handle tensions surrounding McCormick Place, Chicago\u2019s convention center, and the largest in North America.    \u201cI sat two unions down. I said, \u2018Work with me and we\u2019ll figure this out,\u2019\u201d he said.    \u201cIt was change. It took sitting down, working through the issues,\u201d Emanuel said, noting the growth that followed as a result. \u201cThe pledge I made was, \u2018There will be a win for you and a win for the city.\u2019\u201d    Appearing alongside Emanuel were Pittsburgh Mayor William Peduto and Karen Freeman-Wilson, mayor of Gary, Ind. The panel focused largely on education, and Emanuel announced he is launching the Summer of Learn and Summer of Earn on Wednesday, which aims to keep children in a learning environment during the summer and in summer jobs programs, such as working in community gardens.    He said there also will be a program at libraries called, Rahm\u2019s Readers, in which children read three books and earn a \u201cdiploma.\u201d    Peduto acknowledged that education institutions, such as Carnegie Mellon University and University of Pittsburgh, helped in Pittburgh\u2019s push for technological advancements and growth in robotic industries.    Freeman-Wilson also cited the partnership with Indiana University as well as the University of Chicago, because of its proximity, in tackling challenges facing Gary.    When the conversation turned back to Washington \u2014 a city Emanuel knows all too well \u2014 all three mayors called for more spending on infrastructure, citing Washington gridlock as a hurdle.    \u201cWhat they do, they\u2019re helpful, they just need to do more of it,\u201d Emanuel said of Washington.    \u201cAll of us would agree on more money for infrastructure,\u201d he said, adding, \u201cYou can\u2019t imagine Chicago without O\u2019Hare.\u201d   History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Joshua Zeitz\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By John A. Farrell\u000a  History Dept.  \u000a\u000a                        By Brian Murphy\u000a  A reported series from Politico Magazine, featuring innovative ideas from cities across the United States at a time of unprecedented urban reinvention. 
